Name: iDRAC Message Registry

PCI1356.Message: A bus uncorrectable error was detected on a component at slot %1.
PCI1356.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1356.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.

PWR8516.Description: Unable to perform the chassis power action requested.
PWR8516.Resolution: Check the tracelog for more information. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR8516.Message: Unable to perform the chassis power action requested.

LC045.Description: The CreateConfigJob operation is currently running. The current operation and system restart must complete before the operation can be attempted again.
LC045.Resolution: Wait for the CreateConfigJob operation that is currently running to complete before requesting another operation.
LC045.Message: An instance of CreateConfigJob is already running.

PR12.Description: The Part Replacement feature has detected a firmware difference and would apply firmware. However, user settings indicate that Part Replacement should perform the upgrade only and not a downgrade to an earlier firmware version.
PR12.Message: Firmware update setting allows version upgrade only and will not be performed.

PR30.Description: Operation validation was unsuccessful. The command, target and operation data are all validated before proceeding. If any of them are missing or incorrect the request is failed.
PR30.Resolution: Enable the Collect System Inventory on Restart attribute of the Lifecycle Controller and restart the system. After the system has restarted, retry the operation.

VRM0010.Description: The virtual media could not be disconnected. Possible reason is that it might be in use.
VRM0010.Message: Unable to disconnect Virtual Media devices.

CTL53.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL53.Message: A controller hot plug has been detected.

VFL0015.Description: The request could not be successfully completed, because the vFlash SD Card partition is in read-only mode. Write operations cannot be performed on the card partition.
VFL0015.Resolution: Change the partition access type to read-write by running the command 'racadm set idrac.vFlashPartition.<index>.accesstype 1'.
VFL0015.Message: vFlash media partition is of read-only type.

BAT1003.Message: The battery on %1 learn cycle has completed.
BAT1003.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

UEFI0145.Description: The Trusted Platform Module (TPM) installed on this system is not supported.
UEFI0145.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Update the BIOS firmware. 2) Replace the TPM with a supported one. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0145.Message: The Trusted Platform Module (TPM) installed on this system is not supported.

PDR1006.Message: Drive %1 in disk drive bay %2 is in the failed array.

STOR0507.Description: The RAID controller does not have sufficient number of initialized physical disks or adequate disk space to create the requested virtual disk.
STOR0507.Resolution: Connect additional physical disks to the RAID controller, initialize the physical disks, and retry the operation. To initialize the physical disks, reboot the system and select Option ROM during system startup.
STOR0507.Message: Insufficient physical disk space on selected RAID controller.

RAC939.Description: The request to perform a system profile export or import operation cannot be started because a firmware update operation is already in progress.
RAC939.Resolution: Wait until the update operation is completed or cancel the update operation, and retry.
RAC939.Message: Unable to start the system configuration profile export or import operation.

AMP0316.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0316.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0316.Message: System level current is outside of range.

IPA0002.Description: Invalid parameters passed to the function.

HWC1002.Resolution: If device disabled unexpectedly, re-enable device.

PWR202.Description: Enabling the Max Power Conservation Mode (MPCM) feature forces servers in to a low-power and limited-performance mode, and then disables the ability to turn on additional servers.
PWR202.Message: Enabling the Max Power Conservation Mode (MPCM) feature forces servers in to a low-power and limited-performance mode, and then disables the ability to turn on additional servers.

SWC8509.Message: Unable to apply %1 Profile to server in slot %2
SWC8509.Resolution: Check if iDRAC is ready and system is running properly. Utilize the RACADM command by running "racadm getversion" to list all the servers and make sure the iDRAC version is displayed. If the iDRAC is listed as Not Ready then wait until it becomes ready. A Virtual Reseat may be required. The Lifecycle log in the server identified in the message may have additional information about the inability of the iDRAC to apply Profile settings.

SYS418.Description: The test event cannot be sent because the Alert service is disabled.
SYS418.Resolution: Enable the attribute IPMILan.1.AlertEnable by using the PATCH operation on the Redfish OemAttributes URL, and then retry the operation.
SYS418.Message: Unable to send the test event because the Alert service is disabled.

CMC8542.Message: The CMC %1 was restarted because of a manual reset.
CMC8542.Description: The CMC specified in the message was manually restarted.

RAC0138.Description: The retrieved certificate came back as a null or empty document.
RAC0138.Message: A valid certificate is not loaded.

STOR0502.Description: No RAID controller is installed on the system.
STOR0502.Resolution: Install the RAID controller and do the following: 1) Reboot the system.2) Press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller.3) Retry RAID configuration.
STOR0502.Message: Unable to launch RAID Configuration wizard.

BAT1010.Message: Battery on %1 requires reconditioning. Initiate a learn cycle.
BAT1010.Resolution: Start a learn cycle on the battery.
BAT1010.Description: Battery is in warn only mode and requires reconditioning.

SWU8501.Message: The reinstall/rollback request to Lifecycle Controller on server %1 was not successful.
SWU8501.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the error persists, contact your service provider.
SWU8501.Description: This message is displayed when:1. A reboot job is unable to provide a valid reboot ID.2. The WSMAN command to set up a job queue on Lifecycle Controller was not successful.

SYS035.Message: Some configuration values were not applied to: %1
SYS035.Resolution: Retrieve and view configuration operation results in the Lifecycle Log. For more information to retrieve the configuration results see the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services User's Guide. Identify the unsuccessful configuration operations. Modify the input data as appropriate for the component and retry the configuration operation.
SYS035.Description: The component configuration operation was completed, however some of the configuration values were not successfully applied.

RAC960.Description: The configuration XML file specified for import cannot be located in the specified repository.
RAC960.Resolution: Make sure the specified file name is correct and is located in the specified repository, and retry the operation. For more information about the syntax, run "racadm help set" to view RACADM help.
RAC960.Message: Unable to find the specified configuration XML file for import.

CTL109.Message: The Reconstruct Rate of %1 is set to %2.
CTL109.Description: The Reconstruct Rate of the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.

RAC0628.Description: The job cannot be scheduled, because the requested recurrent Automatic Update job is already scheduled.
RAC0628.Resolution: Delete the current scheduled job, and then retry to create a new Automatic Update job with a new schedule.
RAC0628.Message: Unable to schedule, because the requested recurrent Automatic Update job is already scheduled.

PST0128.Description: System BIOS was unable to detect memory in the system . This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video (BIOS Post Exception 80).

PSU0006.Resolution: Review server product documentation for supported power supplies and power supply configurations.
PSU0006.Description: The power supply identified in the message must be supported by the platform. Generally, multiple power supplies in the server should have the same feature set and power rating.

UEFI0092.Description: The number of DIMM ranks has exceeded the maximum allowed ranks per channel limit.
UEFI0092.Resolution: Check the total number of ranks in each channel to make sure it does not exceed the maximum allowed limit. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0092.Message: The number of DIMM ranks has exceeded the maximum allowed ranks per channel limit.

BAT1019.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PWR8686.Message: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to turn on the storage sleds associated with server in slot %1 because the iDRAC firmware version in the server does not support the chassis storage module.
PWR8686.Resolution: Update the iDRAC firmware identified in the message to the supported latest available version and retry the operation. For information about the supported firmware versions, refer to the Chassis Management Controller user's Guide available at the support site.
PWR8686.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to turn on the storage sled controller identified in the message because iDRAC version installed on the server is not compatible.

SWU001.Description: The expander or storage enclosure processor firmware is successfully updated.
SWU001.Message: The expander or storage enclosure processor firmware is successfully updated.

NIC011.Description: Configuration job already created on the specified target. No further command is allowed until the existing job is completed.
NIC011.Resolution: Cancel the configuration job or wait for the job to complete. Refer to documentation on job cancellation.
NIC011.Message: Configuration job already created, pending data cannot be deleted

SWC8604.Message: Quick Deploy Profile: Server %1 does not support configuration using profiles.
SWC8604.Description: The target server identified in the message does not support server configuration using profiles.

OSD63.Description: The DetachDrivers invoke method cannot be run because the driver files are not attached.
OSD63.Message: Unable to run the DetachDrivers invoke method because the driver files are not attached.

SUP0116.Message: The RAC configuration has initiated restoration to factory defaults. Please wait up to a minute for this process to complete before accessing the RAC again.

STOR0512.Description: Unable to apply the encryption key due to an internal error.
STOR0512.Resolution: Exit Lifecycle Controller, press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation. If the problem persists, update the RAID controller firmware to the latest version and retry the operation.
STOR0512.Message: Unable to apply the encryption key.

RAC0620.Description: Lifecycle Controller is currently busy performing tasks. The selected jobs cannot be deleted until the following: 1) The Lifecycle Controller tasks are completed. 2) The system completes all the Power-on-Self-test (POST) operations.
RAC0620.Resolution: Wait until Lifecycle Controller completes the current tasks and the system completes Power-on Self-test (POST).
RAC0620.Message: Lifecycle Controller is unable to delete the selected jobs.

SEL1500.Message: The chassis management controller (CMC) is redundant.

TMP0119.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0119.Message: The system inlet temperature is less than the lower critical threshold.

RAC0269.Resolution: Enter a valid NIC MTU. Expected range: 576-1500 or 0x240-0x5DC.
RAC0269.Message: The NIC MTU is invalid. Expected range: 576-1500 or 0x240-0x5DC.

UEFI0282.Description: One or more graphics processing unit (GPU) adapters are not operating correctly because the power cables between graphics processing unit (GPU) adapters and motherboard are not correctly connected.
UEFI0282.Resolution: Make sure that the cable connections between GPU adapters and motherboard are correct and retry the operation.
UEFI0282.Message: One or more graphics processing unit (GPU) adapters are not operating correctly because the power cables between the GPU adapters and motherboard are not correctly connected.

SYS024.Description: Unable to complete the operation because attribute dependency checking did not complete successfully. This attribute is dependent on a related attribute that has an incorrect value. The related attribute is the parent in a parent-child value dependency relationship and has an affect on what values the child attribute can have.
SYS024.Resolution: Make sure the dependency related attribute has the correct value and retry the operation. For more information on attribute dependency, Refer to the Dell Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Quick Start Guide and Profile Documents available at the support site.
SYS024.Message: Unable to complete the operation because attribute dependency checking did not complete successfully.

CMC8564.Description: The KVM is not mapped to any of the server slots.
CMC8564.Message: The KVM mapping feature is disabled.

FAN0002.Message: Fan %1 RPM is greater than the upper warning threshold.
FAN0002.Resolution: Remove and re-install the fan at the next scheduled service window. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0002.Description: The fan is not performing optimally. The fan may be installed improperly or may be failing.

PR23.Description: The specified job is ready to start. It is waiting for scheduling from job control. This message is no longer in use in Lifecycle Controller 2.0 as the job control functionality handles this operation.

RDU8508.Message: CMC%1: cannot failover since the other CMC is non-functional.
RDU8508.Resolution: Check the status of the standby CMC and make sure the firmware version matches the primary CMC. Then reseat the CMC and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RDU8508.Description: For failover to occur, the standby CMC needs to be present, at the same version as the primary and healthy. During failover, the active CMC resets and the standby CMC becomes active. This message is logged when the standby CMC is absent, unhealthy or at a different firmware version.

PDR27.Description: A user assigned a physical disk as a dedicated hot spare to a virtual disk. See Protecting Your Virtual Disk with a Hot Spare for more information. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PSU0037.Message: Fan failure detected on power supply %1.
PSU0037.Resolution: Check for fan blockage. If not replace the power supply.

VF027.Description: This partition is attached and attempts to attach it will fail.

USR106.Resolution: Retry the operation using user credentials that are authorized to perform the operation.
USR106.Description: The username provided does not have sufficient privileges to perform the invoke operation on the method.

SWC0024.Description: The Test Network Connection ping test timed-out. The network cable is disconnected or the network is not configured correctly.
SWC0024.Resolution: Check the network cable connection and network configuration settings, then retry the operation. If the problem persists, reconfigure the network settings and retry the operation.
SWC0024.Message: The Test Network Connection ping test timed-out.

RDU8520.Description: The standby CMC is recovered from unhealthy state by the monitoring daemon.

IOV121.Message: PCIe ride-through time out has changed from %1 to %1 seconds.
IOV121.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) has changed the PCIe ride-through timeout to the value identified in the message. PCIe adapters will remain turned on for the number of seconds specified by the ride-through timeout value after the server they are assigned to is turned off. Note: A value of zero equals infinite number of seconds.

SWU8540.Message: Unable to update the PSU firmware, because the transfer of Image file is not successful. ErrorCode=0x%1.
SWU8540.Resolution: Make sure that the PSU firmware image file is available at the location specified in the operation, and then retry the operation.
SWU8540.Description: The PSU firmware update operation was not successful, because the firmware Image file could not be transferred.

PWR8578.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on the iDRAC on server-%1 because power required is less than available power.
PWR8578.Resolution: Make sure there is enough power supply to distribute power. Go to, the Chassis Overview > Power > Power Budget Status. In the Total Input Power Available For Allocation field, view the available power. To add more power, insert more PSUs or remove unused components from the chassis. Remove and reinsert the server when enough power is available.
PWR8578.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on the iDRAC because power required is less than available power.

UEFI0007.Description: A CPU coprocessor segment overrun exception (type 0x09) occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0007.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.
UEFI0007.Message: CPU Exception Type 0x09: Coprocessor Segment Overrun (Software).

RAC0301.Description: User will be unable to connect to Remote File Share.
RAC0301.Resolution: Make sure proper connectivity exists between the client and the remote file share before using this feature.
RAC0301.Message: Remote File Share connection is unavailable. Check the settings and try again.

PWR8677.Description: Dynamic Power Supply Engagement configuration is changed.
PWR8677.Message: Dynamic Power Supply Engagement configuration is changed.

LC009.Description: There were insufficient parameters specified for this command.
LC009.Resolution: Confirm that the parameters provided are correct. For a list of parameters for this method refer to the Lifecycle Controller User Guide.

SYS440.Description: The Job creation cannot be done because the End Time entered is invalid.
SYS440.Resolution: Enter the End Time in the String format, and then retry the operation For example, YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SS. For more information about recommended End Time format, see the iDRAC Redfish User's Guide available on the support site.
SYS440.Message: Unable to Create Job because the End Time entered is invalid.

BAR003.Description: The Backup partition is being created for storing the backup file.

SYS034.Description: The configuration operation for the specified device is in progress.

CTL31.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SWC0261.Description: The option requested is not available on the interface being used.
SWC0261.Resolution: Refer to the help to get the list of commands/options valid for the interface.
SWC0261.Message: The specified option is not supported with the interface being used.

UEFI0287.Message: The QuickPath Interconnect (QPI) link %1 of the processor %2 has a downgraded clock speed or dropped clock because of an initialization error.
UEFI0287.Resolution: Reseat all processors in the system, make sure all processors are of the same type/capacity/model, check for damage, and then retry the operation. For more information, see the Troubleshooting section in the platform Owners Manual. If the issues persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0287.Description: The QuickPath Interconnect (QPI) link of the processor identified in the message has a downgraded clock speed or dropped clock because of an initialization error.

SWC0026.Description: Status of backup Server Profile operation could not be retrieved because an unrecoverable error occurred while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0026.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC, hold the System ID button down for 15 seconds or longer and wait for 90 seconds for the iDRAC to restart. For more information on the error, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0026.Message: Unable to retrieve status of backup Server Profile operation.

RAC0100.Description: Communication with the Smart Card has been lost.
RAC0100.Resolution: Insert a valid Smart Card and try again.
RAC0100.Message: The Smart Card is removed. Further communication is not possible.

UEFI0069.Description: A CMOS checksum error has occurred resulting in an invalid BIOS configuration. BIOS configuration is reset to default settings.
UEFI0069.Resolution: Go to the System Setup and configure the desired settings. Save and exit to apply the settings.
UEFI0069.Message: A CMOS checksum error has occurred. CMOS is reinitialized.

SYS095.Description: Unable to unmount an iDRAC internal storage partition.
SYS095.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issues persists, reset the iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for at least 15 seconds, and then retry the operation after the iDRAC has finished restarting.
SYS095.Message: Unable to unmount an iDRAC internal storage partition.

LIC906.Description: The license file is not present or accessible from the network share location.
LIC906.Resolution: Verify the license file is located on the network share and file access permissions are correct, then retry the operation.
LIC906.Message: License file is not accessible on the network share.

VF014.Description: Enabling vFlash was not successful because the vFlash feature is not disabled.
VF014.Resolution: The vFlash is enabled and any attempt to enable it will not be successful.

PR26.Description: The configuration data associated with the specified job could not be located.
PR26.Resolution: Retry the operation. If this issue persists, contact technical support.

PDR1116.Resolution: If unintended, verify drive installation. Remove and reseat the indicated disk. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PDR1116.Description: The controller detected a drive removal.

SWU8551.Description: The firmware update process of Active CMC was not successful, because of a firmware image checksum error.
SWU8551.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8551.Message: Unable to update the firmware of Active CMC. The checksum process was not successful.

DIS014.Description: Auto Discovery client is using the customer provided Certificate Authority certificate to authenticate the Provisioning Server for the SSL connection.
DIS014.Message: Auto Discovery client using customer provided CA certificate to authenticate Provisioning Server.

CTL12.Message: An invalid SAS configuration has been detected on %1. Details: %2
CTL12.Resolution: Refer to the storage hardware documentation for information on correct cabling configurations.
CTL12.Description: The controller and attached enclosures are not cabled correctly.

PSU8508.Message: %1, PSU%2 firmware update is in progress.
PSU8508.Resolution: Retry the operation after the PSU firmware update is completed.
PSU8508.Description: Unable to set the Power configuration because the PSU firmware update is in progress.

RAC1140.Description: The file name cannot be specified when the Technical Support Report (TSR) is exported to a remote share.
RAC1140.Resolution: Run the command without using the -f option. For more information on exporting Technical Support Report (TSR), run the command 'racadm help techsupreport export'.
RAC1140.Message: File name is not required to export the Technical Support Report (TSR) to a remote share.

UEFI0187.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.
UEFI0187.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0187.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Clock Detection phase.

SYS159.Description: The vFlash SD Card erase operation was unsuccessful. This may be because the SD card is not enable, not licensed or not initialized.
SYS159.Resolution: Make sure the vFlash SD Card is enabled, licensed and initialized, and then retry the System Erase operation with only the vFlash option selected.

BAR056.Description: The configuration import was successful for the specified device.

SEC0033.Description: The chassis is open while the power is off. System security may have been comprised.
SEC0033.Resolution: Close the chassis and verify hardware inventory. Check system logs.
SEC0033.Message: The chassis is open while the power is off.

LC075.Description: Deleting the custom signed certificate should regenerate a new unique certificate . Reset iDRAC to apply new certificate. Until iDRAC is reset old certificate will be active.
LC075.Message: The Custom Signed Certificate (CSC) is deleted successfully. Reset iDRAC to complete the delete action of the certificate.

RED033.Description: The request to shut down the operating system did not complete successfully. The iDRAC was unable to complete the system reboot. Any operation that depends on the system reboot will not complete until reboot is complete.
RED033.Resolution: Identify and resolve any operating system issues that prevented the shutdown. After resolving the issues preventing the operating system shutdown, retry the operation or reboot the system using other methods or interfaces.

UEFI0252.Description: The watchdog timer is armed before the BIOS boot manager invokes an UEFI boot option. The watchdog is set to a period of 5 minutes. The Operating System boot loader from the boot option is required to disable the watchdog timer after it is successfully loaded, otherwise the system will reset if the timer expires.
UEFI0252.Resolution: Check the boot option image and boot loader. Update them to the latest version if possible.
UEFI0252.Message: Unable to boot a boot option because the watchdog timer has expired. System will reset.

UEFI0183.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.
UEFI0183.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0183.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot identified in the message. The error occurred during Early Vref Centering initialization.

PR8.Resolution: If the part is present, make sure it is properly installed. Ensure that the device has not been disabled in the system BIOS or other configuration utility. Contact technical support if the device is still non functional.
PR8.Description: The indicated device has been removed from the system, is no longer functioning, or has been disabled.

RAC0171.Description: Certificate upload failed because the certificate has expired.
RAC0171.Resolution: Certificate has expired. Try creating a new Certificate Signing Request (CSR) and then upload the certificate.
RAC0171.Message: Certificate upload failed: Certificate has expired.

FC103.Message: The %1 port %2 network connection is successfully started.
FC103.Description: The network connection of the FC controller port link identified in the message is successfully started.

PDR35.Message: The only hot spare available is a SATA disk %1.
PDR35.Resolution: Add a SAS disk that is large enough to be used as the hot spare and assign the new disk as a hot spare.
PDR35.Description: The only physical disk available to be assigned as a hot spare is using SATA technology. The physical disks in the virtual disk are using SAS technology. Because of this difference in technology, the hot spare cannot rebuild data if one of the physical disks in the virtual disk fails.

TMP0101.Message: The system board %1 temperature is less than the lower critical threshold.
TMP0101.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.

STOR9.Description: No supported RAID controllers have been detected. Access to shared storage will not be available.
STOR9.Resolution: Ensure supported RAID controllers are installed.
STOR9.Message: No RAID controllers have been detected. Access to shared storage will not be available.

RAC1035.Description: The command is unable to clear the pending state for attributes of the specified component because there are no pending values.
RAC1035.Resolution: Make sure that there is at least one attribute on the specified device has a pending value, and retry the operation.
RAC1035.Message: There are no pending values to be cleared.

SYS031.Description: The configuration is being applied to a component.

BOOT8500.Message: Unable to change the BIOS boot order for the Server %1
BOOT8500.Resolution: Reset iDRAC or wait until iDRAC reboots, and retry the operation.
BOOT8500.Description: Unable to change the BIOS boot order for the server because of a broken communication between the CMC and iDRAC, or iDRAC is rebooting.

SUP0504.Description: The catalog file in the update repository is not digitally signed.
SUP0504.Resolution: Use a repository that has the catalog file from a trusted source and retry the operation. If the catalog is from a trusted source, click OK to proceed without digital signature verification.
SUP0504.Message: Unable to authenticate the catalog file in the update repository.

SYS428.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the property %1 is a required property and must be included in the request.
SYS428.Resolution: Make sure that the property is in the request body and has a valid value, and retry the operation.
SYS428.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the property identified in the message is not supplied as part of the request.

UEFI0075.Description: The Network Daughter Card 1 is not detected.
UEFI0075.Resolution: Install a Network Daughter Card in the system.
UEFI0075.Message: Network Daughter Card 1 is not detected.

RAC1161.Description: Unable to initiate the techsupreport collect operation because the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) is not running.
RAC1161.Resolution: Run the command 'racadm get iDRAC.ServiceModule to make sure that iDRAC Service Module is installed and running on the server operation system (OS) and also to verify that the collection of the server OS data is enabled.
RAC1161.Message: Unable to initiate the techsupreport collect operation for the Tech Support Report (TSR) because the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) is not running.

SWC0008.Description: The export As Shipped hardware inventory operation did not complete because the destination: 1) does not have the specified folder, 2) does not have enough free space, or 3) is read-only.
SWC0008.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, verify the following and retry the operation: 1) Destination has the specified folder. 2) Destination has enough free space. 3) Destination is not write-protected.
SWC0008.Message: Unable to write the As Shipped hardware inventory to the specified destination.

MEM9015.Message: Multi-bit memory errors detected on a Dual In-line Memory Module (DIMM) device %1.
MEM9015.Resolution: Re-install the memory component identified in the message. If the issue persists, contact your service provider. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
MEM9015.Description: The memory device identified in the message has encountered a uncorrectable error. System performance may be degraded. The operating system and/or applications may fail as a result.

PCI1308.Message: A PCI parity error was detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.
PCI1308.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1308.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.

SYS404.Description: The operation cannot be successfully completed because the If-Match request header is missing.
SYS404.Resolution: Make sure that the If-Match request header is entered and retry the operation. For information about the necessary headers, see the Redfish specification and Redfish Users Guide available on the support site.
SYS404.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the If-Match request header is missing.

OSD48.Description: ISO Images of more than 4GB are not supported and cannot be copied to VFlash.
OSD48.Resolution: Use an ISO that is smaller than 4GB.
OSD48.Message: ISO Images of more than 4GB not supported.

UEFI0247.Description: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization encountered a programmatic error. The requested Memory Mapped IO (MMIOH) size is not supported. MMIOH allocation was forced instead.
UEFI0247.Resolution: Reseat all processors in the system and ensure all processors are matching. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0247.Message: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization error detected.

PWR223.Description: Cannot perform a 110V AC operation because the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature is enabled.
PWR223.Resolution: Disable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature and retry the operation.
PWR223.Message: Cannot perform a 110V AC operation because the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature is enabled.

OSD18.Description: Unable to find the ISO file specified in the network share. Make sure that the correct ISO file path was entered into the command and that all other user credentials are correct.
OSD18.Resolution: Rerun the command with the correct ISO file path.
OSD18.Message: Unable to locate the ISO image on the network share point.

HWC1200.Message: The sled %1 is inserted in slot %2.
HWC1200.Description: The sled identified in the message is inserted in the slot identified in the message.

SWC0209.Message: Connect or disconnect image server connections

USR0014.Description: The user session which is currently in use is invalid.
USR0014.Message: The current user session is invalid.

IOV007.Description: For each adapter assigned to a server, power is allocated when the server is turned on. If the available power is less than the required power, the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) will not power on the adapters associated with the server.
IOV007.Resolution: To release the required power, turn off one or more servers by pressing the Power Button on the individual server units.
IOV007.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to allocate power to one or more PCIe adapters in the Chassis Infrastructure component.

FAN0017.Message: %1 RPM is within normal operating range.
FAN0017.Description: The RPM of the fan identified in the message is functioning correctly.

PWR8577.Message: A virtual reseat operation is initiated on Sleeve or Sled %1.
PWR8577.Description: A virtual reseat operation is initiated on the Sleeve or Sled identified in the message. A virtual reseat is the same as removing and inserting a Sleeve or Sled.

SYS136.Description: An issue was encountered while communicating with iDRAC Service Module (iSM) present on the operating system.
SYS136.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Restart the iDRAC Module Service on the OS and retry the operation. 2) Stop iDRAC Service Module Service on the OS and try manually executing the OS Collector application .
SYS136.Message: An issue was encountered while communicating with iDRAC Service Module (iSM) present on the operating system.

SWC0001.Description: The network cable may not be connected or an internal error occurred. For more information about the failure, see Lifecycle Log.
SWC0001.Resolution: Verify the network cable is connected and retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0001.Message: Unable to save the network settings.

SWC0245.Description: Local configuration using RACADM is disabled. This limits local configuration privileges such as resetting object values.
SWC0245.Resolution: Within group cfgRacTuning set the property cfgRacTuneLocalConfigDisable to 0.
SWC0245.Message: Failed to set object value because local configuration using RACADM is disabled.

PWR2204.Message: The system is in a non-volatile sleep state.

VDR8.Message: %1 is degraded either because the physical disk drive in the drive group is removed or the physical disk drive added in a redundant virtual drive has failed.
VDR8.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) Insert a physical disk drive. After the drive is inserted, the previous data is automatically rebuilt by the system. 2) If not already done, configure a hot-spare for the virtual drive. 3) If a physical disk drive is removed from the disk drive group, either replace the disk or restore the original disk drive.
VDR8.Description: The virtual drive on the Controller identified in the message is degraded either because the physical disk drive in the drive group is removed or the physical disk drive added in a redundant virtual drive has failed.

PSU0091.Message: Power supply unit %1 rating exceeds the system power distribution limits.
PSU0091.Resolution: Remove the power supply unit identified in the message and review server product documentation for appropriate configuration.
PSU0091.Description: The rating of the power supply unit identified in the message should not exceed system power distribution limits.

UEFI0224.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0224.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0224.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Transmit Buffer Per Bit Deskew Training phase.

RDU0018.Description: The storage system has multiple redundant power lines. One or more of these power lines is no longer available.
RDU0018.Resolution: Turn system off and remove AC input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. If the issue still persists, contact your service provider. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
RDU0018.Message: The storage power redundancy is degraded.

HWC2005.Message: The system board %1 cable or interconnect is not connected, or is improperly connected.
HWC2005.Resolution: Check presence, then re-install or reconnect.
HWC2005.Description: The cable may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.

STOR026.Description: A configuration job was not created because there are no pending configuration changes.
STOR026.Message: A configuration job was not created because there are no pending configuration changes.

VF018.Description: The specified partition index is not valid for the command.

CPU0802.Message: A predictive failure detected on CPU %1 voltage regulator module.
CPU0802.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
CPU0802.Description: System performance may be degraded or the system may fail to operate.

SYS260.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because the destination file system does not have sufficient free space or does not have sufficient free user quota.
SYS260.Resolution: Make sure that the following are correct and retry the operation: a) file transfer parameters b) remote host file system free space.
SYS260.Description: Unable to transfer a file because the destination file system does not have sufficient free space or does not have sufficient free user quota.

SYS094.Description: The Tech Support Report collection job could not be started, because a report collection job is already running on the server.
SYS094.Resolution: Wait until the current Tech Support Report operation is complete and then retry the operation.
SYS094.Message: The iDRAC is unable to start the Tech Support Report job, because a report collection job is already running on the server.

RAC071.Description: The iDRAC reset operation cannot be completed because a firmware upgrade operation is in progress.
RAC071.Resolution: Wait for the current update process to complete and retry the operation.
RAC071.Message: Unable to perform the iDRAC reset operation because the firmware upgrade operation is in progress.

LC078.Description: The Message Registry was successfully exported to the specified destination file folder.
LC078.Message: The Export Message Registry operation was successfully completed.

RAC1056.Description: The requested firmware Rollback operation was initiated successfully.

SUP0535.Resolution: No response action is required. Do not turn off the system while the update is in progress.
SUP0535.Description: Component firmware update is in progress.

TMP0200.Message: CPU %1 temperature is less than the lower warning threshold.

SYS433.Description: The server configuration profile data cannot be uploaded because the file type used for the data file is not in the JSON or XML format.
SYS433.Resolution: Make sure that the file format used is of JSON or XML format, and then retry the operation.
SYS433.Message: Unable to upload the server configuration profile data because the file type used for the data file is not in the JSON or XML format.

SUP027.Resolution: Verify the required parameter value for the method is specified and retry the operation.
SUP027.Description: The required parameter identified in the message is missing.

SYS125.Description: The OS Collector application is unable to communicate with the WMI service. This may be because the user context the application is running in does not have appropriate access privileges or firewall/security settings are preventing retrieving registry and software data from WMI.
SYS125.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Make sure the user context the OS Collector application is running in has the appropriate privileges to access WMI. Make sure that firewall or security settings are set to allow access and retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, restart the WMI service and retry the operation. 3) If the issue continues to persists, restart the server OS and retry the operation.
SYS125.Message: OS Collector: Unable to communicate with WMI services.

ISM0027.Message: An unprivileged user %1 tried to perform an iDRAC Hard Reset operation from the operating system (OS).
ISM0027.Description: An unprivileged user identified in the message tried to perform an iDRAC Hard Reset operation from the operating system (OS).

CTL13.Resolution: Verify that the battery and memory are functioning properly.
CTL13.Description: The controller has flushed the cache and all data in the cache has been lost. This may occur when the system has memory or battery problems that cause the controller to distrust the cache. Although user data may have been lost, this alert does not always indicate that relevant or user data has been lost.

VDR93.Message: %1 bad block medium error is cleared.
VDR93.Description: This alert message occurs if there are medium errors in the physical drives.

PCI5009.Message: The PCIe adapter in the PCIe slot%1 was removed from the slot while the server%2 was turned-on.
PCI5009.Resolution: Perform a 'Power Cycle' operation on the associated server. Restarting the operating system will not resolve this issue. Only remove PCIe adapters when the associated server is turned-off.
PCI5009.Description: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected that a PCIe adapter was removed from a server which was turned-on. This may cause the server operating system to stop responding or to function in an improper manner.

LIC901.Resolution: To provide the correct value for the specified parameter, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
LIC901.Description: The value provided for the specified parameter is invalid.

UEFI0181.Message: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.
UEFI0181.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the correctable error persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0181.Description: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on the memory slot identified in the message. A corrected Write DQ/DQS error was detected.

RAC031.Description: The operation cannot be completed because an incorrect username is entered.
RAC031.Resolution: Enter a valid username and retry the operation.
RAC031.Message: Unable to complete the operation because an incorrect username is entered.

SWC0058.Resolution: Reboot the system and retry the operation.

PDR21.Resolution: Replace the disk that has received the SMART alert. If the physical disk is a member of a non-redundant virtual disk, then back up the data before replacing the disk. Removing a physical disk that is included in a non-redundant virtual disk will cause the virtual disk to fail and may cause data loss.
PDR21.Description: A disk has received a SMART alert (predictive failure). The disk is likely to fail in the near future.

RFM1031.Message: Removable Flash Media has finished booting.

CMC8561.Message: Unable to send the email to %1 after trying %2 times.
CMC8561.Resolution: Make sure to use a valid email address.
CMC8561.Description: Unable to send the email alerts to the destination.

STOR0107.Description: No EMMs data to display. The system is powered off, no enclosure EMMs are present, or the EMMs are not connected to the enclosures.
STOR0107.Resolution: Check if the server has power, EMMs are available, and EMMs are connected to the enclosure.
STOR0107.Message: EMMs are not connected to enclosures or data about EMMs is unavailable.

PDR3.Resolution: Remove and re-insert the physical disk drive identified in the message and make sure the physical disk drive is inserted properly. If the issue persists, replace the physical disk drive.
PDR3.Description: The RAID Controller may not be able to read/write data to the physical disk drive indicated in the message. This may be due to a failure with the physical disk drive or because the physical disk drive was removed from the system.

SWC0104.Description: The specified log does not take in the -r option.
SWC0104.Message: The -R option is not valid for the specified log.

RAC0228.Description: SD Card needs to be formatted to make it usable. The card must be initialized.
RAC0228.Resolution: Click Initialize to initialize the card and make it usable.
RAC0228.Message: SD Card is detected with an unrecognized format. Click Initialize to initialize the card.

VFL0009.Description: Unable to access the vFlash media, because another operation is currently using the vFlash media.
VFL0009.Resolution: Wait until the vFlash media is available for the requested operation, and then retry the operation.
VFL0009.Message: vFlash media is currently in use by another operation.

CMC8547.Message: Missing kernel module %1. Failover condition detected.
CMC8547.Resolution: No response action is required. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8547.Description: A firmware error occurred causing the failover. If this condition continues, a failover will result. If multiple failovers occur, contact Service.

VFL0016.Description: The requested vFlash media partition is already attached to the host operating system.
VFL0016.Message: vFlash media partition is already in attached state.

PDR105.Message: The physical disk drive %1 is assigned as a dedicated hot-spare.
PDR105.Description: The physical disk drive identified in the message is assigned as a dedicated hot-spare.

SWC0069.Description: The new boot mode settings for BIOS were successfully applied.
SWC0069.Message: Successfully applied the new boot mode settings for BIOS.

STOR084.Description: The requested job cannot be run because another job is currently running. Two options for running jobs on multiple storage controllers are: 1) Run the jobs on each controller individually. Wait for each job to complete before starting the configuration and job creation on the next controller. 2) Schedule multiple jobs to run at a later time using the scheduling options.
STOR084.Resolution: Make sure that the currently running job is completed, and then retry the operation. If necessary, recreate the configuration and the job. For information about running jobs on multiple storage controllers, see the iDRAC Online Help or iDRAC Users Guide.
STOR084.Message: Unable to create the job because another job is currently running

CMC8601.Description: The Chassis group identified in the message is created. This chassis is the leader of the group.

LOG506.Description: The requested operation cannot be started because the ExportChassisLog operation is already running.
LOG506.Resolution: Wait for the current ExportChassisLog operation to complete and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
LOG506.Message: Unable to start the requested operation because the ExportChassisLog operation is already running.

SWC8522.Message: Chassis Group Leader update of member %1 configuration successful.
SWC8522.Description: Successfully completed a configuration sync with the member identified in the message.

UEFI0128.Description: Both the primary and secondary SD cards are in write-protected mode.
UEFI0128.Resolution: No response action is required if this is intentional.
UEFI0128.Message: Both the primary and secondary SD cards are in write-protected mode.

RAC0140.Description: The firmware update process returned an 'Update Failed' status.
RAC0140.Resolution: Try the firmware update again in a few minutes. If the problem persists, try uploading the firmware through another interface such as Web GUI, RACADM, or DUPs.

SEL1511.Message: Member %1 removed from the Chassis Group.

VF006.Description: Creating a partition without image failed.
VF006.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Rerun the command after about 2 minutes 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.

BAR008.Resolution: Verify the request parameters and retry. Check passphrase for rule validity. NOTE: A valid passphrase contains 8 to 32 characters. It must include a combination of uppercase and lowercase letters, numbers, and symbols without spaces.

SYS230.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported protocol value, %2.
SYS230.Resolution: Make sure that the correct protocol value is used, and then retry the operation.
SYS230.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an unsupported protocol value.

CTL43.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes. The text for this alert is generated by the utility that ran the diagnostics and can vary depending on the situation.

CTL27.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PDR1101.Resolution: Remove and reseat the failed disk. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PDR1101.Description: The controller detected a failure on the disk and has taken the disk offline.

RDU0030.Message: The storage voltage of %1 is redundant.
RDU0030.Description: The storage voltage of the device identified in the message is redundant.

MEM1015.Message: Memory device at location %1 is in a power active state.

BAT1022.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SWC4006.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility detected between system BIOS in slot %1 and CMC.
SWC4006.Resolution: Check firmware versions of BIOS and CMC. Update to latest version.
SWC4006.Description: FlexAddress is not implemented in one of the versions of firmware. Please update the firmware.

SUP0529.Description: The selected USB drive is disconnected.
SUP0529.Resolution: Make sure the USB drive is connected and retry the operation.

LOG204.Description: The archive operation did not complete. 10% of the events from the cache will be dropped to make space for new events.
LOG204.Message: Lifecycle Log archive operation did not complete.

UEFI0161.Message: An unsupported DIMM population has been detected on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0161.Resolution: Remove all unsupported DIMM modules from the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0161.Description: An unsupported DIMM population has been detected on memory slots identified by this message.

RAC1132.Description: The firmware could not be successfully updated, because one or all of the following values are incorrect:A) logon ID.B) IP address of TFTP or FTP server.C) Full path of the firmware file.
RAC1132.Resolution: Run the racadm command "racadm help <subcommand>" to get more details about the various options applicable for this command and the values accepted by the command.
RAC1132.Message: Unable to update the firmware. The value entered for an option is invalid.

SWU8545.Description: The firmware update operation of the Standby CMC was not successful.
SWU8545.Message: Unable to update the Standby CMC firmware.

ISM0020.Description: The OS Collector application did not start successfully on the server operating system (OS) because the iDRAC emulated USB device with the OS Collector application was not found.
ISM0020.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
ISM0020.Message: The OS Collector application did not start successfully on the server operating system (OS) because the iDRAC emulated USB device with the OS Collector application was not found.

SWC0031.Description: iDRAC is unable to initiate the backup Server Profile operation because an unrecoverable error occurred.
SWC0031.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC, hold the System ID button down for 15 seconds or longer and wait for 90 seconds for the iDRAC to restart. For more information on the error, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0031.Message: Unable to initiate the backup Server Profile backup operation.

PCI5008.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) could not successfully connect to the PCIe switch board.
PCI5008.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Perform an AC Power Cycle operation on the Chassis by disconnecting the chassis from AC power, waiting for 30 seconds, and then reconnecting AC power. 2) Power on at least one server. Using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) web interface, select Server Overview->Power->Control and then click the Operation field and select the Power On Server operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PCI5008.Message: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to communicate with the PCIe switch board.

RAC0513.Description: There are no virtual disks to be displayed. There may be no virtual disks created, the controller(s) may not be in RAID mode, or there may be pending creation or deletion jobs that have not completed.
RAC0513.Resolution: Check the following: 1) Check if the server is turned off. If the server is turned off, turn it on and wait until POST completes. 2) If no virtual disks are created, to start the virtual disk creation process, click #{create_virtualdisk_link}. 3) If create virtual disk operation(s) are in a pending state, complete the creation process. To complete the virtual disk(s) creation, go to the Pending Operations page and create a configuration job on the appropriate controller. 4) If delete virtual disk operation(s) are in pending state, then cancel the operation. To cancel delete virtual disk pending operation(s), go to the Pending Operations page and delete all pending operation(s) on the appropriate controller. 5) If the Controller(s) are in HBA mode, switch the controller(s) to RAID mode. To switch controller(s) to RAID mode using the F2 System Setup utility, go to Device Settings > RAID Controller > Controller Management > Advanced Controller Management > Switch to RAID mode.
RAC0513.Message: There are no virtual disks to be displayed.

ENC22.Resolution: Refer to the storage hardware documentation for more information.
ENC22.Description: The enclosure has a bad sensor. The enclosure sensors monitor the fan speeds, temperature probes, and so on.

SWC0231.Description: The partition image type specified is not available on local racadm.
SWC0231.Message: Partition of type \"image\" not supported on local racadm.

PCI1354.Message: A bus correctable error was detected on a component at slot %1.
PCI1354.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, remove and re-install the device at the next scheduled service time.

STOR0106.Description: No fan data to display. The system is powered off, no fan enclosures are present in the system, or the fans are not connected to the enclosures.
STOR0106.Resolution: Check if the server has power, enclosure fan is available, and fan is connected to the enclosure.
STOR0106.Message: Fans are not connected to enclosures or data about fans is unavailable.

RAC1016.Description: iDRAC does not allow duplicate user names for each of the 16 users.
RAC1016.Resolution: Make sure that each of the 16 user names are unique.
RAC1016.Message: The specified user already exists. Duplicate user names are not allowed.

SYS257.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because the verification certificate is not available.
SYS257.Resolution: Upload the verification certificate or select the Ignore Certificate Warning setting, and then retry the operation.
SYS257.Description: The file cannot be transferred because the verification certificate is not available. The file transfer settings are set to verify the certificate of the remore host server, but the necessary verification certificate is not uploaded.

OSD40.Description: This is not a Dell-licensed vFlash.
OSD40.Resolution: Insert a Dell vFlash and then retry this command.

UEFI0133.Description: Unable to perform PXE boot because the VLAN settings conflict with that of the iSCSI device settings.
UEFI0133.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Go to System Setup and change the VLAN configuration for the PXE device to match that of the iSCSI device. Either both devices must be configured with VLAN enabled or both devices must be configured with VLAN disabled. 2) Change the PXE device interface setting to use a different NIC interface than the NIC interface used by the iSCSI device.
UEFI0133.Message: Unable to perform PXE boot because the VLAN settings conflict with that of the iSCSI device settings.

IPA0003.Description: Invalid parameters passed to the function.

BOOT011.Description: The provided vFlash partition could not be set for one time boot.
BOOT011.Resolution: Power cycle system and reapply firmware packages for Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC.
BOOT011.Message: Failed to set vFlash partition for one time boot

BOOT006.Description: One or more of the Boot Source instance ID's does not contain valid data.
BOOT006.Resolution: Verify that all of the Boot Source instance IDs being entered are as they appear in the DCIM_BootSourceSetting enumeration.

RAC0289.Description: When creating a user account, the same value must be entered for New Password and Confirm New Password.
RAC0289.Resolution: Enter the same values for both New Password and Confirm New Password.
RAC0289.Message: Values in New Password and Confirm New Password fields do not match.

SYS409.Description: The object properties cannot be set because an incorrect object value is entered.
SYS409.Resolution: Enter a valid object value and retry the operation. For information about recommended values, see the schema or the attribute registry based on the type of resource.
SYS409.Message: Unable to set the object properties because an incorrect object value is entered.

RAC061.Description: The IPMI Watchdog can not be enabled at the same time as the OS Watchdog.
RAC061.Resolution: Disable the OS Watchdog before enabling IPMI Watchdog.
RAC061.Message: Unable to set the IPMI Watchdog because the OS Watchdog is already enabled.

RAC0766.Message: Unable to assign USB NIC IP address %1 to the OSBMC device because only Link Local IP address can be allowed.
RAC0766.Resolution: Enter appropriate Link Local IP address, and then retry the operation. For information about supported IP addresses, refer to the iDRAC Users Guide available at the support site.
RAC0766.Description: The USB NIC IP address identified in the message cannot be assigned to the OSBMC device because only Link Local IP address can be allowed.

LC055.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because the number of AttributeName input parameters provided to the method exceeded the number of attributes available in iDRAC.
LC055.Resolution: Retry the operation with an input parameter array that matches the available attributes in iDRAC.
LC055.Message: The operation did not complete successfully because of an invalid attribute array.

CMC8608.Message: Unable to start the operation on server in slot %1, because of insufficient user privileges.
CMC8608.Resolution: Retry the operation by using user credential that has Server Debug privileges. For more information about recommended user privileges, contact your system administrator or service provider.
CMC8608.Description: The operation cannot be started on the server identified in the message because of insufficient user privileges.

CTL28.Message: The Background Initialization (BGI) rate has changed for %1.
CTL28.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC1191.Description: The file import operation has failed because of large file size.
RAC1191.Resolution: The file import operation has timed out, because the file is invalid or is exceeding the permissible size. Retry the operation with a valid file.
RAC1191.Message: Unable to import the specified file to iDRAC.

PWR8564.Message: Unable to turn on the Server %1 because the power request exceeded the System Input Power Cap.
PWR8564.Resolution: Utilize the Chassis Management Controller web interface to check the System Input Max Power Capacity Power and server power requirements. If sufficient power is available, retry the operation. Otherwise, increase the System Input Power Cap value.
PWR8564.Description: The server identified in the message was not turned on because the available power is less than the requested power.

SWC0215.Description: The process to disable the file share has started. Use the -s option to know more about the status.
SWC0215.Resolution: If required check the status using the -s option.
SWC0215.Message: Disable Remote File Started. Please check status using -s option to know Remote File Share is ENABLED or DISABLED.

SUP0530.Description: The catalog repository path entered is not accessible.
SUP0530.Resolution: Retry the operation with the correct catalog repository path.

HWC4012.Message: Hardware successfully updated for embedded NIC.

OSD58.Description: The connect ISO operation using Remote File Share (RFS) did not complete successfully.
OSD58.Resolution: Verify all the parameters are correct. If the problem persists. then reset iDRAC and retry the operation.
OSD58.Message: Unable to connect an ISO using Remote File Share (RFS).

LIC020.Description: Importing an upgrade license without a base license is not allowed, as it may be a violation of the license EULA agreement. If the base license was deleted, the system allows the user to override the warning by invoking the import override option.
LIC020.Resolution: If the base license was deleted, override the warning by invoking the import override option.
LIC020.Message: Import failed: End User License Agreement (EULA) import upgrade warning.

SWC0155.Message: CSR generated and downloaded from RAC successfully

PDR1007.Message: Rebuild is in progress for drive %1 in disk drive bay %2.

PST0005.Description: System BIOS has started copying image from flash to system memory.

SWC0296.Description: Either the password field or the username field is empty.
SWC0296.Resolution: Enter the command with the username and password.
SWC0296.Message: The specified value is not allowed to be configured if the user name \nor password is blank.

TMP0120.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm.
TMP0120.Message: The system inlet temperature is greater than the upper warning threshold.

CBL0001.Resolution: Reconnect or replace the power cable. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CBL0001.Description: A backplane signal cable was detected, but the accompanying power cable was not present.

UEFI0188.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.
UEFI0188.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0188.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Host Impedance phase.

RAC0154.Description: Displayed when a group of redundant power supplies has one or more individual power supplies with bad status.
RAC0154.Resolution: Replace the degraded power supply unit. Check the Power Supplies page for more information.
RAC0154.Message: Non-redundant power mode: Secondary power supply has degraded.

SWC8563.Message: Boot Identity profile %1 is cleared from server in slot %2.
SWC8563.Description: The Boot Identity profile identified in the message is cleared from the server identified in the message.

PST0132.Description: System BIOS detected a failure with CMOS memory during system POST. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception Code 84).
PST0132.Resolution: Check system event log for CMOS battery exceptions. Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

SYS029.Resolution: Remove the unsupported parameter and retry the operation.
SYS029.Description: The parameter name is not supported.

SYS166.Description: The collection of OS and Application Data did not start within the allocated time.
SYS166.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) Make sure the OS does not have any firewall setting to block USB device enumeration, and then retry the operation. 3) Make sure the OS is not configured to attach USB devices as read-only, and then retry the operation. 4) Make sure the OS is supported by the OS Collector application. 5) Reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation. 6) For more information about the collection of OS and application data, see the iDRAC8 User's Guide.
SYS166.Message: The collection of OS and Application Data did not start within the allocated time.

SYS100.Message: Unable to find an FQDD equivalent for the token %1
SYS100.Resolution: Make sure that only valid FQDDs are entered as input to the Target parameter, and then retry the operation.
SYS100.Description: A FQDD equivalent for the token name identified in the message cannot be found.

SUP016.Description: Only jobs with the job status of Downloading / Downloaded / Pending Reboot can be scheduled.
SUP016.Resolution: In case there is an update job, wait until the job status is Downloaded and then retry the action.

STOR093.Description: The configuration operation cannot be performed because the controller is not available for import process.
STOR093.Resolution: Make sure an operation is not pending on the controller. If an operation is pending, wait for the operation to complete or cancel the pending operation and then retry the operation. Refer to the storage controller documentation for compatibility information.
STOR093.Message: Unable to run the configuration operation because the controller is not available for the import process.

CTL81.Message: Security key assigned to %1 is modified.
CTL81.Description: The security key assigned to the controller identified in the message is modified.

PDR41.Message: The clear operation on %1 was cancelled.
PDR41.Description: The clear command did not complete on the physical disk. This means that some data was not cleared and may be recoverable.

UEFI0220.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0220.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0220.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Write Voltage Training phase.

SYS090.Description: The configuration profile contains DOCTYPE tags which may contain injection security threats. The DOCTYPE tag is not supported in configuration profiles.
SYS090.Resolution: Check the input XML file for DOCTYPE XML tags and remove them before retrying the operation.
SYS090.Message: The configuration profile contains unsupported DOCTYPE tags.

SYS149.Description: Initiating iDRAC reset to defaults operation because of a System Erase operation. The iDRAC will restart after firmware default values are restored.
SYS149.Message: The process of resetting iDRAC to default settings is initiated.

CPU0800.Message: CPU %1 voltage regulator module is present.

MEM1209.Message: Memory spare redundancy is degraded. Check memory device at location %1.

SUP0519.Message: Unable to validate firmware image for %1.
SUP0519.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, download the latest Update Package from your service provider and retry the operation.
SUP0519.Description: The update firmware image operation is unable to process the firmware image provided. The image is invalid or incompatible with the installed component.

UEFI0072.Message: Unable to load the firmware from %1 because of the Secure Boot policy.
UEFI0072.Resolution: If the Secure Boot feature is not desired, disable it in System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings page. Otherwise, do the following: 1) Make sure the firmware on the failing device is up-to-date. 2) If subsequent failures occur, review the Secure Boot Policy Summary in System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings page. The device firmware must be authorized by a public key or hash value in the Authorized Signature Database. The public key or hash value must not be present in the Forbidden Signature Database.
UEFI0072.Description: When the Secure Boot feature is enabled, the system BIOS authenticates each UEFI driver against the Secure Boot policy. If a UEFI driver does not meet the policy criteria, the system BIOS does not load or execute the UEFI driver and displays this message at the end of POST. The Secure Boot policy consists of authorized and unauthorized X.509 certificates; signed drivers must chain to an authorized certificate. The policy may also authorize hash values of individual UEFI driver images. Users can configure the Secure Boot feature and the Secure Boot policy in F2 System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings page.

RAC1138.Description: Unable to export the remote diagnostics results because the remote diagnostics results have not been generated.
RAC1138.Resolution: Using the RACADM command line interface, run the "racadm diagnostics run" command to make sure that the diagnostics results are available, and then retry the operation.
RAC1138.Message: Unable to export the diagnostics results because the results do not exist.

NIC013.Resolution: Enter the correct AttributeName available in the system. Refer to the enumeration response for desired attribute.
NIC013.Description: An unknown AttributeName was entered for the operation.

RAC0108.Description: A non-specific error is detected when accessing the Smart Card.
RAC0108.Resolution: Review the error message preceding or following this message.
RAC0108.Message: An internal error is encountered. Insert a valid Smart Card and try again.

BIOS005.Description: The number of AttributeName and AttributeValue parameters do not match.
BIOS005.Resolution: Enter the same number of parameters for AttributeName and AttributeValue. Refer to documentation for method input parameter details.
BIOS005.Message: Mismatch in AttributeName and AttributeValue count

PWR8557.Description: The current Power Cap setting cannot be enforced. This may be the result of changing the redundancy mode or by changing the PSUs. The power cap setting must be increased to be usable.
PWR8557.Resolution: Increase the Power Cap value. To increase the Power Cap do one of the following: 1) Using CMC Web interface: Select "Chassis Overview" -> Power -> Configuration and then adjust System Input Power Cap values. 2) Run the following RACADM command at the command line interface: "config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisPowerCap <value>".Try setting the power cap above the lower bound displayed on the power configuration page.
PWR8557.Message: The System Input Power Cap is too low to be enforced using the current Power Supply configuration.

HWC3006.Message: Unable to QuickDeploy server in slot %1.
HWC3006.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Check the number of reserved IPv4 addresses for QuickDeploy. 2) Modify it such that the newly inserted blade will obtain an IP address for QuickDeploy. 3) Reseat the server to retry the QuickDeploy operation or manually configure the network parameters for the server. (Note that some chassis models may require a response at the LCD panel).
HWC3006.Description: There are not enough IPv4 addresses reserved for the servers in this chassis. Therefore the newly inserted server could not be configured with the QuickDeploy feature.

UEFI0270.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the network connection to DHCPv4 server is not established.
UEFI0270.Resolution: Check the network cable connection of the initiator or the DHCPv4 server and retry the operation.
UEFI0270.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the network connection to DHCPv4 server is not established.

SUP020.Description: The specified job was successfully deleted from the job queue.

STOR0701.Description: There are no RAID controllers, physical disks or virtual disks discovered by instrumentation that can be configured.
STOR0701.Resolution: Storage objects are unavailable in the current system configuration. Make sure that the storage devices are installed in the system, and then retry the operation after the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature has updated the system inventory. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
STOR0701.Message: Storage objects are unavailable in the current system configuration.

UEFI0026.Description: iDRAC is not responding to BIOS commands. The BIOS will reset the system to retry the initialization process.
UEFI0026.Resolution: Wait for the BIOS to reset the system and reinitialize the iDRAC. If the issue persists, remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system.

ENC23.Description: There is a problem with a physical connection or PHY in the enclosure identified in the message.

PDR44.Resolution: Verify that the disk is present and not in a Failed state. Make sure the cables are attached securely. See the storage hardware documentation for more information on checking the cables. Restart the Clear task.
PDR44.Description: A Clear task was being performed on a physical disk but the task was interrupted and did not complete successfully. The controller may have lost communication with the disk, the disk was removed, or the cables may be loose or defective.

UEFI0261.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the R920 I/O riser is not supported in R930.
UEFI0261.Resolution: Replace the R920 I/O riser with an R930 I/O riser. For information about the supported I/O risers, see the product documentation available at the support site.
UEFI0261.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the R920 I/O riser is not supported.

RAC0713.Description: Server failed to power up due to fabric mismatch.
RAC0713.Resolution: Ensure that the hardware compatibility between the IO Module (IOM) and the Mezzanine (Mezz) card is correct. Check the M1000e Hardware Manual for correct component compatibility.
RAC0713.Message: Server failed to power up due to fabric mismatch.

PDR116.Resolution: Back up the data on the device, and contact your service provider for further instructions.
PDR116.Description: The PCIe Solid-State Drive is predicted to fail. Many physical disks contain Self Monitoring Analysis and Reporting Technology (SMART). When enabled, SMART monitors the disk health based on indications such as the number of write operations that were performed on the disk.

STOR12.Description: One or more RAID controllers is disabled. This prevents Fault Tolerant mode from operating.
STOR12.Message: Chassis is operating with a disabled RAID controller.

ASR0002.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate to the baseboard management controller (BMC). The system powered off per the configured setting.
ASR0002.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0002.Message: The watchdog timer powered off the system.

CBL0004.Message: The %1 cable is incorrectly connected to backplane %2 connector %3.
CBL0004.Resolution: Make sure the cable identified in the message is cabled correctly. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CBL0004.Description: The cable identified in the message is incorrectly connected to the backplane connector.

SUP0505.Description: The catalog file in the selected repository is corrupt.
SUP0505.Resolution: Select a repository with a valid catalog file, and retry the operation.

PCI3003.Message: Virtual MAC address for component at bus %1 device %2 function %3 was successfully programed.

CMC8609.Message: Unable to read the Complex Programmable Logical Device (CPLD) version number of sleeve %1 because the CPLD version is very old, or the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to identify the version.
CMC8609.Resolution: Update the CPLD version of sleeve and retry the operation. For more information about the recommended CPLD versions, see the Chassis Management Controller User's Guide available at the support site.
CMC8609.Description: The version number of Complex Programmable Logical Device (CPLD) on the sleeve identified in the message cannot be read because the CPLD version is very old, or the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to identify the version.

OSD56.Description: An ISO is already connected using Remote File Share (RFS). The connection might have been initiated from iDRAC GUI, racadm, or Remote Services API.
OSD56.Resolution: Disconnect the Remote File Share (RFS) using iDRAC GUI, racadm, or Remote Services API and then retry the operation to connect the ISO again.
OSD56.Message: An ISO is already connected using Remote File Share (RFS).
