STOR059.Description: The requested operation cannot be completed because there are no virtual disks (VD) available on the specified controller.
STOR059.Resolution: Create a virtual disk and retry the operation.
STOR059.Message: The requested operation is not currently valid because there are no virtual disks on the controller.

UEFI0254.Description: Unable to enable NUMA Fault Resilient Memory operating mode because of channel configuration mismatches.
UEFI0254.Resolution: Make sure identical memory modules in corresponding slots of channel pairs are populated. For more information, see platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0254.Message: Unable to enable NUMA Fault Resilient Memory operating mode because of channel configuration mismatches.

RFM1026.Description: An error is reported during a SD card read or write.
RFM1026.Resolution: Re-install the flash media, if the issue persists replace the media.
RFM1026.Message: Failure detected on Removable Flash Media.

SWC0306.Description: The syntax of the fwupdate command is invalid.
SWC0306.Resolution: Refer the help text for fwupdate subcommand.
SWC0306.Message: The -a option requires -g and -u to also be specified.

CTL42.Message: Enclosure Management Module (EMM) hot plug is not supported on %1.
CTL42.Resolution: If the new enclosure and its device are not detected by the operating system, try restarting your system to verify the newly attached enclosure and its sub-components are detected. See the hardware documentation for more information.
CTL42.Description: An attempt to hot plug an Enclosure Management Module (EMM) has been detected.

TMP1002.Message: %1 has exceeded the maximum failure threshold.
TMP1002.Resolution: Check for factors that may cause overheating. For example, verify that the enclosure fan is working. You should also check the thermostat settings and examine whether the enclosure is located near a heat source. Make sure the enclosure has enough ventilation and that the room temperature is not too hot. Refer to the enclosure documentation for more diagnostic information.
TMP1002.Description: The enclosure is too hot. A variety of factors can cause the excessive temperature. For example, a fan may have failed, the thermostat may be set too high, or the room temperature may be too hot.

HWC5004.Message: A link tuning failure detected on %1.
HWC5004.Resolution: Update the CMC firmware. If the problem persists, contact support.
HWC5004.Description: CMC has old firmware and does not recognize the new device which has requested link tuning information. After updating the firmware the CMC will recognize the device.

VFL1014.Message: Removable Flash Media %1 is write protected.
VFL1014.Resolution: If unintended, remove the media and disable write protection.
VFL1014.Description: The card is write-protected by the physical latch on the SD card. IDSDM cannot use a write-protected card.

RAC0607.Description: The integrated NICs in the system do not support OS to iDRAC Pass-Through.
RAC0607.Resolution: Make sure the integrated NICs are enabled from BIOS setup and support OS to iDRAC Pass-Through, then retry the operation. To access BIOS setup, press F2 during system startup. For more information about OS to iDRAC Pass-Through, see iDRAC7 Users Guide.
RAC0607.Message: Unable to perform OS to iDRAC Pass-Through with the current system configuration.

CMC8517.Message: A double height server is detected in slot %1, however the server is not detected in the bottom slot.
CMC8517.Resolution: Remove the server from the chassis, check for any broken or bent pins at the rear of the server. If there is no damage, reinsert the server into the chassis.
CMC8517.Description: A double height server is detected in slot specified in the message, however the server is not detected in the bottom slot. This occurs if the server is not correctly inserted into the chassis.

STOR071.Message: The Span Count is not valid for creating a RAID 10. Valid Span counts are %1.
STOR071.Resolution: Enter a valid span count, and then retry the operation.
STOR071.Description: The configuration operation could not be performed because the specified span count is not valid.

CMC8563.Message: The KVM is mapped to the server slot %1.
CMC8563.Description: The KVM is mapped to the server slot number specified in the message.

DKM1000.Resolution: Check for network connectivity. Review network, server, and client configuration.
DKM1000.Message: A network problem detected. Cannot contact key management server.

PWR1006.Resolution: Review system configuration, upgrade power supplies or reduce system power consumption.
PWR1006.Message: The system halted because system power exceeds capacity.

CTL66.Message: Attempted to import Unsupported Virtual Disk type RAID%1 on %2.
CTL66.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

VDR13.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

VF012.Description: There is no SD card detected.

IOV116.Message: PCIE AUX power cable %1.was disconnected while powered on.
IOV116.Resolution: Make sure AUX power cable identified in the message is fully plugged into the adapter and the AUX cable harness.
IOV116.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected a power fault in an PCIE AUX power cable after the adapter was powered on. A power fault may be caused by a loose cable connection to the adapter or between the cable and the AUX cable harness.

RAC0222.Description: The specified email address does not match an email address format. Ex: "janedoe@email.com".
RAC0222.Message: The Destination E-mail Address is invalid.

PSU8522.Message: PSU %1 reported input under voltage fault and has been turned off.
PSU8522.Resolution: 1) Check PSU AC input power source. 2) Remove AC power and reapply power to the PSU to get it functional again. 3) If the issue persists, contact technical support.
PSU8522.Description: The power supply unit (PSU) identified in the message was turned off because the input under voltage fault occurred.

SEC0607.Message: The network boot password violation was corrected.

SYS009.Message: String exceeds maximum length for attribute: %1
SYS009.Resolution: Check Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation and retry the command with string value length less than maximum length allowed.
SYS009.Description: Length of string for specified attribute exceeded the maximum length allowed.

UEFI0158.Description: The iDRAC request to reset BIOS to default settings cannot be completed.
UEFI0158.Resolution: Restart the system and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0158.Message: Unable to complete the iDRAC request to reset BIOS to default settings.

RAC1039.Description: The subcommand entered is not supported on the specified server.
RAC1039.Message: The subcommand entered is not supported on the specified server.

CMC8613.Message: The reset process of iDRAC Non Maskable Interrupt (NMI) on sled %1 is initiated.
CMC8613.Description: The reset process of iDRAC Non Maskable Interrupt (NMI) on sled identified in the message is initiated.

UEFI0150.Description: The system has detected a storage backplane that is not supported in this system or configuration. The backplanes functionality may be degraded or disabled.
UEFI0150.Resolution: Install a supported backplane configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0150.Message: The system has detected a storage backplane that is not supported in this system or configuration. The backplanes functionality may be degraded or disabled.

LIC010.Description: A license is not imported to the iDRAC when one of the following conditions exists:1) The license is not for the iDRAC.2) The target system may not be upgraded to the product class specified by the license (for example, user may not upgrade from an express product class to an enterprise product class).
LIC010.Resolution: Verify this system may be upgraded to the product class specified by the license. If this system cannot be upgraded to the product class specified, obtain a new license file.
LIC010.Message: Import failed: This license is not for the specified device.

ISM0013.Description: The feature identified in the message is enabled by using the one of the iDRAC interfaces.

FC011.Description: Configuration job already created on the specified target. No further command is allowed until the existing job is completed.
FC011.Resolution: Cancel the configuration job or wait for the job to complete. Refer to documentation on job cancellation.
FC011.Message: Configuration job already created, pending data cannot be deleted.

BAR018.Description: A system profile backup file validation request has completed.

DH007.Resolution: Check that the private key parameter is correct. The passphrase can be validated against the private key, passphrase, and certificate can be validated using OpenSSL tools.
DH007.Message: The password unlocked the private key but it was the wrong private key.

HWC0010.Description: Operation failed because the folder name entered is incorrect or the USB drive is disconnected.
HWC0010.Resolution: Enter a valid folder name or attach the USB drive and retry the operation.
HWC0010.Message: Invalid folder name or USB drive not found.

USR8507.Message: %1 login was not successful (username=%2, ip=%3, error=0x%4)
USR8507.Resolution: Contact the administrator and ensure the username and password credentials used are correct. Retry the operation with valid credentials.
USR8507.Description: The login attempt with details specified in the message was not successful.

JCP033.Description: This job is newly created. This is the default message in a job when it has just been created.

PDR77.Message: %1 state changed from READY to Non-RAID.
PDR77.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PSU0044.Message: Cannot obtain status information from power supply %1.
PSU0044.Resolution: If problem persist, remove and re-install power supply.
PSU0044.Description: The power supply is operating but the system cannot get status information.

RAC0662.Description: Clear foreign configuration will delete the foreign virtual disk information from the controller's associated physical disk drives. Clearing will remove metadata associated with the virtual disks, making the physical disk drives available for creating new virtual disks. To remove foreign data, perform an initialization operation.
RAC0662.Message: The Clear Foreign Configuration operation will delete the foreign virtual disk information from the controller's associated physical disk drives. Clearing will remove metadata associated with the virtual disks, making the physical disk drives available for creating new virtual disks. To remove foreign data, perform an initialization operation.

PSU8511.Message: Successfully updated the firmware for the PSU in slot %1.
PSU8511.Description: The firmware for the PSU identified in the message was successfully updated.

SEL1502.Description: An action or failure has taken place that degrades CMC redundancy. This includes firmware mismatch between CMC's and a CMC missing SD card.
SEL1502.Resolution: Chassis management controller (CMC) redundancy is degraded.
SEL1502.Message: Chassis management controller (CMC) redundancy is degraded.

LC023.Description: Credentials or network share identity information provided did not result in a network connection being established.
LC023.Resolution: Check network share access credentials (IP address, user name, password, share type, and so on). Refer to Lifecycle Controller Profile documentation for more details.

RAC962.Description: Lifecycle Controller must be enabled to run the operation.
RAC962.Resolution: Enable the Lifecycle controller using the racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState 1 command, and retry the operation.
RAC962.Message: Unable to continue with the operation because Lifecycle Controller is in recovery state.

PSU0911.Message: Soft power control restored on power unit %1.

CMC8519.Message: The LOM riser FRU for slot %1 FRU ID %2 is not functioning.
CMC8519.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC of the specified server or virtual reseat the server. 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8519.Description: FRU of the LOM riser specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.

RAC0643.Description: The job could not be successfully scheduled, because an invalid value is entered for 'month' while scheduling a job.
RAC0643.Resolution: Enter a correct numerical value in the following format: Day [1 to 31] of every [1 to 12] month(s). For example, Day 4 of every 11 months. Retry the operation.
RAC0643.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid 'month' value is entered.

UEFI0140.Description: The System Service Mode (SSM) cannot be entered because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible. This situation is caused by missing LC partitions.
UEFI0140.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0140.Message: Unable to enter System Service Mode (SSM) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible.

RAC0636.Description: The requested network file share cannot be accessed, because an invalid proxy password is entered.
RAC0636.Resolution: Enter a valid proxy password, and then retry the operation.
RAC0636.Message: Unable to access the network file share, because an invalid proxy password is entered.

PSU0032.Message: The temperature for power supply %1 is in a warning range.
PSU0032.Resolution: Check the system operating environment, including airflow and inlet temperature. Check system logs for temperature and thermal component failures.

UEFI0153.Description: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology 2.0 (DPAT 2.0) Enterprise license. Related DPAT 2.0 BIOS settings will be lost if the license is not found in three consecutive reboots.
UEFI0153.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reload the license. 2) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 3) Update the iDRAC firmware.
UEFI0153.Message: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology (DPAT) Enterprise license. Related DPAT BIOS settings will be lost if the license is not found in three consecutive reboots.

CMC8514.Message: Fabric mismatch is detected in the I/O Module %1.
CMC8514.Resolution: Refer to Chassis Management Controller User's Guide for additional information.
CMC8514.Description: This error may occur due to any of the following conditions: 1) Invalid I/O Module and mezzanine card configuration, where a newly installed I/O Modules fabric type and the resident mezzanine cards fabric types do not match or are incompatible. 2) Invalid I/O Module and I/O Module configuration, where a newly installed I/O Module has a different or incompatible fabric type from an I/O Module already installed in the fabric.

RAC0224.Description: A partial string used to construct a complete error message.

ENC14.Message: The number of enclosures connected on %1 has exceeded the maximum limit supported by the controller.
ENC14.Resolution: Remove the extra enclosures. Refer to the storage hardware documentation for maximum number of enclosures that can be connected.
ENC14.Description: There are too many enclosures attached to the controller port. When the enclosure limit is exceeded, the controller loses contact with all enclosures attached to the port. This is an unsupported configuration.

RAC0710.Resolution: Ensure that the IO Module (IOM) and Mezzanine (Mezz) cards are appropriately matched. Check the M1000e Hardware Manual for correct component compatibility.

RED081.Description: The requested operation was not successful because an Automatic Update schedule already exists.
RED081.Resolution: Delete the existing Automatic Update schedule operation before retrying the operation.
RED081.Message: The Automatic Update schedule already exists.

RAC0902.Description: The syntax of the specified command is invalid. In this case, the usage of the -f option is invalid.
RAC0902.Resolution: See the help text/documentation for the valid syntax of the subcommand.
RAC0902.Message: The -f option requires -d to also be specified.

RED010.Resolution: Correct the target information and retry the operation.

SWC0233.Description: Indexed groups in the configuration file is more than the indexed groups in iDRAC.
SWC0233.Resolution: Verify if the number of indexed groups available in iDRAC match the indexed groups in the configuration file. If it does not match, either reset the unnecessary indexes on iDRAC or remove the extra groups from the configuration file.
SWC0233.Message: No indexes are available to configure additional groups.

PWR8655.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to turn on the component %1-%2 because of insufficient power. The minimum required power is %3 AC Watts, but only %4 AC Watts is available.
PWR8655.Resolution: Make sure there is sufficient power available, and then retry the operation. To view the available power, on the CMC Web interface, click Chassis Overview > Power > Power Budget Status. The available power is displayed in the Total Input Power Available For Allocation field. To increase available power, add more PSUs or remove unused components from the Chassis.
PWR8655.Description: CMC could not successfully turn on the component identified in the message, because of insufficient power available.

SYS045.Description: An error occurred while copying the Server Configuration Profile to the network share.
SYS045.Resolution: If the file is being exported to an NFS share, make sure that it is accessible from iDRAC. If the file is being exported to a CIFS share, make sure that it is accessible from iDRAC by using share access credentials with the appropriate privileges. If the share is by using http or https protocol, make sure that you have correctly configured the share and it can be accessible by using iDRAC.
SYS045.Message: Unable to copy the Server Configuration Profile to the network share.

VRM0011.Description: The Virtual Media server is already disconnected.
VRM0011.Message: The Virtual Media image server is not currently connected.

CPU0008.Resolution: If unexpected, check presence, and system setup (BIOS) configuration.
CPU0008.Description: System is unable to boot or may run in a degraded state.

PWR8678.Message: The value of the property %1 is %2.
PWR8678.Description: The power property identified in the message is changed as identified in the message.

RAC0508.Description: The server encountered an unexpected condition. This may be due to invalid JavaScript Object Notation.
RAC0508.Resolution: Wait for few minutes and refresh the page. If the problem persists, contact service provider.

OSD66.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'OSName' is missing.
OSD66.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "OSName" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD66.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'OSName' is missing.

UEFI0222.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0222.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0222.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Round Trip Training phase.

RAC0603.Description: The Job Queue is updated with the selected update jobs. The status of the update jobs can be viewed and managed within the Job Queue page.
RAC0603.Resolution: Click Job Queue button to view the status of the update jobs.
RAC0603.Message: Updating Job Queue. Status of the update jobs can be viewed and managed within the Job Queue page.

LC008.Description: The parameter value is not supported.
LC008.Resolution: Confirm that the parameters provided are correct. For a list of parameters for this method refer to the Lifecycle Controller User Guide.

USR0183.Description: A bezel with the iDRAC Quick Sync feature is detected.
USR0183.Message: A bezel with the iDRAC Quick Sync feature is detected.

UEFI0068.Description: The mezzanine card configuration used is not supported on this Chassis. Server modules used in different Chassis may require cards with different configuration properties. For more information, contact your service provider.
UEFI0068.Resolution: Make sure that a supported mezzanine card is used and retry the operation. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual of the Chassis available at the support site.
UEFI0068.Message: The mezzanine card configuration used is not supported on this Chassis.

RDU8501.Message: CMC%1: waiting to be reset by other CMC
RDU8501.Description: The Active CMC has detected a problem or a low memory condition. It is waiting for the Standby CMC to reset the Active CMC.

RAC1052.Description: The Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature is not enabled.
RAC1052.Resolution: To enable, run the RACADM command "racadm set lifecyclecontroller.lcattributes.autobackup 1".
RAC1052.Message: The Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature is not enabled.

VFL0011.Description: The vFlash media is not disabled.
VFL0011.Resolution: Disable the vFlash media by running the command 'racadm set idrac.vFlashSD.Enable 0'.

DIS107.Description: Unable to start the AutoConfig file import operation, because an invalid AutoConfig time-to-wait value is specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.
DIS107.Resolution: In the DHCP scope option field where VendorID=iDRAC, enter a time-to-wait (-t) value more than 300 seconds and less than 3600 seconds and then retry the operation.
DIS107.Message: Unable to start the AutoConfig file import operation, because an invalid AutoConfig time-to-wait value is specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

OSD49.Description: vFlash cannot be accessed because RIPS mode is enabled.
OSD49.Resolution: Disable the RIPS mode from BIOS or from the iDRAC GUI, and then continue executing the method.
OSD49.Message: Disable RIPS mode to access VFlash.

CMC8538.Description: The length of the CMC firmware version to be sent in the message from local CMC to peer CMC is too long. Under these conditions, CMC version in the message is displayed as 1.0.
CMC8538.Message: Firmware version string is too long.

SWU8559.Description: The firmware downgrade operation is unsuccessful. A downgrade to the firmware version uploaded is not supported.
SWU8559.Resolution: Refer to the platform Owner's Manual for more information or contact your service provider.
SWU8559.Message: The firmware downgrade operation is unsuccessful. A downgrade to the firmware version uploaded is not supported.

CMC8558.Description: The system health has recovered from a failover condition.

USR0180.Description: The Quick Sync feature is enabled because the activate button on the bezel was pressed.
USR0180.Message: The Quick Sync feature is enabled because the activate button on the bezel was pressed.

RAC0507.Description: The requested information cannot be displayed, because the system did not find any matching resource. This occurs because the system is turned off, resource is not present, or the resource is removed or deleted. For example, resources such as physicals disks, vFlash SD card, SSL certificate or custom signing certificate.
RAC0507.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Turn on the system. 2) Make the resource available.
RAC0507.Message: Unable to find the requested resource.

HWC7004.Message: Server %1 health changed to a critical state from either a normal or warning state.
HWC7004.Resolution: Review System Log or front panel for additional information.
HWC7004.Description: Server health changed to a critical state from either a normal or warning state.

PWR8523.Description: The chassis power cycle operation was completed.

SWC0117.Description: Invalid parameters passed to the function.
SWC0117.Resolution: Refer the help text for sslcertdownload subcommand.
SWC0117.Message: Invalid syntax. Both -f and -t must be specified.

RED045.Message: A recurring operation of type %1 was unable to create a job because the necessary user access rights are not available now.
RED045.Resolution: Use a username that has the necessary access rights and retry the operation.
RED045.Description: The necessary user access rights for performing the operation identified in the message were removed or the username was removed and the iDRAC is unable to create the next job in the sequence.

RAC0683.Description: Unable to perform split mode configuration on enclosure(s).
RAC0683.Resolution: Check the following: 1) The controller must have Real Time Configuration Capability and the associated enclosure(s) must have Split Mode Capability in order to perform the operation. 2)The controller(s) associated with the enclosure(s) support real time configuration. To verify the controller real time configuration support, go to the Controller Properties page, select the required controller and verify the Real Time Configuration Capability value.3)The enclosure(s) supports split mode configuration. To verify the enclosure, go to the Enclosure Properties page, select the required enclosure, and verify the Enclosure Split Mode Capability property value.
RAC0683.Message: Unable to perform split mode configuration on enclosure(s).

SYS227.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of the reason described by the code %2 sent by the proxy server.
SYS227.Resolution: View the proxy server documentation to resolve the issue. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SYS227.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of the reason described by the code identified in the message. For every unsuccessful file transfer, the proxy server returns an error code, where each code has a description about the reason for failure.

STOR031.Description: For 11G systems: System Services must be enabled to perform the requested operation. System Services has been disabled through the iDRAC configuration utility accessed by pressing CTRL+E on boot up or through a remote operation. For 12G and above generations: Lifecycle Controller must be enabled to perform the requested operation. Lifecycle Controller has been disabled by pressing F2 Setup, selecting iDRAC Configuration, and selecting Lifecycle Controller Settings on boot up or through a remote operation.
STOR031.Resolution: For 11G systems: Use the iDRAC configuration utility to enable the System Services by pressing on the CTRL+E option on boot up at the targeted system. For 12G and above generations: Use F2 Setup, select iDRAC Configuration, and select Lifecycle Controller Settings, to enable the Lifecycle Controller on boot up of the targeted system.

CMC8533.Message: Unable to read the FRU information, status = %1
CMC8533.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the server. The CMC will retry the read operation of the FRU information. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8533.Description: Unable to read the header of the extended FRU information. This can occur if there is a problem in the communication between the CMC and the server.

CTL110.Message: The Patrol Read Rate of %1 is set to %2.
CTL110.Description: The Patrol ReadRate of the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.

BAR107.Description: The vFlash media reader requires a license to function.
BAR107.Resolution: Obtain the license for vFlash media from your service provider. Install the license and retry the operation.
BAR107.Message: vFlash media reader license not present.

MEM0021.Message: Persistent correctable memory error limit reset for a memory device at location %1.

IOID118.Description: The iDRAC has applied I/O Identity Configuration on NIC and FC HBA devices. One or more of the setting configuration operations did not complete successfully.
IOID118.Resolution: Review the previous log entries and identify the devices that did not successfully complete configuration operations. For the identified devices, do the following and then restart the server: 1) Make sure the device is installed properly. 2) Make sure the device has latest firmware installed. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
IOID118.Message: Unable to configure some or all I/O Identity settings based on current persistence policy settings.

UEFI0163.Message: Unsupported DIMM module with less than 2Gb technology is installed on memory slot: %1.
UEFI0163.Resolution: Remove the unsupported DIMM module from the identified memory slot and replace it with a supported module. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0163.Description: Unsupported DIMM module with technology less than 2Gb is installed on the memory slot identified in the message.

PWR8568.Message: Server %1 did not gracefully shutdown before the timer expired.
PWR8568.Resolution: Check if the OS in the server identified in the message has successfully shutdown, if not, manually complete the shutdown or wait for the shutdown to complete normally. If the issue persists, perform a forced power down of the server identified in the message.
PWR8568.Description: The server identified in the message did not gracefully shutdown before the CMC shutdown timer expired. This happens if the server did not show power off status change within 60 seconds after the operation was initiated, or if the OS in the server has not successfully shutdown.

BIOS003.Description: An invalid number of arguments was passed to the method.
BIOS003.Resolution: Enter all the required command parameters. Check documentation and try again.
BIOS003.Message: Missing required parameter. Refer to the inserted comment.

RAC0659.Message: Unable to perform the storage configuration operation(s) on %1 because a job is currently pending or is running on the adapter.
RAC0659.Resolution: Wait for the job to completely run, or delete the job, and then retry the operation. To view the status of the scheduled jobs, go to the Job Queue page of iDRAC.
RAC0659.Description: The storage configuration operation(s) cannot be performed on the adapter identified in the message because a job is currently pending or is running on the adapter.

CTL117.Message: Unable to complete the operation because an invalid passphrase is passed for the controller %1.
CTL117.Resolution: Enter a valid passphrase and retry the operation.
CTL117.Description: The operation cannot be completed because an invalid passphrase is passed for the controller identified in the message.

SWC0214.Message: Makes a remote ISO image available to the server

LIC009.Description: An upgrade license carries specific information about the license it is replacing. If that information does not match, then the license import is aborted.
LIC009.Resolution: Obtain a new license file with the correct upgrade information.

UEFI0233.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0233.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0233.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Write Leveling Training - FIFO Reset phase.

PDR108.Message: The physical disk drive %1 is unassigned as a global hot spare.
PDR108.Resolution: No response action is required. Assigning a new global hot spare is recommended.
PDR108.Description: The physical disk identified in the message that had been assigned as a hot spare has been unassigned and is no longer functioning as a hot spare. The physical disk was unassigned by a user or automatically by the storage management software. When one of the disks in a virtual disk fails, data is rebuilt onto the hot spare, The hot spare becomes a member of the virtual disk and is no longer assigned as a hot spare. In this situation, assigning a new hot spare to maintain data protection in recommended.

PDR1019.Message: Drive %1 in disk drive bay %2 is no longer the hot-spare drive.

SWC0067.Description: The location of the operating system configuration file specified in the operation is not valid.
SWC0067.Resolution: Make sure that the specified source file path is correct and retry the operation.
SWC0067.Message: Unable to import operating system configuration file.

SWC0124.Description: The syntax of the sslcsrgen command is invalid.
SWC0124.Resolution: Refer the help text for sslcsrgen subcommand.
SWC0124.Message: The -u option requires -f to be specified.

SWC8507.Description: A new Profile identified in the message has been created.

RAC0238.Description: vFlash is unable to service the request at this time. Try again later.
RAC0238.Resolution: Try the operation after a few minutes.
RAC0238.Message: vFlash is currently in-use by another process. Try again later.

RDU8509.Message: CMC%1: cannot failover, chassis is in non-redundant state
RDU8509.Resolution: Check the status of the standby CMC and make sure the firmware version matches the primary CMC. Then reseat the CMC and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RDU8509.Description: For failover to occur, the standby CMC needs to be present, at the same version as the primary and healthy. During failover, the active CMC resets and the standby CMC becomes active. This message is logged when the standby CMC is absent, unhealthy or at a different firmware version.

RAC918.Description: Racadm unable to obtain the inlet temperature data. This happens if there is no data populated in the temperature tables or if the underlying instrumentation does not return valid values.
RAC918.Resolution: Wait for the underlying instrumentation to populate the thermal tables. Retry the operation.
RAC918.Message: Unable to get the inlet temperature data.

SEC0605.Message: A setup password violation was corrected.

SEC0608.Description: This may apply to a physical or remote access attempt.
SEC0608.Resolution: Check system logs for intrusion attempts, and ensure strong password policies.

SWC8616.Message: Server in slot %1 is not ready to be accessed remotely because of one or more of the following reasons: 1) iDRAC is not ready. 2) Lifecycle Controller for of the server is disabled.
SWC8616.Resolution: Make sure that the iDRAC on the server identified in the message is operating properly and that Lifecycle Controller is enabled, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, perform a virtual reseat of the server and retry the operation. The server can be virtually reseated by using the CMC Web GUI interface and selecting Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components and then selecting Virtual Reseat from the drop down menu.
SWC8616.Description: The server identified in the message cannot be accessed remotely by iDRAC because of one or more of the following reasons: 1) iDRAC is not ready. 2) Lifecycle Controller for of the server is disabled.

TMP0300.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is enabled.
TMP0300.Message: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is enabled.

OSE1004.Description: The system OS has successfully booted from the PXE server.

HWC2006.Resolution: Check presence, then re-install or reconnect.
HWC2006.Description: The device may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.

HWC0016.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to communicate with iDRAC.
HWC0016.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.

PWR8669.Message: Unable to turn on the server %1 because of an inconsistency between the chassis and server components.
PWR8669.Resolution: Make sure that the chassis PCIe components and mezzanine card are compatible. For information about compatibility of hardware components, see the Modular System Chassis Hardware Manual available at the support site.
PWR8669.Description: The server identified in the message could not be successfully turned on because of incompatibility between the chassis PCIe components and mezzanine card.

RAC0711.Description: Unknown power on response from the CMC.
RAC0711.Resolution: Try resetting the CMC. Also try resetting the server.
RAC0711.Message: Unknown power on response from the CMC.

PR18.Message: Firmware version difference detected for device: %1
PR18.Description: The Part Replacement feature has detected a firmware difference between the current and previous components. Depending on the Part Firmware Update setting value this may cause a firmware update to the replaced part.

BAT1029.Message: The battery on %1 can no longer recharge.
BAT1029.Description: The controller battery cannot recharge. The battery may have already recharged the maximum number of times or the battery charger may not be working.

SWC0042.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to retrieve the status of the Import Server Profile operation.
SWC0042.Resolution: Exit the Import Server Profile wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, do the following: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0042.Message: Unable to retrieve the status of the Import Server Profile operation.

VLT0102.Message: Processor module %1 voltage is greater than the upper warning threshold.
VLT0102.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Remove the processor module. Inspect processor socket for bent pins. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0102.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

CPU0804.Message: The power input for CPU %1 voltage regulator module is outside of range.
CPU0804.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
CPU0804.Description: System performance may be degraded or the system may fail to operate.

SYS259.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because the resume value is not supported.
SYS259.Resolution: Make sure that the resume value is correct and retry the operation.
SYS259.Description: The file cannot be transferred because the resume value is not supported.

OSD28.Description: Hash verification on the ISO image has failed. The hash value specified in the command is either incorrect or the ISO image has been changed.
OSD28.Resolution: 1) Verify that the hash value specified in the command is correct. 2) Make sure that the ISO has not been changed 3) Replace the ISO image on the share and rerun the command.
OSD28.Message: Hash verification on the ISO image failed.

LC050.Description: The value provided to set the attribute identified in the message is invalid.
LC050.Resolution: For more information on the valid values, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation. Retry the operation with a valid value for the SystemServicesState attribute.

HWC0005.Description: Internal error while retrieving firmware version for the currently installed components. For more information about the failure, see Lifecycle Log.
HWC0005.Resolution: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
HWC0005.Message: Internal error while retrieving update information.

JCP016.Description: The UntilTime input parameter for the job or job queue creation must be at least 5 minutes after the value specified in the StartTime parameter.
JCP016.Resolution: Set the UntilTime at least 5 minutes after StartTime and retry the operation.
JCP016.Message: Invalid UntilTime value. A minimum of 5 minutes is required.

HWC7014.Description: An invalid cable related hardware configuration detected on the system.
HWC7014.Resolution: Make sure the hardware and related cables are installed correctly. For information about configuration and installation procedures, see the system's Owners Manual available at the support site.
HWC7014.Message: An invalid cable or incorrect cable configuration is detected.

CTL67.Message: Attempted to import Virtual Disk with missing span on %1.
CTL67.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC0152.Description: While the system is powered off it is unable to retrieve information about power supplies.
RAC0152.Resolution: Turn the system on to view this information.
RAC0152.Message: Unable to retrieve the power supply information. The system is powered off.

TMP0126.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.
TMP0126.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0126.Message: Disk drive bay temperature is greater than the upper warning threshold.

FAN0012.Message: %1 RPM is less than the lower warning threshold.
FAN0012.Resolution: Remove and re-install the device at the next scheduled service. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0012.Description: The device is not performing optimally. The device may be installed improperly.

OSD13.Description: iDRAC was unable to mount the drivers as a USB device for the OS installation to proceed.
OSD13.Resolution: 1) Rerun the command. 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD13.Message: Cannot mount the USB device needed to copy drivers for the selected operating system.

SWC0289.Message: Invalid value in config file. Group: %1, Object: %2, Value: \"%3\", Line [%4}
SWC0289.Resolution: Configure the specified object and assign a valid value.
SWC0289.Description: The specified object value is invalid.

UEFI0160.Message: The number of DIMM ranks has exceeded the maximum allowed ranks per channel limit on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0160.Resolution: Check the total number of ranks in the channel to make sure it does not exceed the maximum allowed limit. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0160.Description: The number of DIMM ranks has exceeded the maximum allowed ranks per channel limit.

RED018.Description: Reinstall or Rollback not supported for this device.
RED018.Resolution: 1. Update the device directly using the update methods since rollback is not supported for this device. 2. Verify that the target specified in the command is correct.
RED018.Message: Reinstall or Rollback not supported for this device.

CTL48.Message: A foreign configuration was detected on %1.
CTL48.Resolution: Import or clear the detected foreign configuration using a configuration tool or utility.
CTL48.Description: The controller has physical disks that were moved from another controller or have been removed and replaced on the current configuration. These physical disks contain virtual disks that were created on the current or other controller. See the storage hardware documentation for Import Foreign Configuration and Clear Foreign Configuration for more information. Foreign configuration is seen when a controller is replaced.

SYS197.Message: Unable to install the OEM ID module because of some issues. %1
SYS197.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle Log report to analyze the issue, resolve the issue, and then retry the installation process.
SYS197.Description: The OEM ID module cannot be installed because of some issues.

RAC953.Description: The comment was added to the specified entry in the Lifecycle Log.
RAC953.Resolution: View the added comment using the racadm lclog view q <seq. no> -n 1 command.

BOOT003.Description: This operation is not supported on the current configuration.
BOOT003.Resolution: This operation is not supported on the current configuration, check documentation and try again.

PDR69.Resolution: Remove drive, insert correct protocol type, and force a rebuild as imposed for controller and system.
PDR69.Description: Physical disk inserted is of the incorrect protocol. SAS or SATA mixing is not supported in the same virtual disk.

SWC0279.Description: The group is not indexed and does not require an index to be specified.
SWC0279.Resolution: Enter the command without the index.
SWC0279.Message: The specified group is not indexed and does not support -i.

PR6.Message: Configuration changes successfully applied to device: %1
PR6.Description: The configuration values stored for the previous device were applied to the current device.

RAC039.Resolution: Verify the value for the specified parameter. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
RAC039.Description: The value provided for the specified parameter is invalid.

STOR061.Description: The initializing virtual disk operation is not supported on the target device.
STOR061.Resolution: For more information about supported operations, see the documentation specific for the targeted RAID controller or the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Quick Start Guide.
STOR061.Message: Initializing virtual disk is not supported on the RAID controller.

SWC0320.Description: Racadm tool failed to get the total number of records.
SWC0320.Message: Unable to get the number of records available.

CTL114.Message: The encryption key of %1 matches with its peer controller.
CTL114.Description: The encryption key for the controller identified in the message matches with its peer.

RAC0223.Description: The Subject line in the email contains invalid characters.
RAC0223.Resolution: Invalid character. Enter a valid value as mentioned in the online help.
RAC0223.Message: Enter an alphanumeric value or a valid symbol for the following (see the online help for more information).

RAC1158.Description: The requested number of Lifecycle log entries exceed the limit and cannot be displayed. The remote RACADM operation may time out before retrieving all the log entries.
RAC1158.Resolution: Retrieve a smaller number of log entries using remote RACADM or use firmware or local RACADM to view all the log entries. To retrieve a limited number of log entries, use the -n option. For example, to view the last 10 log entries, run the command 'racadm lclog view -n 10'.
RAC1158.Message: The requested number of log entries exceeds the limit.

SYS142.Description: The OS driver pack is deleted because of a System Erase operation.
SYS142.Message: The OS driver pack is deleted.

USR0175.Message: The Front Panel USB Port Over Current is detected for the attached device on Disk.USBFront.%1.
USR0175.Resolution: Reinsert the USB device in the Front Panel USB Port and retry the operation. If the issue persists, use a different USB device.
USR0175.Description: The USB device attached to the port identified in the message is drawing more current than is supported by the port.

MEM7000.Message: The memory riser mismatch was corrected.

DKM1001.Message: The key management service is operating correctly.

RAC0612.Description: Cancelling the firmware update operation will cancel all firmware updates selected and delete all uploaded firmware files.
RAC0612.Resolution: Select Yes to cancel the firmware update operation and delete all uploaded firmware files. Select No to dismiss the message and continue the firmware update operation.
RAC0612.Message: Cancelling the firmware update operation will delete all the uploaded firmware files. Do you want to continue?

STOR069.Message: Unable to run the %1 method, because the number of elements entered for VDPropNameArray and VDPropValueArray is unequal.
STOR069.Resolution: Enter equal number of elements (pair value), and then retry the operation.
STOR069.Description: The method name identified in the message could not be successfully completed, because the number of elements entered for VDPropNameArray and VDPropValueArray is not equal.

LC059.Message: Cannot set read only attribute specified in AttributeName %1.
LC059.Description: The attribute specified is read only and the value cannot be changed.

CMC8525.Message: The FRU on the sleeve %1 is not functioning.
CMC8525.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC of the specified server or virtual reseat the server. 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8525.Description: The FRU on the sleeve specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.

AMP0308.Message: Disk drive bay %1 current is greater than the upper warning threshold.
AMP0308.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0308.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.

SEL1206.Message: An entry was added to auxiliary log.

TMP0118.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0118.Message: The system inlet temperature is less than the lower warning threshold.

SWC0080.Description: iDRAC exited from Integrated Data Center Troubleshooting Mode. Integrated Data Center may revert some of the network settings made by the user while in Troubleshooting Mode.
SWC0080.Message: iDRAC exited from Integrated Data Center Troubleshooting Mode.

USR0032.Message: The session for %1 from %2 using %3 is logged off.
USR0032.Description: The session for the username, IP address, and interface identified in the message is logged off.

RAC0135.Description: A separate message will provide more detail about this error which was detected while detaching the vFlash partition.
RAC0135.Message: An error has occurred while detaching a partition.

SYS169.Description: The iDRAC Service Module installed on the operating system is not up to date and does not support the Technical Support Report.
SYS169.Resolution: Make sure the operating system (OS) is a supported OS for the Technical Support Report feature and the latest iDRAC Service Module software is installed on the OS.
SYS169.Message: The iDRAC Service Module installed on the operating system is not up to date and does not support the Technical Support Report feature.

MEM9014.Message: A correctable memory error has occurred in Dual In-line Memory Module (DIMM) device %1.
MEM9014.Resolution: This is a correctable error. Review log information and if multiple correctable errors have occurred on the DIMM identified in the message, re-install the memory device. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
MEM9014.Description: The memory device identified in the message has encountered a correctable memory error. This may be an early indicator of a possible future uncorrectable error.

JCP010.Description: The method invoked was successfully completed.

SYS426.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the value %1 entered for the property %2 is not in the list of acceptable values.
SYS426.Resolution: Enter a valid value from the enumeration list that Redfish service supports and retry the operation.For information about valid values, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
SYS426.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the value entered for the property identified in the message is not in the enumeration list.

SYS253.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because the remote host server or remote host file system is set to read-only mode.
SYS253.Resolution: Make sure that the file transfer parameters and the remote host file system properties are correct, and then retry the operation.
SYS253.Description: The file cannot be transferred because the remote host server or remote host file system is set to read-only mode.

SWC1905.Description: RAC Virtual Console configuration has been changed.
SWC1905.Message: RAC Virtual Console configuration has been changed.

RAC1177.Description: A USB device is attached to the iDRAC and accessible from the iDRAC.
RAC1177.Resolution: No response action is required. To attach the USB device to the server instead of the iDRAC, remove the USB device from the front panel USB port, change the USB Management Port mode settings and then reinsert the USB device.
RAC1177.Message: A USB device is attached to the iDRAC.

STOR068.Description: The requested RAID configuration operation did not succeed because the Lifecycle Controller version on the target server does not have the necessary capabilities.
STOR068.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle Controller version on the target server and update it with the latest version available.
STOR068.Message: Unable to perform the requested RAID configuration because the Lifecycle Controller version on the server does not have the necessary capabilities.

RAC015.Message: Unable to run the method because the input value is not one of the possible values for AttributeName %1.
RAC015.Resolution: Provide valid attribute value for the attribute identified in the message and retry the operation.
RAC015.Description: The input attribute value is not valid for the attribute identified in the message.

SYS083.Description: Unable to export ePSA Diagnostics results because iDRAC internal storage could not be accessed.
SYS083.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Delete all jobs, 2) Reset iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for at least 15 seconds, and 3) Retry the operation.
SYS083.Message: Unable to export ePSA Diagnostics results because iDRAC internal storage could not be accessed.

RAC1111.Description: Unable to clear pending values or operations from the specified storage device because there are no pending operations for the specified device.
RAC1111.Message: Unable to delete the pending values or operations of the specified device.

CMC8512.Description: The Extended Storage feature is not activated if the removable flash media SD card on the secondary CMC does not respond within 90 seconds after activation is initiated.
CMC8512.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) In the CMC Web interface, go to Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration, and verify if the SD card on secondary CMC displays errors. 2) If errors are displayed, execute the following racadm command: "racadm cmcchangeover". 3) Repair the removable flash media SD Card by selecting the Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration > Repair Active Controller Media in the CMC Web interface. Repairing is only allowed on the SD card of the primary CMC. If the problem persists, replace the card.
CMC8512.Message: The Extended Storage feature activation timed out. The feature is not active.

DKM1004.Resolution: Check for network connectivity. Review network, server, and client configuration.
DKM1004.Message: The key management server received a bad request.

STOR073.Description: The iDRAC Service Module version present on the server OS does not support the requested PCIe SSD (NVMe) device operation.
STOR073.Resolution: Update the Dell iDRAC Service Module (ISM) to the version that supports the requested operation on the PCIe SSD (NVMe) device.
STOR073.Message: The iDRAC Service Module version present on the server OS does not support the requested PCIe SSD (NVMe) device operation.

SYS419.Description: The operation cannot be successfully completed because the Redfish attribute is disabled.
SYS419.Resolution: Make sure that the Redfish.1.Enable attribute is set to Enabled by running the HTTP PATCH method on "Managers OemAttributes" Redfish API, and then retry the operation.
SYS419.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the Redfish attribute is disabled.

SUP1909.Resolution: Check that the image is available and retry the operation.

VLT0206.Message: The memory module %1 %2 voltage is less than the lower warning threshold.
VLT0206.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0206.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

IOV001.Description: The operation or operation parameter sent to the Chassis Manager is invalid or not supported.
IOV001.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to Chassis Manager product documentation to determine the contact method for the service provider.
IOV001.Message: The operation contains an invalid request or argument.

SWC0062.Description: The destination folder is not present, the destination is full or write-protected.
SWC0062.Resolution: Verify the following and retry the operation:1) Destination folder is present.2) Destination has enough free space.3) Destination is not write-protected.If the problem persists, perform an AC power cycle and retry.

SWC0146.Message: Last ASR screen was cleared successfully

PWR8665.Description: The property chassis power button is either enabled or disabled as identified in the message.

SWC8541.Description: The Profile identified in the message is imported.

POW002.Description: Host failed to power up because unsupported components installed in Fabric1/fabric2.This messages has been replaced by Message ID PWR2252.
POW002.Resolution: Check for unsupported components installed in Fabric1/Fabric2.
POW002.Message: Power on permission error, unknown component installed in Fabric1/Fabric2.

RAC005.Description: The name value pairs do not match in the input specified in the method invocation parameters.
RAC005.Message: Mismatch in AttributeName and AttributeValue count.

PSU8502.Message: The PSU in slot %1 detected 110 VAC input voltage and does not match chassis configuration.
PSU8502.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Check the power configuration "Allow 110 VAC Operation" setting and make sure it is enabled. 2) Check if the input voltage of all the PSUs are the same. 3) If the input voltage of the PSU specified in the message is not the same, then remove the unmatched PSU.
PSU8502.Description: The input voltage of the PSU specified in the message does not match the input voltage of the PSUs already present in the chassis.

RRDU0003.Description: Either one of the SD card or both the SD cards are not functioning properly.
RRDU0003.Message: Internal Dual SD Module redundancy is degraded.

RAC063.Message: The string length of the provided value for %1 is inappropriate.
RAC063.Resolution: Make sure that the string length is correct and retry the operation.
RAC063.Description: The string length of the entered value for the attribute identified in the message may be less than the minimum length or greater than the maximum length allowed.

CTL95.Message: %1 has left the fault tolerant pair.
CTL95.Resolution: This situation may resolve itself in a few minutes. If the situation does not resolve itself or this message is repeated, contact your service provider.
CTL95.Description: The controller identified in the message has stopped operating in a fault tolerant mode.

LC054.Description: The network share may be read-only or it may not have sufficient space for the export operation.
LC054.Resolution: Verify the network share is not read-only and has sufficient space for exporting, then retry the operation.
LC054.Message: Unable to write to the network share.

CMC8504.Message: Unable to access server: %1, because the NIC is disabled on the identified server.
CMC8504.Resolution: Enable the NIC on the server identified in the message using the CMC command line or CMC Web interface, so that the link to launch iDRAC is displayed on the CMC Web interface. To enable the NIC for DHCP using RACADM, enter "racadm setniccfg -m server-<slot number> -d" where <slot number> is the server identified in the message. To enable the NIC using the Web interface, click Server Overview > select the identified server, go to Setup > select the Enable LAN check box.
CMC8504.Description: The NIC is disabled on the server identified in the message, and the CMC is unable to display the link to launch the iDRAC web interface.

USR0005.Resolution: Contact the iDRAC administrator and ensure the username and password credentials used are correct.
USR0005.Description: Login failed from UserID: IP Address.

VRM0009.Description: No virtual media was found to disconnect.
VRM0009.Message: No Virtual Media devices are currently connected.

PDR115.Resolution: Back up the data on the device, and contact your service provider for further instructions.
PDR115.Description: The PCIe solid state device identified in the message is in read-only mode.

SWC8520.Message: Unable to modify user name from %1 to %2: %3-%4
SWC8520.Resolution: Make sure: 1) The login credentials for the operation have user config administration privilege, 2) The user name given is valid. If the issue persists, restart the CMC and retry the operation.
SWC8520.Description: Unable to modify the user name specified in the message.

SUP0110.Description: The firmware update is being uninitialized.
SUP0110.Message: Uninitializing firmware update services. Please wait.

RAC922.Description: The specified path (specified with the l parameter) for the remote share is too long. This path should be less than 256 characters in length.
RAC922.Resolution: Try the same command with a different remote share location, which is less than 256 characters in length.

OSD55.Description: Cannot attach the ISO image since it is already attached to the host.
OSD55.Resolution: ISO Image is already attached to the host server. Detach the ISO and then rerun the command.
OSD55.Message: ISO Image is attached to host

OSD7.Description: Unable to connect to Lifecycle Controller because of an existing open connection or an internal error.
OSD7.Resolution: Reset iDRAC, and rerun the command to correct the problem.
OSD7.Message: Unable to retrieve Lifecycle Controller handle.

VDR14.Message: The consistency check on %1 was cancelled.
VDR14.Description: A user cancelled the consistency check operation for a virtual disk.

LIC001.Description: The command or command parameters passed to License Manager is invalid. This is an internal error indicative of memory corruption. Under normal circumstances this error should not occur.
LIC001.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
LIC001.Message: The License Manager command parameter used is invalid.

PWR2257.Message: The target power allocation override is %1. The target power allocation (AC) is %2 Watts.
PWR2257.Description: The target power allocation override has been enabled or disabled as identified in the message.

STOR078.Description: The requested operation cannot be performed because it involves server reboot type which is different than the reboot type of pending operations. Combining operations with different reboot types for the same RAID controller is not supported by iDRAC.
STOR078.Resolution: Cancel any pending operations on the RAID controller and then retry the operation.
STOR078.Message: The requested operation requires a reboot type that does not match the reboot type required for pending operations.

SYS246.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported proxy password value.
SYS246.Resolution: Make sure that the correct proxy password value is entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS246.Description: The file cannot be transferred because a proxy password value is not entered, or the entered value is not supported.

PWR8530.Description: Max Power Conservation Mode is disabled.
PWR8530.Message: Max Power Conservation Mode is disabled.

PR1.Message: A replacement part was detected for device: %1
PR1.Description: The specified device has been replaced.

RAC0679.Description: Unable to process the request because a job operation is already running.
RAC0679.Resolution: Wait until the running job is completed or delete the scheduled job and retry the operation.
RAC0679.Message: A job operation is already running. Retry the operation after the existing job is completed.

RFL2003.Message: Internal Dual SD Module %1 is online.

RAC041.Description: The event filters set operation did not complete successfully due to invalid input parameters.
RAC041.Resolution: Verify the specified input parameters and retry the operation. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
RAC041.Message: The set operation on the event filters failed.

PST0144.Description: System BIOS is unable to load the required BIOS files.
PST0144.Resolution: Remove and reapply power to server. If the problem persists, contact your server provider. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PST0144.Message: Unable to load required BIOS files.

SWC0159.Message: Kerberos Keytab successfully uploaded to the RAC.

UEFI0063.Description: An attribute cannot be successfully configured because of an issue in the ACI data block.
UEFI0063.Resolution: Check the ACI data block for any invalid configuration data and settings, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0063.Message: Unable to change an attribute because of issues in the Attribute Configuration Interface (ACI) data block.

SWC0305.Description: The syntax of the fwupdate command is invalid.
SWC0305.Resolution: Refer the help text for fwupdate subcommand.
SWC0305.Message: The -p option requires -u to also be specified.

MEM1014.Message: Memory device at location %1 is in a power save state.

SEL1513.Description: The iDRAC communication link to Chassis Controller is restored. Any issues related to network communication between Chassis Controller and iDRAC, incorrectly seated Chassis Controller, or unavailability of Chassis Controller is now resolved successfully.
SEL1513.Message: The status of Chassis Controller has changed from critical to OK.

PCI2001.Message: The component at bus %1 device %2 function %3 recovered from a fatal IO error.

PCI1316.Message: A bus uncorrectable error was detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.
PCI1316.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1316.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.

RAC0658.Description: The iDRAC Service Module service can now be started on the server operating system. This service needs to be started manually on the server operating system.
RAC0658.Message: The iDRAC Service Module service can now be manually started on the server operating system.

UEFI0124.Description: The size and speed of the primary SD card do not match those of the secondary SD card. The secondary SD card needs to have equal or greater capacity and speed than the primary SD card.
UEFI0124.Resolution: Replace the secondary SD card with one that has equal or greater capacity and speed than the primary SD card.
UEFI0124.Message: The size and speed of the secondary SD card do not match those of the primary SD card.

RAC0642.Description: The job could not be successfully scheduled, because an invalid value is entered for 'day' of a month while scheduling a job.
RAC0642.Resolution: Enter a correct numerical value in the following format: Day [1 to 31] of every [1 to 12] month(s). For example, Day 4 of every 11 months. Retry the operation.
RAC0642.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid value is entered for the 'day' of a month.

SWC0221.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0221.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0221.Message: The -l option requires -c to also be specified.

CTL30.Message: The Check Consistency rate has changed for %1.
CTL30.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SWC0260.Description: The value of specified parameter is invalid.
SWC0260.Resolution: Refer the list of objects in the corresponding group.

SWC0016.Description: The operating system driver pack is missing or not accessible.
SWC0016.Resolution: Exit the OS Deployment wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, exit Lifecycle Controller and retry the operation.
SWC0016.Message: Unable to initialize OS Deployment wizard.

RAC0240.Description: vFlash needs to be enabled before attempting this operation.
RAC0240.Resolution: Enable vFlash before trying the operation.

LIC203.Message: The license %1 has encountered an error.
LIC203.Resolution: Delete and re-import the license file.
LIC203.Description: Signature verification failed due to an error in the saved license file.

PST0008.Description: System BIOS has started System Management Mode (SMM) initialization.

CTL8.Message: Bad block extended sense error on %1.
CTL8.Resolution: See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.
CTL8.Description: A portion of a physical disk is damaged. See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.

RAC981.Description: A passphrase is required only for passphrase protected certificate, which is specified using the value of 3 for the -t option.
RAC981.Resolution: If the file being uploaded is passphrase protected, specify the file type as 3 using the -t option. If the file is not passphrase protected, retry the command, without specifying the -p option.
RAC981.Message: The type of certificate specified does not require a passphrase.

SYS010.Message: Invalid character in value for attribute: %1
SYS010.Resolution: Refer to Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation and provide valid attribute value for the specified attribute.
SYS010.Description: The input value for the specified attribute is not valid.

SWC4012.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility is detected between %1%2 and %3%4.
SWC4012.Resolution: Update the firmware or software of the components identified in the message. For information about the identified components, see the product documentation available at the service provider support site.
SWC4012.Description: The system has detected a firmware or software incompatibility between the components identified in the message. A mismatch between component versions may cause the system to not function appropriately.

PWR8554.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to send power allocation information to %1-%2 at priority %3.
PWR8554.Resolution: Perform a Virtual Reseat of the component identified in the message. Using the CMC Web UI, go to Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components, and then select slot for the component identified in the message and apply the Virtual Reseat.
PWR8554.Description: This situation occurs if the iDRAC is found to be turned off after power allocation information is sent by the CMC or if the communications between the CMC and iDRAC is non functional.

PST0088.Description: System BIOS is preparing to boot the system.

RAC1050.Description: One or more required options to configure the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature are missing.
RAC1050.Resolution: For more information, view the help details by running the RACADM command "racadm help systemconfig backup".
RAC1050.Message: Unable to configure the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings. The required options are either invalid or not provided.

OSD42.Description: There was an error while copying the ISO image from the network share to the vFlash.
OSD42.Resolution: 1) Make sure the network connection is working. 2) Make sure the Dell vFlash does not have any hardware issues by accessing it through the iDRAC GUI.
OSD42.Message: Downloading ISO File to VFlash failed.

RAC0911.Resolution: Try again later. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
RAC0911.Message: Data about version details is unavailable.

SYS038.Description: Unable to locate the configuration data associated with the job.
SYS038.Resolution: Retry the operation. If this issue persists, contact your service provider.

FC009.Description: Lifecycle Controller cannot gain access to internal storage due to use by another application or operation.
FC009.Resolution: Wait for Lifecycle Controller to complete the current operation. Make sure that the system is: 1) Not currently in Lifecycle Controller Unified Server Configurator 2) Not waiting for user intervention at F1/F2 POST error 3) Not in any of the device or controller Option ROMs and retry the operation.
FC009.Message: Lifecycle Controller is currently in use.

CTL25.Message: Auto Copyback on Predictive Failure has changed for %1.
CTL25.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

CPU0000.Description: System event log and OS logs may indicate the source of the error.
CPU0000.Resolution: Review System Event Log and Operating System Logs. These logs can help the user identify the possible issue that is producing the problem.
CPU0000.Message: Internal error has occurred check for additional logs.

SWU8531.Description: The firmware update operation is not successful, because the Update process was not completed within the firmware update timeout duration.
SWU8531.Message: Unable to update the iKVM firmware. The firmware update timeout limit is exceeded.

PCI1346.Message: A software error was detected on a component at slot %1.
PCI1346.Resolution: Reboot the system and update the component drivers.

HWC1105.Message: The %1 is removed from the slot %2.
HWC1105.Description: The peripheral sled identified in the message is removed from the unsupported slot identified in the message.

BAR098.Description: The Service Tag installed on the system is invalid. The Backup and Restore feature will not operate without a valid Service Tag.

PSU8524.Description: The system power is automatically recovered because of an AC brownout in the power supply unit (PSU).
PSU8524.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Make sure that the system load is within the power capacity of power supply unit (PSU) and no short circuit exists.2) Make sure that the AC input to the PSU is correct. For information about input voltage specifications, see the "CMC Technical Guide". 3) Disconnect the power supply and reconnect. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PSU8524.Message: The system power is automatically recovered because of an AC brownout in the power supply unit (PSU).

RED071.Description: Unable to get the Automatic Backup schedule information because the schedule is not configured.
RED071.Message: Unable to get the Automatic Backup schedule information.

PWR8683.Message: Initiated the Virtual Reseat of peripheral %1.
PWR8683.Description: A Virtual Reseat for the peripheral sled identified in the message is initiated. A Virtual Reseat is the same as removing and inserting a peripheral sled.

LC049.Description: The value provided to set the attribute identified in the message is invalid.
LC049.Resolution: For more information on the valid values, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation. Retry the operation with a valid value for the VirtualAddressManagement attribute.

SWC8547.Description: Some or all of the Media Access Control (MAC) addresses cannot be added to the pool because they are already present in the MAC address pool.
SWC8547.Message: Unable to add some of the Media Access Control (MAC) addresses because the MAC addresses are already present in the MAC address pool of Boot Identity profile operations.

RAC1065.Description: Unable to initiate the SystemErase operation because iDRAC encountered an internal issue.
RAC1065.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and then retry the operation after the iDRAC has finished restarting.
RAC1065.Message: Unable to initiate the SystemErase operation because iDRAC encountered an internal issue.

TMP0112.Message: The %1 temperature is less than the lower warning threshold.
TMP0112.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.

VLT0301.Message: CPU %1 %2 voltage is less than the lower critical threshold.
VLT0301.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0301.Description: Low voltages may be the result of a problem with the voltage regulator or a problem with the processor. When the critical threshold is crossed, the processor will fail to operate. The system may power down.

SEC0044.Description: TXT initialization cannot be completed because system configuration may have changed.
SEC0044.Resolution: Check system hardware inventory for TPM presence, clear and reconfigure TPM and TXT in BIOS setup menu.
SEC0044.Message: SINIT Authenticated Code Module detected an Intel Trusted Execution Technology (TXT) problem at boot.

UEFI0088.Message: Unsupported 8Gb technology DIMM module is installed on memory slot: %1.
UEFI0088.Resolution: Remove the unsupported DIMM module from the identified memory slot and replace it with a supported module. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0088.Description: Unsupported 8Gb technology DIMM module is installed on the memory slot identified in the message.

PWR8566.Message: Unable to turn off the Server %1 before the Power Off timer expired.
PWR8566.Resolution: The Server may need more time to turn off. Wait for ten seconds and check the power status. If the Server was not turned off, retry the operation. If the issue persists, remove and reinsert the Server, wait for the iDRAC to complete startup, and retry the operation.
PWR8566.Description: Unable to turn off the Server before the Power Off timer has expired. This happens if the Server did not show "power off" status change within 30 seconds after the operation was initiated. This situation may also occur when iDRAC is rebooting.

SWC8601.Message: Quick Deploy Profile unable to apply profile %1 to server %2
SWC8601.Resolution: Recreate source profile or choose a different one.
SWC8601.Description: The source profile is not correct in form or content.

RED067.Description: The recurring scheduled update from repository job completed and updates were staged. The system will now restart to apply the staged updates.
RED067.Message: The recurring scheduled update from repository job completed and updates were staged. The system will now restart to apply the staged updates.

UEFI0025.Description: The Management Engine firmware cannot be initialized. The BIOS will reset the system to retry the initialization process.
UEFI0025.Resolution: Wait for the BIOS to reset the system and reinitialize the Management Engine. If the issue persists, turn off the input power to the system and turn on again.
UEFI0025.Message: Unable to initialize Management Engine firmware.

RED006.Description: The Update Package cannot be successfully downloaded.
RED006.Resolution: Check the network connection and access to the update package from the iDRAC.

MEM9003.Message: Intel SMI 2 Memory interconnect %1 has a correctable error.
