MEM9003.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reseat the memory riser and restart the server. 2) If the issue is not resolved by preceding action, reseat the processor and restart the server. 3) If the issue persists, contact your services provider.
MEM9003.Description: A correctable error was detected in propagation of signals between processor and memory through the Intel SMI 2 memory interconnect identified in the message.

BOOT016.Description: The input source argument value referring to the boot device is incorrect or empty. The boot device identifier must match the InstanceID for the Boot Source Setting instance that represents the boot device.
BOOT016.Resolution: Use the correct source argument value for the boot device and retry the operation.
BOOT016.Message: Input source argument value for the boot device is incorrect or not found among the boot devices on the system.

BAR103.Description: System branding data is being collected and copied to the backup Server Profile.

LIC503.Message: Unable to complete the current operation. The currently installed license does not support the following features: %1.
LIC503.Resolution: Acquire and install the license to enable the required feature, and retry the operation. If the problem persists, contact technical support or see product documentation for more information.
LIC503.Description: The currently installed license does not support the feature for the requested operation. The operation requires a valid license to enable specific features in the system. Since the required license is missing or expired, the features that are being accessed during the operation are disabled.

SYS022.Description: The operation could not complete because of an internal resource allocation issue with the firmware.
SYS022.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and retry the operation.

LC044.Description: The Lifecycle Controller system configuration wipe operation is currently running. The operation deletes user information from system hardware and resets BIOS, iDRAC and Lifecycle Controller to default settings. The current operation and system restart must complete before the operation can be attempted again.
LC044.Resolution: Wait for the Lifecycle Controller system configuration wipe operation that is currently running to complete before requesting another operation.
LC044.Message: An instance of Lifecycle Controller system configuration wipe is already running.

PWR8680.Message: The %1 firmware in the server slot %2 does not support the storage sled.
PWR8680.Resolution: Update the firmware identified in the message to the supported latest available version. See the latest iDRAC User Guide for information on the versions that support the storage sled.
PWR8680.Description: The firmware identified in the message does not support the storage sled.

UEFI0136.Description: The CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) operation cannot be executed because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible. This issue is caused by missing LC partitions.
UEFI0136.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0136.Message: Unable to execute CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible.

HWC0001.Description: The error is caused due to iDRAC failure.
HWC0001.Resolution: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord and turn on the system.
HWC0001.Message: Unable to complete the operation as there is no response from iDRAC.

SYS145.Description: vFlash SD Card data is deleted because of a System Erase operation.
SYS145.Message: vFlash SD Card data is deleted.

PDR36.Message: The only hot spare available is a SAS disk %1.
PDR36.Resolution: Add a SATA disk that is large enough to be used as the hot spare and assign the new disk as a hot spare.
PDR36.Description: The only physical disk available to be assigned as a hot spare is using SAS technology. The physical disks in the virtual disk are using SATA technology. Because of this difference in technology, the hot spare cannot rebuild data if one of the physical disks in the virtual disk fails.

BOOT007.Description: One or more of the Boot Source instance IDs does not belong to the affected Boot Configuration.
BOOT007.Resolution: ChangeBootOrderByInstanceID only accepts Boot Sources from the impacted Boot Configuration. Verify that all source arguments belong to the desired Boot Configuration.
BOOT007.Message: Boot Source does not belong to specified Boot Configuration

SWC0270.Description: Local Configuration using RACADM may be disabled.
SWC0270.Resolution: Check if the Local Configuration using RACADM is disabled and enable it through GUI.
SWC0270.Message: Unable to clear the SEL. Possible reason may be that Local Configuration using RACADM is disabled.

SWC0226.Description: The Remote/Firmware racadm did not find any AD/LDAP certificate at specified path.
SWC0226.Message: No valid directory service certificate exists

PSU8517.Description: The operation to change the PSU redundancy policy is complete.

SWC0294.Description: The group name specified is incorrect.
SWC0294.Resolution: Refer to the list of groups available and choose the correct one.

SWC0035.Description: The backup operation did not initialize because the system does not have a service tag.
SWC0035.Resolution: Assign a service tag to the system and retry the operation. To assign the service tag, contact your service provider.
SWC0035.Message: Unable to initialize backup Server Profile operation.

UEFI0082.Description: The system was reset due to a timeout from the watchdog timer.
UEFI0082.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) or crash dumps from Operating System to identify the source that caused the watchdog timer reset. Update the firmware or driver for the identified device.
UEFI0082.Message: The system was reset due to a timeout from the watchdog timer.

SEL1406.Message: The platform generated a SNMP trap.

RAC956.Description: The allocated size for the Lifecycle Log entries has reached its maximum limit, and no further comments can be added to the Lifecycle Log.
RAC956.Message: There is no free space to add new comments to the Lifecycle Log.

SYS054.Description: The current configuration for components that require staged configuration already match the configuration specified by the input file. A system restart to apply staged configuration is not required.
SYS054.Message: No configuration changes requiring a system restart need to be applied.

OSE1002.Description: The system OS has successfully booted from C:.

RAC992.Resolution: To monitor the current set of the jobs, use the "racadm jobqueue view" command.
RAC992.Description: The job ID specified in the message is invalid or was already deleted.

BAR035.Description: The Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC) Configuration import did not complete successfully.
BAR035.Resolution: Manually reset the Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC) configuration.
BAR035.Message: Unable to Restore Integrated Remote Access Controller configuration.

VFL1006.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media.
VFL1006.Description: At boot, the Card Identification (CID) signature of the card is different from the Non-volatile (NV) storage value or the card is the destination of a copy operation that is in-progress.

RAC1169.Description: The RACADM "config" command will be deprecated in a future version of iDRAC firmware.
RAC1169.Resolution: Run the RACADM "racadm set" command to configure the iDRAC configuration parameters. For more information on the set command, run the RACADM command "racadm help set".
RAC1169.Message: The RACADM "config" command will be deprecated in a future version of iDRAC firmware.

IOV115.Message: Unable to allocate %1 WATTS for discovery of PCIE adapters.
IOV115.Resolution: Using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) RACADM command line interface, run the command "racadm config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisPowerCap <Power cap>" to increase the power cap or add an additional power supply.
IOV115.Description: The discovery process for PCIE adapters was unable to allocate the power required to power on the PCIE adapters.

SWC0268.Description: The ASR screen is already cleared.
SWC0268.Message: There is no ASR screen currently available to clear

SUP0537.Description: Unable to continue the firmware update due to an internal error.
SUP0537.Resolution: Reboot the system and retry. If the problem persists, contact your service provider for the latest Update Package.
SUP0537.Message: Unable to continue the firmware update.

UEFI0194.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.
UEFI0194.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0194.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Fine Command Training phase.

HWC8504.Message: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) cannot communicate with the %1 control panel because of internal issues.
HWC8504.Resolution: Disconnect the input power supplied to the chassis and reconnect. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
HWC8504.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) cannot communicate with the control panel identified in the message because of internal issues.

SWC8621.Message: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to process inventory data from the server in slot %1.
SWC8621.Resolution: Restart the Chassis Management Controller (CMC). To restart the CMC, start an SSH session to the CMC and enter the command "racadm racreset". Wait for the CMC to finish restarting and check if the inventory data is collected. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8621.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to process inventory data from the server slot identified in the message. This can happen if there is no free temporary storage in CMC.

UEFI0009.Description: A CPU segment not present exception (type 0x0B) occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0009.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.
UEFI0009.Message: CPU Exception Type 0x0B: Segment Not Present (Software).

SWC1927.Description: The iDRAC Quick Sync access feature is set to the read-only mode.
SWC1927.Message: The iDRAC Quick Sync access feature is set to the read-only mode.

TMP0116.Message: The %1 temperature is outside of range.
TMP0116.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0116.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or cool.

HWC5012.Message: On screen display (OSCAR) is not functional for the %1.
HWC5012.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.

VME0003.Description: Virtual Console session fails to start.
VME0003.Resolution: Retry the Virtual Console session initiation.
VME0003.Message: Virtual Console session fails to start.

OSD064.Description: The process of installing an operating system or hypervisor is abruptly stopped either by the user or the installation infrastructure.
OSD064.Message: The process of installing an operating system or hypervisor is abruptly stopped either by the user or the installation infrastructure.

RED066.Description: The recurring scheduled update from repository job completed and updates are staged to run after the next system restart.
RED066.Resolution: A system restart is required to apply the staged updates.
RED066.Message: The recurring scheduled update from repository job completed and updates are staged to run after the next system restart.

BAR002.Description: The system profile Backup partition detection operation is in progress.

AMP0310.Message: Disk drive bay %1 current is outside of range.
AMP0310.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0310.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.

PST0141.Description: Quick Path Interconnect failed during system POST. Reboot the system. If problem persists, remove input power and reseat processors. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video.
PST0141.Resolution: Reboot the system. If problem persists, remove input power and reseat processors.

BAR030.Description: The import system profile is complete. iDRAC restarts to complete restore.
BAR030.Message: Import System Profile Complete, restarting Integrated Remote Access Controller.

VDR54.Description: You have cancelled the virtual disk initialization.

DIS001.Description: Auto Discovery starts automatically, but was unable to find a valid license. Once you have obtained a valid license and installed it, restart.
DIS001.Resolution: Follow service providers instructions to enable the license.

SWC8510.Message: Unable to apply %1 Profile to requested Server(s)
SWC8510.Resolution: Check if iDRAC is ready and system is running properly. Utilize the RACADM command by running "racadm getversion" to list all the servers and make sure the iDRAC version is displayed. If the iDRAC is listed as Not Ready then wait until it becomes ready. A Virtual Reseat may be required. The Lifecycle log in the server may have additional information about the inability of the iDRAC to apply Profile settings.
SWC8510.Description: Unable to communicate with the iDRAC of the requested Server.

UEFI0154.Description: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology (DPAT) Enterprise license after three consecutive boots. The Dell Controlled Turbo BIOS setup configuration is being reverted to default because of the absent license.
UEFI0154.Resolution: If the absence of license is expected, no action is necessary. Otherwise do one of the following: 1) Reload the license. 2) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 3) Update the iDRAC firmware.
UEFI0154.Message: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology (DPAT) Enterprise license after three consecutive boots. The Dell Controlled Turbo BIOS setup configuration is being reverted to default because of the absent license.

BAT0019.Resolution: Check the battery to confirm presence.
BAT0019.Description: System settings may be preserved if input power is not removed from the power supplies.

PST0193.Description: System BIOS POST memory test failed. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST exception code C1).
PST0193.Resolution: Compare system memory installation to supported system memory configurations. Reduce system configuration to minimum memory configuration.

TMP0114.Message: The %1 temperature is greater than the upper warning threshold.
TMP0114.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0114.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.

SWC5004.Description: System Controller (SC) has started functioning again because either a server health issue is resolved or SC has completed a firmware update process.

SYS231.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported source file path value.
SYS231.Resolution: Make sure that the correct source file path is used, and then retry the operation.
SYS231.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an unsupported source file path value.

UEFI0130.Description: The system time and data are invalid.
UEFI0130.Resolution: Go to the System Setup to set the current time and date.
UEFI0130.Message: The system time and date are invalid.

BAR072.Description: The vFlash backup partition format operation was not successful.
BAR072.Resolution: Enable and initialize the vFlash media and retry the export. If the issue persists, try a new vFlash media or use the network share option(s).
BAR072.Message: Format of vFlash Backup partition unsuccessful.

VFL0719.Description: The SD card is in use by another process. Initialization requires exclusive access to the SD card to complete the initialization.
VFL0719.Resolution: The SD card is in use by another process. Retry after a few minutes.
VFL0719.Message: One or more partitions are in use; the SD card could not be initialized.

PST0004.Description: System BIOS has started memory configuration.

SWC0240.Description: The requested object is auto-assigned if DNS Server DHCP is enabled, and hence cannot be configured.
SWC0240.Resolution: Disable DNS Server DHCP and re-try the command.
SWC0240.Message: The IPv6 DNS Server IP address is not allowed to be configured if IPv6 DNS Server DHCP (cfgIPv6DNSServersFromDHCP6) is enabled.

CTL102.Description: The controller identified in the message is enabled by a user action.

SWC0125.Description: The CSR file could not be generated.

RAC0694.Description: Unable to configure the attributes of the selected controller, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
RAC0694.Resolution: To enable Lifecycle Controller, reboot the server. During server startup, press F2 to enter System Setup. Go to iDRAC Settings -> Lifecycle Controller, select Enable, and save the changes. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
RAC0694.Message: Unable to configure the attributes of the selected controller, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

RAC0722.Message: Failed to program the Chassis assigned MAC address for the NIC.Integrated.%1.
RAC0722.Description: Failed to program the Chassis assigned MAC address for the NIC.Integrated in the specified slot number.

PDR87.Description: The physical device was reset. This is a normal part of operations and is not a cause for concern.

VF029.Description: The user account credentials provided for this vFlash operation do not have the correct privileges. Virtual Media Access privilege is required to perform vFlash SD Card media operations.
VF029.Resolution: Use a different user account the has Virtual Media Access privilege.

HWC5001.Resolution: If unexpected, check presence, then re-install or reconnect.

RFM1021.Description: The removable flash media is installed but improperly configured or failed to initialize.
RFM1021.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media.
RFM1021.Message: Removable Flash Media is not IPMI-function ready.

LIC502.Description: The attempted features are not available in the system.
LIC502.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.

PWR8504.Description: The chassis power button press is detected but the button has been disabled.
PWR8504.Resolution: The chassis power button is disabled. To enable the chassis power button use the CMC RACADM command line interface, CMC Web interface. Using the command line, enter "racadm config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisPowerButtonEnable 1". Using the Web interface, click Chassis Overview > Power > Configuration. Clear the Disable Chassis Power Button check box.
PWR8504.Message: Chassis power button is pressed, but the button is disabled.

SYS437.Description: The job cannot be created because the EndTime value entered is less than 5 minutes of StartTime value.
SYS437.Resolution: Enter an EndTime value that is greater than 5 minutes of the StartTime value.
SYS437.Message: Unable to create the job because the EndTime value entered is less than 5 minutes of StartTime value.

RAC1181.Description: USB Management Port state cannot be changed because of an unknown hardware or firmware issue.
RAC1181.Resolution: To change the Management Port mode settings do the following: If a device is present, remove and reinsert the USB device from the front panel USB Management port and retry the operation. If the issue persists restart the iDRAC and retry the operation.
RAC1181.Message: Unable to change USB Management Port mode.

VLT0200.Message: The system board %1 voltage is less than the lower warning threshold.
VLT0200.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0200.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

SYS056.Description: Waiting for the system to shut down before applying configuration changes.
SYS056.Message: Waiting for the system to shut down.

HWC7010.Message: Server %1 health changed to a critical state from a non-recoverable state.
HWC7010.Resolution: Review System Log or front panel for additional information.
HWC7010.Description: Server <number> health changed to a critical state from a non-recoverable state.

USR105.Description: The user account used as credentials to access iDRAC is not enabled or configured to perform the operation.
USR105.Resolution: Retry the operation after creating the user account.

PR32.Description: The configuration changes requested, for the indicated job, have not passed the device specific verification check and will not be applied.
PR32.Resolution: Check the scripts or company documentation and try again.

RAC964.Description: The operation cannot be performed because of an internal error.
RAC964.Resolution: Wait for some time before retrying the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

OSD50.Description: Lifecycle Controller is in field service mode and needs to be updated before proceeding further.
OSD50.Resolution: Install the Lifecycle Controller field services package using the iDRAC GUI.
OSD50.Message: Lifecycle Controller is in field service mode.

VDR97.Message: Patrol Read corrected a media error on %1.
VDR97.Description: The Patrol Read task has encountered an error such as a bad disk block and remapped data to correct the error.

SWC1903.Description: RAC SSL Certificate has been changed.
SWC1903.Message: RAC SSL Certificate has been changed.

STOR0514.Description: The physical disk drive(s) cannot be initialized because the selected RAID controller does not support this operation while in non-RAID mode.
STOR0514.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Select a controller that is in RAID mode and retry the operation. 2) Update the controller firmware to the latest version and retry the operation.
STOR0514.Message: Unable to initialize the selected physical disk drive(s).

PCI3015.Message: The component at slot %1 recovered from a non-fatal PCIe error.

OSD57.Description: Remote File Share (RFS) is currently configured to be in auto-attach mode. For Web services to attach an ISO, RFS should be changed to attach mode.
OSD57.Resolution: Change the Remote File Share (RFS) mode to Attach using iDRAC GUI or Remote Services API and retry.
OSD57.Message: Remote File Share (RFS) is in Auto-Attach mode.

AMP0300.Message: The system board %1 current is less than the lower warning threshold.
AMP0300.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.

RDU8500.Description: The CMC is identified in the message is active.

SWC8611.Message: Profile "%1" and Server (Service Tag: %2 in Slot %3) are not compatible.
SWC8611.Resolution: Make sure to select the correct version of the profile and/or server, and then retry the operation.
SWC8611.Description: CMC cannot perform the server profile application because the selected profile version and the server identified in the message are not compatible.

SUP0117.Message: Firmware rollback initiated successfully. The iDRAC will now reset to complete the firmware rollback operation.

VDR58.Message: Bad block medium error is detected at block %1 on %2.
VDR58.Resolution: Recovering a physical disk bad block depends on the RAID level and state of the virtual disk. If a virtual disk is redundant, the controller can recover a bad block on a physical disk. If a virtual disk is not redundant, then the physical disk bad block results in a virtual disk bad block.
VDR58.Description: Virtual disk bad blocks are due to presence of unrecoverable bad blocks on one or more member physical disks.

LIC017.Description: This error can occur when the license file: 1) Signature is not valid. 2) Data is not in the correct format. 3) Missing needed data. 4) Contains unknown data.5) Has not been unzipped.
LIC017.Resolution: Download the license file, unzip and import the license.
LIC017.Message: The license file is corrupted, has not been unzipped, or is not a valid license file.

CTL4.Description: You have disabled the controller alarm. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

CTL107.Message: The Rebuild Rate of %1 is set to %2.
CTL107.Description: The Rebuild Rate of the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.

SWC1916.Description: Network Time Protocol server configuration has changed.
SWC1916.Message: Network Time Protocol server configuration has changed.

NIC024.Description: The attribute specified in the operation is currently read only and the value cannot be modified.
NIC024.Resolution: For more information on the attribute, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
NIC024.Message: The set operation did not complete successfully as the attribute is read-only.

UEFI0014.Description: A CPU alignment check exception (type 0x11) occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0014.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.

UEFI0166.Message: Unable to configure memory interleaving on DIMM modules on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0166.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure interleaving can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0166.Description: Memory could not be interleaved because the number of allowable Target Address Decode (TAD) rules exceeded during memory initialization.

STOR074.Description: The requested RAID configuration operation will not be allowed because the RAID controller is currently in HBA mode.
STOR074.Resolution: In order to perform a RAID configuration operation, change the controller mode to RAID and retry the operation. For switching to RAID mode using the F2 System Setup utility, go to Device Settings > "RAID Controller "> Controller Management > Advanced Controller Management > Switch to RAID mode.
STOR074.Message: The requested RAID configuration operation is not allowed because the controller is currently in HBA mode.

PDR62.Message: The rebuild failed due to errors on the target %1.
PDR62.Resolution: Replace the target disk. If a rebuild does not automatically start after replacing the disk, then initiate the Rebuild task. You may need to assign the new disk as a hot spare to initiate the rebuild.
PDR62.Description: It is not possible to rebuild data that resides on a defective disk.

OSD23.Description: Cannot continue with DetachISOImage because another command is in the process of exposing the ISO image and booting to it.
OSD23.Resolution: See the ConcreteJob status to make sure that the current running process is complete and then run DetachISOImage.
OSD23.Message: Unable to continue with DetachISOImage - another command is in the process of exposing the ISO Image and booting to it.

BOOT019.Description: The ChangeBootOrderByInstanceID command cannot be run because the BIOS Export operation is in progress.
BOOT019.Resolution: Wait for the BIOS Export operation to complete and retry the operation.
BOOT019.Message: Unable to run the ChangeBootOrderByInstanceID command because the BIOS Export operation is in progress.

SUP0522.Description: Write protection is enabled for the BIOS image and local BIOS update is disabled.
SUP0522.Resolution: To flash the BIOS locally, enable local BIOS update by selecting System Setup.
SUP0522.Message: Unable to update the BIOS firmware because write protection is enabled.

UEFI0249.Description: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization encountered a programmatic error. A requested resource could not be allocated. Resource was forced to maximum possible value instead.
UEFI0249.Resolution: Reseat all processors in the system and ensure all processors are matching. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0249.Message: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization error detected.

UEFI0017.Description: Unable to locate a file required to run Lifecycle Controller. No Lifecycle Controller functionality is available while in Recovery Mode.
UEFI0017.Resolution: Repair Lifecycle Controller firmware using the Lifecycle Controller Dell Update Package (DUP) or Lifecycle Controller Repair Package via iDRAC. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.
UEFI0017.Message: Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible and is therefore in Recovery mode.

SUP0518.Message: Successfully updated the %1 firmware to version %2.
SUP0518.Description: The specified firmware for the component was successfully updated.

PDR10.Description: This message is generated after a rebuild starts on a physical disk.

UEFI0051.Description: Brand information is successfully collected. The system is being restarted. The rebranding process is completed.
UEFI0051.Message: Brand information is successfully collected. The system is being restarted.

PCI2002.Message: A fatal IO error detected on a component at slot %1.
PCI2002.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, remove and re-install the device.
PCI2002.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.

MEM0016.Message: Memory device at location(s) %1 is operating correctly.

SWC0089.Description: One or more iDRAC configurations cannot be saved by using the Initial Setup feature of Lifecycle Controller.
SWC0089.Resolution: Make sure that the network cable is connected, DHCP server is turned on, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, perform the following steps: 1) Turn off the server and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait for five seconds. 3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the server, and then retry the operation.
SWC0089.Message: Unable to save one or more iDRAC configurations by using the Initial Setup feature of Lifecycle Controller.

SYS199.Description: The state of Lifecycle Controller is successfully changed to "disabled", but other attributes are not set. When the LifecycleControllerState attribute is set to disabled in the SCP profile, other attributes settings in the SCP profile are not applied.
SYS199.Resolution: The Lifecycle Controller state must be "enabled" before performing the import SCP operation and the LifecycleControllerState attribute should not be set to disabled in the SCP profile while attempting to configure other attribute settings. To set LifecycleControllerState attribute to enabled using the RACADM command line utility, type "racadm set lifecyclecontroller.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState Enabled".
SYS199.Message: The state of Lifecycle Controller is successfully changed to "disabled", but other attributes specified in the Server Configuration Profile (SCP) profile are not changed.

PSU1010.Description: The power supply unit is switched off. Either you have switched off the power supply unit or it is defective.
PSU1010.Resolution: Check to see whether the power switch is turned off or on. If it is turned off, turn it on. If the problem is not corrected, verify that the power cord is attached and functional. If the problem continues or if the power switch is already turned on, then replace the power supply unit.
PSU1010.Message: The DC power supply is switched off.

VDR25.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

VDR96.Message: Bad block table on %1 is 80 percent full.
VDR96.Resolution: Replace the disk in the Virtual disk, generating this message.
VDR96.Description: This message occurs if the virtual disk has bad blocks.

RAC010.Description: The input value for the attribute being set contains characters that are not allowed.
RAC010.Resolution: Retry the operation using valid input characters. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.

RAC032.Description: The DNS RAC name specified is not valid.
RAC032.Resolution: Retry operation with valid DNS RAC name.
RAC032.Message: Invalid value specified for DNS RAC name.

SYS249.Message: A network connection is successfully started to the remote host, but the file, %1, is unable to be transferred.
SYS249.Resolution: Make sure that correct parameters are entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS249.Description: A network connection is successfully started to the remote host, but the file is unable to be transferred.

VFL1003.Message: Removable Flash Media %1 is not IPMI-function ready.
VFL1003.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media and module.
VFL1003.Description: The removable flash media is installed but improperly configured or failed to initialize.

SYS401.Description: The operation cannot be successfully completed because the media type entered is not supported.
SYS401.Resolution: Enter a media type that is supported and retry the operation. For more information about the supported media types, see the Redfish User's Guide available on the support site.
SYS401.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the media type entered is not supported.

HWC4010.Message: Hardware successfully updated for mezzanine card %1.

ISM0004.Description: The iDRAC Service Module has successfully started communication with iDRAC.
ISM0004.Message: The iDRAC Service Module has successfully started communication with iDRAC.

UEFI0227.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0227.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0227.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Receive Enable Training - Configuration Read phase.

UEFI0216.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0216.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0216.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Late Command Training phase.

UEFI0175.Message: A Octal Rank DIMM module is installed on memory slot %1 after a Quad Rank DIMM module.
UEFI0175.Resolution: Quad Rank and Octal Rank DIMM modules cannot be mixed on a channel. Populate memory modules in a supported configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0175.Description: A memory population violation has been detected on the identified DIMM slot.

CTL45.Resolution: Replace the Dual In-line Memory Module (DIMM) to avoid data loss or data corruption. The DIMM is a part of the controller battery pack. Refer to hardware documentation for information on replacing the DIMM.
CTL45.Description: The Dual In-line Memory Module (DIMM) is beginning to malfunction.

UEFI0291.Description: The Processor Embedded Memory mode cannot be enabled because no on-package memory was detected.
UEFI0291.Resolution: Replace the processor to make sure that the Processor Embedded Memory mode is supported, and then retry the operation. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0291.Message: Unable to configure the requested Processor Embedded Memory mode because no on-package memory was detected.

RED085.Description: The Chassis firmware cannot be updated because communication between iDRAC and CMC took more time than expected.
RED085.Resolution: Verify the status of CMC by accessing the CMC and making sure it is functioning and responding and then retry the operation. For more information about troubleshooting a CMC issue, see the CMC User Manual. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RED085.Message: Unable to update the Chassis firmware, communication with Chassis Management Controller took more time than expected.

LIC206.Message: EULA warning: Importing license %1 may violate the End-User License Agreement.
LIC206.Resolution: Remove the license if the import violates the EULA.
LIC206.Description: The license was imported after the user overrode EULA warning.

ASR0105.Description: The operating system or an application failed to failed to communicate within the timeout period. The system was powered off. (IPMI sensor type code 23h offset - 02h event 3:0 - 4h).
ASR0105.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0105.Message: The OS watchdog timer powered off the system.

SWC0291.Description: Another object of the same value exists. Typically in the case of username.
SWC0291.Resolution: Change the specified value and re-try.
SWC0291.Message: Another object exists with the specified value. Duplicate values are not allowed for the requested object.

SUP028.Description: The GetRepoBasedUpdateList method was not successfully executed because the InstallFromRepo method was not executed first.
SUP028.Resolution: Execute InstallFromRepo method, and then retry the operation.
SUP028.Message: The GetRepoBasedUpdateList method did not complete successfully.

RAC0670.Description: Deleting the virtual disk will remove the virtual disk from the controller's configuration. If the specified virtual disk is a boot device, the server will not boot unless another boot device is selected in BIOS.
RAC0670.Resolution: If the specified virtual disk is a boot device, the server will not boot. Press OK to continue.
RAC0670.Message: Deleting the virtual disk will remove the virtual disk from the controller's configuration.

HWC0012.Description: The USB drive is write protected.
HWC0012.Resolution: Remove write protection on the USB drive before retrying the operation.
HWC0012.Message: Unable to write to the USB drive.

PR4.Message: Older version of firmware found on device: %1
PR4.Description: The current component firmware version is lower than the previous component firmware version.

RAC944.Description: A configuration job cannot be created if Lifecycle Controller is disabled.
RAC944.Resolution: Run "racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState 1" to enable Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation.
RAC944.Message: Unable to create the configuration job.

DH009.Description: An unexpected internal problem has occurred and the operation did not complete successfully.
DH009.Resolution: Remove AC power from the system and re-apply AC power to the system. After the server restarts, retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
DH009.Message: The operation did not complete successfully because of an unexpected internal problem.

TMPS0101.Description: Inlet temperature has been above the critical threshold for duration of 0.8% or more for the operational time during the last one year.
TMPS0101.Resolution: This condition will occur if the ambient temperature is high. Make sure the ambient temperature of the environment is in normal range.
TMPS0101.Message: Inlet temperature is above critical level for extended duration.

RAC0182.Message: The iDRAC firmware was rebooted with the following reason: %1.
RAC0182.Description: The iDRAC was reset for the reason identified in the message. The reasons may include: AC Power Cycle, Watchdog timer expiry, or a reset initiated via user interface or ID Button.

PWR8528.Description: The Max Power Conservation Mode can be enabled only when Server Based Power Management Mode is disabled.
PWR8528.Resolution: The Max Power Conservation Mode can be changed when Server Based Power Management mode is disabled. Using the CMC Web UI, navigate to the Chassis Overview > Power > Configuration page, then uncheck the Enable Server Based Power Management checkbox. Retry the operation.
PWR8528.Message: Unable to set Max Power Conservation Mode because the Server Based Power Management mode is enabled.

PCI5001.Message: A PCIe card carrier containing a PCIe card is inserted in PCIe slot%1 .
PCI5001.Resolution: Turn on or power cycle the associated server to enable the PCIe card.
PCI5001.Description: A PCIe card carrier containing a PCIe card is present in the slot identified in the message. This PCIe card will be enabled when the associated server is turned on or power cycled.

BAR009.Description: The vFlash media is not present on the system.
BAR009.Resolution: Insert the appropriate vFlash media in the designated vFlash portal, enable and initialize it, and retry.

ENC31.Resolution: Attempt to download the enclosure firmware again. If problems continue, verify that the controller can communicate with the enclosure. Make sure that the enclosure is powered ON. Refer to the storage hardware documentation for information on checking the cables.
ENC31.Description: The system was unable to download firmware to the enclosure. The controller may have lost communication with the enclosure. There may have been problems with the data transfer or the download media may be corrupt.

SWC0065.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to copy the OS drivers from the OS driver pack.
SWC0065.Resolution: Exit the OS Deployment wizard and retry the operation. If the issue persists, do one of the following:1) Update the system with the latest operating system driver packs using the Firmware Update feature and retry the operation. 2) Reboot the system, press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation.
SWC0065.Message: Unable to retrieve the drivers for the selected operating system.

UEFI0008.Description: A CPU invalid task segment state (TSS) exception (type 0x0A) occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0008.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.
UEFI0008.Message: CPU Exception Type 0x0A: Invalid Task Segment State Segment (TSS) (Software).

CBL0007.Message: Backplane %1 %2 cable and backplane %1 %2 cable are swapped.
CBL0007.Resolution: Make sure the cables identified in the message are cabled correctly. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CBL0007.Description: The backplane cables identified in the message need to be connected to the correct backplane bays.

SYS023.Description: There are no pending values to change.
SYS023.Resolution: Ensure there are pending values for the attributes that need to be set and retry the operation.

SYS256.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an out-of-memory condition.
SYS256.Resolution: Check the iDRAC health and retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and retry the operation after the iDRAC has fully restarted.
SYS256.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an out-of-memory condition. The issue is not because of network conditions, proxy status, or remote host status.

SEC0102.Description: The module or Storage tray identified in the message is closed.

JCP006.Description: One or more of the specified values for creating a job are invalid or an internal error has occurred when scheduling the job.
JCP006.Resolution: Use the correct value for the job attribute and retry the operation.

LC068.Description: The import or export system configuration operation cannot be performed because there are pending attribute changes or a configuration job is in progress.
LC068.Resolution: Apply or cancel any pending attribute changes. Changes can be applied by creating a targeted configuration job, or the changes can be cancelled by invoking the DeletePendingConfiguration method. If a configuration job is in progress, wait until it is completed before retrying the import or export system configuration operation.
LC068.Message: Unable to perform the import or export operation because there are pending attribute changes or a configuration job is in progress.

STOR307.Description: Unable to perform the configuration operation because the export log operation is currently in progress.
STOR307.Resolution: Wait until the current export operation is complete, and then try the configuration operation again.
STOR307.Message: Unable to perform the configuration operation because the export log operation is currently in progress.

CMC8566.Message: KVM mapping is disabled for the server slot %1.
CMC8566.Description: The KVM mapping is disabled for the server slot specified in the message. The KVM cannot be mapped to this server slot.

UEFI0067.Message: A PCIe link training failure is observed in %1 and device link is disabled.
UEFI0067.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Turn off the input power to the system and turn on again. 2) Update the PCIe device firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0067.Description: A PCIe link failure is observed in the PCIe device identified in the message and device link is disabled.

VF041.Description: The remote share could not be mounted.
VF041.Resolution: Try the operation again. If this problem persists, check your login credentials and network.

BAR054.Description: The attempt to clean up after an unsuccessful Backup/Restore of a system profile operation has not been successful. The Lifecycle Controller/System Services related operations may not execute as expected until the system is properly restored to a functional configuration.
BAR054.Resolution: Enter the iDRAC configuration utility. Select the System Services option in the main selection screen. Choose the Cancel Lifecycle Controller Actions / Cancel System Services operation and follow the directions to ensure this operation is performed. If Cancel Lifecycle Controller Actions / Cancel System Services is not available, remove power from the system, wait 1 minute and reapply power. If the issue persists, contact your technical service provider.
BAR054.Message: System Reset or Lifecycle Controller Actions Canceled, System Profile Failure Recovery unsuccessful.

BIOS016.Message: AttributeValue cannot be changed for disabled AttributeName %1.
BIOS016.Description: A set attribute operation was attempted on a disabled attribute.

BAR092.Description: The attempt to disconnect from the specified NFS location was not successful.
BAR092.Resolution: If this happens on a backup request, restart the Integrated Remote Access Controller and try the operation again. If this is a restore request the Integrated Remote Access will be restarted during the execution of the request. Only restart the Integrated Remote Access Controller if it does not restart on its own.

UEFI0139.Description: The System Service Mode (SSM) cannot be entered because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible. This situation is caused by LC partition attach issues.
UEFI0139.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0139.Message: Unable to enter System Service Mode (SSM) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible.

MEM0008.Message: Memory device at location %1 is spare memory.

PDR57.Message: Bad block table on %1 is full. Unable to log block %2.
PDR57.Resolution: Replace the disk generating this message and restore from a backup copy. You may have lost data.
PDR57.Description: The bad block table is the table used for remapping bad disk blocks. This table fills as bad disk blocks are remapped. When the table is full, bad disk blocks are no longer remapped, which means that disk errors are no longer corrected. At this point, data loss can occur.

SWC0224.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0224.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0224.Message: Invalid syntax. The -d option is not valid with -u.

PWR8563.Message: Unable to turn on Server %1 due to I/O fabric inconsistency.
PWR8563.Resolution: Make sure that the hardware compatibility between the I/O Module (IOM) and the Mezzanine (Mezz) card is correct. Check the M1000e Hardware Manual for correct component compatibility.
PWR8563.Description: The Server identified in the message did not turn on due to a fabric mismatch between the I/O Module and the Mezzanine card on the Server.

RAC0696.Description: The iDRAC is unable to retrieve hardware overview related information while the server is turned off.
RAC0696.Resolution: Turn the server on to view the hardware overview information.
RAC0696.Message: Unable to retrieve the hardware overview information because the server is turned off.

SYS079.Description: The Preview operation indicates the input file for Server Configuration Profile is not compliant with the configuration profile schema.
SYS079.Resolution: Make sure that the input file is compliant with the system configuration XML schema published on www.delltechcenter.com/lc.
SYS079.Message: The Preview operation indicates the input file for Server Configuration Profile is not compliant with the configuration profile schema.

OSD065.Description: The Operating System/Hypervisor installation did not complete successfully. The system may be unable to boot into the operating system/hypervisor because of the incomplete installation.
OSD065.Resolution: Check the installation logs of operating system or hypervisor, resolve any issues identified, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
OSD065.Message: Operating System/Hypervisor Installation did not complete successfully.

RAC0245.Description: The vFlash partition is in-use by another process. Therefore, the current operation cannot proceed.
RAC0245.Resolution: Try the operation after a few minutes or with another partition. If the problem persists, reset iDRAC and repeat the operation.
RAC0245.Message: The partition is in-use by another process.

RAC025.Description: Unable to set static values for DNS1 or DNS2 when DNS from DHCP is Enabled.
RAC025.Resolution: Disable DNS from DHCP to set values for DNS1 or DNS2.
RAC025.Message: Unable to set values for DNS1 or DNS2 attributes because DNS from DHCP is Enabled.

VFL0716.Description: An error has occurred while initializing SD Card because the SD card is not an approved vFlash SD card.
VFL0716.Resolution: Insert a vFlash SD card and try again.
VFL0716.Message: SD Card is not a vFlash SD Card; the SD card could not be initialized.

SEC0612.Description: The default username and password is currently in use and unauthorized access to the iDRAC may occur because the default values are widely known. This is a severe security risk.
SEC0612.Resolution: To change the credentials using RACADM command, run the following at the command line interface (CLI): "racadm set iDRAC.Users.<index>.Password <new password string>". Alternately, to disable the default credential in use message, run "racadm config -g cfgractuning -o cfgRacTuneDefCredentialWarningEnable 0".
SEC0612.Message: The default username and password is currently in use. It is recommended to immediately change the default credentials.

DIS103.Description: The network share folder cannot be accessed by using the credentials specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.
DIS103.Resolution: Verify whether or not the following are correctly entered in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC, and then retry the operation: 1) Network share name. 2) The IP address of the network share folder. 3) The username and password (-u <username> & -p <password>).
DIS103.Message: The AutoConfig operation is unable to access a network share folder, because incorrect credentials are specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

SWC5003.Description: The System Controller (SC) has either stopped functioning or is updating a firmware version.
SWC5003.Resolution: Make sure that the System Controller is functioning.
SWC5003.Message: System Controller (SC) has either stopped functioning or is updating a firmware version.

PST0083.Description: System is at the BIOS Boot Menu.

PSU0005.Message: The power input for power supply %1 is outside of the allowable range, but it is attached to the system.
PSU0005.Resolution: Verify the input power is within the operating requirements for the power supply.
PSU0005.Description: The operating requirements for the power supply may be found in product documentation or on the power supply itself.

STOR051.Description: The requested operation cannot be completed because the specified StartingLBA and Size value combination is greater than allowed by the physical disk size.
STOR051.Resolution: Specify the Size value only and allow the instrumentation to calculate the StartingLBA value then retry the operation.
STOR051.Message: StartingLBA and Size value combination is greater than allowed by the physical disk size.

PWR8596.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because PSU redundancy is lost and the available power is insufficient.
PWR8596.Resolution: Make sure there is enough power supply to distribute power. Go to, the Chassis Overview > Power > Power Budget Status. In the Total Input Power Available For Allocation field, view the available power. To add more power, insert more PSUs or remove unused components from the chassis. When enough power is available, retry the operation.
PWR8596.Description: The Chassis Management Controller cannot turn on the server identified in the message, because PSU redundancy is lost or PSUs are removed. Sufficient power is not available for the operation.

PST0007.Description: System BIOS has started power on self test.

SYS233.Message: Unable to transfer the file, %1, because of an unsupported hostname value, %2.
SYS233.Resolution: Make sure that the correct hostname value is used, and then retry the operation.
SYS233.Description: The file identified in the message cannot be transferred because of an unsupported hostname value.

CMC8541.Message: The watchdog has reset the CMC %1.
CMC8541.Description: The CMC specified in the message was reset by a watchdog event.

RAC021.Description: The static values for IPAddress Net mask or Gateway cannot be set because DHCP is enabled.
RAC021.Resolution: Disable DHCP to set static values for IPAddress Net mask or Gateway.
RAC021.Message: Unable to set static values for IPAddress Net mask or Gateway because DHCP is Enabled.

PCI1320.Message: A bus fatal error was detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.
PCI1320.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1320.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.

SWC0108.Description: The Service Tag string is empty.
SWC0108.Message: The service tag is not currently populated.

NIC101.Message: The %1 Port %2 network link is started.
NIC101.Description: The transition from network link not started (down) to network link started (up) has been detected on the NIC controller port identified in the message.

CBL0005.Message: Backplane %1 %2 connector incorrectly connected to the motherboard SATA controller.
CBL0005.Resolution: Make sure the cable identified in the message is cabled correctly. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CBL0005.Description: The backplane connector identified in the message is incorrectly connected to the motherboard SATA controller.

RAC0101.Description: The data returned is not in a known format.
RAC0101.Resolution: This error may occur because:1. Smart Card is invalid. Insert a valid Smart Card and try again. 2. Check connection between reader and system.3. There may be an issue with the Smart Card reader. Try reinstalling the reader driver or use a different reader.
RAC0101.Message: The inserted Smart Card is not valid or the Smart Card reader is not supported.

BOOT013.Description: The boot list is currently not active. Changes cannot be made to boot list that is not active.
BOOT013.Resolution: Alter boot mode to set the boot list active and retry the operation.
BOOT013.Message: Cannot make changes to non-active boot list.

SWC0144.Message: Certificate successfully uploaded to the RAC. The RAC will now reset to enable the new certificate and may be offline temporarily.

IPA0001.Description: Invalid parameters passed to the function.
IPA0001.Message: Invalid NIC IP address parameter specified.

OSD22.Description: Unable to detach ISO image from the host because either the image is already detached, or iDRAC may not be operating normally.
OSD22.Message: Unable to detach ISO image from the host.

LC014.Resolution: Limit the number of characters in the comment to 255 characters.

RAC940.Description: If an existing system profile import or export job is running, then a system configuration profile backup or restore operation cannot be started.
RAC940.Resolution: Wait until the existing system profile export or import job is completed or cancel the job before retrying the operation.
RAC940.Message: Unable to start the system configuration profile export or import operation.

RED028.Description: Update files were not selected, therefore the installation did not proceed.
RED028.Resolution: Select one or more update files to install.

MEM8501.Resolution: If multiple resets occur, contact your service provider.
MEM8501.Description: A low memory condition was detected. If this condition continues, a failover or a reset may occur.

ISM0006.Description: The iDRAC Service Module could not successfully communicate with iDRAC, because the OS to iDRAC Pass-through channel is not configured in the USB-NIC mode.
ISM0006.Resolution: Make sure that the OS to iDRAC Pass-through channel is configured only in the USB-NIC mode, and then retry the operation. To enable the OS-to-iDRAC Pass-through channel, run the following command in the order they are listed: 1) racadm set idrac.os-bmc.PTMode usb-p2p 2) racadm set idrac.os-bmc.UsbNicIpAddress <ip address> 3) racadm set idrac.os-bmc.adminstate enabled.
ISM0006.Message: The iDRAC Service Module is unable to communicate with iDRAC using the OS to iDRAC Pass-through channel.

OSD44.Description: The ISO on vFlash is not currently attached, so the DetachISOFromVFlash command could not be executed.
OSD44.Resolution: Since the ISO image is not attached, the DetachISOFromVFlash command does not have to be run.
OSD44.Message: Unable to detach ISO image on VFlash.

RAC014.Description: The method cannot be run because an invalid attribute name is entered.
RAC014.Resolution: Enter a valid attribute name and retry the operation.
RAC014.Message: Unable to run the method because an invalid attribute name is entered.

RDU8513.Description: The firmware version of Active CMC and Standby CMC are the same.

PWR8571.Message: Unable to perform the power action requested for the server %1because another power action is in progress.
PWR8571.Resolution: Wait for the power action in progress to complete and retry the operation. It may take a few minutes for the current power action to complete.
PWR8571.Description: Another power action is in progress. The requested power action cannot be carried out until the power action in progress completes.

USR0151.Message: The remote VNC session from the IP address %1 is logging off.
USR0151.Description: The VNC client from the IP address identified in the message is logged off.

VDR46.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

USR8500.Message: Excessive login failures from %1; blocked for %2 seconds.
USR8500.Resolution: Make sure the username and password credentials used are correct, wait for the duration specified in the message and then retry the login.
USR8500.Description: Multiple login attempts were unsuccessful from the identified IP address. After detecting this error condition, this IP address will be blocked from login for the duration specified in the message.

IOV1005.Resolution: Perform the Enumerate operation on the DCIM_ChassisPCISlot class to determine the correct FQDD value for the required slot. Retry the operation with the correct FQDD value.
IOV1005.Description: The FQDD (Fully Qualified Device Descriptor) entered for the operation does not map to any instance of the DCIM_ChassisPCISlot class.

SWC0262.Description: The IPMI drivers or the RAC controller may not be installed.
SWC0262.Resolution: Check if the required modules are installed.
SWC0262.Message: Unable to perform operation. Please make sure RAC controller and appropriate IPMI drivers are installed.

HWC0008.Description: An internal error occurred while communicating with iDRAC.
HWC0008.Resolution: Exit the wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.

UEFI0193.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.
UEFI0193.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0193.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Coarse Command Training phase.

SYS171.Description: The import operation cannot be completed successfully because the SHA1v3Key and the MD5V3Key values must both be supplied.
SYS171.Resolution: The SHA1v3Key and the MD5V3Key values must be entered together for an import operation.
SYS171.Message: Unable to successfully complete the import operation because not all hash password values have been entered.

CMC8503.Description: CMC is unable to access the IPv4 information for the specified server. Unable to display the specified server's Launch iDRAC link on the CMC Web interface.
CMC8503.Resolution: Enable IPv4 on the specified slot's iDRAC via the CMC command line or Web GUI interface, for the iDRAC's launch point to show up on the CMC web GUI. For the command line options or navigation for Web interface, see the Troubleshooting section in the CMC User's Guide.
CMC8503.Message: Unable to access the IPv4 information of the server.

PDR1022.Message: Drive %1 in disk drive bay %2 is no longer in the failed array.

CPU0803.Message: The power input for CPU %1 voltage regulator module is lost.
CPU0803.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
CPU0803.Description: System performance may be degraded or the system may fail to operate.

HWC4016.Message: Hardware incompatibility detected with mezzanine card %1.
HWC4016.Resolution: 1) Review system documentation for supported mezzanine cards. 2) Replace mezzanine card with a supported mezzanine card.
HWC4016.Description: The system has detected a mezzanine card that is not supported on this system.

RAC1018.Description: This occurs when an incorrect syntax is used or an incorrect object is specified during the command invocation.
RAC1018.Resolution: Make sure to use the correct syntax and correct object names, and retry the operation. For information related to the corresponding group, see RACADM help or the RACADM User's Guide.
RAC1018.Message: The specified object or syntax is invalid.

SWC0143.Message: SSL key successfully uploaded to the RAC.

VFL0017.Description: The file system on the specified vFlash media partition could not be recognized. Data on the partition may be corrupted.
VFL0017.Resolution: Format the vFlash SD Card using the 'racadm vflashsd initialize' command and retry the operation.
VFL0017.Message: Unable to perform the vFlash media operation because the vFlash media partition is corrupted.

VLT0234.Message: The mezzanine card %1 %2 voltage is outside of range.
VLT0234.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions. 2) Reseat the mezzanine card. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0234.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

PCI1312.Message: An EISA fail-safe time-out was detected.

RAC963.Description: iDRAC is unable to read Lifecycle Controller status. Lifecycle Controller must be enabled to run the operation.
RAC963.Resolution: Run the racadm get LifecycleController.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState command to get the status of the Lifecycle Controller. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC963.Message: Unable to retrieve the status of Lifecycle Controller.

STOR14.Message: The peripheral sled in slot %1 initialization is not complete.
STOR14.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Check system log for further information about the issue, 2) Remove and re-insert the peripheral sled identified in the message or virtual reseat the sled, 3) Reset the CMC and wait for a few minutes for the CMC to finish restarting. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
STOR14.Description: Peripheral sled initialization is not successful with following possible reasons: 1) FRU is not functioning. 2) Sled internal components are not responding. 3) Component power state is not good. 4) Hardware configuration errors.

PWR8595.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server %1 due to insufficient power for the %2.
PWR8595.Resolution: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) will retry turning on the server and the corresponding components associated to the server after a predefined interval. If the issue persists, refer to the Managing and Monitoring Power section in the CMC User Guide for more information on configuring power management settings.
PWR8595.Description: The turn-on request for the server identified in the message did not succeed because of insufficient power to the chassis component identified in the message.

SWC0052.Description: An error occurred while retrieving the operating system drivers.
SWC0052.Resolution: Exit the OS Deployment wizard and update the system with the latest operating system driver packs available from the service provider and retry the operation. For more information, see the Lifecycle Controller user's guide.
SWC0052.Message: Unable to continue with OS Deployment operation.

RDU8517.Message: CMC%1: no action allowed while firmware update is in progress
RDU8517.Resolution: No response action is required. Wait until the firmware update is complete and retry the operation.
RDU8517.Description: No failover or other action can occur while a CMC firmware update is in progress.

FAN0010.Description: The fan may be required for optimal performance.

SWC8614.Message: Legacy profile setting: %1 is not recognized.
SWC8614.Resolution: Recreate the profile or use a different profile.
SWC8614.Description: The setting identified in the message is not recognized because the profile is not in a usable format or contains settings that are no longer supported.

STOR054.Description: The controller or the firmware on the controller does not support the CacheCade feature.
STOR054.Resolution: Refer to the specific controller users guide for more information.

HWC7008.Message: Server %1 health changed to a warning state from more severe state.
HWC7008.Resolution: Review System Log or front panel for additional information.
HWC7008.Description: Server <number> health changed to a warning state from more severe state.

TMPS0103.Description: Inlet temperature has been above the critical threshold for duration of 1% or more for the operational time during the last one year.
TMPS0103.Resolution: This condition will occur if the ambient temperature is high. Make sure the ambient temperature of the environment is in normal range.
TMPS0103.Message: Inlet temperature is above critical level for extended duration.

ASR0107.Description: The operating system or an application failed to respond to a pre-notification with-in the timeout period. (IPMI sensor type code 11h - offset 07h).
ASR0107.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0107.Message: The OS watchdog timer pre-timeout interrupt was initiated.

BAT1014.Description: Diagnostic event for service to determine if there is an ambient temperature problem.

SUP0123.Resolution: Re-connect to the iDRAC after a minute.
SUP0123.Message: Firmware update completed successfully. The RAC is in the process of resetting. Your connection will be lost. Please wait up to a minute before starting a new session.

SYS416.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the username and/or password is not entered, and therefore authentication failed.
SYS416.Resolution: Enter valid user name and password and retry the operation.
SYS416.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the username and/or password is not entered, and therefore authentication failed.

STOR079.Description: The requested operation cannot be performed because it is either not supported by the device or the device was not in the right state to perform the operation.
STOR079.Resolution: Make sure the device supports the requested operation. If the operation is supported, then make sure the server is turned on and retry the operation.
STOR079.Message: The device does not support this operation or is in a state that does not allow this operation.

CMC8513.Description: The Extended Storage feature activation on the secondary CMC timed out. If the media on Standby CMC does not respond within 90 seconds of confirming activation the feature returns to single CMC mode.
CMC8513.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) In the CMC Web interface, go to Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration, and verify if the SD card on secondary CMC displays errors. 2) If errors are displayed, execute the following racadm command: "racadm cmcchangeover". 3) Repair the removable flash media SD Card by selecting the Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration > Repair Active Controller Media in the CMC Web interface. Repairing is only allowed on the SD card of the primary CMC. If the problem persists, replace the card.
CMC8513.Message: The Extended Storage feature activation on the secondary CMC timed out. The feature is being returned to single CMC mode.

STOR040.Resolution: Specify a valid AttributeName value for the attribute identified in the message and retry the operation.
STOR040.Description: Unable to complete the requested operation because an invalid AttributeName value is specified.

RAC1072.Message: Unable to set maximum non critical threshold value of %1, because the value entered is less than, or equal to the minimum critical threshold value.
RAC1072.Resolution: Check the minimum critical threshold level using an appropriate RACADM command. For example, to view the minimum critical threshold value of a sensor, run the 'racadm getsensorinfo' command at the command line interface, and then retry the operation. For more information about other RACADM commands, run the racadm help command.
RAC1072.Description: The maximum non critical threshold value identified in the message cannot be set, because the value entered is less than or equal to the minimum critical threshold value.

PWR8670.Message: Unable to turn on server%1 because the required power %2 AC Watts exceeds the subsystem Connector Limit %3 AC Watts for IO modules, Blowers and Servers.
PWR8670.Resolution: Make sure the system operates within the subsystem Connector Limit for the components specified. To review power budget information select Chassis Overview -> Power -> Budget Status. Turn off unused components within the subsystem to make power available for the server to turn on or turn off low priority servers and try the operation again.
PWR8670.Description: The server identified in the message cannot be turned on if the Connector Limit for the subsystems identified in the message is exceeded .

SYS072.Description: The import of Server Configuration Profile did not complete as the operation took too long.
SYS072.Resolution: Delete all jobs, reset iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for at least 15 seconds, and retry the operation.
SYS072.Message: Server Configuration Profile import operation timed-out.

BAT0013.Message: The storage battery for disk drive bay %1 is present.

PST0064.Description: System BIOS is displaying power on splash screen.

RAC0681.Description: Shared component updates through the Server OS or Lifecycle controller cannot be applied because the CMC setting for Chassis Management at Server Mode is not set to 'Manage and Monitor'.
RAC0681.Resolution: To enable this feature do the following: 1) Launch CMC Web UI. 2) Navigate to Chassis Overview -> Setup -> General, and select 'Manage and Monitor' option for the Chassis Management at Server Mode. 3) Click Apply to save changes in CMC. 4) Retry the operation in iDRAC. For more information, refer to the CMC User Guide.
RAC0681.Message: Shared component updates through the Server OS or Lifecycle controller cannot be applied because the CMC setting for Chassis Management at Server Mode is not set to 'Manage and Monitor'.

VF021.Description: The size specified is greater than the maximum allowed for a partition.
VF021.Resolution: Try a partition size that is smaller than 4GB and the available space on the card.

VDR41.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RDU8511.Message: Unable to failover, CMC%1 in unknown state.
RDU8511.Resolution: Check the status of the standby CMC and make sure the firmware version matches the primary CMC. Then reseat the CMC and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RDU8511.Description: For failover, the standby CMC needs to be present, at the same firmware version as the primary CMC and healthy. During failover, the active CMC resets and the standby CMC becomes active. This message is logged when the standby CMC does not meet this criteria.

IOV122.Message: %1 %2 is mapped/assigned to extension of server slot %3.
IOV122.Description: The PCIE Slot or PERC Virtual Adapter (VA) identified in the message has been assigned to the extension of the server slot identified in the message.

RAC0298.Description: A Root Domain Name must be specified for Active Directory configuration.
RAC0298.Resolution: Root Domain Name must be configured.
RAC0298.Message: Root Domain Name must be configured.

UEFI0098.Message: The memory Built-In Self-test (BIST) has detected one or more errors on the DIMM installed on memory slot: %1. As a result, the corresponding DIMM has been disabled.
UEFI0098.Resolution: Replace the DIMM module identified in the message. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0098.Description: The memory Built-In Self-test (BIST) has detected one or more errors on the DIMM installed on memory slot: <slot number>. As a result, the corresponding DIMM has been disabled.

BAT1027.Message: The battery on %1 completed a charge cycle.
BAT1027.Description: The battery successfully completed a charge cycle.

VDR42.Message: Dedicated hot spare assigned physical disk %1.
VDR42.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

VFL1016.Message: Media not present for Removable Flash Media %1.
VFL1016.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media.
VFL1016.Description: The SD card is not detected or not installed.

PWR8515.Description: Unable to perform the chassis power action because the chassis is not turned on.
PWR8515.Resolution: Turn the chassis on and retry the operation.
PWR8515.Message: Unable to perform the chassis power action because the chassis is not turned on.

PWR8555.Message: Chassis Management Controller unable to turn on %1-%2 at priority %3 because of insufficient power. Minimum power needed is %4 AC Watt, but only %5 AC Watt is available.
PWR8555.Resolution: Make sure there is enough power supply to distribute power. Using the CMC Web UI, go to Chassis Overview > Power > Power Budget Status. In the Total Input Power Available For Allocation field view the available power. To add more power, insert more PSUs or remove unused components from the chassis.
PWR8555.Description: The request to turn on the component identified in the message was not successful because insufficient power is available at the identified priority for the component.

PCI1348.Message: A PCI parity error was detected on a component at slot %1.
PCI1348.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1348.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.

RAC927.Description: The recurrence value was successfully modified to the specified value.

LIC011.Description: License Manager does not allow the replacement of a non-evaluation license with an evaluation license.
LIC011.Resolution: To replace a non-evaluation license, first delete the non-evaluation license, then import the evaluation license.
LIC011.Message: A non-evaluation license cannot be replaced with an evaluation license.

MEM9009.Message: Intel DDR Memory interconnect %1 has a correctable error.
MEM9009.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reseat all DIMMs on the memory riser, 2) Reseat the memory riser, and 3) Restart the server. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
MEM9009.Description: A correctable error was detected in the propagation of signals on the Intel DDR memory interconnect identified in the message.

NIC506.Description: The requested operation requires the DNS registration to be enabled.
NIC506.Message: The requested object requires DNS registration to be enabled.

RAC0259.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the IPv6 address does not conform to the required format.

UEFI0095.Message: A DIMM with unsupported voltage is installed on memory slot %1.
UEFI0095.Resolution: Remove the unsupported DIMM module and replace it with a DIMM with a supported voltage. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0095.Description: A DIMM with unsupported voltage is installed on the memory slot identified in the message.

STOR016.Description: The physical disk drive cannot be assigned as the hot-spare of this virtual disk because the capacity of the physical disk is not sufficient.
STOR016.Resolution: Specify a physical disk with a larger capacity or replace the specified physical disk with one with more capacity, and then retry the operation.
STOR016.Message: The physical disk specified is not large enough to be a hot spare for this virtual disk.

SWC0319.Description: The syntax for the getraclog command is invalid.
SWC0319.Resolution: Refer the help text for getraclog command.
SWC0319.Message: The -i option is not valid with any other options.

STOR070.Message: Unable to run the WS-MAN method %1, because an invalid parameter %2 is entered.
