STOR070.Resolution: Enter a valid parameter, and then retry the operation. For more information about a valid parameter, refer to the SimpleRAIDProfile document available at DellTechCenter http://en.community.dell.com/techcenter/extras/m/white_papers/20263535.aspx.
STOR070.Description: The method name identified in the message could not be successfully completed, because the number of elements entered for VDPropNameArray and VDPropValueArray is not equal.

PST0003.Description: System BIOS has started chipset initialization.

SYS063.Description: The input file for the import configuration operation does not contain a closed root element.
SYS063.Resolution: Open the input file in any Web browser to check for invalid content before the expected root element. Correct the invalid content and make sure that the profile is compliant to the system configuration schema before retrying the operation.
SYS063.Message: Input file for import configuration operation is invalid. The expected root element was not closed.

CMC8506.Description: A command to shut down the CMC was initiated.
CMC8506.Message: A command to shut down the CMC was initiated.

SYS091.Description: Unable to complete the operation because the method is not supported.
SYS091.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the method is not supported.

RAC996.Description: Unable to set the specified object value because the object DNS RAC Name is not configured.
RAC996.Resolution: Configure DNS Rac Name using "racadm set iDRAC.NIC.DNSRacName <Name>" command, and retry the operation.
RAC996.Message: Unable to set the object value because the DNS RAC Name object is not configured.

PSU8513.Message: Unable to complete the PSU slot %1 firmware update. Error=0x%2.
PSU8513.Resolution: Retry the firmware update operation. If the problem persists, contact your service provider.
PSU8513.Description: Unable to update the PSU firmware due to PMBus communication errors.

RFM1020.Message: Removable Flash Media is IPMI-function ready.

LC056.Description: The name value pairs in the input parameter arrays do not match in the input.
LC056.Resolution: Retry the operation with a valid (AttributeName, AttributeValue) pair.

LC016.Resolution: Include all the parameters required for the command. Check Lifecycle Controller Profile documentation and try again.
LC016.Description: A required method argument was missing.

RAC1163.Message: The peak utilization value of out-of-band performance monitoring sensor %1 is successfully reset.
RAC1163.Description: The peak utilization value of out-of-band performance monitoring sensor identified in the message is successfully reset.

PWR2254.Description: The use of 110V is unacknowledged for the chassis and the chassis cannot grant power on permission to the server.
PWR2254.Resolution: Check for unacknowledged use of 110V and change to acknowledged. Using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) web interface, select Chassis Overview>Power>Configuration and then check the 110V Acknowledge field. Retry the operation to turn on the server.
PWR2254.Message: The use of 110V is unacknowledged and the chassis cannot grant power on permission to the server.

PR15.Message: Unable to verify configuration changes for device: %1
PR15.Description: The configuration changes requested have not passed the device specific verification check and will not be applied.

VFL0714.Message: SD card is not ready and could not be initialized.

RAC073.Description: The iDRAC reset operation cannot be completed because a vFlash partition creation operation is in progress.
RAC073.Resolution: Wait for the vFlash partition creation process to complete and retry the operation.
RAC073.Message: Unable to perform the iDRAC reset operation because a vFlash partition creation operation is in progress.

UEFI0049.Description: The NMI button cannot be enabled because either the NMI button is stuck or iDRAC firmware is not updated.
UEFI0049.Resolution: Correct the NMI button if stuck or update iDRAC firmware on the system.
UEFI0049.Message: Unable to enable the Non-maskable Interrupt (NMI) button because either the NMI button is stuck or iDRAC firmware is not updated.

VDR27.Message: The consistency check on a %1 has been resumed.
VDR27.Resolution: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
VDR27.Description: The check consistency on a virtual disk has resumed processing after a pause.

IOV114.Description: The PCIE Slot or PERC Virtual Adapter (VA) identified in the message has been assigned to the server identified in the message.

TMP0121.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm.
TMP0121.Message: The system inlet temperature is greater than the upper critical threshold.

UEFI0036.Description: The iDRAC Shared Memory Architecture (SMA) interface cannot be initialized. The BIOS will use the Keyboard Controller Style (KCS) interface.
UEFI0036.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware on the system.
UEFI0036.Message: Unable to initialize the iDRAC Shared Memory Architecture (SMA) interface.

VLT0220.Message: The %1 voltage is greater than the upper warning threshold.
VLT0220.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0220.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

RAC0617.Description: An error occurred while generating new iDRAC SSL Certificate or signing it with new custom signing certificate.
RAC0617.Resolution: Make sure to upload an PKCS#12 file that contains a valid custom signing certificate and private key, then retry the operation.
RAC0617.Message: An error was encountered while generating new SSL Certificate.

PCI3010.Message: A non-fatal IO error detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.
PCI3010.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, remove and re-install the device at the next service window.

PDR95.Resolution: Retry the update. If the update fails a second time, verify the update package is valid. If the update package is valid, replace the failing disk. Contact technical support if the problem persists.
PDR95.Description: The attempt to update the physical disk has failed. This is due to too much activity on the bus, a bad update package, or a bad disk.

PST0135.Description: System BIOS detected a timer refresh failure during system POST. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception code 87).
PST0135.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

PDR1122.Message: Drive %1 is no longer in the failed array.

FAN0006.Description: The fan may be required for optimal performance.

DIS113.Description: The AutoConfig configuration import operation could not be started, because no options were specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.
DIS113.Resolution: Make sure that the following are correctly entered in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC, and then retry the operation: 1) Filename -f <filename>). 2) The IP address of the network share folder (-i <ip-address>). 3) Network share name (-n <share-name>). 4) The share type (-s <0 or 2>) where 0 = NFS, 2 = CIFS. 5) The username and password (-u <username> & -p <password>) 6) Shutdown type (-d <0 or 1>) where 0 = Graceful shutdown and 1 = Forced shutdown. 7) Time to wait (-t <value>) where value is more than 300 seconds and less than 3600 seconds.
DIS113.Message: Unable to start the AutoConfig file import operation, because no options were specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

SWC0081.Description: Dell Integrated Data Center mode enabled.

PWR2255.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is configured in Max Power Conservation Mode and is unable to grant power on permission to the server.
PWR2255.Resolution: Disable the Max Power Conservation Mode on the chassis and retry the operation. Using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) web interface, select Chassis Overview>Power>Configuration and then uncheck the Max Power Conservation Mode field.
PWR2255.Message: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is configured in Max Power Conservation Mode and is unable to grant power on permission to the server.

RAC0655.Description: The Replicate Lifecycle Controller Log in OS Log and Auto System Recovery Action features are disabled in the iDRAC Service Module because the OpenManage Server Administrator is installed on the server operating system.
RAC0655.Message: The Replicate Lifecycle Controller Log in OS Log and Auto System Recovery Action features are disabled in the iDRAC Service Module because the OpenManage Server Administrator is installed on the server operating system.

LIC002.Description: The error may occur when License Manager: 1) Is unable to allocate system resources.2) Determines one or more files is incompatible with the current firmware version. This occurs when an older firmware version has been uploaded to a system that was previously running a newer firmware version. If this occurs, the current internal License Manager files are deleted and new ones are created, which align with the firmware version. A license reimport may be required. NOTE: All import, delete, export, view license commands are blocked until this issue is resolved.
LIC002.Resolution: If the firmware has been rolled back to a previous version, this error may occur. All previously installed licenses must be re-imported. If this is not the case, contact technical support.
LIC002.Message: License Manager is unable to allocate the required resources at startup.

UEFI0259.Description: The BIOS operation cannot be completed because the R920 baseboard does not support the R930 BIOS firmware.
UEFI0259.Resolution: Update the BIOS firmware to a supported R920 BIOS version. For a list of supported firmware versions, see the Owners Manual available at the support site.
UEFI0259.Message: Unable to complete the BIOS operation because the R920 baseboard does not support the R930 BIOS firmware.

SWC0086.Description: The Public IP access feature has been enabled in iDRAC by the Integrated Data Center solution. The iDRAC can now be managed via the Public IP interface.
SWC0086.Message: The Integrated Data Center Public IP mode is enabled.

SWU8538.Message: Unable to update the iKVM firmware. Reason = 0x%1.
SWU8538.Resolution: Retry the Update operation. If the issue persists, reinsert the iKVM and retry the operation.
SWU8538.Description: The iKVM firmware update operation was not successful.

RAC1188.Description: Unable to configure the Upper Non-Critical value for the System Performance sensor because the value provided is not in valid range.
RAC1188.Resolution: Specify a value in the range of 0 to 100 to set the upper non-critical value.
RAC1188.Message: Unable to configure the Upper Non-Critical value for the System Performance sensor.

SYS164.Description: The System Erase operation attempted to access Lifecycle Controller internal storage that is already being accessed by another function. Exclusive access to the internal storage is required for the System Erase operation. The System Erase operation attempts Lifecycle Controller internal storage access for 10 minutes. After the timeout the current job completes with an unsuccessful status.
SYS164.Resolution: Check the server and make sure that it is not in BIOS POST startup processing or stopped in the POST phase of startup. The server can also be stopped during POST because the <F2> is pressed or Option ROM setup utilities are being used. After the BIOS startup has completed, retry the operation.
SYS164.Message: Access to Lifecycle Controller internal storage was not acquired.

VDR60.Description: There are two modes of virtual disk initialization, full and fast. This initialization type identified in the message is running on the virtual disk identified in the message.

MEM9000.Description: An issue is detected in the propagation of signals between the processor and the memory.
MEM9000.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reseat the memory riser and restart the server. 2) If the issue is not resolved by preceding action, reseat the processor and restart the server. 3) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

JCP011.Resolution: To provide the correct value for the specified parameter, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation. Retry the operation requested with corrected value.
JCP011.Description: The value provided for the specified parameter is invalid and must be corrected for the invoked method to complete successfully.

AMP0320.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0320.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0320.Message: Chassis power level current is greater than the upper warning threshold.

STOR7.Description: The storage monitoring instrumentation detected a burst of events from underlying storage controllers. To overcome this overload condition, all the outstanding events have been purged and a fresh inventory will be performed automatically.
STOR7.Message: The storage management instrumentation is performing an inventory refresh operation.

UEFI0102.Description: The Memory Sparing feature cannot be enabled because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the feature.
UEFI0102.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure Memory Sparing feature can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0102.Message: Unable to enable the Memory Sparing feature because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the feature.

BAR048.Description: The server motherboard does not have a Service Tag assigned, the operation cannot continue.
BAR048.Resolution: Perform a System Profile import from a previous backup file. If no backup file is available, contact your service provider.

PWR8549.Description: The requested chassis shutdown operation did not complete successfully.
PWR8549.Message: Chassis shutdown did not complete successfully.

SYS438.Description: The Secure Boot keys cannot be reset because the installed BIOS version does not support the operation.
SYS438.Resolution: Update the BIOS to the latest version and retry the operation. For information about updating BIOS, see the iDRAC Users Guide available on the support site.
SYS438.Message: Unable to reset the Secure Boot keys because the installed BIOS version does not support the operation.

JCP035.Description: New jobs cannot be created because a backup job is currently running.
JCP035.Resolution: Wait for the running job to complete, and then retry the operation. To view a list of the jobs currently running, use the RACADM command "racadm jobqueue view" or using the WSMAN API, enumerate DCIM_LifeCycleJob to view the list of jobs that are currently scheduled.
JCP035.Message: Unable to create new jobs because a backup job is currently running.

PSU1004.Message: Power supply cable has been inserted into %1.
PSU1004.Description: The enclosure detected that AC power supply was restored to the power supply unit.

RDU8516.Message: CMC%1: failover initiated by RACADM interface.
RDU8516.Description: A failover has been requested from the RACADM command line interface.

SEC0100.Resolution: Close the Storage disk tray identified in the message.
SEC0100.Description: The Storage disk tray identified in the message is open. The tray should be closed as soon as any service action is completed. Leaving the tray open for an extended period may result in drives over heating.

LC100.Description: The server screen shot cannot be exported because of File Write Error.
LC100.Resolution: Wait for some time and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
LC100.Message: Unable to export the server screen shot because of File Write Error.

IOV112.Description: Chassis infrastructure firmware is not valid and must be reinstalled.
IOV112.Resolution: Update the Chassis Infrastructure firmware. Using Chassis Management Controller (CMC) RACADM, run the command "racadm fwupdate -g -u -a <TFTP server IP Address> -d mainboard.bin -m main_board" to upload the latest firmware version to the Chassis Infrastructure Mainboard.
IOV112.Message: Chassis Infrastructure firmware is not valid.

BAR067.Description: The system profile export destination is not initialized.
BAR067.Resolution: Initialize the vFlash media and retry the operation.

RAC0623.Description: A firmware update is not required for the components on the server, because current firmware versions are the latest available in the repository.
RAC0623.Message: The firmware versions on all the components of this server are up-to-date.

SEL1512.Description: The Chassis Controller is not responding or is not inserted properly.
SEL1512.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reinsert Chassis Controller, if removed. 2) If Chassis Controller is present but is not responding, reset the Chassis Controller. To reset the Chassis Controller using the graphical user interface (GUI), click Chassis Overview > Power > Control > Reset CMC. To reset by running the RACADM command at the command line interface (CLI), enter: "racadm racreset".
SEL1512.Message: The Chassis Controller is not responding or is not inserted properly. The status of Chassis Controller is critical.

RED024.Description: Lifecycle Controller is in use or currently processing another job. The specified job starts when Lifecycle Controller is available.
RED024.Resolution: Wait for current Lifecycle Controller task to complete.
RED024.Message: The specified job starts when Lifecycle Controller is available.

RAC0400.Description: iDRAC is running low on memory.

RED048.Message: The job %1 was deleted because the recurring operation %2 was cleared.
RED048.Description: The next job in the recurring operation sequence identified in the message was not started and was deleted, because an Automatic Server Profile Backup or Automatic Update operation was cleared.

ENC24.Resolution: Power down all enclosures attached to the system and reboot . If the problem persists, upgrade the firmware to the latest supported version. Verify the cable configuration is valid. See the storage hardware documentation for valid cabling configurations.
ENC24.Description: The controller is not receiving a consistent response from the enclosure. There could be a firmware problem or an invalid cabling configuration. If the cables are too long, they degrade the signal.

UEFI0115.Description: The BIOS has recovered the Management Engine after it became unresponsive via the HECI interface. There is no performance degradation and the Management Engine is functioning normally now.
UEFI0115.Resolution: The Management Engine is functioning normally now. No response action is required.
UEFI0115.Message: The Management Engine firmware has recovered from one or more correctable errors.

CMC8511.Description: The data on the Extended Storage removable flash media SD cards is not synchronized when the CMC is unable to determine which card has the latest data.
CMC8511.Resolution: Disable and then enable the Extended Storage feature. Using racadm, execute the following commands: "racadm feature -d -c Extended Storage" to disable and then "racadm -a -c Extended Storage" to enable the feature. NOTE: All the data on the removable flash media SD card is erased when the feature is disabled.
CMC8511.Message: Unable to synchronize the data in the Extended Storage removable flash media in the primary and secondary CMCs.

RAC0903.Description: The syntax of the specified command is invalid. In this case, the usage of the -d option is invalid.
RAC0903.Resolution: See the help text/documentation for valid syntax of the subcommand.
RAC0903.Message: The -d option cannot be used with any other options.

VLT0207.Message: The memory module %1 %2 voltage is less than the lower critical threshold.
VLT0207.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0207.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

SYS052.Description: Configuration changes that do not require a system restart are currently being applied.
SYS052.Message: Analyzing iDRAC, System, or Lifecycle Controller configuration for changes to be applied.

OSD60.Description: Connecting ISO using Remote File Share (RFS) was unsuccessful.
OSD60.Resolution: Verify ISO is connected using Remote File Share (RFS) and retry the operation.
OSD60.Message: Unable to connect to ISO using Remote File Share (RFS).

PWR8520.Description: The chassis reset operation was initiated.

PDR31.Message: A global hot spare has been removed.%1
PDR31.Resolution: Verify that the disk is healthy and installed. Check the cables. Refer to the product documentation and see the Cables Attached Correctly section for more information on checking the cables. If necessary, replace the disk and reassign the global hot spare.
PDR31.Description: The controller cannot to communicate with a disk that is assigned as a global hot spare. The disk either failed or was removed. There may also be a bad or loose cable.

RAC0181.Message: The iDRAC recovered from a firmware boot loader error with the following reason : %1.
RAC0181.Description: The iDRAC recovered from a firmware Bootloader error that occurred because of the reason identified in the message.

PWR2205.Message: The system is in a soft-off state.

CMC8571.Description: The coin cell battery in the primary CMC is not working. The battery needs to be replaced.
CMC8571.Resolution: Replace the coin cell battery in the primary CMC.
CMC8571.Message: The coin cell battery in the primary CMC is not working.

PST0090.Description: A problem was detected related to the previous server boot. The next logged message contains more specific details for the detected issue.
PST0090.Resolution: Review the next logged message for the recommended response action to resolve the problem.
PST0090.Message: A problem was detected related to the previous server boot.

RFM1032.Description: The card is write-protected by the physical latch on the SD card. IDSDM cannot use a write-protected card.
RFM1032.Resolution: If unintended, remove the media and disable write protection.
RFM1032.Message: Removable Flash Media is write protected.

SWC0122.Description: The syntax of the sslcertupload command is invalid.
SWC0122.Resolution: Refer the help text for sslcertupload subcommand.
SWC0122.Message: Invalid syntax. SSL key type (-t) must be specified.

CPU0703.Description: System event log and OS logs may indicate that the exception is external to the processor.
CPU0703.Resolution: 1) Check system and operating system logs for exceptions. If no exceptions are found continue. 2) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 3) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 4) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

SYS261.Message: Unable to transfer the file, %1, because initial network connection to the remote host server is not successfully started.
SYS261.Resolution: Check the file transfer parameters, health of the remote host, and then retry the operation.
SYS261.Description: The file cannot be transferred because initial network connection to the remote host server is not successfully started. The other probable reasons are: 1) issue in the network 2) remote host server is not turned on 3) remote host server is turned on but not functioning 4) issue in protocol negotiation.

PCI3019.Message: A low-severity issue is detected in the SSD bay %1, Slot %2.
PCI3019.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the component identified in the message, and then monitor the log for a re-occurrence of the issue. If the issue persists, and occurs during server startup, update the component firmware. If the issue persists and occurs during OS runtime, restart the server and update the OS drivers for the component identified in the message.
PCI3019.Description: A low-severity issue was detected in the SSD bay identified in the message.

PSU1001.Resolution: Check for other messages related to the state of the power supply unit/enclosure. These may help determine the cause of this event. Contact technical support if the issue still persists.
PSU1001.Description: The enclosure detected that a power supply unit has failed.

SEC0606.Description: This may apply to a physical or remote access attempt.
SEC0606.Resolution: Check system logs for intrusion attempts, and ensure strong password policies.
SEC0606.Message: The network boot password violation detected.

CTL38.Message: The Patrol Read operation completed for %1.

CMC8570.Message: The server slot %1 is enabled for DVD drive mapping.
CMC8570.Description: The server slot specified in the message is disabled for DVD drive mapping. The DVD drive cannot be mapped to this server slot.

BIOS013.Resolution: Enter the correct AttributeName available in the system. Refer to the enumeration response for desired attribute.
BIOS013.Description: An unknown AttributeName was specified in the operation.

SWC8551.Message: Unable to apply the boot identity profile because the profile %1 is already in use by the server in slot %2.
SWC8551.Resolution: Clear the boot identity of server identified in the message to apply another profile. Using the CMC GUI, navigate to the Boot Identity page, Boot Identities are cleared using "Clear Identity" option provided "Boot Identity Profiles" tab.
SWC8551.Description: The boot identity profile cannot be applied because the profile identified in the message is in use by the server in the slot identified in the message.

SWC5006.Description: System Controller (SC) reported a successful Firmware Update.

OSD20.Description: Unable to get the size or label for selected operating system from the Driver Pack present in Lifecycle Controller. The driver pack may be corrupt.
OSD20.Resolution: Update the Driver Pack using USC or DUP and rerun the command.
OSD20.Message: Unable to get size or label from Driver Pack for selected operating system.

RAC1038.Description: Unable to clear pending values for the specified component. This may be because there is an existing configuration job for the component.
RAC1038.Resolution: Make sure that a config job is not scheduled for this component. For more information, view the help command by running the RACADM command "racadm jobqueue help delete".
RAC1038.Message: Unable to clear pending values for the specified component.

LIC212.Description: The features are updated because the license was imported or deleted, or the license has expired.

VRM0012.Description: The Virtual Media server is already connected.
VRM0012.Message: The Virtual Media image server is already connected.

RDU0013.Description: The current power operational mode is non-redundant because of a power supply exception, a power supply inventory change, or a system power inventory change. The system was previously operating in a power redundant mode.
RDU0013.Resolution: Check the event log for power supply failures. Review system configuration and power consumption.

PDR56.Message: Bad block table on %1 is 80% full.
PDR56.Resolution: Replace the disk generating this message.
PDR56.Description: The bad block table is the table used for remapping bad disk blocks. This table fills as bad disk blocks are remapped. When the table is full, bad disk blocks are no longer remapped, which means that disk errors are no longer corrected. At this point, data loss can occur. The bad block table is now 80 percent full.

AMP0309.Message: Disk drive bay %1 current is greater than the upper critical threshold.
AMP0309.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0309.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.

AMP0323.Message: Chassis power level current is within range.

ASR0100.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate to the system board within the timeout period. The system was reset per the configured setting. (IPMI sensor type code 23h offset 01h event 3:0 - 2h).
ASR0100.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0100.Message: The BIOS watchdog timer reset the system.

RAC0632.Description: The requested network file share cannot be accessed, because an invalid hostname or IP address is entered.
RAC0632.Resolution: Enter a valid network file share hostname or IP address, and then retry the operation.
RAC0632.Message: Unable to access the network file share, because an invalid network file share hostname or IP address is entered.

SYS039.Description: The requested configuration changes have not passed the component specific verification checks, and therefore the changes will not be applied.
SYS039.Resolution: Check the scripts or related documentation and retry the operation.
SYS039.Message: Verification of requested configuration changes failed.

SUP0105.Description: The firmware image provided by the user is not valid.

SWC0061.Description: Write-protection is enabled on the vFlash SD card.
SWC0061.Resolution: Remove the write-protection on the vFlash SD card and retry the operation.

RAC0614.Description: The specified password was incorrect for the PKCS#12 file.
RAC0614.Resolution: Make sure to use the correct password for the PKCS#12 file. If the PKCS#12 file is encrypted with a password, add it in required password box. Leave the password box empty if the file was not encrypted with a password.

SYS441.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the index %1 entered is not a valid offset in the array.
SYS441.Resolution: Enter a valid index within the limits of the array and retry the operation.
SYS441.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the index entered as identified in the message is not a valid offset in the array.

BAR081.Description: Importing the Lifecycle Controller firmware image data is from the system profile backup file.

IOID004.Message: Virtual Address Persistence Policy setting for Non-Auxiliary powered devices is changed to %1.
IOID004.Description: The Virtual Address Persistence Policy setting for Non-Auxiliary powered devices is changed to the restart type identified in the message.

UEFI0113.Description: The Fault Resilient Memory (FRM) feature cannot be enabled because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the feature.
UEFI0113.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure the Memory Mirroring feature can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0113.Message: Unable to enable the Fault Resilient Memory (FRM) feature because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the feature.

SYS132.Description: An issue occurred while loading the OS Collector IPMI library. This may be because the OS collector binary images are not valid and need to be re-installed.
SYS132.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SYS132.Message: OS Collector: Unable to communicate with OS Collector IPMI library.

UEFI0204.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0204.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0204.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Clock Training FIFO Reset phase.

UEFI0231.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0231.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0231.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Write Leveling Training - Configuration Read phase.

RAC0610.Description: Different values were entered for passphrase and confirm passphrase field.
RAC0610.Resolution: Values entered in passphrase and confirm passphrase fields must be the same.
RAC0610.Message: The passphrase and confirm passphrase values entered do not match.

SWC0316.Description: The value for index must be greater than zero.
SWC0316.Resolution: Enter a positive value for index.
SWC0316.Message: The index must be greater than 0.

SYS248.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because the proxy credentials are not entered, or the proxy credentials entered do not correspond to an authorized user of the proxy server.
SYS248.Resolution: Make sure that the correct proxy credentials are entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS248.Description: The file cannot be transferred because proxy credentials are not entered, or the proxy credentials entered do not correspond to an authorized user of the proxy server.

RAC1000.Description: Unable to set the object value for iDRAC IPv6 Address and IPv6 Gateway, because the object IPv6 Autoconfig is enabled.
RAC1000.Resolution: Disable the object IPv6 AutoConfig using "racadm set iDRAC.IPv6.AutoConfig <0 | Disabled >", and retry the operation.
RAC1000.Message: Unable to set the object value for iDRAC IPv6 address or gateway.

IOV013.Description: Unable to assign a virtual adapter (VA) to a server that is already assigned a VA, because a server may be assigned only one VA.
IOV013.Resolution: Unassign the server's current virtual adapter (VA) and retry the operation. To unassign the VA using RACADM, run the following command "racadm setpciecfg".
IOV013.Message: Unable to assign a virtual adapter (VA) to a server that is already assigned a VA, because a server may be assigned only one VA.

RAC1063.Description: Unable to initiate the SystemErase operation because Lifecycle Controller is disabled.
RAC1063.Resolution: Run the RACADM command "racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState 1" to enable Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation.
RAC1063.Message: Unable to initiate the SystemErase operation because Lifecycle Controller is disabled.

SWC0293.Description: The specified object is not present in the iDRAC.
SWC0293.Message: The specified object is not recognized by iDRAC.

SYS005.Description: The AttributeName input array and AttributeValue input array do not have the same number of elements.
SYS005.Resolution: Verify AttributeName and AttributeValue pairs match and are valid. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services documentation.
SYS005.Message: AttributeName array and AttributeValue array element count mismatch.

UEFI0000.Description: A CPU type 0x00, divide by zero exception, (type 0x00) occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment. The software attempted to do a mathematical divide by zero, an illegal operation.
UEFI0000.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception.Update or remove the hardware or software.
UEFI0000.Message: CPU Exception Type 0x00: Divide by Zero (Software).

RED076.Description: Unable to create the Automatic Update schedule because an input parameter is invalid.
RED076.Resolution: Verify the values for all the input parameters are correct and retry the operation.
RED076.Message: Unable to create an Automatic Update schedule, because an invalid parameter is entered.

RED053.Description: Processing of update packages has completed.
RED053.Message: Processing of update packages has completed.

RAC1061.Description: The requested SystemErase operation was initiated successfully.
RAC1061.Resolution: Check the job status by running the RACADM command: "racadm jobqueue view -i <JobID>".

SYS071.Description: The export of Server Configuration Profile did not complete because the operation took too long.
SYS071.Resolution: Make sure the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) Lifecycle Controller setting is enabled and reboot the system. Retry the operation after CSIOR has completed. If the problem persists, reset iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for at least 15 seconds and retry the operation after iDRAC has fully restarted.
SYS071.Message: Server Configuration Profile export operation timed-out.

OSD68.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'ShareName' is missing.
OSD68.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "ShareName" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD68.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'ShareName' is missing.

PST0000.Description: The BIOS provided a progress code to the iDRAC, but that progress code is not recognized by the current iDRAC firmware.
PST0000.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Update the iDRAC firmware. 2) Restart the system and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

PCI3004.Message: Device option ROM on mezzanine card %1 failed to support Link Tuning or FlexAddress.
PCI3004.Resolution: Update BIOS, BMC/iDRAC, and mezzanine card firmware. If problem persists please contact customer support.
PCI3004.Description: Either the BIOS, BMC/iDRAC, or mezzanine card firmware is out of date and does not support FlexAddress.

RAC0131.Description: A separate message will provide more detail about this error which was detected while deleting the vFlash partition.
RAC0131.Message: An error has occurred while deleting a partition.

SWC8529.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to enable the iDRAC root user. This can happen if the communication to the iDRAC from CMC is non-functional or iDRAC is rebooting.
SWC8529.Resolution: If communications with the iDRAC is not functioning, reset the iDRAC and retry the operation after a few minutes. Run the RACADM command "racadm ping server-<slot number> " to check the communications. If the communications are not functional, restart the iDRAC by performing a Virtual Reseat of the server using the RACADM command "racadm racreset -m server-<slot id>".
SWC8529.Message: Chassis Management Controller unable to enable the iDRAC root user.

MEM1208.Message: Memory spare redundancy is lost. Check memory device at location %1.
MEM1208.Resolution: Review system logs for memory exceptions. Re-install memory at location <location>.
MEM1208.Description: The assigned spare is no longer available.

RAC0634.Description: The requested network file share cannot be accessed, because an invalid username is entered.
RAC0634.Resolution: Enter a valid network file share username, and then retry the operation.
RAC0634.Message: Unable to access the network file share, because an invalid network file share username is entered.

HWC4017.Message: A hardware incompatibility is detected between %1%2 and %3%4.
HWC4017.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Review system documentation for the hardware components identified in the message. 2) Replace unsupported components with supported components.
HWC4017.Description: The system has detected an unsupported hardware component. A hardware incompatibility is detected between the components identified in the message.

TMPS0100.Description: Inlet temperature has been above the warning threshold for duration of 8% or more for the operational time during the last one year.
TMPS0100.Resolution: This condition will occur if the ambient temperature is high. Make sure the ambient temperature of the environment is in normal range.
TMPS0100.Message: Inlet temperature is above warning level for extended duration.

SYS251.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because the file is not available at the source file path.
SYS251.Resolution: Check the file transfer parameters and retry the operation.
SYS251.Description: The file cannot be transferred because the file is not available at the source file path.

MEM0000.Message: Persistent correctable memory errors detected on a memory device at location(s) %1.
MEM0000.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
MEM0000.Description: The memory is operational. This is an early indicator of a possible future uncorrectable error.

SUP019.Description: For 11G systems: System Services must be enabled to perform the requested operation. System Services has been disabled through the iDRAC configuration utility accessed by pressing CTRL+E on boot up or through a remote operation. For 12G and above generations : Lifecycle Controller must be enabled to perform the requested operation. Lifecycle Controller has been disabled by pressing F2 Setup, selecting iDRAC Configuration, and selecting Lifecycle Controller Settings on boot up or through a remote operation.
SUP019.Resolution: For 11G systems: Use the iDRAC configuration utility to enable the System Services by pressing on the CTRL+E option on boot up at the targeted system. For 12G and above generations: Use F2 Setup, select iDRAC Configuration, and select Lifecycle Controller Settings, to enable the Lifecycle Controller on boot up of the targeted system.

PWR8654.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to send power allocation information to the component %1-%2.
PWR8654.Resolution: Perform a Virtual Reseat operation of the component, and then retry the operation. To virtually reseat a component, log in to the CMC Web interface, select Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components > select the option corresponding to the component, and then click Virtual Reseat.
PWR8654.Description: CMC could not successfully send the power allocation information to the component identified in the message, because either iDRAC is stopped after the power allocation was sent by CMC or the communication between CMC and iDRAC has ended.

UEFI0121.Description: The primary SD card is missing, not responding, or in write-protected mode.
UEFI0121.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Install a SD card media in the primary SD card slot. 2) Reseat or replace the SD card media. 3) If write-protected mode is expected, then no response action is required.
UEFI0121.Message: The primary SD card is missing, not responding, or in write-protected mode.

STOR311.Description: A drive firmware update was applied but requires a DC power cycle (cold boot) to activate. If the drive is internal to the system performing the update, no further action is required. If the drive is in an external enclosure, the enclosure must be turned off and then turned on in order for the updated drive firmware to activate.
STOR311.Resolution: If the drive is internal to the system performing the update, no further action is required. If the drive is in an external enclosure, the enclosure must be turned off and then turned on in order for the updated drive firmware to activate. After turning off the external enclosure, wait for drives to spin down before turning the enclosure back on. The drive firmware will activate after the enclosure is turned back on.
STOR311.Message: A firmware update was applied to a drive that requires a DC power cycle (cold boot). If the drive is in an external enclosure, the updated firmware will only be activated after a DC power cycle of the enclosure.

UEFI0212.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0212.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0212.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Early Command Training phase.

LIC904.Description: The network share is not accessible from the iDRAC.
LIC904.Resolution: Verify the network share connection and retry the operation.
LIC904.Message: Could not connect to network share.

BAR077.Description: The collection and export of host system firmware images was not successful.
BAR077.Resolution: Apply Dell Update Packages for all devices and software, and try the operation again. If the error continues, repair the Lifecycle Controller and apply the packages again, and retry the operation.
BAR077.Message: Unable to collect the Firmware images.

USR8511.Message: Login was successful %1 from %2 (username=%3, type=%4, sid=%5)
USR8511.Description: Successful login from IP address by Username identified in the message.

RAC0630.Description: The job cannot be scheduled, because the requested network file share type is not supported.
RAC0630.Resolution: Enter a correct network file share type, and then retry the operation.
RAC0630.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid network file share type is entered.

MEM1017.Message: Memory device at location %1 is installed correctly.

SYS043.Description: The current configuration of the system components (BIOS, RAID, NIC, iDRAC, and so on) was written to a Server Configuration Profile and successfully copied to the specified location.

SWC0128.Description: The Common Name field is necessary for generating a CSR. It is not generated if Common Name is empty.
SWC0128.Resolution: Configure the Common Name field by using config command.
SWC0128.Message: The Common Name (CN) field of the CSR Security group must be configured before a CSR can be generated.

VRM0020.Description: Racadm tool failed to obtain the data.
VRM0020.Message: Unable to determine current Remote Image state.

SWC0027.Description: The backup Server Profile operation successfully completed.
SWC0027.Message: Successfully backed up a Server Profile by using the Lifecycle Controller GUI.

RAC928.Description: Racadm unable to set the recurrence value. This occurs if the underlying instrumentation do not set the value.
RAC928.Resolution: Wait for a few minutes and retry the command. If the problem persists, contact the service provider.
RAC928.Message: Unable to modify the recurrence value.

SWC0263.Description: The length of path to the firmware image is longer than the specified value.
SWC0263.Resolution: Enter a shorter path to the firmware image file.

UEFI0228.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0228.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0228.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Receive Enable Training - Configuration Write phase.

BAR101.Description: Importing license data from the backup Server Profile.

PFM0003.Message: The value of %1 is less than the lower warning threshold.
PFM0003.Resolution: The workload on server is almost zero. Consider assigning additional workloads to the server.
PFM0003.Description: The utilization value of the sensor identified in the message is lower than the lower warning threshold value.

RAC0690.Description: The iDRAC Service Module is not installed on the operating system of the server.
RAC0690.Resolution: Install the iDRAC Service Module and retry the operation.
RAC0690.Message: The iDRAC Service Module is not installed on the operating system of the server.

ENC12.Description: Communication with an enclosure has been restored. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

STOR028.Description: The requested operation cannot be completed because the specified virtual disk is not found.
STOR028.Resolution: Provide a valid virtual disk FQDD (Fully Qualified Device Descriptor) and retry the operation.

LC081.Description: The Server Screen Shot export operation cannot be completed because of internal firmware issues.
LC081.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart iDRAC by invoking the WS-Man iDRACReset method which is defined in the DCIM_iDRACCardService class (input parameters are not required for this method), and then retry the operation.
LC081.Message: Unable to complete the Server Screen Shot export operation because of internal firmware issues.

PWR2202.Message: The system is sleeping with lost processor context.

RAC974.Description: The value specified for the wait time (w) option is invalid. The valid range is 300 to 3600 seconds.
RAC974.Resolution: Make sure to specify a valid wait time (-w) option and retry the command. The range of supported values are 300 to 3600 seconds.

SWC0077.Description: iDRAC is unable to initiate the Repurpose or Retire System operation because the iDRAC is not responding or another operation is in progress.
SWC0077.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, do one the following: 1) Check if there are other operations running on the iDRAC and wait for the operations to complete, and retry the operation. 2) Restart the server, and retry the operation.
SWC0077.Message: Unable to initiate the Repurpose or Retire System operation.

RAC979.Description: The custom signing certificate was extracted from the Public Key Cryptography Standards version 12 (PKCS12) file and applied to the system configuration.
RAC979.Message: Successfully uploaded the custom signing certificate to iDRAC.

SWC8602.Message: Quick Deploy Profile for server %1 was not successful.
SWC8602.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, make sure any other operations have completed and then retry the operation.
SWC8602.Description: The system is busy with other operations. The feature was unable to get mutex.

SWC0127.Description: The file may be write protected and hence could not be edited.
SWC0127.Resolution: Check if the file is write protected.
SWC0127.Message: Unable to open file for writing.

CTL16.Message: None of the %1 properties are set.
CTL16.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

LC021.Description: The contents of the PKCS12 parameter was not valid because: 1) not a valid PKCS12 file 2) not a valid pfx file 3) did not contain a valid key.
LC021.Resolution: Validate that the PKCS12 file was Base64 encoded. OpenSSL can be used to create or validate a PKCS12 file.
LC021.Message: PKCS12 decrypt of private key could not complete.

SWC1914.Description: Network Time Protocol configuration is disabled.
SWC1914.Message: Network Time Protocol configuration is disabled.

SYS8500.Resolution: If no errors are shown, no response is required. If errors are listed in the message, navigate to the named servers and make sure that IDRAC and Lifecycle Controller firmware versions are the latest available.
SYS8500.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) sent messages to delay power throttling to all capable servers in the chassis. This was done because the CMC firmware was updated or a failover was initiated. If specific server errors are shown in the message, verify that the iDRAC and Lifecycle Controller firmware versions on those servers is updated to the most current version available.

UEFI0147.Description: The system hardware or cabling configuration is invalid.
UEFI0147.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Make sure the system cables, risers, and CPU configuration are installed correctly. 2) Reseat each PCIe riser and reconnect the cables. For more information, see the system Owner's Manual.
UEFI0147.Message: The system hardware or cabling configuration is invalid.

ASR0104.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate within the timeout period. The system was powered cycled. (IPMI sensor 23h offset - 03h event 3:0 - 4h).
ASR0104.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0104.Message: The OS watchdog timer powered cycle the system.

HWC4019.Description: The fan speed cannot be controlled because a sled mismatch or hardware incompatibility is detected. This results in fans rotating at the maximum allowed speed (RPM).
HWC4019.Resolution: Remove the sled in which a hardware incompatibility is detected and replace with a compatible working sled. For more information about hardware compatibility, see the platform Owners Manual available on the support site.
HWC4019.Message: Unable to control the fan speed because a sled mismatch or hardware incompatibility is detected.

RAC024.Description: Unable to VLAN is Disabled so cannot set VLAN Priority because VLAN is Disabled.
RAC024.Resolution: Enable VLAN to set VLAN Priority.
RAC024.Message: Unable to VLAN is Disabled so cannot set VLAN Priority because VLAN is Disabled.

SYS172.Description: A Remote Diagnostic operation has been interrupted because the server was restarted during the operation.
SYS172.Resolution: Make sure that there are no diagnostic operations in progress before restarting the server or wait for the Remote Diagnostic operation to complete.
SYS172.Message: A Remote Diagnostic operation has been interrupted.

RAC0121.Description: SD card not readable. The card must be initialized.
RAC0121.Resolution: Initialize the SD card before it can be used.

ISM0015.Description: The iDRAC Service Module detected a change in the host name of the server OS.
ISM0015.Message: The iDRAC Service Module detected a change in the host name of the server operating system (OS).

SWC8619.Message: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to process data from the server in slot %1.
SWC8619.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) Make sure the latest firmware is installed on the network cards and iDRAC on the server identified in the message. 2) Reset the Chassis Management Controller. 3) Reset the server iDRAC. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8619.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to process inventory data from the server in the slot identified in the message. This can happen if: 1) There is a communications issue between the CMC and the iDRAC on the server identified in the message. 2) Incorrect firmware is installed on network cards. 3) Incorrect firmware is installed on the server iDRAC. 4) There is no free temporary storage in the CMC.

PSU500.Description: Racadm tool cannot obtain the power status possible reason is that the IPMI call failed.
PSU500.Message: Unable to get the current server power status.

SYS188.Description: Unable to perform the import operation because the specified file has a file size of zero, which is not valid.
SYS188.Resolution: Make sure the import configuration file is valid before retrying the operation.
SYS188.Message: Unable to perform the import operation because the specified file has a file size of zero, which is not valid.

OSE1003.Resolution: Review system boot configuration and boot media. Verify the media in C: is bootable. See system video for additional information.

SWC0003.Description: An unrecoverable error occurred while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0003.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0003.Message: Unable to display the Lifecycle log.

USR8508.Message: %1 login was not successful (username=%2, ip=%3, reason=%4)
USR8508.Resolution: Maximum sessions already in use, so close any of existing session and retry the operation.
USR8508.Description: The login attempt with details specified in the message was not successful.

RAC0263.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the Alternate IPv6 DNS Server address does not conform to the required format.
RAC0263.Resolution: Enter a valid Alternate IPv6 DNS server address.
RAC0263.Message: The Alternate IPv6 DNS Server Address is invalid.

UEFI0065.Description: One or more attributes are successfully configured. The system is automatically turned off in 5 seconds.
UEFI0065.Message: One or more attributes are successfully configured. The system will be automatically turned off in 5 seconds.

SUP0534.Description: The catalog file cannot be found in the specified location.
SUP0534.Resolution: Specify the correct repository location and retry the operation.
SUP0534.Message: Unable to locate the catalog file.

BAT0015.Resolution: Check the battery at the next service window.
BAT0015.Description: System settings may be preserved if input power is not removed from the power supplies.

UEFI0263.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the network cable is not connected.
UEFI0263.Resolution: Check the network cable connection of the system and retry the operation.
UEFI0263.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the network cable is not connected.

RDU0005.Description: One of more fans have failed or have been removed or a configuration change occurred which requires additional fans.
RDU0005.Resolution: Remove and re-install failed fans or install additional fans.
RDU0005.Message: The fans are not redundant. Insufficient resources to maintain normal operations.

STOR0109.Description: No power supply unit data to display. The system is powered off, no power supply unit is present in the system, or the power supply unit is not connected to the enclosure.
STOR0109.Resolution: Check if the server has power, enclosure power supply unit is available, and power supply unit is connected to the enclosure.
STOR0109.Message: Power supply unit is not connected to the enclosure or data about power supply unit is unavailable.

TMP0124.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0124.Message: Disk drive bay temperature is less than the lower warning threshold.

RED013.Description: The DUP specified is not compatible with the target device.
RED013.Resolution: Download and use the DUP that matches the device being targeted.
RED013.Message: The DUP specified is not compatible with the target device.

CTL49.Message: The NVRAM has corrupted data on %1.
CTL49.Resolution: No response action is required as the controller is taking the required corrective action. However, If this message is generated often (such as during each reboot), then replace the controller.
CTL49.Description: The NVRAM has corrupted data. This may occur after a power surge, a battery failure, or for other reasons. The controller is reinitializing the NVRAM.

UEFI0005.Description: A CPU math coprocessor not available (type 0x07) exception occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0005.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.
UEFI0005.Message: CPU Exception Type 0x07: Math Coprocessor Not Available (Hardware).

RFL2008.Message: Internal Dual SD Module %1 is disabled.
RFL2008.Description: The Internal Dual SD Card redundancy feature was disabled. The SD card identified in the message is disabled.

UEFI0101.Description: The total amount of installed memory has exceeded the amount supported by the platform.
UEFI0101.Resolution: Remove memory modules from the system to reduce the total amount of installed memory. For more information on installed memory limit, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0101.Message: Total amount of installed memory has exceeded limit.

RAC0286.Description: When creating a user account, the New Password and Confirm New Password fields cannot be empty.
RAC0286.Resolution: Enter valid passwords for New Password and Confirm New Password.
RAC0286.Message: New Password and Confirm New Password fields cannot be empty.

OSE1009.Resolution: Review system boot configuration and boot media. Verify the media in the CDROM is bootable. See system video for additional information.

LC006.Description: The Auto-Discovery action selected is invalid.
LC006.Resolution: Verify that the selected Auto-Discovery action is supported. The supported commands are documented in the Lifecycle Controller User Guide.

RAC965.Description: Any operation involving remote share (CIFS) cannot continue if the location (-l) is not specified. The u and p options represent the user name and password for the remote share, and -l represents the location of the remote share.
RAC965.Resolution: Make sure to specify the location (-l) of the remote share along with the user name and password, and retry the operation. To view the list of options that can used for the required subcommand, use the racadm help <subcommand> command.
RAC965.Message: The -l option must be specified if -u and -p are used.

DIS002.Description: Use the Lifecycle Controller or other service to enable Auto Discovery and restart.
DIS002.Resolution: If you want AutoDiscovery to locate a Provisioning Server, enable this feature.

PDR53.Message: A redundant path has been restored for %1.
PDR53.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC1046.Description: Unable to view the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings because the feature has not been configured.
RAC1046.Resolution: Configure the Automatic Update feature by running the RACADM command "racadm autoupdatescheduler create" with the desired option settings.
RAC1046.Message: Unable to view the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings because the feature has not been configured.

RAC027.Description: Unable to set static values for Speed or Duplex when the Auto Negotiation attribute is enabled.
RAC027.Resolution: Disable Auto Negotiation in order to set values for Speed or Duplex.
RAC027.Message: Unable to set values for Speed or Duplex because Auto Negotiation is Enabled.

SUP0125.Message: Current firmware update status is unknown

SWC0120.Description: The syntax of the sslcertview command is invalid.
SWC0120.Resolution: Refer the help text for sslcertview subcommand.
SWC0120.Message: Invalid syntax. Certificate type (-t) must be specified.

RAC0137.Description: A separate message will provide more detail about this error which was detected while changing the read-write state of the vFlash partition.
RAC0137.Message: An error has occurred while changing the read-write state for the partition.

PDR48.Description: This message is generated after rebuild resumes on a physical disk.

VF023.Description: Partition with this label exists. Duplicate labels are not supported.

BAR042.Description: Lifecycle Controller/System services are not available. There is another operation using the resources at this time.
BAR042.Resolution: Wait for the other operation to release the resources, as indicated by the System Services option presence and retry the operation.

MEM0600.Message: Memory device was added at location %1.

USR0174.Description: The Front Panel USB device is removed from the operating system.
USR0174.Message: The Front Panel USB device is removed from the operating system.

RAC1229.Message: Unable to initiate the %1 firmware update.
RAC1229.Resolution: Wait until the existing firmware update jobs are completed or scheduled before retrying the operation.
RAC1229.Description: A new firmware update job cannot be initiated while an existing firmware update job is still in one of these states: "New", "Downloading", or "Running".

RAC948.Description: A test event notification for the specified message ID was not sent to the configured destination.
RAC948.Resolution: Make sure to the use a valid message ID, set the required notification filter, and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC948.Message: Unable to send the notification for the specified event to the configured destination.

CMC8576.Description: The RAC CA Certificate is changed.
CMC8576.Message: The RAC CA Certificate is changed.

SWC8615.Description: A profile was successfully generated from a server.

CTL90.Message: %1 is not operating in Fault Tolerant Mode because of an incompatible peer controller.
CTL90.Resolution: Replace the peer controller with the same model controller as the controller identified in the message.
CTL90.Description: The peer controller is not compatible with the controller identified in the message because of a hardware mismatch.

PDR100.Message: Dedicated Hot Spare %1 no longer useful for all arrays.
PDR100.Resolution: Verify that the disk is healthy and that it has not been removed. Check the cables. See the Cables Attached Correctly section for more information on checking the cables. If necessary, replace the disk and reassign the dedicated hot spare.
PDR100.Description: The controller is not able to communicate with a disk that is assigned as a dedicated hot spare. The disk may have been removed. There may also be a bad or loose cable.

VDR94.Message: Controller preserved cache was recovered for %1.
VDR94.Description: This message occurs if the controller pinned cache is recovered.

STOR018.Description: This operation did not detect any foreign drives. This may be because no foreign drives are present or the only foreign drives are in a secured locked state.
STOR018.Resolution: If the only foreign drives present are in a secured locked state, run a secure erase operation on the drives to securely erase data or unlock these drives and retry the operation. Otherwise the operation was not successful because there are no foreign drives.

SYS236.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported username value.
SYS236.Resolution: Make sure that the correct username value is used, and then retry the operation.
SYS236.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an unsupported username value.

CPU0012.Message: Correctable Machine Check Exception detected on CPU %1.
CPU0012.Resolution: Review System Event Log and Operating System Logs. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

SWC0106.Description: The specified option is not supported on the RAC.
SWC0106.Message: The -u option is not supported on the current RAC configuration.

RAC0688.Message: Applying this configuration operation will also apply all existing pending operations on the %1.
RAC0688.Resolution: Click Create Job button to create the configuration job. Click Cancel to quit job creation.
RAC0688.Description: Applying this configuration operation will also apply all existing pending operations on the controller identified in the message.

VLT0232.Message: The mezzanine card %1 %2 voltage is greater than the upper warning threshold.
VLT0232.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the mezzanine card.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0232.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

LOG303.Description: Unable to rename current Chassis Log file during archive operation. Some log entries may be lost.
LOG303.Message: Unable to archive the Chassis Log file.

OSD34.Description: Unable to continue with BootToPXE command because the system has an ISO image attached. Detach the ISO image before continuing with BootToPXE.
OSD34.Resolution: Run the DetachISOImage command and then run BootToPXE.
OSD34.Message: Unable to continue with BootToPXE - ISO image is attached to the system.

UEFI0223.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0223.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0223.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Receive Buffer Per Bit Deskew Training phase.

BAR112.Description: Server Profile backup file validation failed because the target system identifier information does not match the value stored in the file. The Server Profile file may be from another system or the iDRAC may need to be restarted to acquire the system identifier information accurately.
BAR112.Resolution: Obtain a valid Server Profile file for the target system and try the operation again. If the problem reoccurs, restart the iDRAC and try the operation again.
BAR112.Message: The system identifier in the Server Profile file does not match the target system.

STOR0101.Description: No RAID controller data to display. The system is powered off, no RAID controller is present in the system, or the RAID controller is not connected to the system.
STOR0101.Resolution: Check if the server has power, RAID controller is available, and that a RAID controller is connected to the system.

RDU0004.Description: One of more fans have failed or have been removed or a configuration change occurred which requires additional fans.
RDU0004.Resolution: Remove and re-install failed fans or install additional fans.

BAR065.Description: Collecting the Integrated Remote Access Controller configuration and copying it into the server profile backup file.
BAR065.Message: Collecting Integrated Remote Access Controller configuration.

ASR8500.Description: Watchdog timer is disabled. The watchdog timer is an internal mechanism used to monitor the health of the Chassis Management Controller. The watchdog timer could be disabled as part of a troubleshooting operation and can be enabled by restarting the Chassis Management Controller.

SWC0295.Description: The object name specified is incorrect.
SWC0295.Resolution: Refer to the list of objects in the group and choose the correct one.

OSD41.Description: vFlash does not contain the ISO Image because either the image was deleted, or it was never copied.
OSD41.Resolution: Download the ISO Image to the vFlash again using the DownloadISOToVFlash method.
OSD41.Message: ISO Image not found on VFlash.

SYS402.Description: The method cannot be run because the requested HTTP method is not allowed.
SYS402.Resolution: Enter a valid HTTP method and retry the operation. For information about valid methods, see the Redfish Users Guide available on the support site.
SYS402.Message: Unable to run the method because the requested HTTP method is not allowed.

LC082.Description: Unable to complete the requested operation because the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) attribute setting is disabled on the system.
LC082.Resolution: Enable the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) attribute setting and then retry the operation. To enable the CSIOR setting using the RACADM command line utility, type "racadm set lifecyclecontroller.LCAttributes.CollectSystemInventoryOnRestart Enabled".
LC082.Message: Unable to complete the requested operation because the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) attribute setting is disabled on the system.

UEFI0167.Message: Unable to configure memory interleaving on DIMM modules on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0167.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure interleaving can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0167.Description: Memory could not be interleaved because the number of allowable Rank Interleave Register (RIR) rules exceeded during memory initialization.

STOR046.Description: Unable to complete the create virtual disk operation because the StartingLBA and Size value combination results in an overlapping virtual disk.
STOR046.Resolution: Refer to the users guide to provide the correct StartingLBA and Size combination values.
STOR046.Message: The specified StartingLBA and Size values combination result in an overlapping virtual disk.

PSU0019.Message: The input power for power supply %1 has been restored.

SWC8600.Message: The selected profile was not applied to %1.
SWC8600.Resolution: Make sure that profile versions are compatible with target servers when attempting application of profiles to servers.
SWC8600.Description: The profile version must be compatible with the server generation and Lifecycle Controller firmware version.

VF002.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an internal issue with the firmware.
VF002.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Rerun the command after about 2 minutes 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.

SYS120.Description: The OS Collector application did not complete its task within the maximum allowed time and the operation is cancelled. This may be because the server OS is not supported by the OS Collector application and the application is unable to function correctly.
SYS120.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Make sure that the OS Collector application supports the OS installed on the server. If the OS is not supported, the OS Collector may not function correctly. 2) Reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation. To install the OS Collector using the iDRAC Web UI, get the latest OC Collector update package and then select the Update and Rollback link from the iDRAC Web UI home page and upload the install package. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SYS120.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the OS Collector is taking too much time. The operation is cancelled.

IOV102.Message: A PCIe adapter %1 is removed from %2 %3.
IOV102.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected the removal of an adapter card from the slot identified in the message.

RAC969.Description: The import operation cannot continue if the value specified for the shutdown option (-b) is incorrect. The supported values are "Graceful" and "Forced".
RAC969.Resolution: Make sure to specify either "Graceful" or "Forced" for the shutdown (-b) option.
RAC969.Message: Incorrect value specified for the shutdown option.

DH005.Resolution: Close other iDRAC sessions and activities. Try again.
DH005.Message: CA Cert is corrupted, expired, or does not have signing privileges.

SEL9900.Description: The current software version cannot decode this event. The source of the event may come from a source that is not compatible with this software or the event may have been added after the release of this software. You may need to review this event using a tool which displays raw data such as Ipmitool with the -vvv option or Racadm with the -E option.

IOID115.Message: Unable to configure the target settings properties of the %1 Port %2.
IOID115.Resolution: Make sure that the iSCSI or FCoE partition of the network port is enabled. Check whether or not the network controller is working.
IOID115.Description: The target settings properties of the NIC port identified in the message could not be configured, because either iSCSI or FCoE partition of the network port is not enabled; or, the network controller is not functioning.

RAC0246.Description: The contents of a read-only partition cannot be modified.
RAC0246.Resolution: Make sure the partition is writable before attempting to change its contents.

SYS070.Description: The configuration changes that require system reboot into the UEFI environment on the system did not complete for all components.
SYS070.Message: Configuration changes that require system reboot were not applied.

SUP026.Message: The input value entered for the parameter %1 is invalid.
SUP026.Resolution: Correct the specified input value and retry the operation.
SUP026.Description: The value entered for the parameter identified in the message is invalid.

UEFI0267.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the IPv4 initiator gateway address is invalid.
UEFI0267.Resolution: Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings page, make sure there is no typographical error in the Initiator Gateway field, and retry the operation.
UEFI0267.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the IPv4 initiator gateway address is invalid.

RAC0113.Description: Data entered is not an integer value in the valid range of numbers.
RAC0113.Resolution: Enter a Remote Syslog Port number. Expected range: [1-65535 or 0x1-0xFFFF].
RAC0113.Message: Remote Syslog Port value is invalid: Valid range is 1-65535 or 0x1-0xFFFF.

DIS010.Resolution: Refer to Lifecycle Controller Remote Services User's Guide for additional information for LCD messages.
DIS010.Description: The Auto Discovery process has encountered a problem. One of the following messages will be displayed on the LCD display and entered in the LC log: 1) No credentials returned, 2) Blocked Because Admin Account Enabled, 3) Blocked Because IPv6 Enabled, 4) No IP on NIC, 5) No provisioning server found, 6) Provisioning server is unreachable/invalid address, 7) SSL connection failed no service at IP/port, 8) SSL connection refused, 9) SSL connection failed (Server authentication), 10) SSL connection failed (client authentication), 11) SSL connection failed other, 12) SOAP failure, 13) Failed to create account, 14) Blocked Because Active Directory Enabled, 15) No Service Tag, and 16) Unknown.

OSD10.Description: Installation for the selected operating system is not supported. Make sure that the correct operating system name was entered.
OSD10.Resolution: Recheck the operating system name with the output of GetDriverPackInfo().
OSD10.Message: Installation not supported for the selected operating system.

BIOS025.Description: The status of the password is Locked in BIOS and must be set to Unlocked for the operation to succeed.
BIOS025.Resolution: Change BIOS password status in the BIOS setup from Locked to Unlocked and retry the operation.
BIOS025.Message: Unable set the BIOS password as the BIOS password status is locked.

VF004.Resolution: Refer the iDRAC and Lifecycle Controller User Guides for the required input parameters for this method.
VF004.Description: The value of the input parameter identified in the message is not a valid value.

RAC052.Description: Unable to create a configuration job because an existing configuration job is already in progress. Only one configuration job for a component can run or can be processed at any time.
RAC052.Resolution: Retry the operation after the existing configuration job is complete, or cancel the existing configuration job and retry the operation.
RAC052.Message: Unable to create a configuration job because an existing configuration job is already in progress.

SWC0238.Description: The key specified by the public key is too long.
SWC0238.Resolution: Request for a valid public key from the system and re-try the command.

CMC8557.Message: The system health failover is requested. Code %1.
CMC8557.Description: The code number specified in the message is displayed after a firmware error occurs before a failover .
