SYS173.Description: The TTY Log cannot be retrieved because another operation is in progress on the RAID controller.
SYS173.Resolution: Do the following: 1) View the job queue and make sure all jobs are in a completed state. 2) Retry the operation.
SYS173.Message: Unable to retrieve the TTY Log because another operation is in progress on the RAID controller.

UEFI0035.Description: The BIOS passwords are disabled because the PWRD_EN jumper is removed from the system board.
UEFI0035.Resolution: To enable the BIOS passwords, install the PWRD_EN jumper.
UEFI0035.Message: The BIOS passwords are disabled because the PWRD_EN jumper is removed from the system board.

SYS133.Description: An issue was encountered while creating an IPMI session.
SYS133.Resolution: Restart the WMI service and retry the operation.

CTL62.Message: %1 on %2 has missing drives and will go offline at boot.
CTL62.Description: Physical disk(s) have been removed from a virtual disk. The virtual disk will be in Failed state during the next system reboot. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

FC003.Description: An invalid number of arguments was provided to the method.
FC003.Resolution: Enter required input parameters and retry. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller User's Guide or the FC HBA Profile specification.

RAC040.Resolution: Verify that all required parameters are provided. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
RAC040.Description: One or more required parameters needed for the method invoked in the operation are missing.

JCP012.Description: The requested operation requires memory or file space allocation. The operation failed due to lack of memory or file space in the iDRAC.
JCP012.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset iDRAC and retry the operation.
JCP012.Message: The operation failed due to an internal iDRAC error.

FAN0018.Message: Enhanced Cooling Mode is not supported for fan %1.
FAN0018.Resolution: Replace the fan identified in the message with another fan which supports Enhanced Cooling Mode.
FAN0018.Description: Enhanced Cooling Mode is not supported by the type of fan identified in the message.

OSD61.Description: The IP Address format is invalid and cannot be validated. The specified IP address may not be a valid IPv4 or IPv6 address.
OSD61.Resolution: Verify the IP address format and retry the operation.

PSU0914.Message: A predictive failure detected on power unit %1.
PSU0914.Resolution: Remove input power and re-install supply at the next service window.
PSU0914.Description: Status from the power supply indicates a power supply exception occurred. The power supply will try to operate. System Performance and power redundancy may be degraded or lost.

SWC0059.Description: The vFlash partitions are being used by other applications such as Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services or RACADM.
SWC0059.Resolution: Wait until the current operations are complete and retry the operation. For information, see the FAQs section of the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services or RACADM User Guide.

VLT0105.Message: Processor module %1 voltage is within range.

TMP0125.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0125.Message: Disk drive bay temperature is less than the lower critical threshold.

DIS008.Message: Notification of iDRAC IP address changed to %1 from %2 sent to Provisioning Server.
DIS008.Description: iDRAC IP address change in progress with Provisioning Server.

VDR22.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SUP017.Description: The specified start time is invalid.
SUP017.Resolution: Start Time should be in the form YYYYMMDDHHMMSS. Or it should be TIME_NOW to specify an immediate update or reboot. Verify the specified start time and retry the action.

PDR1003.Message: Drive %1 in disk drive bay %2 is the hot-spare drive.

FAN904.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode cannot be enabled because the Maximum Power Conservation Mode is enabled.
FAN904.Resolution: Disable the Maximum Power Conservation Mode, and then retry the operation. To disable the mode by using CMC Web interface, click Chassis Overview > Power > Configuration. To disable the mode using the RACADM utility, run the command "racadm config -g cfgThermal -o cfgThermalEnhancedCoolingMode 0".
FAN904.Message: Cannot enable the Enhanced Cooling Mode because the Maximum Power Conservation Mode is enabled.

VLT0205.Message: The system board %1 voltage is within range.

SWU8558.Description: Invalid firmware: The uploaded firmware image validation was unsuccessful.
SWU8558.Resolution: Use a valid firmware image and retry the operation.
SWU8558.Message: Invalid firmware: The uploaded firmware image validation was unsuccessful.

PWR8540.Message: Power Remote Logging Interval set to %1.
PWR8540.Description: The interval for remote logging of power information is set to the value identified in the message.

RAC924.Description: The inlet temperature history was successfully exported to the specified file.

SWC8525.Message: Unable to add member to Chassis Group. Maximum members supported is %1.
SWC8525.Resolution: Try removing an existing member and retry the operation.
SWC8525.Description: Unable to add member because the maximum number of Chassis Group members indicated in the message has been reached.

RED0101.Description: The firmware was rolled back to the previous version.

SWC0217.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0217.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0217.Message: The -c option requires -u to also be specified.

SWC0304.Description: The syntax of the fwupdate command is invalid.
SWC0304.Resolution: Refer the help text for fwupdate subcommand.
SWC0304.Message: The -g option requires -u to also be specified.

RFL2009.Message: Internal Dual SD Module %1 is enabled.
RFL2009.Description: The Internal Dual SD Card redundancy feature was enabled. The SD card identified in the message is enabled.

RED077.Description: Unable to get the Automatic Update schedule information because the schedule is not configured.
RED077.Message: Unable to get the Automatic Update schedule information.

PWR8583.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because unacknowledged 110V PSUs are present.
PWR8583.Resolution: On the Power Configuration page, in the Web UI, select the Allow 110VAC Operation for power supplies and retry the operation. Using the RACADM utility, run the following command, "racadm config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisAllow110VACOperation 1".
PWR8583.Description: To enable 110V operation, the Allow 110VAC Operation feature must be enabled. If the feature is not enabled, the server turn-on operation will not be processed.

PDR85.Resolution: Verify the disk is a Secure Encrypted Disk and is not locked. If it is not, replace the disk with a Secure Encrypted Disk. See the storage hardware documentation for more information.
PDR85.Description: Errors were detected with security related operations on the disk. The data on the disk might not be retrieved or stored successfully. In addition, the security of the stored data might be at risk.

SWC0251.Message: Invalid index value. Only index values %1 - %1 are permitted.
SWC0251.Resolution: Enter the index value as specified by the message.
SWC0251.Description: The value of specified parameter is invalid.

CTL80.Message: %1 experienced the following warning during startup: %2.
CTL80.Resolution: To resolve this issue, see Troubleshooting section in the Dell Shared PowerEdge RAID Controller (SPERC8) documentation.
CTL80.Description: The controller identified in the message has an issue as displayed in the message.

SYS097.Description: The Lifecycle Controller State has been set to disabled by the configuration profile import operation. Further changes to the system configuration require the Lifecycle Controller State to be enabled before the changes are processed.
SYS097.Resolution: If further configuration changes are required for the system, the Lifecycle Controller State must be enabled prior to attempting the configuration change. To enable the Lifecycle Controller State, run the racadm command "racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState Enabled".
SYS097.Message: The state of Lifecycle Controller is disabled by the configuration profile import operation.

LOG501.Description: The command cannot be run because a general issue occurred.
LOG501.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the CMC, and then retry the operation.
LOG501.Message: Unable to run the command because of a general issue.

USR8513.Description: Successful login from IP address identified in the message by username identified in the message.

ISM0029.Description: Unable to complete the iDRAC Hard Reset operation because BIOS on the server does not support this feature.
ISM0029.Resolution: Install the required BIOS version and retry the operation. To know about the recommended BIOS version, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
ISM0029.Message: Unable to complete the iDRAC Hard Reset operation because BIOS on the server does not support this feature.

BAT0006.Message: The storage battery is operating normally.

UEFI0232.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0232.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0232.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Write Leveling Training - Configuration Write phase.

LC035.Description: This method is not supported in this version of Firmware.
LC035.Resolution: Update the iDRAC firmware to a version that supports this method.
LC035.Message: As-Shipped Hardware Inventory Export method is not supported.

SUP0113.Description: The cfgRhostsFwUpdateTftpEnable object must be set.
SUP0113.Resolution: Set the cfgRhostsFwUpdateTftpEnable object in cfgRemoteHosts group using config subcommand.
SUP0113.Message: TFTP firmware update is currently disabled.

SWC0132.Description: Either the destination Ip address is not reachable or the required values are not configured.
SWC0132.Resolution: Check for the connectivity to the configured Ip address.
SWC0132.Message: Unable to send test trap. Please make sure that your trap has been configured correctly and connectivity to the destination endpoint exists.

RAC1175.Description: The user configuration cannot be modified, because modification is not allowed at index 1.
RAC1175.Message: Unable to change the user configuration because modifying the user configuration at index 1 is not allowed.

RAC072.Description: The iDRAC reset to factory defaults operation cannot be completed because a firmware upgrade operation is in progress.
RAC072.Resolution: Wait for the current update process to complete and retry the operation.
RAC072.Message: Unable to perform the iDRAC reset to factory defaults operation because the firmware upgrade is in progress.

BAR026.Description: The configuration is being set for each component.

HWC7000.Message: Server %1 health changed to a normal state.

RAC0159.Description: Certificate upload failed because there is no pending Certificate Signing Request (CSR) or private key.
RAC0159.Resolution: Upload failed due to no pending Certificate Signing Request (CSR). Try creating a new CSR and then upload the certificate.
RAC0159.Message: Certificate upload failed: No pending CSR or private key.

RED008.Description: The firmware payloads in the Update Package cannot be extracted. This may be because the file is not valid or the security signature cannot be verified.
RED008.Resolution: Re-acquire the Update Package from the service provider.
RED008.Message: Unable to extract payloads from Update Package.

SWC0267.Description: Unable to edit the SD card, since it is write protected.
SWC0267.Resolution: Check if the SD card is write protected. If yes, disable the write protection.
SWC0267.Message: Unable to perform the requested operation. Make sure a non write protected SD card is inserted.

RAC0669.Description: Initializing the virtual disk will permanently delete data from the virtual disk.
RAC0669.Message: Initializing the virtual disk will permanently delete data from the virtual disk.

STOR047.Message: Unable to change the value of attribute %1 because it is ReadOnly.
STOR047.Description: Unable to change the value of the attribute identified in the message because it is ReadOnly.

UEFI0258.Description: An issue is observed on the Hard-drive/SSD backplane.
UEFI0258.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Make sure the correct type of Hard-drive/SSD backplane is installed. 2) Check the configuration of Hard-drive/SSD backplane and make sure its power cable is connected. Restart the system and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0258.Message: An issue is observed on the Hard-drive/SSD backplane.

RAC0621.Description: The message appears in Job Queue page when the iDRAC firmware update job status is completed. Communication to the iDRAC will be lost .
RAC0621.Resolution: The iDRAC will be ready for login once the restart is complete.
RAC0621.Message: Successfully completed the iDRAC firmware update. All current user sessions will be closed.

FC013.Resolution: Enter the correct AttributeName available for the component in the system. Identify the correct AttributeName from the attribute enumeration response for the component or refer to the FC HBA Profile specification.
FC013.Description: An incorrect AttributeName parameter name was provided.

PWR8676.Message: Unable to set the chassis power property %1.
PWR8676.Description: The chassis power property identified in the message cannot be set.

SYS406.Description: The configuration operation cannot be started because the System Lockdown mode is enabled.
SYS406.Resolution: Make sure that the Lockdown.1.SystemLockdown attribute is set to Disabled by running the HTTP PATCH method on "Managers OemAttributes" Redfish API, and then retry the operation.
SYS406.Message: Unable to start the configuration operation because the System Lockdown mode is enabled.

VDR11.Description: This message is generated after initialization of a virtual disk starts.

SYS060.Description: Some configuration changes for the component identified by the Fully Qualified Device Descriptor (FQDD) in the configuration job results were not successfully applied.
SYS060.Resolution: Export the Lifecycle Log and identify the configuration changes that did not complete or retrieve the configuration results using the GetConfigResults() method. Retry those changes that did not complete in a separate import operation.

RFM1027.Message: Removable Flash Media is operating normally.

PWR8532.Description: Server Based Power Management Mode is disabled.
PWR8532.Message: Server Based Power Management Mode is disabled.

PWR2403.Description: The iDRAC controller established communication to the power management firmware. System performance will return to normal.
PWR2403.Message: iDRAC communication with power management firmware has been restored.

CMC8569.Message: The server slot %1 is enabled for DVD drive mapping.
CMC8569.Description: The server slot specified in the message is enabled for DVD drive mapping. The DVD drive can be mapped to this server slot.

PWR8509.Description: Unable to change the server power priority because Server Based Power Management mode is enabled.
PWR8509.Resolution: The server power priority can be changed once Server Based Power Management mode is disabled. Using the CMC Web UI, navigate to the Chassis Overview > Power > Configuration page, then uncheck the Enable Server Based Power Management checkbox. Retry the operation.
PWR8509.Message: Unable to change the server power priority because Server Based Power Management mode is enabled.

RAC994.Description: The jobs cannot be deleted if they are in one of these states: "Scheduled" or "Running". However, all jobs in one of these states: "Completed" or "Failed" will be deleted.
RAC994.Resolution: To monitor the job status, use the "racadm jobqueue view -i <job ID>", and delete the jobs one at a time using the "racadm jobqueue delete -i <job ID>" command.
RAC994.Message: Unable to run the "jobqueue delete --all" command.

TMP0106.Message: The memory module %1 temperature is less than the lower warning threshold.
TMP0106.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.

RAC978.Description: The Lifecycle Controller firmware version on the target system does not support the configuration XML file import or export operations.
RAC978.Resolution: Update to the latest Lifecycle Controller firmware and retry the operation.
RAC978.Message: Unsupported Lifecycle Controller firmware version detected.

VDR104.Description: The secure virtual disk operation was successful on the security capable virtual disk identified in the message. A security capable virtual disk is created using only Self-Encrypting Drives (SED).

SWC8511.Description: The user name identified in the message was added successfully.

PSU0040.Message: An output under voltage fault detected on power supply %1.
PSU0040.Resolution: 1) Remove the power supply input cord and then remove power supply. 2) Re-install the power supply and then re-install the power supply cord. 3) If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0040.Description: The power supply output voltage is insufficient to keep system operating at a normal levels.

VDR12.Description: This message is generated after reconfiguration of a virtual disk starts.

RAC0635.Description: The requested network file share cannot be accessed, because an invalid domain name is entered.
RAC0635.Resolution: Enter a valid domain name, and then retry the operation.
RAC0635.Message: Unable to access the network file share, because an invalid domain name is entered.

PCI1344.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1344.Message: An I/O channel check error was detected.

UEFI0277.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the iSCSI target configuration data obtained from DHCPv6 server is invalid.
UEFI0277.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reconfigure the DHCPv6 server boot file URL option, and note that server name must be specified. 2) Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings > Connection Settings page, disable Target Info via DHCP and configure the parameters manually. Retry the operation.
UEFI0277.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection number identified in the message because the iSCSI target configuration data obtained from DHCPv6 server is invalid.

PCI1358.Message: A fatal error was detected on a component at slot %1.
PCI1358.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1358.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.

BAR034.Description: The Integrated Remote Access Controller(iDRAC) firmware import did not complete successfully.
BAR034.Resolution: Download the firmware for the Integrated Remote Access Controller(iDRAC) and apply it.
BAR034.Message: Unable to Restore Integrated Remote Access Controller firmware.

SWC8565.Message: The Boot Identity profile %1 is created with %2 templates.
SWC8565.Description: The Boot Identity profile identified in the message is created with number of templates as identified in the message.

UEFI0132.Description: Unable to load one or more option ROMs because of insufficient base memory. The base memory is memory below 640K.
UEFI0132.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove unused PCIe card(s) to free up option ROM space. 2) Disable unused boot protocol instances (such as PXE, iSCSI, etc.) from applicable PCIe card(s) option ROM configurations. 3) If possible, install and run the Operating System in UEFI boot mode.
UEFI0132.Message: Unable to load one or more option ROMs because of insufficient base memory.

TMP0109.Message: The memory module %1 temperature is greater than the upper critical threshold.
TMP0109.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0109.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.

VLT0304.Message: CPU %1 %2 voltage is outside of range.
VLT0304.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0304.Description: Voltages outside the allowable range may damage electrical components or may cause the system to shutdown.

RAC941.Description: A system configuration profile export operation may take several minutes to complete depending on the system configuration.
RAC941.Resolution: Monitor the job status using "racadm jobqueue view -i <Job ID>".
RAC941.Message: Successfully initiated the export operation. This operation may take several minutes to complete.

VF046.Description: File transfer was not successful. This could be because of network problems or an operational problem with the file server.
VF046.Resolution: Try the download again. If the issue persists, validate that the network share is operational.
VF046.Message: HTTP download operation was not successful.

BAR007.Description: System profile export operation is successfully completed.

BAT0001.Message: The system board battery is operating normally.

IOV106.Message: Unable to power on PCIe adapter %1 in %2 %3.
IOV106.Resolution: Make sure a supported PCIe device is used and that it is properly inserted in the PCIe slot. For a list of supported devices, contact the service provider.
IOV106.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to power on adapter. Possible reasons for power failures are: 1) Adapter not an approved adapter. 2) Adapter not fully inserted in the slot 3) Auxiliary power cable not connected (applicable to slot 1 - 3 only). 4) Adapter is damaged.

OSD52.Resolution: Enable the vFlash from the iDRAC GUI or RACADM, and then proceed.

HWC0015.Description: iDRAC has encountered a hardware error.
HWC0015.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.

BIOS012.Description: No changes to BIOS attribute data are available between the previous configuration and the current configuration.

RAC0616.Description: iDRAC was unable to continue with the operation after the PKCS#12 file was uploaded, because it is not able to extract the custom signing certificate and private key.
RAC0616.Resolution: Make sure to upload the PKCS#12 file that contains a valid custom signing certificate and private key.
RAC0616.Message: Error while extracting custom signing certificate and private key from the PKCS#12 file.

TMPS0102.Description: Inlet temperature has been above the warning threshold for duration of 10% or more for the operational time during the last one year.
TMPS0102.Resolution: This condition will occur if the ambient temperature is high. Make sure the ambient temperature of the environment is in normal range.
TMPS0102.Message: Inlet temperature is above warning level for extended duration.

LC079.Description: The export operation cannot be started because Lifecycle Controller is currently running an instance of Export Message Registry operation.
LC079.Resolution: Wait for the current export process to complete, and then retry the operation.
LC079.Message: Unable to start the export operation because Lifecycle Controller is currently running an instance of Export Message Registry operation.

SYS061.Description: Some configuration changes for the component identified by the Fully Qualified Device Descriptor (FQDD) in the configuration job results were not successfully applied.
SYS061.Resolution: Export the Lifecycle Log and identify the configuration changes that did not complete or retrieve the configuration results using the GetConfigResults() method. Retry those changes that did not complete in a separate import operation.

SWU8516.Message: Unable to update the iDRAC firmware on the server in slot %1. Transfer is not successful. ErrorCode=0x%2.
SWU8516.Resolution: Make sure the iDRAC firmware Image file is available in the given path and retry the operation.
SWU8516.Description: iDRAC firmware update operation was not successful. The firmware Image file could not be transferred.

CMC8505.Message: Unable to access server: %1 because both IPv4 and IPv6 are disabled. NIC Enabled = %2.
CMC8505.Resolution: Enable IPv4 or IPv6 for the specified server using the CMC command line or CMC Web GUI interface, so that the link to launch iDRAC is displayed on the CMC Web interface. To enable the NIC for DHCP using RACADM, enter "racadm setniccfg -m server-<slot number> -d" where <slot number> is the server identified in the message. To enable the NIC using the Web interface, click Server Overview > select the identified server, go to Setup > select the Enable IPv4 check box and/or the Enable IPv6 check box.
CMC8505.Description: IPv4 and IPv6 are disabled on the specified server and the CMC is unable to display the link to launch iDRAC web interface.

PWR8592.Description: The request to turn on or turn off the chassis was issued before the previous power operation was completed.
PWR8592.Resolution: Retry the operation after the current operation is complete.
PWR8592.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on or turn off the chassis because another chassis power operation is in progress.

CTL37.Message: A Patrol Read operation started for %1.
CTL37.Description: A patrol read operation was initiated by the controller or the user.

IOV109.Description: An error condition associated with the PCIe slot is cleared.
IOV109.Message: An error condition associated with the PCIe slot is cleared.

OSD27.Description: Copying drivers for selected operating system failed. The Driver Pack may be unusable.
OSD27.Resolution: Update the Driver Pack using USC or DUP and then rerun the command.
OSD27.Message: Copying drivers for selected operating system failed.

BAR105.Description: Importing system branding data from the Server Profile backup file.

PCI3007.Message: Link Tuning or FlexAddress data successfully obtained.

SUP0115.Description: The rac cannot be reset, while the firmware update is in progress.
SUP0115.Resolution: Wait for the firmware update to finish.
SUP0115.Message: A firmware update is currently in progress. Unable to reset the RAC at this time.

SWC0322.Description: The starting record value has to be lesser than the number of records available.
SWC0322.Resolution: Get the number of records available, and then run the command. If the command is gettracelog, try executing the command again.
SWC0322.Message: Starting record specified exceeds number of records available.

BAT1017.Message: The %1 battery learn mode has changed to Warn.
BAT1017.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

ENC13.Resolution: Replace one of the EMMs with the matching SCSI rate EMM.
ENC13.Description: An unsupported configuration was detected. The SCSI rate of the Enclosure Management Modules (EMMs) are not the same.

LC013.Description: No changes are available between the previous configuration and the current configuration. At least one attribute should be changed to create a configuration job.
LC013.Resolution: Change the configuration of one or more attributes before creating a configuration job.
LC013.Message: Operation cannot be completed because there are no pending configuration.

FAN901.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode is successfully disabled.
FAN901.Message: The Enhanced Cooling Mode is successfully disabled.

BAT1034.Message: The battery properties for %1 have changed.
BAT1034.Description: One or more battery properties were modified.

RAC0261.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the IPv6 gateway address does not conform to the required format.
RAC0261.Resolution: Enter a valid IPv6 gateway address.

RAC0271.Description: Locking the user account prevents them from gaining access to iDRAC.
RAC0271.Resolution: Press OK to lock this user account. This action will prevent future access for this user. If undesired press Cancel.

PR7.Description: The specified device was added to the system.

PR29.Description: The device that the job was intended for has no previous information recorded. The request has failed as this information is required to initiate the operation. This has been deprecated.
PR29.Resolution: Enable the Collect System Inventory on Restart attribute of the Lifecycle Controller and restart the system. Alternatively, use the Unified Server Configurator utility.
PR29.Message: Unable to locate device in previous configuration.

RAC1033.Description: The server component software inventory cannot be retrieved because of an internal error.
RAC1033.Resolution: Make sure to enable Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature, reboot the server, and retry the operation. If CSIOR is already enabled, restart iDRAC using "racadm racreset" command, and retry the operation.
RAC1033.Message: Unable to retrieve the server component software inventory.

SWU8547.Description: The firmware update operation of Standby CMC was not successful. The firmware image could not be transferred.
SWU8547.Resolution: Make sure that the CMC firmware image file is available at the location specified in the operation, and then retry the operation.
SWU8547.Message: Unable to update the Standby CMC firmware. The Image transfer process was not successful.

PFM0002.Message: The value of %1 is greater than the upper warning threshold.
PFM0002.Resolution: Check the work load of the server and reduce the workload if necessary to bring the system performance into required ranges. For more information about the specified values, see the relevant product documentation available at the support site.
PFM0002.Description: The utilization value of the sensor identified in the message is higher than the upper warning threshold.

UEFI0012.Description: A CPU page fault (type 0x0E) exception occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment. A program accessed a page mapped in the virtual address space, but not loaded in physical memory.
UEFI0012.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.

RED100.Description: iDRAC initiated the download update package files operation. Wait for a few minutes.
RED100.Message: iDRAC initiated the download update package files operation. Wait for a few minutes.

SWC0019.Description: The Test Network Connection ping test timed-out. The network cable is disconnected or the network is not configured correctly.
SWC0019.Resolution: Check the network cable connection and network configuration settings, then retry the operation. If the problem persists, reconfigure the network settings and retry the operation.
SWC0019.Message: The Test Network Connection operation completed with errors.

SYS167.Description: The TTY Log data export did not complete within the allocated time. Currently the maximum allocated time is 20 minutes.
SYS167.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and retry the operation.
SYS167.Message: TTY Log data export did not complete within the allocated time.

IOV011.Description: All servers that PCIe slots or virtual adapter (VA) will be assigned-to and unassigned-from must be turned off before an assign or unassign operation can be performed.
IOV011.Resolution: Turn off all servers that the PCIe slots or virtual adapter (VA) will be assigned-to and unassigned-from, and then retry the operation.
IOV011.Message: Unable to assign or unassign PCIe slot(s) or virtual adapter (VA) because all affected servers must be turned off.

PR19.Description: The specified job has completed successfully.

RED091.Description: Unable to install Lifecycle Controller firmware.
RED091.Resolution: Reinstall the iDRAC7 firmware (DUP) to repair Lifecycle Controller. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.
RED091.Message: Unable to install Lifecycle Controller firmware.

RAC1144.Message: The Job: %1 is invalid or is not present in the job queue and a related Lifecycle Log entry is not found.
RAC1144.Resolution: Check the job ID identified in the message and retry the operation with a valid job ID. To check valid job IDs in the current job queue, using RACADM, run the command "racadm jobqueue view".
RAC1144.Description: No configuration results information is available for the job ID identified in the message because the job ID is invalid or is not present in the job queue and a related Lifecycle Log entry is not found.

PSU0031.Resolution: Remove and re-install the power supply. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0031.Description: The power supply may operate, however power supply monitoring will be degraded. System performance may be degraded.

SWC0038.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to export the file to the network share because the destination folder is read-only or inaccessible.
SWC0038.Resolution: Remove the write protection on the destination folder and verify the folder is accessible, then retry the operation. If the problem persists, check network settings and retry.
SWC0038.Message: Unable to export the file to the network share.

MEM0006.Message: Memory device at location %1 is present.

SYS030.Description: Collecting the data required for component configuration.

PWR8572.Message: Unable to shutdown the server %1 because the server is off.
PWR8572.Description: The server identified in the message can be shutdown only if the server is turned on.

SYS062.Description: The input file for the import configuration operation does not contain a valid profile root element.
SYS062.Resolution: Open the input file in any Web browser to check for invalid content before the expected root element. Correct the invalid content and make sure that the profile is compliant to the system configuration schema before retrying the operation.
SYS062.Message: Input file for import configuration operation is invalid. The expected profile root element was not found.

PFM0001.Message: The value of %1 is greater than the upper critical threshold.
PFM0001.Resolution: Check the work load of the server and reduce the workload if necessary to bring the system performance into required ranges. For more information about the specified values, see the relevant product documentation available at the support site.
PFM0001.Description: The utilization value of the sensor identified in the message is higher than the upper critical threshold.

SUP0114.Message: The firmware update operation could not be completed successfully.

ASR0103.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate within the timeout period. The system was powered down. (IPMI sensor type code 23h offset - 02h event 3:0 - 4h).
ASR0103.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0103.Message: The OS watchdog timer powered down the system.

LOG505.Description: The network share access cannot be accessed.
LOG505.Resolution: Make sure that correct network share access credentials are entered (such as IP address, username, password, and share type). For more information, see the Chassis Record Log Profile.
LOG505.Message: Unable to access the network share.

SWC0264.Description: The resources required for the execution are in use by another process.
SWC0264.Resolution: Wait for the process to release the resources and try again.
SWC0264.Message: Resource currently in use by another process. Please retry again later.

LIC205.Description: The License Manager sets a maximum time period that its database may be locked. If that timeout exceeds, it releases the lock conditions and reports the error. The user must assume that the Lifecycle Controller backup or restore operation failed and should repeat the operation.
LIC205.Resolution: Repeat the backup or restore operation.
LIC205.Message: License Manager database lock timeout has been exceeded.

PWR8512.Description: Power configuration data in memory cannot be accessed due to synchronization issues.
PWR8512.Message: CMC rebooted, because the power configuration data could not be accessed.

IOV1002.Description: The operation did not complete successfully due to an exception from the instrumentation layer.
IOV1002.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset CMC and retry the operation when the CMC has completed restarting. The CMC may take 2 to 3 minutes to complete restarting.

RFL2005.Message: Internal Dual SD Module %1 is operating normally.

RAC921.Description: The file type specified (with the t parameter) is invalid. The temperature history can be exported in XML or CSV.
RAC921.Resolution: Change the requested export file type to either XML or CSV. To do this, change the argument given to the t parameter. The argument given to the parameter is case-insensitive.
RAC921.Message: The temperature history can be exported in XML or CSV format only.

BAR024.Description: The restoration environment is being initialized.

CTL61.Message: Physical disks found missing from configuration during boot time on %1.
CTL61.Resolution: Shut down the system. Re-insert the removed physical disks and re-start the system.
CTL61.Description: The controller has detected a change in the storage configuration between since its last shut down. This can generally happen if some configured physical disks are removed from the system when the system was shutdown.

ENC40.Message: A new enclosure was detected on %1.
ENC40.Description: The controller detected a new enclosure. This is due either to a hot plug of an enclosure, or a power state change of an enclosure. In addition, this message is generated if the daisy chain order of the enclosures changes.

RAC0639.Description: The job could not be successfully scheduled, because an invalid value is entered for 'minute' while scheduling a job.
RAC0639.Resolution: Enter a correct value from 0 to 59, and then retry the operation.
RAC0639.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid 'minute' value is entered.

UEFI0116.Description: One or more boot drivers have reported issue(s) via the UEFI Driver Health Protocol.
UEFI0116.Resolution: Check the Driver Health Menu in Boot Manager for details.
UEFI0116.Message: One or more boot drivers have reported issue(s).

ENC7.Description: You have enabled the enclosure alarm. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC1178.Description: A USB device is attached to the iDRAC and a configuration XML import operation is in progress.
RAC1178.Resolution: Wait until the configuration XML import operation has completed before attempting another operation. Verify the status of the configuration XML import operation by running the RACADM command "racadm jobqueue view".
RAC1178.Message: A USB device is attached to the iDRAC and a configuration XML import operation is in progress.

PWR205.Description: The Server Performance Over Power Redundancy (SPOPR) feature cannot be enabled because the Extended Power Performance is enabled.
PWR205.Resolution: Disable Extended Power Performance and retry the operation.
PWR205.Message: The Server Performance Over Power Redundancy (SPOPR) feature cannot be enabled because the Extended Power Performance is enabled.

SWU8520.Message: The firmware update operation of the iDRAC on the server in slot %1 is not successful.
SWU8520.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the original source, and then retry the operation.
SWU8520.Description: The firmware update operation of the iDRAC identified in the message is not successful.

SYS153.Message: Deleting hardware cache data for controller: %1.
SYS153.Description: The non-volatile cache of the controller identified in the message is being erased.

BAR109.Description: The OEMDRV partition is mounted for performing operating system deployment use. This situation prevents the Export and Import Server Profile operation from continuing.
BAR109.Resolution: Dismount the OEMDRV partition by selecting F10 during boot and retry the operation.

OSD29.Description: Driver Pack configuration file not found in Lifecycle Controller. Driver Pack may be unusable.
OSD29.Resolution: Update the Driver Pack using USC or DUP and then rerun the command.
OSD29.Message: Driver Pack configuration file not found in Lifecycle Controller. The Driver Pack might be corrupt.

LC083.Message: The Redfish Event service cannot deliver notifications to %1 because of network communication issues.
LC083.Resolution: Make sure that the server is connected to the network and retry the operation. If the issue persists, delete the subscription and then subscribe by using an IP that is connected to the network.
LC083.Description: The Redfish Event service cannot deliver notifications to the IP Address identified in the message because of network communication issues.

RAC1180.Description: A USB Device inserted in the front panel USB Management port and is in use by the server operating system. The device needs to not be in use in order to change the port mode settings.
RAC1180.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the USB device and retry the operation.
RAC1180.Message: A USB device is inserted in the front panel USB Management port and is in use by the server operating system.

PR24.Description: The specified job was cancelled. This could be due to user action or system error. This message is no longer in use in Lifecycle Controller 2.0 as the job control functionality handles this operation.

PDR60.Resolution: Verify the health of attached devices. Review the Lifecycle log for significant events. Replace faulty hardware, if required. Make sure the cables are attached securely. Refer to the storage hardware documentation for more information on checking the cable connections.
PDR60.Description: The reason for the error can vary depending on the situation. The firmware error code is indicated in the message.

HWC0003.Description: The vFlash SD card was successfully initialized.

RAC975.Description: The share type specified using the l parameter is invalid. Only CIFS or NFS share types are supported for this operation.
RAC975.Resolution: See the subcommand help text for supported share types.

DKM1006.Resolution: Review server error logs for additional information.

STOR053.Description: The system could not obtain a controller key from the Dell Key Management Server.
STOR053.Resolution: For more information about obtaining a key, see Dell Key Manager or Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Guide available at dell.com/support/manuals.
STOR053.Message: The controller key is not present. The key must be retrieved from the Dell Key Management Server.

UEFI0146.Description: Unable to verify the chassis type via iDRAC and CMC/OME-Modular. System configuration may be incorrect as a result.
UEFI0146.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware and then restart the system. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0146.Message: Unable to verify the chassis type via iDRAC and CMC/OME-Modular. System configuration may be incorrect as a result.

RDU8519.Message: Unable to communicate with peer CMC %1.
RDU8519.Resolution: Wait for 10 minutes for: 1)Firmware update operations to complete and 2) The CMC to finish restarting. If the communication is not reestablished, remove and reinsert the CMC.
RDU8519.Description: The communication between the primary and standby CMCs was lost. This may occur when the CMC identified in the message is restarting, or a firmware update operation is in progress. If the issue persists, a failover will occur.

SUP0533.Description: The file cannot be downloaded from FTP share due to network issues.
SUP0533.Resolution: Check network connection and retry download. If the issue persists, reconfigure the network settings and retry.
SUP0533.Message: Unable to download the update package files from the FTP server.

RAC1122.Description: One or more of the group or component attributes specified in the operation do not exist on the targeted server.
RAC1122.Message: The specified group or object is not supported on the server.

STOR023.Description: Unable to perform configuration operations because a configuration job for the device already exists.
STOR023.Resolution: Wait for the current job for the device to complete or cancel the current job before attempting more configuration operations on the device.
STOR023.Message: Unable to perform configuration operations because a configuration job for the device already exists.

BIOS0001.Message: Trusted Compute Module (TPM) Physical Presence Operation %1 logged.
BIOS0001.Description: BIOS logged a Trusted Compute Module (TPM) Physical Presence Operation.

SWC0017.Description: An unrecoverable error occurred while retrieving the drivers.
SWC0017.Resolution: Exit the OS Deployment wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, exit Lifecycle Controller and perform an AC power cycle.
SWC0017.Message: Unable to retrieve the drivers for the selected operating system.

CTL7.Resolution: See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.
CTL7.Description: A portion of a physical disk is damaged. See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.

SWC0140.Message: RAC reset operation initiated successfully. It may take up to a minute for the RAC to come back online again.

RAC1048.Description: The Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings must already exist in order to be cleared.
RAC1048.Message: Unable to clear the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings because there is currently no configuration.

SWC8555.Description: The Boot Identity operation cannot be started because a Boot Identity operation is already in progress.
SWC8555.Resolution: Wait for the current operation to complete, and then retry. Only one Boot Identity operation can be performed at a time.
SWC8555.Message: Unable to start the Boot Identity profile operation because a Boot Identity operation is already in progress.

USR0030.Message: Successfully logged in using %1, from %2 and %3.
USR0030.Description: Successful login for the username, IP address, and interface identified in the message.

STOR304.Description: Controller mode cannot be changed as the controller has virtual disk or hotspare associated with it.
STOR304.Resolution: Delete the Virtual Disks and/or Hotspares and retry the operation.
STOR304.Message: Unable to change controller mode while Virtual Disks and/or Hotspares are present on the controller.

PR27.Description: The system ran out of memory while attempting to perform an operation. This has been deprecated.
PR27.Resolution: Retry the operation. If more than one operation was attempted retry them one at a time.

PDR1102.Message: A predictive failure detected on drive %1.
PDR1102.Resolution: The drive will need replacement at the next service window.
PDR1102.Description: The controller received a SMART error from the drive. The drive is operational but needs replacement.

CMC8578.Description: The Remote Access Controller (RAC) SSL Certificate and key is changed.
CMC8578.Message: The Remote Access Controller (RAC) SSL Certificate and key is changed.

MEM1006.Message: Memory device at location %1 is online.

FAN1000.Resolution: Re-insert the fan into the enclosure. Contact technical support if the issue persists.
FAN1000.Description: The enclosure detected that a fan was removed and the enclosure is no longer functioning in optimal condition.

PDR9.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC1037.Description: Unable to clear pending attribute(s). This may be because the FQDD entered is incorrect.
RAC1037.Resolution: Check that the FQDD entered is correct. View the Help information by running the RACADM command "racadm help clearpending".

USR8506.Description: The operation to invalidate the Session identified in the message was successful.

UEFI0165.Message: Unable to configure memory interleaving on DIMM modules on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0165.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure interleaving can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0165.Description: Memory could not be interleaved because the number of allowable System Address Decode (SAD) rules exceeded during memory initialization.

MEM9011.Description: BIOS logged location information of a QuickPath Interconnect (QPI) warning. This information can be reviewed by using a tool which displays raw IPMI SEL data such as IPMItool with the -vvv option or RACADM with the -E option.
MEM9011.Message: QuickPath Interconnect (QPI) Reference Code warning location information is logged.

CMC8610.Message: Unable to read because the Field Replaceable Unit (FRU) is not functioning on the sled %1.
CMC8610.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation. 1) Reset iDRAC on the sled identified in the message or reseat the sled. 2) Reset Chassis Management Controller (CMC) and wait few minutes. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.Reset iDRAC using racadm racreset -m server-nReset CMC using racadm racreset. From GUI, navigate to Chassis Overview->Troubleshooting Reset CMC using Reset/Failover CMC. Reset iDRAC using iDRAC reset from dropdown.
CMC8610.Description: The read operation cannot be done because the Field Replaceable Unit (FRU) is not functioning on the sled identified in the message.

SEC0601.Message: A secure mode violation was corrected.

RAC1054.Description: Successfully cleared the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings.
RAC1054.Message: Successfully cleared the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings.

RAC1154.Description: The requested techsupreport collect or export operation is initiated.
RAC1154.Resolution: Run the RACADM jobqueue sub-command, using the job id to check the status of the requested operation.

HWC7002.Message: Server %1 health changed to a warning state from a normal state.
HWC7002.Resolution: Review System Log or front panel for additional information.
HWC7002.Description: Server health changed to a warning state from a normal state.

FC002.Description: Unable to allocate memory required to perform the operation.
FC002.Resolution: Perform an AC power cycle and retry Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC firmware update.

PST0002.Description: System BIOS has started loading the processor microcode.

RAC0740.Description: The Prepare to Remove operation will stop any activity on the PCIe SSD device so that it can be removed safely. The device is safe to remove when the disk shows the safe to remove LED pattern.
RAC0740.Message: The Prepare to Remove operation will stop any activity on the PCIe SSD device so that it can be removed safely. The device is safe to remove when the disk shows the safe to remove LED pattern.

RAC0253.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the IPv4 address does not conform to the required format.
RAC0253.Resolution: Enter a valid IP Address. Expected range: [1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].
RAC0253.Message: The IP Address is invalid. Expected range: [1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].

FCD8501.Resolution: Turn chassis OFF and remove card. Alternately, to repair the card, perform Repair by navigating to the CMC GUI -> Chassis Controller -> Flash Media page.
FCD8501.Description: The FlexAddress, FlexAddress+ or extended storage feature is deactivated. Turn chassis off and remove the feature card.

PST0065.Description: System BIOS is configuring PCI devices.

RAC1031.Description: The custom signing certificate on iDRAC cannot be deleted because of an internal error.
RAC1031.Resolution: Verify if iDRAC has a custom signing certificate. If it has the certificate, retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC1031.Message: Unable to delete the custom signing certificate.

RAC0216.Description: Login failed because of an unknown reason.
RAC0216.Resolution: Try the operation after a few minutes. If the problem persists, reset iDRAC and repeat the operation.

CTL111.Message: The CopyBack Mode of %1 is set to %2.
CTL111.Description: The CopyBack Mode the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.

SWC0278.Description: The value of specified parameter is invalid.
SWC0278.Resolution: Enter the values for the group name and object name correctly.

SEL1304.Description: PXE is one way to boot a system from the network. (IPMI sensor type code 1eh - offset 02h).
SEL1304.Resolution: Check network and PXE server configuration.

SWC0287.Description: The value of a parameter in the config file is invalid.

RAC0250.Description: The vFlash partitions are read-only. Therefore, the current operation cannot proceed.
RAC0250.Resolution: Make sure the partitions are writable before attempting to change their contents.
RAC0250.Message: One or more partitions are read-only.

SEL1400.Message: The platform generated a page alert.

VF022.Description: The size specified is lower than the minimum allowed for a partition.

PDR17.Description: A user has have assigned a physical disk as a global hot spare. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

LC040.Description: Unable to allocate required memory to perform the operation.
LC040.Resolution: Power cycle system and retry the operation. If the problem persists, reapply firmware packages for Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC.

HWC0002.Description: The vFlash SD Card is either not present or not correctly inserted.
HWC0002.Resolution: Insert the vFlash SD card or reinsert the vFlash SD card, and retry the operation.
HWC0002.Message: Unable to detect vFlash SD card.

RAC0602.Description: The value for alert recurrence must be within the range 0-365.

PR11.Description: A valid license for this feature is not present.
PR11.Message: A required license for the Part Replacement feature is not present, replacement action(s) will not be performed.

SWC0323.Description: The number of records specified to be displayed should be lesser than number of records available.
SWC0323.Resolution: Get the number of records available, and then run the command.
SWC0323.Message: Number of records specified exceeds number of records available.

LC073.Description: An SSL Certificate cannot be generated because of internal firmware issues.
LC073.Resolution: Make sure that the security attributes are valid and retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC by invoking the WS-Man iDRACReset method which is defined in the DCIM_iDRACCardService class , and then retry the operation.
LC073.Message: Unable to generate an SSL Certificate because of internal firmware issues.

CTL105.Message: The Patrol Read attribute %1 is set to %2 for %3.
CTL105.Description: The Patrol Read attribute identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message for the controller identified in the message.

CPU0701.Resolution: 1) Check system and operating system logs for exceptions. If no exceptions are found continue. 2) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 3) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 4) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
CPU0701.Description: System event log and OS logs may indicate that the exception is external to the processor.

BAT0003.Message: The system board battery is present.

RAC1008.Description: The Active Directory object DCLookupByUserDomain cannot be disabled, because the Active Directory object DCLookupDomainName is not configured.
RAC1008.Resolution: Configure the Active Directory object DCLookupDomainName using "racadm set iDRAC.ActiveDirectory.DCLookupDomainName <Name>", and retry the operation.
RAC1008.Message: The Active Directory object DCLookupByUserDomain cannot be disabled.

PR28.Description: The device that the job was intended for is no longer detected. This could be due to the device being removed, disabled, or a failure.
PR28.Resolution: If the device was removed, reinsert the device and retry the operation. If the device was disabled, re-enable the device and retry the operation.
PR28.Message: Unable to locate device in current configuration.

OSD74.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'ShareType' is invalid.
OSD74.Resolution: Check the value provided for input parameter "ShareType" and retry the operation.
OSD74.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'ShareType' is invalid.

SWC0044.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to retrieve the status of the Import Server Profile operation. For more information, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0044.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, do the following: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait five seconds. 3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0044.Message: Unable to retrieve the status of the Import Server Profile operation.

SUP0501.Description: The catalog file is not in the supported XML format, or the catalog file is corrupted.
SUP0501.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) If the catalog file is customized, recreate the file using Repository Manager, and retry the operation. 2) Update the catalog file from the service provider's FTP server and retry the operation. 3) Update the catalog file from the System Update Utility media or from the System Build Update Utility media and retry the operation. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.

SYS036.Description: The configuration settings could not be applied to the component. This may indicate configuration changes since the last system inventory collection was completed.
SYS036.Resolution: Retry the operation or try the attribute set operation for the component.
SYS036.Message: Unable to apply the configuration to the component.

SYS042.Description: The requested component configuration successfully completed.

BOOT018.Description: The Boot Control List specified in the operation is read-only and cannot be modified.
BOOT018.Resolution: Refer to the documentation on validity of operation for the Boot Control List specified. For more information on the operation, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
BOOT018.Message: Specified Boot Control List is read-only

STOR050.Description: The controller is in Local Key Management mode.
STOR050.Message: Controller is in Dell Key Management mode.

BAR058.Description: The system profile import or export network destination is being tested for access.

STOR0103.Description: No physical disk data to display. The system is powered off, physical disks are not present on the system, or physical disks are not connected to the enclosure or backplane.
STOR0103.Resolution: Check if the server has power, physical disks are available, and physical disks are connected to the enclosure or backplane.

UEFI0143.Resolution: Replace the processor(s) with supported ones. For more information about supported processors, contact your service provider.

HWC2008.Message: A fabric mismatch detected for mezzanine card %1.
HWC2008.Resolution: Check chassis fabric type in CMC GUI and compare to the type of IOM or mezzanine card.
HWC2008.Description: The fabric type for the IOM and mezzanine cards must match. Once an IOM or mezzanine card is inserted into the chassis, the fabric type is then set for the CMC and the CMC will ensure that all subsequent IOM's and mezzanine cards match.

CMC8701.Message: The Member Chassis could not join the chassis group %1 because either the Member Chassis is already a part of the other chassis group; or, the Member Chassis could not be reached.
CMC8701.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) If the Member Chassis is a part of other chassis groups, remove the Member Chassis from the other groups by using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) graphical user interface (GUI): Log in to the Member Chassis. Click Chassis Overview > Setup > Group Administration. From the drop-down menu, select None. 2) Restart the Member Chassis by clicking Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components > Reset/Failover CMC. To reset by running RACADM command at the command line interface (CLI), enter racadm chassisaction reset.
CMC8701.Description: The Member Chassis could not join the chassis group identified in the message because either the Member Chassis is already a part of the other chassis group; or, the Member Chassis could not be reached.

UEFI0023.Description: The End of POST message could not be sent to the Management Engine because the Management Engine is not responding.
UEFI0023.Resolution: Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system.
UEFI0023.Message: BIOS is unable to send the End of POST message to Management Engine because the Management Engine is not responding.

VF035.Description: The image file is not valid.

CTL21.Message: Abort CC on Error and Load Balance has changed for %1.
CTL21.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

UEFI0151.Message: A PERC storage adapter is installed in %1 but the internal storage slot is empty. This configuration is not supported.
UEFI0151.Resolution: Install a compatible storage adapter in the internal storage slot. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0151.Description: A PERC storage adapter is installed in a slot identified by this message but the internal storage slot is empty This configuration is not supported.

UEFI0070.Description: One or more correctable PCIe errors have occurred. Data about the errors are logged into SEL during the POST operation.
UEFI0070.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the PCIe device, and then update its firmware.
UEFI0070.Message: One or more correctable PCIe errors have occurred.

UEFI0245.Description: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization failed to configure all installed processors to the maximum common frequency.
UEFI0245.Resolution: Reseat all processors in the system and ensure all processors are matching. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0245.Message: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) link initialization error detected.

HWC1005.Description: The storage adapter may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.

RED098.Description: Unable to complete the firmware update operation because the specified firmware image is not compatible with the target system.
RED098.Resolution: Identify and download the firmware version that corresponds to the system model being updated, and retry the operation. For a list of supported firmware versions, refer to the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
RED098.Message: Unable to complete the firmware update operation because the specified firmware image is not compatible with the target system model.

BAR070.Description: Access to the NFS export/import destination is not possible or has been denied.
BAR070.Resolution: Verify that the input parameters are correct, connectivity exists to the destination end point, and retry the operation.

SYS003.Resolution: Refer to the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services documentation and retry the operation with the required parameters.
SYS003.Description: One or more required parameters needed for the operation are missing.

OSE1006.Description: The system has successfully booted to diagnostics.

FAN0000.Message: Fan %1 RPM is less than the lower warning threshold.
FAN0000.Resolution: Remove and re-install the fan at the next scheduled service window. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0000.Description: The fan is not performing optimally. The fan may be installed improperly or may be failing.

SWC8623.Message: Unable to save the I/O Aggregator configuration in %1.
SWC8623.Resolution: Power-cycle the IOA and retry the operation.
SWC8623.Description: The current configuration details of IOA in the slot identified in the message could not be saved to its startup configuration.

PST0126.Description: System is currently booting to an UEFI compatible operating system. No more POST codes will be generated in this boot sequence.
PST0126.Message: Giving control to UEFI aware OS.

LIC014.Description: An attempt to lock the License Manager database for Lifecycle Controller backup or restore occurred when the License Manager database was already locked. This may occur when two or more users attempt to do a backup or restore operation simultaneously.
LIC014.Resolution: Repeat the Lifecycle Controller backup or restore operation.
LIC014.Message: Multiple backup or restore operations have been simultaneously attempted on the License Manager database.

RAC1058.Description: The requested firmware Rollback operation did not complete successfully because Lifecycle Controller is disabled.
RAC1058.Resolution: Run the RACADM command "racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState 1" to enable Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation.
RAC1058.Message: Rollback operation did not complete successfully because Lifecycle Controller is disabled.

DIS109.Description: The server could not be configured because the End Host Power State value specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC is incorrect.
DIS109.Resolution: In the DHCP scope option field where VendorID=iDRAC, enter a end-host-power-state (-e <0 or 1>) where 0 = Powered Off and = Powered On, and then retry the operation.
DIS109.Message: Unable to start the AutoConfig file import operation, because an invalid End Host Power State value is specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

RED061.Description: The job is successfully scheduled. The job will automatically start at the specified start time.

RAC0644.Description: The job could not be successfully scheduled, because an invalid value is entered for 'year', while scheduling a job.
RAC0644.Resolution: Enter a correct value, and then retry the operation.
RAC0644.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid 'year' value is entered.

CMC8550.Description: If the chassis health status changes, new status is logged. The possible states are Invalid, Other, Unknown, Healthy, Non-critical, Critical, and Non-recoverable.

MEM7002.Resolution: Review product documentation for proper memory riser installation and configuration.
MEM7002.Message: A hardware mismatch detected for memory riser.

LC102.Description: The server screen shot cannot be exported because iDRAC could not get the necessary screen data.
LC102.Resolution: Wait for some time and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
LC102.Message: Unable to export the server screen shot because iDRAC could not get the necessary screen data.

PWR1001.Description: To avoid shutdown, system performance has been degraded.
PWR1001.Resolution: Review system configuration and power consumption.

SYS422.Description: The ETag in the response headers cannot be displayed because of unknown internal issues.
SYS422.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC, and then retry the operation. Reset the iDRAC by using the "Manager Reset Actions" Redfish API.
SYS422.Message: Unable to display the ETag in the response headers because of unknown internal issues.

PWR8590.Message: The server-%1 does not have PCIe Mezzanine card in slot C1.
PWR8590.Resolution: Insert a PCIe Mezzanine card in slot C1.
PWR8590.Description: The PCIe Mezzanine card in the slot C1 is absent. Without PCIe Mezzanine cards, the chassis PCIe cards will not be available for servers.

SWC5001.Resolution: Reboot the system and attempt the upgrade again.

STOR4.Description: There was a software problem in initializing the CEM storage management components. Storage inventory and monitoring will be affected.
STOR4.Resolution: Reboot the system or iDRAC. If the problem is not resolved, contact technical support.
STOR4.Message: CEM Storage Management encountered internal error.

SYS147.Description: Starting non-secure erase-capable drives erase operations because of a System Erase operation request.
SYS147.Message: Starting non-secure erase-capable drive erase operations.

VLT0213.Message: The disk drive bay %1 voltage is less than the lower critical threshold.
VLT0213.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat hard disks in the bay. Reconnect all cables attached to the bay.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0213.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

CTL36.Message: The Patrol Read mode has changed for %1.
CTL36.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SWC0227.Description: Invalid values passed to the function.
SWC0227.Resolution: Enter a shorter path to the firmware image file.
SWC0227.Message: Partition label exceeds maximum limit of 6 alphanumeric characters.

HWC1009.Description: The backplane may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.
HWC1009.Resolution: If removal was unintended, check presence, then re-install or reconnect.

RAC1186.Description: Only possible configurations for the DRAC NIC are 10Mbps and 100 Mbps. For documentation with respect to this setting, refer to the racadm User Guide under cfgNetTuning group.
RAC1186.Message: 1000Mbps speed setting is Read Only and cannot be configured for the iDRAC NIC.

RRDU0002.Description: Either one of the SD card or both the SD cards are not functioning properly.
RRDU0002.Message: Internal Dual SD Module redundancy is lost.

LC057.Description: The attribute name provided is not valid for the current method.
LC057.Resolution: Retry the operation with a valid AttributeName parameter value.

BAR099.Description: License data is being collected and copied into the backup Server Profile.

RAC0626.Description: The job cannot be scheduled, because all or some of the schedule parameters entered are incorrect.
RAC0626.Resolution: Enter correct input schedule parameters and retry the operation.
RAC0626.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid schedule parameter is entered.

SWU8544.Description: The firmware update operation of the Standby CMC was not successful. The Standby CMC could not be prepared for firmware update.
SWU8544.Message: Unable to update the Standby CMC firmware because the Standby CMC could not be prepared for firmware update.

TMP1003.Message: %1 has crossed the minimum failure threshold.
TMP1003.Resolution: Check whether the thermostat setting is too low and whether the room temperature is too cool.

VDR37.Message: Dead disk segments are restored on %1.
VDR37.Description: Disk space that was formerly "dead" or inaccessible to a redundant virtual disk has been restored. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SEC0018.Message: The I/O card area is closed.

PDR55.Message: Insufficient space available on the %1 to perform a rebuild.
PDR55.Resolution: Replace the physical disk with one of correct protocol (SAS, SATA) with at least the required size. Force rebuild if it does not start automatically.
PDR55.Description: The physical disk inserted is too small for the rebuild to occur.

RAC026.Description: Unable to set DNS Domain Name because "Domain Name From DHCP" is Enabled.
RAC026.Resolution: Disable "Domain Name From DHCP" to set values for DNS Domain Name.
RAC026.Message: Unable to set DNS Domain Name because "Domain Name From DHCP" is Enabled.

BIOS011.Description: Configuration job already created on the specified target. No further command is allowed until the existing job is completed.
BIOS011.Resolution: Cancel the configuration job or wait for the job to complete. Refer to documentation on job cancellation.
BIOS011.Message: Configuration job already created, pending data cannot be deleted.

RAC0678.Description: Unable to perform Prepare to Remove or Secure Erase operations on the PCIe SSD disk drives.
RAC0678.Resolution: Make sure PCIe SSD disk drives are inserted into the enclosure or attached to the backplane and retry the operation. If there are NVMe SSDs inserted check whether it is in RAID mode. Operations are supported only in non-RAID mode. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC0678.Message: Unable to perform Prepare to Remove or Secure Erase operations on PCIe SSD disk drives.

TMP1004.Message: The temperature sensor %1 is now within configured threshold values.
TMP1004.Description: The enclosure temperature sensor identified in the message is operating within the upper and lower configured temperature thresholds.

LC070.Description: The configuration XML file used for the import operation does not exist on the specified network share.
LC070.Resolution: Make sure the input configuration XML file for the operation exists on the network share.
LC070.Message: Unable to find the configuration XML import file.

RAC055.Description: The user name for the user account cannot be cleared because the user account is enabled in the configuration XML file.
RAC055.Resolution: Retry the operation after disabling the user account in the configuration XML file.
RAC055.Message: User name cannot be cleared because the user account is enabled in the input configuration XML file.

BAR083.Description: System profile backup file validation failed because the host system model information does not match the value stored in the file.
BAR083.Resolution: Obtain a valid host system backup image and try the operation again. Reboot the remote access controller and try the operation again. If the error continues, download a new remote access controller firmware image and try the operation again.
BAR083.Message: Host System Model does not match the Backup file System Model information.

DIS114.Description: The AutoConfig feature timed out while waiting for Remote Services to be ready.
DIS114.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset iDRAC. To reset iDRAC by using RACADM command, run the racadm racreset command at the command line interface (CLI). For more information about resetting iDRAC, see iDRAC Users Guide available at the support site.
DIS114.Message: The AutoConfig feature timed out while waiting for Remote Services to be ready.

RAC957.Description: Another import or export operation cannot be started until the current operation is complete.
RAC957.Resolution: Wait until the current import or export operation is complete before starting another operation. Use the racadm jobqueue view command to check the status of the current import or export operation.
RAC957.Message: An import or export operation is currently in progress.

HWC8506.Description: During a Chassis Management Controller (CMC) firmware update, the control panel firmware synchronization failed. The control panel may be inoperable.
HWC8506.Resolution: Remove and reapply chassis input power. If problem persists, contact your service provider.
HWC8506.Message: Unable to synchronize control panel firmware due to internal error.

BAR040.Description: Access to the vFlash media is not possible, or has been denied.
BAR040.Resolution: Make sure the vFlash SD media is enabled, not write protected, and initialized. Retry the operation.

PCI2003.Message: The component at slot %1 recovered from a fatal IO error.

PDR103.Message: Cryptographic Erase operation is successfully completed on %1.
PDR103.Description: Cryptographic Erase operation is successfully completed on the physical disk drive identified in the message.

SYS192.Description: The provided Server Configuration Profile is being previewed on the system. No configuration changes will be applied.
SYS192.Resolution: No response action is required. Use the GetConfigResults() method to get the preview job results or export the Lifecycle Log to review the preview job results.

SYS196.Message: The OEM ID module is installed but with some errors. %1
SYS196.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle Log report to analyze the issue. Review settings and branding information that the ID module configured, resolve the issue, and then retry the installation process.
SYS196.Description: The OEM ID module installation process tried to apply all settings and branding information, but had issues during installation.

SWC0724.Description: Resetting to defaults did not complete within the maximum process allotted time.
SWC0724.Message: Error occurred while Resetting to defaults due to a timeout.

SYS254.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of one or more of the following: 1) remote host cannot be reached. 2) remote share name is not present. 3) incorrect credentials are entered.
SYS254.Resolution: Make sure that the file transfer parameters are correct, and then retry the operation.
SYS254.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of one or more of the following: 1) remote host cannot be reached. 2) remote share name is not present. 3) incorrect credentials were entered.

NIC014.Resolution: Refer to the documentation on valid attribute values.
NIC014.Description: AttributeValue may be invalid because of the following causes: 1) Length of new AttributeValue is not within minLength and maxLength 2) Value of new AttributeValue is not within LowerBound and UpperBound 3) Value of new AttributeValue is not one of the possible values.

SWC0257.Description: Invalid number of arguments were passed to the command.
SWC0257.Resolution: Refer the help text for the command.
SWC0257.Message: Invalid syntax. Too many options specified.

BAR079.Description: The collection and export of Integrated Remote Access Controller configuration was not successful.
BAR079.Resolution: Apply the integrated remote access controller firmware, manually set the configuration attributes, and try the operation again.
BAR079.Message: Unable to collect the Integrated Remote Access Controller configuration.

ASR0008.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate to the baseboard management controller (BMC) within the timeout period. The BMC invoked a system interrupt. (IPMI sensor type code 23h - offset 00h).
ASR0008.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0008.Message: The watchdog timer interrupt was initiated.

SWC0029.Description: Status of backup Server Profile operation could not be retrieved because an unrecoverable error occurred while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0029.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC, hold the System ID button down for 15 seconds or longer and wait for 90 seconds for the iDRAC to restart. For more information on the error, see the Lifecycle Log.
