SWC0029.Message: Unable to retrieve status of backup Server Profile operation.

VDR40.Description: This message is generated after the reconfiguration of a virtual disk resumes.

RED037.Description: The currently installed firmware of the components on the server match with the specified remote repository.
RED037.Message: All components' firmware match with the specified remote repository.

UEFI0242.Message: Unable to enable the requested Partial Mirror size of %1GB due to the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the requested size. %2GB was allocated instead.
UEFI0242.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure the requested Partial Mirror size can be supported. For more information, see platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0242.Description: The Partial Memory Mirroring feature cannot be enabled because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the requested size.

BAT1037.Message: A battery is detected on the Controller %1.
BAT1037.Description: A battery is detected on the Controller identified in the message.

RAC0290.Description: The user name value does not accept spaces.
RAC0290.Resolution: Do not enter spaces in the user name. If desired, use underscores.
RAC0290.Message: The user name cannot have spaces.

PWR8543.Message: Server %1 power inventory is not valid. Power inventory reading is Max Power=%2 AC Watt, Min Power=%3 AC Watt, Allocated Power=%4 AC Watt.
PWR8543.Resolution: Turn on the server identified in the message. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR8543.Description: Invalid power inventory reported by the iDRAC of the server identified in the message to the CMC.

FAN0004.Message: Fan %1 RPM is outside of range.
FAN0004.Resolution: Remove and re-install the fan. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0004.Description: The fan is not performing optimally. The fan may be installed improperly or may be failing.

UEFI0191.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.
UEFI0191.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0191.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the VCK Reference Clock phase.

BAT1009.Message: Write policy on %1 was changed to Write Back.
BAT1009.Description: The controller battery health has returned to normal.

SYS252.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because the file is not available at the remote host location.
SYS252.Resolution: Make sure that the file is available at the remote host location and retry the operation.
SYS252.Description: The file cannot be transferred because the file is not available at the remote host location.

LC030.Description: The file path specified for the operation is a read-only file system.
LC030.Resolution: Enable write access to the file path and try again.
LC030.Message: The file path is to a read-only file system.

SUP0109.Description: The firmware update cannot proceed without the TFTP IP address.
SUP0109.Message: A TFTP IP address has not been specified but is required.

PWR2209.Message: The system is in an undermined sleep state.

USR8512.Resolution: Contact the administrator and ensure the username and password credentials used are correct. Retry the operation with valid credentials.
USR8512.Description: The login attempt with details specified in the message was not successful.

UEFI0205.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0205.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0205.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Command Clock Training - Group 0 phase.

BAT1002.Message: The battery on %1 learn cycle has started.
BAT1002.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

STOR303.Description: Controller mode cannot be changed as the controller has foreign configuration associated with it.
STOR303.Resolution: Clear the foreign configuration and retry the operation.
STOR303.Message: Unable to change controller mode while foreign configuration is present on the controller.

SWC0298.Description: The specified object value cannot be configured if local configuration is disabled or smart card logon is enabled. If smart card logon is enabled, serial, SSH, telnet and IPMI over LAN is disabled by force and cannot be enabled.
SWC0298.Resolution: Enable Local Configuration (through GUI) or Disable Smart Card Logon to change the value.
SWC0298.Message: The specified object value cannot be configured if local configuration is disabled or smart card logon is enabled. If smart card logon is enabled, serial, SSH, telnet and IPMI over LAN is disabled by force and cannot be enabled.

PR34.Message: %1 failed after exceeding retry attempt limit.
PR34.Description: The job was attempted but failed unexpectedly. An AC Power loss, system crash, or other interruption during the job processing can cause this failure.

HWC4015.Description: CMC has old firmware and does not recognize the new device which has requested link tuning information. After updating the firmware the CMC will recognize the device.
HWC4015.Resolution: Update the CMC firmware. If the problem persists, contact support.

RAC989.Message: Unable to apply the %1 firmware update.
RAC989.Resolution: The file used for the operation is invalid. For the list of supported files, use "racadm help update". For the correct version of the file specific to the system, contact the service provider.
RAC989.Description: Only Windows-based Update Package (.exe extension), iDRAC Firmware (.d7 extension), Personality Module Firmware (.pm extension), Lifecycle Controller firmware repair package (.usc) are supported for the firmware update operation.

MEM8500.Description: A low memory condition was detected. If this condition continues, a failover or a reset may occur. If multiple resets occur, contact your service provider.
MEM8500.Resolution: If multiple resets occur, contact Service.

VDR33.Description: Background initialization of a virtual disk was cancelled. This may be due to user action. This operation may automatically restart.

SWC8620.Message: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to communicate with the iDRAC in server slot %1.
SWC8620.Resolution: Reset the server iDRAC. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8620.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to communicate with the iDRAC in server slot identified in the message.

SYS187.Description: Unable to start the collection of TTY log data because the server is in POST and has not finished startup.
SYS187.Resolution: Retry the operation after the server has finished starting and POST has completed.
SYS187.Message: Unable to start the collection of TTY log data because the server is in POST and has not finished startup.

SWU8521.Message: The firmware update operation of the iDRAC on the server in slot %1 was stopped. The selected Image file is not compatible with the server hardware.
SWU8521.Resolution: Make sure that the Image file is compatible with the server hardware, and then retry the operation.
SWU8521.Description: The firmware update operation of iDRAC identified in the message was stopped. The selected Image file is not compatible with the server hardware.

RAC0511.Description: Physical disks cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the host system is powered off, physical disks are removed, or incorrect filters are applied.
RAC0511.Resolution: 1. Check if the host system is powered off or shutdown. 2. Check if the physical disks are inserted into the enclosure or attached to the backplane. 3. Check if correct filters are applied. 4. Check that the Storage Enclosure is on. 5. verify that the adapter cables are properly connected and there are no bent pins.
RAC0511.Message: There are no physical disks to be displayed.

PSU1002.Resolution: Re-insert the power supply unit into the enclosure. Re-connect the AC power cable and switch on the power supply unit. Contact technical support if the issue persists.
PSU1002.Description: The enclosure detected that a power supply unit was removed and is no longer functioning in optimal condition.

VF039.Description: The detaching partition operation did not complete successfully.
VF039.Message: Detach partition operation did not complete successfully.

PWR1005.Description: To avoid exceeding the user defined capacity, system performance has been degraded.
PWR1005.Resolution: If unintended, review system configuration changes and power policy.
PWR1005.Message: The system performance degraded because of user-defined power capacity has changed.

UEFI0169.Message: Unable to configure memory interleaving on DIMM modules on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0169.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure interleaving can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0169.Description: Memory could not be interleaved because low memory (i.e. memory below the 4GB boundary) cannot be split evenly across processor sockets during memory initialization.

DIS104.Description: The AutoConfig operation is unable to access the network share folder, because an invalid filename is specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.
DIS104.Resolution: Specify a valid file name in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC using the (-f <filename>).
DIS104.Message: The AutoConfig operation is unable to access the network share folder, because an invalid filename is specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

HWC0014.Description: The import operation failed because the vFlash SD card is missing or disabled.
HWC0014.Resolution: Make sure the vFlash SD card is inserted and enabled before retrying the operation.
HWC0014.Message: Unable to detect vFlash SD card.

HWC8501.Description: The operation could not successfully completed because of an issue with the I/O panel cable.
HWC8501.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Connect the I/O panel cable properly 2) Replace the I/O panel cable.
HWC8501.Message: Unable to complete the operation because of an issue with the I/O panel cable.

PDR52.Description: The controller has two connectors that are connected to the same enclosure. The communication path on one connector has lost connection with the enclosure. The communication path on the other connector is reporting this loss.
PDR52.Resolution: Make sure the cables are attached securely. See the Cables Attached Correctly section for more information on checking the cables. Make sure both Enclosure Management Modules (EMMs) are healthy.

STOR0509.Description: The controller does not have the minimum number of initialized disks to create a virtual disk.
STOR0509.Resolution: Connect required number of initialized physical disks to the RAID controller and retry the operation.

RAC0248.Description: This message is displayed when trying to delete a vFlash partition.
RAC0248.Resolution: Press OK to delete this partition of the SD Card. This action will erase all the data in this partition. If undesired press Cancel.
RAC0248.Message: This operation deletes the partition permanently. Do you want to continue?

SWC0025.Description: The operation completed successfully, however the system is unable to automatically shut down.
SWC0025.Resolution: Manually shut down the system. For more information about the failure, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0025.Message: The operation completed successfully, however the system is unable to automatically shut down.

VDR32.Description: Background initialization of a virtual disk has started. This is an automated process that writes the parity or mirror data on newly created virtual disks.

USR8503.Message: Domain user authentication was not successful. Reason code = %1
USR8503.Resolution: Contact the administrator and ensure the username and password credentials used in the operation are correct.
USR8503.Description: The Active Directory authentication was not successful for the specified username.

SWC0222.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0222.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0222.Message: Invalid syntax. The -d option is not valid with -c.

NIC100.Message: The %1 Port %2 network link is down.
NIC100.Resolution: Verify that the network port is enabled and if the port has Activity/Speed LEDs, that they are lit. Check the network cable, network cable connections, and the attached network switch.
NIC100.Description: The network link is down. Either the network cable is not connected or the network device is not working.

RAC0283.Description: This is the time span (in seconds) within which IP Blocking Fail Count failures must occur to trigger the IP Blocking Penalty Time. The default value is 3600 seconds (1 hour).
RAC0283.Resolution: Enter a valid IP Blocking Fail Window. Expected range: 10-65535.
RAC0283.Message: IP Blocking Fail Window is invalid. Expected range: 10-65535.

STOR035.Description: Unable to perform operation because either the number of storage objects specified is insufficient or the storage objects are not in a required state to perform this operation.
STOR035.Resolution: Check the number and state of storage objects and retry the operation.
STOR035.Message: Unable to perform operation because either the number of storage objects specified is insufficient or the storage objects are not in a required state to perform this operation.

PDR88.Message: Power state change failed on %1. (from %2 to %2)
PDR88.Resolution: Replace the physical disk and try again. Contact technical support if the issue persists.
PDR88.Description: When physical drives in spun down power state are configured, the drives should transition to spun up power state. If the drive is not functioning properly, this transition could fail.

USR0008.Description: The Default Login Warning feature is disabled. No warning is provided if any local user is configured with default credentials.
USR0008.Message: The Default Login Warning feature is disabled.

RAC1032.Message: %1 jobs was cancelled by the user.
RAC1032.Description: The job specified in the message were cancelled.

JCP003.Description: The Job did not complete successfully.
JCP003.Resolution: Retry the operation, and if necessary, make sure that valid parameters are provided for the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
JCP003.Message: The Job did not complete successfully.

RAC0912.Description: The management system could not connect to the iDRAC.
RAC0912.Resolution: Verify whether the IP address of the remote iDRAC is correct. Verify whether connectivity exists between the management system and the iDRAC.
RAC0912.Message: Unable to connect to RAC at specified IP address.

VF034.Description: The specified partition access type is not a valid type.
VF034.Resolution: Try a partition access type that is supported.

PWR8667.Description: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is resetting iKVM to its default settings.
PWR8667.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is resetting iKVM to its default settings.

PCI1300.Description: The front panel diagnostic was pressed, and the system may be halted as a result. The interrupt was user induced.
PCI1300.Resolution: Reset the system to continue operation.
PCI1300.Message: A front panel diagnostic interrupt was detected.

STOR056.Description: Unable to complete the requested operation because the specified physical disk does not support data encryption.
STOR056.Resolution: Specify a physical disk that is security capable and retry the operation.
STOR056.Message: Physical disk is not security capable.

CMC8605.Message: The chassis health state is no longer OK and is currently %1.
CMC8605.Resolution: Review the Chassis log or the Chassis Management Controller(CMC) SEL log for any outstanding issue(s) and resolve any issues found by performing the recommended response action for each issue found. If the issue persists, export the chassis log and CMC SEL log and contact your support provider.
CMC8605.Description: The chassis health state is no longer OK and is currently the state identified in the message. Actions should be taken to resolve any outstanding issues so that the chassis health state will return to OK.

RDU0015.Description: The system may power down or operate in a performance degraded state.
RDU0015.Resolution: Check the event log for power supply failures. Review system configuration and power consumption and upgrade or install power supplies accordingly.
RDU0015.Message: The power supplies are not redundant. Insufficient resources to maintain normal operations.

SEL1404.Message: A platform event trap (PET) was generated.

OSE0001.Description: The system halted due to an exception while the operating system was running. This is a kernel panic or bug check event.
OSE0001.Resolution: Review operating system logs and system video for additional information.

RAC0208.Description: Upload failed possibly due to invalid key data.
RAC0208.Resolution: Upload a certificate with a valid key.
RAC0208.Message: Upload failed: May be due to invalid key data.

PCI3011.Message: The component at bus %1 device %2 function %3 recovered from a non-fatal IO error.

SWC0286.Description: Objects in the cfgUserAdmin group corresponding to index 1 cannot be modified.
SWC0286.Message: Modifying the user configuration at index 1 is not allowed.

BOOT014.Description: The system's SD card has been removed or is in use.
BOOT014.Resolution: Verify that the SD card is inserted and that another operation is not in progress, and try again.

TST106.Description: The email alert being tested is not properly configured.
TST106.Resolution: Configure the email alert and retry the operation. If the failure persists, reset iDRAC.
TST106.Message: Email alert destination address not configured.

STOR009.Description: Physical disk did not identify valid physical disk for the operation.
STOR009.Resolution: Provide compatible physical disk with the operation.
STOR009.Message: Physical disk FQDD did not identify a valid physical disk for the operation.

RAC0504.Description: Enclosures cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the host system is powered off, there is no enclosure connected to the controller, or there is a bad or disconnected adapter cable for the enclosure.
RAC0504.Resolution: 1. Check if the host system is ON. 2. Check if the Storage Enclosure is ON. 3. Verify that the adapter cables are properly connected and there are no bent pins.
RAC0504.Message: There are no enclosures to be displayed.

RAC0727.Description: Auto-throttling is enabled for the server based on a request from the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) because the CMC has restarted.
RAC0727.Message: Auto-throttling is enabled for the server.

HWC8508.Description: A device causing an issue in the I/O panel USB port is removed.
HWC8508.Message: A device causing an issue in the I/O panel USB port is removed.

UEFI0273.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the iSCSI target configuration data obtained from DHCPv4 server is invalid.
UEFI0273.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reconfigure the DHCPv4 server root path option, and note that server name must be specified. 2) Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings > Connection Settings page, disable Target Info via DHCP and configure the parameters manually. Retry the operation.
UEFI0273.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the iSCSI target configuration data obtained from DHCPv4 server is invalid.

SWC8627.Message: Unable to configure the storage array in slot %1, because there is no communication between Chassis Management Controller (CMC) and the storage device.
SWC8627.Resolution: 1. Reset iDRAC by using the graphical user interface (GUI): Click Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components. In the Reset Server section, from the Reset drop-down menu, select iDRAC Reset corresponding to the server iDRAC to be reset, and then click Apply Selection. Or, reset iDRAC by running the following command at the command line interface (CLI): racadm racreset -m server-n.2. Reset Chassis Management Controller (CMC) by using the GUI: Click Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components, and then click Reset/Failover CMC. Or, reset CMC by running the following command at the CLI: racadm racreset.For more information about the syntax and parameters used, see the iDRAC 8/7 v2.30.30.30 RACADM CLI Guide and the Chassis Management Controller Version 5.0 for Dell PowerEdge M1000e RACADM Command Line Reference Guide available on the support site.
SWC8627.Description: Unable to configure storage array. This could happen if CMC could not communicate with storage device.

BOOT010.Description: The provided vFlash partition index could not be found on the system.
BOOT010.Resolution: Verify that a vFlash partition with the desired index exists on the System.
BOOT010.Message: Could not locate vFlash partition index

USR0182.Description: Server information has been accessed by using the iDRAC Quick Sync feature.
USR0182.Message: Server information has been accessed by using the iDRAC Quick Sync feature.

AMP0312.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0312.Message: System level current is less than the lower warning threshold.

RAC074.Description: The iDRAC reset to factory defaults operation cannot be completed because a vflash partition creation operation is in progress.
RAC074.Resolution: Wait for the vFlash partition creation process to complete and retry the operation.
RAC074.Message: Unable to perform the iDRAC reset to factory defaults operation because a vFlash partition creation operation is in progress.

OSD70.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'Username' is missing.
OSD70.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "Username" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD70.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'Username' is missing.

VDR23.Description: This message is generated after initialization completes on a virtual disk.

PSU0007.Message: Power supply %1 is operating at 110 volts, and could cause a circuit breaker fault.
PSU0007.Resolution: Check input power source and cabling. Use recommended input power. Review the product documentation. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0007.Description: A power supply that is designed to operate at 220V, but is connected to a 110V power source requires additional current for operation. The additional current may trip circuit-breakers or cause other electrical issues with the input source.

RAC0698.Description: Unable to modify USB management settings because the USB device is currently in use.
RAC0698.Resolution: Wait for the current USB operations to complete and retry the operation.
RAC0698.Message: Unable to modify USB management settings because the USB device is currently in use.

NIC516.Message: Static IP configuration enabled and modified successfully

TST102.Description: The destination address of the email is not configured.
TST102.Resolution: Configure the email alert destination address and retry the operation.
TST102.Message: Email alert destination address not configured.

SWU8557.Description: Invalid firmware: The uploaded firmware image does not contain a verification signature.
SWU8557.Resolution: Use a valid firmware image and retry the operation.
SWU8557.Message: Invalid firmware: The uploaded firmware image does not contain a verification signature.

SEL1506.Message: Lost communications with Chassis Group Member %1.
SEL1506.Resolution: Check network cable and network connections.
SEL1506.Description: The primary CMC has lost communication with the indicated member CMC.

RAC0141.Description: Firmware update verification process failed; the firmware update status is unknown.
RAC0141.Resolution: Verify if the firmware has been updated by checking the new firmware version number. If it has not been updated try the firmware update again in a few minutes. If the problem persists, try uploading the firmware through another interface such as Web GUI, RACADM, or DUPs.
RAC0141.Message: Firmware update verification failed: The update status is unknown.

RAC0684.Description: Unable to perform split mode configuration on the selected enclosures, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
RAC0684.Resolution: To enable Lifecycle Controller, reboot the server. During server startup, press F2 to enter System Setup. Go to iDRAC Settings -> Lifecycle Controller, select Enable, and save the changes. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
RAC0684.Message: Unable to perform split mode configuration on the selected enclosures, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

PWR8552.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on %1-%2 because of insufficient power.
PWR8552.Resolution: Make sure there is enough power supply to distribute power. Using the CMC Web UI, go to Chassis Overview > Power > Power Budget Status. In the Total Input Power Available For Allocation field view the available power. To add more power, insert more PSUs or remove unused components from the chassis. Contact your service provider for information on the power required for the component identified in the message.
PWR8552.Description: There is insufficient power for the component identified in the message to turn on.

SWU8519.Message: The firmware update operation of the iDRAC on the server in slot %1 is stopped. The Image file is corrupted.
SWU8519.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the original source, and then retry the operation.
SWU8519.Description: The iDRAC firmware update operation was stopped, because the Image file is corrupted.

SYS126.Description: Application data source was not found. An issue occurred while collecting Application Data because of an unknown exception.
SYS126.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SYS126.Message: OS Collector: Unable to collect Application Data.

OSE1013.Resolution: Review system boot configuration and boot media. See system video for additional information.

RAC022.Description: Unable to set values for User Password, IPMILan, IPMISerial or User Admin Privilege because the User Name is not configured.
RAC022.Resolution: Set User Name before attempting to set values of other identified attributes.
RAC022.Message: Unable to set values for User Password, IPMILan, IPMISerial or User Admin Privilege because the User Name is not configured.

SWU8500.Message: The %1 request to Lifecycle Controller on server %2 was not successful.
SWU8500.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the error persists, contact your service provider.
SWU8500.Description: This message is displayed when:1. A reboot job is unable to provide a valid reboot ID.2. The WSMAN command to set up a job queue on Lifecycle Controller was not successful.

RAC1189.Description: The idrac.serviceModule.watchdogtimer object can not be enabled if the OS watch dog timer is already enabled.
RAC1189.Resolution: Disable the object using "racadm set BIOS.integratedDevices.osWatchdogTimer Disabled " Then retry the operation.
RAC1189.Message: Unable to set the object value for iDRAC Service Module.

RAC1184.Description: The getuscvresion RACADM subcommand will be deprecated in a future release.
RAC1184.Resolution: Instead of getuscversion, run the getversion -f lc subcommand.
RAC1184.Message: The getuscvresion RACADM subcommand will be deprecated in a future release.

FAN0016.Message: %1 RPM is outside of normal operating range.
FAN0016.Resolution: Remove and re-install the cooling device. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0016.Description: The cooling device is not performing optimally. The cooling device may be installed improperly.

CTL46.Message: Single-bit ECC error. The %1 DIMM is critically degraded.
CTL46.Resolution: Replace the DIMM immediately to avoid data loss or data corruption. The DIMM is a part of the controller battery pack. Refer to the storage hardware documentation for information on replacing the DIMM.
CTL46.Description: The Dual In-line Memory Module (DIMM) is malfunctioning. Data loss or data corruption may occur.

STOR301.Description: The requested operation could not be completed because there is an operation pending to change the controller mode. This operation is exclusive because it requires a server reboot for changes to apply.
STOR301.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Create a job to complete the pending controller mode change request operation, allow the job to complete, restart the server, and then retry the operation. 2) Cancel any pending operations on the RAID controller, and then retry the operation.
STOR301.Message: Unable to perform the operation because the controller mode change request is pending.

IOV103.Message: A PCIe adapter %1 in %2%3 is replaced by PCIe adapter %1.
IOV103.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected the replacement of an adapter in the slot identified in the message.

PDR111.Message: The volatile memory backup device on %1 is no longer functional.
PDR111.Resolution: Back up the data on the device, and contact your service provider for further instructions.
PDR111.Description: The volatile memory backup device on the PCIe solid state device identified in the message is no longer functional. Data loss is possible.

PDR47.Message: A block on %1 was punctured by the controller.
PDR47.Resolution: Back up the data from the disk. Start disk initialization and wait for it to complete, and then restore the data from a backup copy.
PDR47.Description: The controller encountered an unrecoverable medium error when attempting to read a block on the physical disk and marked that block as invalid. If the controller encountered the unrecoverable medium error on a source physical disk during a rebuild or reconfigure operation, it punctures the corresponding block on the target physical disk. The invalid block clears on a write operation.

RFM1024.Description: At boot, the Card Identification (CID) signature of the card is different from the Non-volatile (NV) storage value or the card is the destination of a copy operation that is in-progress.
RFM1024.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media.

UEFI0293.Description: DDR memory initialization of the Dual In-line Memory Modules (DIMMs) installed in the system cannot be completed because the DIMMs are installed in an unsupported, asymmetrical configuration between the Integrated Memory Controllers (iMCs).
UEFI0293.Resolution: Remove the Dual Inline Memory Module's (DIMMs) and install in a supported, symmetric configuration between the Integrated Memory Controllers (iMCs). For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual available on the support site.
UEFI0293.Message: Unable to initialize all Dual Inline Memory Modules (DIMMs) in the system because DIMMs are installed in an unsupported, asymmetric configuration between the Integrated Memory Controllers (iMCs).

STOR006.Description: The operation could not be completed because of an issue with the management controller (either the iDRAC or the Chassis Management Controller (CMC)) that is managing the storage.
STOR006.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

CTL23.Message: Copyback and Auto Copyback on Predictive Failure has changed for %1.
CTL23.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SWC4008.Description: FlexAddress is not implemented in one of the versions of firmware. Please update the firmware.
SWC4008.Resolution: Check firmware versions. Update CMC 1 and CMC 2 firmware to match.
SWC4008.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility detected between CMC 1 and CMC 2.

PSU8504.Description: Selecting the Allow 110 VAC Operation involves potential risk that an overload can occur. The overload risk was not acknowledged in the CMC Web interface when the selection was made.
PSU8504.Resolution: Select the Allow 110 VAC Operation and accept the subsequent dialog that acknowledges the overload risk.
PSU8504.Message: The Allow 110 VAC Operation overload risk is not acknowledged.

RAC0514.Description: Virtual disk(s) cannot be created because of one or more reasons identified in the Recommended Response Action.
RAC0514.Resolution: Check the following: 1) If no physical disk drives are available for virtual disk (VD) creation, install additional physical disk drives. 2) If the maximum number of VDs that can be created on the controller has been reached, a new VD cannot be created until an existing VD is deleted. 3) If the maximum number of VDs supported by drive group has been created, a new VD cannot be created until an existing VD is deleted from the selected drive group. 4) If the physical disk drive(s) are in non-RAID mode, convert them to RAID mode by pressing Ctrl+R while restarting the server, and then select the required controller. Press F2 and select the Convert to RAID capable option, and then complete the operation. 5) If a job is currently running or scheduled on the selected controller, the job must be completed or deleted before attempting a new operation. Status of the scheduled job can be viewed and managed on the Job Queue page on iDRAC. Click Job Queue link to view the status of the scheduled jobs.
RAC0514.Message: Unable to create virtual disk(s) on the selected controller.

LC072.Description: An SSL Certificate is successfully generated in response to the requested operation.
LC072.Resolution: Download the SSL Certificate and get it signed by an authority.
LC072.Message: An SSL Certificate is successfully generated.

HWC2010.Message: The riser board cable or interconnect is connected.

PCI2000.Message: A fatal IO error detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.
PCI2000.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, remove and re-install the device.
PCI2000.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.

CMC8703.Message: The Member chassis has joined the Chassis group%1.
CMC8703.Description: The Member chassis identified in the message has joined the chassis group.

SUP001.Description: Insufficient Parameters provided for the WSMAN command.
SUP001.Resolution: Make sure the parameters are correct and in the right number and format and retry the action.

RAC1017.Description: Any staged operation requires a job and system reboot to apply the object values.
RAC1017.Resolution: To apply modified value, create a configuration job and reboot the system. To create the commit and reboot jobs, use "jobqueue" command. For more information about the "jobqueue" command, see RACADM help.
RAC1017.Message: Successfully modified the object value and the change is in pending state.

SEC0000.Description: The chassis is open. System performance may be degraded, and security may be compromised.
SEC0000.Resolution: Close the chassis. Check system logs.

RED054.Description: A job for applying an update package was created.

IOV004.Description: The chassis manager is unable to turn on the PCIe device because of one of the following reasons: 1) PCIe device is not supported, 2) The device is not properly inserted in the slot, 3) The device is not functioning properly, or 4) The device power requirements exceed the power available for the slot.
IOV004.Resolution: Make sure a supported PCIe device is used and that it is properly inserted in the PCIe slot. For a list of supported devices, contact the service provider.
IOV004.Message: Unable to turn on PCIe adapter.

STOR066.Description: The requested operation did not succeed because the selected RAID controller is not T10 Protection Information capable.
STOR066.Resolution: Verify that the RAID controller selected for the operation is T10 Protection Information capable, and then retry the operation.
STOR066.Message: Controller is not T10 Protection Information capable.

RAC1128.Description: Any operation involving remote share (CIFS) cannot continue if the location (-l option) is not specified. The -u and -p options represent the user name and password for the remote share, and -l represents the location of the remote share.
RAC1128.Resolution: Make sure to specify the location (-l option) of the remote share along with the user name and password, and retry the operation. To view the list of options that can used for the required subcommand, run the RACADM command "racadm help <subcommand>".
RAC1128.Message: The -l option must be specified if -u and -p options are used.

VDR45.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

LC015.Resolution: Check for correct parameter values: 1) Disabled 2) Apply always 3) Apply only if firmware match.

PWR2252.Description: The server did not turn on because an NDC or Mezzanine card is incompatible with the I/O Module or PCIe subsystem.
PWR2252.Resolution: Check the release notes for the product and make sure to install compatible components in the server.
PWR2252.Message: Unable to turn on the server because an NDC or Mezzanine card is incompatible with the I/O Module or PCIe subsystem.

PSU8521.Message: PSU %1 exceeded upper temperature threshold and has been turned off.
PSU8521.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the PSU or remove AC power and reapply power to the PSU to get it functional again.
PSU8521.Description: The power supply unit (PSU) identified in the message was turned off because the temperature exceeded the high temperature threshold in the unit.

PWR8500.Message: Chassis power state updated to %1 from %2.
PWR8500.Description: The chassis power state from the configuration database and the current state are different. The current chassis power state will be updated in the configuration database. This is to insure the chassis power state will be the same if the CMC is rebooted or a CMC failover occurs. Note that the numerical value of the state is intended for technical support use.

OSD8.Description: The BIOS boot order set to PXE using a standard IPMI command has failed.
OSD8.Resolution: 1) Check BIOS PXE settings. 2) Rerun the command. 3) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD8.Message: Setting Boot to PXE through IPMI failed.

PDR8.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PDR106.Message: The physical disk drive %1 is unassigned as a dedicated hot-spare.
PDR106.Resolution: No response action is required. Assigning a new dedicated hot spare to the virtual disk is recommended.
PDR106.Description: A physical disk identified in the hot-spare that was assigned as a hot spare has been un-assigned and is no longer functioning as a hot spare. The physical disk was unassigned by a user or automatically by the storage management software. When one of the disks in a virtual disk fails, data is rebuilt onto the hot spare, The hot spare becomes a member of the virtual disk and is no longer assigned as a hot spare. In this situation, assigning a new hot spare to maintain data protection in recommended.

OSE0000.Description: The system halted due to an exception during operating system load or operating system initialization.
OSE0000.Resolution: Review operating system logs and system video for additional information.
OSE0000.Message: A critical stop occurred during OS load.

RAC1001.Description: Unable to set the object value for iDRAC IPv6 DNS1 or DNS2, because the object DNSFromDHCP6 is enabled.
RAC1001.Resolution: Disable the object DNSFromDHCP6 using "racadm set iDRAC.IPv6.DNSFromDHCP6 <0 | Disabled>", and retry the operation.
RAC1001.Message: Unable to set the object value for iDRAC IPv6 DNS1 or DNS2.

VF019.Resolution: Check all the partitions, delete the ones that are not necessary and try this operation again.
VF019.Message: Not enough space on SD card

TMP0100.Message: The system board %1 temperature is less than the lower warning threshold.
TMP0100.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.

JCP001.Description: The UEFI automated task related to the job was successfully scheduled.

SEC0703.Description: The Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) mode is disabled.
SEC0703.Message: The Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) mode is disabled.

CMC8575.Description: The RAC SSL Certificate is changed.
CMC8575.Message: The RAC SSL Certificate is changed.

OSE1011.Resolution: Check system event logs for additional exception information. Power down the system and attempt to boot again.

SWC0046.Description: Unable to initiate Import operation since another Import operation is already in progress.
SWC0046.Resolution: Wait until current Import operation is complete before initiating a new Import operation.

RED062.Description: Unable to successfully authenticate. The username or password entered is incorrect, or HTTP server does not support BASIC or Digest authentication types.
RED062.Resolution: Verify username, password and server authentication type. To manually update, retry the operation.
RED062.Message: Unable to successfully authenticate user credentials to the specified repository.

HWC1001.Description: The absent device may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.

IOID113.Message: Unable to configure the initiator properties of %1 Port %2.
IOID113.Resolution: Make sure that the iSCSI or FCoE partition of the network port is enabled. Check whether or not the network controller is working and then retry the operation.
IOID113.Description: The initiator properties of the NIC port could not be configured because either iSCSI or FCoE partition of the network port is not enabled, or the network controller is not functioning.

BAR113.Description: The Automatic Backup job that was earlier schedule was not successfully created. This could be due to an invalid parameter entered to create the job.
BAR113.Resolution: Using the iDRAC Web UI, select Server Profile from the navigation panel, and then the Automatic Backup tab. Clear Settings and reenter appropriate data, the select Schedule Backup to restart the Automatic Backup jobs. Using the RACADM CLI or WSMAN API, clear the scheduled backup settings and retry the Automatic Backup scheduling operation.
BAR113.Message: Unable to create an Automatic Backup job.

SYS414.Description: A new resource is successfully created.
SYS414.Message: A new resource is successfully created.

BAR028.Description: The component restoration on the host system has completed, but there were errors. The Host System will shutdown.
BAR028.Resolution: View configuration data and request attributes update for the components or retry system profile import.
BAR028.Message: Host System Component Restore completed with errors, shutting down Host System.

RDU8510.Message: CMC%1: cannot failover, CMC firmware versions are different
RDU8510.Resolution: Check the status of the standby CMC and make sure the firmware version matches the primary CMC. Then reseat the CMC and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RDU8510.Description: For failover to occur, the standby CMC needs to be present, at the same version as the primary and healthy. During failover, the active CMC resets and the standby CMC becomes active. This message is logged when the standby CMC is absent, unhealthy or at a different firmware version.

RAC0276.Description: If the Enable NIC checkbox is cleared, remote access to iDRAC is disabled.
RAC0276.Message: To save the changes and update this page, click Apply.

PDR97.Resolution: Provide the security key required to unlock the secure encrypted drives.
PDR97.Description: The controller detected drives that require security keys for access. Without providing security keys, the drives are unstable.

SWC0275.Description: The syntax for the config command is invalid.
SWC0275.Resolution: Refer to the help text for the 'config' subcommand.
SWC0275.Message: Invalid syntax. The -c option is only valid with -f or -g.

SWC4011.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility is automatically corrected between the %1%2 in Server-%3 and the Chassis Management Controller (CMC).
SWC4011.Description: A firmware or software incompatibility was automatically corrected between the network device in the Server identified in the message and the Chassis Management Controller (CMC).

USR0016.Description: Unable to obtain the session info from RAC.
USR0016.Message: Unable to get session info from the RAC.

IOV1003.Resolution: Refer to the DCIM Chassis PCI Management Profile document and provide the required parameter.
IOV1003.Description: One or more parameters identified in the message required for the method are missing.

RED092.Message: The %1 firmware updated successfully. Previous version: %2, Current version: %3
RED092.Description: The firmware for the component identified in the message was updated successfully to the firmware version identified in the message.

SYS267.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because the network connection from the proxy server to the remote host server is unsuccessful.
SYS267.Resolution: Make sure that correct file transfer parameters are set, the health of remote host is good, and then retry the operation.
SYS267.Description: Unable to transfer a file because the network connection from the proxy server to the remote host server is unsuccessful.

LIC201.Message: License %1 assigned to device %2 expires in %3 days.
LIC201.Resolution: Purchase a new license to prevent interruption of licensed features.
LIC201.Description: This license is going to expire. An expired license could result in the loss of functionality that is specific to the features supported by the license.

STOR067.Description: The operation did not succeed since the selected controller does not support creating uneven span RAID10 virtual disks.
STOR067.Resolution: The selected controller is not capable of creating an uneven span RAID10 virtual disk. Specify the proper span length and span depth combination for creating RAID10 virtual disk on the selected controller, and then retry the operation.
STOR067.Message: Controller does not support uneven span RAID10 virtual disks.

VFL0012.Description: The vFlash media is not enabled.
VFL0012.Resolution: Enable the vFlash media by running the command 'racadm set idrac.vFlashSD.Enable 1'.

PST0196.Description: System BIOS detected an invalid memory population. Reinstall the memory to match the supported population. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception code C4).
PST0196.Resolution: Re-install memory to match supported memory configuration.

BIOS009.Description: Lifecycle Controller cannot gain access to internal storage because of use by another application or operation.
BIOS009.Resolution: Wait for the current Lifecycle Controller operation to complete. Verify that the system is 1) Not currently in Lifecycle Controller Unified Server Configurator utility 2) Waiting for user intervention at F1/F2 POST error 3) Not in any of the device or controller Option ROMs and retry the operation.
BIOS009.Message: Lifecycle Controller is currently in use.

BOOT020.Description: The ChangeBootOrderByInstanceID command cannot be run because the BIOS Import operation is in progress.
BOOT020.Resolution: Wait for the BIOS Import operation to complete and retry the operation.
BOOT020.Message: Unable to run the ChangeBootOrderByInstanceID command because the BIOS Import operation is in progress.

CMC8607.Message: Unable to retrieve information about the firmware on server in slot %1, because there is no communication between Chassis Management Controller (CMC) and iDRAC.
CMC8607.Resolution: 1.Reset iDRAC by using the graphical user interface (GUI): Click Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components. In the Reset Server section, from the Reset drop-down menu, select iDRAC Reset corresponding to the server iDRAC to be reset, and then click Apply Selection. Or, reset iDRAC by running the following command at the command line interface (CLI): racadm racreset -m server-n.2.Reset Chassis Management Controller (CMC) by using the GUI: Click Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components, and then click Reset/Failover CMC. Or, reset CMC by running the following command at the CLI: racadm racreset.For more information about the syntax and parameters used, see the iDRAC 8/7 v2.30.30.30 RACADM CLI Guide and the Chassis Management Controller Version 5.0 for Dell PowerEdge M1000e RACADM Command Line Reference Guide available on the support site.
CMC8607.Description: Information about the firmware on server in slot identified in the message cannot be retrieved because there is no communication between Chassis Management Controller (CMC) and iDRAC.

USR8504.Description: The IP range filter feature is enabled in CMC. The IP address from where the login attempt was made is not in the specified range of IP address that can access the CMC.
USR8504.Resolution: If access needs to be given to this specified IP address, change the IP range address and IP range mask accordingly and retry the operation.
USR8504.Message: The IP address specified is out of range.

PWR2404.Description: Power supply capacity alert disabled due to user configuration.

RAC0718.Description: Remote File Share service is busy with the previous connection.
RAC0718.Resolution: Stop the Remote File Share session and retry the operation.
RAC0718.Message: Remote File Share service is busy with the previous connection.

SWC0070.Description: The SupportAssist collection has been successfully copied to the USB drive.
SWC0070.Message: The SupportAssist collection has been successfully copied to the USB drive.

UEFI0260.Description: The R930 baseboard does not support R920 memory risers.
UEFI0260.Resolution: Replace R920 memory risers with R930 memory risers. For information about the supported memory riser types, see the Owners Manual available at the support site.
UEFI0260.Message: The R930 baseboard does not support R920 memory risers.

STOR025.Description: The pending configuration cannot be deleted because the configuration job is already scheduled.
STOR025.Resolution: Delete the current configuration job for the device to stop pending configuration changes.
STOR025.Message: Unable to delete any pending configuration because the configuration job is already scheduled.

RAC0214.Description: Login page is missing a password.

FSD001.Message: Debug authorized by Dell; debugcaps: %1, at %2, was authorized by Dell employee: %3, for the time period %4 to %5.
FSD001.Description: Dell has authorized the specified debug capabilities. Each debug capability represents a certain action Dell engineers can perform to debug iDRAC.

LC101.Description: The server screen shot cannot be exported because the operation timed out before capturing the screen shot.
LC101.Resolution: Wait for some time and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
LC101.Message: Unable to export the server screen shot because the operation timed out before capturing the screen shot.

OSE1000.Description: The system OS has successfully booted from A:.

SYS407.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the value %1 entered for the query parameter %2 is invalid.
SYS407.Resolution: Enter a valid value and retry the operation. The minimum value that can entered for top query parameter is 1.
SYS407.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the value entered for the query parameter identified in the message is invalid.

STOR062.Description: One or more physical disks specified are full and cannot be used to create additional virtual disks.
STOR062.Resolution: Make sure all physical disks specified to create a virtual disk have the required amount of free space and retry the operation.
STOR062.Message: One or more physical disks specified are full and cannot be used to create additional virtual disks.

CTL11.Description: A user operation to reset the controller configuration was performed.

PWR203.Description: The System Input Power Cap value cannot be set to less than or equal to 13300 W, because the Extended Power Performance feature is enabled.
PWR203.Resolution: Enter a Power cap value greater than 13300 W, and then retry the operation.
PWR203.Message: Unable to set the System Input Power Cap value to less than or equal to 13300 W (45381 BTU/h), because the Extended Power Performance feature is enabled.

JCP014.Description: The number of jobs specified in the SetupJobQueue request combined with the existing job count contains more jobs IDs than the maximum number of jobs supported by the system (256). Completed jobs are automatically deleted if they are older than the delete on completion timeout setting.
JCP014.Resolution: Reduce the number of jobs specified in the operation or reduce the existing job count before retrying the operation. Perform one of the following to reduce the job count: 1) Delete one or more jobs and retry the operation. 2) Wait until existing jobs have an elapsed time since completion that is greater than the delete on completion timeout setting and are automatically deleted. 3) Change the delete on completion timeout setting to a smaller value so that completed jobs are automatically deleted sooner.

CTL74.Resolution: Check for the existence of a foreign configuration and import if any. Check that enclosures are cabled correctly.
CTL74.Description: The controller has preserved data in the cache from a virtual disk, which it can no longer locate. No data loss has occurred as the controller is saving these operations in its cache.

SWU8504.Message: Successfully scheduled the %1 operation on the server %2.
SWU8504.Description: The specified Lifecycle Controller operation is successfully submitted and the operation will be executed on the basis of scheduling criteria.

PWR8547.Description: The chassis was already turned off, when the power off request was received.

VF043.Description: The file size is too large to be used.

SWC0105.Description: The command does not take in the -m option.
SWC0105.Resolution: Refer the help text for getraclog command.
SWC0105.Message: Invalid -m option. Try --more or refer help for proper usage.

PSU0906.Message: An interlock power down error detected on power unit %1.
PSU0906.Resolution: Remove input power at the power supply.
PSU0906.Description: In order to meet service requirements the supply must be shut down.

SEC0701.Description: This warning message is displayed when using the default username and password (root and calvin). Using the default password causes a severe security risk for iDRAC.
SEC0701.Resolution: To change the password, run the following racadm commands: racadm set iDRAC.Users.<index>.Password <new password string>.Alternatively, to avoid this warning message run the following racadm command: racadm set iDRAC.Tuning.DefaultCredentialWarning Disable.
SEC0701.Message: Warning: Default username and password are currently in use. It is strongly recommended to change the default password immediately.

SYS157.Description: Unable to successfully complete requested options of the System Erase operation. Retrying the System Erase operation may be required.
SYS157.Resolution: Retry the System Erase operation. To retry the System Erase operation using the Lifecycle Controller utility, restart the server and when the company logo is displayed, press <F10>. Select Hardware Configuration > Retire or Repurpose System, check appropriate options, and then retry the operation. Also disable "F1/F2 Prompt on Error" in BIOS settings for System Erase operation to continue without intervention.
SYS157.Message: Unable to successfully complete requested System Erase tasks.

SWC8532.Description: The starting IP address specified cannot accommodate all the servers. The starting iDRAC IPv4 Address specifies the static IPv4 address of the iDRAC located in the first slot. The static IPv4 address of each subsequent iDRAC is calculated as a slot number increment of this IPv4 address.
SWC8532.Resolution: Make sure there are enough IPv4 addresses for all the iDRACs and then retry the operation.
SWC8532.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to set chassis assigned QuickDeploy IP addresses because the starting IP address cannot accommodate all iDRACs.

UEFI0125.Description: Unable to finish The Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) image rebuild process because of issues.
UEFI0125.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reseat or replace the SD card media. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. Restart the system and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0125.Message: Unable to finish The Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) image rebuild process because of issues.

SYS078.Description: Unable to retrieve the Server Configuration Profile from the network share for the requested preview operation. This may be due to issues with network accessibility.
SYS078.Resolution: If the configuration profile is on an NFS share, make sure that the network share is accessible from iDRAC. If the configuration profile is on a CIFS share, make sure that the network share is accessible from iDRAC using the share credentials specified. Test the network share access using the Test Network Connection method. For more information, see the Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.
SYS078.Message: Unable to retrieve the Server Configuration Profile from the network share for preview.

OSD9.Description: Resetting the targeted server using the standard IPMI command has failed.
OSD9.Resolution: 1) Rerun the command. 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD9.Message: Failed to reboot the system using an IPMI command.

RAC920.Description: From firmware racadm, the inlet temperature history can be exported only to a remote file share.
RAC920.Resolution: Create a remote file share to export the inlet temperature history. Else, use remote/local racadm to export to the file system accessible by the racadm executable.
RAC920.Message: This interface does not support the specified option.

UEFI0229.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0229.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0229.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Receive Enable Training - Calibration phase.

VF044.Description: File transfer was not successful. This could be because of network problems or an operational problem with the file server.
VF044.Resolution: Try the download again. If the issue persists, validate that the network share is operational.
VF044.Message: TFTP download operation was not successful.

FAN908.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is already disabled.
FAN908.Message: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is already disabled.

RAC1137.Description: Remote unattended diagnostic results export operation initiated.
RAC1137.Resolution: Using the RACADM command line interface, run the "racadm jobqueue view -i <job id>" command to view the status of the operation.
RAC1137.Message: Remote unattended diagnostic results export operation initiated.

SYS158.Description: Unable to erase hardware caches during the System Erase operation.
SYS158.Resolution: Retry the System Erase operation with only the hardware cache erase option selected.

RAC1005.Description: The hardware inventory was successfully exported.

ISM0024.Message: The NVMe Device %1 is successfully prepared for removal from PCIe slot %2.
ISM0024.Resolution: No further response action is required before removing the NVMe Device identified in the message. To enable the NVMe Device for use, remove and re-insert the device or restart the system with the device inserted.
ISM0024.Description: The NVMe Device identified in the message is successfully prepared for removal from the PCIe slot identified in the message.

CMC8524.Message: The Mezz card 4 FRU for the server %1 is not functioning.
CMC8524.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC of the specified server or virtual reseat the server. 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8524.Description: The Mezz card 4 FRU for the server specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.

SYS156.Description: The requested component erase tasks of the System Erase operation is successfully completed.
SYS156.Message: Erase operations for System Erase tasks successfully completed.

SUP0538.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Download the latest Update Package from your service provider. 2) Disable the Trusted Platform Module feature in BIOS settings. 3) Update the Lifecycle Controller firmware to the latest version.
SUP0538.Description: Unable to update firmware due to one the following:1) Update Package is not supported. 2) Trusted Platform Module feature is enabled in BIOS settings.

UEFI0256.Description: Unable to allocate legacy I/O resources for one of more PCIe devices because the legacy I/O space limit was reached. The legacy I/O space limit is 64K.
UEFI0256.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Remove unused PCIe cards to free up legacy I/O space. 2) Go to System Setup and disable unused PCIe cards to free up legacy I/O space.
UEFI0256.Message: Unable to allocate legacy I/O resources for one of more PCIe devices because the legacy I/O space limit was reached.

FAN905.Description: Applying fan configuration settings. This may take several seconds.
FAN905.Message: Applying fan configuration settings. This may take several seconds.

UEFI0093.Message: The DIMM installed on the memory slot: %1 does not meet the minimum supported frequency.
UEFI0093.Resolution: Remove all unsupported DIMM modules from the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0093.Description: The DIMM installed on the memory slot identified in the message does not meet the minimum supported frequency.

RAC067.Description: iDRAC reset to factory defaults operation was not successful. This may be due to IPMI communications issues.
RAC067.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, remove AC input power from the server and re-apply AC power to the server and retry the operation. 3) If the issue continues to persist, contact your service provider.
RAC067.Message: iDRAC reset to factory defaults operation was not successful.

VLT0229.Message: The memory module %1 voltage is within range.

STOR099.Message: Unable to find the FQDD %1 because an invalid FQDD is entered or an operation is pending on the specified FQDD.
STOR099.Resolution: Do the following and then retry the operation: 1) Make sure the FQDD entered is valid. 2) Make sure an operation is not pending on the FQDD identified in the message. For more information refer to the RACADM Command Line Reference Guide.
STOR099.Description: The FQDD cannot be found because an invalid FQDD is entered or an operation is pending on the FQDD identified in the message.

PST0084.Description: System started the Automated Task application.

ISM0030.Description: Unable to complete iDRAC Hard Reset operation because this feature is not supported on this platform.
ISM0030.Resolution: Refer to the platform User's Guide documentation for information about whether the iDRAC Hard Reset feature is available.
ISM0030.Message: Unable to complete the iDRAC Hard Reset operation because this feature is not supported on this platform.

PWR8674.Description: Unable to change the value of the Allow 110 VAC Operation property because it is not supported in NEBS configuration PWR or PSU.
PWR8674.Message: Unable to change the value of Allow 110 VAC Operation property because it is not supported in NEBS configuration PWR or PSU.

CMC8532.Message: Unable to perform the requested action on the peripheral sled %1, because of insufficient privileges.
CMC8532.Resolution: Use a different user account that has Server Administrator privilege, and retry the operation. For more information, contact your system administrator or service provider.
CMC8532.Description: The user account does not have sufficient privileges to perform the requested operation. Server Administrator privilege is required to perform the requested action.

SYS098.Description: A Remote Diagnostic (ePSA) job already exists and only one job of this type can exist at a time.
SYS098.Resolution: A response action is not required if the scheduled start time of the existing Remote Diagnostic (ePSA) job is ok. Else, delete the existing Diagnostics (ePSA) job and recreate another with an appropriate start time.
SYS098.Message: A Remote Diagnostic (ePSA) job already exists.

STOR027.Description: Setting the Virtual disk name is not a valid operation on the specified controller.
STOR027.Resolution: Do not specify the virtual disk name and retry the operation.
STOR027.Message: Virtual Disk name is not supported.

RAC0500.Description: Batteries cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the host system is powered off or there is a bad or disconnected cable for batteries connected to the controller.
RAC0500.Resolution: 1. Check if the host system is powered off or shutdown. 2. Verify that the batteries are connected properly.
RAC0500.Message: There are no batteries to be displayed.

FAN0019.Message: An incompatibility between operating mode and fan type was corrected for fan %1.
FAN0019.Description: An incompatibility between operating mode and fan type was corrected for the fan identified in the message.

RAC0105.Description: Communication with the Smart Card reader cannot be established, or is lost.
RAC0105.Resolution: This error may occur because:1. Check connection between reader and system.2. There may be an issue with the Smart Card reader. Try reinstalling the reader driver or use a different reader.
RAC0105.Message: The Smart Card reader cannot be detected. Check whether the reader is installed correctly.

VRM0019.Description: The Remote Image is now configured and ready to use.

STOR039.Description: Unable to complete the requested operation because of a mismatch in the number of AttributeName and AttributeValue values specified.
STOR039.Resolution: Specify a valid number of AttributeName and AttributeValue pair values and retry the operation.
STOR039.Message: Mismatch in AttributeName and AttributeValue count.

STOR055.Description: The BIOS on the server is not Dell Key Management capable.
STOR055.Resolution: For more information about key management capabilities, see Dell Key Manager or Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Guide available at dell.com/support/manuals.
STOR055.Message: BIOS does not support Dell Key Manager capabilities.

TMP0201.Message: CPU %1 temperature is less than the lower critical threshold.

STOR058.Description: Unable to complete the operation either because the operation is not supported on the target device, or the RAIDType of "MD Software RAID" does not allow the operation.
STOR058.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) Make sure that the target device supports the operation. 2) Make sure that the if the RAIDType is set to "MD Software RAID" ensure that is the desired value. . For more information, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
STOR058.Message: The operation cannot be completed either because the operation is not supported on the target device, or the RAIDType of "MD Software RAID" does not allow the operation.

VF010.Description: Formatting the specified partition did not complete successfully.
VF010.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Rerun the command after about 2 minutes 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
VF010.Message: Partition formatting did not complete successfully.

RED015.Description: The download protocol specified is not supported.
RED015.Resolution: The supported protocols include NFS, CIFS, HTTP, FTP, TFTP.
RED015.Message: The download protocol specified is not supported.

VDR98.Message: %1 has switched active controllers. Its active path is now through %2.
VDR98.Description: The virtual disk identified in the message has changed active paths. This can be because of an attempt to optimize the throughput of the system or it could be because of a controller failover.

VF026.Description: This partition index has already been used.
VF026.Resolution: This partition index has already been used. Try a different index.

UEFI0117.Description: Card identification signature is not present on Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) SD card 1.
UEFI0117.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Check the IDSDM or the SD card media. 2) Try reseat or replace the SD card media. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0117.Message: Card identification signature is not present on Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) SD card 1.

SWC0129.Description: Racadm tool was not able to send a test email for the configuration.
SWC0129.Resolution: Check for the parameters mentioned in the message.
SWC0129.Message: Unable to send test email. Please make sure that your email alerts have been configured correctly and connectivity to the SMTP server exists.

PSU0038.Message: Power supply %1 fan is operating normally.

UEFI0108.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.
UEFI0108.Resolution: Remove input power to the system, reseat the DIMM module and restart the system. If the issues persist, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0108.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot identified in the message. The error occurred during Read Receiving Enable initialization.

LIC907.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of lack of an unknown error in the iDRAC.
LIC907.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC.
LIC907.Message: Unable to perform the operation due to an unknown error in iDRAC.

RAC012.Description: The user credentials supplied do not have sufficient privileges to perform the operation.
RAC012.Resolution: Retry the operation with user credentials authorized for the requested operation.
RAC012.Message: Unable to perform the operation because of insufficient user privileges.

SWU8555.Description: Active and Standby CMC firmware update process is initiated.
SWU8555.Message: Active CMC and Standby CMC firmware updates have been initiated.

IOV107.Message: PCIe adapter %1 in slot %2 was removed while powered on.
IOV107.Resolution: Power down the affected server(s) and then power on the server(s). Note: OS reboot only will not correct this issue.
IOV107.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) has detected the removal of a PCIe adapter card while it was powered on.

LC053.Description: Lifecycle Controller Remote Service is either not ready or currently reloading server information.
LC053.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, refer to Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation for more information.
LC053.Message: Lifecycle Controller Remote Services is currently unavailable.

RAC0243.Description: There was a conflict with a concurrent session. Another user may have logged in using a separate browser or RACADM.
RAC0243.Resolution: There was a conflict with a concurrent session. Refresh the page to see the currently available options.
RAC0243.Message: Partition failed: A partitioning conflict has occurred with another session.

SWC1929.Message: The iDRAC Quick Sync inactivity timeout value is set to %1.
SWC1929.Description: The iDRAC Quick Sync inactivity timeout value is set to the value identified in the message.

STOR021.Description: Operation cannot be completed because a controller key is not present.
STOR021.Resolution: Set an appropriate controller key and retry the operation.
STOR021.Message: The controller key is not present.

SYS048.Message: Server Configuration Profile contains invalid characters, %1 at line %2.
SYS048.Resolution: View the file in any Web browser to check for invalid characters. Remove the invalid characters and make sure that the file is a valid XML and is compliant with the system configuration schema published on delltechcenter.com/lc in the LC profile Schema Guide.
SYS048.Description: The operation expected a valid profile that is compliant with the system configuration schema. However, the Server Configuration Profile does not contain valid profile content.

RED089.Description: A Chassis firmware update operation is in progress. Any attempt to update Chassis firmware during this period will be unsuccessful.
RED089.Message: A Chassis firmware update operation is in progress.

BAR061.Description: Collecting system information and copying it into the backup file. The operation collects system information that includes System Model and Service Tag.

TMP0135.Message: The control panel temperature is within range.

VLT0211.Message: The memory module %1 %2 voltage is within range.

UEFI0203.Message: A failing memory buffer has been detected during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.
UEFI0203.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0203.Description: A failing memory buffer has been identified on the memory riser identified in the message.

PWR211.Description: The Fresh Air (FA) mode cannot be set because the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature is enabled.
PWR211.Message: Unable to set the Fresh Air (FA) mode because the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature is enabled.

BAR037.Description: Adjustments to Lifecycle and Integrated Remote Access Controller environments are complete.
BAR037.Message: System Reset or Lifecycle Controller Actions Canceled, System Profile Failure Recovery completed.

SYS1003.Description: System is performing a CPU reset because of system power off, power on or a warm reset like CTRL-ALT-DEL.

STOR033.Description: The requested operation cannot be completed because an invalid value is specified for Start/Until Time.
STOR033.Resolution: Enter a valid Start/Until Time and retry the operation. For more information about the Start/Until Time, see the RAID Profile specification.
STOR033.Message: Invalid parameter value for Start/Until Time.

SYS266.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because either an unsupported access type value is set or the value is not set at all.
SYS266.Resolution: Make sure that correct access type value is entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS266.Description: Unable to transfer a file because either an unsupported access type value is set or the value is not set at all.

SWC0079.Description: iDRAC entered into Dell Integrated Data Center Troubleshooting Mode.
SWC0079.Message: iDRAC entered into Integrated Data Center Troubleshooting Mode.

PFM0004.Message: The value of %1 is within specified limits.
PFM0004.Description: The value of the sensor identified in the message is within specified limits.

ISM0019.Description: The OS Collector application did not start successfully on the server operating system (OS), because checksum verification did not succeed for some files.
ISM0019.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the OS Collector on the iDRAC to the most recent version available, and then retry the operation.
ISM0019.Message: The OS Collector application did not start successfully on the server operating system (OS) because checksum verification did not succeed for some files.

RAC1142.Description: The Remote diagnostic operation cannot be performed because the difference between "Start Time" and "Expiration Time" is less than 5 minutes.
RAC1142.Resolution: Make sure that the Expiration Time is greater than five minutes, and then retry the operation.
RAC1142.Message: Unable to start the Remote Diagnostics operation because the Expiration Time entered (difference between Start Time and Expiration Time) is less than five minutes.

VDR7.Resolution: Create a new virtual disk and restore from a backup.
VDR7.Description: One or more physical disks included in the virtual disk have failed. If the virtual disk is non-redundant (does not use mirrored or parity data), then the failure of a single physical disk can cause the virtual disk to fail. If the virtual disk is redundant, then more physical disks have failed than you can rebuild using mirrored or parity information.

LIC021.Description: All the features in the evaluation license are currently licensed in the system. The license is not imported as it would duplicate existing and active licensed features.
LIC021.Resolution: Remove the license(s) that contain the license set from the evaluation license.
LIC021.Message: Import failed: The features contained in the evaluation license are already licensed.

SWC1910.Message: User ID %1 User Name has been changed.
SWC1910.Description: User ID Name has been changed.

PCI3009.Message: PCIe is operating normally on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

VFL0001.Description: The requested operation for the vFlash SD Card completed successfully.
VFL0001.Message: The vFlash SD Card operation is successful.

RAC0708.Description: Previous reboot was due to a firmware watchdog timeout.
RAC0708.Message: Previous reboot was due to a firmware watchdog timeout.

STOR048.Description: Either the controller or the firmware on the controller does not support the Dell Key Management feature.
STOR048.Message: Controller is not Dell Key Management capable.

BAT1024.Description: The battery or the battery charger is not functioning properly. The battery may have an inadequate charge.

OSE0005.Description: Graceful shutdown request to an agent via the BMC did not occur due to a system hardware or software exception.
OSE0005.Resolution: Review operating system logs and system video for additional information.

SWU8527.Description: The iKVM firmware update operation is successful.
SWU8527.Message: Successfully completed the iKVM firmware update.

UEFI0269.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the iSCSI target IP address is invalid.
UEFI0269.Resolution: Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings > Connection Settings page, do the following: 1) Make sure the Target IP Address is set corresponding to the mode enabled (IPv4/IPv6). 2) Make sure there is no typographical error in the Target IP Address field. 3) Retry the operation.
UEFI0269.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the iSCSI target IP address is invalid.

SWC8534.Description: All keys saved in the Chassis Management Controller for PK SSH Authentication are deleted.
SWC8534.Message: All keys deleted for all slots of service account.
