RAC1130.Description: The requested operation could not be successfully completed because of an unsupported version of BIOS, USC, and/or iDRAC firmware.
RAC1130.Resolution: Verify whether or not a correct version of BIOS, Lifecycle Controller, and/or iDRAC firmware is installed. For more information on the appropriate firmware version required, refer to the RACADM Command Line Reference Guide. Also check if there is a limitation in terms of platforms such as monolithic or modular, and then retry the operation.
RAC1130.Message: Unable to complete the operation. This feature is not supported on the currently-used platform.

ENC15.Message: An enclosure blink operation has initiated on %1.
ENC15.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SWC1917.Description: HTTP to HTTPS redirection is disabled. Any iDRAC connection made over the HTTP port (default port number 80) will no longer be redirected to the secure HTTPS port (default port number 443). This will make the connections insecure as the data transmitted over the port is no longer encrypted.

UEFI0112.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.
UEFI0112.Resolution: Remove input power to the system, reseat the DIMM module and restart the system. If the issues persist, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0112.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot identified in the message. The error occurred during the LRDIMM interface initialization.

RAC1192.Description: The Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is currently disabled. If the system inventory is not up-to-date, the system configuration profile that is being copied will not have the latest inventory information.
RAC1192.Resolution: To get latest inventory information, cancel the current job, run "racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.CollectSystemInventoryOnRestart 1" to enable CSIOR, and re-initiate the operation.
RAC1192.Message: The Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled.

BAR055.Message: Previously stored configuration values not applied to Device: %1.
BAR055.Resolution: The system event log captures the values that were not set, and must be reset manually.
BAR055.Description: Attempted configuration import was not successful for the specified device.

RAC0758.Message: Tech Support Report (TSR) data is being collected. This operation will take less than %1 minutes.
RAC0758.Resolution: To cancel the reports collection click Cancel.
RAC0758.Description: The Tech Support Report generation will take the time identified in the message to complete.

SEC0001.Description: The drive bay is open. A drive may be added or removed. System performance may be degraded.
SEC0001.Resolution: Close the drive bay. Check system logs.

PCI3000.Description: Either the BIOS, BMC/iDRAC, or LOM firmware is out of date and does not support FlexAddress.
PCI3000.Resolution: Update BIOS, BMC/iDRAC, and LOM firmware. If problem persists please contact customer support.
PCI3000.Message: Device option ROM on embedded NIC failed to support Link Tuning or FlexAddress.

RAC0142.Description: The firmware update process identified an invalid firmware image.
RAC0142.Resolution: Upload a valid iDRAC firmware image.
RAC0142.Message: File is not valid for iDRAC firmware update.

CPU0001.Message: CPU %1 has a thermal trip (over-temperature) event.
CPU0001.Resolution: Review logs for fan failures, replace failed fans. If no fan failures are detected, check inlet temperature (if available) and reinstall processor heatsink.
CPU0001.Description: The processor temperature increased beyond the operational range. Thermal protection shut down the processor. Factors external to the processor may have induced this exception.

RAC0156.Description: While the system is powered off it is unable to retrieve information about system voltage.
RAC0156.Resolution: Turn the system on to view this information.
RAC0156.Message: Unable to retrieve the voltage information. The system is powered off.

RAC0158.Description: The Kerberos keytab is needed by the iDRAC to authenticate itself to the Kerberos (Active Directory) server. It is created on the AD server, and issued for the iDRAC. Its like a password, and therefore should be kept secret.
RAC0158.Resolution: The Kerberos keytab file may be corrupt. Upload a valid Kerberos keytab file.

SWC0047.Description: The passphrase specified is not correct.
SWC0047.Resolution: Enter the valid passphrase and retry the operation.
SWC0047.Message: Incorrect backup Server Configuration Profile file passphrase provided.

VFL0010.Description: Another operation is currently in progress on the SD card.
VFL0010.Resolution: Wait until the current operation is completed, and then retry the requested operation.
VFL0010.Message: An operation is in progress on the SD card.

SWC0253.Description: Unable to allocate memory to perform the operation, see the inserted comment.
SWC0253.Resolution: Power Cycle the system and re-enter the command.
SWC0253.Message: Unable to allocate memory needed to perform operation.

SYS093.Description: The iDRAC is exporting the Tech Support Report to the specified destination.
SYS093.Message: The iDRAC is exporting the Tech Support Report.

CTL14.Message: Single-bit ECC error limit exceeded on the %1 DIMM.
CTL14.Description: The storage controller memory identified in the message is not operating correctly.

VLT0300.Message: CPU %1 %2 voltage is less than the lower warning threshold.
VLT0300.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0300.Description: Low voltages may be the result of a problem with the voltage regulator or a problem with the processor. The low voltage may cause the processor to fail to operate.

SUP0516.Description: Do not turn off the system while firmware update is in progress.

UEFI0064.Description: One or more attributes were successfully configured. The system will be automatically restarted.
UEFI0064.Message: One or more attributes are successfully configured. The system is being restarted.

PCI3016.Description: Either the BIOS, BMC/iDRAC, or mezzanine card firmware is out of date and does not support FlexAddress.
PCI3016.Resolution: Update BIOS, BMC/iDRAC, and mezzanine card firmware. If problem persists please contact customer support.
PCI3016.Message: Device option ROM on mezzanine card failed to support Link Tuning or FlexAddress.

SYS006.Message: Unable to set read only attribute: %1
SYS006.Resolution: Refer to the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services documentation for the specific attribute behavior.
SYS006.Description: The attribute being set is currently read-only and cannot be changed.

MEM9004.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the server and check whether the issue persists. 2) If the issue is not resolved by the preceding action, reseat the processors and restart the server. 3) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
MEM9004.Description: A link degradation was detected in propagation of signals between processors through the Intel QPI interconnect interconnect identified in the message. The system will continue to operate at reduced performance.

SYS421.Description: The Active Directory object DCLookupByUserDomain cannot be disabled, because the DCLookupDomainName object of Active Directory is not configured.
SYS421.Resolution: Configure the DCLookupDomainName object by using the PATCH operation on the Redfish OemAttributes URL, and then retry the operation.
SYS421.Message: The Active Directory object DCLookupByUserDomain cannot be disabled, because the DCLookupDomainName object of Active Directory is not configured.

SYS263.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because the operation is taking longer time than the set time limit.
SYS263.Resolution: Check the file transfer parameters, health of the remote host, and then retry the operation.
SYS263.Description: The file cannot be transferred because the operation is taking longer time than the set time limit. The other probable reasons are: 1) issue in the network 2) remote host server is not turned on 3) remote host server is turned on but not functioning 4) issue in protocol negotiation.

USR0015.Description: The specified user does not exist.
USR0015.Resolution: Verify the existing users and enter a valid username.
USR0015.Message: The specified user does not exist.

FSD002.Message: Debug authorization failed; for debugCaps: %1, authorized by iDRAC user: %2, and Dell employee: %3, at %4 for the period: %5 to %6.
FSD002.Resolution: Verify all of the following 1) ensure that the unblock, grant, and invoke/start/stop/resume commands are all executed against the same iDRAC. 2) ensure dat.ini file has not been changed in any way. 3) ensure that current date falls between the start and end times. Note that Dell can further restrict both the set of debugCaps that is authorized and the start and stop times. If an authorized person did not enter a RACADM debug command then an attacker may have entered the command.
FSD002.Description: A RACADM Debug command failed. If the RACADM Debug command was executed under the direction of Dell tech support then further assistance from tech support should be requested. Otherwise this command is not intended for customer use.

UEFI0184.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.
UEFI0184.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0184.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot identified in the message. The error occurred during Load Reduced DIMM (LR-DIMM) buffer initialization.

BOOT009.Description: No Boot Sources could be found for the desired Boot Configuration.
BOOT009.Resolution: Verify that Boot Sources for the indicated Boot Configuration are displaying when enumerating DCIM_BootSourceSetting. Power cycle system and reapply firmware packages for Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC.
BOOT009.Message: Boot Sources cannot be found for this Boot Configuration

LIC003.Description: System resources may be unavailable at the time command is issued.
LIC003.Resolution: Re-issue the command. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
LIC003.Message: License Manager was unable to create and/or allocate the required resources.

PDR23.Resolution: Replace the disk that has received the SMART alert. If the physical disk is a member of a non-redundant virtual disk, then back up the data before replacing the disk. Removing a physical disk that is included in a non-redundant virtual disk will cause the virtual disk to fail and may cause data loss.
PDR23.Description: A disk is degraded and has received a SMART alert (predictive failure). The disk is likely to fail in the near future.

SWC8557.Message: Unable to delete the profile %1 because the profile is in use.
SWC8557.Description: The profile identified in the message cannot be deleted because it is currently in use.

LOG008.Description: The complete Lifecycle Log was successfully created for a requested export operation.
LOG008.Message: The complete Lifecycle Log was successfully created for an export operation.

PWR2208.Message: The system is in a sleep state.

VDR95.Message: Unable to log block %1.Bad block table on %2 is full.
VDR95.Resolution: Replace the disk in the Virtual disk, generating this alert and restore from backup. You may have lost data.
VDR95.Description: This alert message occurs if the virtual disk has bad blocks.

CPUA0023.Resolution: Verify processor installation. If present, reseat the processor.

LC036.Description: The Lifecycle Controller has been disabled through the iDRAC configuration utility accessed by pressing CTRL+E or F2 on boot up or through a remote command.
LC036.Resolution: For 11G systems: Use the iDRAC configuration utility to enable the System Services by pressing on the CTRL+E option on boot up at the targeted system. For 12G and above generations : Use F2 Setup, select iDRAC Configuration, and select Lifecycle Controller Settings, to enable the Lifecycle Controller on boot up of the targeted system.

PDR101.Message: Global Hot Spare %1 does not cover all arrays.
PDR101.Description: This alert message occurs if there are arrays not protected with a global hot spare.

OSD3.Description: Lifecycle Controller is currently locked by another process. Make sure that the process completes before attempting to run another command.
OSD3.Resolution: 1) After two minutes, rerun the command. 2) Make sure that USC or DUP is not currently running on the server. 3) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD3.Message: Lifecycle Controller is being used by another process.

RED095.Description: An item named rSPI that is dependent on the Diagnostics package was not updated successfully when the Diagnostics package was updated.
RED095.Message: Update of rSPI was not successful after the Diagnostics package was updated.

BAR088.Description: The maximum number of partitions are already in use.
BAR088.Resolution: Delete partitions and free up 384MB of space on the current vFlash media or obtain new vFlash media.
BAR088.Message: No partitions available on vFlash media.

PDR104.Message: The %1 has turned off because the critical temperature threshold is exceeded.
PDR104.Description: The PCIe solid state device identified in the message has turned off because the critical temperature threshold of the device was exceeded.

DIS108.Description: The server could not be successfully configured, because Lifecycle Controller is either not installed or not enabled.
DIS108.Resolution: Verify that the Lifecycle Controller firmware on the server being configured is installed and enabled, then restart the iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for 15 seconds. For more information about Lifecycle Controller, see the Lifecycle Controller Users Guide available at dell.com/support/manuals.
DIS108.Message: Unable to start the AutoConfig import operation, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

SYS008.Message: Invalid boolean in value for attribute: %1.
SYS008.Resolution: Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation and provide a valid boolean value for the specified attribute.
SYS008.Description: The input value for the specified attribute is not a valid boolean value for the attribute.

UEFI0091.Message: A Quad-Rank (QR) DIMM is installed on memory slot: %1. QR DIMMs should be installed on the first DIMM slot in a channel if there is only one QR DIMM in the channel. QR DIMMs cannot be installed on the third slot of the channel.
UEFI0091.Resolution: Install the QR DIMM in the correct channel. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0091.Description: A Quad-Rank (QR) DIMM is installed on the memory slot identified in the message. QR DIMMs should be installed on the first DIMM slot in a channel if there is only one QR DIMM in the channel. QR DIMMs cannot be installed on the third slot of the channel.

RAC0505.Description: Devices are not displayed. This error may occur because these components are removed or disconnected.
RAC0505.Resolution: 1. Check if the host system is ON. 2. Check if the Storage Enclosure is ON. 3. Verify that the adapter cables are properly connected and there are no bent pins.
RAC0505.Message: There are no devices to be displayed.

RED047.Message: A recurring operation %1 was not created because the operation is already configured.
RED047.Resolution: Clear the existing configuration settings for the operation identified in the message and retry the operation.
RED047.Description: An Automatic Server Profile Backup or Automatic Update operation is already configured.

PWR8535.Description: Unable to set Server Based Power Management Mode to disable.
PWR8535.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR8535.Message: Unable to set Server Based Power Management Mode to disable.

RAC951.Description: Up to 256 characters are allowed for a work note.
RAC951.Resolution: Do not exceed 256 characters in the work note, and retry the operation.
RAC951.Message: The number of characters entered for the work note exceeds the supported limit.

SWC1924.Description: The server configuration cannot be modified by using Quick Sync because issues were found with the configuration information.
SWC1924.Resolution: Review the server configuration operation results and correct any issues detected, then retry the operation.
SWC1924.Message: Unable to modify the server configuration by using Quick Sync.

PWR2261.Message: Current Monitor initialization issue observed, IMON Revision %1, CPLD IMON MFR Revision %2.
PWR2261.Description: The iDRAC experienced an issue initializing the Current Monitor. The system motherboard may need replacement.

VF017.Description: The SD card is not initialized.
VF017.Resolution: In order to perform this operation, first initialize the SD Card.

PDR12.Resolution: Replace the failed or corrupt disk. Identify a disk that has failed by locating the disk that has a red "X" for its status. Restart the initialization.
PDR12.Description: The physical disk has failed or is corrupt.

IOV118.Resolution: Power cycle the chassis. Using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) RACADM command line interface, run the command "racadm chassisaction powercycle".
IOV118.Description: The Fabric identified in the message is not up and a chassis power cycle is required.

BIOS002.Description: Unable to allocate required memory to perform the requested operation; see the inserted comment.
BIOS002.Resolution: Power cycle system and reapply firmware packages for Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC.

CMC401.Message: Changing the Reserved QuickDeploy IP Addresses setting to %1 may create an issue in the future if higher density server nodes are inserted in to the Chassis (for example, quarter-height servers). Press OK to continue.
CMC401.Resolution: Select a higher number to accommodate future higher density server node additions, otherwise no response action is required.
CMC401.Description: Changing the Reserved QuickDeploy IP Addresses setting to <number of IP address> may create an issue in the future if higher density server nodes are inserted in to the Chassis (for example, quarter-height servers).

SWC8503.Description: The Profile identified in the message has been renamed.

UEFI0086.Message: Unsupported Small Outline Dual In-line Memory Module (SODIMM) memory is installed on RDIMM memory slot: %1.
UEFI0086.Resolution: Remove the unsupported SODIMM module from the identified memory slot and replace it with a supported module. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0086.Description: Unsupported Small Outline Dual In-line Memory Module (SODIMM) memory is installed on the RDIMM memory slot identified in the message.

VF040.Description: The downloaded image did not successfully complete the hash verification.
VF040.Resolution: Try the download again. If this issue persists, check the network connectivity.
VF040.Message: Image hash verification was not successful.

SWC0048.Description: The backup server profile operation did not complete because:1) The backup server configuration profile image file present on the vFlash SD card is invalid for this system.2) The passphrase entered does not match the passphrase used to secure the backup server configuration profile image file.
SWC0048.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation:1) Reinsert the vFlash SD card with correct backup image file.2) Enter the passphrase that was used to secure the backup server configuration profile image file.
SWC0048.Message: Unable to validate the backup server configuration Profile image file for this system.

PWR8673.Description: Displays voltage change with power configuration change.

LOG508.Description: The network share may be read-only or it may not have sufficient space for the export operation.
LOG508.Resolution: Verify the network share is not read-only and has sufficient space for exporting, then retry the operation.
LOG508.Message: Unable to write to the network share.

ASR0106.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate within the timeout period. No action was taken. (IPMI sensor type code 23h - offset 00h event 3:0 - 4h).
ASR0106.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.

SWC0033.Description: Exporting the Server Configuration Profile image file to the network share was successful.
SWC0033.Message: Successfully exported the Server Configuration Profile image file to network share.

USR0190.Message: Peak value is reset for %1 sensor.
USR0190.Description: The peak value of the sensor identified in the message is reset.

RAC971.Description: The import or export operation cannot continue if the value specified for the file type is incorrect. The correct value for the file type is "xml" or "ini".
RAC971.Resolution: Make sure to specify either "xml" or "ini" for the file type (-t) option. If no file type is specified, "ini" is used as default.

CTL5.Resolution: See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.
CTL5.Description: A portion of a physical disk is damaged. See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.

SYS250.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an internal error.
SYS250.Resolution: Check the system health and retry the operation.
SYS250.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an internal issue. This is not related to any issue in network, proxy status, or remote host status.

UEFI0257.Description: Cannot boot to Service Partition because the target Service Partition was not found in the boot list.
UEFI0257.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Update the system BIOS. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware.
UEFI0257.Message: Unable to boot to Service Partition because the target Service Partition was not found in the boot list.

SYS186.Description: Unable to start the collection of TTY log data because the server OS is turned off.
SYS186.Resolution: Turn on the server and wait until the OS finishes booting, and then retry the operation.
SYS186.Message: Unable to start the collection of TTY log data because the server is turned off.

PST0256.Description: System BIOS detected a functional or configuration issue during system POST. Check the system video screen for more information. The system event log may contain additional details.
PST0256.Resolution: Check system video and review event log for additional information.

RED000.Resolution: Check the uniform resource identifier (URI) target path and make sure the repository server is available.

JCP009.Description: Scheduled jobs were deleted as a result of a cancel job request. The job cancellation request is manually or programmatically initiated. Lifecycle Controller enters Recovery mode when unrecoverable and persistent errors occur.
JCP009.Resolution: If the job was not cancelled manually, then Lifecycle Controller may be in Recovery mode. To verify or change Recovery mode, use F2 Setup to select iDRAC Configuration then Lifecycle Controller Settings.

CTL9.Message: Bad block extended medium error on %1.
CTL9.Resolution: See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.
CTL9.Description: A portion of a physical disk is damaged. See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.

CMC8545.Message: Detected a missing process failover condition detected. Process = %1.
CMC8545.Resolution: No response action is required. If multiple failovers occur, contact your service provider.
CMC8545.Description: A firmware error has occurred causing a CMC failover. The process identified in the message was not detected. The CMC will restart automatically.

CTL24.Message: Abort CC on Error and Auto Copyback on Predictive Failure has changed for %1.
CTL24.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

STOR11.Description: The current hardware configuration is setup correctly for High Availability. However, the current firmware does not provide this functionality and one of the cards will be kept in a powered down state until High Availability capable firmware is installed.
STOR11.Message: The currently detected hardware configuration is High Availability Ready. However, the current software solution does not yet support high availability.

SWC0075.Description: Unable to perform RAID operations because the selected controller is in HBA mode.
SWC0075.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Retry the operation using other controllers that support RAID operations and are not in HBA mode. 2) Change the mode of the controller from HBA mode to RAID mode and retry the operation.
SWC0075.Message: Unable to perform RAID operations because the selected controller is in HBA mode.

RAC0209.Description: Certificate upload failed because iDRAC unable to upload at this time.
RAC0209.Resolution: Try the operation again in a few minutes.
RAC0209.Message: Certificate upload failed: iDRAC unable to upload at this time.

SWU8502.Message: A %1 request was submitted to the Lifecycle Controller on server %2.
SWU8502.Description: The specified Lifecycle Controller operation is successfully submitted and the operation will be executed on the basis of scheduling criteria.

RED070.Description: Unable to configure the Automatic Backup schedule due to invalid input parameters.
RED070.Resolution: Verify the input parameters to the set Automatic Backup schedule method are correct and retry the operation.
RED070.Message: Unable to configure the Automatic Backup schedule.

CBL0002.Resolution: Reconnect or replace the signal cable for the backplane identified in the message. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CBL0002.Description: A backplane power cable was detected, but the accompanying signal cable was not present.

SYS143.Description: ePSA Diagnostics are deleted because of a System Erase operation.

RAC0625.Description: The requested job cannot be scheduled, because job schedule types such as Automatic Backup or Automatic Update is not enabled.
RAC0625.Resolution: Enable the correct job schedule type, and then retry the operation. For example, to enable the Automatic Backup feature, select the Enable Automatic Backup option.
RAC0625.Message: Unable to schedule, because the requested job schedule type is not enabled.

PSU0042.Message: An output over current fault detected on power supply %1.
PSU0042.Resolution: 1) Remove the power supply input cord and then remove power supply. 2) Re-install the power supply and then re-install the power supply cord. 3) If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

PWR8567.Message: Unable to turn off Server %1 on a power cycle action.
PWR8567.Resolution: The Server could have taken more time to turn off than expected. If the Server is turned off, turn on to complete the power cycle. If the Server has not completed a power cycle, retry the operation.
PWR8567.Description: Unable to turn off the Server on a power cycle operation. This happens if the Server did not show a "power off" status change within the expected time.

PSU0041.Message: An output over voltage fault detected on power supply %1.
PSU0041.Resolution: 1) Remove the power supply input cord and then remove power supply. 2) Re-install the power supply and then re-install the power supply cord. 3) If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

PDR58.Resolution: Refer to the hardware documentation for information on replacing disks.
PDR58.Description: A user attempted to replace a disk with another disk that is using an incompatible technology. For example, replaced one side of a mirror with a SAS disk when the other side of the mirror is using SATA technology.

RAC029.Description: The operation cannot be completed because necessary dependency values are not found in the input.
RAC029.Resolution: Refer to the Dell Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Quick Start Guide and Profile Documents available at the support site, and then retry the operation.
RAC029.Message: Unable to complete the operation because necessary dependency values are not found in the input.

SWC0223.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0223.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0223.Message: Invalid syntax. The -d option is not valid with -p.

PWR8519.Description: Unable to perform the chassis power action because the chassis is already turned off.
PWR8519.Message: Unable to perform the chassis power action because the chassis is already turned off.

SYS184.Description: The checksum cannot be computed because OS Collector files are not readable.
SYS184.Resolution: Reinstall the OS Collector in the iDRAC and retry the operation. To install the OS Collector using the iDRAC Web UI, get the latest OC Collector update package and then select the Update and Rollback link from the iDRAC Web UI home page and upload the install package. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SYS184.Message: Unable to compute the checksum because OS Collector files are not readable.

CMC8502.Description: CMC is unable to access the specified server's IPv6 information. Unable to display the specified server's Launch iDRAC link on the CMC Web interface.
CMC8502.Resolution: Enable IPv6 for the specified server using the CMC command line or CMC Web GUI interface, so that the link to launch iDRAC is displayed on the CMC Web interface. For the command line options or navigation for Web interface, see the Troubleshooting section in the CMC User's Guide.
CMC8502.Message: Unable to access the IPv6 information of the server.

OSD67.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'IPAddress' is missing.
OSD67.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "IPAddress" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD67.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'IPAddress' is missing.

SWC8548.Description: The Media Access Control (MAC) addresses cannot be deleted from the pool because they are not present in the MAC address pool.
SWC8548.Message: Unable to delete some of the Media Access Control (MAC) addresses because the MAC addresses are not present in the MAC address pool or used by Boot Identity profile.

LC005.Description: The value provided for the update mode parameter is invalid.
LC005.Resolution: Verify that the correct firmware update mode was entered. The choices are: 1) Disable (default) 2)Allow version upgrade only 3) Match firmware of replaced part.

CTL39.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SEC0034.Message: The chassis is closed while the power is off.

RAC017.Description: The requested job has been created.
RAC017.Message: Job created to apply the attribute value.

RAC0671.Description: Going out of this page will not save the operations or configuration settings that were selected.
RAC0671.Resolution: Press OK to continue. Press Cancel to continue working on the page.
RAC0671.Message: Going out of this page will not save the operations or configuration settings that were selected.

PWR8503.Message: The current value of System Input Power Cap (%1W AC) is less than the upper limit (%1W AC).
PWR8503.Description: This Information is provided to enable checking whether the powercap is lower than the maximum supported powercap limit.

BAR078.Description: The collection and export of Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC)firmware was not successful.
BAR078.Resolution: Apply the integrated remote access controller firmware, manually set the configuration attributes, and try the operation again.
BAR078.Message: Unable to collect the Integrated Remote Access Controller firmware.

SWC0307.Description: The syntax of the fwupdate command is invalid.
SWC0307.Resolution: Refer the help text for fwupdate subcommand.
SWC0307.Message: The -d option requires -p or -g to also be specified.

IOID114.Message: The target settings properties of the %1 Port %2 are successfully configured.
IOID114.Description: The target setting properties of the NIC port identified in the message are successfully configured.

SYS041.Description: The configuration update is complete, however all of the values were not correctly applied.
SYS041.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle Log for the values that were not set. Resolve the issues in the XML configuration input file and retry the operation. Alternatively, configure each of the attributes using the component service methods. For more information, see the Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.
SYS041.Message: Unable to apply some component configuration values.

BOOT008.Description: More source arguments were provided than are available for the impacted Boot Configuration.
BOOT008.Resolution: Verify that all of the Boot Source instance IDs being entered are as they appear in the DCIM_BootSourceSetting enumeration.
BOOT008.Message: Source argument contains more devices than are present on the system

RAC1028.Description: The certificate cannot be downloaded if the certificate type specified is other than "1", "2", or "3".
RAC1028.Resolution: Make sure to specify either "1", "2", or "3" for the certificate type (-t) option, and retry the operation.
RAC1028.Message: Unable to download the specified certificate type.

IOV123.Message: %1 %2 is unassigned/unmapped from extended server slot %3.
IOV123.Description: The PCIE Slot or PERC Virtual Adapter(VA) identified in the message has been unassigned/unmapped from the extension of the server slot identified in the message.

RAC0907.Description: The System ID LED was successfully set to on.

PSU0077.Message: Power supply %1 vendor type mismatch detected.
PSU0077.Resolution: Install matched power supplies and review product documentation for proper configuration.
PSU0077.Description: Power supplies should be of the same input type and power rating.

RAC1194.Description: The server firmware is up to date and matches the catalog definitions.
RAC1194.Message: Successfully compared the firmware versions on the server to the versions defined in the specified catalog. The server firmware is up to date and matches the catalog definitions.

UEFI0315.Description: An iDRAC request to configure Secure Boot keys cannot be processed because of a communication error between BIOS and iDRAC.
UEFI0315.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and then reconnect the input power. Turn on the server and retry the operation. 2) Make sure the iDRAC firmware and BIOS firmware on the system is up to date and retry the operation.
UEFI0315.Message: Unable to process an iDRAC request to configure Secure Boot keys because of a communication error between BIOS and iDRAC.

RAC1011.Description: The OS to iDRAC pass-through cannot be enabled, because the NIC is in Dedicated mode.
RAC1011.Resolution: Change the iDRAC NIC mode to shared mode using "racadm set idrac.nic.selection <value>", and retry the operation.
RAC1011.Message: The OS to iDRAC pass-through cannot be enabled.

RDU0003.Description: One of more fans have failed or have been removed or a configuration change occurred which requires additional fans.
RDU0003.Resolution: Remove and re-install failed fans or install additional fans.

PWR8587.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because the chassis enclosure is open.
PWR8587.Resolution: The chassis enclosure is open. Retry the operation after closing the enclosure.
PWR8587.Description: The server cannot be turned on if the chassis enclosure is open.

SWC0071.Description: The SupportAssist collection has been successfully exported to the network share folder.
SWC0071.Message: The SupportAssist collection has been successfully exported to the network share folder.

TMP1001.Message: %1 has crossed the minimum warning threshold.
TMP1001.Resolution: Check whether the thermostat setting is too low and whether the room temperature is too cool.

RAC997.Description: The DHCP for Domain Name cannot be enabled if IPv4 and IPv4 DHCP or IPv6 and IPv6 AutoConfig is disabled.
RAC997.Resolution: Make sure that IPv4 and IPv4 DHCP are enabled, or IPv6 and IPv6 AutoConfig are enabled.
RAC997.Message: The object DNSDomainFromDHCP cannot be enabled.

RFM1022.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media.

SYS434.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the uploaded firmware image file extension is not supported.
SYS434.Resolution: Make sure to use a valid firmware image and retry the operation. For information about the supported file extension types, see the Redfish Users Guide available on the support site.
SYS434.Message: Unable to upload the firmware image because the file extension is not supported.

RRDU0008.Description: Internal Dual SD Module rebuild failed because read/write to one of the SD cards failed.
RRDU0008.Resolution: Replace the failed SD card and retry rebuild.
RRDU0008.Message: Internal Dual SD Module rebuild did not complete successfully.

RAC1068.Message: Unable to set minimum non critical threshold value of %1, because the value entered is greater than, or equal to the maximum non critical threshold value.
RAC1068.Resolution: Check the maximum non critical threshold level using an appropriate RACADM command. For example, to view the maximum non critical threshold value of a sensor, run the 'racadm getsensorinfo' command at the command line interface, and then retry the operation. For more information about other RACADM commands, run the racadm help command.
RAC1068.Description: The minimum non critical threshold value identified in the message cannot be set, because the value entered is greater than, or equal to the maximum non critical threshold value.

UEFI0119.Description: Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) RAID redundancy was lost. The system BIOS should have prompted the user for the rebuild process.
UEFI0119.Resolution: No additional response action is required if you have followed the instructions on the screen to start the rebuild process.
UEFI0119.Message: The Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) RAID redundancy was lost.

SYS064.Message: Input file for import configuration operation is invalid at line %1.
SYS064.Resolution: Open the input file in any Web browser to check for invalid content before the expected root element. Correct the invalid content and make sure that the XML file is compliant to the system configuration schema before retrying the operation.
SYS064.Description: The input file for the import configuration operation contains invalid XML data at the line specified.

LNK0002.Description: The DNS query did not complete successfully. This may be because the connection timed out due to an incorrect host name or a DNS server configuration issue.
LNK0002.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Verify host name entered is valid and retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, verify the DNS server settings are configured properly to resolve the host name.

PWR200.Description: Enabling the Max Power Conservation Mode (MPCM) feature will disable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature. MPCM forces servers in to a low-power and limited-performance mode, and then disables the ability to turn on additional servers.
PWR200.Message: Enabling the Max Power Conservation Mode (MPCM) feature will disable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature.

FC102.Message: The %1 port %2 link is not functioning either because the FC cable is not connected or the FC device is not functioning.
FC102.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Make sure that the FC port is enabled. 2) Make sure the Activity/Speed LEDs are lit if the physical port has LEDs. 3) Check the FC cable and FC cable connections for proper installation. 4) Check that the attached FC switch is functioning.
FC102.Description: The FC controller port link identified in the message is not functioning either because the FC cable is not connected or the FC device is not functioning.

FAN0014.Message: %1 RPM is greater than the upper warning threshold.
FAN0014.Resolution: Remove and re-install the cooling device. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0014.Description: The cooling device is not performing optimally. The cooling device may be installed improperly.

VFL1009.Message: Removable Flash Media %1 is operating normally.

NIC015.Message: AttributeValue cannot be changed to read only AttributeName %1.
NIC015.Description: A set attribute operation was attempted on a read only attribute.

TMP0113.Message: The %1 temperature is less than the lower critical threshold.
TMP0113.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.

MEM9006.Message: Intel QPI interconnect %1 has a non-recoverable issue.
MEM9006.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the server and check whether the issue persists. 2) If the issue is not resolved by the preceding action, reseat the processors and restart the server. 3) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
MEM9006.Description: A non-recoverable link issue was detected in propagation of signals between processors through the Intel QPI interconnect interconnect identified in the message.

RAC995.Description: The hardware inventory cannot be retrieved because another hardware inventory operation may already be in progress or due to an internal error whether or not Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) is enabled or disabled.
RAC995.Resolution: Another hardware inventory operation may already be in progress and must complete before retrying the operation. If no other hardware inventory operation was in progress, make sure to enable Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature, reboot the system, and retry the operation. If CSIOR is already enabled and no other hardware inventory operation was in progress, reboot the iDRAC using "racadm racreset" command and then retry the operation.
RAC995.Message: Unable to retrieve the hardware inventory.

RAC915.Description: The auto-negotiation property for the iDRAC NIC can be changed only if the NIC is in dedicated mode. To change the NIC mode to dedicated, an iDRAC Enterprise license is required.
RAC915.Resolution: Change the NIC mode to dedicated mode by using "racadm set idrac.nic.selection <1 | Dedicated>", and retry the operation.
RAC915.Message: Unable to change auto-negotiation property for the NIC.

VF042.Description: The remote file could not be found.

SYS235.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported workgroup value.
SYS235.Resolution: Make sure that the correct workgroup value is used, and then retry the operation.
SYS235.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an unsupported port number value.

VLT0214.Message: The disk drive bay %1 voltage is greater than the upper warning threshold.
VLT0214.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat hard disks in the bay. Reconnect all cables attached to the bay.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0214.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

ENC3.Resolution: Check for factors that may cause overheating or excessive cooling. For example, verify that the enclosure fan is working. You should also check the thermostat settings and examine whether the enclosure is located near a heat source. Make sure the enclosure has enough ventilation and that the room temperature is not too hot or too cold. Refer to the enclosure documentation for more diagnostic information.
ENC3.Description: The physical disk enclosure is either hotter or cooler than the maximum or minimum allowable temperature range.

PWR8579.Message: Request to reset the CMC %1 is initiated.
PWR8579.Description: A request to reset the CMC identified in the message is initiated. If a second CMC is present, a failover to the other CMC will occur as a result.

SWC0121.Description: The syntax of the sslcertview command is invalid.
SWC0121.Resolution: Refer the help text for sslcertview subcommand.
SWC0121.Message: Invalid syntax. User index (-i) must be specified.

BAR044.Description: Waiting for the host system to successfully get turned off.
BAR044.Message: Waiting for the host system to successfully get turned off.

FC005.Description: The number of AttributeName and AttributeValue array elements are not equal.
FC005.Resolution: Provide equal number of array elements for AttributeName and AttributeValue parameters. For more information about input parameters, see FC HBA Profile specification.
FC005.Message: The number of AttributeName array elements does not match the AttributeValue array element count.

FC007.Description: Configuration job already created on the specified target. No further command is allowed until the existing job succeeded or the job is cancelled.
FC007.Resolution: Wait for the existing job to complete or cancel the existing job and retry the operation.
FC007.Message: A configuration job already exists. Unable to create another configuration job on specified target until existing job is completed or is cancelled.

SYS127.Description: OS log data was not collected. An issue occurred while collecting OS log data because of an unknown exception.
SYS127.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SYS127.Message: OS Collector: Unable to collect OS log data

RAC008.Description: The attribute boolean value is not valid for the specified attribute.
RAC008.Resolution: Provide valid boolean value for the specified attribute.

BAR010.Description: The Backup partition creation operation did no complete successfully.
BAR010.Resolution: Make sure that the vFlash media is not write-protected. Enable and initialize the vFlash media, retry backup. If that fails Try new vFlash media or use the Network Share option(s).
BAR010.Message: Unable to create Backup partition on vFlash media.

LNK2700.Resolution: Check network cable and network connections.

STOR0513.Description: Unable to encrypt unsecure virtual disks due to an internal error.
STOR0513.Resolution: Exit Lifecycle Controller, press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation. If the problem persists, update the RAID controller firmware to the latest version and retry the operation.

PWR8533.Message: Power cap changed from %1 W AC to %1 W AC.

VF028.Description: This partition is detached and attempts to detach it will fail.

SWC0055.Description: Unable to load the View Current Version page due to an internal error.
SWC0055.Resolution: Retry the operation. If problem persists, update the iDRAC firmware to the latest version and retry the operation.
SWC0055.Message: Unable to load the View Current Version page.

SYS415.Description: The operation cannot be completed because an invalid username and/or password is entered, and therefore authentication failed.
SYS415.Resolution: Enter valid user name and password and retry the operation.
SYS415.Message: Unable to complete the operation because an invalid username and/or password is entered, and therefore authentication failed.

OSD45.Description: The ISO Image present in vFlash is attached to the host system. The ISO Image cannot be deleted from vFlash.
OSD45.Message: Cannot delete ISO image from VFlash.

SYS239.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported share name value, %2.
SYS239.Resolution: Make sure that the correct share name value is used, and then retry the operation.
SYS239.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an unsupported share name value.

RED083.Description: The Chassis firmware is not updated because the firmware version currently on the Chassis is same as the requested version.
RED083.Message: The Chassis firmware is not updated because the version currently on the Chassis is same as the requested version.

FC014.Message: Invalid AttributeValue parameter content for corresponding AttributeName %1.
FC014.Resolution: For valid attribute values, see the FC HBA Profile specification.
FC014.Description: The AttributeValue parameter is invalid due to one of the following: 1) The length of new AttributeValue is not within the minimum length and maximum length range or does not comply with the governing regular expression 2) Value of new AttributeValue is not within the lower bound and upper bound range limits 3) The value is not one of the possible values.

RAC0211.Description: Firmware update has failed. This may be due to a corrupt firmware image, poor network connection, or another issue.
RAC0211.Resolution: Download a new firmware image and try loading the firmware again.

PST0142.Description: BIOS Memory testing failed. Compare system memory installation to supported system memory configurations. Reduce system configuration to minimum memory configuration. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video.
PST0142.Resolution: Compare system memory installation to supported system memory configurations. Reduce system configuration to minimum memory configuration.

USR0171.Message: The Front Panel USB port is detached from the iDRAC Disk.USBFront.%1. Device Details: Device Class %2, Vendor ID %3, Product ID %4.
USR0171.Description: The device identified in the message is connected to the Front Panel USB port and detached from the iDRAC.

UEFI0060.Description: Power required by the system exceeds the power supplied by the PSUs. Continuing to restart the system may automatically turn off the system without any notification.
UEFI0060.Resolution: Check the PSU and system configuration, and then upgrade the PSU, if necessary.
UEFI0060.Message: Power required by the system exceeds the power supplied by the Power Supply Units (PSUs).

BAR006.Description: The system profile backup file is being finalized and closed.

RAC1062.Description: Unable to initiate the requested SystemErase operation. The component identifier specified is not valid.
RAC1062.Resolution: Run the RACADM command "racadm help systemerase" to see the list of supported components.
RAC1062.Message: Unable to initiate the SystemErase operation. The component identifier specified is not valid.

LC039.Description: Lifecycle Controller is locked by another instance of the As-Shipped Inventory export process. Allow the process to complete before attempting another export operation.
LC039.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Rerun the command after about 2 minutes 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
LC039.Message: An instance of As-Shipped Inventory export is already in progress.

SWC0053.Description: The file extension of the Update Package is not supported or the Update Package is invalid.
SWC0053.Resolution: Use a valid Windows-based Update Package with an .exe extension.
SWC0053.Message: File extension is not supported or the Update Package is invalid.

RAC0723.Message: The firmware version %1 of the Chassis Management Controller is earlier than the required version %1.
RAC0723.Resolution: Update the Chassis Management Controller firmware to the required version identified in the message.
RAC0723.Description: The Chassis Management Controller firmware version identified in the message is earlier than the version required to support the server.

RAC946.Description: The "Auto Dedicated NIC" mode cannot be set for a NIC if the NIC selection mode is set to "Dedicated NIC".
RAC946.Resolution: To set the NIC to Auto Dedicated NIC mode, set NIC selection mode to "Shared NIC", and retry the operation.
RAC946.Message: Unable to set the NIC to Auto Dedicated NIC mode.

STOR007.Description: The operation could not be completed because of insufficient memory space on the management controller (either the iDRAC or the Chassis Management Controller (CMC)) managing the storage.
STOR007.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

SYS264.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because the proxy server was incapable of performing the file transfer operations.
SYS264.Resolution: Make sure that correct proxy settings and file transfer parameters are set, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, try connecting to a different proxy.
SYS264.Description: Unable to transfer a file because the proxy server was incapable of performing the file transfer operations even when the network connection is available to the proxy server.

SEL1302.Description: The disk in the drive is not formatted correctly or does not contain the necessary operating system files(IPMI sensor type code 1eh - offset 01h).

OSD59.Description: Disconnecting ISO using Remote File Share (RFS) operation did not complete successfully.
OSD59.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation.
OSD59.Message: Unable to disconnect from ISO using Remote File Share (RFS).

USR0152.Message: Unable to connect the remote VNC session, because an incorrect VNC password was entered from the IP %1.
USR0152.Resolution: Enter the correct VNC password and retry the operation.
USR0152.Description: Could not successfully connect to the remote VNC session, because an incorrect VNC password was entered from the IP address identified in the message.

SWC8530.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to set the server administrator access to the iDRAC root user. This can happen if the communication to the iDRAC from CMC is non-functional or the iDRAC is rebooting.
SWC8530.Resolution: If communications with the iDRAC is not functioning, reset the iDRAC and retry the operation after a few minutes. Run the RACADM command "racadm ping server-<slot number> " to check the communications. If the communications are not functional, restart the iDRAC by performing a Virtual Reseat of the server using the RACADM command "racadm racreset -m server-<slot id>".
SWC8530.Message: Chassis Management Controller unable to set administrator access to the iDRAC root user.

SEC0101.Message: The %1 in slot %2 is opened for more than 3 minutes.
SEC0101.Resolution: Close the Storage disk tray as it may affect the system performance or may cause hard drives to overheat. Check system logs .
SEC0101.Description: The Storage disk tray in the slot identified in the message has been open for an extended period of time. The tray should be closed as soon as any service action is completed. Leaving it open for extended period may result in drives overheating.

RAC0212.Description: This is a generic error message used on all the login pages.
RAC0212.Message: Login failed. Verify that username and password is correct.

PCI3005.Message: Device option ROM on mezzanine card %1 was successfully updated.

BAR005.Description: The Lifecycle Controller data is being collected and copied into the backup file.

USR0020.Description: The specified session id does not exist and is invalid.

RAC0506.Description: This error occurs when the user tries to access a program or function that is beyond user granted privileges.
RAC0506.Resolution: Contact the system administrator to perform the operation or grant the required privileges.
RAC0506.Message: You do not have privileges to perform this operation.

BAT1023.Message: The charge level for the battery on %1 is within normal limits.
BAT1023.Description: The battery health has returned to normal.

RAC942.Description: The system configuration profile import operation is initiated. No other operations can be performed on the system while the system configuration server profile is being imported from the system configuration profile.
RAC942.Resolution: Monitor the job status using "racadm jobqueue view -i <Job ID>".
RAC942.Message: Successfully initiated the import operation. This operation may take several minutes to complete and may cause multiple system restarts while device firmware and configuration are applied.

DIS015.Description: Auto Discovery client is using the default Certificate Authority certificate to authenticate the Provisioning Server for the SSL connection.
DIS015.Message: Auto Discovery client using default CA certificate to authenticate Provisioning Server.

RAC0759.Description: A running Tech Support Report job has been cancelled.
RAC0759.Resolution: Click Job Queue button to view the status of the cancelled job.
RAC0759.Message: A running Tech Support Report job has been cancelled.

BAR064.Description: Collecting the Integrated Remote Access Controller firmware and copying it in the server profile backup file.
BAR064.Message: Collecting Integrated Remote Access Controller firmware.

CPU0004.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is inserted correctly, if the processor is removable.3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

VLT0231.Message: The mezzanine card %1 %2 voltage is less than the lower critical threshold.
VLT0231.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the mezzanine card.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0231.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

BAR013.Description: The request to shut the Host system down did not complete successfully.
BAR013.Resolution: Restart the Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC) and retry the operation.

LC060.Description: Lifecycle controller is currently performing tasks and another task cannot be scheduled until the previous task finishes.
LC060.Resolution: Wait until Lifecycle controller finishes performing current tasks and host system to finish POST.
LC060.Message: Lifecycle controller is currently not ready to take provisioning requests

CMC8573.Resolution: Review the Chassis log or the Chassis Management Controller(CMC) SEL log for the failure or Export chassis log and SEL log and contact technical support .
CMC8573.Description: The chassis health is critical or non-recoverable.

RED046.Message: A recurring operation of type %1 was unable to create a job because the task type is now disabled.
RED046.Resolution: Enable the operation identified in the message and retry the operation. To enable the Automatic Server Profile Backup operation, run the following racadm command: "racadm set lifecycleController.lcattributes.AutoBackup 1". To enable the Automatic Update operation, run the following racadm command: "racadm set lifecycleController.lcattributes.AutoUpdate 1".
RED046.Description: The operation identified in the message was disabled and the iDRAC was unable to create the next job in the sequence.

RAC1010.Description: The power cap cannot be set if the object Power.Cap is disabled.
RAC1010.Resolution: Enable Power Cap setting using "racadm set System.Power.Cap.Enable < 1 | Enabled >", and retry the operation.
RAC1010.Message: Unable to set the power cap value.

VDR2.Description: The virtual disk has returned to a healthy state and is working properly.

JCP038.Message: Unable to run the (installation or configuration) job %1 because %2.
JCP038.Resolution: Navigate to the Maintenance->overview->Lifecycle Log page in the iDRAC GUI. Look for logs with the prefix "RED" within the timeframe. Perform the recommended response action for these messages by referring to the error message guide.
JCP038.Description: The (installation or configuration) job identified in the message cannot be run. For more information, see the Job Queue.

PDR37.Resolution: If the physical device is supported, then update the firmware to a supported version. If the physical device is not supported, then replace the physical device with one that is supported.
PDR37.Description: The physical device may not have a supported version of the firmware or the physical device may not be supported.

PWR8537.Description: Server Performance Over Power Redundancy is disabled.
PWR8537.Message: Server Performance Over Power Redundancy is disabled.

PWR2203.Message: The system is sleeping with system hardware and processor context lost.

HWC5037.Resolution: Reseat I/O module. If problem persists, contact the service provider.
HWC5037.Description: The firmware on the I/O module did not boot. The problem may be because the I/O module is not inserted correctly.

RED086.Description: The Chassis firmware cannot be updated because the Chassis Management at Server (CMAS) attribute is incorrectly set. The CMAS attribute must be set to Monitor and Configure on the CMC in order to update CMC firmware from and iDRAC.
RED086.Resolution: Make sure that the Chassis Management at Server attribute is set to Monitor and Configure, and then retry the operation. To set the correct attribute using Chassis Management Controller (CMC) GUI, navigate to Chassis Overview, then Setup, then General, and then click on the Chassis management at Server attribute to select the correct value.
RED086.Message: Unable to update the Chassis firmware, Chassis Management at Server is not set to Monitor and Configure.

TMP0115.Message: The %1 temperature is greater than the upper critical threshold.
TMP0115.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0115.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.

VDR57.Message: Background Initialization in %1 corrected medium error.
VDR57.Resolution: Consider replacing the disk. If you receive this alert frequently, ensure to replace the disk. It is recommended to routinely back up your data.
VDR57.Description: A disk media error was detected while the controller was completing a background task. A bad disk block was identified. The disk block has been remapped.

PCI1314.Message: A bus correctable error was detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.
PCI1314.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable re-install the device at the next scheduled service time.

SUP0130.Message: TFTP firmware update has been initiated. This update process may take several minutes to complete.

SYS180.Message: There was an issue encountered when attempted to export TTY Log data for the storage controller %1.
SYS180.Resolution: While exporting the TTY log, make sure that the server is not in BIOS POST, and then retry the operation. Use GetRemoteServicesAPIStatus() invoke method and check for output parameter RTStatus and ensure it shows 0 (ready status) and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset iDRAC, and retry the operation.
SYS180.Description: The TTY log data of the storage controller identified in the message cannot be exported because an issue was encountered while communicating with the controller.

PWR8524.Description: The redundancy was lost because the power requirement of the chassis exceeds the current redundant policy.
PWR8524.Resolution: No response action is required. Review the power requirements and determine if more PSUs are needed to restore redundancy.
PWR8524.Message: Redundancy was lost, while Server Performance Over Power Redundancy is enabled.

SUP0126.Message: Firmware update in progress. Please wait.

MEM1007.Message: Memory device at location %1 failed to transition to online.

SYS151.Description: A System Erase job with the job ID identified in the message is completed.

VDR100.Message: %1 is unavailable because of incompatibilities with the current controller.
VDR100.Resolution: Update the controller firmware and license to match the peer controller.
VDR100.Description: The virtual disk identified in message cannot be used because of missing features on the current controller. The features may be missing because they are not available in the firmware version on the controller or the necessary licenses are not installed.

RAC0654.Description: Unable to perform operations on the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) because the iSM is not installed on the server operating system. All fields in the iDRAC GUI iSM page are disabled.
RAC0654.Resolution: Make sure that the iDRAC Service Module is installed on the server operating system, and then retry the operation.
RAC0654.Message: No operations can be performed on the iDRAC Service Module.

VF016.Description: The SD card is not writable.
VF016.Resolution: Check the write-protection tab of the SD card.

FAN906.Description: Changes are not made to the current settings.
FAN906.Resolution: Make sure that changes are made to the settings and retry the operation.
FAN906.Message: Changes are not made to the current settings.

OSD77.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'ResetType' is missing.
OSD77.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "ResetType" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD77.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'ResetType' is missing.

RAC0215.Description: Login failed because the user does not have 'Login to iDRAC' privilege.
RAC0215.Resolution: Login to iDRAC' privilege is needed.
RAC0215.Message: Login failed: User does not have 'Login to iDRAC' privilege.

UEFI0180.Message: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.
UEFI0180.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the correctable error persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0180.Description: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on the memory slot identified in the message. A corrected Write Leveling error was detected.

PSU0002.Message: A predictive failure detected on power supply %1.
PSU0002.Resolution: Remove and re-install the power supply at the next service window. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0002.Description: System performance and power redundancy may be degraded or lost.

MEM1002.Message: Memory device at location %1 is in test.

RED060.Description: The specified repository catalog is either not supported or the structure is incorrect. Only Windows Update Packages are supported by iDRAC and Lifecycle Controller for the operation. If the structure is incorrect, either the expected elements are not present, or unexpected elements are present in the catalog XML file. The catalog XML file should be generated by the Repository Manager tool.
RED060.Resolution: Check the repository catalog file name and contents. Rebuild the catalog XML file using Repository Manager by selecting Windows Update Packages only, and retry the operation.
RED060.Message: The specified repository catalog is not supported.

RAC1145.Description: The value entered for the -t option is invalid.
RAC1145.Resolution: Check help text for the list of valid log types and retry the operation by entering a valid log type.
RAC1145.Message: The entered log type is invalid.

OSD16.Description: Unable to mount the network share using the parameters specified in the command because either the IP address or share name is incorrect.
OSD16.Resolution: Rerun the command with the correct IP address and share name.
OSD16.Message: Mount network share failed - incorrect IP address or share name.

CTL99.Message: Security key assigned to %1 is deleted.
CTL99.Description: The security key assigned to the controller identified in the message is deleted.

ENC33.Resolution: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
ENC33.Description: Data redundancy has been restored to an enclosure that previously suffered a loss of redundancy.

IOV006.Description: The Chassis Infrastructure Mainboard firmware is not at the correct version.
IOV006.Resolution: Run the command "racadm fwupdate -g -u -a <TFTP server IP Address> -d mainboard.bin -m main_board" to upload the latest firmware version to the Chassis Infrastructure Mainboard.
IOV006.Message: Incorrect Chassis Infrastructure Mainboard firmware version.

SYS411.Description: The file cannot be uploaded because the file size is greater than specified limit.
SYS411.Resolution: Make sure that the file size is less than the specified limit. For information about specified limit, see the Redfish User's Guide available on the support site.
SYS411.Message: Unable to upload the file because the file size is greater than specified limit.

BAR029.Description: The Integrated Remote Access Controller firmware and configuration import is in progress.
BAR029.Message: Restoring Integrated Remote Access Controller firmware.

PDR61.Message: The rebuild of %1 failed due to errors on the source physical disk.
PDR61.Resolution: Replace the source disk and restore data from backup.
PDR61.Description: It is not possible to rebuild data that resides on a defective disk.

MEM1004.Message: Memory device at location %1 is powered off.

CMC8611.Message: Unable to read the Complex Programmable Logical Device (CPLD) version number of sled %1 because the CPLD version is very old, or the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to identify the version.
CMC8611.Resolution: Update the CPLD version of sled and retry the operation. For more information about the recommended CPLD versions, see the Chassis Management Controller User's Guide available at the support site.
CMC8611.Description: The version number of Complex Programmable Logical Device (CPLD) on the sled identified in the message cannot be read because the CPLD version is very old, or the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to identify the version.

PWR2258.Message: The Power Supply Unit (PSU) hotspare thresholds were modified. Wake Threshold: %1 %, Sleep Threshold: %2 %.
PWR2258.Description: The Power Supply Unit (PSU) hotspare thresholds were modified to the Wake Threshold and Sleep Threshold identified in the message.

UEFI0206.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0206.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0206.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Command Clock Training - Group 1 phase.

RED102.Description: The Chassis firmware cannot be downgraded because the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) does not allow the downgrade operation when the Federal Information Processing Standard (FIPS) mode is enabled.
RED102.Resolution: Disable the Federal Information Processing Standard (FIPS) mode, and then retry the operation. To downgrade by using Chassis Management Controller (CMC) graphical user interface (GUI), click Chassis Overview > Network > Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS), select "Disabled", and then click "Apply Changes". To downgrade by running RACADM command at the command line interface (CLI), enter "racadm racresetcfg".
RED102.Message: Unable to downgrade the Chassis firmware because the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) does not allow the downgrade operation when the Federal Information Processing Standard (FIPS) mode is enabled.

RDU0031.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
RDU0031.Description: The system has redundant voltage lines. One of voltage line is no longer available.

RAC013.Description: The method cannot be run because an invalid FQDD is entered.
RAC013.Resolution: Enter a valid FQDD and retry the operation.
RAC013.Message: Unable to run the method because an invalid FQDD is entered.

RAC1135.Description: The RACADM command could not be run because the internal instrumentation components are either busy or have stopped functioning.
RAC1135.Resolution: Wait for a minute for the internal instrumentation component to respond, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for 15 seconds, wait for the iDRAC to finish restarting, and then retry the operation. If the issue continues to persist, contact your service provider.
RAC1135.Message: Unable to run the RACADM command because an internal instrumentation component has stopped functioning.

CPU0025.Resolution: Check presence and reinstall the terminator.
CPU0025.Description: System is unable to boot or may run in a degraded state.

HWC4000.Description: A hardware incompatibility was detected between BMC/iDRAC firmware and Processor(s). An iDRAC or BMC firmware update is needed.
HWC4000.Resolution: Update the BMC/iDRAC firmware. If the problem persists, contact support.
HWC4000.Message: A hardware incompatibility detected between BMC/iDRAC firmware and CPU.

PWR8527.Description: Server slot power priorities were changed. Power to servers is being reallocated.
PWR8527.Message: Server slot power priorities changed - reallocating power.

RAC0129.Description: No status response was returned after completing the initialization request.
RAC0129.Resolution: Try reinitializing the card again in a few minutes.
RAC0129.Message: An error has occurred while initializing the SD card.

PDR2.Message: Insufficient space available on %1 to perform a copyback operation.
PDR2.Resolution: Replace the physical disk with a larger physical disk, and then restart the copyback operation.
PDR2.Description: This message is generated if a physical disk does not have enough space to do a copyback operation.

NIC504.Description: The value of the specified parameter cannot be changed.
NIC504.Message: The IPv6 DNS Server IP address is not allowed to be configured if IPv6 DNS Server DHCP (cfgIPv6DNSServersFromDHCP6) is enabled.

BAT1015.Description: Diagnostic event for service to determine if there is an ambient temperature problem.

VFL1005.Message: Removable Flash Media %1 is not ready.
VFL1005.Resolution: Please wait for the media to be ready.
VFL1005.Description: The media is being prepared or is under maintenance. If the problem persists, reinstall the card.

RAC0302.Description: This error message is displayed when iDRAC does not have a valid Enterprise license.
RAC0302.Resolution: Upgrade to iDRAC Enterprise for supporting this feature.
RAC0302.Message: iDRAC Express does not support this feature.

PWR8545.Message: Chassis Management Controller turned off the server %1 because of incorrect power data retrieved from iDRAC at inventory.
PWR8545.Resolution: Invalid power inventory information could be due to outdated iDRAC firmware or server BIOS firmware versions. Update the components to their latest versions.
PWR8545.Description: Incorrect power inventory information reported by the iDRAC for the server identified in the message.

NIC010.Description: For 11G systems: System Services must be enabled to perform the requested operation. System Services has been disabled through the iDRAC configuration utility accessed by pressing CTRL+E on boot up or through a remote operation. For 12G and above generations: Lifecycle Controller must be enabled to perform the requested operation. Lifecycle Controller has been disabled by pressing F2 Setup, selecting iDRAC Configuration, and selecting Lifecycle Controller Settings on boot up or through a remote operation.
NIC010.Resolution: For 11G systems: Use the iDRAC configuration utility to enable the System Services by pressing on the CTRL+E option on boot up at the targeted system. For 12G and above generations: Use F2 Setup, select iDRAC Configuration, and select Lifecycle Controller Settings, to enable the Lifecycle Controller on boot up of the targeted system.
NIC010.Message: Lifecycle Controller is not enabled, cannot create Configuration job.

NIC003.Description: An invalid number of arguments was passed to the method.
NIC003.Resolution: Enter all the required command parameters. Check documentation and try again.

UEFI0138.Description: The CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) operation cannot be executed because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware is unable to complete a requested task or function.
UEFI0138.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0138.Message: Unable to execute CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was unable to complete a requested task or function.

PSU0907.Message: An interlock power down error was corrected for power unit %1.
PSU0907.Resolution: Remove input power at the power supply.

PCI1362.Message: Bus performance degraded for a component at slot %1.
PCI1362.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, remove and re-install the device at the next scheduled service time.
PCI1362.Description: System performance may be degraded. The bus is not operating at maximum speed or width.

UEFI0083.Description: One or more PCI System errors (SERR) have occurred.
UEFI0083.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the PCI device that caused the SERR. Update the identified device firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0083.Message: One or more PCI System errors (SERR) have occurred.

SUP029.Description: The catalog in the repository specified in the operation has the same firmware versions as currently present on the server. Firmware updates in the specified repository are not applicable to the server.
SUP029.Message: Firmware versions on server match catalog, applicable updates are not present in the repository.

RED063.Message: The iDRAC firmware updated successfully. Previous version: %1, Current version: %2
RED063.Description: The iDRAC firmware updated successfully to the firmware version identified in the message.

SWC0002.Description: The Part Replacement policy configuration operation encountered an unexpected error while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0002.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0002.Message: Unable to set Part Replacement policies.

UEFI0033.Description: The NVRAM_CLR jumper is installed to clear the BIOS configuration. After clearing the BIOS configuration, remove the NVRAM_CLR jumper so that the system can function normally and any non-default BIOS system setting changes can be persistently saved.
UEFI0033.Resolution: To change the system BIOS settings and persistently save the settings, remove the NVRAM_CLR jumper and then go to the System Setup to configure system settings.
