UEFI0033.Message: Default system BIOS settings are in use because NVRAM_CLR jumper is installed on the system board.

STOR6.Description: A comparison of storage inventory collected before and after the host re-boot/re-set. reports differences. There could have been some storage components added or removed when the host was powered down.
STOR6.Message: CEM Storage Management detected inventory change(s) after host re-boot.

SWC0116.Description: The syntax of the setniccfg command is invalid.
SWC0116.Resolution: Refer the help text for setniccfg subcommand.
SWC0116.Message: The -s option requires IP address, subnet mask, and gateway.

RRDU0004.Resolution: Install additional SD card and configure for redundancy if redundancy is desired.
RRDU0004.Message: Internal Dual SD Module is not redundant.

UEFI0031.Message: PCIe downtrain is detected on %1. Expected link width: %2 Actual link width: %2.
UEFI0031.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 2) Update the firmware on the PCIe device. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0031.Description: The PCIe device identified in the message was not trained at the expected link width.

FAN8501.Description: Disabling Enhanced Cooling Mode allows for reduced power consumption by reducing the maximum speed of the blowers while still providing sufficient blade airflow.

STOR312.Message: Unable to update the firmware of the physical disk drive %1 because an incorrect firmware image file is used.
STOR312.Resolution: Acquire the correct firmware image file for the drive model identified in the message, and then retry the operation. The correct image file can be found by using the drive model information and searching the support site for related firmware.
STOR312.Description: The firmware package being used to update the physical disk drive is not valid for the drive model identified in the message. The firmware package contains the drive component id in the list of supported drives, but the firmware image is not valid for the drive model identified in the message.

RAC0503.Description: Out-of-band controllers cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the host system is powered off, or controllers are removed or disconnected.
RAC0503.Resolution: Check if the host system is powered off or shutdown.
RAC0503.Message: There are no out-of-band capable controllers to be displayed.

PST0209.Description: System BIOS has halted and is unable to continue. System BIOS has detected a Non-Maskable Interrupt (NMI) which may have been caused by a hardware change.
PST0209.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) If new hardware has been added, remove the new hardware and restart the server, 2) Turn server off and back on using the power button, or 3) Remove and reapply server input power. If the problem persists, contact your service provider. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PST0209.Message: System BIOS has halted due to Non-Maskable Interrupt (NMI).

UEFI0201.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.
UEFI0201.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0201.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Write Training phase.

LOG503.Message: Unable to run the method because the parameter %1 is not valid.
LOG503.Resolution: Enter all the parameters required in the command as per the enumeration, and then retry the operation. For more information, see the Chassis Record Log Profile.
LOG503.Description: The command cannot be run because the value of the parameter identified in the message is not valid.

SWC0230.Description: vFlash is not enabled. This may be because the user does not have enough privileges.

ENC19.Resolution: Reset the Enclosure Management Module (EMM). See the storage hardware documentation for information on replacing the EMM. Replace the EMM. Contact technical support if the issue persists.
ENC19.Description: An Enclosure Management Module (EMM) has failed. The failure may be caused by a loss of power to the EMM. The EMM self-test may also have identified a failure. There may also be a firmware problem or a multi-bit error.

BAR039.Description: The license required for operation is not present.
BAR039.Resolution: Use supported vFlash media and licensing for this feature, and try the operation again.

VLT0230.Message: The mezzanine card %1 %2 voltage is less than the lower warning threshold.
VLT0230.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the mezzanine card.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0230.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

SWU8541.Message: Unable to update the PSU firmware, because the Image file is not accessible. ErrorCode=0x%1.
SWU8541.Resolution: Make sure that the PSU firmware image file is available at the location specified in the operation, and then retry the operation.
SWU8541.Description: The PSU firmware update operation was not successful, because the firmware Image file could not be transferred.

USR0033.Message: Login for %1 from %2 using %3 was incomplete.
USR0033.Description: The IPMI over LAN login attempt was ended by the IPMI client before success or failure.

CTL44.Resolution: Refer to the storage hardware documentation for more information on the diagnostic test.
CTL44.Description: A diagnostics test failed. The text for this message is generated by the tool that ran the diagnostics and can vary depending on the situation.

RAC1156.Description: The server network interface information cannot be received because the iDRAC Service Module is not installed or not running on the server operating system (OS) or collection of the OS data is disabled.
RAC1156.Resolution: Run the command 'racadm get iDRAC.ServiceModule' to check if iDRAC Service Module is installed and running on the server operation system, and the collection of the OS data is enabled.
RAC1156.Message: Unable to display the information about the server network interfaces.

SWC1922.Message: User %1 has successfully modified the server configuration by using Quick Sync.
SWC1922.Description: The user identified in the message has successfully modified the server configuration by using Quick Sync.

RED012.Description: Unable to create a Lifecycle Controller update task. The related job status is marked Failed.
RED012.Resolution: Retry the update operation after one minute.
RED012.Message: Unable to create Lifecycle Controller update task.

RAC0237.Description: A separate message will provide more detail about this error which was detected while uploading the vFlash image.
RAC0237.Resolution: Try uploading the vFlash image again.
RAC0237.Message: An error occurred while uploading the vFlash image.

SYS040.Description: An operation to update the firmware of a component did not complete successfully.
SYS040.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle Log for more details about the unsuccessful operation. Resolve the issue and retry the operation.
SYS040.Message: The firmware update operation did not complete successfully.

SWC0717.Description: For security reasons, the local configuration is disabled. Enable local configuration from the iDRAC Web interface.
SWC0717.Resolution: Enable iDRAC local configuration from iDRAC Web interface.
SWC0717.Message: iDRAC Local Configuration is disabled. iDRAC Settings are accessed in read-only mode.

VLT0103.Message: Processor module %1 voltage is greater than the upper critical threshold.
VLT0103.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Remove the processor module. Inspect processor socket for bent pins. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0103.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

HWC1013.Description: The USB cable may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.
HWC1013.Resolution: If removal was unintended, check presence, then re-install or reconnect.

RAC038.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an unknown error in the iDRAC.
RAC038.Resolution: Retry the action. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC.
RAC038.Message: Unable to perform the operation due to an unknown error in iDRAC.

PWR2263.Description: User continued after receiving power supply oversubscription warning (F1/F2).
PWR2263.Message: User ignored Power Supply Oversubscription Warning.

UEFI0246.Description: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization encountered a programmatic error. Link option mismatch detected.
UEFI0246.Resolution: Reseat all processors in the system and ensure all processors are matching. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0246.Message: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization error detected.

PDR1004.Message: Consistency check is in progress for drive %1 in disk drive bay %2.

RED005.Description: The uniform resource identifier (URI) specified for the share location is invalid.
RED005.Resolution: Provide a valid uniform resource identifier (URI) for the share location.

UEFI0123.Description: The secondary SD card has now become the primary SD card.
UEFI0123.Resolution: Check the screen display or the Lifecycle Log for prior messages. If the switch is expected, then no response action is required.
UEFI0123.Message: The secondary SD card has now become the primary SD card.

USR0150.Message: Opening a remote VNC session from IP address %1.
USR0150.Description: The VNC client is connected from the IP address identified in the message to the iDRAC VNC Server.

SYS137.Description: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
SYS137.Resolution: Enable the Lifecycle Controller by pressing F2 during server startup and select iDRAC Settings > Lifecycle Controller and then enable the Lifecycle Controller. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
SYS137.Message: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

SYS181.Description: The collect OS and Application Data operation cannot be completed because the OS Collector is not installed on the iDRAC.
SYS181.Resolution: Install OS Collector on the iDRAC and retry the operation. To install the OS Collector using the iDRAC Web UI, get the latest OC Collector update package and then select the Update and Rollback link from the iDRAC Web UI home page and upload the install package.
SYS181.Message: Unable to collect OS and Application Data because the OS Collector is not installed on the iDRAC.

RAC1012.Description: Unable to change the auto-negotiation state for the current NIC selection mode, because the iDRAC NIC is in dedicated mode.
RAC1012.Resolution: Change the iDRAC NIC mode to shared mode using "racadm set idrac.nic.selection <value>", and retry the operation.
RAC1012.Message: Unable to change the auto-negotiation state for the current NIC selection mode.

JCP031.Description: The job ID specified as input to the operation has configuration data that is currently being processed by the iDRAC. The job can be deleted after the processing is done.
JCP031.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for 15 seconds, wait for the iDRAC to finish restarting, and then retry the operation.
JCP031.Message: Unable to delete the job because the configuration is still being committed.

SWC0040.Description: The location of the backup Server Configuration Profile image file provided is incorrect.
SWC0040.Resolution: Enter the correct location of the backup Server Configuration Profile image file and retry the operation.
SWC0040.Message: Unable to complete the Import operation.

SYS099.Description: The diagnostics results could not be exported because either the diagnostics tests were never run on the system or the results could not be found on the internal storage of the iDRAC.
SYS099.Resolution: Run the RunEPSADiagnostics method to make sure that the diagnostics results are available, and then retry the operation.
SYS099.Message: Unable to export the diagnostics results because the results do not exist.

RED022.Description: The version compatibility check of the firmware update package was not successful for the device specified.
RED022.Resolution: The version compatibility check was not successful for the device specified. Verify that the firmware version pre-requisites specified in the release notes are satisfied.
RED022.Message: Version compatibility check was not successful.

BIOS004.Resolution: Verify that parameter values passed to the method are entered as they appear in the enumeration and parameter data type matches the documentation.
BIOS004.Description: The value for the specified parameter is invalid.

VDR39.Message: The check consistency has made corrections and completed for %1.
VDR39.Resolution: No response action is required. As a precaution, monitor the Log for other errors related to this virtual disk. If problems persist, contact technical support.
VDR39.Description: The virtual disk check consistency has identified issues and made corrections. For example, the check consistency may have encountered a bad disk block and remapped the disk block to restore data consistency. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

OSD65.Description: The ISO file is successfully attached. The next host reboot is scheduled to boot to the ISO file.
OSD65.Message: The ISO file is successfully attached. The next host reboot is scheduled to boot to the ISO file.

RAC1069.Message: Unable to set minimum non critical threshold value of %1, because the value entered is greater than, or equal to the maximum critical threshold value.
RAC1069.Resolution: Check the maximum critical threshold level using an appropriate RACADM command. For example, to view the maximum critical threshold value of a sensor, run the 'racadm getsensorinfo' command at the command line interface, and then retry the operation. For more information about other RACADM commands, run the racadm help command.
RAC1069.Description: The minimum non critical threshold value identified in the message cannot be set, because the value entered is greater than, or equal to the maximum critical threshold value.

CMC005.Description: The operation cannot be completed because of a mismatch between AttributeName and AttributeValue count.
CMC005.Resolution: Enter a valid AttributeName and AttributeValue count, and then retry the operation.
CMC005.Message: Unable to complete the operation because of a mismatch between AttributeName and AttributeValue count.

SWC8618.Message: Server Profiles: request %1 for server in slot %2 was unsuccessful. Message ID %3. Returned fault: %4.
SWC8618.Resolution: Make sure that iDRAC is ready and system is functioning correctly. run the RACADM command at the command line interface (CLI), "racadm getversion" to list all the servers and make sure that the iDRAC version is displayed. If the iDRAC is listed as Not Ready then wait until it becomes ready. A Virtual Reseat may be required.
SWC8618.Description: The request for the WS-Man method identified in the message for server in slot identified slot is unsuccessful.

PDR4.Description: A physical drive that was previously in an error state has returned to a ready state.

CMC8612.Message: The Link Tuning Table is successfully updated by using iDRAC on slot %1.
CMC8612.Description: The Link Tuning Table is successfully updated by using iDRAC on the slot identified in the message.

PSU0036.Message: An over current fault detected on power supply %1.
PSU0036.Resolution: 1) Remove and re-install the power supply.2) Check cables and subsystem components in the system for damage. 3) If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0036.Description: This failure may be the result of an electrical issue with cables or subsystem components in the system.

PSU0912.Message: A failure detected on power unit %1.
PSU0912.Resolution: Check input power. Re-install the power supply. If problem persists contact support.
PSU0912.Description: Status from the power supply indicates a power supply exception occurred. The power supply will try to operate in a degraded state. System Performance and power redundancy may be degraded or lost.

HWC2003.Message: The storage %1 cable is not connected, or is improperly connected.
HWC2003.Resolution: Check presence, then re-install or reconnect.
HWC2003.Description: The cable may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.

SEL1209.Description: System policies or permissions may prevent the action from executing. If configured, the system will not execute the action on a platform event (power down, cycle, interrupt, send alert).
SEL1209.Message: The platform event filter action failed.

SYS129.Description: Unable to complete XML transform on the data collected because the collected data is in an unexpected format.
SYS129.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SYS129.Message: OS Collector: Unable to complete XML transform on the data collected.

LOG507.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of lack of memory or file space in the CMC.
LOG507.Resolution: Reset the CMC and retry the operation.
LOG507.Message: Unable to allocated required CMC resources.

UEFI0010.Description: A CPU stack-segment fault (type 0x0C) exception occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0010.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.

CTL69.Message: Attempted to import virtual disk with outdated physical disk information on %1.
CTL69.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SWC0030.Description: iDRAC is unable to complete the backup Server Profile operation.
SWC0030.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC, hold the System ID button down for 15 seconds or longer and wait for 90 seconds for the iDRAC to restart. For more information on the error, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0030.Message: Unable to complete the backup Server Profile backup operation.

CMC8602.Description: The Chassis group identified in the message is deleted. This chassis was the leader of the group.

RAC068.Description: Both SHA256Password and Plain Password cannot be attempted to set together on Configuration import per user.
RAC068.Resolution: One of either SHA256Password or Plain password can be attempted to be imported for an user.
RAC068.Message: SHA256Password and Plain Password cannot be imported together.

PR5.Message: The configuration values stored for the previous device could not be applied to device: %1
PR5.Resolution: Check the device's configuration and ensure that the new configuration is correct for the system.
PR5.Description: Some or all configuration values stored for the previous device could not be applied to the current device. This may be due to firmware version or other differences in the part.

SWU8554.Description: Local CMC firmware update process is initiated.
SWU8554.Message: Local CMC firmware update has been initiated.

JCP000.Message: A new job with ID %1 is created.
JCP000.Description: A new job with the ID identified in the message is created.

RAC947.Description: The value used for the object set operation is invalid.
RAC947.Resolution: Make sure to specify the value depending on the type of object. For more information, see RACADM help.

JCP023.Resolution: Use the correct job ID and retry. Use the GetAllJobs method to retrieve all open jobs.
JCP023.Description: One of the job ID values specified as input to the operation is a duplicate. The duplicated Job ID is indicated in the message.

SYS067.Description: Some or all configuration actions during the import of configuration profile operation did not complete successfully. The configuration action details are logged into the Lifecycle Log.
SYS067.Resolution: Export the Lifecycle Log and identify the configuration changes that did not successfully complete. Resolve any issues with the configuration profile content and retry the import operation.
SYS067.Message: Unable to complete application of configuration profile values.

RAC0148.Description: While the system is powered off it is unable to retrieve information about the batteries.
RAC0148.Resolution: Turn the system on to view this information.
RAC0148.Message: Unable to retrieve the batteries information. The system is powered off.

SWC0028.Description: iDRAC is unable to complete the backup Server Profile operation because an unrecoverable error occurred.
SWC0028.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC, hold the System ID button down for 15 seconds or longer and wait for 90 seconds for the iDRAC to restart. For more information on the error, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0028.Message: The backup Server Profile operation did not successfully complete.

STOR310.Description: The virtual disk cannot be initialized because the RAID controller selected does not support the initialization mode.
STOR310.Resolution: Make sure that the RAID controller selected for the operation supports the initialization mode, and they retry the operation. For more information about supported RAID controllers, see the specific documentation of RAID controller. Also, refer to the Dell Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Quick Start Guide available at the support site.
STOR310.Message: Unable to initialize the virtual disk because the RAID controller selected does not support the initialization mode.

PWR8685.Message: The %1 firmware in the server slot %2 supports the storage sled.
PWR8685.Description: The firmware identified in the message supports the storage sled.

CTL26.Message: Copyback and Abort CC on Error has changed for %1.
CTL26.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PST0086.Description: System BIOS has launched the Lifecycle Controller user interface.

SWC0064.Description: The details provided to access the network share are incorrect.
SWC0064.Resolution: Enter the correct network share details, and retry the operation.
SWC0064.Message: Unable to mount the network share.

HWC0006.Description: If a vFlash SD card is not present in the system or if the card is locked, Lifecycle Controller cannot save the settings.
HWC0006.Resolution: Insert the vFlash SD card or unlock the vFlash SD card and retry the operation.
HWC0006.Message: Unable to save vFlash SD card settings.

UEFI0235.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0235.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0235.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Write Leveling Training - Calibration phase.

RAC0645.Description: The job could not be successfully scheduled, because an invalid value is entered for 'recurrence frequency' while scheduling a job.
RAC0645.Resolution: Enter a correct value, and then retry the operation.
RAC0645.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid value is entered for the recurrence frequency.

BAT1020.Message: The %1 battery is executing a learn cycle.
BAT1020.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

OSD71.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'Password' is missing.
OSD71.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "Password" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD71.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'Password' is missing.

BAT1008.Message: Write policy on %1 was changed to Write Through.
BAT1008.Resolution: Verify the battery health is good. See the storage hardware documentation to verify battery health. Contact technical support.
BAT1008.Description: The controller battery cannot maintain cached data for the required period of time. For example, if the required period of time is 24 hours, then the battery cannot maintain cached data for 24 hours.

RAC0613.Description: An internal error occurred because of an invalid file.
RAC0613.Resolution: Make sure to upload the required file in the correct format and retry the operation.

PWR8518.Description: Unable to perform the chassis power action because the chassis is already turned on.
PWR8518.Message: Unable to perform the chassis power action because the chassis is already turned on.

CTL64.Message: Attempted to import Unsupported Virtual Disk type RAID%1 on %2.
CTL64.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

HWC0007.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to retrieve vFlash SD card information from iDRAC.
HWC0007.Resolution: Reinsert the vFlash SD card and retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
HWC0007.Message: Unable to load vFlash SD card settings.

VDR18.Resolution: If a physical disk has failed, replace the physical disk. Restart the virtual disk initialization.
VDR18.Description: A physical disk included in the virtual disk has failed or was removed.

CTL101.Description: The controller identified in the message is disabled by a user action.

MEM0004.Message: Memory device at location %1 is disabled.
MEM0004.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. Review product documentation for supported memory configurations. If the problem continues, contact support.
MEM0004.Description: The memory may not be seated correctly, misconfigured, or has failed. Memory size is reduced.

BAR069.Description: The system profile export did not complete successfully because there is insufficient space on the vFlash media.
BAR069.Resolution: Delete partitions and free up 384 MB of space on the current vFlash media, or use new vFlash media.

RED056.Description: An internal error occurred because of insufficient memory available on iDRAC.
RED056.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC and retry the operation.
RED056.Message: An internal error occurred. Unable to complete the specified operation.

VFL1002.Message: Removable Flash Media %1 is IPMI-function ready.

STOR0108.Description: No temperature data to display. The system is powered off, no enclosure temperature probes are present in the system, or the temperature probes are not connected to the enclosures.
STOR0108.Resolution: Check if the server has power, enclosure temperature probe is available, and temperature probe is connected to the enclosure.
STOR0108.Message: Temperature probes are not connected to enclosures or data about temperature is unavailable.

RAC916.Description: The value given is greater than the maximum threshold value.
RAC916.Resolution: Set values lesser than the maximum threshold value. To view the maximum threshold value, run racadm get System.Power. Cap.MaxThreshold at the command prompt.
RAC916.Message: Value given exceeds the maximum threshold value.

PDR14.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

CMC8508.Description: The Extended Storage feature is not activated if the removable flash media SD Card on the secondary CMC is not functioning properly.
CMC8508.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) In the CMC Web interface, go to Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration, and verify if the SD card on secondary CMC displays errors. 2) If errors are displayed, execute the following racadm command: "racadm cmcchangeover". 3) Repair the removable flash media SD Card by selecting the Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration > Repair Active Controller Media in the CMC Web interface. Repairing is only allowed on the SD card of the primary CMC. If the problem persists, replace the card.
CMC8508.Message: Unable to synchronize the primary and secondary CMC removable flash media and the Extended Storage feature is not available.

BAT1000.Resolution: Verify that the device is present and then check the cables. See the storage hardware documentation to verify cabling. In addition check the connection to the controller battery and the battery health. A battery with a weak or depleted charge may cause this message.
BAT1000.Description: The controller cannot communicate with the battery. The battery is absent or improperly connected. A battery with a weak or depleted charge may also cause this message.

TST103.Resolution: To provide the correct parameters, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
TST103.Description: One or more required parameters needed for the operation are missing.

SEL1508.Message: Member %1 could not join the Chassis Group.
SEL1508.Resolution: 1)Check that the Name or IP address, User Name, and Password of the member are correct. 2)Check that the member is not a leader or member of another group. 3)Check that the member can be reached by the leader.
SEL1508.Description: The indicated member may be a member of another chassis group or may be incompatible with membership.

VDR15.Resolution: If a physical disk failed, then replace the physical disk. Restart the virtual disk initialization.
VDR15.Description: The initialization operation could not be completed. This may be due to a user action or a physical disk failure.

UEFI0055.Description: The debranding process cannot be completed because of the reasons identified on the computer screen.
UEFI0055.Resolution: Check the screen display for details of the failure. Retry the debrand process again, or update the system BIOS and then retry.
UEFI0055.Message: Unable to complete the debranding operation because of the issue(s) displayed earlier.

SWC1918.Description: HTTP to HTTPS redirection is enabled. Any iDRAC connection made over the HTTP port (default port number 80) will be redirected to the secure HTTPS port (default port number 443).

PWR8672.Message: The server in slot %1 does not have a %2 mezzanine card in slot %3.
PWR8672.Resolution: Insert a mezzanine card in the slot identified in the message.
PWR8672.Description: The server identified in the message does not have a card in the Mezzanine slot as identified in the message. A mezzanine card position is identified with the following numbers: For quarter-width server, the position number is 1. For half-width server mezzanine C & B maps to position numbers 1 & 2 respectively. For full-width server, mezzanine C & B on the upper- or left part of the server maps to position numbers 1 & 2 respectively. Mezzanine C & B on the lower- or right part of the server maps to position numbers 3 & 4 respectively.

RAC986.Description: The "vmkey" sub-command is deprecated, and the functionality is available using "vflashsd" sub-command.
RAC986.Resolution: Use "vflashsd" sub-command instead of "vmkey". For more information about the sub-command, use "racadm help vflashsd" command.

VLT0204.Message: The system board %1 voltage is outside of range.
VLT0204.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0204.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

BAR046.Description: The Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC) is preparing to switch over to the recently loaded firmware. During this switch over, the connection to iDRAC is lost. The server will startup after iDRAC restarts.
BAR046.Message: Host System will power up approximately 10 minutes after Integrated Remote Access Controller Restore (iDRAC).

RAC0239.Description: The contents of a write protected SD Card cannot be modified.
RAC0239.Resolution: Make sure the SD Card is not write-protected before attempting to change its contents.

RAC0695.Description: Unable to perform security key operations on the selected controller, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
RAC0695.Resolution: To enable Lifecycle Controller, reboot the server. During server startup, press F2 to enter System Setup. Go to iDRAC Settings -> Lifecycle Controller, select Enable, and save the changes. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
RAC0695.Message: Unable to perform security key operations on the selected controller, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

LIC213.Description: This error can occur when:1) License Manager fails to load due to lack of system resources.
LIC213.Message: A system error was detected during License Manager startup.

PST0134.Description: System BIOS detected a failure with the interrupt controller during system POST. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception code 86).
PST0134.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

LC034.Description: The As-Shipped from the factory Hardware Inventory information is not present on the system.
LC034.Message: Unable to retrieve As-Shipped Hardware Inventory from the system.

PDR18.Resolution: Although this alert is provided for informational purposes, you may need to assign a new hot spare to the virtual disk. See Protecting Your Virtual Disk with a Hot Spare for more information.
PDR18.Description: A physical disk assigned as a hot spare was unassigned and is no longer functioning as a hot spare. The physical disk was unassigned by a user or automatically unassigned by Storage Management. Storage Management unassigns hot spares were used to rebuild data. Once the data is rebuilt onto the hot spare, the hot spare becomes a member of the virtual disk and is no longer assigned as a hot spare. Assign a new hot spare to maintain data protection in this situation.

PWR8517.Description: Chassis power state transition did not complete successfully. This may be due to one of the following: 1) Unable to turn off one or more servers, 2) A firmware update may be in progress.
PWR8517.Resolution: Check the tracelog for more information. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR8517.Message: Unable to turn off chassis power.

RAC0146.Resolution: Try the operation after a few minutes. If the problem persists, reset iDRAC and repeat the operation.

UEFI0028.Description: The iDRAC is not responding after a recovery system reset was performed. BIOS will continue POST startup with iDRAC in a non functional state.
UEFI0028.Resolution: Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system.
UEFI0028.Message: iDRAC is not responding after a recovery system reset was performed.

SWC0248.Description: The specified command has invalid syntax.
SWC0248.Resolution: Verify that the correct command syntax is specified. See the help text or documentation for valid commands.

RAC0277.Description: This warning message appears when IPv4 is disabled.
RAC0277.Resolution: Use IPv6 network to access iDRAC remotely.
RAC0277.Message: Disabling IPv4 prevents access to iDRAC using an IPv4 address.

IOID116.Description: The iDRAC has started to apply I/O Identity settings on NIC and FC HBA devices based on the current persistence policy settings.
IOID116.Message: Applying I/O Identity settings based on current persistence policy settings.

SWC8603.Message: Unable to apply profile to server %1 using Quick Deploy feature, because the CSIOR feature on Server %1 is disabled.
SWC8603.Resolution: Make sure that CSIOR on the server identified in the messages is enabled and retry the operation. For 11th generation servers, to enable CSIOR, restart the server, and select the Ctrl-E setup. Select System Services, and enable CSIOR. For 12th generation and above, to enable CSIOR using Lifecycle Controller GUI, restart the server, click <F2> when the company's logo is displayed. On the iDRAC Settings page, click Lifecycle Controller, and enable CSIOR.
SWC8603.Description: The selected profile cannot be applied to the server identified in the message, because the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature on the server is disabled.

SWC8617.Message: Server Profiles: request %1 for server in slot %2 was unsuccessful. Returned fault: %3.
SWC8617.Resolution: Make sure that iDRAC is ready and system is functioning properly. Run the RACADM command "racadm getversion" to list all the servers and make sure the iDRAC version is displayed. If the iDRAC is listed as Not Ready then wait until iDRAC is ready for use. A Virtual Reseat may be required.
SWC8617.Description: The request by the WS-Man method identified in the message for the server in slot identified slot is unsuccessful.

RDU8512.Resolution: Update the firmware so that the Active and Standby CMC firmware versions are the same.
RDU8512.Description: The firmware versions of the Active CMC and the Standby CMC are different.

BAR063.Description: Collecting the Lifecycle Controller firmware images and copying them in the server profile backup file.

ISM0025.Message: Unable to prepare the NVMe device %1 for removal from the PCIe slot %2 because of one or more of the following reasons: 1) NVMe device is busy, 2) NVMe device is not present or 3) NVMe driver is not installed.
ISM0025.Resolution: Make sure of the following: 1)That the NVMe device identified in the message is not in use, 2) the NVMe device is present, and 3) NVMe device drive is installed.
ISM0025.Description: The NVMe device cannot be prepared for removal from (the PCIe slot identified in the message because of one or more of the following reasons: 1) NVMe device is busy, 2) NVMe device is not present or 3) NVMe driver is not present.

SWC0297.Description: After the Groups are downloaded to a file, the passwords are to be deleted.
SWC0297.Message: Unable to remove passwords because file could not be saved.

RAC0908.Description: The System ID LED was successfully set to off.

BAR066.Description: The system profile export destination is not enabled.
BAR066.Resolution: Enable the vFlash media and retry the operation.

MEM1011.Message: Memory device at location %1 is on-duty.

UEFI0137.Description: The CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) operation cannot be executed because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible. This issue is caused by missing LC files.
UEFI0137.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0137.Message: Unable to execute CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible.

RAC0611.Description: The IP address cannot be blank for import or export of system configuration profile operation.
RAC0611.Resolution: Enter a valid IP Address for network location.

RAC042.Description: The number of input parameters provided is not valid to perform the operation.
RAC042.Resolution: Verify that all required parameters are provided. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.

RAC1042.Description: One or more required options to configure the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature are missing.
RAC1042.Resolution: For more information, view the help details by running the RACADM command "racadm help autoupdatescheduler".
RAC1042.Message: Unable to configure the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings. The required options are either invalid or not provided.

SWU8518.Message: The firmware update operation on the iDRAC on the server in slot %1 is stopped.
SWU8518.Resolution: Reinsert the server and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWU8518.Description: The server was pulled out from the chassis during the iDRAC firmware update operation.

DIS004.Description: The Auto Discovery process has timed out and stopped. The Auto Discovery process runs for 24 hours from the initial system power on or re-initialization request. Every 90 seconds the Auto Discovery client will attempt to identify and contact the Provisioning Server during this period.
DIS004.Resolution: Check for previous messages in the Lifecycle Controller Log that provide more specific information why the timeout occurred.
DIS004.Message: Auto Discovery 24-hour timeout occurred. Stopping Auto Discovery process.

SEC0611.Message: An Out-of-band password violation was corrected.

IPA0100.Message: The iDRAC IP Address changed from %1 to %2.
IPA0100.Resolution: Remote management consoles that have cached or stored the iDRAC IP address may have to be updated with the new IP address either through a re-discovery or manual reconfiguration. A response action may not be required if the console receives this SNMP notification and updates the iDRAC IP address accordingly.
IPA0100.Description: The iDRAC IP Address changed from the earlier IP Address identified in the message to the new IP Address identified in the message. This notification will be generated when the iDRAC network card selection is changed, if the DHCP lease expires and the DHCP server assigns another address, or if iDRAC IP address is manually changed.

FC015.Description: A set attribute operation was not successful because the attribute is read-only.

BAR116.Description: Unable to create a recurring export Server Profile job because an existing scheduled Backup Image job is scheduled within the next 24 hours.
BAR116.Message: Unable to create a recurring export Server Profile job because an existing scheduled Backup Image job is scheduled within the next 24 hours.

OSD64.Description: The ConfigurableBootToNetworkISO method cannot be run by specifying the ResetType parameter as 'warm reboot' because the server is in turned-off state.
OSD64.Resolution: Make sure that the server is turned on and retry the operation.
OSD64.Message: Unable to invoke the ConfigurableBootToNetworkISO method by specifying the ResetType parameter as 'warm reboot' because the server is in turned-off state.

SWC0301.Description: The IP address provided is not valid.
SWC0301.Message: The specified IP address is not valid.

UEFI0234.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0234.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0234.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Write Leveling Training - Memory Test phase.

FAN903.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode cannot be enabled because an unsupported fan is present in the Chassis.
FAN903.Resolution: Insert a fan that is supported by the Chassis, and then retry the operation. For a list of fans that are supported by Chassis, see the Chassis Management Controller Users Guide.
FAN903.Message: Cannot enable the Enhanced Cooling Mode because an unsupported fan is inserted in the Chassis.

LNK0003.Description: Cannot connect to the DNS server because of network issues or there is no response from the DNS server.
LNK0003.Resolution: Verify that the server is connected to the network and retry the operation.
LNK0003.Message: Unable to connect to the DNS server.

BAR059.Description: The system profile import or export network destination is being tested for access.

PWR1008.Description: To avoid shutdown, system performance has been degraded.
PWR1008.Resolution: Review system configuration, upgrade power supplies or reduce system power consumption.
PWR1008.Message: The system performance degraded because power draw exceeds the power threshold.

RAC056.Message: Unable to set the Authentication Protocol attribute to None because the Privacy Protocol attribute is enabled for user ID: %1
RAC056.Resolution: Disable the Privacy Protocol attribute for the identified user ID account by setting the value to None, and retry the operation to set Authentication Protocol attribute to None.
RAC056.Description: The Authentication Protocol attribute for the user account identified in the message cannot be disabled because the Privacy Protocol attribute is enabled. The Privacy Protocol for the user account is not set to None.

AMP0314.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0314.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0314.Message: System level current is greater than the upper warning threshold.

UEFI0030.Description: A keyboard device is not connected to the system.
UEFI0030.Resolution: Connect a keyboard device to the system.
UEFI0030.Message: A keyboard device is not connected to the system.

RAC0510.Description: This error occurs if Lifecycle log events have not occurred recently.
RAC0510.Message: There are no events to be displayed.

LC067.Description: The Export Certification operation successfully exported the SSL Certificate.

RAC1023.Description: Configuration jobs are created only if at least one object on the device or component (for example, NIC.Slot.1 or BIOS) has a pending value to be applied.
RAC1023.Resolution: Make sure that there is at least one object on the specified device or component that has a pending value, and retry the operation.
RAC1023.Message: Unable to create the configuration job.

RAC0257.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the Alternate DNS IPv4 address does not conform to the required format.
RAC0257.Resolution: Enter a valid Alternate DNS Server Address. Expected range: [0.0.0.0 or 1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].
RAC0257.Message: The Alternate DNS Server Address is invalid. Expected range: [0.0.0.0 or 1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].

PWR221.Description: The Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature is already disabled.
PWR221.Message: The Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature is already disabled.

RAC1118.Description: Successfully initiated the update operation specified in the command.
RAC1118.Resolution: To know about the status of a command that is initiated, run the following command:racadm jobqueue view -I <job ID>.
RAC1118.Message: Successfully initiated the update operation specified in the command.

LC058.Message: Invalid AttributeValue parameter value for corresponding AttributeName value, %1.
LC058.Resolution: Retry the operation with a valid attribute value for the corresponding specified attribute.
LC058.Description: The attribute value specified in the AttributeValue array is not valid for the corresponding specified attribute.

MEM9005.Message: Intel SMI 2 Memory interconnect %1 has degraded.
MEM9005.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reseat the memory riser and restart the server. 2) If the issue is not resolved by preceding action, reseat the processor and restart the server. 3) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
MEM9005.Description: A link degradation was detected in propagation of signals between processor and memory through the Intel SMI 2 memory interconnect identified in the message.

RAC961.Description: Another import operation cannot be started if an import operation that was performed earlier has some pending or committed configuration changes.
RAC961.Resolution: Wait until the configuration changes are applied before starting another import operation. Use the racadm jobqueue view command to check the status of the current import operation.
RAC961.Message: A pending or committed system configuration change exists.

RAC1162.Description: The requested techsupreport collect operation cannot be initiated because another techsupreport collect operation for the Tech Support Report (TSR) is in progress.
RAC1162.Resolution: Wait for the current collect operation to complete before initiating another collect operation. To view the status of the techsupreport collect operation, run the command 'racadm jobqueue view'.
RAC1162.Message: Unable to initiate the techsupreport collect operation for the Tech Support Report (TSR) because another collect operation is in progress.

MEM0003.Message: Stuck bit memory error detected on a memory device at location %1.
MEM0003.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
MEM0003.Description: The memory is operational. This is an early indicator of a possible future uncorrectable error.

PWR2006.Message: The OS run-time software initiated a warm reset.

SYS182.Description: Collecting OS and Application Data cannot be completed because Lifecycle Controller is used by another operation.
SYS182.Resolution: Make sure all other Lifecycle Controller operations are finished and retry the operation. Using the iDRAC Web UI, select Server > Job Queue, check the job queue for unfinished jobs and wait for the jobs to finish before retrying the operation. Also, check whether there are update packages being executed in the server OS and wait for these operations to finish before retrying the operation. For remote web services API access, make sure that the GetRemoteServicesAPIStatus method returns Ready status, and then retry the operation.
SYS182.Message: Unable to collect OS and Application Data because another Lifecycle Controller operation is currently in progress.

PDR16.Resolution: Replace the physical disk. Even though the disk may not have failed yet, it is strongly recommended that the disk be replaced. Review other messages for additional information.
PDR16.Description: The physical disk is predicted to fail. Many physical disks contain Self Monitoring Analysis and Reporting Technology (SMART). When enabled, SMART monitors the disk health based on indications such as the number of write operations that were performed on the disk.

TMP0301.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is disabled.
TMP0301.Message: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is disabled.

PWR8586.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because it is not supported in the VRTX chassis.
PWR8586.Resolution: The server inserted is not supported in the Chassis. Remove the server from the Chassis.
PWR8586.Description: The Chassis does not support the server identified in the message.

RAC917.Description: The syntax of the specified command is incorrect.
RAC917.Resolution: See the command help text. To see the help text, run "racadm help <subcommand>".
RAC917.Message: The syntax of the specified command is not correct.

SWC0082.Description: An error occurred while joining the Dell Integrated Data Center Network because the Provisioning Server on Integrated Data Center did not respond. Refer to Integrated Data Center setup instructions to setup the Provisioning Server.
SWC0082.Resolution: Refer to Integrated Data Center User Guide for setup instructions.
SWC0082.Message: Unable to join Integrated Data Center network.

UEFI0089.Message: Incompatible x16 data bus width DIMM is installed on memory slot: %1.
UEFI0089.Resolution: Remove the unsupported DIMM module from the identified memory slot and replace it with a supported module. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0089.Description: Incompatible x16 data bus width DIMM is installed on the memory slot identified in the message.

OSE1005.Resolution: Review system boot configuration, local PXE configuration, and PXE server configuration.

RDU0014.Description: The current power supply configuration does not meet the platform requirements to enable redundancy. If a power supply fails the system may shut down.
RDU0014.Resolution: If unintended, review system configuration and power consumption and install power supplies accordingly. Check power supply status for failures.
RDU0014.Message: The power supplies are not redundant.

SWC8537.Message: Unable to add key for slot %1 of service account, due to the key being too long.
SWC8537.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8537.Description: The add key operation did not complete successfully for the slot identified in the message due to the key being too long.

UEFI0199.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.
UEFI0199.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0199.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Write Level Fine Training phase.

STOR0702.Message: The value entered for the %1 option is invalid
STOR0702.Resolution: For more information, run the RACADM command "racadm raid help createvd".
STOR0702.Description: The value entered for the option name identified in the message is invalid.

SYS075.Description: Unable to perform the import operation because the specified file does not exist on the remote share.
SYS075.Resolution: Make sure the import configuration file exists on the remote share before retrying the operation.
SYS075.Message: Unable to perform the import operation because the specified file does not exist on the remote share.

RAC1195.Message: User %1 via IP %2 requested state / configuration change to %3 using %4.
RAC1195.Description: User requested state / configuration change using specified interface.

RAC0676.Description: Unable to assign physical disk drives as global hotspare(s). This may be because there are no disk drives available in a ready state or there are no virtual disks present.
RAC0676.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) If there are no disk drives available in ready state, insert additional disk drives and make sure the drives are in ready state. 2) If no virtual disks are present, click <create virtualdisk link> and create at least one virtual disk. 3) If the physical disk drive(s) are in non-RAID mode, convert them to RAID mode by pressing Ctrl+R while restarting the server, and then select the required controller. Press F2 and select the Convert to RAID capable option, and then complete the operation.
RAC0676.Message: Unable to assign physical disk drives as global hotspare(s).

SWU8548.Description: The firmware update operation of Standby CMC was not successful. The firmware image could not be accessed.
SWU8548.Resolution: Make sure that the CMC firmware image file is available at the location specified in the operation, and then retry the operation.
SWU8548.Message: Unable to update the Standby CMC firmware. The Image was not accessible.

RAC1049.Description: Successfully configured the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings.
RAC1049.Message: Successfully configured the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings.

SYS400.Description: The precondition check operation such as Open Data Protocol (OData) Version, If-Match request-header, and If-Not-Modified request-headers cannot be completed.
SYS400.Resolution: Make sure that the prerequisites specified for the request are satisfied. For more information about the prerequisites, see the Redfish Specification and Redfish Users Guide available on the support site.
SYS400.Message: Unable to successfully complete the precondition check operations such as Open Data Protocol (OData) Version, If-Match request-header, and If-Not-Modified request-headers.

ISM0000.Description: The iDRAC Service Module is started on the OS of server.
ISM0000.Message: The iDRAC Service Module is started on the operating system (OS) of server.

CTL93.Message: %1 has been successfully changed to operate in Fault Tolerant mode.
CTL93.Description: The controller identified in the message has been changed to operate as part of a fault tolerant pair.

PDR73.Resolution: Replace the disk and retry the operation.
PDR73.Description: The physical disk participating in the copyback operation failed.

CTL82.Description: The controller identified in the message is functioning normally.

STOR043.Description: One or more physical disk drives selected for the operation are part of a virtual disk that is not Secondary RAID Level 0.
STOR043.Resolution: This operation is not supported unless the previous virtual disk on the selected physical disk drives are deleted first. To perform the operation, delete any virtual disk on the selected physical disks drives and retry the operation.
STOR043.Message: One or more selected physical disk drives are part of virtual disk that is not Secondary RAID Level 0.

SYS032.Description: The staged component configuration update performed in the UEFI environment on the host system is complete.

PWR8561.Message: Unable to power on server %1 because of iDRAC communication issue.
PWR8561.Resolution: Wait for three minutes and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, remove and reinsert the server and wait for the iDRAC to finish restarting.
PWR8561.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to communicate with the Server iDRAC service processor and the server could not be powered on. This situation may occur when iDRAC is rebooting.

IOID117.Description: The iDRAC has applied I/O Identity settings on NIC and FC HBA devices. All the device configuration related to virtual addresses, initiator and target settings have been configured successfully according to the current persistence policy settings.
IOID117.Message: The operation to apply I/O Identity settings based on current persistence policy settings has completed successfully.

IOV002.Description: CMC could not successfully allocate resources because of the following reasons: 1) The chassis manager is unable to allocate required resources. 2) The chassis manager or chassis infrastructure firmware is rolled back to an earlier version. 3) There is an issue with the internal communications between chassis components.
IOV002.Resolution: Make sure the firmware for the various chassis components are compatible with each other. If this is the case, do the following: 1) Turn off the chassis, by pressing the chassis Power Button, 2) run the following CMC RACADM command "racadm racresetcfg". If the problem persists, contact your technical service provider.
IOV002.Message: Unable to create or allocate the required resources.

STOR076.Description: The requested operation could not be completed because at least one other pending operation was found on the RAID controller. This operation needs exclusivity because it involves changing RAID backplane topology.
STOR076.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Create a job to complete the pending operations, allow the job to complete, and then retry the operation. 2) Cancel any pending operations on the RAID controller, and then retry the operation.
STOR076.Message: Enclosure configuration mode (Split/Unified) cannot be changed because there are already pending operations.

CMC8548.Description: The active Chassis Management Controller is not connected to an external network for more than 25 seconds. A failover is performed if the standby CMC is connected to the external network.
CMC8548.Resolution: Make sure that the external network cable is connected to the active CMC and the network switch. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8548.Message: The active Chassis Management Controller is no longer connected to an external network.

SWU8528.Description: The process of iKVM firmware update is not successful due to a checksum error of the firmware image.
SWU8528.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source folder, and then retry the operation.
SWU8528.Message: Unable to update the iKVM firmware, because of a checksum error.

SWU8505.Message: Successfully scheduled the reinstall/rollback operation on the server %1.
SWU8505.Description: The specified Lifecycle Controller operation is successfully submitted and the operation will be executed on the basis of scheduling criteria.

CTL56.Resolution: See the hardware documentation for more information.
CTL56.Description: The text for this alert is generated by the controller and can vary depending on the situation. This text is from events in the controller event log that were generated while Storage Management was not running.

UEFI0034.Description: A CMOS battery loss is detected resulting in an invalid BIOS configuration.
UEFI0034.Resolution: Go to the System Setup to configure system settings, system time and date.
UEFI0034.Message: A CMOS battery loss is detected resulting in an invalid BIOS configuration.

VFL1013.Message: Removable Flash Media %1 has finished booting.

UEFI0019.Description: The system boot process did not complete repeatedly due to problems encountered while performing a Lifecycle Controller task for function. No Lifecycle Controller functionality is available while in Recovery Mode.
UEFI0019.Resolution: Repair Lifecycle Controller firmware using the Lifecycle Controller Dell Update Package (DUP) or Lifecycle Controller Repair Package via iDRAC. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.
UEFI0019.Message: Lifecycle Controller (LC) is unable to complete a requested task or function and prevented the boot process from completing on multiple attempts. LC is in Recovery Mode.

UEFI0264.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot because the iSCSI initiator name is invalid.
UEFI0264.Resolution: Go to System Setup > Network Settings page, make sure there is no typographical error in the iSCSI Initiator Name field, and retry the operation.
UEFI0264.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot because the iSCSI initiator name is invalid.

SYS144.Description: Starting controller hardware cache data erase operations because of a System Erase operation request.
SYS144.Message: Starting controller hardware cache data erase operations.

PST0082.Description: System is at the BIOS Setup Menu.

RAC047.Description: The event action selected is not supported for the event filter specified.
RAC047.Resolution: Refer to the iDRAC User Guide and Lifecycle Controller documentation and retry the operation with a valid event action selection on the specified filter.
RAC047.Message: Unsupported event action for the specified event filter.

RAC0151.Description: While the system is powered off it is unable to retrieve information about removable flash media.
RAC0151.Resolution: Turn the system on to view this information.
RAC0151.Message: Unable to retrieve the removable flash media information. The system is powered off.

RAC0748.Description: The BIOS watchdog must be disabled if Automatic System Recovery option is enabled.
RAC0748.Resolution: Make sure the BIOS watchdog timer is disabled before enabling the Automatic System Recovery option.
RAC0748.Message: The BIOS watchdog timer must be disabled if the Automatic System Recovery option is enabled.

RFL2000.Message: Internal Dual SD Module %1 is present.

CTL92.Message: %1 is not operating in Fault Tolerant Mode because of an incompatible license setting on its peer controller.
CTL92.Resolution: Update the license on the peer controller.
CTL92.Description: The controller identified in the message licensed features do not match its peer.

SWC0152.Message: RAC configuration from file completed successfully

RAC0280.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the IPv4 address does not conform to the required format.
RAC0280.Resolution: Enter a valid IP Range Address. Expected range: 0.0.0.0 - 255.255.255.255.
RAC0280.Message: The IP Range Address is invalid. Expected range: 0.0.0.0 - 255.255.255.255.

JCP021.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of lack of an unknown error in the iDRAC.
JCP021.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC.
JCP021.Message: The operation failed due to an internal iDRAC error.

SUP0513.Description: The specified filename path to the Update Package is incorrect.
SUP0513.Resolution: Enter the correct file path where the Update Package is located and retry the operation. If the problem persists, reboot the system and retry the operation.
SUP0513.Message: Unable to access the Update Package.

SUP0532.Description: The repository contains corrupt Update Packages.
SUP0532.Resolution: Enter another repository location that contains the desired Update Packages and retry the operation.
SUP0532.Message: The repository contains corrupt Update Packages.

RAC988.Message: Unable to initiate the %1 firmware update.
RAC988.Resolution: Wait until the existing firmware update jobs are completed or scheduled before retrying the operation. To monitor the status of the existing jobs, use the "racadm jobqueue view" command.
RAC988.Description: A new firmware update job cannot be initiated while an existing firmware update job is still in one of these states: "New", "Downloading", or "Running".

SWC0325.Message: The specified object is WRITE-ONLY and cannot be displayed.

DH003.Resolution: Try again. If the error persists, use RACADM command racreset to clear the issue.
DH003.Message: Service tag could not be read.

FAN0003.Message: Fan %1 RPM is greater than the upper critical threshold.
FAN0003.Resolution: Remove and re-install the fan. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0003.Description: The fan is not performing optimally. The fan may be installed improperly or may be failing.

PDR38.Description: A user has initiated a clear operation on a physical disk.

CTL41.Description: An error involving a single bit has been encountered during a read or write operation. The error correction algorithm has corrected this error.

UEFI0192.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.
UEFI0192.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0192.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Clock Alignment phase.

RED021.Description: The component InstanceID specified could not be located on the system.
RED021.Resolution: Ensure the component specified for updates is present in the system. Restart the system with Collect System Inventory on Restart enabled and verify that the component is represented by an instance of DCIM_SoftwareIdentity.
RED021.Message: The component InstanceID specified is not present on the system.

AMP0318.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0318.Message: Chassis power level current is less than the lower warning threshold.

SWC0078.Description: The server has been successfully removed from Integrated Data Center. All configurations will be restored to Factory defaults.
SWC0078.Message: The server has been successfully removed from Integrated Data Center.

JCP040.Message: User %1 via IP %2 created configuration / update Job ID %3 with Job Name %4 using %5.
JCP040.Description: User created configuration / update Job with specified Job Name using specified interface.

PDR1104.Message: Consistency check is in progress for drive %1.

RAC936.Description: iDRAC cannot enable or disable the hot spare property, because the system has a non-PMBus PSU.
RAC936.Message: Unable to change the hot spare property for the PSU.

RAC0755.Description: The selected value is not supported on this server.
RAC0755.Resolution: Retry the operation with another value.
RAC0755.Message: The selected value is not supported on this server.

LOG201.Description: Lifecycle Controller Log corruption was detected during iDRAC boot. The Lifecycle Controller Log was truncated at the point of corruption.
LOG201.Message: Recovered from Lifecycle Controller Log corruption.

RAC066.Description: iDRAC was successfully reset to factory-default properties.
RAC066.Message: iDRAC is successfully reset to factory-default properties.

SWU8526.Message: The firmware update operation of the iDRAC on the server in slot %1 is initiated.
SWU8526.Description: The firmware update operation of iDRAC identified in the message is initiated.

SWC0302.Description: The syntax of the fwupdate command is invalid.
SWC0302.Resolution: Refer the help text for fwupdate subcommand.
SWC0302.Message: The -s option is not valid with any other option.

OSD73.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'HashValue' is missing.
OSD73.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "HashValue" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD73.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'HashValue' is missing.

RED059.Message: Unable to create an update job for %1.
RED059.Resolution: Retry the operation for the component identified in the message.
RED059.Description: Unable to create an update job for the component identified in the message.

LNK0005.Description: Error occurred while communicating with the DHCP server because the network settings are not configured correctly or the DHCP server could not be contacted.
LNK0005.Resolution: Verify if the network cable is connected and network configuration settings are correct, and retry the operation. If the problem persists, update the network interface controller (NIC) firmware to the latest version and retry the operation.
LNK0005.Message: Unable to connect to DHCP server.

RAC0107.Description: Communication with the Smart Card reader is established and a Smart Card is inserted, but there are problems accessing the Smart Card. The appropriate Cryptographic Service Provider (CSP) drivers are not installed.
RAC0107.Resolution: There may be an issue with the Smart Card Cryptographic Service Provider (CSP) drivers. Use the client OS to install CSP driver. If the OS has problem with Smart Card, then there will have problem using the Smart Card. So make sure Smart Card can login with Windows OS.
RAC0107.Message: The inserted Smart Card cannot be recognized. Ensure that the correct Smart Card CSP drivers are installed.

ASR0001.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate to the baseboard management controller (BMC) within the timeout period. The system was reset per the configured setting.
ASR0001.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0001.Message: The watchdog timer reset the system.

SYS179.Description: Unable to export TTY log data because the storage controller present in the server does not support the feature.
SYS179.Resolution: Make sure that at least one storage controller is present in the server that supports the TTY log feature, and then retry the operation.
SYS179.Message: Unable to export TTY log data because the storage controller present in the server does not support the feature.

RFL2006.Message: Internal Dual SD Module %1 is write protected.
RFL2006.Resolution: If unintended, remove the media and disable write protection.
RFL2006.Description: The module is write-protected. Changes may not be written to the media.

PDR66.Message: %1 that was marked as missing has been replaced.
PDR66.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC1019.Description: Some objects have dependencies on other objects that are required to perform a task. The specified object is not available because of such dependencies.
RAC1019.Resolution: Verify the object dependency using "racadm help <device class>.<group name>.<object name>", and retry the operation. For example, racadm help NIC.VndrConfigGroup.1.VirtWWPN.
RAC1019.Message: The specified object is not supported for the current system configuration.

SWC8502.Message: A Profile is successfully generated with [ %1 ] settings.
SWC8502.Description: A Profile is successfully generated with the number of settings identified in the message.

VLT0202.Message: The system board %1 voltage is greater than the upper warning threshold.
VLT0202.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0202.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

UEFI0079.Description: One or more Uncorrectable Memory errors occurred in the previous boot.
UEFI0079.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the non-functional DIMM, and then replace the DIMM.
UEFI0079.Message: One or more Uncorrectable Memory errors occurred in the previous boot.

VDR1.Resolution: Replace the failed component. You can identify which component has failed by locating the component that has a red "X" for its status. Perform a rescan after replacing the failed component.
VDR1.Description: A storage component such as a physical disk or an enclosure has failed. The failed component may have been identified by the controller while performing a task such as a rescan or a check consistency.

PWR8544.Message: Chassis Management Controller turned off the Server %1 because of insufficient power at inventory.
PWR8544.Resolution: Make sure there is enough power supply to distribute power. Using the CMC Web UI, go to Chassis Overview > Power > Power Budget Status. In the Total Input Power Available For Allocation field view the available power. To add more power, insert more PSUs or remove unused components from the chassis.
PWR8544.Description: Insufficient power is available for the server identified in the message to function. The server will be turned off until there is sufficient power available.

RDU8521.Message: CMC%1: active CMC has been removed
RDU8521.Resolution: Reinstall the CMC that was removed.
RDU8521.Description: The active CMC has been removed from the chassis. If standby CMC is present, it will become active.

SYS240.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported mount-point path value.
SYS240.Resolution: Make sure that the correct mount-point path value is entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS240.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an unsupported mount-point path value.

RED072.Description: Unable to delete the Automatic Backup schedule information because the schedule is not configured.
RED072.Message: Unable to delete the Automatic Backup schedule.

NIC505.Description: The value of the specified parameter cannot be changed.
NIC505.Message: The DNS domain name is not allowed to be configured if domain name DHCP (cfgDNSDomainNameFromDHCP) is enabled.

SUP0525.Description: Unable to verify the digital signature of the Update Package.
SUP0525.Resolution: Download the latest Update Package from your service provider and retry the operation.
SUP0525.Message: Unable to verify the digital signature of the Update Package.

PSU8512.Message: Unable to update the firmware for the PSU in slot %1. Error=0x%2 (%3)
PSU8512.Resolution: Retry the firmware update operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PSU8512.Description: The firmware update operation for the PSU identified in the message did not complete, because of internal communication errors.

HWC6000.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
HWC6000.Description: Information and status from the controller is unavailable.

RAC0285.Description: The user name cannot be empty when creating a user account.

RAC954.Description: Up to 128 characters are allowed for a comment.
RAC954.Resolution: Do not exceed 128 characters for the comment, and retry the operation.
RAC954.Message: The number of characters entered for the comment exceeds the supported limit.

CMC8522.Message: The Mezz card 2 FRU for the server %1 is not functioning.
CMC8522.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC of the specified server or virtual reseat the server. 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8522.Description: The Mezz card 2 FRU for the server specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.

LC064.Message: The value exceeds the maximum length of %1 characters for %2.
LC064.Resolution: Reduce the number of characters to the maximum length allowed for this parameter.
LC064.Description: The maximum number of characters allowed for the parameter is displayed.

RAC0624.Description: The requested operation could not be completed, because an incorrect job type or job ID is entered.
RAC0624.Resolution: Enter the correct job type or ID, and then retry the operation.
RAC0624.Message: Unable to find the requested job type or ID.

VF015.Description: Disabling vFlash was not successful because the vFlash feature is not enabled.
VF015.Resolution: The vFlash is disabled and an attempts to disable it will not be successful.

MEM0024.Message: Memory device at location %1 is no longer spare memory.

PSU0039.Message: An under current fault detected on power supply %1.
PSU0039.Resolution: 1) Remove and re-install the power supply input cord. 2) Check power distribution or PSU input source for anomalies. 3) If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0039.Description: Insufficient amount of current to keep power supply operating at a normal levels.

SEC0003.Description: The processor area is open. A drive may be added or removed. System performance may be degraded.
SEC0003.Resolution: Close the processor area. Check system logs.

SWC8605.Message: Quick Deploy Profile: Server %1 generation information is not recognized.
SWC8605.Resolution: Restart the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) and retry the operation. The CMC can be restarted by using the Web UI interface and selecting Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components and then select the Reset/Failover CMC button. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8605.Description: Information about the server identified in the message is not recognized.

UEFI0104.Message: The DIMM module on memory slot %1 is populated out of order in the DIMM channel.
UEFI0104.Resolution: Install DIMM modules in sequential order without skipping any slots in the channel. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
