UEFI0104.Description: The DIMM module on memory slot identified in the message is populated out of order in the channel.

PSU0904.Message: Could not power down 240VA on power unit %1.
PSU0904.Resolution: Remove input power at the power supply.
PSU0904.Description: In order to meet service requirements the supply must be shut down.

RAC1044.Description: The Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature is not enabled.
RAC1044.Resolution: To enable, run the RACADM command "racadm set lifecyclecontroller.lcattributes.autoupdate 1".
RAC1044.Message: The Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature is not enabled.

BOOT005.Description: One or more of the invoked methods required parameters are missing.
BOOT005.Resolution: Check documentation for the method in question and try again.

RAC1053.Description: Unable to view the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings because the feature has not been configured.
RAC1053.Resolution: Configure the Automatic Backup feature by running the RACADM command "racadm systemconfig backup" with the desired option settings.
RAC1053.Message: Unable to view the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings because the feature has not been configured.

PWR8522.Description: The chassis power cycle operation was initiated.

MEM1013.Message: Memory device at location %1 is in a full state.

IOV008.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) was unable to reset the PCIe subsystem into factory default mode.
IOV008.Resolution: Turn off the chassis, turn on the chassis, and then retry the operation.
IOV008.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to put PCIe subsystem into factory default mode.

CMC8521.Message: The Mezz card 1 FRU for the server %1 is not functioning.
CMC8521.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC of the specified server or virtual reseat the server. 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8521.Description: The Mezz card 1 FRU for the server specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.

CTL103.Message: The Check Consistency Mode value of %1 is set to %2.
CTL103.Description: The Check Consistency Mode value of the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.

SEL1517.Description: The sleds are automatically turned off because of a power button release simulation triggered by Chassis Controller. An I2C sensor in not correctly responding because of a corrupted signal in the sensor.
SEL1517.Resolution: Check the firmware version of Fan Controller Block (FCB) and make sure that the Power Supply Unit (PSU) is functional. For more information about the firmware version and PSU ratings, see PSQN SLN300669 available on the support site.
SEL1517.Message: The sleds are automatically turned off because of a power button release simulation triggered by Chassis Controller.

PSU0035.Message: An over voltage fault detected on power supply %1.
PSU0035.Resolution: Check input power, replace or re-install the power supply. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

PWR207.Description: The Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) feature cannot be enabled because the Extended Power Performance mode is enabled.
PWR207.Resolution: Disable Extended Power Performance and retry the operation.
PWR207.Message: The Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) feature cannot be enabled because the Extended Power Performance mode is enabled.

HWC4018.Message: A hardware incompatibility was corrected between %1%2 and %3%4.
HWC4018.Description: A hardware incompatibility was corrected between the components identified in the message.

LIC015.Description: This error occurs when the Lifecycle Controller restore operation is interrupted before it completes. This can occur due to a power outage or when a system is rebooted before the operation is completed.
LIC015.Resolution: Repeat the Lifecycle Controller restore operation. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
LIC015.Message: The License Manager database restore operation failed.

RFM1035.Message: Media is present for Removable Flash Media.

OSD21.Description: Booting to ISO has failed. Either BIOS was unable to boot to the ISO image or the provider did not get a response in 5 minutes from BIOS on successful boot to ISO image.
OSD21.Resolution: 1) Make sure that a POST error did not result in user interaction (Press F1 to continue or F2 to run BIOS setup). 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD21.Message: Unable to boot to ISO image.

SEC0041.Description: TXT initialization cannot be completed because system configuration may have changed.
SEC0041.Resolution: Check system hardware inventory for TPM presence, clear and reconfigure TPM and TXT in BIOS setup menu.
SEC0041.Message: BIOS is unable to configure the Intel Trusted Execution Technology (TXT).

TST101.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of lack of memory or file space in the iDRAC firmware.
TST101.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and retry the operation.

MEM8502.Description: An ECC memory condition was detected on the primary CMC and a failover was initiated.
MEM8502.Resolution: Reseat the primary CMC and initiate a failover back to the primary CMC. If the problem persists and multiple failovers occur, contact your service provider.
MEM8502.Message: ECC Memory error rate failover condition detected.

RAC019.Description: The submitted job did not complete successfully.
RAC019.Resolution: Examine source of the errors by inspecting the results from the job execution, and after resolving the issues, retry the operation. Job results can be retrieved from the Lifecycle Log or the WSMan API.

RAC0147.Description: Firmware rollback image is missing or is corrupt.

CPU0822.Message: CPU %1 voltage regulator module is configured correctly.

STOR045.Description: The specified physical disks have fragmented disk space, therefore StartingLBA and Size parameters are required to be specified in order to create a virtual disk.
STOR045.Resolution: Specify StartingLBA and Size parameters and retry the operation.
STOR045.Message: StartingLBA and Size parameters are required to create a virtual disk.

STOR038.Resolution: Specify a valid value for identified parameter.
STOR038.Description: Unable to complete the requested operation because one or more input parameters identified in the message are not valid.

BOOT012.Description: A job was created to configure a OneTime boot to the specified vFlash SD card partition. If this partition was not attached to the system, the job attaches it as well.
BOOT012.Message: Job started to attach and set vFlash SD card partition for OneTime boot.

RAC036.Description: The value of the specified attribute is dependent on the value of another attribute. The current value dependency is invalid. The other attribute value must be changed before the specified attribute value can be set.
RAC036.Resolution: Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation for the specified attribute dependency on another attribute value and retry the operation.

STOR1.Message: A device %1 is in an unknown state.
STOR1.Resolution: See the storage hardware documentation for information on checking the cables. Check for problems with any enclosures attached to the system. Verify that the controller has a supported version of the driver and firmware. Rebooting the system may resolve this problem.
STOR1.Description: The controller cannot communicate with a device. The state of the device cannot be determined. There may be a bad or loose cable, or a missing device, or a problem with the driver or firmware.

SWC0090.Description: iDRAC is successfully configured by using the Initial Setup feature of Lifecycle Controller.
SWC0090.Message: iDRAC is successfully configured by using the Initial Setup feature of Lifecycle Controller.

BAR033.Description: A Lifecycle Controller internal data import operation did not complete successfully.
BAR033.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Download and apply the Dell Update Package for the Unified Server Configurator (USC). 2) Run System Services to update the database if CSIOR is not enabled. 3) Reboot the system and retry the operation. If these response actions do not resolve the issue, download the Field Service Repair software and repair the Lifecycle Controller. Download and install all the DUPs for USC, diagnostics, driver packs, and device firmware of all the devices of the host system.
BAR033.Message: Unable to Restore Lifecycle Controller data.

LNK0004.Description: Unable to connect to FTP server due to a network error.
LNK0004.Resolution: Check the network connection, network configuration settings, and retry. If the problem persists, restart the FTP server.
LNK0004.Message: Unable to connect to FTP server.

BAR053.Description: Restoring device firmware on the device identified in the message.

UEFI0272.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the BIOS cannot obtain the initiator information from DHCPv4 server.
UEFI0272.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Check the configuration of DHCPv4 server. 2) Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings > Connection Settings page, disable DHCP and configure the initiator information manually. Retry the operation.
UEFI0272.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the BIOS cannot obtain the initiator information from DHCPv4 server.

UEFI0189.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.
UEFI0189.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0189.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Transmit DQS DCC phase.

BAR074.Description: The collection and export of firmware inventory data did not complete successfully.
BAR074.Resolution: Apply the Dell Update Package for Unified Server Configurator (USC). If collect system inventory on reboot (CSIOR) is not enabled, enter and exit System Services in USC to update the database, reboot the system and try the operation again. If the error continues, use the field service repair software to repair the Lifecycle Controller. Download all Dell Update Packages for USC, Diagnostics Driver Packs, and device firmware for all host system devices, install all packages and retry the operation.
BAR074.Message: Unable to collect Firmware Inventory information.

SWC0126.Description: Racadm tool was unable to download the generated CSR file.

RAC0725.Description: Unable to update the Quick Sync Firmware.
RAC0725.Message: Unable to update the Quick Sync Firmware.

RAC0226.Description: Sending the test mail failed. This will prevent alert messages from being sent to this email address.
RAC0226.Resolution: Confirm that:1. A valid SMTP server address is configured in the iDRAC. 2. The remote email server is configured properly to send and receive emails.

SYS058.Description: Running Lifecycle Controller Automated Task Execution application in Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) environment to apply configuration changes.

RED032.Description: The rollback firmware images previously stored were deleted to provide space for storing the firmware images for the requested operation. All the rollback firmware images are deleted.
RED032.Message: Reached maximum size limit allowed for storing firmware images. Deleted all rollback firmware images.

RED057.Description: An internal error occurred because of insufficient memory available on iDRAC.
RED057.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC and retry the operation.
RED057.Message: An internal error occurred. Unable to complete the specified operation.

SWC0005.Description: The view current hardware inventory operation encountered an unexpected error while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0005.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0005.Message: Unable to display the current hardware inventory.

CMC8523.Message: The Mezz card 3 FRU for the server %1 is not functioning.
CMC8523.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC of the specified server or virtual reseat the server. 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8523.Description: The Mezz card 3 FRU for the server specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.

PDR1106.Message: Drive %1 is in the failed array.

PWR8682.Message: Unable to turn on the storage sled controller %1 in slot %2 because the %3 module is not functioning.
PWR8682.Resolution: Remove the storage sled identified in the message, re-insert it and observe whether the issue is resolved. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR8682.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to turn on the storage sled controller identified in the message. The Chassis storage sled controller is unable to turn on due to a configuration or hardware issue.

PSU8519.Description: The Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) feature is suspended due to the configuration or the type of PSU present. The feature is enabled, but suspended until a supported PSU configuration is in place.
PSU8519.Resolution: Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) is not supported by the current power supply configuration. Verify the PSUs are supported. Replace the unsupported PSUs.
PSU8519.Message: Enhanced Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) is not supported by the current power supply configuration and is suspended.

RAC970.Description: The import operation cannot continue if the value specified for the end power state of the system option (-s) is incorrect. The supported values are "On" and "Off".
RAC970.Resolution: Make sure to specify either "On" or "Off" for the end power state (-s) option.
RAC970.Message: Incorrect value specified for the end power state option.

UEFI0197.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.
UEFI0197.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0197.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Read Level Coarse Training phase.

TMP0108.Message: The memory module %1 temperature is greater than the upper warning threshold.
TMP0108.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0108.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.

USR0024.Message: Unable to log in to iDRAC from %1:%2 using Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI) because an incorrect user name or password is entered.
USR0024.Resolution: Enter the correct user name and password and retry the operation.
USR0024.Description: Cannot log in to iDRAC from the user name and IP address identified in the message by using Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI) because an incorrect user name or password is entered.

PWR8588.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because a chassis infrastructure firmware update is in progress.
PWR8588.Resolution: The chassis infrastructure firmware update is in progress. Retry the operation after the firmware update is complete.
PWR8588.Description: The server identified in the message cannot be turned on while a chassis infrastructure firmware update operation is in progress.

UEFI0173.Message: A Quad Rank DIMM module is installed on memory slot %1 after a Dual Rank DIMM module.
UEFI0173.Resolution: Quad Rank DIMM modules must be installed before Dual Rank DIMM modules on the channel. Populate memory modules in a supported configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0173.Description: A memory population violation has been detected on the identified DIMM slot.

PDR25.Description: Portions of the physical disk that were formerly inaccessible have been recovered. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SWC0084.Description: The iDRAC has successfully joined Integrated Data Center network. This iDRAC will now be managed by the Integrated Data Center solution.
SWC0084.Message: The iDRAC successfully joined Integrated Data Center network.

SYS019.Description: The input is missing a required dependency necessary for the operation.
SYS019.Resolution: Provide the required dependency and retry. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller Remote Services documentation.

PST0080.Description: System is at the F1/F2 prompt because the system BIOS detected an issue other than "No bootable devices".
PST0080.Resolution: Check post display screen for details. Press F1 to continue boot, or press F2 to go to setup.
PST0080.Message: An issue was detected. System at boot F1/F2 prompt. Requires entry to continue.

PDR1119.Message: Drive %1 is no longer the hot-spare drive.

USR0184.Description: A bezel with the iDRAC Quick Sync feature has been disconnected and the feature is not available.
USR0184.Resolution: Connect a bezel with the iDRAC Quick Sync feature. Press the activate button to enable the Quick Sync feature.
USR0184.Message: A bezel with the iDRAC Quick Sync feature has been disconnected and the feature is not available.

HWC8509.Description: The heatsinks are critical for providing cooling to the PCIe switches. If a PCIe switch stops functioning due to improper cooling, the PCIe subsystem may no longer function correctly and data loss may occur.
HWC8509.Resolution: Immediately turn off the Chassis by pressing the Chassis power button or removing chassis input power. The Chassis can be turned off remotely by running the following RACADM command "racadm chassisaction -m chassis nongraceshutdown". After turning off, contact your service provider.
HWC8509.Message: One or more PCIe switch heatsinks are not properly attached.

POW003.Description: Host failed to power up because PCI/Mezz cards not installed in Fabric1/Fabric2.This messages has been replaced by Message ID PWR2253.
POW003.Message: Power on permission error, no PCI/Mezz card installed in Fabric1/Fabric2.

STOR16.Message: The storage sled %1 configuration is normal.
STOR16.Description: The configuration of the storage sled in the slot identified in the message is normal.

SWC8517.Description: Successfully modified the password for the User identified in the message.

RAC943.Description: The Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is currently disabled. If the system inventory is not up-to-date, the system configuration profile that is being copied will not have the latest inventory information.
RAC943.Resolution: To get latest inventory information, cancel the current export job, run "racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.CollectSystemInventoryOnRestart 1" to enable CSIOR, and re-initiate the export operation.
RAC943.Message: Warning: Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled.

SYS074.Description: Unable to apply configuration changes because another configuration job is in progress.
SYS074.Resolution: Wait until the current configuration job is complete and retry the operation.
SYS074.Message: Unable to apply configuration changes because another configuration job is in progress.

SWC0087.Description: The Public IP access feature in iDRAC is disabled by the Integrated Data Center solution. The iDRAC can no longer be accessed via the public IP interface.
SWC0087.Message: The Integrated Data Center Public IP mode is disabled.

CPU0005.Resolution: Review product documentation for supported CPU configurations.
CPU0005.Description: System is unable to boot or may run in a degraded state.

RAC0638.Description: The requested network file share cannot be accessed, because an invalid proxy host name or IP address is entered.
RAC0638.Resolution: Enter a valid proxy host name or IP address, and then retry the operation.
RAC0638.Message: Unable to access the network file share, because an invalid proxy host name or IP address is entered.

SYS177.Description: There was an issue retrieving Hardware data from the iDRAC internal storage. This may be because Collect System Inventory on Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled and has never executed or the iDRAC Remote Services API status may not be in the Ready state.
SYS177.Resolution: Make sure the Collect System Inventory on Restart (CSIOR) is enabled and has run at least once before retrying this operation. For remote web services API access, make sure the GetRemoteServicesAPIStatus method returns Ready status before trying this operation. If the issue persists, reset iDRAC and retry the operation.
SYS177.Message: There was an issue retrieving Hardware data.

CTL108.Message: The Check Consistency Rate of %1 is set to %2.
CTL108.Description: The Check Consistency Rate of the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.

SYS162.Description: The server will be turned on to enter UEFI System Services Manager (SSM). The storage-related erase operations selected, if any, will be processed by SSM.
SYS162.Message: Turning on the server to perform System Erase tasks.

LC029.Description: An invalid File Path was specified in the export operation.
LC029.Resolution: Correct the specified file path and try again.

UEFI0239.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0239.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0239.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Write DQ/DQS Training - Calculation phase.

PST0136.Description: System BIOS detected an failure with the programmable interval timer during POST. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video.(BIOS POST Exception code 88).
PST0136.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

PSU0034.Message: An under voltage fault detected on power supply %1.
PSU0034.Resolution: 1) Remove and re-install the power supply.2) Check cables and subsystem components in the system for damage. 3) If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0034.Description: This failure may be the result of an electrical issue with cables or subsystem components in the system.

PWR8585.Message: Chassis Management Controller granted the power required to turn on server-%1.
PWR8585.Description: Chassis Management Controller granted the power required to turn on the server identified in the message.

LC065.Message: The iDRAC static IP address information is not fully configured. The missing attribute InstanceID is %1.
LC065.Resolution: Configure the iDRAC static IP address information by setting the related iDRACCard Attributes. The related attributes that must be configured are the following:: 1) In the IPv4 group: Address, NetMask, Gateway, DNS1 2) In the NIC Static group: DNSDomainName.
LC065.Description: The static IPv4 information for the iDRAC represented by the related iDRACCard Attributes must be configured correctly.

SWC0072.Description: SupportAssist collection cannot be exported to the destination folder.
SWC0072.Resolution: Verify the following and retry the operation: 1) Destination folder is present. 2) Destination folder has sufficient free disk space. 3) Destination folder is not write-protected. If the issue persists, perform an AC power cycle operation, and then retry the operation.
SWC0072.Message: Unable to export the SupportAssist collection to destination folder.

LOG502.Message: Unable to run the command because the method parameter %1 is missing.
LOG502.Resolution: Enter all the parameters required in the command, and then retry the operation. For more information, see the Chassis Record Log Profile.
LOG502.Description: The command cannot be run because the method parameter identified in the message is missing.

IOV120.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) has enabled PCIe ride-through mode. PCIe adapters will remain turned on for the number of seconds specified by the ride-through timeout value after the server they are assigned to is turned off.

STOR029.Description: The requested operation cannot be completed because the specified physical disk is not found.
STOR029.Resolution: Provide a valid physical disk FQDD (Fully Qualified Device Descriptor) and retry the operation.

SYS403.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the resource %1 entered in not found.
SYS403.Resolution: Enter the correct resource and retry the operation. For information about valid resource, see the Redfish Users Guide available on the support site.
SYS403.Description: The operation cannot be successfully completed because the resource identified in the message does not exist.

ENC11.Resolution: Make sure that the service tag was changed under authorized circumstances.
ENC11.Description: An enclosure service tag was changed. In most circumstances, this service tag should only be changed by the service provider.

PWR8582.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because Max Power Conservation Mode is enabled.
PWR8582.Resolution: Disable the Max Power Conservation Mode and retry the operation.
PWR8582.Description: Unable to turn on the server identified in the message because the Max Power Conservation Mode (MPCM) is enabled. After MPCM is enabled, the chassis will be in power conservation mode and the CMC cannot process any further server power on operation requests.

RAC0906.Description: Unable to perform the requested operation.
RAC0906.Resolution: Try again later. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method.

ASR0000.Description: The operating system or potentially an application failed to communicate to the baseboard management controller (BMC) within the timeout period.
ASR0000.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.

SWC8606.Message: Quick Deploy Profile: Timeout exceeded while waiting for remote services ready on Server %1.
SWC8606.Resolution: Make sure that the iDRAC on the server identified in the message is operating properly and that Lifecycle Controller is enabled, then retry the operation. If the issue persists, perform a virtual reseat of the server and retry the operation. The server can be virtually reseated by using the CMC Web UI interface and selecting Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components and then select Virtual Reseat from the drop down operation for the server identified in the message.
SWC8606.Description: The server identified in the message never reported that remote services were ready.

RAC1164.Description: A remote diagnostics operation is already under execution and another operation can be started only after the current execution is completed.
RAC1164.Resolution: Initiate another diagnostics operation only after the currently running operation is completed.
RAC1164.Message: A remote diagnostics operation is currently running and not completed.

PWR2212.Message: The system is in legacy OFF state.

PWR2401.Description: The iDRAC controller detected that the power management firmware did not initialize properly. The system may operate in a performance degraded state.
PWR2401.Resolution: 1) Disconnect system input power, wait one minute, reconnect system input power.2) Re-flash system BIOS.3) Upgrade system BIOS to the latest revision.

SYS432.Description: The Power Cap value cannot be set because the PowerCapSetting feature is disabled.
SYS432.Resolution: Enable the PowerCapSetting feature by using the PATCH operation on the Redfish OemAttributes URL, and then retry the operation.
SYS432.Message: Unable to set the Power Cap value because the PowerCapSetting feature is disabled.

AMP0307.Message: Disk drive bay %1 current is less than the lower critical threshold.
AMP0307.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.

USR0153.Message: Logging off the remote VNC session from the IP address %1, because the session timed out.
USR0153.Resolution: To re-establish the remote VNC session, log in again using the VNC client.
USR0153.Description: The VNC client is logged off from the IP address identified in the message.

FAN0013.Message: %1 RPM is less than the lower critical threshold.
FAN0013.Resolution: Remove and re-install the cooling device. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0013.Description: The cooling device is not performing optimally. The cooling device may be installed improperly.

HWC6004.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
HWC6004.Description: Information and status from the controller is unavailable.

RAC049.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of lack of memory or file space in the iDRAC.
RAC049.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and retry the operation.

HWC2013.Message: Fabric mismatch corrected on fabric %1 with server in slot %2.

BAR019.Description: A system profile backup file validation is in progress.
BAR019.Message: Validating Restore operation, allow several minutes for this to complete.

RAC0667.Description: This setting will be applied after the server has been turned off and turned on again. This may result in loss of configuration and/or access physical disk drive(s) or virtual disk(s) being marked offline. This may also result in some disk(s) being identified as foreign disks. Foreign physical disk drive(s) or virtual disk(s) can be imported or cleared.
RAC0667.Message: This setting will be applied after the server has been turned off and turned on again. This may result in loss of configuration and/or access to physical disk drive(s).

RAC1168.Description: The RACADM "getconfig" command will be deprecated in a future version of iDRAC firmware.
RAC1168.Resolution: Run the RACADM "racadm get" command to retrieve the iDRAC configuration parameters. For more information on the get command, run the RACADM command "racadm help get".
RAC1168.Message: The RACADM "getconfig" command will be deprecated in a future version of iDRAC firmware.

BAR021.Description: The system profile export could not complete successfully as there is insufficient space on the network share or connectivity was lost.
BAR021.Resolution: Delete files to free up 384 MB of space on the current network share, or specify another destination that has enough space.

RAC1110.Description: Unable to run the command, because an incorrect Proxy port number was entered. The Proxy port value must be a positive integer.
RAC1110.Resolution: Enter only numbers for a Proxy port value.
RAC1110.Message: Unable to run the command, because an incorrect Proxy port number was entered.

FAN902.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode cannot be set because required power is not available.
FAN902.Resolution: Add PSUs with higher power capability or remove Chassis components such as I/O Modules or servers until the power requirements have been lowered enough to enable the Enhanced Cooling Mode, and then retry the operation.
FAN902.Message: Cannot enable the Enhanced Cooling Mode because sufficient power is not available.

DIS011.Description: Customer provided client certificate is being used. Auto Discovery client is using this certificate for the SSL connection with the Provisioning Server.
DIS011.Message: Auto Discovery client using customer signed client certificate.

STOR063.Description: In order to prevent data loss, the system has prevented the assignment of a Virtual Disk to multiple Virtual Adapters because the clustered assignment mode is not enabled.
STOR063.Resolution: Enable clustered assignment mode or unassign the virtual disk from the Virtual Adapter it is currently assigned to and retry the operation.
STOR063.Message: Unable to assign the specified virtual disk to multiple Virtual Adapters in single assignment mode.

SYS278.Description: The factory-assigned MAC address of iDRAC is restored which may cause the iDRAC to restart in some situations. iDRAC is restarted by using a factory default MAC address that can potentially change the DHCP assigned iDRAC IP address.
SYS278.Resolution: No response action is required. However, if this message is displayed multiple times indicating that the MAC address of iDRAC is restored to factory default, contact your service provider.
SYS278.Message: The factory assigned MAC address of iDRAC is restored which may cause the iDRAC to restart in some situations.

PDR78.Message: %1 state changed from Non-RAID to READY.
PDR78.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RED079.Message: The input value entered for the parameter %1 is invalid.
RED079.Resolution: Verify the value for the parameter identified in the message is valid and retry the operation.
RED079.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an invalid value for the parameter identified in the message.

RAC0249.Description: The vFlash partition is in-use by another process. Therefore, the current operation cannot proceed.
RAC0249.Resolution: Try the operation after a few minutes. If the problem persists, reset iDRAC and repeat the operation.
RAC0249.Message: One or more partitions are in-use by another process.

SWC8562.Description: All of the specified MAC addresses are deactivated from the Virtual MAC Address Pool.
SWC8562.Message: All of the specified MAC addresses are deactivated from the Virtual MAC Address Pool of Boot Identity profile operations.

RAC0501.Description: Physical disks cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the host system is powered off or the physical disks are removed. This may result in communication loss while retrieving controller data.
RAC0501.Resolution: 1. Check if the host system is powered off or shutdown. 2. Check if the physical disks are inserted into the enclosure or attached to the backplane. 3. There are no out-of-band capable controllers detected.
RAC0501.Message: There are no physical disks to be displayed.

VLT0101.Message: Processor module %1 voltage is less than the lower critical threshold.
VLT0101.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Remove the processor module. Inspect processor socket for bent pins. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0101.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

SYS146.Description: Starting secure erase-capable drive erase operations because of a System Erase operation request.
SYS146.Message: Starting secure erase-capable drive erase operations.

BAR011.Description: Hardware Inventory data collection and export did not complete successfully.
BAR011.Resolution: Enter system services to enter Unified Server Configurator (USC), and select exit and reboot option in USC to instantiate the database, if Collect System Inventory on Restart (CSIOR) is not enabled. If the hardware inventory database is present, restart the Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC)and retry.
BAR011.Message: Unable to collect Hardware Inventory information.

SUP015.Description: One of the parameters specified received a NULL value that prevented the action from completing.
SUP015.Resolution: Correct the parameter value and retry the command.
SUP015.Message: Input parameters values should not be NULL.

RAC0274.Description: If the Enable NIC checkbox is cleared, remote access to iDRAC is disabled.
RAC0274.Resolution: See iDRAC user documentation for more information on using racadm.
RAC0274.Message: See the iDRAC user documentation for more information on using the Racadm utility or the serial interface.

STOR044.Description: One or more physical disks specified to create virtual disk (VD) is not valid because it is not part of the same disk group.
STOR044.Resolution: Enumerate existing virtual disks to find the physical disks of the same disk group. Specify physical disks that are of the same disk group and retry the operation.
STOR044.Message: All physical disks specified are not part of the same disk group.

USR0007.Description: UserID closing session from IP Address.

HWC0011.Description: The USB drive does not have sufficient free space to copy the file.
HWC0011.Resolution: Make sure the USB drive has sufficient free space before retrying the operation.
HWC0011.Message: Insufficient space to copy the file to the USB drive.

SYS057.Description: The current system configuration is being collected and the Server Configuration Profile is being generated.

SUP1907.Resolution: Reacquire the image from the original source and retry the operation.

VLT0219.Message: The %1 voltage is less than the lower critical threshold.
VLT0219.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0219.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

IPA0004.Description: Invalid parameters passed to the function.

SWC8552.Message: The server in slot %1 does not have a profile associated with it.
SWC8552.Description: The server in slot identified in the message does not have a profile associated with it.

PDR74.Description: A user cancelled the copyback operation.

STOR075.Description: The requested operation could not be completed because there is an operation pending to change the enclosure configuration mode (Split or Unified). This operation is exclusive because it involves changing the RAID backplane topology.
STOR075.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Create a job to complete the pending enclosure mode change request operation, allow the job to complete, restart the server, and then retry the operation. 2) Cancel any pending operations on the RAID controller, and then retry the operation.
STOR075.Message: The operation cannot be performed because the enclosure configuration mode (Split or Unified) change request is pending.

SWC0283.Description: The value given for the object is not valid.
SWC0283.Resolution: Enter a valid value for the corresponding object.
SWC0283.Message: The specified object value is not valid.

BAR115.Description: The number of Automatic Server Profile backup files has reached the specified limit. Restarting the numbering from 1 which will overwrite the oldest backup file.
BAR115.Message: The number of Automatic Server Profile backup files has reached the specified limit. Restarting the numbering from 1.

RED080.Message: The required parameter %1 is not present.
RED080.Resolution: Verify that all required parameters for the method are present and retry the operation.
RED080.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because the required parameters identified in the message is not present in the method invocation.

AMP0319.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0319.Message: Chassis power level current is less than the lower critical threshold.

PST0194.Description: System BIOS could not configure the Remote Access controller This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST exception code C2).
PST0194.Resolution: Cycle input power and power on the system. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

OSD4.Description: Driver Pack partition in Lifecycle Controller is not accessible. The Lifecycle Controller or the iDRAC might be unresponsive.
OSD4.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and rerun the command. If the command fails again, check if the iDRAC is functional and accessible on the system.
OSD4.Message: Cannot access Lifecycle Controller Driver Pack partition.

SEL1207.Message: An entry was removed from auxiliary log.

UEFI0006.Description: A CPU double fault exception (type 0x08) occurred.
UEFI0006.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.

LIC006.Description: The license end date has been reached.
LIC006.Resolution: Obtain a replacement license and import it.

JCP028.Description: An install or configuration job status is successfully updated on iDRAC.

SUP1908.Resolution: Reacquire the image from the original source and retry the operation.

NIC004.Resolution: Verify that parameter values passed to the method are entered as they appear in the enumeration and parameter data type matches the documentation.
NIC004.Description: The value for the specified parameter is invalid.

SWC4013.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility was corrected between %1%2 and %3%4.
SWC4013.Description: A firmware or software incompatibility was corrected between the components identified in the message.

USR0176.Message: The Front Panel USB Port Over Current condition is cleared for the attached device Disk.USBFront.%1.
USR0176.Description: The Front Panel USB Port Over Current condition is cleared for the port identified in the message.

RAC0647.Description: The job could not be successfully scheduled, because an invalid value is entered for 'week of the month' while scheduling a job.
RAC0647.Resolution: Enter a correct value from 1 to 4, and then retry the operation.
RAC0647.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid value is entered for the 'week of the month'.

SEL1308.Description: The system has failed to boot to an operating system and needs the user to select a boot source. (IPMI sensor type code 1eh - offset 04h).
SEL1308.Resolution: Select boot source within the time allowed.
SEL1308.Message: A time-out occurred while waiting for user to select a boot source.

VFL0708.Message: SD card is busy with another operation and could not be initialized.

BAT1006.Message: The battery on %1 learn cycle will start in %2 days.
BAT1006.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PDR33.Message: A dedicated hot spare has been removed. %1
PDR33.Resolution: Verify that the disk is healthy and installed. Check the cables. Refer to the product documentation and see the Cables Attached Correctly section for more information on checking the cables. If necessary, replace the disk and reassign the dedicated hot spare.
PDR33.Description: The controller cannot to communicate with a disk that is assigned as a dedicated hot spare. The disk either failed or was removed. There may also be a bad or loose cable.

PSU0003.Message: The power input for power supply %1 is lost.
PSU0003.Resolution: Verify the input source is attached to the power supply. Verify the input power is within the operating requirements for the power supply.
PSU0003.Description: The power supply is installed correctly but an input source is not connected or is not functional.

TMP8500.Message: I/O Module %1 temperature exceeded operating range.
TMP8500.Resolution: Check the chassis event log for fan issues and fix any issues present. If no fan issues are detected, check chassis ambient temperature and make sure the temperature is within operating range. Utilize the RACADM command "racadm getsensorinfo" to check the chassis ambient temperature.
TMP8500.Description: The temperature of the I/O Module identified in the message has increased beyond the operational range. Thermal protection shut down the I/O Module. Factors external to the I/O Module may have caused this situation.

SYS150.Message: Starting System Erase operation. Job ID: %1
SYS150.Description: A System Erase job with the job ID identified in the message is initiated.

SWC4007.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility was corrected between system BIOS in slot %1 and CMC.

SYS430.Description: The operation is successfully completed. The configuration changes will become effective after restarting the host server next time.
SYS430.Resolution: No response action is required.However, to make them immediately effective, restart the host server.

ENC18.Resolution: Make sure the cables are attached securely. See the storage hardware documentation for more information on checking the cables. Reboot the system.
ENC18.Description: The controller has lost communication with an Enclosure Management Module (EMM). The cables may be loose or defective.

RAC0561.Description: iDRAC lost connection with CMC proxy component that enables agent free monitoring of PCIe slots. Agent free monitoring will not be supported for Chassis PCIe slots while this connection is not functioning.
RAC0561.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Check the Lifecycle Log for the subsequent RAC0562 communications restored message that will indicate the link was re-established automatically. 2) If there is no subsequent RAC0562 message in the Lifecycle Log, restart the iDRAC. The iDRAC can be restarted by using the RACADM command line utility and entering "racadm racreset". 3) After the iDRAC has restarted, if the communications link is still not functioning, restart the CMC and check the Lifecycle Log for this link error after the CMC has restarted. 4) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC0561.Message: iDRAC to CMC communication link is not functioning for agent free monitoring of chassis PCIe slots.

SWC0085.Description: Integrated Data Center Mode is disabled because of one of the following reasons: 1) The feature was disabled 2) The server is not supported for the Integrated Data Center solution 3) The default user credentials on the iDRAC were changed 4) Suppression of the default credentials warning was selected.
SWC0085.Message: The Integrated Data Center mode is disabled.

RAC0606.Description: The selected network connection test operation was successful.
RAC0606.Message: The network connection test operation was successful.

SWC0063.Description: The share name and login credentials provided are incorrect.
SWC0063.Resolution: Enter the correct share name and login credentials, and retry the operation.
SWC0063.Message: Unable to authenticate the login credentials and share name.

SWC0112.Description: A network time-out occurred while trying to perform the power action.
SWC0112.Message: Timeout while waiting for server to perform requested power action.

CMC8509.Message: Unable to activate the extended storage feature on the secondary CMC: %1. The feature will be deactivated.
CMC8509.Resolution: Do one of the following, and retry the operation: 1) In the CMC Web interface, go to Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration and verify if the card on the secondary CMC displays errors. 2) Do a failover and then reprovision the card from the same GUI page. Reprovisioning is only allowed on the card of primary CMC. However, if both the options 1 and 2 fail, the card may be no longer functional.
CMC8509.Description: The extended storage feature is not activated if the media on the secondary CMC is no longer functional.

CTL52.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes. The text for this alert is generated by the controller and can vary depending on the situation.

IOID002.Description: After the I/O Identity optimization feature is disabled, the time during boot to configure I/O Identity attributes using the Server Configuration Profile (Configuration XML) import feature will increase.
IOID002.Message: The Input/Output Identity (I/O Identity) optimization feature is disabled.

CMC8567.Message: The DVD drive is mapped to the server slot %1.
CMC8567.Description: The DVD drive is mapped to the server slot specified in the message.

RAC0604.Description: The system inventory may not be up-to-date because the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled. The CSIOR feature retrieves detailed system inventory information during system startup and stores this information on iDRAC.
RAC0604.Resolution: Enable CSIOR, restart the system and retry the operation. To enable CSIOR, press F2 (System Setup) during system startup, navigate to iDRAC Settings >Lifecycle Controller, and select the Enabled option for Collect System Inventory on Restart.
RAC0604.Message: System inventory may not be up-to-date because Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) is disabled.

SWC8613.Message: Unable to fully extract %1 boot list settings from the profile.
SWC8613.Resolution: Recreate the profile or use a different profile.
SWC8613.Description: The selected profile does not contain setting information for the boot list identified in the message in a usable format.

UEFI0107.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.
UEFI0107.Resolution: Remove input power to the system, reseat the DIMM module and restart the system. If the issues persist, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0107.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on the memory slot identified in the message. The error occurred during Read DQ/DQS initialization.

SYS128.Description: Unable to generate a zip archive of the OS and Application Data report.
SYS128.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SYS128.Message: OS Collector: Unable to generate a zip archive of the OS and Application Data report.

UEFI0162.Description: An incompatibility has been detected between an installed memory buffer and the downstream DDR channel design.
UEFI0162.Message: A 3 DIMM Per Channel (DPC) configuration has been detected on a 2 DPC memory buffer.

RAC976.Description: The configuration XML file export operation was initiated.
RAC976.Resolution: Use the racadm jobqueue view i <Job ID> command to view the status of the operation.
RAC976.Message: Export configuration XML file operation initiated.

SWC0073.Description: The Repurpose or Retire system operation cannot be successfully started because the current version of iDRAC firmware does not support the operation.
SWC0073.Resolution: Update iDRAC firmware to the latest version and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC0073.Message: Unable to start operation with the current iDRAC version.

PSU8523.Message: PSU %1 reported input over current fault and has been turned off.
PSU8523.Resolution: 1) Verify system load is within PSU capacity and no short circuits are present in the system. 2) Remove AC power and reapply power to the PSU to get it functional again. 3) If the issue persists, contact technical support.
PSU8523.Description: The power supply unit (PSU) identified in the message was turned off because the input over current fault occurred.

PWR222.Description: The Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature is already enabled.
PWR222.Message: The Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature is already enabled.

STOR3.Message: CEM Storage Management has lost communication with the %1.
STOR3.Resolution: Reboot the system or iDRAC. If the problem is not resolved, contact technical support.
STOR3.Description: Storage Management has lost communication with a controller. This may occur if the connectivity between the controller and iDRAC is disrupted or any underlying hardware problems are encountered.

FCD8500.Message: Unable to apply the %1 configuration. The affected servers (slot %2) are not turned off.
FCD8500.Resolution: Turn off the server and retry the operation.
FCD8500.Description: The server specified in the message must be turned off or the server slot must be empty before changing the FlexAddress configuration.

UEFI0094.Message: Unsupported Non-ECC memory module is installed on memory slot: %1.
UEFI0094.Resolution: Remove all Non-ECC DIMMs and replace them with ECC DIMMs. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0094.Description: Unsupported Non-ECC memory module is installed on the memory slot identified in the message.

PWR213.Description: Cannot enable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) mode because the Max Power Conservation Mode (MPCM) is enabled.
PWR213.Resolution: Disable the Max Power Conservation Mode and retry the operation.
PWR213.Message: Cannot enable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) mode because the Max Power Conservation Mode (MPCM) is enabled.

SYS170.Description: The SHA256 Hash value and the clear text value for an iDRAC user password cannot be used at the same time for a password configuration operation.
SYS170.Resolution: Make sure that the user password is configured using either the clear text or the SHA256 Hash, but not both.
SYS170.Message: The SHA256 Hash value and the clear text value for an iDRAC user password cannot be entered together.

PWR2262.Description: The Intel Management Engine is unable to utilize the PECI over DMI facility.
PWR2262.Resolution: Look for the PWR2264 "normal system operation" message in the Lifecycle Log after the PWR2262 entry. It may take 30 seconds for the message to be logged. If the PWR2264 message does not appear, do the following: Disconnect power from the server and reconnect power. Turn on the server. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR2262.Message: The Intel Management Engine has reported an internal system error.

BIOS030.Description: The BIOS password cannot be configured because an Import Server Profile operation is already running.
BIOS030.Resolution: Wait until the current import operation is completed, and then retry the operation.
BIOS030.Message: Unable to change the BIOS password because an Import Server Profile operation is already running.

PWR8536.Description: Server Performance Over Power Redundancy is enabled.
PWR8536.Message: Server Performance Over Power Redundancy is enabled.

SWC0043.Description: The Import Server Profile operation has completed with errors. For more information, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0043.Resolution: Exit the Import Server Profile wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, do the following: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait for five seconds. 3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0043.Message: Import Server Profile operation completed with errors.

SWC0237.Description: The key text in the public key specified is corrupt.
SWC0237.Resolution: Request for a valid public key from the system and re-try the command.
SWC0237.Message: Key text appears to be corrupted.

PR20.Description: The specified job is in progress.

UEFI0077.Description: One or more PCIe device errors occurred in the previous boot.
UEFI0077.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the PCIe device with errors, and then update its firmware.
UEFI0077.Message: One or more PCIe device errors occurred in the previous boot.

VF033.Description: The specified format type is not a valid type.
VF033.Resolution: Try a format type that is supported.

RAC0728.Description: The Quick Sync communication or the connection to the iDRAC is no longer functioning.
RAC0728.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove and reseat the bezel. 2) Turn the bezel on by pressing the activation button. 3) Try the Quick Sync feature again. If the issue persists, contact your technical support provider.
RAC0728.Message: The Quick Sync communication is no longer functioning.

ENC21.Description: A device has been removed and the system is no longer functioning in optimal condition.

VF051.Description: The copying partition operation did not complete successfully.
VF051.Message: Export partition operation did not complete successfully.

RED002.Description: Package has been successfully downloaded. The Job Scheduler will schedule it at the time specified.
RED002.Resolution: Schedule the job if it is not already scheduled.

MEM1008.Message: Memory device at location %1 is offline.

DH008.Description: Unable to save the provided client certificate to internal persistent storage.
DH008.Resolution: Try again. If the error persists, use RACADM command racresetcfg to clear the issue.
DH008.Message: There was a problem saving the certificate to persistent storage.

VFL0711.Description: An error occurred while initializing the SD card because the SD card write-protection feature is enabled.
VFL0711.Resolution: Move the SD card write-protection tab to the disabled position and try again.
VFL0711.Message: SD card is write-protected and could not be initialized.

BAT1025.Message: %1 is unable to recover cached data from the Battery Backup Unit (BBU).
BAT1025.Resolution: Verify that the battery is charged and in good health. See the hardware documentation for more information. When the battery charge is unacceptably low, the battery cannot maintain cached data. Data loss may also have occurred, restoring data from backups may be needed. Verify whether the battery has met its recharge limit. The battery may need to be recharged. Contact technical support if the issue persists.
BAT1025.Description: The controller was unable to recover data from the cache. This may indicate data loss has occurred.

PST0081.Description: System is at F1/F2 prompt because the system BIOS was unable to detect a bootable device.
PST0081.Resolution: Make sure a bootable device is attached to the system and enabled in BIOS setup. If device is attached and enabled, remove and reapply power to server. If the problem persists, contact your service provider. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

PWR2400.Description: The power management firmware cannot reduce power consumption to meet configuration or user defined settings.
PWR2400.Resolution: 1) Review system power policy.2) Check system event logs for thermal or power related exceptions.
PWR2400.Message: Power management firmware unable to maintain power limit.

SYS412.Description: The file cannot be uploaded because of unknown internal issues.
SYS412.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC, and then retry the operation. Reset the iDRAC by using the "Manager Reset Actions" Redfish API.
SYS412.Message: Unable to upload the file because of unknown internal issues.

BAR076.Description: The collection and export of Lifecycle Controller Configuration Database failed.
BAR076.Resolution: Enter System Services in USC, and select Exit and Reboot to reset and update the database. If the error continues repair the Lifecycle Controller, apply the Dell Update Packages for USC, diagnostics, device firmware and driver pack and retry the operation.
BAR076.Message: Unable to collect the Configuration database.

BAT1031.Message: The battery temperature on %1 is above normal.
BAT1031.Resolution: Verify that the room temperature is normal and that fans are functioning properly. See the storage hardware documentation for acceptable operating temperatures.
BAT1031.Description: The room temperature may be too hot. In addition, the system fan may be degraded or failed.

SEL0012.Description: If the system event log failed to initialize platform status and failure events are not captured. Some management software will not report platform exceptions.
SEL0012.Resolution: Reboot the management controller or iDRAC. Cycle system input power. If problem persists call support.
SEL0012.Message: Could not create or initialize the system event log.

PDR1001.Message: Fault detected on drive %1 in disk drive bay %2.
PDR1001.Resolution: Remove and reseat the failed drive. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PDR1001.Description: The controller detected a failure on the disk and has taken the disk offline.

MEM0700.Message: The persistent correctable memory error rate is at normal levels for a memory device at location %1.

SYS086.Description: Unable to copy the ePSA Diagnostics results file to the specified network share.
SYS086.Resolution: If the results are being exported to an NFS share, make sure that the network share is accessible from iDRAC. If the results are being exported to a CIFS share, make sure that the network share is accessible from iDRAC using the specified share access credentials.
SYS086.Message: Unable to copy the ePSA Diagnostics results file to the network share.

UEFI0085.Description: One or more chipset errors have occurred.
UEFI0085.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the chipset error. Do one of the following: 1) Turn off the input power to the system and turn on again. 2) Update the PCIe device firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0085.Message: One or more chipset errors have occurred.

RAC0206.Description: Certificate upload failed because this is not a certificate file.
RAC0206.Message: Certificate upload failed: Not a certificate file.

ENC28.Message: Enclosure Management Module (EMM) firmware version mismatch detected in %1.%2 %3.
ENC28.Resolution: Upgrade to the same version of the firmware on both EMM modules and then powercycle the system and attached enclosures.
ENC28.Description: The firmware on the EMM modules is not the same version. Both modules must have the same firmware version. This message is caused when you attempt to insert an EMM module that has a different firmware version than an existing module.

OSD32.Description: Cannot continue with DetachISOImage because the system does not have an attached ISO image.
OSD32.Resolution: The call to DetachISOImage is unnecessary since the ISO image is not currently attached.

UEFI0144.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.
UEFI0144.Resolution: Remove input power to the system, reseat the DIMM module and restart the system. If the issues persist, replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0144.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot identified in the message. The error happens during the identification of memory module type or memory size.

UEFI0157.Description: The request to reset BIOS to default settings is successfully completed.
UEFI0157.Message: The iDRAC request to reset BIOS to default settings is successfully completed.

PST0138.Description: System BIOS detected a failure with the SIO. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST code exception code 8A).
PST0138.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

BAR032.Description: The system profile backup file validation did not complete successfully.
BAR032.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) An incorrect passphrase may have been entered, correct the input and retry the operation. 2) Download a valid backup image of the host system and retry. 3) Reboot the Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC) and retry. 4) Download a new firmware image for the iDRAC and retry.

PWR8684.Message: Storage sled controller %1 in slot %2 turned on successfully.
PWR8684.Description: The storage sled controller in the slot identified in the message turned on successfully.

RAC0675.Description: Results are not available for the search criterion entered.
RAC0675.Resolution: Enter another criterion and retry the operation.
RAC0675.Message: Results are not available for the search criterion entered.

BAT0000.Description: System settings may be preserved if input power is not removed from the power supplies.
BAT0000.Resolution: Check the system board battery at the next service window.
BAT0000.Message: The system board battery is low.

OSD5.Description: A Driver Pack was not found on the Lifecycle Controller.
OSD5.Resolution: Update the Driver Pack using USC or DUP and then run the command again.
OSD5.Message: Lifecycle Controller Driver Pack not found.

SUP0526.Description: Unable to continue the firmware update because the catalog file or the update package is corrupt.
SUP0526.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, download the latest Update Package or Catalog file from your service provider and retry the operation.
SUP0526.Message: Unable to continue with firmware update.

UEFI0238.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0238.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0238.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Write DQ/DQS Training - Calibration phase.

BAR093.Description: The attempt to disconnect from the specified CIFS location was not successful.
BAR093.Resolution: If this happens on a backup request, restart the Integrated Remote Access Controller and try the operation again. If this is a restore request the Integrated Remote Access will be restarted during the execution of the request. Only restart the Integrated Remote Access Controller if it does not restart on its own.

SWU8549.Description: The firmware update process of Active CMC and Standby CMC was not successful, because of a firmware image checksum error.
SWU8549.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8549.Message: Unable to update the firmware of Standby CMC and Active CMC. The checksum process was not successful.

RAC0512.Description: Virtual disks cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the host system is powered off, no virtual disks were created, or incorrect filters are applied.
RAC0512.Resolution: 1. Check if the host system is ON. 2. Check if virtual disks are created. 3. Check if correct filters are applied. 4. Check if the Storage Enclosure is ON. 5. Verify that the adapter cables are properly connected and there are no bent pins.
RAC0512.Message: There are no virtual disks to be displayed.

BOOT004.Description: An invalid number of source arguments was passed to the method.
BOOT004.Message: Invalid number of Boot Source arguments

LIC018.Description: The license is already imported on the system and does not need to be reimported.

PWR8531.Description: Server Based Power Management Mode is enabled.
PWR8531.Message: Server Based Power Management Mode is enabled.

SWC1926.Description: The iDRAC Quick Sync interface is enabled.
SWC1926.Message: The iDRAC Quick Sync interface is enabled.

CBL8500.Message: SAS cable %1 to expander %2 is not connected.
CBL8500.Resolution: Check whether or not the SAS cables are connected to the expander. Reconnect the cables and retry the operation.
CBL8500.Description: SAS cables are not connected to the expander correctly.

LIC207.Resolution: Obtain and import a replacement license.
LIC207.Description: The license has expired. This could result in the loss of functionality that is specific to the features supported by the license.

LOG007.Message: The previous log entry was repeated %1 times.
LOG007.Description: This message is generated after a series of sequential duplicate events. Log entry count is the number of times the previous message was repeated.

USR8502.Description: The operation to close a user session using the session ID identified in the message was successful.

SUP0111.Message: Timeout waiting for firmware update process to complete.

MEM0701.Message: Correctable memory error rate exceeded for %1.
MEM0701.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem continues, contact support.
MEM0701.Description: The memory may not be operational. This an early indicator of a possible future uncorrectable error.

LC003.Description: An error occurred while trying to set the firmware update mode.
LC003.Resolution: Verify that the firmware version supports this mode. Also confirm that the command and parameters are correct. The parameter choices are: 1) Disable (default) 2) Allow version upgrade only 3) Match firmware of replaced part.
LC003.Message: Failed to change the firmware update mode.

CTL35.Message: A foreign configuration was imported on %1.
CTL35.Resolution: Verify the foreign configuration was successfully imported by viewing the virtual disks and hot spares. See the hardware documentation for more information.
CTL35.Description: The operation to import foreign configuration (virtual disks, host spares, and so on) completed successfully.

ISM0028.Description: The iDRAC Hard Reset operation cannot be performed either because of an unsupported CPLD firmware version or the iDRAC Hard reset feature is currently disabled on iDRAC.
ISM0028.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Update the CPLD version by using iDRAC graphical user interface (GUI). 2) To enable the iDRAC Hard Reset feature by running RACADM command, enter the following at the command line interface (CLI): "racadm set idrac.servicemodule.idrachardreset enabled".
ISM0028.Message: Unable to perform the iDRAC Hard Reset operation either because of an unsupported CPLD firmware version or the iDRAC Hard Reset feature is currently disabled on iDRAC.

LC037.Description: Lifecycle Controller is locked by another instance of Lifecycle Controller Log Export operation. Wait for that operation to complete before attempting to run another command.
LC037.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Wait approximately 2 minutes and retry the operation. 2) Reset iDRAC and retry the operation.
LC037.Message: An instance of Lifecycle Controller Log Export is already running.

TMP7.Description: A device has been failed and the system is no longer functioning in optimal condition.

OSD33.Description: The system has an older version of BIOS that does not support this method. Install the latest version of BIOS to use this method.
OSD33.Resolution: Update the BIOS to version 1.2 or later and then rerun the command.
OSD33.Message: Installed BIOS version does not support this method.

RAC007.Description: The attribute value is outside the acceptable range.
RAC007.Resolution: Enter a value within the range and retry the operation. For more information about the acceptable range, refer to the Dell Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Quick Start Guide and DCIM Profile Documents available at the support site.
RAC007.Message: The attribute value is outside the acceptable range.

SWC8506.Description: The Profile identified in the message has been deleted.

ENC25.Resolution: Verify the health of the enclosure and its components. See the storage hardware documentation for more information. Contact technical support.
ENC25.Description: The enclosure or an enclosure component is in a Failed or Degraded state.

UEFI0066.Message: A PCIe link training failure is observed in %1 and the link is disabled. The system has halted.
UEFI0066.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Turn off the input power to the system and turn on again. 2) Update the PCIe device firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0066.Description: A PCIe Link failure is observed in the device identified in the message and device link is disabled. The system will be halted.

PSU8520.Description: The Dynamic Power Supply Engagement feature is supported and fully operational.
PSU8520.Message: Enhanced Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) is fully supported.

USR0018.Description: There are no active sessions on the iDRAC which can be displayed.

UEFI0210.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0210.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0210.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Receive Buffer Vref Training phase.

SYS410.Description: The attribute cannot be modified because the attribute is read-only and depends on other attributes. Some attributes have dependencies on other attributes that are required to perform a task. However, some of the attributes are read-only because of the current system configuration and the values of the dependent attributes.
SYS410.Resolution: Verify if the attribute has dependency on other attributes and retry the operation. To verify, view the attribute registry based on the type of resource.
SYS410.Message: Unable to modify the attribute because the attribute is read-only and depends on other attributes.

STOR0104.Description: No virtual disk data to display. The system is powered off, physical disks are not present on the system, or virtual disks are not created.
STOR0104.Resolution: Check if the server has power, physical disks are available, and virtual disks are created.

VFL0713.Resolution: Detach the partitions and try again.
VFL0713.Message: One or more partitions are currently attached; the SD card could not be initialized.

LC033.Description: The Hardware Inventory XML file representing the system configuration as shipped from the factory was successful.
LC033.Message: As-Shipped Hardware Inventory export was successful.

PDR75.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

BAR047.Description: The System Profile operation was canceled as part of a clean up operation performed during a restart of the Integrated Remote Access Controller.
BAR047.Message: System Profile operation canceled by user.

PWR220.Message: The Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature cannot be enabled because slot %1 is empty.
PWR220.Resolution: Insert an appropriate PSU in the slot identified in the message and retry the operation.
PWR220.Description: The Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature cannot be enabled because the slot identified in the message is empty.

BIOS010.Description: For 11G systems: System Services must be enabled to perform the requested operation. System Services has been disabled through the iDRAC configuration utility accessed by pressing CTRL+E on boot up or through a remote operation. For 12G and above generations: Lifecycle Controller must be enabled to perform the requested operation. Lifecycle Controller has been disabled by pressing F2 Setup, selecting iDRAC Configuration, and selecting Lifecycle Controller Settings on boot up or through a remote operation.
BIOS010.Resolution: For 11G systems: Use the iDRAC configuration utility to enable the System Services by pressing on the CTRL+E option on boot up at the targeted system. For 12G and above generations: Use F2 Setup, select iDRAC Configuration, and select Lifecycle Controller Settings, to enable the Lifecycle Controller on boot up of the targeted system.
BIOS010.Message: Lifecycle Controller is not enabled, cannot create Configuration job.

LIC019.Description: A leased license may not be imported prior to the actual start date of the license.
LIC019.Resolution: Import the license on or after the license start date.
LIC019.Message: A leased license may not be imported prior to its start date.

USR0170.Message: The Front Panel USB port is attached to iDRAC Disk.USBFront.%1. Device details: Device class %2, Vendor ID %3, Manufacturer Name %4, Product ID %5, Product Name %6, Serial Number %7.
USR0170.Description: The device identified in the message is connected to the Front Panel USB port and attached to the iDRAC.

RAC1067.Message: Unable to set the minimum non critical threshold value of %1, because the value entered is lesser than, or equal to the minimum critical threshold value.
RAC1067.Resolution: Check the minimum critical threshold level using an appropriate RACADM command. For example, to view the minimum threshold value of a sensor, run the 'racadm getsensorinfo' command at the command line interface, and then retry the operation. For more information about other RACADM commands, run the racadm help command.
RAC1067.Description: The minimum non critical threshold value identified in the message cannot be set, because the value entered is lesser than, or equal to the minimum critical threshold value.

PDR82.Description: Security on a secure encrypted disk was activated.

PSU8505.Description: Unable to set the chassis redundancy policy to AC Redundancy.
PSU8505.Resolution: Retry the operation using the CMC command line interface or CMC Web interface. To set the chassis redundancy policy using the command line, enter "racadm config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisRedundancyPolicy 1". To configure the chassis redundancy policy using the Web interface, click Chassis Overview > Power > Configuration. From the Redundancy drop-down menu, select AC Redundancy.
PSU8505.Message: Unable to set the chassis redundancy policy to AC Redundancy.

BAR004.Description: Hardware Inventory data is being collected and copied into the backup file.

SYS068.Description: Some configuration changes that require system reboot were not applied because the values specified in the input XML file are incorrect.
SYS068.Resolution: Use the GetConfigResults() method to get the configuration job results or export the Lifecycle Log and review the configuration job results to identify the errors. Make changes to the input XML to correct the errors. Retry the import operation.
SYS068.Message: Configuration changes that require system reboot were not applied.

SYS245.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported proxy username value.
SYS245.Resolution: Make sure that the correct proxy username value is entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS245.Description: The file cannot be transferred because a proxy username value is not entered, or the entered value is not supported.

USR8510.Description: Successful login by Username identified in the message.

DIS101.Description: The AutoConfig operation is started by iDRAC using the AutoConfig import file specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.
DIS101.Message: The execution of AutoConfig operation is started.

UEFI0262.Message: Unable to initialize DIMM modules on memory riser %1 because of a DDR training error.
UEFI0262.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM modules and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory modules identified in the message.
UEFI0262.Description: An issue is observed initializing DDR (double data rate) on the memory riser identified in the message. A possible cause is the DIMM modules are incorrectly seated in the slots.

PST0139.Description: System BIOS detected a failure with the Keyboard Controller. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST exception code 8B).
