PST0139.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

BAT1030.Message: The %1 battery charge level is normal.
BAT1030.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC1060.Description: The system inventory information may not be current because the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled.
RAC1060.Resolution: To enable the CSIOR feature, run the RACADM command "racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.CollectSystemInventoryOnRestart 1". Then restart the server to cause system inventory information to be collected.
RAC1060.Message: System inventory may not be current because the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled.

POW000.Description: Host failed to power up because chassis infrastructure is not ready. This messages has been replaced by Message ID PWR2250.
POW000.Message: Power on permission error, chassis infrastructure not ready.

SEL1516.Description: The sleds are automatically turned off because of a power button press simulation triggered by Chassis Controller. An I2C sensor in not correctly responding because of a corrupted signal in the sensor.
SEL1516.Resolution: Check the firmware version of Fan Controller Block (FCB) and make sure that the Power Supply Unit (PSU) is functional. For more information about the firmware version and PSU ratings, see PSQN SLN300669 available on the support site.
SEL1516.Message: The sleds are automatically turned off because of a power button press simulation triggered by Chassis Controller.

SUP0517.Message: Unable to update the %1 firmware to version %2.
SUP0517.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, download the latest update package from your service provider, and retry the operation.
SUP0517.Description: The firmware image specified in the operation did not apply successfully. An internal error may have occurred.

TMP0137.Description: The system cooling is working normally.
TMP0137.Message: The system cooling is working normally.

SUP0541.Message: The maximum disk space (storage capacity) for storing firmware image files is reached. The rollback firmware image file of %1 was deleted to create free disk space.
SUP0541.Description: The maximum disk space (storage capacity) for storing firmware image files is reached. The rollback firmware image file identified in the message was deleted to create free disk space.

PCI1321.Message: A high-severity issue is detected in a component of the bus %1, device 0, function %2.
PCI1321.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the component identified in the message, and then monitor the log for a re-occurrence of the issue. If the issue persists, and occurs during server startup, update the component firmware. If the issue persists and occurs during OS runtime, restart the server and update the OS drivers for the component identified in the message.
PCI1321.Description: A high-severity issue is detected in the component identified in the message.

BAR045.Description: The host system is powering down to facilitate the import of the Integrated Remote Access Controller system profile.
BAR045.Message: Powering down the Host System for Integrated Remote Access Controller Restore.

HWC1015.Resolution: If removal was unintended, check presence, then re-install or reconnect.
HWC1015.Description: The mezzanine card may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.

RED020.Description: The feature invoked is not supported by the current version of the Unified Server Configurator.
RED020.Resolution: Upgrade Unified Server Configurator to the latest available version before using this feature.
RED020.Message: Feature not supported on current version of USC.

BAT1005.Message: The battery on %1 learn cycle has been postponed.
BAT1005.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

STOR8.Description: High Availability RAID is not supported by this firmware release. This event may occur during the upgrade process.
STOR8.Message: Detected two RAID controllers in integrated slots. This configuration is not currently supported and the second controller will not be powered on.

UEFI0248.Message: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization error detected on processor %1.
UEFI0248.Resolution: Reseat all processors in the system and ensure all processors are matching. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0248.Description: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization encountered a programmatic error. A resource allocation was forced because resources were not requested for the identified processor. .

PST0091.Description: A problem was detected in Memory Reference Code (MRC). The next logged message contains more specific details for the detected issue.
PST0091.Resolution: Review the next logged message for the recommended response action to resolve the problem.
PST0091.Message: A problem was detected in Memory Reference Code (MRC).

PR31.Description: All the tasks in the Job were attempted, but some did not complete successfully.
PR31.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle Log for more details associated with this warning then retry the operation if appropriate.

PWR8580.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because the Chassis is not turned on.
PWR8580.Resolution: Turn on the Chassis, and then retry the operation. To turn on the Chassis using the Chassis Management Controller Web UI, go to Chassis Overview > Power > Control, select the Power On System option, and then click Apply.
PWR8580.Description: The power on request for the server identified in the message was not successful because the Chassis is turned off.

VF030.Description: The specified hash type is not a valid type.

PDR22.Resolution: Do the following:1) Determine why the physical disk reached an unacceptable temperature. For example, a fan failure, incorrect thermostat settings, or the room temperature may be too hot or cold. 2) Verify that the fans in the server or enclosure are working. 3) If the physical disk is in an enclosure, check the thermostat settings and examine whether the enclosure is located near a heat source. Verify the enclosure has enough ventilation and that the room temperature is not too hot. Refer to the enclosure documentation for more diagnostic information. 4) If you cannot identify why the disk has reached an unacceptable temperature, then replace the disk. If the physical disk is a member of a non-redundant virtual disk, then back up the data before replacing the disk. Removing a physical disk that is included in a non-redundant virtual disk causes the virtual disk to fail and may cause data loss.
PDR22.Description: A disk has reached an unacceptable temperature and received a SMART alert (predictive failure). The disk is likely to fail in the near future.

UEFI0018.Description: An internal error occurred. No Lifecycle Controller functionality is available while in Recovery Mode.
UEFI0018.Resolution: Repair Lifecycle Controller firmware using the Lifecycle Controller Dell Update Package (DUP) or Lifecycle Controller Repair Package via iDRAC. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.
UEFI0018.Message: Lifecycle Controller (LC) is unable to complete a requested task or function and therefore is in Recovery Mode.

UEFI0076.Description: A Corrected Machine Check error(s) has occurred.
UEFI0076.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the Corrected Machine Check (CMC) errors. Resolve the issue identified in the SEL that caused the CMC.
UEFI0076.Message: One or more Corrected Machine Check(CMC) errors have occurred.

LC022.Description: The Lifecycle Controller Log was successfully exported to the destination specified.
LC022.Message: Lifecycle Controller Log Export was successful.

LIC024.Description: The License can not be installed, deleted or replaced when the device is on.
LIC024.Resolution: Turn off the respective device and retry the License operation.
LIC024.Message: License operation did not complete successfully because the device is turned on.

RAC0904.Description: The iDRAC cannot access the remote file location. The credentials or path to the remote file location is incorrect or iDRAC cannot connect to the network address.
RAC0904.Resolution: Confirm that the path and credentials to remote file are correct, and check that the iDRAC can connect to the network address.
RAC0904.Message: The remote file location is not accessible or reachable.

TMP0111.Message: The memory module %1 temperature is within range.

PWR8551.Message: Successfully set Virtual Infrastructure Device power to %1 DC Watt.
PWR8551.Description: This will be logged when a Virtual Infrastructure Device power allocation is configured.

PDR5.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) If a physical disk was removed from the disk group, either replace the disk or restore the original disk. Identify the disk that was removed by locating the disk that has a red "X" for its status. 2) Perform a rescan after replacing or restoring the disk. 3) If a disk was not removed from the disk group, then check for cable problems. Refer to product documentation for more information on checking the cables. 4) Make sure that the enclosure is powered on. 5) If the problem persists, check the enclosure documentation for further diagnostic information.
PDR5.Description: A physical disk has been removed from the disk group. This alert can also be caused by loose or defective cables or by problems with the enclosure.

PST0192.Description: System BIOS shutdown test failed during POST. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST exception code C0).
PST0192.Resolution: Check system event log for CMOS battery exceptions. Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

CTL96.Message: %1 has entered safe mode with limited functionality due to %2
CTL96.Resolution: To resolve this issue, see Troubleshooting section in the Dell Shared PowerEdge RAID Controller (SPERC8) documentation.
CTL96.Description: The controller identified in the message has an issue as displayed in the message.

VFL1008.Message: Failure detected on Removable Flash Media %1.
VFL1008.Resolution: Re-install the flash media, if the issue persists replace the media.
VFL1008.Description: An error is reported during a SD card read or write.

PDR40.Message: The blink operation has ceased on %1.
PDR40.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

MEM1205.Message: Memory mirror redundancy is lost. Check memory device at location(s) %1.
MEM1205.Resolution: Review system logs for memory exceptions. Re-install memory at location <location>.
MEM1205.Description: The memory may not be seated correctly, misconfigured, or has failed.

LC098.Description: The server screen shot cannot be exported because the iDRAC is busy in capturing the current screen shot.
LC098.Resolution: Wait for the current process to complete and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
LC098.Message: Unable to export the server screen shot because the iDRAC is busy in capturing the current screen shot.

RAC1146.Description: The SNMPv3 username cannot be set because SNMPv3 is not enabled for the specified user on iDRAC.
RAC1146.Resolution: Enable SNMPv3 for the specified user by running the command "racadm set iDRAC.Users.<user index>.SNMPv3Enable 1", and then retry the operation.
RAC1146.Message: Unable to set the SNMPv3 username because SNMPv3 is not enabled for the specified user on iDRAC.

SWC8549.Message: The status of Media Access Control (MAC) address %1 is not valid for Boot Identity profile operations.
SWC8549.Resolution: Edit the Virtual MAC Address Pool to correct the MAC address status. Possible MAC address status values are unassign, assign and active. The value is "unassigned" if the MAC address is not used in any profile. The value is "assigned" if the MAC address used in a profile. The value is "active" if used in a profile applied to a server. The status must be same for all Virtual MAC addresses if assigned to a profile.
SWC8549.Description: The status of Media Access Control (MAC) address identified in the message is not valid. Possible MAC address status values are unassign, assign and active. The value is "unassigned" if the MAC address is not used in any profile. The value is "assigned" if the MAC address used in a profile. The value is "active" if used in a profile applied to a server. The status must be same for all Virtual MAC addresses if assigned to a profile.

BAR020.Description: The Lifecycle Controller data is being imported from the backup file.

JCP025.Description: Lifecycle Controller must be enabled to perform the requested operation. Lifecycle Controller can be enabled in the F2 Setup application or through a remote operation.
JCP025.Resolution: If Lifecycle Controller is in Recovery mode a firmware update of Lifecycle Controller may be required. To change the Lifecycle Controller mode, do the following: 1) Restart the system and press F2 to launch the System Setup application 2) Select iDRAC Configuration 3) Select Lifecycle Controller Settings to enable Lifecycle Controller.

PDR72.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

AMP0303.Message: The system board %1 current is greater than the upper critical threshold.
AMP0303.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0303.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.

RDU0017.Description: The storage system has redundant power lines. One of power lines is no longer available.
RDU0017.Resolution: Turn system off and remove AC input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. If the issue still persists, contact your service provider. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
RDU0017.Message: The storage power redundancy is no longer available.

VDR10.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC930.Description: Racadm is currently unable to obtain the inlet temperature data. This happens if there is no data populated in the temperature tables or if the instrumentation does not return valid values.
RAC930.Resolution: Wait for the instrumentation to populate the thermal tables. Retry the operation. If the problem persists, contact the service provider.
RAC930.Message: Unable to export the inlet temperature data.

SEL1306.Description: The disk in the drive is not formatted correctly or does not contain the necessary operating system files (IPMI sensor type code 1eh - offset 03h).

SWC0234.Description: The remote host specified for the ftp update is not reachable.
SWC0234.Resolution: Check the connectivity between iDRAC and the remote host used for the ftp update.
SWC0234.Message: Remote host is not reachable or connection is interrupted.

RAC002.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Rerun the command. 2) Reset iDRAC and retry the operation.

SWC0130.Description: The Trap needs to be set for the particular index for the testtrap to go through.
SWC0130.Resolution: Set cfgIpmiPetAlertEnable in cfgIpmiPet group using config subcommand for the corresponding index.
SWC0130.Message: Trap at specified index is not currently enabled.

RAC1026.Description: A custom signing certificate must be present in the system to delete or download the certificate.
RAC1026.Message: A custom signing certificate does not exist.

BAT1018.Resolution: If the battery is being charged, then charging the battery should be stopped until the battery cools down and charging should be resumed. If this is not case, then some other condition exists and should be investigated.
BAT1018.Description: The temperature of the battery is high. This may be due to the battery being charged.

JCP004.Description: The job's time window expired and the job failed to complete.
JCP004.Resolution: Retry the action and increase the time window so that the job can complete.

OSD72.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'ImageName' is missing.
OSD72.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "ImageName" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD72.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'ImageName' is missing.

VF053.Description: CreatePartitionUsingImage method cannot be completed because the URI and Share Type entered do not match.
VF053.Resolution: Make sure that the URI and Share Type match, and then retry the operation.
VF053.Message: Unable to CreatePartition because the URI and Share Type entered do not match.

SYS168.Description: The requested System Erase job cannot complete because there was another job or System Services task already in progress.
SYS168.Resolution: Wait for the job or System Services task in progress to complete before initiating a System Erase job.
SYS168.Message: Unable to complete the System Erase job because another operation is in progress.

RAC0627.Description: The job cannot be scheduled, because the requested recurrent Automatic Backup job is already scheduled.
RAC0627.Resolution: Delete the current scheduled job, and then retry to create a new Automatic Backup job with a new schedule.
RAC0627.Message: Unable to schedule, because the requested recurrent Automatic Backup job is already scheduled.

RAC0217.Description: Client did not receive a response for the login request.
RAC0217.Resolution: Try pinging the iDRAC and then try again.

SYS122.Description: The operation to collect OS and Application Data is successfully completed.
SYS122.Message: OS Collector: The operation to collect OS and Application Data is successfully completed.

STOR308.Description: The Controller is in HBA mode, RaidAction CreateAuto value is not supported.
STOR308.Resolution: In order to perform a RAID configuration operation, change the controller mode to RAID and retry the operation. For switching to RAID mode using the F2 System Setup utility, go to Device Settings > "RAID Controller "> Controller Management > Advanced Controller Management > Switch to RAID mode.
STOR308.Message: Controller is in HBA mode, RaidAction CreateAuto value is not supported.

BAR095.Description: The request to restore a System Profile from a Backup file did not complete successfully because there is already a request in progress.
BAR095.Resolution: If possible monitor the in progress job for completion and then retry the request. If that is not possible try clearing all jobs and try the request again. If the issue persists, restart the Integrated Remote Access controller and try the request again.
BAR095.Message: Another Restore operation already in progress.

BAR096.Description: The current BIOS firmware installed on the system does not have Backup and Restore feature support.
BAR096.Resolution: Obtain the System BIOS firmware with Backup and Restore support, update the system and try the operation again.

SWC0299.Description: The Email Address provided is invalid.
SWC0299.Message: The Destination Email Address is invalid.

LOG002.Message: An invalid parameter ID is entered for %1.
LOG002.Resolution: Enter the correct WS-Man parameter for the instance ID or job ID. For information about valid parameters, see the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Quick Start Guide available on the support site.
LOG002.Description: An invalid parameter ID is entered for the instance ID or job ID identified in the message.

TMP0204.Message: CPU %1 temperature is outside of range.
TMP0204.Resolution: Check system operating environment, fans, and heatsinks.

RAC0747.Description: Unable to perform reset configuration on the selected controller, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
RAC0747.Resolution: Enable the Lifecycle Controller and retry the operation. To enable Lifecycle Controller, reboot the server. During server startup, press F2 to enter System Setup. Go to iDRAC Settings -> Lifecycle Controller, select Enable, and save the changes.
RAC0747.Message: Unable to perform reset configuration on the selected controller, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

BAT1007.Message: The battery on %1 learn cycle will start in %2 hours.
BAT1007.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RFL2002.Message: Internal Dual SD Module %1 is offline.
RFL2002.Description: The SD card module is installed but may be improperly installed or configured incorrectly.

PSU8501.Message: Unable to retrieve PSU %1 input voltage information.
PSU8501.Resolution: Remove the PSU from the chassis, wait for two minutes, and reinsert it. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PSU8501.Description: Unable to retrieve input voltage information for the PSU specified in the message.

UEFI0087.Message: Unsupported 4Gb technology DIMM module is installed on memory slot: %1.
UEFI0087.Resolution: Remove the unsupported DIMM module from the identified memory slot and replace it with a supported module. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0087.Description: Unsupported 4Gb technology DIMM module is installed on the memory slot identified in the message.

MEM9013.Description: BIOS logged location information of a Memory Reference Code (MRC) warning. This information can be reviewed by using a tool which displays raw IPMI SEL data such as IPMItool with the -vvv option or RACADM with the -E option.
MEM9013.Message: Memory Reference Code (MRC) warning location information is logged.

STOR032.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to gain access to internal storage because it is in use by another application or operation.
STOR032.Resolution: Wait for current Lifecycle Controller operation to complete. Verify that the system is 1) Not currently in Lifecycle Controller Configuration utility 2) Not waiting for user intervention at F1/F2 POST error 3) Not in any of the device or controller Option ROMs and retry the operation.
STOR032.Message: Lifecycle Controller is currently in use.

STOR022.Description: The operation cannot be completed because controller is not security capable.
STOR022.Message: The controller is not security capable.

CTL19.Message: Abort CC on Error, Copyback, and Load Balance has changed for %1.
CTL19.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

UEFI0038.Description: Unable to communicate with iDRAC because an expected interrupt(s) from the iDRAC SMA (Shared Memory Architecture) interface did not happen. Continuing to boot may result in unexpected power loss because of unknown power inventory and unavailability of features such as active power management, thermal management.
UEFI0038.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware on the system.
UEFI0038.Message: Unable to communicate with iDRAC because of missing interrupts on the Shared Memory Architecture (SMA) interface.

LIC202.Description: This error can occur when:1) Platform table has invalid value for default license feature set and permissible license upgrade path. In this case, the system sets the default licensed feature set to Basic Management and does not restrict the license upgrade path.2) License Manager fails to load due to lack of system resources.
LIC202.Message: A system error was detected during License Manager startup.

CMC8579.Description: The security certificate cannot be uploaded because of an Unexpected Event issue in the Remote Access Controller.
CMC8579.Resolution: Upload the certificate again and retry operation.
CMC8579.Message: Unable to upload the security certificate because of an Unexpected Event issue in the Remote Access Controller (RAC).

UEFI0196.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.
UEFI0196.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0196.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Error Training phase.

VLT0303.Message: CPU %1 %2 voltage is greater than the upper critical threshold.
VLT0303.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0303.Description: High voltages may be the result of problem with the voltage regulator or a problem with the processor. Elevated voltages may result in damage to the processor or other system electrical components. The system may power down.

RAC955.Description: The specified record does not exist in the Lifecycle Log.
RAC955.Resolution: Run the racadm lclog view -i command to get the sequence number of the records logged in the Lifecycle Log, and retry the command with a valid sequence number.
RAC955.Message: Unable to retrieve the information related to the specified record in the Lifecycle Log.

BIOS023.Description: An unrecoverable error occurred in the operation while communicating with iDRAC.
BIOS023.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue continues, reset the iDRAC.
BIOS023.Message: Cannot perform the operation due to an unknown error in iDRAC.

CMC8604.Message: The FRU on storage sled %1 is not functioning.
CMC8604.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reinsert the specified storage sled or virtual reseat the sled 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes for the CMC to finish restarting. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8604.Description: The FRU on the storage sled specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.

SUP007.Description: The iDRAC communication channel is open and being used by another process; this can be caused by an open session of USC locally on the server.
SUP007.Resolution: If USC is in use, wait until USC has exited and retry the action. Otherwise retry after 30 seconds to check if network connectivity caused this error.

UEFI0276.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the initiator information from DHCPv6 server cannot be obtained.
UEFI0276.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Check the configuration of DHCPv6 server. 2) Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings > Connection Settings page, disable DHCP and configure the initiator information manually. Retry the operation.
UEFI0276.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the initiator information from DHCPv6 server cannot be obtained.

CMC8543.Message: The CMC %1 has reset because the thermal threshold was exceeded.
CMC8543.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Review the Hardware Log and check if there are fans that are not functioning properly. 2) Replace the fans that are not functioning properly. 3) If all the fans are functioning, check the chassis temperature in the CMC Web Interface or by using RACADM. When the fans are functioning properly and the chassis temperature is too high, the ambient air temperature is too high or the air inlets are not receiving sufficient air.
CMC8543.Description: The CMC specified in the message has reset because of thermal issues.

VDR3.Resolution: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
VDR3.Description: Data redundancy has been restored to a virtual disk that previously suffered a loss of redundancy.

RAC035.Description: There are no pending values for the any of the iDRAC attributes.
RAC035.Resolution: Make sure there are pending values for the attributes that are targeted for configuration.

UEFI0243.Message: Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) operating at reduced width on memory riser %1.
UEFI0243.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0243.Description: The Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) channel identified in the message is operating at a degraded width. This allows continued uptime although indicates an error condition requiring further investigation. This maybe an early indication of upcoming memory riser failure.

CTL83.Resolution: Restart the server. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CTL83.Description: The management controller is not communicating with the storage controller identified in the message. This may be because of any one of the following: 1) PCIe subsystem is has stopped functioning 2) An issue in the storage controller 3) An issue in the management controller.

TMP0103.Message: The system board %1 temperature is greater than the upper critical threshold.
TMP0103.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0103.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.

UEFI0099.Description: The Memory Mirroring feature cannot be enabled because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the feature.
UEFI0099.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure the Memory Mirroring feature can be supported. For more information, see platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0099.Message: Unable to enable the Memory Mirroring feature because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the feature.

SWU8550.Description: The firmware update process of Active CMC and Standby CMC was not successful.
SWU8550.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8550.Message: Unable to update the firmware of Standby CMC and Active CMC.

BAR016.Description: A system profile import operation has been requested.

FSD000.Message: Debug authorized by customer; debugcaps: %1, was authorized by: %2, at %3 for the period: %4 to %5.
FSD000.Description: The customer has authorized the specified debug capabilities on this iDRAC. (This should occur in response to a request from Dell tech support.) Each debug capability represents a certain action Dell engineers can perform to debug iDRAC.

SWC0049.Description: The Import operation cannot continue because backup image file is not present on the vFlash SD card, the image is invalid, or the entered passphrase is incorrect.
SWC0049.Resolution: Make sure that the backup image file is present on the vFlash SD card, the image is valid, and the entered passphrase is correct.
SWC0049.Message: Unable to continue the Import operation.

IOID119.Description: The FlexAddress feature is enabled on the system. The iDRAC will assign FlexAddress defined MAC and WWN values to all the ports and/or partitions of bNDCs and mezzanine adapters of the system.
IOID119.Message: FlexAddress is enabled on all NIC and FC HBA devices.

CTL32.Message: Abort CC on Error is modified for %1.
CTL32.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC0293.Description: This error is displayed when LDAP or Active Directory cannot find an associated Certificate Authority (CA) certificate.
RAC0293.Resolution: Upload a valid root Certificate Authority (CA) certificate.
RAC0293.Message: When certificate validation is enabled, a valid root Certificate Authority (CA) certificate must be uploaded. The CA certificate is used to verify the directory server SSL certificate.

SWC1928.Description: The iDRAC Quick Sync access feature is set to the read-write mode.
SWC1928.Message: The iDRAC Quick Sync access feature is set to the read-write mode.

STOR037.Resolution: Enter all the required parameters and retry the operation.
STOR037.Description: Unable to complete the requested operation because one or more input parameters identified in the message are not specified.

OSD37.Description: ISO Image size is bigger than the available size in vFlash.
OSD37.Resolution: 1) Use a smaller size ISO Image. 2) Format the vFlash using the iDRAC GUI, RACADM, or iDRAC configuration utility and then retry this command.

SEL1402.Message: The platform generated a LAN alert.

LC011.Description: There was a general failure in the certificate import process.
LC011.Resolution: Try one of the following: 1) Rerun the command. 2) Reset iDRAC and run the command.

PSU0908.Resolution: Verify the input source is attached to the power supply. Verify the input power is within the operating requirements for the power supply.
PSU0908.Description: The power supply is installed correctly but an input source is not connected or is not functional.

BAT1026.Message: The %1 has recovered cached data from the Battery Backup Unit (BBU).
BAT1026.Description: The controller has retrieved cached data.

BAR014.Description: Unable to access the server profile Backup file and the operation cannot continue. This can be due to a media error or loss of connectivity.
BAR014.Resolution: If using vFlash media replace media and try again. If a network share, make sure there is connectivity to and existence of the destination.
BAR014.Message: Backup file or partition access error.

BAR108.Description: The license required for Server Profile Import and Export operations to function is not present.
BAR108.Resolution: Obtain the license for Server Profile Export and Import, install the license and retry the operation.
BAR108.Message: License to Export and Import Server Profile not present.

SUP0514.Description: An internal error occurred while performing firmware rollback operation.
SUP0514.Resolution: Exit the Firmware Rollback wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, reboot the system and retry the operation.

DH002.Resolution: Try again. If the error persists, use RACADM command racreset to clear the issue.

SYS423.Description: The test event cannot be sent because there are no subscriptions.
SYS423.Resolution: Create a subscription using HTTP POST operation to the URI of the subscription resource.
SYS423.Message: Unable to send the test event because there are no subscriptions.

UEFI0275.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the TCP connection timed out when connecting to the iSCSI target.
UEFI0275.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Make sure the iSCSI target system is online with the firewall configured to allow TCP access. 2) Make sure the server network infrastructure is configured to allow access to the iSCSI target. 3) Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings > Connection Settings page, make sure the iSCSI initiator settings (iSCSI, DHCP, VLAN, initiator/target IP addresses) are configured correctly. 4) Retry the operation.
UEFI0275.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the TCP connection timed out when connecting to the iSCSI target.

SUP0502.Description: iDRAC is unable generate the inventory file or the inventory file received from iDRAC is faulty. For more information about the failure, see Lifecycle Log.
SUP0502.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists do the following: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord. 2.) Wait for five seconds. 3.) Reconnect the power cord and turn on the system. 4) Press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation. If the problem continues to persist, update iDRAC firmware to the latest version, and retry the operation. Else, contact the service provider.

TMP0134.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or cool.
TMP0134.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0134.Message: The control panel temperature is outside of range.

RAC1151.Description: The export operation did not complete successfully.
RAC1151.Resolution: Run the RACADM techsupreport collect command again and then retry the export operation.

SYS033.Description: The staged component configuration update performed in the UEFI environment on the host system has completed, but there were errors.
SYS033.Message: Staged component configuration completed with errors.

SUP0101.Description: Unable to get the update status.
SUP0101.Message: Unable to get firmware update status.

RAC0136.Description: A separate message will provide more detail about this error which was detected while attaching the vFlash partition.
RAC0136.Message: An error has occurred while attaching a partition.

RAC030.Description: This attribute is dependent on a related attribute that has an incorrect value. The related attribute is the parent in a parent-child value dependency relationship and has an affect on what values the child attribute can have.
RAC030.Resolution: Refer to the Lifecycle Controller - Remote Services User Guide or the DCIM iDRAC Card Profile to determine the required values for the related attribute and retry the operation with the appropriate value.
RAC030.Message: This attribute is dependent on a related attribute that has an incorrect value.

SWC0312.Description: The syntax of the getconfig command is invalid.
SWC0312.Resolution: Refer the help text for getconfig subcommand.
SWC0312.Message: Invalid syntax. The -u option is not valid with any other options.

LC019.Description: The PKCS12 string could not be decoded from the Base64 encoding into a PKCS12 binary file.
LC019.Resolution: Validate that the contents of the PKCS12 parameter is base64 encoded. OpenSSL can be used to validate the encoding.
LC019.Message: Base64 decode of PKCS12 content was not successful.

SYS238.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an incorrect file path value.
SYS238.Resolution: Make sure that the correct file path value is entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS238.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an incorrect file path value.

BIOS014.Resolution: Refer to the documentation on valid Attribute values.
BIOS014.Description: AttributeValue may be invalid because of the following causes: 1) Length of new AttributeValue is not within required minimum length and maximum length 2) Value of new AttributeValue is not within required LowerBound and UpperBound 3) Value of new AttributeValue is not one of the possible values.

PWR214.Description: Cannot enable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) mode because Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) is enabled.
PWR214.Resolution: Disable Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) and retry the operation.
PWR214.Message: Cannot enable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) mode because Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) is enabled.

PSU8507.Message: Insufficient power available because PSU in the slot %1 is not present.
PSU8507.Resolution: Insert a PSU in the slot identified in the message.
PSU8507.Description: The PSU identified in the message has been disengaged or removed. Insufficient power is available.

RAC0909.Description: The specified command is missing object name syntax.
RAC0909.Resolution: Specify the correct subcommand object name syntax. See the help text or documentation for valid syntax.
RAC0909.Message: Invalid subcommand syntax: Specify the object name.

HWC4001.Message: A hardware incompatibility was corrected between BMC/iDRAC firmware and CPU.

RAC0221.Description: The Destination E-mail Address can contain up to 64 characters.
RAC0221.Resolution: Enter an email address that contains up to 64 characters.
RAC0221.Message: The Destination E-mail Address is too long. The maximum length is 64 characters.

UEFI0177.Message: A DIMM module is installed on memory slot %1 after a Quad Rank DIMM module.
UEFI0177.Resolution: Only a single Quad Rank DIMM module can be installed on a channel. Populate memory modules in a supported configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0177.Description: A memory population violation has been detected on the identified DIMM slot.

SWU8503.Message: A reinstall/rollback request was submitted to the Lifecycle Controller on server %1.
SWU8503.Description: The specified Lifecycle Controller operation is successfully submitted and the operation will be executed on the basis of scheduling criteria.

LOG509.Message: Unable to run the command because the parameter value of %1 exceeds the maximum allowed number of %2 characters.
LOG509.Resolution: Enter a value for the parameter identified in the message that is equal to or less than the maximum allowed characters.
LOG509.Description: The command cannot be run because the value of the parameter identified in the message exceeds the maximum length identified in the message.

RAC1029.Description: The certificate cannot be deleted if the certificate type specified is not "3".
RAC1029.Resolution: Make sure to specify "3" for the certificate type (-t) option, and retry the operation.
RAC1029.Message: Unable to delete the specified certificate type.

OSE0004.Description: A separate exception or status condition shutdown the operating system. (IPMI sensor type 20h - offset 04h).
OSE0004.Resolution: Review system event log for platform events capable of shutting the system down.
OSE0004.Message: A soft shut-down initiated by platform event filter.

UEFI0100.Description: The Memory Mirroring feature cannot be enabled because of mismatches in the DIMM channel configurations.
UEFI0100.Resolution: Make sure identical memory modules in corresponding slots of channel pairs are populated. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0100.Message: Unable to enable the Memory Mirroring feature because of mismatches in the DIMM channel configurations.

CTL60.Message: A user has discarded data from the %1 cache.
CTL60.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC1165.Description: Unable to configure the port number that is entered for either http or https ports of the iDRAC Web server, because the port number is already in use.
RAC1165.Resolution: Enter a port number that is not already in use and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC1165.Message: Unable to configure the port number that is entered for either http or https ports of the iDRAC Web server, because the port number is already in use.

CTL86.Message: %1 is operating in Fault Tolerant Mode.
CTL86.Description: The controller is operating in conjunction with another controller to service the same set of virtual and physical disks, providing better redundancy.

UEFI0159.Message: Unsupported Unregistered Dual In-line Memory Module (UDIMM) memory is installed on memory slot: %1.
UEFI0159.Resolution: Remove the unsupported DIMM module from the identified memory slot and replace it with a supported module. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0159.Description: Unsupported 4Gb technology DIMM module is installed on the memory slot identified in the message.

SWC0118.Description: The syntax of the sslcertupload command is invalid.
SWC0118.Resolution: Refer the help text for sslcertupload subcommand.

NIC018.Description: The input BIOS password used in the operation is invalid.
NIC018.Resolution: Use a valid BIOS password and retry.

SWC0141.Message: Certificate successfully downloaded from the RAC

UEFI0268.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the iSCSI target name is invalid.
UEFI0268.Resolution: Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings > Connection Settings page, make sure the iSCSI Target Name in the iSCSI setup page is correct, and retry the operation.
UEFI0268.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the iSCSI target name is invalid.

IOV1001.Description: The requested operation was successfully executed.
IOV1001.Message: The requested operation was successfully executed.

SYS092.Description: The iDRAC is collecting information about the server for a Tech Support Report.
SYS092.Message: The iDRAC is collecting information about the server for a Tech Support Report.

RAC973.Description: The configuration XML file which was specified for import, had the same configuration as the current system configuration.
RAC973.Resolution: Make any desired system configuration changes to the configuration XML file and retry the operation.
RAC973.Message: The imported configuration XML file matches the current system configuration.

RED058.Message: A repository update job %1 was created.
RED058.Description: A repository update job with the job ID identified in the message was created.

RED016.Description: The remote share location that has the file(s) or ISO image did not mount correctly.
RED016.Resolution: 1. Verify that the path to the share is correct and that the parameters to the call are correct. 2. Verify that there are no network connectivity issues. 3. Verify that the mount point exists.

LC051.Description: There can only be one Server Profile Export job at a time.
LC051.Resolution: Wait for the existing Server Profile Export job to run and complete or cancel it, before retrying the operation.
LC051.Message: Cannot create multiple Server Profile Export jobs.

CTL18.Message: Load Balance and Auto Copyback on Predictive Failure has changed for %1.
CTL18.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SEL1518.Message: The performance of CPU%1 is automatically readjusted by Chassis Controller because of unacceptable change in the thermal and power conditions.
SEL1518.Resolution: Check the firmware version of Fan Controller Block (FCB) and make sure that the Power Supply Unit (PSU) is functional. For more information about the firmware version and PSU ratings, see PSQN SLN300669 available on the support site.
SEL1518.Description: The performance of CPU is automatically readjusted by Chassis Controller because of unacceptable change in the thermal and power conditions.

CTL55.Resolution: If there is a problem, review the controller event log and the Server Administrator alert log for significant events or alerts that may assist in diagnosing the problem. Verify the health of the storage components. See the hardware documentation for more information.
CTL55.Description: The text for this alert is generated by the controller and can vary depending on the situation. This text is from events in the controller event log that were generated while Storage Management was not running.

PDR1121.Message: Drive %1 is no longer in the critical array.

HWC2002.Message: The storage %1 cable or interconnect is connected.

PDR1025.Message: Drive mismatch corrected for drive %1 in disk drive bay %2.

PR22.Description: This is the initial job status value when a job is created. This message is no longer in use in Lifecycle Controller 2.0 as the job control functionality handles this operation.

LC080.Description: The Export Server Screen Shot operation successfully exported the server screen shot file.
LC080.Resolution: Download the encoded Base64 format server screen shot file, decode the Base64 file and then save it as a *.png file.
LC080.Message: The Export Server Screen Shot operation successfully exported the server screen shot file.

RAC1183.Description: The IP addresses 169.254.0.3 and 169.254.0.4 cannot be assigned to the device identified in the message because the IP addresses entered are reserved for the iDRAC Direct feature.
RAC1183.Resolution: Enter another appropriate IP address, and then retry the operation.
RAC1183.Message: Unable to assign IP addresses 169.254.0.3 and 169.254.0.4 to the device OSBMC USBNIC because the IP addresses entered are reserved for the iDRAC Direct feature.

MEM0702.Message: Correctable memory error rate exceeded for %1.
MEM0702.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem continues, contact support.
MEM0702.Description: The memory may not be operational. This an early indicator of a possible future uncorrectable error.

TMP0123.Message: The system inlet temperature is within range.

CMC8507.Description: The Extended Storage feature synchronizes data from the primary CMC removable flash media SD Card is synchronized with the secondary CMC removable flash media SD Card.
CMC8507.Message: Extended Storage for primary CMC and secondary CMC synchronization is complete.

RAC0270.Description: This is a warning message that continuing this operation does not allow subsequent GUI interactions to this NIC.
RAC0270.Resolution: Enable IPv4 or IPv6 before continuing the operation.

USR0181.Description: The Quick Sync feature is deactivated because the inactivity timeout limit was reached.
USR0181.Resolution: Press the activate button on the bezel to activate the iDRAC Quick Sync feature.
USR0181.Message: The Quick Sync feature is deactivated because the inactivity timeout limit was reached.

VLT0302.Message: CPU %1 %2 voltage is greater than the upper warning threshold.
VLT0302.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0302.Description: High voltages may be the result of problem with the voltage regulator or a problem with the processor. Elevated voltages may result in damage to the processor or other electronic components inside the system.

SWC0110.Description: The build information is not available for racdump.
SWC0110.Message: No build information is currently available.

CPU0010.Resolution: Review system logs for power or thermal exceptions.
CPU0010.Description: The CPU is throttled due to thermal or power conditions.

PWR8546.Description: A chassis shutdown was already in progress, when the additional shutdown request was received.

BAR102.Description: Unable to import license data from the backup Server Profile.
BAR102.Resolution: Refer to iDRAC User Guide documentation license installation instructions and retry the operation.

SWU8525.Message: Unable to update the iDRAC firmware on the server in slot %1. The firmware update timeout limit is exceeded.
SWU8525.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWU8525.Description: The firmware update operation is not successful. The update process was not completed within the firmware update timeout duration.

MEM0009.Message: Memory device at location %1 is throttled.
MEM0009.Resolution: If unexpected, review system logs for power or thermal exceptions.

SYS265.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because the remote host server did not allow file transfer operations.
SYS265.Resolution: Make sure that the file transfer parameters and credentials, and remote host server configuration are correct, and then retry the operation.
SYS265.Description: The file cannot be transferred because the remote host server did not allow file transfer operations even when the remote host is successfully contacted.

RAC0726.Description: Auto-throttling is disabled for the server based on a request from the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) because the CMC is restarting.
RAC0726.Message: Auto-throttling is disabled for the server.

VLT0217.Message: The disk drive bay %1 voltage is within range.

SEL1205.Message: The unknown system hardware failure was corrected.

JCP032.Description: The configuration job cannot be created because the -r and --realtime options cannot be used at the same time.
JCP032.Resolution: Make sure that only one of either -r or --realtime option is entered. For example, to run a job immediately, enter the --realtime option. To schedule a job that will be run after restarting a server, use the -r option. For more information about options, see the RACADM Command Line Reference Guide available at the support site. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
JCP032.Message: Unable to create a job because conflicting options are entered.

SWC0244.Description: The specified Fully Qualified Device Descriptor (FQDDs) system component name is invalid.
SWC0244.Resolution: Verify that the correct Fully Qualified Device Descriptor (FQDD) system component name is specified. See the help text (The help text for the get subcommand can be obtained by running "racadm help get") or documentation for valid FQDD system component names.

HWC7012.Message: Server %1 health changed to a non-recoverable state.
HWC7012.Resolution: Review System Log or front panel for additional information.
HWC7012.Description: Server <number> health changed to a non-recoverable state.

BIOS008.Description: No changes are available between the previous configuration and the current configuration. To create a configuration job, at least one attribute should be changed.
BIOS008.Resolution: Change the configuration of one or more attributes and then create a configuration job.
BIOS008.Message: No pending data present to create a Configuration job.

RAC913.Description: The management system could not login to the iDRAC.
RAC913.Resolution: Verify whether the username and password given for the iDRAC are correct.
RAC913.Message: Unable to login to RAC using the specified address

SYS175.Description: Selective Export / Import could not find any matches for the FQDDs specified.
SYS175.Resolution: Make sure that only valid FQDDs are entered as input to the Target parameter, and then retry the operation.
SYS175.Message: Unable to find a device configuration for the FQDD entered.

CMC8546.Message: Issues identified with Process %1. Failover condition detected.
CMC8546.Resolution: No response action is required. A failover may result from this condition. If multiple failovers occur, contact your service provider.
CMC8546.Description: A firmware error has occurred in the internal firmware process identified in the message. This condition will cause a CMC failover to occur. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

TST105.Resolution: To provide the correct value for the specified parameter, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
TST105.Description: The value provided for the specified parameter is invalid.

PWR8569.Message: Unable to power cycle the server %1 because the server is off.
PWR8569.Resolution: Turn on the server, if necessary, before requesting a power cycle operation.
PWR8569.Description: The requested power cycle operation cannot be performed when the server is not turned on. The server should be already turned on for the power cycle operation to be successful.

SWC8564.Message: Unable to clear the Boot Identity profile from the server in slot %1 because there is no response from the server iDRAC.
SWC8564.Resolution: Make sure that the server is not used until the Persistence Policy settings are returned to default values and the Virtual MAC Address settings have been cleared. Persistence Policy settings can be reset to default values by resetting the server iDRAC to factory default settings. If the iDRAC cannot be reset to default values, contact your service provider before attempting to use the server.
SWC8564.Description: The Boot Identity profile from the server identified in the message cannot be cleared because there is no response from the server iDRAC. A MAC Address conflict is possible if the server retains virtual MAC Address values and they are also allocated to another server.

PWR8501.Message: Successfully set Virtual Infrastructure Device power to %1 WDC.
PWR8501.Description: Power allocation succeeded for Virtual infrastructure.

UEFI0013.Description: A CPU floating point error (type 0x10) exception occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0013.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.
UEFI0013.Message: CPU Exception Type 0x10: Floating Point Error (Software).

VF025.Resolution: To perform a write operation on this partition, change its access type to read-write and try this operation again.

UEFI0110.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.
UEFI0110.Resolution: Remove input power to the system, reseat the DIMM module and restart the system. If the issues persist, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0110.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot identified in the message. The error occurred during Write DQ/DQS initialization.

SWC0285.Description: The value given for the object is not valid.
SWC0285.Resolution: Enter a valid value for the corresponding object.

MEM8001.Message: Persistent correctable memory error logging enabled for a memory device at location %1.

CTL58.Resolution: There may be a SAS topology error. See the hardware documentation for information on correct SAS topology configurations. There may be problems with the cables such as a loose connection or an invalid cabling configuration. See the Cables Attached Correctly section for more information on checking the cables. See the hardware documentation for information on correct cabling configurations. Verify that the firmware version is supported.
CTL58.Description: The text for this alert is generated by the firmware and can vary depending on the situation. The reference to SMP in this text refers to SAS Management Protocol.

PSU0910.Message: Soft power control failure detected on power unit %1.
PSU0910.Description: The system did not respond correctly to a power down request.

SYS066.Description: No iDRAC, System, or Lifecycle Controller configuration changes were applied. The settings specified in the system configuration XML input file match the current configuration for these components.
SYS066.Message: No changes detected for iDRAC, System, or Lifecycle Controller configuration.

SYS073.Description: The import of Server Configuration Profile operation completed with errors because the Lifecycle Controller State was disabled in the input profile. Configuration changes requiring a system reboot were not applied.
SYS073.Resolution: Enable the Lifecycle Controller State setting and retry the operation.
SYS073.Message: Unable to apply changes that require system reboot because the Lifecycle Controller State setting is disabled in the Server Configuration Profile.

PSUA0016.Resolution: Install the power supply if needed.
PSUA0016.Description: The supply has been removed or has failed.

SWC0109.Description: There is no RAC diagnostic information available.
SWC0109.Message: No process information is currently available.

RAC0133.Description: A non-specific error has been detected when downloading the partition.
RAC0133.Resolution: Try downloading the partition again in a few minutes. If the problem persists, reset iDRAC before trying the operation again.
RAC0133.Message: An error has occurred while downloading a partition.

RAC990.Resolution: Enable Lifecycle Controller using the "racadm set lifecyclecontroller.lcattributes.lifecyclecontrollerstate 1" command, and retry the operation.
RAC990.Description: If Lifecycle Controller is disabled, the firmware update operation cannot continue.

BIOS018.Description: The BIOS password specified in the operation is not valid. A valid BIOS password must be made from the following: 0 to 32 characters in length, numbers 0 to 9, lowercase letters a to z, special characters <>|-,+./;[\]'.
BIOS018.Resolution: Retry the operation with a BIOS password that conforms with system BIOS password requirements.

CTL50.Description: The NVRAM has corrupt data. The controller is unable to correct the situation.

CPU0702.Description: System event log and OS logs may indicate that the exception is external to the processor.
CPU0702.Resolution: Check system and operating system logs for exceptions. If no exceptions found, remove input power, reinstall the processor, then apply input power.

CTL3.Description: You have enabled the controller alarm. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PR2.Description: The specified device configuration is different from the previous device configuration.

PDR28.Resolution: Although this alert is provided for informational purposes, you may need to assign a new hot spare to the virtual disk. Refer to product documentation and see the section Protecting Your Virtual Disk with a Hot Spare for more information.
PDR28.Description: A physical disk that was assigned as a hot spare has been unassigned and is no longer functioning as a hot spare. The physical disk was unassigned by a user or automatically unassigned by Storage Management. Storage Management unassigns hot spares that have been used to rebuild data. Once data is rebuilt onto the hot spare, the hot spare becomes a member of the virtual disk and is no longer assigned as a hot spare. Assign a new hot spare to maintain data protection in this situation.

JCP015.Description: The job is currently executing and cannot be deleted. The job needs to finish running, whether successful or not, before it can be deleted.
JCP015.Resolution: Wait for the job to have a completed job status. Retry the operation.
JCP015.Message: A running job cannot be deleted.

RAC0267.Resolution: Enter a valid VLAN Priority. Expected range: 0-7.

VLT0221.Message: The %1 voltage is greater than the upper critical threshold.
VLT0221.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0221.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

UEFI0050.Message: The process of collecting Brand information is started.

OSD76.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'ResetType' is invalid.
OSD76.Resolution: Check the value provided for input parameter "ResetType" and retry the operation.
OSD76.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'ResetType' is invalid.

UEFI0129.Description: The Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) has encountered an unknown issue. This may be because new error codes are coming from the IDSDM firmware and the system BIOS or the iDRAC firmware need to be updated to process correctly.
UEFI0129.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Update the system BIOS. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. 3) Reseat or replace the SD card media. Restart the system and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0129.Message: The Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) has encountered an unknown issue.

UEFI0135.Description: The CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) operation cannot be executed because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible. This issue is caused by LC partition attach issues.
UEFI0135.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0135.Message: Unable to execute CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible.

PST0137.Description: System BIOS detected a parity error during post This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST exception code 89).
PST0137.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

PWR8574.Message: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to communicate to the iDRAC, when trying to hard reset the server %1.
PWR8574.Resolution: Wait for three minutes, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, remove and reinsert the server and wait for the iDRAC to finish restarting before retying the operation.
PWR8574.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is not able to communicate with the iDRAC on the server identified in the message. Therefore the server could not be hard reset. This situation may occur when iDRAC is restarting.

UEFI0209.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0209.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0209.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Transmit Buffer Per Bit Deskew Training phase.

CMC003.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the parameter %1 is missing.
CMC003.Resolution: Enter the missing parameter and retry the operation. For information about the parameters, see the CMC Profile document available on the support site.
CMC003.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the parameter identified in the message is missing.

PR33.Description: The platform system motherboard was replaced.

PCI1306.Message: A software error was detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.
PCI1306.Resolution: Reboot the system and update the component drivers.

OSD69.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'ShareType' is missing.
OSD69.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "ShareType" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD69.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'ShareType' is missing.

SWC8527.Description: Chassis Management Controller unable to update the IDRAC root user username as root. This can happen if the communication to the iDRAC from CMC is non-functional or if the username supplied is not valid.
SWC8527.Resolution: Make sure the user name is valid. If communication with iDRAC is not successful, reset the iDRAC. Retry the operation after a few minutes.
SWC8527.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to update the iDRAC user name to "root".

PCI5003.Message: A PCIe card carrier is removed from the PCIe slot%1 .
PCI5003.Description: A PCIe card carrier is removed from the PCIe slot identified in the message.

SYS193.Message: A configuration change is detected for component: %1.
SYS193.Description: A configuration change is detected in the component identified in the message.

PDR65.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

STOR092.Description: The requested configuration operation cannot be run because a foreign configuration import operation on the controller is already in progress.
STOR092.Resolution: Wait for the import process to complete before running any configuration operation.
STOR092.Message: Unable to run the configuration operation on the controller because foreign configuration import operation is in progress.

SUP022.Description: JobStore file has exceeded the size limit. Delete all unneeded JobIDs from the job store.
SUP022.Resolution: New JobID cannot be stored. Manually delete the failed jobs and retry the operation.
SUP022.Message: Job store has reached the maximum storage limit.

SWC0050.Description: Unable to initiate Import operation since iDRAC is not responding.
SWC0050.Resolution: Retry the Import operation using a valid backup image file and the correct passphrase. If the problem persists, do the following: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait for five seconds. 3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.

VLT0201.Message: The system board %1 voltage is less than the lower critical threshold.
VLT0201.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0201.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

IOID003.Message: The Virtual Address Persistence Policy setting for Auxiliary powered devices is changed to %1.
IOID003.Description: The Virtual Address Persistence Policy setting for Auxiliary powered devices is changed to the restart type identified in the message.

SWU8529.Description: The iKVM firmware update operation was not successful, because the firmware Image file could not be transferred to the target.
SWU8529.Resolution: Make sure that the iKVM firmware Image file is available at the specified location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8529.Message: Unable to update the iKVM firmware, because the Image file was not transferred to the iKVM target.

STOR060.Description: The requested operation is not supported on the specified storage controller.
STOR060.Resolution: For more information about supported operations, see the documentation specific for the targeted storage controller.
STOR060.Message: Configuration operations are not supported on the specified storage controller.

RED029.Description: The scheduled action requires a system reboot and reboot will be performed at the scheduled start time.

VLT0209.Message: The memory module %1 %2 voltage is greater than the upper critical threshold.
VLT0209.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0209.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

BAT1016.Message: The %1 battery learn mode has changed to Auto.
BAT1016.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SUP0131.Message: FTP firmware update has been initiated. This update process may take several minutes to complete.

RAC0693.Description: Pending operations are created for the selected operations on the selected physical disk drives.
RAC0693.Resolution: To view the pending operations, click the Pending Operations button.
RAC0693.Message: Pending operations are created for the selected operations on the selected physical disk drives.

FAN900.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode is successfully enabled.
FAN900.Message: The Enhanced Cooling Mode is successfully enabled.

PSU1006.Description: The enclosure detected that a power supply unit was inserted.

PWR8556.Message: Server %1 was shutdown due to insufficient power.
PWR8556.Description: The Server identified in the message was shutdown due to insufficient power.

RAC0742.Description: A Secure Erase operation on a PCIe SSD overwrites all blocks in an encrypted way and all the data on the PCIe SSD device will be permanently lost. The changes will happen after reboot of the system or loss of power to the drive.
RAC0742.Message: The Secure Erase command will be executed on the selected PCIe SSD disk drives(s) only after the reboot of the system or loss of power to the disk drives(s).

PST0012.Description: System extended memory test in progress.

UEFI0071.Description: One or more UEFI network interfaces is not available. The corresponding UEFI network devices are disabled.
UEFI0071.Resolution: Connect the missing network interface card to the system and enable the UEFI network interface in System Setup.
UEFI0071.Message: One or more UEFI network interfaces is not available. The corresponding UEFI network devices are disabled.

RAC0656.Description: The iDRAC Service Module (iSM) service cannot be started by just enabling in iDRAC web interface because the service has to also be manually restarted on the server operating system.
RAC0656.Resolution: To re-enable the iDRAC Service Module (iSM), do the following: 1) Enable the iSM in the iDRAC web interface, 2) Start the iSM service on the server operating system.
RAC0656.Message: Are you sure you want to disable the iDRAC Service Module on the server operating system?

BAT1021.Message: The charge level for the battery on %1 is below the normal threshold.
BAT1021.Resolution: Check for other events related to the state of the battery. These may help determine the cause of this event.
BAT1021.Description: The controller battery cannot maintain sufficient charge level to function properly or the battery is discharging.

VF052.Description: The device is not ready to access media information.

SYS123.Description: An unexpected issue has occurred. This could be because the application encountered an unexpected exception or was terminated by a user. This issue could also be because the application was running in an unsupported OS.
SYS123.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the OS Collector on the iDRAC to the most recent version available, and then retry the operation.
SYS123.Message: OS Collector: An unexpected issue has been encountered.

UEFI0059.Description: The Power Supply Units (PSUs) in the system do not match.
UEFI0059.Resolution: Check the PSU types and make sure they are appropriately matched, and then retry the operation. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0059.Message: The Power Supply Units (PSUs) in the system do not match.

HWC2012.Message: A fabric mismatch detected on fabric %1 with server in slot %2.
HWC2012.Resolution: Check chassis fabric type in CMC GUI and compare to the type of IOM or mezzanine card.
HWC2012.Description: The fabric type on the server does not match that of the IO module.

PWR2250.Description: The server did not turn on because the chassis infrastructure is not ready. The chassis infrastructure includes: PCIe subsystem, storage components, and the chassis management controller.
PWR2250.Resolution: Check the status of the chassis infrastructure in the CMC Web or RACADM interface. Wait until the chassis infrastructure components are fully turned on.
PWR2250.Message: Unable to turn on the server because the chassis infrastructure not ready.

SWC0258.Description: Insufficient resources to execute the command.
SWC0258.Resolution: Power Cycle the system and re-enter the command.

BAR012.Description: Lifecycle Controller data collection and export has failed.
BAR012.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Download and apply the Dell Update Package (DUP) for USC. 2) Run System Services to update the database if CSIOR is not enabled. 3) Reboot the system and retry. If the issue persists after performing these operations, download the Field Service Repair software and repair the Lifecycle Controller. Download and install all the DUPs for USC, diagnostics, driver packs, and device firmware of all the devices of the host system.
BAR012.Message: Unable to collect Lifecycle Controller data.

SYS141.Description: The Lifecycle Controller data is deleted because of a System Erase operation.

STOR0503.Description: Existing RAID configuration was successfully erased.

VLT0212.Message: The disk drive bay %1 voltage is less than the lower warning threshold.
VLT0212.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat hard disks in the bay. Reconnect all cables attached to the bay.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0212.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

USR8505.Description: The operation to invalidate the Session identified in the message was successful.

UEFI0185.Message: Load Reduced DIMM (LR-DIMM) training errors have occurred on memory riser %1.
UEFI0185.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0185.Description: A Load-Reduced DIMM (LR-DIMM) buffer initialization failure was detected during memory initialization.

RAC1109.Description: Unable to run the command, because an incorrect Share type was entered.
RAC1109.Resolution: Enter an appropriate Share location of the following types: FTP, NFS, or CIFS. For more information, run the "racadm help update" command.
RAC1109.Message: Unable to run the command, because an incorrect Share type is entered.

UEFI0207.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0207.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0207.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Command Clock Training - Group 2 phase.

SYS154.Message: Initiating secure erase operation on secure erase-capable drives for controller: %1.
SYS154.Description: Initiating secure erase operation on secure erase-capable drives for the controller identified in the message.

LIC016.Description: The license includes features that are dependent upon additional licensed features not included in this license. These licensed features are not activated until license(s) with the dependent licensed features are imported to the system.
LIC016.Resolution: Import the license(s) that meet the license features dependencies.
LIC016.Message: The feature dependencies of the license are not met.

ASR0108.Message: The system returned from an OS watchdog timer event.

SWC0157.Message: User certificate successfully uploaded to the RAC.

SYS140.Description: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) is not running in the server OS.
SYS140.Resolution: Enable and start the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) from within the server OS and then retry the operation.
SYS140.Message: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) is not running in the server OS.

LOG003.Description: The log entry with the specified InstanceID does not have any associated configuration results.
LOG003.Resolution: Verify the ConfigResults availability for the InstanceID through enumeration of the LogEntry class and retry the operation. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
LOG003.Message: ConfigResults not available for log entry specified.

SWC0246.Message: Value specified is invalid: Valid range is %1.
SWC0246.Resolution: Verify that a valid value is specified. See the help text or documentation for valid values.
SWC0246.Description: The specified value is outside of the valid range.

RAC0707.Description: Primary Firmware image is invalid. Currently booted from backup image. To restore primary image, update the firmware.
RAC0707.Resolution: Acquire an iDRAC firmware image of the version desired. Using the latest version available is recommended. Update the iDRAC firmware.
RAC0707.Message: Primary Firmware image is invalid. Currently booted from backup image. To restore primary image, update the firmware.

SYS015.Description: The requested job has been created.

CMC8539.Message: The CMC %1 is unable to log %2 event to the Hardware Log.
CMC8539.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Save the Hardware Log if required. 2) Clear the Hardware Log.
CMC8539.Description: CMC cannot log new events to Hardware Log if Hardware Log is full. Therefore, new events are not written to the log unless older events are cleared. This issue also occurs if event logging is disabled.
