SWC0007.Description: The export current hardware inventory operation did not complete because the destination: 1) does not have the specified folder, 2) does not have enough free space, or 3) is read-only.
SWC0007.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, verify the following and retry the operation: 1) Destination has the specified folder. 2) Destination has enough free space. 3) Destination is not write-protected.
SWC0007.Message: Unable to write the current hardware inventory to the specified destination.

RAC0291.Description: The user name value does not accept these characters.
RAC0291.Resolution: Do not enter /, \, @, ., or " (quotation mark) for user name.
RAC0291.Message: The user name cannot contain: /, \, @, ., or " (quotation mark).

PSU0043.Message: An output under current fault detected on power supply %1.
PSU0043.Resolution: 1) Remove the power supply input cord and then remove power supply. 2) Re-install the power supply and then re-install the power supply cord. 3) If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

PWR8506.Message: Cumulative power computation (KWH) time is reset on %1.
PWR8506.Description: Resetting the power computation reading causes the log to report time at which it is reset.

BAT1033.Resolution: Make sure that the battery is present and properly connected. If the battery is present, wait for a few minutes and re-check if the battery is detected. If the contact point between the battery and the controller is degraded, you must replace the battery, the controller, or both. Refer to the storage hardware documentation for information on how to safely access, or remove. Contact technical support if the issue persists.
BAT1033.Description: The controller cannot communicate with the battery. Either the battery was removed, or the contact point between the controller and the battery is degraded.

SUP0503.Description: Unable to retrieve the system ID from BIOS.
SUP0503.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, do one of the following: 1) Reboot the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the BIOS firmware to the latest version and retry the operation. If the problem continues to persist contact the service provider.
SUP0503.Message: Unable to retrieve the system ID.

VME0004.Description: Virtual Media session fails to start.
VME0004.Resolution: Retry the Virtual Media session initiation.
VME0004.Message: Virtual Media session fails to start.

HWC1103.Message: The %1 installed in an unsupported slot %2 is removed.
HWC1103.Description: The peripheral sled identified in the message is removed from the unsupported slot identified in the message.

ENC30.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

CMC002.Description: The operation cannot be successfully completed because of an unknown issue.
CMC002.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) Reset CMC and retry the operation.
CMC002.Message: Unable to complete the operation because of an unknown issue.

SWC0018.Description: The BIOS boot mode settings could not be applied due to an internal error.
SWC0018.Resolution: Exit the OS Deployment wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, exit the Lifecycle Controller and perform an AC power cycle.
SWC0018.Message: Unable to apply the boot mode settings for BIOS.

RAC0757.Description: The requested operation using the USB Management Port cannot be completed because the port is disabled in BIOS configuration.
RAC0757.Resolution: Enable the USB Management Port in BIOS configuration to use this feature.
RAC0757.Message: USB Management Port is currently disabled in BIOS configuration.

RAC0680.Description: The USB Configuration XML feature is not available if the iDRAC user credentials and BIOS passwords are not set to default values.
RAC0680.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC user credentials and BIOS passwords to default and retry the operation.
RAC0680.Message: Server iDRAC user credentials and/or BIOS passwords are not currently set to default credentials. The USB Configuration XML feature is not available unless default credentials are set.

LC025.Resolution: Make more space available on the network share and try the operation again.

HWC5032.Message: A fabric mismatch detected on IO module %1.
HWC5032.Resolution: Check chassis fabric type in CMC GUI and compare to the type of both IOM's.
HWC5032.Description: The fabric type for IOM's on the same chassis fabric must match.

SWC0034.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to export the file to the network share because it has insufficient free space.
SWC0034.Resolution: Make sure that the network share has sufficient free space then retry the operation. If the problem persists, check network settings and retry the operation.
SWC0034.Message: Unable to export the file to the network share.

SEC0702.Description: The Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) mode is enabled.
SEC0702.Message: The Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) mode is enabled.

PSU0080.Message: Power supply %1 voltage rating does not match the system's requirements.
PSU0080.Resolution: Review product documentation, change power supply with correct voltage rating.
PSU0080.Description: The system does not support mixed voltage power supplies.

FAN1001.Description: The enclosure detected that a fan was inserted.

CTL57.Message: The factory default settings were restored on %1.
CTL57.Description: The controller was reset to factory default configuration settings.

CTL17.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PDR1023.Message: Rebuild completed for drive %1 in disk drive bay %2.

STOR017.Description: The virtual disk specified is not compatible with the requested operation or a specified operation parameter is not appropriate for the virtual disk type specified.
STOR017.Resolution: Make sure the operation parameters are appropriate for the virtual disk type. Specify a compatible virtual disk for the requested operation and retry the operation.
STOR017.Message: The specified Virtual Disk is not valid for the operation.

SYS124.Description: The OS and Application data collection by the OS Collector application is unable to execute on the OS installed on the server because the OS is not supported.
SYS124.Message: OS Collector: The OS Collector application does not support execution in the OS installed on the server.

HWC1104.Message: The %1 installed in slot %2 is not supported by the chassis.
HWC1104.Resolution: Make sure that the peripheral sled identified in the message is supported by the chassis and the CMC firmware. For information about the supported sleds and firmware versions, see the System Manual available at the support site.
HWC1104.Description: The peripheral sled identified in the message that is inserted in the slot identified in the message is not supported by the chassis or the current CMC firmware version.

UEFI0040.Description: The TXT has been disabled due to an unexpected issue. Check the SEL (System Event Log) for details of the issue.
UEFI0040.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 2) Update the BIOS firmware on the system. For information about the issue, see System Event Log (SEL).
UEFI0040.Message: The TXT feature is disabled because of an unexpected issue.

HWC3000.Resolution: If removal was unintended, check presence, then re-install or reconnect.
HWC3000.Description: The removed device may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.

RAC0266.Resolution: Enter a valid VLan ID. Expected range: 1-4094.

PDR76.Description: Copyback not possible as SAS or SATA mixing is not supported in the same virtual disk. This alert is provided for informational purposes.
PDR76.Message: Copyback not possible as SAS or SATA mixing is not supported.

RAC0619.Description: The message appears in Firmware Rollback page when the iDRAC firmware rollback action completed successfully.
RAC0619.Resolution: Reconnect iDRAC communications sessions after iDRAC is restarted. The iDRAC will be ready for login once the restart is complete.
RAC0619.Message: The iDRAC firmware rollback will cause an iDRAC restart and all current user sessions will be closed.

UEFI0240.Message: An error occurred during Voltage Regulator (VR) initialization on memory riser %1.
UEFI0240.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0240.Description: An error occurred during Memory Voltage Regulator initialization during the VR0 SVID Ramp phase.

HWC1006.Resolution: If adapter disabled unexpectedly, re-enable the storage adapter.

BOOT017.Description: The boot device(s) specified in the source argument used in the operation cannot be enabled or disabled. This behavior applies to BCV devices and one-time boot.
BOOT017.Resolution: Refer to the documentation on validity of operation for the boot device specified. For more information on the operation, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
BOOT017.Message: Source argument does not support enable or disable mode.

RFL2004.Message: Failure detected on Internal Dual SD Module %1.
RFL2004.Resolution: Reinstall the SD module and remove and reinstall SD cards.
RFL2004.Description: The SD card module is installed but improperly configured or failed to initialize.

SEL1503.Message: The chassis management controller (CMC) is not redundant.

OSD39.Description: Unable to get vFlash information from internal instrumentation.
OSD39.Resolution: 1) Make sure the Dell vFlash is seated correctly. 2) Make sure a Dell licensed vFlash card is inserted 3) Make sure the Dell vFlash does not have any hardware issues by accessing it through the iDRAC GUI.

SWC0054.Description: There was an internal error while saving the settings.
SWC0054.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, reboot the system or update the Lifecycle Controller firmware to the latest version and retry the operation.

RAC1003.Description: The smart card certificate revocation list (CRL) cannot be enabled, because the object SmartCardLogonEnable is disabled.
RAC1003.Resolution: Enable the object SmartCardLogonEnable using "racadm set iDRAC.SmartCard.SmartCardLogonEnable <1 | Enabled>", and retry the operation.
RAC1003.Message: The smart card certificate revocation list (CRL) cannot be enabled.

VDR20.Resolution: Replace the failed or corrupt disk. You can identify a disk that has failed by locating the disk that has a red "X" for its status. Restart the virtual disk rebuild.
VDR20.Description: A physical disk included in the virtual disk has failed or is corrupt. You may also have cancelled the rebuild.

SYS183.Description: The memory cannot be allocated because of insufficient storage space in iDRAC.
SYS183.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and then retry the operation.
SYS183.Message: Unable to allocate memory because of insufficient storage space in iDRAC.

PWR2402.Description: The iDRAC controller cannot communicate with the power management firmware due to an problem with the interface to the power management engine or with the power management engine itself. The system may operate in a performance degraded state.
PWR2402.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle Controller Log (LC Log) and make sure that there are no subsequent log entries indicating that Communication with power management firmware has been restored. If this log entry is not present then do one of the following: 1) Disconnect system input power, wait one minute, reconnect system input power. 2) Re-flash system BIOS. 3) Upgrade system BIOS to the latest revision.
PWR2402.Message: iDRAC is unable to communicate with power management firmware.

PDR51.Message: Hot spare %1 SMART polling has failed.%2
PDR51.Resolution: Verify the health of the disk assigned as a hot spare. Replace the disk and reassign the hot spare. Make sure the cables are attached securely. See the storage hardware documentation for more information on checking the cables.
PDR51.Description: The controller firmware attempted to do SMART polling on the hot spare but could not complete the SMART polling. The controller may have lost communication with the hot spare.

SWC0250.Resolution: Enter the subcommand without any options.
SWC0250.Message: Invalid syntax. The specified subcommand does not require any options.

PSU0004.Message: The power input for power supply %1 is outside of range.
PSU0004.Resolution: Verify the input source is attached to the power supply. Verify the input power is within the operating requirements for the power supply.
PSU0004.Description: The operating requirements for the power supply may be found in product documentation or on the power supply itself.

SYS427.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the property %1 is a read only property and cannot be assigned a value.
SYS427.Resolution: Remove the property from the request body and retry the operation.
SYS427.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the property identified in the message is a read only property.

RAC0149.Description: While the system is powered off it is unable to retrieve information about the fans.
RAC0149.Resolution: Turn the system on to view this information.
RAC0149.Message: Unable to retrieve the fan information. The system is powered off.

OSE1010.Description: The system has successfully booted to ROM.

PSU1003.Resolution: Check whether the power switch on the power supply unit is turned off or on. If it is turned off, turn it on. If the problem is not corrected, verify that the power cord is attached and functional. See the storage hardware documentation for more information.
PSU1003.Description: The power supply is not providing any power. This may be because the power supply switch is in the off position or the power supply has failed.

ENC1.Description: An Enclosure Management Module (EMM) has failed is inserted into the enclosure.

SYS163.Description: The iDRAC environment has changed and the iDRAC must be restarted to apply the changes requested. Normal operation will return after the restart has completed. One exception is, the iDRAC has been reset to its default settings. In this case additional setup is required to use the iDRAC. For more information, see the iDRAC User's Guide.
SYS163.Message: The iDRAC is restarting to complete the System Erase operation. Do not restart server until the iDRAC restarts.

RAC0279.Description: An invalid IPMI encryption key was entered.
RAC0279.Resolution: Enter a valid encryption key of up to 40 characters. Odd number of characters and blank spaces are not allowed.
RAC0279.Message: Invalid Encryption Key. Expected format: 0 to 40 characters, even number of characters and no blank spaces are allowed.

BAT1028.Message: The battery voltage on %1 is low.
BAT1028.Resolution: The battery needs to recharged. Wait 24 hours to see if the charge is restored.
BAT1028.Description: The controller battery voltage is low. This may indicate that the battery is no longer protecting the controller cache.

PST0130.Description: During memory configuration system BIOS encountered device failures or speed configurations that resulted in unused memory. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception code 82).
PST0130.Resolution: Remove input power. Reseat memory devices or reduce system to minimum supported memory configuration.
PST0130.Message: Memory is configured, but not usable.

SWC0006.Description: The view As Shipped hardware inventory operation encountered an unexpected error while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0006.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0006.Message: Unable to display the As Shipped hardware inventory.

RAC0801.Description: iDRAC closes all the existing sessions and all configuration settings are set to default values. The iDRAC IP address is set to the default static IP address.
RAC0801.Message: iDRAC has reset to default settings.

ENC9.Description: You have changed the enclosure asset tag. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

LC031.Description: An internal error occurred while exporting the Hardware Inventory XML file.
LC031.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the command.
LC031.Message: Internal error occurred while exporting inventory.

SWC0101.Description: Racadm is unable to read the available log records at this point. Retry the command.
SWC0101.Message: Unable to read available log records.

CTL10.Description: The controller alarm test has run successfully. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC0741.Description: Unable to perform Prepare to Remove or Secure Erase operations on the selected PCIe SSD disk drive(s), because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
RAC0741.Resolution: To enable Lifecycle Controller, reboot the server. During server startup, press F2 to enter System Setup. Go to iDRAC Settings -> Lifecycle Controller, select Enable, and save the changes. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
RAC0741.Message: Unable to perform Prepare to Remove or Secure Erase operations on the selected PCIe SSD disk drive(s), because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

RED009.Resolution: Verify if Lifecycle Controller is installed on the system by pressing F10 on boot up. If the Lifecycle Controller application is not present, use the update package to reinstall it.

SWU8535.Message: Unable to update the LKVM firmware, because the Image file transfer is not successful. ErrorCode=0x%1.
SWU8535.Resolution: Make sure that the iKVM firmware image file is available at the specified location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8535.Description: The LKVM firmware update operation was not successful, because the firmware Image file could not be transferred.

RAC0169.Description: Certificate upload failed because the certificate is not valid.
RAC0169.Resolution: Certificate may be corrupt. Try creating a new Certificate Signing Request (CSR) and then upload the certificate.
RAC0169.Message: Certificate upload failed: Certificate is not valid.

RAC914.Description: The specified value is not within the valid range. To set the LED state to off, enter 0. To set the LED state to on, enter 1.
RAC914.Resolution: Set the numeric value to 0 (Off) or 1 (On).
RAC914.Message: Value specified is invalid: Must be 0 (Off) or 1 (On).

UEFI0046.Description: An issue in observed in the previous invocation of TXT SINIT Authenticated Code Module (ACM) because the TXT information stored in the TPM chip may be corrupted.
UEFI0046.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Update the BIOS firmware. 2) Go to System Setup > System Security page, click the "Clear" option under TPM command. Restart the system, go to System Setup > System Security page, click the "Activate" option under TPM command, and then enable TXT.
UEFI0046.Message: An issue is observed in the previous invocation of TXT SINIT Authenticated Code Module (ACM) because the TXT information stored in the TPM chip may be corrupted.

VF049.Description: The initializing SD card operation did not complete successfully.
VF049.Message: Initialize media operation did not complete successfully.

PWR2264.Description: The Intel Management Engine has recovered the ability to utilize the PECI over DMI facility.
PWR2264.Resolution: If the PWR2262 "internal system error" was logged within the previous 30 seconds, ignore the message. No response action required.
PWR2264.Message: The Intel Management Engine has reported normal system operation.

SYS089.Description: The Preview operation of Server Configuration Profile is complete.
SYS089.Message: Preview of Server Configuration Profile is complete.

RED031.Description: The internal space available for storing firmware images is almost full. Normal operations will continue until the critical limit is reached. When the critical limit is reached, all the rollback firmware images will be deleted.
RED031.Message: Approaching maximum size limit allowed for storing firmware images.

ENC8.Description: You have disabled the enclosure alarm.

UEFI0131.Description: Unable to load one or more option ROMs because of insufficient shadow memory. The option ROM shadow memory is located between C0000h and F0000h.
UEFI0131.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove unused PCIe card(s) to free up option ROM space. 2) Disable unused boot protocol instances (such as PXE, iSCSI, etc.) from applicable PCIe card(s) option ROM configurations. 3) If possible, install and run the Operating System in UEFI boot mode.
UEFI0131.Message: Unable to load one or more option ROMs because of insufficient shadow memory.

LC041.Description: The length of the Console name exceeds the maximum length allowed or the file operation error encountered.
LC041.Resolution: Change the name of a console to a name less than 32 characters.

SWU8560.Description: The firmware update process of Active CMC and Standby CMC was not successful because of a unrecognized image error.
SWU8560.Resolution: Obtain a valid firmware image from your service provider and retry the operation.
SWU8560.Message: The firmware update process of Active CMC and Standby CMC was not successful because of a unrecognized image error.

PCI3006.Description: Either the BIOS or BMC/iDRAC firmware is out of date and does not support FlexAddress.
PCI3006.Resolution: Update BIOS, and BMC/iDRAC firmware. If problem persists please contact customer support.
PCI3006.Message: Failed to get Link Tuning or FlexAddress data from iDRAC.

SYS185.Description: The Tech Support Report job that was running has been cancelled by user request.
SYS185.Resolution: To start another Tech Support Report job, wait until the current job that is being cancelled completes and then retry the operation.
SYS185.Message: The Tech Support Report job has been cancelled.

PWR2200.Message: The system is in the ON state.

PDR1002.Message: A predictive failure detected on drive %1 in disk drive bay %2.
PDR1002.Resolution: The drive will need replacement at the next service window.
PDR1002.Description: The controller received a SMART error from the drive. The drive is operational but needs replacement.

SWU8552.Description: The firmware update process of Active CMC was not successful.
SWU8552.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8552.Message: Unable to update the firmware of Active CMC.

UEFI0172.Message: A Quad Rank DIMM module is installed on memory slot %1 after a Single Rank DIMM module.
UEFI0172.Resolution: Quad Rank DIMM modules must be installed before Single Rank DIMM modules on the channel. Populate memory modules in a supported configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0172.Description: A memory population violation has been detected on the identified DIMM slot.

RFM1023.Description: The media is being prepared or is under maintenance. If the problem persists, reinstall the card.
RFM1023.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media.
RFM1023.Message: Removable Flash Media is not ready.

PWR201.Description: Selecting the Server Based Power Management Mode option sets your power cap to a maximum value, server priorities to a default priority, and then disables the Max Power Conservation Mode.
PWR201.Message: Selecting the Server Based Power Management Mode option sets your power cap to a maximum value, server priorities to a default priority, and then disables the Max Power Conservation Mode. Do you want to continue?

RED065.Description: The recurring scheduled update from repository job completed and updates were applied. A system restart was not required.
RED065.Message: The recurring scheduled update from repository job completed and updates were applied. A system restart was not required.

SUP009.Description: Because of the size of the driver pack, the update process removes the older version of the driver pack from the system before installing the newer version. For that reason, the driver pack update cannot be deleted.
SUP009.Resolution: Wait for the Driver Pack update to complete. To revert to the previous version of the update, download and update the firmware to the version desired.
SUP009.Message: Driver pack update in progress - Delete failed.

PDR30.Resolution: Verify that the disk is healthy and installed. Check the cables. Refer to the product documentation and see the Cables Attached Correctly section for more information on checking the cables. If necessary, replace the disk and reassign the global hot spare.
PDR30.Description: The controller cannot to communicate with a disk that is assigned as a global hot spare. The disk either failed or was removed. There may also be a bad or loose cable.

SWC0292.Message: The specified object at index %1 does not exist.
SWC0292.Resolution: Check for the objects available at the specified index and re-try.
SWC0292.Description: The queried object does not exist at the specified index.

SWC0066.Description: Unable to connect to the Network Share due to one of the following: 1) Login credentials entered are incorrect. 2) Network is inaccessible. 3) System IP address conflicts with another system on the network.
SWC0066.Resolution: Verify the login credentials. Make sure the Network Share is accessible and the system IP address does not conflict with any other system on the network. If the problem persists, perform an AC power cycle and retry.
SWC0066.Message: Unable to connect to the Network Share.

TMP0136.Description: The system is automatically turned off because of insufficient cooling.
TMP0136.Resolution: Replace the fans that have stopped functioning, or add the minimum number of fans recommended. For more information, see the system Owner's Manual available at the support site.
TMP0136.Message: The system is automatically turned off because of insufficient cooling.

ISM0002.Description: The OS to iDRAC Pass-through mode is disabled. The iDRAC Service Module is currently enabling the OS to iDRAC Pass-through mode in the USB NIC mode. This operation is done only for the first run of iDRAC Service Module. If OS to iDRAC Pass-through is disabled after this point of time, iDRAC Service Module will not be able to connect to iDRAC until user enables the OS-iDRAC Pass-through in the USB mode.
ISM0002.Message: The OS to iDRAC Pass-through is disabled. The iDRAC Service Module is currently enabling the OS to iDRAC Pass-through in the USB NIC mode.

SWU8556.Message: Unable to configure the sled network uplink on sled %1.
SWU8556.Resolution: Perform a Virtual Reseat operation, and then retry the operation. To virtually reseat a server 1) Using the CMC Web UI, go to Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components, and then select slot for the component identified in the message and apply the Virtual Reseat or 2) Run the following RACADM command at the command line interface: "racadm serveraction -f -m sled-<slot number> reseat".
SWU8556.Description: The sled network uplink on the sled identified in the message could not be configured. The servers on the sled may not have expected network connectivity.

RAC0752.Description: The value for information or warning threshold should not be greater than upper critical threshold value.
RAC0752.Resolution: Enter a threshold value that is lower than the upper warning or critical threshold values and retry the operation.
RAC0752.Message: The threshold value entered is greater than the upper warning or critical threshold.

HWC8502.Description: The internal cable that connects the I/O panel to the system board is properly connected.
HWC8502.Message: The I/O panel cable is connected.

MEM1009.Message: Memory device at location %1 failed to transition to offline.

OSD62.Description: The command cannot be run because an invalid firmware image file name is entered.
OSD62.Resolution: Make sure that a valid firmware image file is entered. The file must not contain any file path components such as forward slash (/) or period (.).
OSD62.Message: Unable to run the command because an invalid firmware image file name is entered.

UEFI0219.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0219.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0219.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Read Timing Centering 2D Training phase.

LC032.Description: This method is not supported in the current version of iDRAC firmware.
LC032.Resolution: Update the iDRAC firmware to a version that supports this method.
LC032.Message: The Hardware Inventory Export method not supported.

PR14.Message: The configuration could not be applied to device: %1
PR14.Resolution: Check the current system configuration and retry the operation.
PR14.Description: The device identified in the message could not apply the configuration settings. This may indicate configuration changes since the last system inventory.

RAC1157.Resolution: Verify whether or not the entered FQDD is valid. Run the command 'racadm gethostnetworkinterfaces' for the list of valid FQDDs.
RAC1157.Message: Unable to find the specified FQDD.

OSD15.Description: Unable to mount the network share using the credentials specified in the command because either the username or password is incorrect.
OSD15.Resolution: Rerun the command with the correct username and password.
OSD15.Message: Mount network share failed - incorrect username or password.

OSD063.Description: The process of installing an operating system or hypervisor is successfully completed.
OSD063.Message: The process of installing an operating system or hypervisor is successfully completed.

FAN0009.Description: The fan may be required for optimal performance.

RAC923.Description: The specified file path (specified with the f parameter) is too long. This path should be less than 64 characters in length.
RAC923.Resolution: Try the same command with a shorter file path (specified with the f parameter) which is less than 64 characters in length.
RAC923.Message: The file path is too long.

BAT0005.Description: To charge the battery, the system has to remain powered on.
BAT0005.Resolution: Allow the PERC RAID controller battery to charge. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

PDR50.Message: Insufficient space on the global hot spare %1.
PDR50.Resolution: Assign a larger disk as the global hot spare.
PDR50.Description: The global hot spare is not large enough to protect all virtual disks that reside on the controller.

CMC8501.Description: Multi Chassis Management feature on CMC allows for pushing the lead chassis configuration data to it's members. This message appears in the member's log when the configuration data is successfully synchronized with the Chassis group leader's configuration data.
CMC8501.Message: Chassis Group Leader has synchronized this member's configuration.

RAC044.Description: Some event filter settings were not updated due to problems encountered processing the input parameters.
RAC044.Resolution: Verify the input parameters provided and retry the operation. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
RAC044.Message: Unable to update some event filter settings.

RAC926.Description: The value given for the recurrence interval is invalid. It has to be a value from 0 to 365.
RAC926.Resolution: Change the argument of r to a value from 0 to 365 and then run the same command.
RAC926.Message: The recurrence interval needs to be an integer from 0 to 365.

CPU0006.Message: Unrecoverable CPU complex error detected on CPU %1.
CPU0006.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
CPU0006.Description: System is unable to boot or may run in a degraded state.

SYS065.Description: An internal error occurred opening the input configuration XML file. An iDRAC reset is required.
SYS065.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation.
SYS065.Message: Input file for import configuration operation cannot be found or opened.

HWC3002.Resolution: If removal was unintended, check presence, then re-insert.

MEM9001.Description: The memory interconnect is functioning normally.

RAC1119.Description: The command could not be successfully run because of one or more of the following reasons:1. The command does not have "--verifycatalog" in it.2. The updates available on the repository are not applicable for the operation that is requested.
RAC1119.Resolution: To generate a comparison report, type "--verifycatalog" in the racadm command, and then retry the operation.
RAC1119.Message: Unable to generate a comparison report for the specified repository.

PDR49.Message: The dedicated hot spare %1 is too small.
PDR49.Resolution: Assign a larger disk as the dedicated hot spare.
PDR49.Description: The dedicated hot spare is not large enough to protect all virtual disks that reside on the disk group.

MEM1201.Message: Memory RAID redundancy is lost. Check memory device at location(s) %1.
MEM1201.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem continues, contact support.

CPU0805.Message: The power input for CPU %1 voltage regulator module is outside of range, but it is attached to the system.
CPU0805.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
CPU0805.Description: System performance may be degraded or the system may fail to operate.

VLT0222.Message: The %1 voltage is outside of range.
VLT0222.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions 2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0222.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition. If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

IOV108.Message: Power fault detected on PCIE adapter %1 in %2 %3.
IOV108.Resolution: Make sure a supported PCIe device is used and that it is properly inserted in the PCIe slot. For a list of supported devices, contact your service provider.
IOV108.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected a power fault in an adapter after the adapter was powered on. A power fault may be caused by a damaged adapter or the adapter power requirements exceed the maximum power limits of the slot.

BAT0009.Description: The PERC RAID controller battery may report absent due to disconnect or thermal exceptions.
BAT0009.Resolution: 1) Verify the PERC RAID controller battery installation.2) If installed, reseat or reconnect the battery and cables. 3) Check the system logs for thermal related issues.

SWC5005.Description: The System Controller (SC) firmware cannot be updated. For information about the causes, see SEL Event Data Byte 2.
SWC5005.Resolution: Retry the SC firmware update operation. If the issue persists, try updating by using a different firmware update file.
SWC5005.Message: Unable to update the System Controller (SC) firmware.

SWC0107.Description: The command takes in only one option which is the Session ID.
SWC0107.Resolution: Enter the command only with one option i.e. the Session ID.
SWC0107.Message: More than one option is not allowed with this command.

HWC1102.Message: The %1 is installed in an unsupported slot %2.
HWC1102.Resolution: Install the Storage sled in a supported slot and retry the operation. For information about the supported sleds and slots, see the User's Guide available at the support site.
HWC1102.Description: The peripheral sled identified in the message is installed in the unsupported slot identified in the message.

SWC8622.Message: Quick Deploy Profile: Unable to access remote network share and apply assigned profile to the server in slot %1.
SWC8622.Resolution: Make sure that the remote network share settings in the CMC are correct and that the remote share NFS/CIFS server is functioning correctly. Use the "Test Network" button in the CMC Web interface to make sure that the CMC can access the remote share.
SWC8622.Description: The remote network share settings are accessible on the CMC web interface at Server Overview/Setup/Remote Network Share tab. These settings must be correct for the CMC to connect to the remote network share and perform the application of the profile as specified in the Quick Deploy tab on the Profiles page.

CMC8534.Message: Unable to turn on the server %1 because the power requirement request exceeds the power cap value.
CMC8534.Resolution: In the CMC Web interface, verify the available power and server power requirements. If sufficient power is available, retry the operation. Otherwise, increase the power cap value.
CMC8534.Description: Unable to turn on the server specified in the message, because the available power is lesser than the requested power.

UEFI0255.Description: Network Daughter Card 1 and Network Daughter Card 2 in the system do not match.
UEFI0255.Resolution: Check the Network Daughter Cards and make sure they are the same type.
UEFI0255.Message: Network Daughter Card 1 and Network Daughter Card 2 in the system do not match.

CTL100.Message: The Patrol Read operation was stopped and did not complete for %1.
CTL100.Description: The Patrol Read operation running on the controller was stopped by user request or an issue was detected by the controller.

PST0208.Description: System BIOS has halted and is unable to continue.
PST0208.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) If new hardware has been added, remove the new hardware and restart the server, 2) Turn server off and back on using the power button, or 3) Remove and reapply server input power. If the problem persists, contact your service provider. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

RAC998.Description: IPv6 cannot be enabled if iDRAC NIC is disabled.
RAC998.Resolution: Enable iDRAC NIC using "racadm set iDRAC.NIC.Enable < 1 | Enabled >" command and retry the operation.

SUP0124.Message: Firmware update is not currently in progress

ENC4.Resolution: Download the same version of the firmware to both EMM modules.
ENC4.Description: The firmware on the EMM modules is not the same version. It is required that both modules have the same version of the firmware. This alert may be caused when you attempt to insert an EMM module that has a different firmware version than an existing module.

RAC949.Description: The specified work note was added to the Lifecycle Log.
RAC949.Resolution: View the work notes using the racadm lclog view c worknotes command.
RAC949.Message: Successfully added a work note to the Lifecycle Log.

SWC1931.Description: The iDRAC Quick Sync inactivity timeout configuration is disabled. The iDRAC Quick Sync feature will remain available after pressing the activate button.
SWC1931.Message: The iDRAC Quick Sync inactivity timeout configuration is disabled.

SWC0041.Description: The specified source file location is incorrect.
SWC0041.Resolution: Make sure that the specified source file location is correct and retry the operation.
SWC0041.Message: Unable to copy the backup Server Configuration Profile.

SWC8516.Message: Unable to modify privileges of User %1: %2-%3
SWC8516.Resolution: Make sure: 1) The login credentials for the operation have user config administration privilege, 2) The user name given is valid. If the issue persists, restart the CMC and retry the operation.
SWC8516.Description: Unable to modify privileges of the User identified in the message.

SUP024.Description: The InstanceID value provided for update operation is invalid.
SUP024.Resolution: Enumerate inventory, copy the InstanceID value and provide that value for the update operation.
SUP024.Message: InstanceID value provided for the update operation is invalid

RAC0124.Description: All characters in the label must be alphanumeric.
RAC0124.Message: Invalid label: Label must be exclusively alphanumeric characters.

STOR011.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the stripe size entered is not supported by the controller.
STOR011.Resolution: Enter a valid stripe size and retry the operation.
STOR011.Message: Stripe size not supported on controller.

ISM0018.Description: The OS Collector application is started on the server Operating System.
ISM0018.Message: The OS Collector application is successfully started on the server operating system (OS).

SWC0271.Description: The syntax for the config command is invalid.
SWC0271.Resolution: Refer to the help text for the 'config' subcommand.
SWC0271.Message: Invalid syntax. The -f option is only valid with -p and -c.

SYS131.Description: Unable to communicate with the OS IPMI service because the service is not running.
SYS131.Resolution: For more information about checking whether the IPMI service is running, see the iDRAC8 User's Guide.
SYS131.Message: OS Collector: Unable to communicate with the OS IPMI service.

LC018.Description: The certificate modification operation was successful. Communication to iDRAC will be lost as iDRAC restarts to use the new server certificate.
LC018.Message: Server certificate successfully modified. iDRAC will now restart and be unavailable during restart.

PWR2256.Description: The chassis infrastructure components are being initialized and are not ready to grant power on permission to the servers.
PWR2256.Resolution: Wait until the chassis infrastructure has been initialized and then retry the operation. To check that the infrastructure is initialized, using the RACADM command line utility run the command "racadm getmodinfo" and check that the "pwrstate" field is on for the chassis component.
PWR2256.Message: Unable to allocate power for servers to turn on because the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is initializing chassis infrastructure components.

SWC0111.Description: The serveraction subcommand requires an option to be specified.
SWC0111.Resolution: Refer the help for serveraction subcommand, and enter a valid option.
SWC0111.Message: A server action command must be specified.

SWC8526.Message: Unable to delete Chassis Group member %1 (%2)
SWC8526.Resolution: Make sure the member identified in the message exists as a member of the Chassis Group. Use the CMC web interface to select the lead chassis, select the setup tab, and then select the group administration sub tab and check if the member exists. If the member exists, restart the group leader and retry the operation.
SWC8526.Description: Unable to delete Chassis Group member identified in the message. Another user may have deleted the member before the operation or the group may have been disbanded.

STOR0105.Description: No enclosure data to display. The system is powered off, enclosures are not present on the system, or enclosures are not connected to the RAID controllers.
STOR0105.Resolution: Check if the server has power, enclosures are available, and enclosures are connected to the RAID controllers.

RAC1007.Resolution: Wait until the specified job is completed, or reboot the system to move the job to Completed state. To view the job status, use"racadm jobqueue view -i <Job ID>".
RAC1007.Description: The job specified in the message cannot be deleted when it is Running, Scheduled, or transitioning from Downloading to Scheduled.

SWC0013.Description: The operation to save the front panel security settings encountered an unexpected error while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0013.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0013.Message: Unable to save the front panel security settings.

SWC0115.Description: The syntax of the setniccfg command is invalid.
SWC0115.Resolution: Refer the help text for setniccfg subcommand.
SWC0115.Message: The -s option cannot be used with any other options.

PDR11.Description: A user has cancelled the rebuild operation.

SWC0225.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0225.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0225.Message: Invalid syntax. The -d option is not valid with -l.

BAR050.Description: The firmware update for the specified device in progress.

SEC0006.Description: The fan area is open. System performance may be degraded.
SEC0006.Resolution: Close the fan area. Check system logs.

SEC0043.Description: TXT POST cannot be completed because system configuration may have changed.
SEC0043.Resolution: Check system hardware inventory for TPM presence, clear and reconfigure TPM and TXT in BIOS setup menu.
SEC0043.Message: BIOS Authenticated Code Module detected an Intel Trusted Execution Technology (TXT) problem during POST.

SWC0702.Description: Power capping is disabled and sets recommended limits for the system.

SWC0277.Description: The syntax for the config command is invalid.
SWC0277.Resolution: Refer to the help text for the 'config' subcommand.
SWC0277.Message: Invalid syntax. The -i option is only valid with -g and -o.

IOID005.Message: Storage Initiator Persistence Policy setting is changed to %1.
IOID005.Description: The Storage Initiator Persistence Policy setting is changed to the restart type identified in the message.

STOR024.Description: Configuration changes for the specified device are already scheduled.
STOR024.Message: Unable to create a configuration job because a configuration job for the device already exists.

VLT0226.Message: The memory module %1 voltage is greater than the upper warning threshold.
VLT0226.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0226.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

PWR8602.Description: The power buttons for all multinode sleds in the chassis are enabled. The operation to enable the power button is only applicable to the multinode sleds available, and does not affect other servers in the chassis.
PWR8602.Resolution: To disable the chassis power button use the CMC RACADM command line interface (CLI) or CMC Web interface. At the CLI, enter "racadm config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisSledPowerButtonEnable 0". Using the Web interface, click Server Overview > Power > Control. Select the "Disable power button for all multinode sleds in the chassis" check box.
PWR8602.Message: The multinode sled power button is enabled.

CPU0011.Message: Uncorrectable Machine Check Exception detected on CPU %1.
CPU0011.Resolution: Review System Event Log and Operating System Logs. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

PCI1318.Message: A fatal error was detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.
PCI1318.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1318.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.

NIC017.Description: Unable to delete vFlash pending one-time boot configuration.
NIC017.Resolution: Remove AC power from system and after restoring AC power, retry the operation.
NIC017.Message: Unable to delete vFlash pending one-time boot configuration

RAC0268.Description: The NIC is disabled. This may adversely affect the current operation, and might not allow subsequent GUI interactions to this NIC.
RAC0268.Resolution: Enable the NIC before performing the operation.

SYS016.Description: All the operations in the Job were attempted, but some did not complete successfully.
SYS016.Resolution: Review the Job content and verify the values are correct. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller Remote Services documentation.

RAC0657.Description: The file name cannot be blank when performing the Backup Server Profile operation.
RAC0657.Resolution: Enter an appropriate file name, and then retry the operation.
RAC0657.Message: The file name field must not be blank.

CMC8614.Message: The reset process of iDRAC Non Maskable Interrupt (NMI) on server %1 is initiated.
CMC8614.Description: The reset process of iDRAC Non Maskable Interrupt (NMI) on server identified in the message is initiated.

VLT0225.Message: The memory module %1 voltage is less than the lower critical threshold.
VLT0225.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0225.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

RAC0115.Description: The IPv4 address does not conform to the addressing standard or the supported IPv4 address range.
RAC0115.Resolution: Enter the Destination IP Address value between [1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].
RAC0115.Message: The Destination IP Address value is invalid.

PSU0076.Message: A power supply wattage mismatch is detected; power supply %1 is rated for %2 watts.
PSU0076.Resolution: Install matched power supplies and review product documentation for proper configuration.
PSU0076.Description: Power supplies should be of the same input type and power rating.

RAC0150.Description: While the system is powered off it is unable to retrieve information about system intrusion.
RAC0150.Resolution: Turn the system on to view this information.
RAC0150.Message: Unable to retrieve the intrusion sensor information. The system is powered off.

STOR090.Description: Unable to create a virtual disk because an invalid combination of span count or disks passed was entered for the RAID level selected.
STOR090.Resolution: Enter a span count value (-sc option) or number of disks (-pdkey option) that is appropriate for the RAID level selected. See the PERC Controller Users Guide for valid span count and number of disks required for a raid level. Retry the operation by running the RACADM storage createvd command with the appropriate options.
STOR090.Message: Unable to create a virtual disk because an invalid combination of span count or number of disks was entered for the RAID level selected.

PDR98.Resolution: Check the disk is present or replace the disk.
PDR98.Description: An error occurred while performing an action on the disk.

VF031.Description: The specified partition label is not a valid label.
VF031.Resolution: Try a label that complies with the standards for an OS volume label.

VFL0005.Description: There are no vFlash partitions available currently for the display.

STOR012.Description: One or more of the specified physical disks cannot be used for the operation requested. Physical disk protocol and media type, along with other physical disk characteristics like Secure Encryption and T10 protection, need to match the requirements of the requested operation.
STOR012.Resolution: Make sure the specified physical disk has the appropriate protocol and media type for the requested operation. Specify a different physical disk with a state appropriate for the requested operation and retry the operation.
STOR012.Message: Provided Physical disk not valid for this operation.

ISM0003.Description: The iDRAC Service Module could not successfully discover iDRAC from the server OS. However, the iDRAC Service Module will continue the discovery operation. Make sure that the IPMI drivers are enabled on the server operating system.
ISM0003.Message: The iDRAC Service Module is unable to discover iDRAC from the operating system of the server.

BIOS028.Description: The BIOS password cannot be simultaneously configured by using plain text and a hash.
BIOS028.Resolution: Wait until the current password configuration process is completed and retry the operation.
BIOS028.Message: Unable to change the BIOS password using plain text because the password is currently being configured using a hash.

SWU8522.Message: Unable to update the iDRAC on the server in %1 firmware: ErrorCode=0x%2.
SWU8522.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the original source, and then retry the operation.
SWU8522.Description: The firmware update operation is not successful.

PDR6.Resolution: Force the physical disk online or assign a hot spare to the virtual disk.
PDR6.Description: A physical disk in the virtual disk is offline. This may have been user initiated.

CMC8568.Description: The DVD drive is disabled and is not mapped to any of the server slots.
CMC8568.Message: The DVD drive mapping feature is disabled.

RAC0160.Description: Certificate upload failed because the certificate could not be validated.
RAC0160.Resolution: Certificate may be corrupt. Try creating a new Certificate Signing Request (CSR) and then upload the certificate.
RAC0160.Message: Certificate upload failed: Cannot validate the certificate.

RAC057.Message: Unable to set Privacy Protocol to an enabled state because the Authentication Protocol attribute is set to None for the user ID: %1
RAC057.Resolution: Enable the Authentication Protocol attribute for the identified user ID account, and retry the operation to set the Privacy Protocol to an enabled state.
RAC057.Description: The Privacy Protocol for the user cannot be enabled because the Authentication protocol is disabled.

MEM8000.Message: Correctable memory error logging disabled for a memory device at location %1.
MEM8000.Resolution: Review system logs for memory exceptions. Re-install memory at location <location>.
MEM8000.Description: Errors are being corrected but no longer logged.

RED019.Description: Reinstall or Rollback cannot be performed since no applicable firmware was found on the Lifecycle Controller.
RED019.Resolution: Directly update to the desired version.
RED019.Message: Reinstall or Rollback cannot be performed since no applicable firmware was found on the Lifecycle Controller.

VLT0215.Message: The disk drive bay %1 voltage is greater than the upper critical threshold.
VLT0215.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat hard disks in the bay. Reconnect all cables attached to the bay.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0215.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

SWC0011.Description: The front panel security settings were successfully configured.
SWC0011.Message: Successfully applied front panel security settings.

VDR17.Resolution: Replace the failed physical disk. Identify the failed physical disk by locating the disk that has a red "X" for its status. Rebuild the physical disk. When finished, restart the virtual disk format operation.
VDR17.Description: A physical disk included in the virtual disk failed.

OSD17.Description: Unable to expose the ISO image as an internal CD device to the host system because the ISO file is no longer present, network errors are preventing access to the ISO file, or iDRAC may not be responsive.
OSD17.Resolution: 1) Rerun the command. 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD17.Message: Exposing ISO image as internal device to the server failed.

SYS059.Description: Configuration changes for the component identified by the Fully Qualified Device Descriptor (FQDD) were successfully applied.
SYS059.Resolution: No response action is required. See Lifecycle Log for details.

PDR46.Message: Patrol Read found an uncorrectable media error on %1.
PDR46.Resolution: Backup your data from the disk. Start disk initialization and wait for it to complete, then restore the data from the backup to the disk.
PDR46.Description: The Patrol Read task has encountered an error that cannot be corrected. There may be a bad disk block that cannot be remapped.

PCI1302.Message: A bus time-out was detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.
PCI1302.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1302.Description: System performance may be degraded. The device has failed to respond to a transaction (master/target abort or completion timeout).

IOV003.Description: A PCIe device error was detected that does not allow the assignment, unassignment, or the turning off of the device. The errors can be caused by incorrect PCIe device installation or installation of an unsupported PCIe adapter card. For a list of supported PCIe adapter cards contact your service provider.
IOV003.Resolution: Make sure that supported adapters are used and installed correctly in the PCIe slots.
IOV003.Message: Unable to manage the device located in the PCIe slot specified in the operation.

FAN0001.Message: Fan %1 RPM is less than the lower critical threshold.
FAN0001.Resolution: Remove and re-install the fan. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0001.Description: The fan is not performing optimally. The fan may be installed improperly or may be failing.

PDR1021.Message: Drive %1 in disk drive bay %2 is no longer in the critical array.

SEC0031.Description: The chassis is open. System performance may be degraded, and security may be compromised.
SEC0031.Resolution: Close the chassis. Check system logs.
SEC0031.Message: The chassis is open while the power is on.

UEFI0156.Description: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology (DPAT) Enterprise license in three consecutive boots. The Number of Cores per Processor and the Dell Controlled Turbo BIOS setup options are being reverted to default because of the absent license.
UEFI0156.Resolution: If the absence of license is expected, no action is necessary. Otherwise do one of the following: 1) Reload the license. 2) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 3) Update the iDRAC firmware.
UEFI0156.Message: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology (DPAT) Enterprise license in three consecutive boots. The Number of Cores per Processor and the Dell Controlled Turbo BIOS setup options are being reverted to default because of the absent license.

FCD8503.Message: The feature is activated in the chassis: %1
FCD8503.Description: Chassis already has the feature identified in the message activated. Only one instance of a feature can be activated at a time. If the feature must be activated on the new card, it must be deactivated before activating.

BAR086.Description: The system profile import of Lifecycle Controller configuration data has failed.
BAR086.Resolution: If collect system inventory on reboot (CSIOR) is not enabled, enter and exit System Services in USC to update the database, reboot the system and try the operation again. If the error continues, use the field service repair software to repair the Lifecycle Controller. Download all Dell Update Packages for USC, Diagnostics Driver Packs, and device firmware for all host system devices, install all packages and retry the operation.
BAR086.Message: Unable to Restore The Lifecycle Controller Configuration database.

RED068.Resolution: For more information about the job, view the job queue.
RED068.Description: Unable to successfully complete the job identified in the message.

ISM0009.Description: iDRAC Service Module detected that OpenManage Server Administrator is not running on the OS of this server. Therefore, one or more features of iDRAC Service Module that were earlier disabled are now enabled on this server.
ISM0009.Message: The features of iDRAC Service Module that were disabled will be enabled on this server, because OpenManage Server Administrator is not running on the operating system (OS) of this server.

SYS1002.Description: System is performing a power cycle.
SYS1002.Message: System is performing a power cycle.

JCP005.Description: System services was cancelled by selecting CTRL+E or F2 on boot up and cancelling it through the iDRAC configuration utility. This prevents jobs from executing further.
JCP005.Resolution: For 11G systems: Use the iDRAC configuration utility to enable the System Services by pressing on the CTRL+E option on boot up at the targeted system. For 12G and above generations: Use F2 Setup, select iDRAC Configuration, and select Lifecycle Controller Settings, to enable the Lifecycle Controller on boot up of the targeted system.

RAC0273.Description: If the Enable NIC checkbox is cleared, remote access to iDRAC is disabled.
RAC0273.Resolution: Enable remote access to access iDRAC remotely.
RAC0273.Message: iDRAC access will be limited to running the Racadm utility on the local server or using the serial interface.

CMC8553.Description: An internal I2C hardware occurred and CMC initiated a failover to clear the hardware error. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8553.Message: An internal error occurred and a failover condition is detected.

JCP027.Message: The (installation or configuration) job %1 is successfully created on iDRAC.
JCP027.Description: The (installation or configuration) job identified in the message is successfully created on iDRAC.

BAR084.Description: System profile backup file validation failed because the host system service tag information does not match the value stored in the file.
BAR084.Resolution: Obtain a valid host system backup image and try the operation again. Reboot the remote access controller and try the operation again. If the error continues, download a new remote access controller firmware image and try the operation again.
BAR084.Message: Host System Service Tag does not match the Backup file Service Tag.

RAC0714.Description: Server failed to power up due to noncontinuous power action.
RAC0714.Resolution: Utilize the Chassis Management Controller web interface to check available power and server power requirements. If sufficient power is available, allocate power necessary and retry the operation.
RAC0714.Message: Server failed to power up due to noncontinuous power action.

SYS194.Description: The Collection of System Inventory successfully completed by Lifecycle Controller firmware.
SYS194.Message: The Collection of System Inventory successfully completed.

VDR48.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes. The virtual disk has inconsistent data. This may be caused when a power loss or system shutdown occurs while data is being written to the virtual disk.

UEFI0288.Description: The Memory Multi-rank Sparing feature cannot be enabled because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the feature.
UEFI0288.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure Memory Multi-rank Sparing feature can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0288.Message: Unable to enable the Memory Multi-rank Sparing feature because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the feature.

RAC0600.Description: Temperature information cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the server is powered off.
RAC0600.Resolution: Power on the server. If the server is already powered on, wait for a few minutes and refresh the page. If the problem persists, contact service provider.
RAC0600.Message: Unable to retrieve the temperature information.

SWC0232.Description: Remote RACADM commands are not supported on the current iDRAC.
SWC0232.Resolution: If remote RACADM is a necessity, upgrade the iDRAC version.
SWC0232.Message: Remote RACADM commands are not supported on this iDRAC. To upgrade your iDRAC version, contact your service provider.

PCI3017.Message: Device option ROM on mezzanine card was successfully updated.

RAC0126.Description: The label field is empty. A label is required to create an empty partition.
RAC0126.Resolution: Enter a label that contains one to six alphanumeric characters.
RAC0126.Message: The label value is invalid. Expected range: 1-6 alphanumeric characters.

DIS112.Message: The AutoConfig operation is using the %1 file.
DIS112.Description: The AutoConfig operation is using the file identified in the message.

SWC0723.Description: iDRAC is not responding to the current Reset status query.
SWC0723.Message: Error occurred while Resetting to defaults. The Reset status is not available.

USR104.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an unknown error in iDRAC.
USR104.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC.
USR104.Message: Unable to perform the operation due to an unknown error in iDRAC.

DKM1002.Message: Key management server certificate problem detected.

CTL29.Message: The Patrol Read rate has changed for %1.
CTL29.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC1064.Description: Unable to initiate the requested SystemErase operation because another SystemErase job is already in progress.
RAC1064.Resolution: To check the job status, run the RACADM command "racadm jobqueue view" and retry the operation after the current SystemErase operation has completed.
RAC1064.Message: Unable to initiate the SystemErase operation because another instance of SystemErase job is already in progress.

PWR8664.Message: The Dynamic Power Supply Engagement feature is %1.
PWR8664.Description: The power configuration property dynamic power supply engagement feature is disabled or enabled as identified in the message.

PST0089.Description: A problem was detected during Power-On Self-Test (POST). The next logged message contains more specific details for the detected issue.
PST0089.Resolution: Review the next logged message for the recommended response action to resolve the problem.
PST0089.Message: A problem was detected during Power-On Self-Test (POST).

BIOS027.Message: Unable to change the BIOS password because the password is currently being configured using plain text. Unable to set the attribute %1.
BIOS027.Resolution: Wait until the current password configuration process is completed, and then retry the operation.
BIOS027.Description: The attribute identified in the message cannot be set, because the password is currently being reset by using plain text. The BIOS password cannot be simultaneously configured by using plain text and a hash.

VFL0715.Resolution: Contact the administrator for the required permissions and try again.
VFL0715.Message: Error occurred while initializing the SD Card due to insufficient permission.

RAC011.Description: A Job has already been scheduled to apply pending iDRAC attribute values. Additional configuration operations are not allowed while there is a configuration Job pending execution.
RAC011.Resolution: Wait for the scheduled Job to complete before setting more attributes.
RAC011.Message: A configuration Job already exists, cannot process more set operations.

UEFI0021.Description: The Lifecycle Controller feature is disabled. The feature was disabled because of one of the following conditions: 1) The feature was disabled manually using the F2 System Setup utility or through an iDRAC interface, 2) BIOS encountered an issue starting the feature and automatically disabled it.
UEFI0021.Resolution: To enable the Lifecycle Controller (LC) feature using F2 System Setup, select the iDRAC Settings > Lifecycle Controller and then select Enabled. If LC becomes disabled automatically, update the Lifecycle Controller firmware or apply the Lifecycle Controller Repair Package.
UEFI0021.Message: The Lifecycle Controller feature is disabled.

SWC0722.Description: iDRAC is processing a previous reset to default command.
SWC0722.Message: Error occurred while resetting to defaults. The reset command was not accepted.

UEFI0052.Description: The rebranding process cannot be completed because of the reasons identified on the computer screen.
UEFI0052.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Update the iDRAC firmware. 2) Update the system BIOS. 3) Update the OEM ID module.
UEFI0052.Message: Unable to complete the rebranding operation because of the issue(s) displayed earlier.

VF011.Description: The specified password was not correct.

MEM1016.Message: Memory device at location %1 is not installed correctly.
MEM1016.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem continues, contact support.
MEM1016.Description: The memory may not be seated correctly, misconfigured, or has failed. Memory size is reduced.

SWC0725.Description: iDRAC is busy and does not respond to iDRAC configurator IPMI requests.
SWC0725.Resolution: Try AC power cycling the server or upgrade the iDRAC firmware.

UEFI0004.Description: A CPU invalid opcode exception (type 0x06) occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment. The software attempted to execute invalid code.
UEFI0004.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.

PDR70.Description: A copyback operation began to copy data from one physical disk to another physical disk. This may be due to a user initiated operation or a predictive failure.

RAC0618.Description: The data entered caused an error while processing the request.
RAC0618.Resolution: Make sure to enter the correct data and retry the operation.

SEL1510.Message: An authentication error detected for Chassis Group Member %1.
SEL1510.Description: Group master CMC could not log into the group member CMC.

FAN907.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is already enabled.
FAN907.Message: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is already enabled.

LC076.Description: Unable to perform the Custom Signed Certificate (CSC) certificate delete operation. This may be due to IPMI communications issues.
LC076.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and retry the operation.
LC076.Message: Unable to perform the Custom Signed Certificate (CSC) certificate delete operation.

SWC0315.Description: The getconfig subcommand failed to get the object value.

DIS100.Description: The AutoConfig operation is successfully completed by the iDRAC using the AutoConfig import file specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

LC043.Description: Work notes cannot include non-printable or reserved characters, such as &, <, >, /.
LC043.Resolution: Do not use non-printable characters or reserved characters such as &, <, >, and /.
LC043.Message: Work note contains non-printable or reserved characters.

SWC8501.Resolution: Check if iDRAC is ready and system is running properly. Utilize the RACADM command by running "racadm getversion" to list all the servers and make sure the iDRAC version is displayed. If the iDRAC is listed as Not Ready then wait until it becomes ready. A Virtual Reseat may be required.

USR8509.Message: Login was not successful (username=%1, ip=%2, error=0x%3, type=%4)
USR8509.Resolution: Contact the administrator and ensure the username and password credentials used are correct. Retry the operation with valid credentials.
USR8509.Description: The login attempt with details specified in the message was not successful.

UEFI0186.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.
UEFI0186.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0186.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the DC Detection phase.

LC004.Description: The Provisioning Server parameter information is not formatted correctly.
LC004.Resolution: Verify the string format. Enter a valid IP address or hostname for the Provisioning Server such as: 1) hostname 2) hostname.domain.com 3) 1.1.1.1 4) hostname:8080 5) hostname.dell.com:8080 6) hostname1:80,hostname2:8080.
LC004.Message: Provisioning Server information is not formatted correctly.

RED017.Description: The DUP specified is not compatible with the target system.
RED017.Resolution: Download and use the DUP that matches the system that the installation is targeting.
RED017.Message: The DUP specified is not compatible with the target system.

CTL113.Message: The controller %1 is operating in Degraded Fault Tolerant Mode because of a mismatch between the encryption key setting of the controller and its peer controller.
CTL113.Resolution: Make sure that the encryption key for the peer controllers matches by using controller security operations such as creating a security key, modifying a security key, deleting a security key, and then power-cycle the chassis. Make sure to use same encryption key identifier on two controllers joining cluster.
CTL113.Description: The controller identified in the message is operating in Degraded Fault Tolerant Mode because of a mismatch between the encryption key setting of controller and its peer controller.

SWC8539.Message: The key delete operation successfully completed for slot %1 of service account.
SWC8539.Description: The Public Key (PK) SSH Authentication key file delete operation is successfully completed for the slot identified in the message.

SEL1501.Description: An action or failure has taken place that breaks CMC redundancy. This includes loss of network connection, hardware failures, firmware update, firmware mismatch between CMC's, CMC reset, and unplugging a CMC.
SEL1501.Resolution: Check CMC network cables and network connections. Check that CMC firmware versions match.
SEL1501.Message: Chassis management controller (CMC) redundancy is lost.

UEFI0037.Description: Unable to communicate with iDRAC because of an issue in the iDRAC Shared Memory Architecture (SMA) Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI). Continuing to boot may result in unexpected power loss because of unknown power inventory and unavailability of features such as active power management, thermal management.
UEFI0037.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware on the system.
UEFI0037.Message: Unable to communicate with iDRAC because of an issue in the iDRAC Shared Memory Architecture (SMA) Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI).

UEFI0029.Description: iDRAC could not be initialized because of some critical issues. Continuing to boot may result in unexpected power loss because of unknown power inventory and unavailability of features such as remote out of band access, active power management, thermal management, inventory collection, LCD, or system error reporting.
UEFI0029.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. 3) Continue to boot. Note: This may result in unexpected power loss because of unknown power inventory and unavailability of features such as remote out of band access, active power management, thermal management, inventory collection, LCD, or system error reporting.
UEFI0029.Message: Unable to initialize iDRAC because of some critical issues.

RAC977.Description: The configuration XML file import operation was initiated.
RAC977.Resolution: Use the racadm jobqueue view i <Job ID> command to view the status of the operation.
RAC977.Message: Import configuration XML file operation initiated.

MEM0010.Message: Memory device at location %1 is overheating.
MEM0010.Resolution: If unexpected, review system logs for power or thermal exceptions.

SWC0241.Description: To modify this property, set the Power Cap Enable option.
SWC0241.Resolution: Set the Power Cap Enable object and modify the required property.
SWC0241.Message: Power Cap Enable not set. Unable to modify this property.

SWC0119.Description: The syntax of the sslcertview command is invalid.
SWC0119.Resolution: Refer the help text for sslcertview subcommand.
SWC0119.Message: Invalid certificate type specified with -t option.

DIS003.Description: Auto Discovery process will try to connect to a Provisioning Server over the next 24 hours.

BAR062.Description: Collecting the Lifecycle Controller configuration database and copying it into the server profile backup file.

RAC037.Description: There are no pending configurations to delete.

RAC0637.Description: The requested network file share cannot be accessed, because an invalid proxy user name is entered.
RAC0637.Resolution: Enter a valid proxy user name, and then retry the operation.
RAC0637.Message: Unable to access the network file share, because an invalid proxy user name is entered.

RAC0241.Message: The specified size exceeds the maximum size of %1 MB.
RAC0241.Resolution: Delete existing data or insert a SD card of greater size and retry.
RAC0241.Description: SD Card does not have enough free space available.

SWC8536.Message: Unable to add key for slot %1 of service account, due to corrupt key.
SWC8536.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8536.Description: The add key operation did not complete successfully for the slot identified in the message due to the key being invalid or corrupt.

SWC0280.Resolution: Enter the command with a valid index for the group.
SWC0280.Description: The group is indexed and an index needs to be specified.

ISM0017.Message: The BMC watchdog auto-recovery action is changed from %1 to %2.
ISM0017.Description: The BMC watchdog auto-recovery action is changed from the original action identified in the message to the new action identified in the message.

OSD12.Description: iDRAC was unable to create and expose the drivers as a USB device for the OS installation to proceed.
OSD12.Resolution: 1) Rerun the command. 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD12.Message: Cannot create the USB device needed to copy drivers for the selected operating system.

RAC1182.Description: The server instrumentation can not provide any information related to power because PMBus capability is not present or the PSU(s) with PMBus capability have been removed.
RAC1182.Message: Unable to retrieve information for the Power group or attribute because the server is not PMBus capable.

PST0129.Description: System BIOS detected memory, but was unable to configure the memory for system operation. Compare system memory installation to supported system memory configurations. Reduce the system to minimum memory configuration if acceptable. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video.(BIOS POST Exception Code 81).
