PST0129.Resolution: Compare system memory installation to supported system memory configurations.
PST0129.Message: Memory is detected, but is not configurable.

SYS420.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the Redfish URI version %1 is not supported.
SYS420.Resolution: Enter a valid URI version and retry the operation. For information about valid URI versions, see the Redfish User's Guide available on the support site.
SYS420.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the Redfish URI version identified in the message is not supported.

SYS431.Description: The import or export configuration changes cannot be applied because an import or export operation is currently in progress.
SYS431.Resolution: Wait for the current import or export operation to complete and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SYS431.Message: Unable to apply the configuration changes because an import or export operation is currently in progress.

TMP0202.Message: CPU %1 temperature is greater than the upper warning threshold.
TMP0202.Resolution: Check system operating environment, fans, and heatsinks.

SWC8561.Description: Some or all or the specified MAC addresses are removed from the Virtual MAC Address Pool. Some MAC addresses could not be removed because they were not present.
SWC8561.Message: Some or all or the specified MAC addresses are removed from the Virtual MAC Address Pool of Boot Identity profile operations.

TMP8503.Message: Temperature of NIC adapter in slot %1 is greater than normal operating range possibly due to an issue in the cooling system or a fan that is no longer functioning correctly.
TMP8503.Resolution: The cooling system may have issues. Contact your authorized Customer Service representative for further assistance.
TMP8503.Description: The NIC adapter in the slot identified in the message may have temperature related issues. The device temperature suggests degraded cooling or possibly a fan not functioning correctly on the adapter card (if adapter card has a fan).

BAR052.Message: Firmware update cannot be performed for Device: %1
BAR052.Description: The required device firmware was not found, and the update cannot continue. The device firmware is either not present on the firmware storage partition or does not match the version stored in the configuration information database. No response action is required, however obtaining and installing the update package for the device indicated will update the firmware storage partition. A backup of the server profile is recommended after updating.

RAC0648.Description: The request cannot be processed, because the length of string entered for one of the input parameter is more than the specified length.
RAC0648.Resolution: Enter a string not more than 4095 characters in length, and then retry the operation.

PWR8589.Message: The server-%1 does not have PCIe Mezzanine card in slot B1.
PWR8589.Resolution: Insert a PCIe Mezzanine card in slot B1.
PWR8589.Description: The PCIe Mezzanine card in the slot B1 is absent. Without PCIe Mezzanine cards, the chassis PCIe cards will not be available for servers.

USR0022.Description: The username specified already exists and cannot be assigned.
USR0022.Message: The specified user already exists. Duplicate user names are not allowed.

MEM1003.Message: Memory device at location %1 failed to transition to in test.
MEM1003.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem continues, contact support.

RAC0106.Description: Communication with the Smart Card reader is established and a Smart Card is inserted, but there are problems reading the Smart Card.
RAC0106.Resolution: This error may occur because:1. Make sure the Smart Card is seated correctly.2. Smart Card is invalid. Insert a valid Smart Card and try again. 3. Check connection between reader and system.4. There may be an issue with the Smart Card reader. Try reinstalling the reader driver or use a different reader.
RAC0106.Message: The Smart Card cannot be detected. Insert the Smart Card correctly.

CTL91.Message: %1 is unable to communicate with its peer.
CTL91.Resolution: Check the cabling between the PERC cards and the expanders. If this does not resolve the issue then contact your service provider.
CTL91.Description: The controller identified in the message is unable to communicate with its peer. This can be because of a cabling issue.

SWC0256.Description: Unable to read the specified file.

BAT0014.Message: The storage battery for disk drive bay %1 is absent.
BAT0014.Resolution: 1) Verify the PERC RAID controller battery installation for the associated bay. 2) If installed, reseat or reconnect the battery and cables. 3) Check the system logs for thermal related issues.
BAT0014.Description: The PERC RAID controller battery may report absent due to disconnect or thermal exceptions.

STOR096.Description: A virtual disk cannot be created because the disk space size value entered for the virtual disk is less than the lower limit value (100 MB).
STOR096.Resolution: Enter a value (the -size option) equal or higher than 100 MB, and then retry the operation.
STOR096.Message: Unable to create a virtual disk because the disk space size value entered for the virtual disk is less than the lower limit value (100 MB).

AMP0311.Message: Disk drive bay %1 current is within range.

CTL63.Message: Previous configuration was found completely missing during boot time on %1.
CTL63.Resolution: Shut down the system. Re-insert the removed physical disks and re-start the system.
CTL63.Description: The controller is unable to retrieve storage configuration saved during last shut down. This can generally happen if some configured physical disks are removed from the system when the system was shutdown.

SYS135.Description: The user context the OS Collector is being run in does not have the necessary privileges for running the application successfully.
SYS135.Resolution: Run the OS Collector application as administrator or as a user added to admin group or domain administrator or Local administrator.
SYS135.Message: OS Collector: The user context the OS Collector is being run in does not have the necessary privileges for running the application successfully.

SYS160.Description: The Lifecycle Controller log data deleted as part of a System Erase operation. All previously stored information is no longer available.
SYS160.Message: The Lifecycle Controller logs are cleared.

PDR42.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SEC0604.Description: This may apply to a physical or remote access attempt.
SEC0604.Resolution: Check system logs for intrusion attempts, and ensure strong password policies.

HWC0004.Description: The vFlash SD card is incorrectly inserted, the vFlash SD card is faulty, or there is an iDRAC communication failure.
HWC0004.Resolution: Reinsert or replace the vFlash SD card, or reset iDRAC, and retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
HWC0004.Message: Unable to initialize vFlash SD card.

IOV010.Description: Unable to assign the PCIe slots because a license is required to assign more than two PCIe slots to a server. Non-licensed systems are allowed only two slots per server.
IOV010.Resolution: Import a license that allows assignments of more than two PCIe slots per server. For more information about licenses, contact your service provider.
IOV010.Message: Unable to assign the PCIe slot(s) because a license is required to assign more than two PCIe slots to a server.

LOG300.Description: The system recovered from Chassis Log file corruption. Some log entries may not be recovered.
LOG300.Message: The system recovered from Chassis Log file corruption.

PDR7.Resolution: Replace the degraded physical disk. Identify the disk that is degraded by locating the disk that has a red "X" for its status. Perform a rescan after replacing the disk.
PDR7.Description: A physical disk has reported an error condition and may be degraded. The physical disk may have reported the error condition in response to a check consistency or other operation.

SWC0074.Description: The export operation of SupportAssist collection cannot be started because the current version of iDRAC firmware does not support the operation.
SWC0074.Resolution: Update iDRAC firmware to the latest version and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC0074.Message: Unable to start operation with the current iDRAC version.

SWC8523.Message: Unable to complete Chassis Group Leader update of member %1.
SWC8523.Resolution: Check the communications between the Chassis Group Leader and the member. Run the RACADM command "racadm ping <DNS or IP address> " to check the communications. If the communications are not functional, resolve the communications issue. If the communications are functional, remove the member from the group and re-add the member. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8523.Description: Unable to complete a configuration sync with the member identified in the message.

USR0021.Description: The session could not be closed. A possible reason is that the session does not exist.
USR0021.Message: Unable to close session with the specified ID

BAT0017.Description: System settings may be preserved if input power is not removed from the power supplies.

PST0006.Description: System BIOS has started initialization multiprocessor support.

MEM1012.Message: Memory device at location %1 is in a degraded state.
MEM1012.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem continues, contact support.

SWU002.Description: The expander or storage enclosure processor firmware update did not complete successfully.
SWU002.Resolution: Check the Storage Enclosure Backplane type and the Firmware version and make sure they are appropriately matched, and then retry the operation. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
SWU002.Message: The backplane firmware update did not complete successfully.

SYS190.Description: The OS-related data cannot be collected because the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installed on the server does not support this feature on the version of Operating System installed.
SYS190.Resolution: Install a iDRAC Service Module (ISM) supported OS, and then retry the operation.
SYS190.Message: Unable to collect the operating system (OS)-related data because the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installed on the server does not support this feature on the version of Operating System installed.

RDU8514.Message: CMC%1: cannot failover, firmware update is in progress.
RDU8514.Description: A failover operation has been requested, but a failover operation cannot be completed while CMC firmware update is in progress.

STOR15.Message: The storage sled %1 is improperly configured.
STOR15.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Change the operating mode of the storage sled identified in the message. 2) Insert the storage sled to a different slot.
STOR15.Description: The storage sled identified in the message was inserted in a location which does not support split dual host operation mode. The storage sled can functionally work in the current location with only primary PERC controller enabled.

VDR47.Message: A disk media error was corrected on %1.
VDR47.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle log for information related to members of this virtual disk.
VDR47.Description: A disk media error was detected while the controller was completing a background task. A bad disk block was identified. The disk block was remapped.

SWC4005.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility was corrected between iDRAC in slot %1 and CMC.

PSU0092.Message: Power supply unit %1 rating is appropriate for the system power distribution limits.
PSU0092.Description: The rating of the power supply unit identified in the message does not exceed system power distribution limits.

SWC8504.Message: %1 Profile renamed to %2 and description edited.
SWC8504.Description: The Profile identified in the message was renamed and the description for the Profile was edited.

RDU8523.Description: The CMC identified in the message was reset by other CMC. This occurs during failover and CMC firmware update to the standby CMC.

ENC32.Message: Storage Enclosure Processor (SEP) for %1 has been rebooted.
ENC32.Description: The SEP has been rebooted as part of the firmware download operation and will be unavailable until the operation completes.

CMC8572.Message: The coin cell battery in CMC %1 is not working.
CMC8572.Resolution: Replace the coin cell battery of the standby CMC.
CMC8572.Description: The coin cell battery in the CMC located in the slot specified in the message is not working. The battery needs to be replaced.

STOR0102.Description: No battery data to display. The system is powered off, batteries are not present on the system, batteries are not connected to the RAID controller, or the batteries are depleted.
STOR0102.Resolution: Check if the server has power, batteries are available, and batteries are connected to the RAID controller.

SYS189.Description: There is no cached copy of OS and Application data in the iDRAC flash storage.
SYS189.Resolution: Collect the OS and Application Data either manually or automatically using the iDRAC Services Module (ISM) tools and then retry the operation.
SYS189.Message: Cached OS and Application Data is not available in the iDRAC.

SEC0032.Message: The chassis is closed while the power is on.

UEFI0122.Description: The secondary SD card is missing, not responding, or in write-protected mode.
UEFI0122.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Install a SD card media in the secondary SD card slot. 2) Reseat or replace the SD card media. 3) If the secondary SD card is intentionally not installed or write-protected mode is expected, then no response action is required.
UEFI0122.Message: The secondary SD card is missing, not responding, or in write-protected mode.

VFL0004.Description: The requested vFlash media operation could not be performed, because some of the iDRAC services are busy.
VFL0004.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and retry the operation. If the issue continues to persist, contact your service provider.
VFL0004.Message: Unable to perform the vFlash media operation.

HWC4011.Message: Hardware unsuccessfully updated for mezzanine card %1.
HWC4011.Resolution: Check presence, re-install or reconnect, then re-attempt the update. If the problem persists, contact support.

SWC0068.Description: The BIOS boot mode settings could not be retrieved because of an internal issue.
SWC0068.Resolution: Exit the OS Deployment wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, exit Lifecycle Controller and perform an AC power cycle.
SWC0068.Message: Unable to retrieve the boot mode settings from BIOS.

VLT0203.Message: The system board %1 voltage is greater than the upper critical threshold.
VLT0203.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0203.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

VLT0228.Message: The memory module %1 voltage is outside of range.
VLT0228.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0228.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

RAC0724.Description: Quick Sync Firmware is successfully updated.
RAC0724.Message: Quick Sync Firmware is successfully updated.

SYS161.Description: The SupportAssist related data has been deleted from iDRAC non-volatile storage.

IOV1006.Description: The PCI slot or Server slot FQDD (Fully Qualified Device Descriptor) values entered for the operation are not valid.
IOV1006.Resolution: Perform the Enumerate operation on the DCIM_ChassisPCISlot class and DCIM_BladeServerView class to get the correct FQDD values for the PCIe slot and Server slot. Retry the operation with the correct FQDD values.
IOV1006.Message: Invalid PCI slot or Server slot.

RAC0281.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the IP Subnet Mask does not conform to the required format.
RAC0281.Resolution: Enter a valid IP Subnet Mask. Expected range: 0.0.0.0 - 255.255.255.255.
RAC0281.Message: The IP Subnet Mask is invalid. Expected range: 0.0.0.0 - 255.255.255.255.

LC012.Description: Lifecycle Controller is in use by another process. Wait for other process to complete before attempting to run another command.
LC012.Resolution: Try one of the following: 1) Rerun the command after about 2 minutes. 2) Make sure that Lifecycle Controller Unified Server Configurator or an Update Package is not currently running on the server 3) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
LC012.Message: Another process is using Lifecycle Controller.

PWR8511.Description: Unable to set the CHASSIS_POWER_button_disable chassis power property.
PWR8511.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR8511.Message: Unable to set the CHASSIS_POWER_button_disable chassis power property.

SEC0700.Description: If the property name is configured without changing the default password, iDRAC may be accessible on the Internet. This causes a severe security risk for iDRAC.
SEC0700.Resolution: To change the password, run the following racadm command: racadm set iDRAC.Users.<index>.Password <new password string>.Alternatively, to avoid this warning message, run the following racadm command: racadm set iDRAC.Tuning.DefaultCredentialWarning Disable.
SEC0700.Message: Warning: Default username and password are currently in use. It is strongly recommended to change the default password before configuring the property. Else, it causes a severe security risk for iDRAC.

PCI5006.Message: The power-related issue of the PCIe adapter in slot%1 is resolved.
PCI5006.Description: The power related issue of the PCIe device in the slot identified in the message is resolved.

SWC8514.Resolution: Make sure: 1) The login credentials for the operation have user config administration privilege, 2) The user name given is valid. If the issue persists, restart the CMC and retry the operation.
SWC8514.Description: Unable to delete the user name identified in the message.

UEFI0127.Description: The secondary SD card is write-protected mode.
UEFI0127.Resolution: No response action is required if this is intentional.
UEFI0127.Message: The secondary SD card is in write-protected mode.

ENC6.Resolution: Check for problems with the cables. See the Cables attached correctly section for more information on checking the cables. You should also check to see if the enclosure has degraded or failed components. To do this, select the enclosure object in the tree view and click the Health subtab. The Health subtab displays the status of the enclosure components. Verify that the controller has the supported driver and firmware versions installed and that each Enclosure Management Modules (EMMs) are running the same version of supported firmware.
ENC6.Description: The controller is unable to communicate with an enclosure. There are several reasons for communication loss. For example, there may be a bad or loose cable. An unusual amount of I/O may also interrupt communication with the enclosure. In addition, communication loss may be caused by software, hardware, or firmware problems, bad or failed power supplies, and enclosure shutdown.

PWR8560.Message: Unable to turn on I/O Module %1 due to insufficient chassis power.
PWR8560.Resolution: Utilize the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) web interface to check available power and I/O Module power requirements. If sufficient power is available, restart the CMC and retry the operation. If sufficient power is not available due to an insufficient number of PSUs, add additional PSU(s) and reinsert the I/O Module.
PWR8560.Description: Unable to turn on the I/O Module identified in the message due to insufficient chassis power.

BAR022.Description: The host system is powering up to perform component firmware and configuration restoration.
BAR022.Message: System powering up to perform component updates.

TMP8501.Description: System was unable to read planar board or control panel temperature sensors. The fan speed was increased to protect system hardware.
TMP8501.Resolution: Remove AC power from the system and reapply AC power. Check to see if the issue is resolved. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
TMP8501.Message: Unable to read planar board temperature sensors. The cooling has been increased to safeguard the system.

MEM0022.Message: Memory device at location %1 is absent.
MEM0022.Resolution: If unexpected, check presence, then re-install.
MEM0022.Description: The memory may not be seated correctly, misconfigured, or has failed. Memory size is reduced.

RAC0227.Description: The SD card is not present, or communication with the SD card is lost. This could result in reduced functionality and capabilities.
RAC0227.Resolution: This error may occur because: 1. Make sure the SD card is seated correctly. 2. The SD card is invalid. Insert a valid SD card of size greater than 256MB and try again.
RAC0227.Message: SD card is not detected: Insert an SD Card of size greater than 256MB.

DH006.Resolution: Validate that the certificate parameter matches the certificate contents; the certificate can be validated using OpenSSL tools.
DH006.Message: Not the right passphrase for the private key (need to re-write).

ISM0005.Description: The iDRAC Service Module has successfully restarted communication with iDRAC.
ISM0005.Message: The iDRAC Service Module has successfully restarted communication with iDRAC.

RAC0213.Description: Login page is missing a username.

CTL2.Description: You have changed the controller rebuild rate. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SUP0507.Description: The FTP server setting details are incorrect.
SUP0507.Resolution: Enter the correct FTP server settings details, and retry the operation.
SUP0507.Message: Unable to download the Update Packages from the FTP server.

SUP006.Description: The DUP is being downloaded and the update cannot be deleted while the download is in progress.
SUP006.Resolution: Wait until the update package is downloaded and retry the action. The download can take more than 5 minutes depending on network speed and size of the update package.

SYS234.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported port number value, %2.
SYS234.Resolution: Make sure that the correct port number value is used, and then retry the operation.
SYS234.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an unsupported port number value.

RAC985.Description: The object "cfgServerBootOnce" cannot be configured if the object "cfgServerFirstBootDevice" is set to F10, F11, or BIOS value.
RAC985.Resolution: Change the value of the object "cfgServerFirstBootDevice" using the RACADM command "racadm config -g cfgServerInfo -o cfgServerFirstBootDevice<value other than F10, F11, and BIOS>", and retry configuring the object "cfgServerBootOnce".
RAC985.Message: Unable to configure the cfgServerBootOnce object.

SUP0102.Description: The TFTP IP Address specified is invalid.
SUP0102.Resolution: Specify a valid TFTP IP Address.

PST0131.Description: Memory errors occurred copying BIOS image into system memory. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception Code 83).
PST0131.Resolution: Remove input power. Reduce system memory to minimum configuration and apply input power.

MEM0001.Message: Multi-bit memory errors detected on a memory device at location(s) %1.
MEM0001.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
MEM0001.Description: The memory has encountered a uncorrectable error. System performance may be degraded. The operating system and/or applications may fail as a result.

FC008.Description: No changes are available between the previous configuration and the current configuration. To create a Configuration job, change at least one attribute.
FC008.Resolution: Change the configuration of one or more attributes and retry creating the Configuration job.
FC008.Message: No pending data present to create a Configuration job.

IOID112.Message: The initiator properties of the %1 Port %2 are successfully configured.
IOID112.Description: The initiator properties of the NIC port identified in the message are successfully configured.

VDR29.Description: A mirrored virtual disk is un-mirrored. When a virtual disk is mirrored, its data is copied to another virtual disk to maintain redundancy. After being un-mirrored, the disk formerly used as the mirror returns to being a physical disk and becomes available for inclusion in another virtual disk.
VDR29.Resolution: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
VDR29.Message: A mirrored virtual disk has been un-mirrored.

RAC1043.Message: Unable to configure the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings. The option %1 is either invalid or not provided.
RAC1043.Resolution: Retry with a correct value for the option identified in the message. For more information, view the help details by running the RACADM command "racadm help autoupdatescheduler".
RAC1043.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an invalid value for the option identified in the message.

PDR84.Description: The Security key on a secure encrypted disk was activated.

CTL77.Message: Flash of new firmware image(s) completed on %1.
CTL77.Description: This alert message occurs if controller firmware is flashed successfully.

PWR8529.Description: The Max Power Conservation Mode is enabled.
PWR8529.Message: Max Power Conservation Mode is enabled.

CMC8528.Message: Unable to obtain or send link tuning or flex address data to server-%1.
CMC8528.Resolution: Make sure that the currently installed CMC firmware is the latest. Otherwise, update the CMC with the latest CMC firmware and retry the operation.
CMC8528.Description: CMC is unable to obtain the link tuning or flex address information for the newly installed hardware (server, Input Output Module, or Mezzanine card), or is unable to send the link tuning or flex address information to iDRAC.

VDR9.Description: A consistency check operation on a virtual disk has started.

LIC004.Description: This error condition is reported when one of the following conditions occur: 1) Operating system detected a file error (for example, bad CRC, bad sector) when reading/writing a license manager file. The error could indicate bad or corrupt FLASH device. 2) License Manager detected an internal memory data corruption.3) The command or command parameters passed to License Manager is invalid. This is an internal error showing memory corruption. Under normal circumstances this error should not occur.4) When exporting a license file, License Manager was unable to allocate the temporary space required for the transfer of the file.
LIC004.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
LIC004.Message: An internal system error has occurred.

SWC0004.Description: The operation to add a work note to the Lifecycle Log encountered an unexpected error while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0004.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0004.Message: Unable to add a work note to the Lifecycle Log.

PSU0800.Message: Power Supply %1: Status = 0x%2, IOUT = 0x%3, VOUT= 0x%4, TEMP= 0x%5, FAN = 0x%6, INPUT= 0x%7.
PSU0800.Description: Lists the complete status of the power supply unit.

USR0002.Description: Details the Username that logged in and the IP Address they are coming from.

UEFI0236.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0236.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0236.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Write DQ/DQS Training - FIFO Reset phase.

RED027.Description: The temporary storage is full. The uploaded files must be installed to clear space for additional uploads.
RED027.Resolution: Select and install the currently uploaded files before uploading additional files.
RED027.Message: Insufficient space to upload the requested file.

RAC0247.Description: This message is displayed when trying to format or download to an attached vFlash partition.
RAC0247.Resolution: Detach this partition and try again.

STOR2.Description: A SCSI device experienced an error, but may have recovered.

SWC8538.Message: Unable to delete key for slot %1 of service account, due to problem saving key file.
SWC8538.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8538.Description: The Public Key (PK) SSH Authentication key file delete operation did not complete successfully because the Chassis Management Controller is unable to access the configuration database.

UEFI0294.Message: Unable to initialize the Dual Inline Memory Module (DIMM) in memory slot %1 because of a mismatch in the number of ranks.
UEFI0294.Resolution: Remove the mismatched Dual Inline Memory Module (DIMM) and replace it with a DIMM with the same rank count as the other installed DIMMs in the Integrated Memory Controllers (iMCs). For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual available on the support site.
UEFI0294.Description: DDR memory initialization of the Dual Inline Memory Module (DIMM) in the specified memory slot cannot be completed because of a mismatch in the number of ranks between the DIMMs installed in the server.

PR9.Description: The Part Replacement feature started the firmware update process based on Part Firmware Update attribute settings.

SWC0102.Description: The option requested is not available on the interface being used.
SWC0102.Resolution: Refer to the help to get the list of options valid for the interface.
SWC0102.Message: The -m option is not supported by the interface being used.

LC0100.Description: A persistent error has occurred while carrying out a Lifecycle Controller operation. This situation causes Lifecycle Controller to enter Recovery mode. Any remote jobs pending execution were cancelled.
LC0100.Resolution: To verify or change Recovery mode, use F2 Setup, select iDRAC Configuration, and select Lifecycle Controller Settings. Updating Lifecycle Controller clears the Recovery mode.
LC0100.Message: Lifecycle Controller has entered Recovery mode.

PDR110.Resolution: Back up the data on the device, and contact your service provider for further instructions.
PDR110.Description: The reliability of the PCIe solid state device identified in the message degraded. Data loss is possible.

JCP002.Description: The Lifecycle Controller is not able to schedule a job at this time because of an internal error.
JCP002.Resolution: Wait up to three minutes and retry the operation. If the problem persists, reboot the system and enumerate DCIM_Lifeycle Job to view the list of jobs that are currently scheduled.

SWC0015.Description: The operating system driver pack is missing or not accessible.
SWC0015.Resolution: Update the system with the latest Lifecycle Controller OS Driver Pack. Obtain the OS Driver Pack from the service provider.
SWC0015.Message: Unable to retrieve the list of supported operating systems.

MEM1005.Message: Memory device at location %1 failed to power off.

ISM0031.Message: The Full Power Cycle operation is triggered by the server operating system (OS) user %1 from the OS on date %2. However, the server components will be AC power cycled when the server is shut down.
ISM0031.Resolution: No response action is required. For information about Full powercycle, see the platform User's Guide available on the support site.
ISM0031.Description: The Full Power Cycle operation is triggered by the server operating system (OS) user from the OS on date as identified in the message. However, the server components will be AC power cycled when the server is shut down.

PDR1008.Message: Rebuild was aborted for drive %1 in disk drive bay %2.

RFM1034.Description: The SD card is not detected or not installed.
RFM1034.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media.
RFM1034.Message: Media not present for Removable Flash Media.

RED078.Description: Unable to delete the Automatic Update schedule information because the schedule is not configured.
RED078.Message: Unable to delete the Automatic Update schedule.

RAC1160.Message: Unable to set USB group objects because of insufficient privilege for user account %1.
RAC1160.Resolution: Contact the iDRAC system administrator and get the System Control privilege added to the account identified in the message or use account credentials that have System Control privilege and retry the operation.
RAC1160.Description: Unable to set USB group objects because the user account identified in the message does not have the System Control privilege, which is required for this operation.

SWC1925.Description: The iDRAC Quick Sync access feature is set to the Disabled mode.
SWC1925.Message: The iDRAC Quick Sync access feature is set to the Disabled mode.

STOR065.Description: Unable to create the requested virtual disk because one or more specified physical disk(s) is not T10 Protection Information capable.
STOR065.Resolution: Verify that the physical disks selected for creating a virtual disk are T10 Protection Information capable, and then retry the operation.
STOR065.Message: One or more physical disks specified for creating a virtual disk are not T10 Protection Information capable.

PDR34.Message: A dedicated hot spare has been automatically unassigned.%1
PDR34.Description: The hot spare is no longer required because the virtual disk it was assigned to has been deleted.

SYS226.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of the reason described by the code %2 sent by the HTTP remote host server.
SYS226.Resolution: View the HTTP remote host server documentation to resolve the issue. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SYS226.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of the reason described by the code identified in the message. For every unsuccessful file transfer, the HTTP remote host server returns an error code, where each code has a description about the reason for failure.

CMC8526.Message: Unable to retrieve the server-%1 CPU information.
CMC8526.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC. 2) Reset CMC. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8526.Description: CMC is unable to obtain the CPU information from the server specified in the message. This occurs if there is no communication between CMC and iDRAC.

UEFI0090.Message: A DIMM with an incompatible number of ranks is installed on memory slot: %1.
UEFI0090.Resolution: Remove the unsupported DIMM module from the identified memory slot and replace it with a supported module. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0090.Description: A DIMM with an incompatible number of ranks is installed on the memory slot identified in the message.

PWR8581.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because another chassis power operation is in progress.
PWR8581.Resolution: Wait until the current chassis power operation is complete and the chassis is On and then retry the operation.
PWR8581.Description: A chassis power operation is currently in progress and the server identified in the message could not be turned on.

VDR34.Resolution: Run a consistency check on the virtual disk. If that fails, check the health of the member drives of the virtual disk and then recreate.
VDR34.Description: Background initialization of a virtual disk failed.

PST0140.Description: System BIOS failed to initialize the system management interrupt. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST exception code 8C) .
PST0140.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

SWC0014.Description: Unable to apply the changes to the date and time settings because an internal error occurred.
SWC0014.Resolution: Exit the Date and Time wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, exit Lifecycle Controller and retry the operation.
SWC0014.Message: Unable to set new date and time.

RED038.Message: A recurring task of type %1 is added.
RED038.Description: An Automatic Server Profile Export or Automatic Update task identified in the message has been added.

VDR16.Resolution: Check that all the physical disks of the virtual disk are in a healthy condition. Replace any disks that are not healthy and restart the operation. If this is not the problem, delete the virtual disk and restore the data to the disk from a backup copy.
VDR16.Description: A physical disk included in the virtual disk failed or there is an error in the parity information. A failed physical disk causes errors in parity information.

UEFI0057.Description: The MCE is logged during Power-on-Self-Test (POST). MCE could have occurred during either the current or the previous POST.
UEFI0057.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify Machine-Check Exception (MCE) event source. Resolve the issue identified in the SEL that caused the MCE. For further information, contact your service provider.
UEFI0057.Message: A Machine-Check Exception (MCE) error has occurred.

RED003.Resolution: Schedule the job if it is not already scheduled.

PDR24.Message: Failure prediction threshold exceeded on %1 due to test. No action needed.
PDR24.Description: A disk has received a SMART alert (predictive failure) due to test conditions.

NIC022.Description: The current BIOS password jumper setting prevents the BIOS password from being changed.
NIC022.Resolution: Change the jumper setting to enable setting the BIOS password.
NIC022.Message: Unable to set the BIOS password because of a jumper setting on the motherboard.

FCD8505.Description: Features cannot be deactivated when the chassis is turned on.
FCD8505.Resolution: Turn off the chassis via the Web interface or RACADM command line interface before deactivating the feature. To turn off the chassis using Racadm type "racadm chassisaction -m chassis powerdown". To deactivate the feature using RACADM, type "racadm <feature> -d" where <feature> is the name of the feature to be deactivated.
FCD8505.Message: The features cannot be deactivated when the chassis is turned on.

POW004.Description: Host failed to power up because of unacknowledged use of 110V. This messages has been replaced by Message ID PWR2254.
POW004.Message: Power on permission error, unacknowledged use of 110V.

PDR26.Description: A drive has entered the online state. This may be because the system just started or could be because a problem with the drive has been corrected.

SWC0032.Description: Exporting the Server Configuration Profile image file to the USB drive was successful.
SWC0032.Message: Successfully exported the Server Configuration Profile image file to the USB drive.

RAC1141.Description: The iDRAC firmware rollback operation was initiated.
RAC1141.Message: The iDRAC firmware rollback operation was initiated.

RAC043.Description: Some event filter settings were not updated due to problems encountered processing the input parameters.
RAC043.Resolution: Verify the input parameters provided and retry the operation. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
RAC043.Message: Unable to update some event filter settings.

LIC905.Description: The LicenseName value is greater than the allowed max length of 64.
LIC905.Resolution: Correct the length of the LicenseName value and retry the operation.
LIC905.Message: The LicenseName value cannot exceed 64 characters.

LC099.Description: The server screen shot cannot be exported because the video signal is not detected.
LC099.Resolution: Turn on the server if turned off, and then retry the operation.
LC099.Message: Unable to export the server screen shot because the video signal is not detected.

VFL0705.Description: An error has occurred while initializing the SD card. The SD card is not present or vFlash is not enabled, or the SD card is write-protected.
VFL0705.Resolution: Re-insert the SD card, enable the SD card, or disable write-protection on the SD card. Then try to initialize the SD card again.
VFL0705.Message: Error occurred and SD card could not be initialized.

SWU8537.Message: Unable to update the LKVM firmware, because the IP address provided is invalid. ErrorCode=0x%1.
SWU8537.Resolution: Make sure the CMC IP address entered is valid, and then retry the Update operation.
SWU8537.Description: The LKVM firmware update operation was not successful, because the IP address of the active CMC that is provided to the LKVM is invalid.

RAC966.Description: Any operation involving remote share (CIFS) cannot continue if user name, password, or both are not specified. The u and p options represent the user name and password for the remote share.
RAC966.Resolution: Make sure to specify both user name and password for the remote share, and retry the operation. To view the list of options that can used for the required subcommand, use the racadm help <subcommand> command.
RAC966.Message: Unable to continue with the operation because the user name or password is not specified.

VF032.Description: The specified partition type is not a valid type.
VF032.Resolution: Try a partition type that is supported.

CTL84.Message: %1 is running an unsupported firmware version.
CTL84.Resolution: Update the CMC Firmware to the latest version available or revert the controller firmware to a previous version.
CTL84.Description: The firmware on the controller identified in the message is not supported by this version of the CMC. This may result in degraded functionality.

LC103.Description: The server screen shot cannot be exported because iDRAC is unable to process the screen data.
LC103.Resolution: Wait for the current process to complete and retry the operation.
LC103.Message: Unable to export the server screen shot because iDRAC is unable to process the screen data.

RAC0134.Description: The SD card is not a valid vFlash SD card. The use of non-Dell media prevents the use of some extended capabilities and functions.
RAC0134.Resolution: Insert a valid vFlash SD card.
RAC0134.Message: This operation is unavailable for non-vFlash SD cards.

UEFI0152.Description: This is a test BIOS and must not be used in production environment.
UEFI0152.Resolution: Do not use this BIOS in production.
UEFI0152.Message: This BIOS is for testing purpose only.

SYS088.Message: Estimated time for applying configuration changes is %1 seconds.
SYS088.Description: Applying the changes defined in the configuration XML file will take approximately the estimated time identified in the message.

LOG302.Description: The Chassis Log file header is corrupted. The Chassis Log will be recreated and all current log entries will not be preserved.
LOG302.Message: The Chassis Log file header is corrupted.

VFL0003.Resolution: Use a partition number of an existing partition for the requested operation.
VFL0003.Description: The partition number identified in the message cannot be queried, because identified partition does not exist.

SWU8534.Description: The iKVM firmware update operation is not successful.
SWU8534.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8534.Message: Unable to update the iKVM firmware.

FC012.Description: No changes to component attribute data are available between the previous configuration and the current configuration.

RAC1129.Description: The BootOnce object could not be modified, because the FirstBootDevice object is set to either F10, F11, or BIOS.
RAC1129.Resolution: Configure the FirstBootDevice object to values other than F10, F11, or BIOS and retry the set operation for the BootOnce object. For more information about possible FirstBootDevice values, run the RACADM command "racadm help idrac.serverboot.firstbootdevice".
RAC1129.Message: Unable to modify the BootOnce object.

LIC008.Description: All bound perpetual licenses contain the unique identifier of a specific device. The unique identifier binds a license to the device. For example, iDRAC's unique identifier is the service tag.
LIC008.Resolution: Obtain a new license file with the correct unique identifier for the device. To use this license, import to the device with the correct unique identifier.
LIC008.Message: The license binding ID does not match the device unique identifier.

SWC0123.Description: The syntax of the sslcsrgen command is invalid.
SWC0123.Resolution: Refer the help text for sslcsrgen subcommand.
SWC0123.Message: The -s option is not valid with any other options.

VDR26.Message: The check consistency on a %1 has been paused (suspended).
VDR26.Resolution: To resume the Check Consistency operation, right-click the virtual disk in the Storage Management tree view and select Resume Check Consistency.
VDR26.Description: You paused the Check Consistency operation on a virtual disk.

CMC8527.Message: Unable to retrieve the server-%1 memory information.
CMC8527.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC. 2) Reset CMC. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8527.Description: CMC is unable to obtain the memory information from the server specified in the message. This occurs if there is no communication between CMC and iDRAC.

BIOS017.Description: Unable to delete vFlash pending one-time boot configuration.
BIOS017.Resolution: Remove AC power from system and after restoring AC power, retry the operation.
BIOS017.Message: Unable to delete vFlash pending one-time boot configuration

RAC0284.Description: This is the time span (in seconds) within which login attempts from an IP address with excessive failures are rejected. The default value is 3600 seconds (1 hour).
RAC0284.Resolution: Enter a valid IP Blocking Fail Penalty Time. Expected range: 10-65535.
RAC0284.Message: IP Blocking Fail Penalty Time is invalid. Expected range: 10-65535.

TMP1000.Resolution: Check for factors that may cause overheating. For example, verify that the enclosure fan is working. You should check the thermostat settings and examine whether the enclosure is located near a heat source. Make sure the enclosure has enough ventilation and that the room temperature is not too hot. Refer to the enclosure documentation for more diagnostic information.
TMP1000.Description: The enclosure is too hot. A variety of factors can cause the excessive temperature. For example, a fan may have failed, the thermostat may be set too high, or the room temperature may be too hot.

HWC0013.Description: The USB drive is disconnected or is not readable.
HWC0013.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the USB drive and retry the operation. If the problem persists, restart the system and retry.
HWC0013.Message: Unable to copy the file to USB drive.

UEFI0155.Description: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology (DPAT) Enterprise license after three consecutive boots. The Number of Cores per Processor BIOS setup configuration is being reverted to default because of the absent license.
UEFI0155.Resolution: If the absence of license is expected, no action is necessary. Otherwise do one of the following: 1) Reload the license. 2) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 3) Update the iDRAC firmware.
UEFI0155.Message: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology (DPAT) Enterprise license after three consecutive boots. The Number of Cores per Processor BIOS setup configuration is being reverted to default because of the absent license.

FAN8500.Description: Enabling Enhanced Cooling Mode will provide increased airflow capability to the blades by increasing the maximum allowable blower speed at the cost of increased power consumption.

SWC0114.Description: The syntax of the setniccfg command is invalid.
SWC0114.Resolution: Refer the help text for setniccfg subcommand.
SWC0114.Message: The -o option cannot be used with any other options.

SUP0120.Message: Preparing for firmware update. Please wait.

OSD36.Description: User has cancelled system services by using the CTRL+E option (iDRAC configuration utility) or F2 option during POST. This action cancels the WSMAN request to boot to ISO.
OSD36.Resolution: To resolve the issue rerun the command. Do not cancel system services using CTRL+E or F2 during POST when system is rebooting to the ISO.
OSD36.Message: Boot to ISO Image has been cancelled by using CTRL+E or F2 option on the server.

RAC0102.Description: The software to communicate with the Smart Card is not loaded in this browser. Smart Card can be used for log in only if the appropriate Smart Card software is installed in the browser.
RAC0102.Resolution: Install the plug-in prompted by the iDRAC Web GUI to log in using Smart Card.
RAC0102.Message: The Smart Card Logon plug-in is not installed. Install the plug-in from the iDRAC Web GUI to log in using Smart Card.

HWC2000.Message: The %1 cable or interconnect is connected.

IOV105.Message: Unable to manage PCIE adapter %1 located in %2 %3.
IOV105.Resolution: Make sure that supported adapters are used and installed correctly in the PCIe slot.
IOV105.Description: An error by the Chassis Infrastructure slot management detected an error which may prevent the physical assignment/unassignment or power off of a slot. The errors may be caused by PCIE training timeouts, false hot plug signals, or installation of an unsupported PCIe adapter card. For a list of supported PCIe adapter cards contact your service provider.

CPU0817.Message: CPU %1 voltage regulator module is operating normally.

HWC8503.Message: The internal communication between the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) and the %1 control panel is restored.
HWC8503.Description: The internal communication between the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) and the control panel identified in the message is restored, and the control panel is normally functioning.

RAC1115.Description: The command could not be successfully run, because of insufficient privileges for the username supplied.
RAC1115.Resolution: Make sure that you have appropriate privileges, and then retry the operation.
RAC1115.Message: Unable to run the command, because of insufficient user privileges.

BAR043.Description: A timeout occurred waiting for the Unified Server Configurator (USC) to exit.
BAR043.Message: Timeout waiting for Unified Server Configurator to exit.

SYS139.Description: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the server is in POST and has not finished startup.
SYS139.Resolution: Retry the operation after the server has finished starting and POST has completed.
SYS139.Message: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the server is in POST and has not finished startup.

RAC0665.Message: RAID Controller Log data is being collected. This operation will take less than %1 minutes.
RAC0665.Resolution: Do not log off from the application until the log data collection process is completed.
RAC0665.Description: RAID Controller Log data is being collected. This operation will take less than the number of minutes identified in the message.

USR102.Resolution: To provide the correct value for the specified parameter, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
USR102.Description: The value provided for the specified parameter is invalid.

SEC0045.Message: Intel Trusted Execution Technology (TXT) is operating correctly.

STOR049.Description: The controller is in Local Key Management mode.
STOR049.Message: Controller is in Local Key Management mode.

RED040.Message: A recurring operation of type %1 created a job %2.
RED040.Description: The job identified in the message was created by an Automatic Server Profile Backup, Automatic Update, or other recurring operation.

VF045.Description: File transfer was not successful. This could be because of network problems or an operational problem with the file server.
VF045.Resolution: Try the download again. If the issue persists, validate that the network share is operational.
VF045.Message: FTP download operation was not successful.

SUP0527.Description: The Update Package does not have this system in the supported platform list.
SUP0527.Resolution: Download the latest Update Package from your service provider and retry the operation.
SUP0527.Message: The Update Package is not supported for this system.

LIC211.Description: License import/delete/expiration resulted in a feature set change.
LIC211.Message: The iDRAC feature set has changed.

UEFI0114.Description: The Fault Resilient Memory (FRM) operating mode cannot be enabled because of mismatches in DIMM channel configurations.
UEFI0114.Resolution: Make sure identical memory modules in corresponding slots of channel pairs are populated. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0114.Message: Unable to enable the Fault Resilient Memory (FRM) operating mode because of mismatches in DIMM channel configurations.

ISM0026.Message: The iDRAC Hard Reset operation is performed by system OS user %1 from the operating system (OS) on date %2.
ISM0026.Resolution: The iDRAC may take up to 2 minutes to fully restart. Wait until the iDRAC is fully restarted before performing further operations with the iDRAC.
ISM0026.Description: The iDRAC Hard Reset operation is performed by system OS user identified in the message from the operating system (OS) on the day-date-time-year identified in the message.

RAC0682.Description: Enabling iDRAC Direct USB Configuration XML allows any USB key containing a correctly formatted configuration XML file to reconfigure the server when plugged into the USB management port identified by the wrench icon. This may include operations on RAID configurations, user accounts, and alert settings.
RAC0682.Message: Enabling iDRAC Direct USB Configuration XML allows any USB key containing a correctly formatted configuration XML file to reconfigure the server when plugged into the USB management port identified by the wrench icon. This may include operations on RAID configurations, user accounts, and alert settings.

SWC4009.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility was corrected between CMC 1 and CMC 2.

RAC009.Description: The requested operation cannot be completed because the length of the input string exceeds maximum length allowed.
RAC009.Resolution: Verify the string length and retry the operation. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
RAC009.Message: Input string length exceeds maximum length.

DIS013.Description: Default client certificate is being used. Auto Discovery client is using this certificate for the SSL connection with the Provisioning Server.
DIS013.Message: Auto Discovery client using default client certificate.

AMP0317.Message: System level current is within range.

PWR216.Description: Unable to enable Extended Power Performance, because redundancy policy is set to Grid Redundancy or No Redundancy.
PWR216.Resolution: Configure Redundancy Policy to Power Supply Redundancy and retry the operation. Using the CMC Web GUI, click Power > Configuration. From the Redundancy Policy drop-down menu, select Power Supply Redundancy.
PWR216.Message: Unable to enable Extended Power Performance, because Redundancy Policy is set to Grid Redundancy or No Redundancy.

NIC002.Description: Unable to allocate required memory to perform the operation.
NIC002.Resolution: Power cycle system and reapply firmware packages for Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC.

SWC0218.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0218.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0218.Message: The -c option requires -p to also be specified.

SYS152.Description: Some of the requested storage component erase tasks were not successful. Retrying the System Erase operation may be required. The vFlash SD Card must be initialized and licensed to be erased successfully.
SYS152.Resolution: Retry the System Erase operation. To retry the System Erase operation using the Lifecycle Controller utility, restart the server and when the company logo is displayed, press <F10>. Select Hardware Configuration > Retire or Repurpose System, check appropriate storage options, and then retry the operation.
SYS152.Message: Erase operations for some System Erase tasks did not complete successfully.

CTL78.Description: This alert message occurs if controller firmware is flashed.

VRM0018.Message: Virtual Media image server operation successful

RED026.Description: An internal error occurred while processing the current update. The update did not complete successfully.
RED026.Message: An internal error occurred while processing updates.

LIC005.Description: The maximum number of installed licenses has been reached.
LIC005.Resolution: Delete one of the currently installed licenses and retry the import.
LIC005.Message: Import failed: The maximum number of licenses are installed.

PWR8507.Message: System Input Power Cap changed from %1W AC to %2W AC.
PWR8507.Description: The system Input Power Cap was changed from the value to the value indicated in the message.

UEFI0211.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0211.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0211.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Transmit Buffer Vref Training phase.

LIC022.Description: License Manager database is locked while a backup and restore operation is in progress. License import/export/delete operations are not allowed but a user can view license information.
LIC022.Resolution: Wait until the backup or restore operation completes and try again.
LIC022.Message: License Manager database locked due to ongoing backup and restore operation.

STOR0501.Description: Unable to create a virtual disk due to unknown reasons.
STOR0501.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation:1) Exit the RAID Configuration wizard.2) Update the RAID controller firmware to the latest version.3) Reboot the system and press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation.

SWC8553.Resolution: Edit the profile and make sure no XML schema or configuration errors are present and then retry the operation.
SWC8553.Description: The profile identified in the message is not valid.

ENC16.Message: An enclosure blink has ceased on %1.
ENC16.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SEL9901.Description: The current software version cannot decode this event. The source of the event may come from a source that is not compatible with this software or the event may have been added after the release of this software. You may need to review this event using a tool which displays raw data such as Ipmitool with the -vvv option or Racadm with the -E option.
SEL9901.Resolution: See product documentation for additional information.

RAC0666.Description: A RAID Controller Log is created.
RAC0666.Resolution: To export the Log report, click OK. To delete the report, click Cancel.
RAC0666.Message: A RAID Controller Log is created.

STOR064.Description: Unable to create the requested virtual disk because the physical disks specified did not have the same block size.
STOR064.Resolution: Verify that the physical disks selected for creating the virtual disk have the same block size and retry the operation. The block size can be determined by reviewing the physical disk inventory and checking the BlockSize property for each physical disk.
STOR064.Message: One or more physical disks specified for creating a virtual disk do not have the same block size.

FC010.Description: For 11G systems: System Services must be enabled to perform the requested operation. System Services has been disabled through the iDRAC configuration utility accessed by pressing CTRL+E on boot up or through a remote operation. For 12G and above generations: Lifecycle Controller must be enabled to perform the requested operation. Lifecycle Controller has been disabled by pressing F2 Setup, selecting iDRAC Configuration, and selecting Lifecycle Controller Settings on boot up or through a remote operation.
FC010.Resolution: For 11G systems: Use the iDRAC configuration utility to enable the System Services by pressing the CTRL+E option on boot up at the targeted system. For 12G and above generations: Use F2 Setup, select iDRAC Configuration, and select Lifecycle Controller Settings, to enable the Lifecycle Controller on boot up of the targeted system.
FC010.Message: Unable to create Configuration job because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

RDU0019.Message: The storage voltage is not redundant.

CTL106.Message: The Background Initialization Rate of %1 is set to %2.
CTL106.Description: The Background Initialization Rate of the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.

SWC0269.Description: Local Configuration using RACADM may be disabled.
SWC0269.Resolution: Check if the Local Configuration using RACADM is disabled and enable it through GUI.
SWC0269.Message: Unable to clear the RAC log. Possible reason may be that Local Configuration using RACADM is disabled.

LOG004.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of lack of memory or file space in iDRAC firmware.
LOG004.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation.

SUP0112.Description: The requested option is not available for remote racadm/operating system.
SUP0112.Message: The -p option is not currently supported for remote RACADM and the operating system being used.

UEFI0081.Description: Memory size has changed from the last time the system was started. No action is required if memory was added or removed.
UEFI0081.Resolution: If the change is expected, no action is necessary. Otherwise, check the DIMM population inside the system and memory settings in System Setup for configuration changes. For more information, see the platform Owners Manual.
UEFI0081.Message: Memory size has changed from the last time the system was started.

SWC1921.Description: The Chassis Management at Server Mode is disabled.
SWC1921.Message: The Chassis Management at Server Mode is disabled.

RAC0254.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the IPv4 Gateway Address does not conform to the required format.
RAC0254.Resolution: Enter a valid Gateway Address. Expected range: [0.0.0.0 or 1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].
RAC0254.Message: The Gateway Address is invalid. Expected range: [0.0.0.0 or 1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].

SYS087.Description: When the configuration XML file specified in the Preview operation is imported to the system, a system reboot will occur to apply the configuration changes.
SYS087.Message: A system reboot will occur when the previewed configuration XML file is imported to the system.

STOR089.Description: The storage configuration operation is successfully completed and the change is in pending state.
STOR089.Resolution: To apply the configuration operation immediately, create a configuration job using the --realtime option. To create the necessary real-time job, run the jobqueue command. For more information about jobqueue command, run the racadm help jobqueue command.
STOR089.Message: The storage configuration operation is successfully completed and the change is in pending state.

SWC0220.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0220.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0220.Message: The -u option requires -c to also be specified.

RAC999.Description: DNSFromDHCP6 cannot be enabled if iDRAC IPv6 AutoConfig is disabled.
RAC999.Resolution: Enable IPv6 AutoConfig using "racadm set iDRAC.IPv6.AutoConfig < 1 | Enabled >" command, and retry the operation.
RAC999.Message: The object DNSFromDHCP6 cannot be enabled.

SYS262.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because either the proxy may not allow file transfer operations or incorrect proxy credentials are entered.
SYS262.Resolution: Make sure that correct proxy settings are enabled and correct proxy credentials are entered and retry the operation.
SYS262.Description: The file cannot be transferred because either the proxy may not allow file transfer operations or incorrect proxy credentials are entered.

MEM9002.Message: Intel QPI interconnect %1 has a correctable error.
MEM9002.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the server and check whether the issue persists. 2) If the issue is not resolved by the preceding action, reseat the processors and restart the server. 3) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
MEM9002.Description: A correctable error was detected in propagation of signals between processors through the Intel QPI interconnect interconnect identified in the message.

TMP0122.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or cool.
TMP0122.Message: The system inlet temperature is outside of range.

PWR8559.Message: Power cycle initiated for I/O Module %1.
PWR8559.Description: Power cycle initiated for the I/O module in the slot identified in the message.

SYS405.Description: The request cannot be successfully completed because the JSON data format entered is invalid.
SYS405.Resolution: Do the following and the retry the operation: 1) Enter the correct JSON data format and retry the operation. 2) Make sure that no syntax error is present in JSON data format. 3) Make sure that a duplicate key is not present in JSON data format.
SYS405.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the JSON data format entered in invalid.

CTL79.Message: Controller in %1 is not supported and will not be powered on.
CTL79.Resolution: Replace the controller with a supported controller.
CTL79.Description: This controller does not support features required for this chassis. This controller will not be powered on to prevent data loss.

RAC0231.Description: This message is displayed when a confirmation is required to format the vFlash SD Card partition.
RAC0231.Resolution: Press OK to initialize this partition of the SD Card. This action will erase all the data in this partition. If undesired press Cancel.
RAC0231.Message: This operation erases all data in the partition. Do you want to continue?

MEM9007.Message: Intel SMI 2 Memory interconnect %1 has a non-recoverable issue.
MEM9007.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reseat the memory riser and restart the server. 2) If the issue is not resolved by preceding action, reseat the processor and restart the server. 3) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
MEM9007.Description: A non-recoverable link issue was detected in propagation of signals between processor and memory through the Intel SMI 2 memory interconnect identified in the message.

VDR31.Message: Controller cache is preserved for missing or offline %1.
VDR31.Resolution: Try importing foreign disks, if any. Check if the enclosure containing the Virtual Disk is disconnected from the controller. Insert any disks that are reported missing or failed. If the enclosure or disks were removed intentionally, the preserved cache can be discarded. See storage hardware documentation for more information on performing these steps.
VDR31.Description: The controller is getting disconnected from its virtual disk, while Input Output (IO) is in-progress.

UEFI0190.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.
UEFI0190.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0190.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Clock DCC Training phase.

SYS255.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported verify certificate value.
SYS255.Resolution: Make sure that the correct verify certificate value is entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS255.Description: The file cannot be transferred because a verify certificate value is not entered, or the entered value is not supported.

UEFI0039.Description: Unable to communicate with iDRAC because of an issue in the iDRAC Keyboard Controller Style (KCS) Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI). Continuing to boot may result in unexpected power loss because of unknown power inventory and unavailability of features such as remote out of band access, active power management, thermal management, inventory collection, LCD, or system error reporting.
UEFI0039.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware on the system.
UEFI0039.Message: Unable to communicate with iDRAC because of an issue in the iDRAC Keyboard Controller Style (KCS) Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI).

STOR300.Description: The requested operation could not be completed because at least one other pending operation was found on the RAID controller. This operation needs exclusivity because it requires a server reboot for changes to apply.
STOR300.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Create a job to complete the pending operations, allow the job to complete, and then retry the operation. 2) Cancel any pending operations on the RAID controller, and then retry the operation.
STOR300.Message: Unable to change the controller mode because there are already pending operations.

RAC1114.Message: Configuration XML file preview operation job is initiated. Job ID = %1
RAC1114.Resolution: Monitor the status of the preview operation job by running the racadm command "racadm jobqueue view -i <job ID>".
RAC1114.Description: The configuration XML preview operation was successfully initiated and has generated a job with the job ID identified in the message.

SWC0036.Description: Unable to launch hardware diagnostics because the Enterprise UEFI Diagnostics application is corrupt or iDRAC is not responding.
SWC0036.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, update the Enterprise UEFI Diagnostics using one of the following methods: 1) Use the Firmware Update feature in Lifecycle Controller. 2) Use the Server Update Utility. 3) Run the Update Package from the operating system. If the problem continues to persist, reset the iDRAC. For more information, contact your service provider.

PDR83.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SUP011.Description: The specified Job ID was not found in the job queue.
SUP011.Resolution: Verify the job ID and retry the action. Retrieve all open jobs by issuing the GetAllJobs command.

STOR041.Resolution: Specify a valid value for the attribute identified in the message and retry the operation.
STOR041.Description: Unable to complete the requested operation because an invalid value for the attribute identified in the message is specified.

TMP5.Message: The temperature probe maximum warning value was changed on %1.
TMP5.Description: You have changed the value for the maximum temperature probe warning threshold. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SYS408.Description: Only one task ID is displayed. By default, the location response header displays information about only one task ID.
SYS408.Resolution: To view all task IDs, run the "Tasks" Redfish API.
SYS408.Message: Only one task ID is displayed in the response.

CTL98.Description: The security key provided as input has been assigned to the controller identified in the message.

SYS020.Description: The value provided for the required attribute is invalid.
SYS020.Resolution: The value specified is not valid. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services documentation for more information.

SWC8531.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to set the administrator role for the iDRAC root user. This can happen if the communication to the iDRAC from CMC is non-functional or iDRAC is rebooting.
SWC8531.Resolution: If communications with the iDRAC is not functioning, reset the iDRAC and retry the operation after a few minutes. Run the RACADM command "racadm ping server-<slot number> " to check the communications. If the communications are not functional, restart the iDRAC by performing a Virtual Reseat of the server using the RACADM command "racadm racreset -m server-<slot id>".
SWC8531.Message: Chassis Management Controller unable to set iDRAC administrator role for root user account.

UEFI0226.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0226.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0226.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the DDR4 LR-DIMM Transmit Buffer Training phase.

RAC050.Description: The country code is not entered in the correct format or does not exist. Refer to ISO 3166 for the correct country code format.
RAC050.Resolution: Enter country code in the correct format as defined in ISO 3166. For example, United States = US.

TMP0102.Message: The system board %1 temperature is greater than the upper warning threshold.
TMP0102.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0102.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.

SWC0282.Description: The value being modified is READ only.
SWC0282.Message: The specified object is READ ONLY for this index and cannot be modified.

SYS021.Message: Unable to set the value for %1
SYS021.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, do one of the following: 1) verify the value being set is correct, 2) reset the iDRAC.
SYS021.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of incorrect parameters or internal firmware issues.

UEFI0164.Message: Unable to enable the Advanced ECC memory operating mode because of mismatches in the DIMM channel configurations on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0164.Resolution: Make sure identical memory modules in corresponding slots of channel pairs are populated. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0164.Description: The Advanced ECC memory operating mode cannot be enabled because of mismatches in the DIMM channel configurations.

PWR2211.Message: The system is in legacy ON state.

OSD2.Resolution: 1) Rerun the command. 2) Reset iDRAC and run the command.

HWC5014.Message: %1 is not functional and is powered off.
HWC5014.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.

RED094.Message: Updating firmware for %1 from version %2 to version %3.
RED094.Description: The firmware for the component identified in the message is being updated to the firmware version identified in the message.

STOR019.Description: The passphrase specified does not follow the passphrase character criteria of the controller character.
STOR019.Resolution: Enter a passphrase that meets the passphrase character criteria of the controller, and then retry the operation.
STOR019.Message: The specified passphrase is not valid.

PDR43.Message: The clear operation on %1 has completed.
PDR43.Description: This message is generated after a clear operation completes on a physical disk.

SWC1923.Description: The server configuration cannot be modified by using Quick Sync because invalid credentials are entered.
SWC1923.Resolution: Make sure that correct user name and password are entered, and then retry the operation.
SWC1923.Message: Unable to modify the server configuration by using Quick Sync because invalid credentials are entered.

ASR0003.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate to the baseboard management controller (BMC). The system powered cycled per the configured setting.
ASR0003.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0003.Message: The watchdog timer power cycled the system.

PWR2201.Message: The system is sleeping with system hardware and processor context maintained.

SYS053.Description: Configuration changes specified in the Server Configuration Profile were successfully applied.
SYS053.Message: Successfully imported and applied Server Configuration Profile.

ISM0033.Message: The user %1, without necessary privileges, tried to perform a Full Power Cycle operation from the operating system (OS).
ISM0033.Description: The user identified in the message, without necessary privileges, tried to perform a Full Power Cycle operation from the operating system (OS).

RAC0673.Description: To export operating system (OS) and application data, the OS Collector utility must be run on the server OS. A virtual USB device labeled DRACRW has appeared in the server OS. After the OS Collector utility execution has completed, return to this page to complete exporting the Tech Support Report (TSR).
RAC0673.Resolution: Invoke the OS Collector utility in the OS and wait for execution completion. Then return to this page to complete exporting the Technical Support Report (TSR).
RAC0673.Message: OS Collector must be run on the server OS in order to export OS and Application Data. A virtual USB device labeled DRACRW has appeared in the server OS. This device contains the OS Collector utility, go to the Server OS and run the version of the utility appropriate to the OS type. After the OS Collector utility execution has completed, return to this page to finish exporting the Technical Support Report (TSR).

PDR1105.Message: Drive %1 is in the critical array.

RED074.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because the required parameters were not present in the method invocation.
RED074.Resolution: Verify that all required parameters for the method are present and retry the operation.
RED074.Message: A required parameter is not present.

ISM0008.Description: iDRAC Service Module detected that OpenManage Server Administrator is running on the OS of this server. Therefore, one or more features of iDRAC Service Module will be disabled.
ISM0008.Resolution: End the OpenManage Server Administrator session. The features will be automatically started by iDRAC Service Module.
