ISM0008.Message: Some features of iDRAC Service Module will be disabled on this server, because OpenManage Server Administrator is running on the operating system (OS) of this server.

RAC0244.Description: This message is displayed when a duplicate vFlash partition name is entered.
RAC0244.Resolution: Enter a unique label name for the partition.
RAC0244.Message: The partition label must be unique.

DIS105.Description: The network share folder cannot be accessed, because an unsupported or invalid share type is specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.
DIS105.Resolution: Enter a valid sharetype in DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC using (-s <0 or 1>) where 0 = NFS, 2 = CIFS.
DIS105.Message: The AutoConfig operation is unable to access the network share folder, because an invalid sharetype value is specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

SWC0313.Description: The syntax of the getconfig command is invalid.
SWC0313.Resolution: Refer the help text for getconfig subcommand.
SWC0313.Message: Invalid syntax. The -h option is not valid with any other options.

STOR042.Resolution: Specify a value for the attribute identified in the message by using one of the possible values currently available for that attribute.
STOR042.Description: Unable to complete the requested operation because the attribute value specified is not supported in the current configuration.

PCI1360.Message: A bus fatal error was detected on a component at slot %1.
PCI1360.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1360.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.

PWR1003.Description: To avoid shutdown, system performance has been degraded.
PWR1003.Resolution: If unintended, review system configuration changes and thermal policy.
PWR1003.Message: The system performance degraded because cooling capacity has changed.

OSD75.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'HashType' is invalid.
OSD75.Resolution: Check the value provided for input parameter "HashType" and retry the operation.
OSD75.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'HashType' is invalid.

VDR49.Resolution: Replace the failed disks and restore from backup.
VDR49.Description: A redundant virtual disk has lost redundancy. This may occur when the virtual disk suffers the failure of more than one physical disk. In this case, both the source physical disk and the target disk with redundant data have failed. A rebuild is not possible because there is no longer redundancy.

LNK8500.Message: Unable to connect the server in slot %1 to the IOM in slot %2 port %3, because the IOM port is down.
LNK8500.Resolution: Do one of the following, and then retry the operation: 1) Check whether or not the external network cable is functioning. 2) Reinstall or replace network cable of the IOM and port identified in the message.
LNK8500.Description: The server identified in the message could not be successfully connected to the external network, because the network connection is not functional.

PCI3008.Message: A non-fatal PCIe error detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.
PCI3008.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, remove and re-install the device at the next service window.

RAC1123.Description: Fibre Channel (FC) objects are not available if Fibre Channel devices are not installed in the server, or if some iDRAC services are busy.
RAC1123.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Power off and remove AC or DC power from the server. 2) Make sure the Fibre Channel devices are correctly installed in the server. 3) Restart the server to allow the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature to update the server inventory. 4) Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC1123.Message: Unable to perform the operation because Fibre Channel (FC) attributes are not available in the current server configuration.

CTL72.Message: The foreign configuration overflow has occurred on %1.
CTL72.Resolution: Import these foreign configurations in multiple attempts.
CTL72.Description: There is too much foreign configuration data to be imported in one attempt.

ISM0032.Message: The Full Power Cycle operation is successfully cancelled by the server operating system (OS) user %1 from the OS on date %2.
ISM0032.Resolution: No response action is required. For information about Virtual AC powercycle, see the platform User's Guide available on the support site.
ISM0032.Description: The Full Power Cycle operation is successfully cancelled by the server operating system (OS) user from the OS on date as identified in the message.

USR107.Message: The operation %1 of the %2 was performed by %3
USR107.Description: The identified user has performed the identified set operation or invoke method operation. The operation is either set on an instance of the class identified or an invocation of the identified method.

UEFI0134.Description: Unable to allocate Memory Mapped Input Output (MMIO) resources for one or more PCIe devices because of insufficient MMIO memory.
UEFI0134.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove unused PCIe card(s) to free up MMIO space. 2) Go to System Setup and enable the 'Memory Mapped I/O above 4GB' option.
UEFI0134.Message: Unable to allocate Memory Mapped Input Output (MMIO) resources for one or more PCIe devices because of insufficient MMIO memory.

RED004.Description: The job cannot be completed because of an internal error.
RED004.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact the service provider.
RED004.Message: Unable to complete the job because of an internal error.

OSD25.Description: Detaching the USB device (that contains drivers for the operating system installation) from the host has failed. The device may be detached, or iDRAC may not be operating normally.
OSD25.Resolution: Reset iDRAC to detach this device automatically.
OSD25.Message: Unable to detach USB device containing operating system drivers.

STOR5.Resolution: Identify and replace the failed components. To identify the failed component, select the Storage object and click the Health subtab. The controller status displayed on the Health subtab indicates whether a controller has a failed or degraded component. Click the controller that displays a Warning or Failed status. This action displays the controller Health subtab which displays the status of the individual controller components. Continue clicking the components with a Warning or Failed status until you identify the failed component. See Storage Health for more information. See the enclosure documentation for information on replacing enclosure components and for other diagnostic information.
STOR5.Description: A virtual disk or enclosure has lost data redundancy. In the case of a virtual disk, one or more physical disks included in the virtual disk have failed. Due to the failed physical disk or disks, the virtual disk is no longer maintaining redundant (mirrored or parity) data. The failure of an additional physical disk will result in lost data. In the case of an enclosure, more than one enclosure component has failed. For example, the enclosure may have suffered the loss of all fans or all power supplies.

NIC503.Description: The value of the specified parameter cannot be changed.
NIC503.Message: The DNS server IP address is not allowed to be configured if DNS server DHCP (cfgDNSServersFromDHCP) is enabled.

SWC8540.Message: The add key operation successfully completed for slot %1 of service account.
SWC8540.Description: The Public Key (PK) SSH Authentication key file is successfully uploaded to the Chassis Management Controller.

SYS055.Description: The configuration specified in the Server Configuration Profile was applied, but there were some errors. The Lifecycle Controller Log contains the details of the component configurations that did not complete successfully.
SYS055.Resolution: Review the Lifecycle Controller Log and identify the configuration changes that did not complete successfully. Retry those changes in a separate operation.
SYS055.Message: Import of Server Configuration Profile operation completed with errors.

SWC8542.Description: The Profile identified in the message is exported.

STOR306.Description: Controller mode cannot be changed as the controller currently has the security key assigned.
STOR306.Resolution: Delete the security key and retry the operation.
STOR306.Message: Unable to change controller mode while security key is assigned to the controller.

PSU0023.Message: Power supply %1 operating at 110 volts has been acknowledged by user.

UEFI0274.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the iSCSI login operation did not complete successfully.
UEFI0274.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings > Connection Settings page, make sure the target name is correct. 2) On the iSCSI target system, make sure the initiator name is added into the target identifiers. 3) Compare the authentication settings in the iSCSI initiator setup page to that of the iSCSI target system and make sure the settings match. 4) Retry the operation.
UEFI0274.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the iSCSI login operation did not complete successfully.

HWC3004.Resolution: If removal was unintended, check presence, then re-insert.

RAC0760.Description: Unable to perform storage configuration operations on physical disk drive(s) as there are no disk drive(s) available with Ready/RAID/NON-RAID state or the selected controller is in HBA mode.
RAC0760.Resolution: Check the following: 1) If there are no physical disk drive(s) in either Ready state or in RAID/NON-RAID state, insert additional disk drive(s). 2) If the Controller(s) are in HBA mode, switch the controller(s) to RAID mode. To switch controller(s) to RAID mode using the F2 System Setup utility, go to Device Settings > RAID Controller > Controller Management > Advanced Controller Management > Switch to RAID mode.
RAC0760.Message: Unable to perform physical disk(s) storage configuration operations for the selected controller.

PR10.Message: Firmware update will not be performed. Firmware package is not present for %1
PR10.Resolution: Use Unified Server Configurator or Dell update package to update device.
PR10.Description: The Part Replacement feature has detected a firmware difference and would apply firmware based on user settings for the system. However, the previous device's firmware update package is not present on the Lifecycle Controller.

UEFI0230.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0230.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0230.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Receive Enable Training - Calculation phase.

RAC0751.Description: The value for information or warning threshold should not be less than lower critical threshold value.
RAC0751.Resolution: Enter a threshold value that is greater than the lower warning or critical threshold values and retry the operation.
RAC0751.Message: The threshold value entered is less than the lower warning or critical threshold.

PDR64.Message: An unrecoverable disk media error occurred on %1.
PDR64.Description: The rebuild or recovery operation encountered an unrecoverable disk media error.

ENC17.Message: An Enclosure Management Module (EMM) has been discovered on %1.
ENC17.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PR13.Description: The Part Replacement feature detected a firmware difference and cannot apply the configuration changes. After the device firmware is updated, configuration changes can be applied.
PR13.Message: Firmware mismatch detected. Configuration changes not applied.

RAC0756.Description: Fan information cannot be displayed. This situation may occur if the server is powered off.
RAC0756.Resolution: Power on the server. If the server is already powered on, wait for a few minutes and refresh the page. If the problem persists, contact your service provider.
RAC0756.Message: Unable to retrieve the fan information.

SYS198.Description: An internal iDRAC memory component is unresponsive.
SYS198.Resolution: The iDRAC requires an AC power cycle. Do the following: 1) Determine a time that the AC power can be removed and then reapplied to the server. 2) Save data and perform an AC power cycle.
SYS198.Message: Unable to communicate with internal iDRAC memory.

RSI0002.Description: The Remote Service database is currently not available.
RSI0002.Message: The remote service is currently not available

HWC2001.Message: The %1 cable or interconnect is not connected or is improperly connected.
HWC2001.Resolution: Check presence, then re-install or reconnect.
HWC2001.Description: The cable may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.

PWR206.Description: The Server Based Power Management (SBPM) feature cannot be enabled because the Extended Power Performance mode is enabled.
PWR206.Resolution: Disable Extended Power Performance and retry the operation.
PWR206.Message: The Server Based Power Management (SBPM) feature cannot be enabled because the Extended Power Performance mode is enabled.

RAC1040.Description: The requested RAID storage operation was successfully accepted and now must be applied by creating a RAID storage configuration job.
RAC1040.Resolution: To apply the configuration operation, create a configuration job, and then restart the server. To create the required commit and reboot jobs, run the jobqueue command. For more information about the jobqueue command, enter the RACADM command "racadm help jobqueue".
RAC1040.Message: Successfully accepted the RAID storage configuration operation. The change is in pending state.

UEFI0054.Description: Debranding process is completed. The system is being restarted.
UEFI0054.Message: Debranding process is completed. The system is being restarted.

IOV119.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) has disabled PCIe ride-through mode. PCIe adapters that are turned on and in "ride-through" mode are immediately turned off.

STOR302.Description: The job could not be created because the Apply Operation Mode selected is not supported for this operation.
STOR302.Resolution: Choose a different Apply Operation mode "Apply at Next Reboot" from the Apply Operation Mode drop-down menu.
STOR302.Message: Unable to create the job because the Apply Operation Mode selected is not supported for this operation.

RRDU0006.Description: Internal Dual SD Module rebuild initiated.
RRDU0006.Message: Internal Dual SD Module rebuild initiated.

RED073.Message: The input value entered for the parameter %1 is invalid.
RED073.Resolution: Verify the value for the parameter identified in the message is valid and retry the operation.
RED073.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an invalid value for the parameter identified in the message.

NIC007.Description: A configuration job already exists for the specified target. No further configuration operation is allowed until the existing job completes or the job is cancelled.
NIC007.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Wait for the existing configuration job to complete and retry the operation, 2) To continue with a configuration change, cancel the existing job and retry the operation.
NIC007.Message: A configuration job already exists, Cannot create another configuration job on specified target until existing job is completed or is cancelled

USR0034.Message: Login attempt alert for %1 from %2 using %3, IP will be blocked for %4 seconds.
USR0034.Resolution: Contact the iDRAC administrator and make sure the username and password credentials used are correct. Check the Lifecycle Controller Log (LC Log) to see if more unauthorized iDRAC access attempts are occurring than would be expected due to forgotten account names or passwords.
USR0034.Description: The account identified in the message is temporarily disabled because of consecutive unsuccessful Login attempts to iDRAC from the IP address identified in the message.

OSD47.Description: Unable to access the network share using the credentials specified or the firewall might be enabled and is preventing access to the share.
OSD47.Resolution: Make sure that the firewall is disabled, and that the credentials (username, password) are correct.

RAC1047.Description: Successfully cleared the Automatic Update(autoupdate) feature settings.
RAC1047.Message: Successfully cleared the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings.

UEFI0015.Description: The BIOS is unable to access the Lifecycle Controller firmware. No Lifecycle Controller functionality is available while in Recovery Mode.
UEFI0015.Resolution: Perform the following actions: 1)Reboot the system. 2) Press F2 during boot to enter System Setup. 3) Select iDRAC Settings then Lifecycle Controller. 4) Change Lifecycle Controller back to Enabled. If subsequent failures occur, press and hold the system ID button down for 15 seconds to reset the iDRAC. For more information on how to reset iDRAC, see iDRAC User's Guide.
UEFI0015.Message: Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible and is therefore in Recovery mode.

RAC1009.Description: The Active Directory objects DCLookupEnable or GCLookupEnable cannot be enabled, because IPv4.DNS1, IPv4.DNS2, IPv6.DNS1, or IPv6.DNS2 is not configured.
RAC1009.Resolution: Configure IPv4.DNS1, IPv4.DNS2, IPv6.DNS1, or IPv6.DNS2 using racadm set command, and retry the operation. For example, "racadm set iDRAC.IPv4.DNS1 <address>".
RAC1009.Message: The Active Directory objects DCLookupEnable or GCLookupEnable cannot be enabled.

TMP0302.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature cannot be enabled because the necessary power or fan configuration is not available.
TMP0302.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Check the available power and the fan configuration. 2) If the required power for Enhanced Cooling mode is not available, remove other chassis components which are not being used in order to obtain sufficient power. 3) If the fan configuration does not support Enhanced Cooling Mode, replace unsupported fans with supported ones. 4) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
TMP0302.Message: Unable to set Enhanced Cooling Mode because the required power or fan configuration is not available.

SYS077.Description: Unable to perform the preview operation because the specified system configuration XML file does not exist on the remote share.
SYS077.Resolution: Make sure the configuration XML file to be previewed exists on the remote share before retrying the operation.
SYS077.Message: Unable to perform the preview operation because the specified file does not exist on the remote share.

SYS155.Message: Initiating clear operation on non-secure erase-capable drives for controller: %1.
SYS155.Description: Initiating clear operation on non-secure erase-capable drives for the controller identified in the message.

VDR38.Description: A user renamed a virtual disk. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PST0085.Description: System is performing CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart).

STOR052.Description: Virtual disks cannot be created because the maximum number of logical drives per controller or diskgroup is reached.
STOR052.Resolution: Refer to the User's Guide of the specific controller available at the support site for information on the number of supported virtual disks allowed.
STOR052.Message: Unable to create virtual disk, maximum number of created virtual disks per controller or diskgroup has been reached.

RAC1070.Message: Unable to set the maximum non critical threshold value of %1, because the value entered is greater than, or equal to the maximum critical threshold value.
RAC1070.Resolution: Check the maximum critical threshold level using an appropriate RACADM command. For example, to view the maximum critical threshold value of a sensor, run the 'racadm getsensorinfo' command at the command line interface, and then retry the operation. For more information about other RACADM commands, run the racadm help command.
RAC1070.Description: The maximum non critical threshold value identified in the message cannot be set, because the value entered is greater than or equal to the maximum critical threshold value.

NIC009.Description: Lifecycle Controller cannot gain access to internal storage because it is use by another application or operation.
NIC009.Resolution: Wait for the current Lifecycle Controller operation to complete. Verify that the system is 1) Not currently in Lifecycle Controller Unified Server Configurator utility 2) Not waiting for user intervention at F1/F2 POST error 3) Not in any of the device or controller Option ROMs and retry the operation.
NIC009.Message: Lifecycle Controller is currently in use.

SWC8550.Description: An insufficient number of unused MAC addresses are available in the Virtual MAC Address database to capture the requested number of profiles.
SWC8550.Resolution: Add more MAC addresses to the Virtual MAC Address Pool and retry the capture Boot Identity profile operation. Using the CMC GUI, navigate to the Boot Identity page. More MAC addresses are added using "Add MAC Address" option provided in "Manage Virtual MAC Address Pool" section.
SWC8550.Message: Unable to capture the server profile because an insufficient number of unused Media Access Control (MAC) addresses in the Virtual MAC Address Pool.

VDR35.Description: Background initialization of a virtual disk completed.

RAC0660.Description: The file server cannot be accessed because of incorrect credentials.
RAC0660.Resolution: Check the file server credentials and retry the operation.
RAC0660.Message: Unable to access the specified file server location.

PWR8681.Message: The %1 firmware in the server slot %2 does not support additional PCIe slots.
PWR8681.Resolution: Update the firmware identified in the message to the supported latest available version. See the latest iDRAC User Guide for information on the versions that support the PCIe reassignment.
PWR8681.Description: The firmware identified in the message does not support the PCIe reassignment operation.

RAC1139.Description: The requested file can be exported from the firmware racadm only to a remote file share.
RAC1139.Resolution: Create a remote file share to export the file or use remote or local racadm to export to the file system that is accessible by the racadm executable.
RAC1139.Message: The entered option is not supported by the interface.

STOR057.Description: The instrumentation for the specified RAID controller is not in state where the requested operation can be performed because system inventory collection (the CSIOR feature) has not been executed.
STOR057.Resolution: Enable the CSIOR (Collect System Inventory On Restart) feature and restart the server to cause CSIOR execution. Make sure the Remote Services status is Ready and retry the operation. To get the Remote Services status, invoke the GetRSStatus method. For more information about this method, see Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Guide.
STOR057.Message: The specified RAID controller is not currently available for configuration.

STOR082.Description: The operation cannot be stopped or canceled because the operation is not currently running.
STOR082.Resolution: Make sure the operation is running before attempting to cancel or stop the operation.
STOR082.Message: The operation cannot be stopped or cancelled because the operation is not currently running.

LC046.Description: The DownloadServerPublicKey operation is in progress. The operation may take a few minutes to complete before the operation can be attempted again.
LC046.Resolution: Wait a few minutes before retrying retry the operation.
LC046.Message: An instance of DownloadServerPublicKey is already running.

VLT0100.Message: Processor module %1 voltage is less than the lower warning threshold.
VLT0100.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Remove the processor module. Inspect processor socket for bent pins. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0100.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

UEFI0056.Description: The PCIe error is logged during Power-on-Self-Test (POST). The error could have occurred during either the current or the previous POST.
UEFI0056.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the PCIe device that is not functioning correctly, and then update the device firmware.

PWR8668.Description: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) has initiated the process of resetting iKVM.
PWR8668.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) has initiated the process of resetting iKVM.

RAC0120.Description: Requested partition size exceeds the available space.
RAC0120.Resolution: Enter a partition size smaller than the unused space on the vFlash SD card.
RAC0120.Message: The selected partition size exceeds the available space.

UEFI0148.Message: The SAS cable %1 for the primary SAS expander daughter card is missing or misconfigured.
UEFI0148.Resolution: Check the cable configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0148.Description: The SAS cable for the primary SAS expander daughter card is missing or misconfigured.

RAC0677.Description: No physical disk drives in ready state, virtual disks, or PCIe SSD drives are available to perform operations on.
RAC0677.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1. If there are no disk drives available in ready state, insert additional disk drives and make sure the drives are in ready state. 2. If no virtual disks are present, click <create virtualdisk link> and create at least one virtual disk. 3. If PCIe SSD drives are inserted into the enclosure or attached to the backplane.
RAC0677.Message: No physical disk drives in ready state, no virtual disks are created, and no PCIe SSD drives are available to perform operations on.

CMC8551.Description: The message is displayed if the chassis health is not OK (non-critical or critical). The message after this message in the log indicates cause for the issue.

VLT0235.Message: The mezzanine card %1 %2 voltage is within range.

SYS424.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the value %1 entered for the property %2 is of different type than the property can accept.
SYS424.Resolution: Enter a valid value in the expected type for the property in the request body and retry the operation.For information about valid values, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
SYS424.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the value entered for the property identified in the message is of invalid type.

SWC0037.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to export the file to the network share because the destination folder is not present or inaccessible.
SWC0037.Resolution: Make sure that the destination folder is present and accessible, then retry the operation. If the problem persists, check network settings and retry the operation.
SWC0037.Message: Unable to export the file to the network share.

SWC5002.Message: %1 upgrade was successful but encountered minor errors.
SWC5002.Resolution: Check system logs for minor errors.

DIS007.Description: Unable to connect to Provisioning Server to notify about new iDRAC IP .
DIS007.Resolution: Check Provisioning Server connectivity and retry.
DIS007.Message: Unable to notify Provisioning Server of iDRAC IP address change.

VLT0208.Message: The memory module %1 %2 voltage is greater than the upper warning threshold.
VLT0208.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0208.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

SWC8518.Message: Unable to modify password of User %1: %2-%3
SWC8518.Resolution: Make sure: 1) The login credentials for the operation have user config administration privilege, 2) The user name and password given are valid. If the issue persists, restart the CMC and retry the operation.
SWC8518.Description: Unable to modify the password of the User identified in the message.

RAC0744.Description: Unable to perform storage configuration operations because neither Storage controllers nor PCIe Extenders detected on the system.
RAC0744.Message: Unable to perform storage configuration operations because neither Storage controllers nor PCIe Extenders detected on the system.

OSD35.Description: Lifecycle Controller is disabled on the system, so none of the remote operating system deployment commands will work. Make sure Lifecycle Controller is enabled before running any command.
OSD35.Resolution: For 11G systems: Use the iDRAC configuration utility to enable the System Services by pressing on the CTRL+E option on boot up at the targeted system. For 12G and above generations: Use F2 Setup, select iDRAC Configuration, and select Lifecycle Controller Settings, to enable the Lifecycle Controller on boot up of the targeted system.

PCI1304.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1304.Message: An I/O channel check error was detected.

RED036.Resolution: Update the component firmware to the version available in the specified remote repository.
RED036.Description: Firmware updates are available for component identified in the message in the specified remote repository and it is recommended to update to the firmware available in the repository.

RAC0207.Description: Certificate upload failed possibly due to poor network connection.
RAC0207.Resolution: Try the operation again in a few minutes. If the problem persists, issue a new Certificate Signing Request (CSR) and try again.

UEFI0022.Description: The Management Engine firmware cannot be initialized because the Management Engine is not responding.
UEFI0022.Resolution: Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system.
UEFI0022.Message: Unable to initialize Management Engine because the Management Engine is not responding.

RAC034.Resolution: Wait for existing jobs to run to completion or delete some jobs from the job queue.
RAC034.Message: Unable to create a job because the job queue is full.

OSD26.Description: Unable to continue with BootToPXE command because another process is using Lifecycle Controller.
OSD26.Resolution: See ConcreteJob status to make sure that the running process is complete, and then run BootToPXE.
OSD26.Message: Unable to continue with BootToPXE - another command is running.

RAC065.Description: The iDRAC reset operation was not successful. This may be due to IPMI communications issues.
RAC065.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, remove AC input power from the server and re-apply AC power to the server and retry the operation. 3) If the issue continues to persist, contact your service provider.
RAC065.Message: iDRAC reset operation was not successful.

SWC8612.Message: Unable to fully extract boot device information from profile: %1.
SWC8612.Resolution: Recreate the profile identified in the message or use a different profile.
SWC8612.Description: The profile identified in the message does not contain boot device information in a usable format.

PCI1350.Message: A PCI system error was detected on a component at slot %1.
PCI1350.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1350.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.

RAC0516.Description: Converting physical disk drives to RAID-compatible will overwrite any OS-created RAID arrays.
RAC0516.Resolution: Make sure that there are no OS-configured RAID arrays, and then click OK.
RAC0516.Message: Converting physical disk drives to RAID-compatible will overwrite any OS-created RAID arrays.

SUP005.Description: Reboot value specified is not supported.
SUP005.Resolution: Verify the reboot value and retry the action. Current options available are 1)Power Cycle 2) Graceful shutdown without forced shutdown 3) Graceful shutdown with forced shutdown (~10 minutes wait time).

JCP8501.Message: Job ID: %1. CMC sent %2 properties from %3 profile to the server (Service Tag: %4 ) in the slot %5.
JCP8501.Description: This job information message occurs if some configuration stored in the profile are not applicable to the target server.

UEFI0215.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0215.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0215.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Basic Write Level Training phase.

PDR1020.Message: Consistency check for drive %1 in disk drive bay %2 completed.

UEFI0251.Message: Memory riser %1 is populated behind an empty processor socket.
UEFI0251.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Populate processors and memory in a supported configuration and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0251.Description: A memory riser was detected behind an empty processor socket. Memory must be installed behind a populated processor socket in order to be recognized by the system and available for usage. Check to make sure processors and memory are installed in a supported configuration.

SWC0308.Description: The syntax of the fwupdate command is invalid.
SWC0308.Resolution: Refer the help text for fwupdate subcommand.
SWC0308.Message: The -d option requires -g to also be specified.

RAC1185.Description: The static IPv6 address is not configured because an invalid IPv6 address or IPv6 Gateway is entered.
RAC1185.Resolution: Enter a valid IPv6 address and IPv6 Gateway, and retry the operation.
RAC1185.Message: Unable to configure static IPv6 address because an invalid IPv6 address or IPv6 Gateway is entered.

ISM0014.Description: The feature identified in the message is disabled by using one of the iDRAC interfaces.

CPU0003.Resolution: 1) Turn off the server and disconnect input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Reduce system configuration to minimum memory and remove all PCI devices. If system completes POST, update system BIOS. Re-install memory and PCI one component at a time to meet the original configuration. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

RAC0132.Description: A separate message will provide more detail about this error which was detected while formatting the vFlash partition.
RAC0132.Message: An error has occurred while formatting a partition.

LC061.Description: Jobs, invoke methods, enumerates can now be performed on Lifecycle controller. Lifecycle controller is ready to take provisioning requests.
LC061.Message: Lifecycle controller is ready to take provisioning requests

SUP018.Description: The specified until time is invalid.
SUP018.Resolution: Until Time should be in the form YYYYMMDDHHMMSS. Verify the specified until time and retry the action.

SEC0600.Description: This may apply to a physical or remote access attempt.
SEC0600.Resolution: Check system logs for intrusion attempts, and ensure strong password policies.

RAC1153.Description: The time stamp was not recorded for the previous techsupreport collect operation.
RAC1153.Resolution: Run the RACADM techsupreport collect command. After the techsupreport collect operation completes, run the RACADM getupdatetime command.
RAC1153.Message: The time stamp is not available to display.

VFL1017.Message: Media is present for Removable Flash Media %1.

OSD46.Description: Another process (iDRAC GUI /racadm/iDRAC configuration utility) is currently accessing vFlash.
OSD46.Resolution: Wait until the access to vFlash is relinquished and then retry this command.

RED084.Description: The Chassis firmware cannot be updated because of an issue in the communication between iDRAC and CMC.
RED084.Resolution: Verify the status of CMC by accessing the CMC and making sure it is functioning and responding and then retry the operation. For more information about troubleshooting a CMC issue, see the CMC User Manual. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RED084.Message: Unable to update the Chassis firmware because of an issue in the network communication between iDRAC and CMC.

RAC1071.Message: Unable to set maximum non critical threshold value of %1, because the value entered is less than, or equal to the minimum non critical threshold value.
RAC1071.Resolution: Check the minimum non critical threshold level using an appropriate RACADM command. For example, to view the minimum non critical threshold value of a sensor, run the 'racadm getsensorinfo' command at the command line interface, and then retry the operation. For more information about other RACADM commands, run the racadm help command.
RAC1071.Description: The maximum non critical threshold value identified in the message cannot be set, because the value entered is less than or equal to the minimum non critical threshold value.

PDR107.Message: The physical disk drive %1 is assigned as a global hot-spare.
PDR107.Description: The physical disk drive identified in the message is assigned as a global hot-spare.

RED051.Description: The update package file download was not successful. This could be due to the following: 1) The update package file is missing, 2) The host address, share, user name, and password information are correct but the file name was invalid, 3) The network file share could not be mounted, or 4) The network file share disconnected before the transfer was complete.
RED051.Resolution: Check the network connection and access to the update package from the iDRAC.
RED051.Message: The network file transfer of an update package was not successful.

RED023.Description: The Lifecycle Controller is unable to access internal storage currently in use by another operation.
RED023.Resolution: Make sure all other Lifecycle Controller operations are finished and retry the operation. Using the iDRAC Web UI, select Server (on 12th and 13th Generation servers) or Maintenance (on 14th Generation Servers) and then Job Queue, check the job queue for unfinished jobs and wait for the jobs to finish before retrying the operation. Also, check whether there are update packages being executed in the server OS and wait for these operations to finish before retrying the operation. For remote web services API access, make sure that the GetRemoteServicesAPIStatus method returns Ready status, and then retry the operation. If OS Deploy has been enabled then boot the server into LC UI to clear. Always exit LC UI using "Exit" and not by removing power.
RED023.Message: Lifecycle Controller in use. This job will start when Lifecycle Controller is available.

SYS165.Description: One or more Tech Support Report data collection options selected did not complete successfully.
SYS165.Resolution: Look at the Lifecycle Log for exception messages and resolve the issues described.
SYS165.Message: One or more Tech Support Report data collection options selected did not complete successfully.

STOR0506.Description: The physical disk is unreadable or the RAID controller is not responding.
STOR0506.Resolution: Exit Lifecycle Controller, press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation. If the problem persists, replace the physical disk or update the RAID controller firmware to the latest version, and retry the operation.

OSE1007.Resolution: Review system boot configuration and boot media. See system video for additional information.

RAC1117.Description: The operation specified in the command could not be successfully completed.
RAC1117.Resolution: Retry the operation after 2 minutes. If the problem persists, contact your service provider.

PCI3012.Description: System performance may be degraded. The bus is not operating at maximum speed or width.
PCI3012.Resolution: Reset the system, if the problem persists reinstall processors.

OSD6.Description: Unable to dynamically allocate memory to perform the task.
OSD6.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and run the command.

VDR50.Message: Background Initialization (BGI) completed with uncorrectable errors on %1.
VDR50.Resolution: Review other messages to identify whether the physical disk that has errors. If the virtual disk is redundant, you can replace the physical disk and continue using the virtual disk. If the virtual disk is non-redundant, you need to recreate the virtual disk after replacing the physical disk. After replacing the physical disk, run a consistency check to verify the data.
VDR50.Description: The background initialization task encountered errors that cannot be corrected. The virtual disk contains physical disks that have unusable disk space or disk errors that cannot be corrected.

SWC0229.Description: Insufficient arguments passed to the command.
SWC0229.Resolution: Refer the help text for vflashpartition command.
SWC0229.Message: Some Necessary tag(s) are missing: -i -o -e -t -f & -s must be specified for create partition.

RAC0401.Description: Critical error from iDRAC service recovery program.

RAC1002.Description: The Active Directory SSO cannot be enabled, because the object SmartCardLogonEnable is enabled.
RAC1002.Resolution: Disable the object SmartCardLogonEnable using "racadm set iDRAC.SmartCard.LogonEnable <0 | Disabled>", and retry the operation.
RAC1002.Message: Active Directory Single Sign On (SSO) cannot be enabled.

RDU0032.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
RDU0032.Description: The system has multiple redundant voltage lines. One or more of these voltage lines is no longer available.

STOR003.Resolution: Refer to the RAID profile to determine required parameters.

RAC0219.Description: Requested power state change has failed.
RAC0219.Resolution: Try the operation after a few minutes. If the problem persists, reset iDRAC and repeat the operation.

PCI1310.Message: A PCI system error was detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.
PCI1310.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1310.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.

MEM0601.Message: Memory device is removed from location %1.

RAC0901.Description: The syntax of the specified command is invalid. In this case, the usage of the -t option is invalid.
RAC0901.Resolution: See the help text/documentation for the valid syntax of the subcommand.
RAC0901.Message: Invalid syntax. The -t option value must set to 1.

RAC006.Description: The attribute value cannot be changed because it is of read-only type.
RAC006.Message: The attribute value cannot be changed because it is of read-only type.

SYS243.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported proxy port number value, %2.
SYS243.Resolution: Make sure that the correct proxy port number value is entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS243.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an unsupported proxy port number value.

BAR117.Description: The firmware version for the iDRAC contained in the hardware Server Profile image is not compatible with this system hardware. Continue to use the installed firmware version or update to later versions if necessary.
BAR117.Message: The iDRAC firmware cannot be restored due to hardware compatibility restraints.

SWC8560.Message: %1 New Media Access Control (MAC) addresses are added to the Virtual MAC Address Pool for Boot Identity profile operations.
SWC8560.Description: New Media Access Control (MAC) addresses are added to the Virtual MAC Address Pool.

SWC0207.Message: Display the version info of RACADM

STOR081.Description: The job could not be created because the reboot type selected for the job creation and the reboot type required for pending operations do not match.
STOR081.Resolution: Change the reboot type for job creation and retry the operation.
STOR081.Message: The job could not be created because the reboot type selected for the job creation and the reboot type required for pending operations do not match.

HWC4002.Description: A hardware incompatibility was detected between BMC/iDRAC firmware and other hardware. An iDRAC or BMC firmware update is needed.
HWC4002.Resolution: Update the BMC/iDRAC firmware. If the problem persists, contact support.
HWC4002.Message: A hardware incompatibility detected between BMC/iDRAC firmware and other hardware.

BAR036.Description: A system profile import did not complete successfully and has left the system in an unusable state. Attempting to setup the environment for normal operation.
BAR036.Message: System Reset or Lifecycle Controller Actions Canceled, System Profile Failure Recovery initiated.

HWC8507.Description: The USB device inserted in to the I/O Panel USB port is causing an issue and cannot be used. The USB device may not be operational.
HWC8507.Resolution: Remove the USB device from the I/O Panel USB port, and then retry the operation with another USB device.
HWC8507.Message: The USB device inserted in to the I/O Panel USB port is causing an issue and cannot be used.

IOV012.Description: By default, the non-licensed system assigns virtual adapters (VA) 1-4 to servers 1-4 respectively.
IOV012.Resolution: Import a license which enables the assignment of a PERC virtual adapter (VA) to any server. For more information about licenses, contact your service provider.
IOV012.Message: Unable to assign a virtual adapter (VA) to a non-default server because a license is required.

LC028.Description: Hardware Inventory information is not retrievable due to an internal error.
LC028.Resolution: Try one of the following: 1) Try the operation again 2) AC power cycle system 3) apply the latest firmware update packages for Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC.
LC028.Message: Unable to retrieve Hardware Inventory information.

UEFI0265.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the iSCSI initiator IPv4 address is invalid.
UEFI0265.Resolution: Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings page, make sure there is no typographical error in the Initiator IP address field, and retry the operation.
UEFI0265.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the iSCSI initiator IPv4 address is invalid.

SEC0610.Description: This may apply to a remote access attempt.
SEC0610.Resolution: Check system logs for intrusion attempts, and ensure strong password policies.

SYS080.Description: Preview of Server Configuration Profile import operation indicates that no changes will be applied successfully. This is likely due to a mismatch between the actual target system components and component FQDDs specified in the configuration profile.
SYS080.Resolution: Make sure that the input file is compliant with the system configuration schema published on www.delltechcenter.com/lcand contains valid FQDDs that represent actual components in the target system.
SYS080.Message: Preview of Server Configuration Profile import operation indicated that no configuration changes will be successful.

RED055.Description: A reboot job for applying one or more update packages has been created. The server will reboot at the specified start time.

RAC0674.Description: Export Report will create a zip file of XML and text-based logs intended for Dell Technical Support assistance with troubleshooting system issues. Choose Advanced Export Options to specify optional report settings and actions.
RAC0674.Message: Export Report will create a zip file of XML and text-based logs intended for Dell Technical Support assistance with troubleshooting system issues. Choose Advanced Export Options to specify optional report settings and actions.

SWC8500.Message: Unable to generate Profile with [ %1 ] settings.
SWC8500.Resolution: Check if iDRAC is ready and system is running properly. Utilize the RACADM command by running "racadm getversion" to list all the servers and make sure the iDRAC version is displayed. If the iDRAC is listed as Not Ready then wait until it becomes ready. A Virtual Reseat may be required.

RAC018.Description: All the tasks in the Job were attempted, but some did not complete successfully.
RAC018.Resolution: Examine source of the errors by inspecting the results from the Job execution, and after resolving the issues, retry the operation. Job results can be retrieved from the Lifecycle Log or the WSMan API.
RAC018.Message: The Job is completed but with errors.

PST0127.Description: System BIOS gave control to the operating system.

RAC0118.Description: The SD card is not a valid vFlash SD card. The use of non-Dell media prevents the use of some extended capabilities and functions.
RAC0118.Resolution: Insert a supported vFlash SD card.

SYS069.Description: The settings specified in the system configuration XML file match the current configuration for all components.
SYS069.Message: No changes were applied since the current component configuration matched the requested configuration.

NIC008.Description: No changes are available between the previous configuration and the current configuration. To create a Configuration job, at least one attribute should be changed.
NIC008.Resolution: Change the configuration of one or more attributes and then create a configuration job.
NIC008.Message: No pending data present to create a Configuration job

RAC053.Description: One or more attributes being set are dependent on OS to iDRAC pass-through being enabled.
RAC053.Resolution: Enable OS to iDRAC pass-through and retry the previous command.
RAC053.Message: OS to iDRAC pass-through is disabled.

SYS013.Resolution: For more information, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
SYS013.Description: The attribute name provided for the requested operation does not exist on the target system or is invalid.

PDR19.Resolution: Replace the disk that has received the SMART alert. If the physical disk is a member of a non-redundant virtual disk, then back up the data before replacing the disk. Removing a physical disk that is included in a non-redundant virtual disk causes the virtual disk to fail and may cause data loss.
PDR19.Description: A disk on the specified controller has received a SMART alert (predictive failure) indicating that the disk is likely to fail in the near future.

RAC0663.Description: Resetting the selected PERC controller's configuration will delete all the virtual disks (VDs) and unassign hot-spares from the associated controller.
RAC0663.Message: Resetting the selected PERC controller's configuration will delete all the virtual disks (VDs) and unassign hot-spares from the associated controller.

RAC0255.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the IPv4 Subnet Mask does not conform to the required format.
RAC0255.Resolution: Enter a valid Subnet Mask. Expected ranges are: 255.XXX.0.0 [Class A], 255.255.XXX.0 [Class B], 255.255.255.XXX [Class C], and XXX.0.0.0 [others], where XXX must be valid (0,128,192,224,240,248,252,254).
RAC0255.Message: The Subnet Mask is invalid. Expected ranges are: 255.XXX.0.0 [Class A], 255.255.XXX.0 [Class B], 255.255.255.XXX [Class C], and XXX.0.0.0 [others], where XXX must be valid (0,128,192,224,240,248,252,254).

RAC0509.Description: The server is currently unable to handle the request due to temporary overloading or server maintenance.
RAC0509.Resolution: Wait for few minutes and refresh the page. If the issue persists, contact service provider.
RAC0509.Message: The server is temporarily unavailable. Try again after sometime.

FAN911.Description: The attempt to enable the Enhanced Cooling Mode (ECM) was not successful because ECM is already enabled or Gen3 fans are not present in the Chassis.
FAN911.Resolution: Check whether or not the Enhanced Cooling Mode (ECM) is already enabled. Make sure there are Gen3 fans in the Chassis and retry the operation.
FAN911.Message: The attempt to enable the Enhanced Cooling Mode was not successful.

SWC1920.Description: The Chassis Management at Server Mode is enabled.
SWC1920.Message: The Chassis Management at Server Mode is enabled.

IOV1004.Description: The parameters for the method identified in the message are not passed correctly.
IOV1004.Resolution: Refer to the DCIM Chassis PCI Management Profile document and provide the required parameters.
IOV1004.Message: Too many slots provided as parameters to Assign and UnAssign Servers methods.

HWC8510.Description: The heat sinks of the PCIe switches are properly attached.
HWC8510.Message: The heat sinks of the PCIe switches are properly attached.

PWR8514.Description: The user account credentials provided for this chassis power action do not have the correct privilege. Chassis control privilege is required to perform chassis power actions.
PWR8514.Resolution: Retry to action with a different user account that has chassis power control privilege.
PWR8514.Message: Unable to perform chassis power action due to insufficient privileges.

SWC8608.Message: Server Profiles: unable to access server: %1 for operation [%2] because of one or more of the following reasons: 1) iDRAC is not ready. 2) Lifecycle Controller of the server is disabled.
SWC8608.Resolution: Make sure that iDRAC on the server identified in the message is operating and that Lifecycle Controller is enabled, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, perform a virtual reseat of the server and retry the operation. To perform a virtual reseat of the server, on CMC Web interface, select Chassis Overview -> Troubleshooting -> Reset Components. On the Reset Components page, select Virtual Reseat from the drop-down menu for the server identified in the message.
SWC8608.Description: The CMC was unable to perform the operation described in the message because of one or more of the following reasons: 1) iDRAC is not ready. 2) Lifecycle Controller of the server is disabled.

RAC967.Description: The configuration XML file can only be exported to a remote share while using Firmware RACADM.
RAC967.Resolution: When using Firmware RACADM, make sure to export the configuration XML file to a remote share only.
RAC967.Message: Exporting the configuration XML file to a local share is not supported when using Firmware RACADM.

PCI3018.Description: New PCI card(s) have been detected in the system that may require additional airflow. Fan speeds may have changed to add additional cooling to the cards.
PCI3018.Resolution: Changing default fan response to PCIe cards should be done with appropriate understanding of the PCIe cooling needs of the cards present in the system. If the automatic cooling response is insufficient, additional cooling can be added by one of the following methods. 1) From iDRAC Web GUI, click Hardware -> Fans -> Setup, then from the fan speed offset drop-down list appropriately select the cooling level needed or set the minimum fan speed to a custom value. 2) From F2 System Setup, select iDRAC Settings -> Thermal, and set a higher fan speed from the fan speed offset or minimum fan speed. 3) For RACADM commands run "racadm help system.thermalsettings". If a lower fan speed is required, contact your service provider for the appropriate IPMI commands to reduce the default fan speed response for new PCIe cards.
PCI3018.Message: New PCI card(s) have been detected in the system. Fan speeds may have changed to add additional cooling to the cards.

UEFI0105.Description: The Cluster on Die (COD) feature cannot be enabled because of an unsupported memory configuration.
UEFI0105.Resolution: Make sure to populate all memory channels in the system with a minimum of one DIMM per channel. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0105.Message: Unable to enable the Cluster on Die (COD) feature because of an unsupported memory configuration.

PSU0803.Description: Insufficient power in chassis to power on server.
PSU0803.Resolution: Utilize the Chassis Management Controller web interface to check available power and server power requirements. If sufficient power is available, retry the operation.
PSU0803.Message: Insufficient power in chassis to power on server.

ISM0001.Message: The iDRAC Service Module detected a OS to iDRAC Pass-through in the %1 mode. Switch the OS to iDRAC Pass-through to a USB NIC mode.
ISM0001.Resolution: Configure OS to iDRAC Pass-through to the USB NIC mode by running the commands: 1) racadm set idrac.os-bmc.PTMode usb-p2p 2) racadm set idrac.os-bmc.UsbNicIpAddress <ip address> 3) racadm set idrac.os-bmc.adminstate enabled.
ISM0001.Description: The iDRAC Service Module detected a OS to iDRAC Pass-through mode as identified in the message. iDRAC Service Module will automatically connect to iDRAC after the OS to iDRAC Pass-through is configured to the USB NIC mode.

RAC982.Description: The PKCS12 file provided is invalid, because it may not be in the correct format.
RAC982.Resolution: For more details, contact the Certificate Authority.
RAC982.Message: Invalid Public Key Cryptography Standards version 12 (PKCS12) file detected.

SEC0005.Description: A removable component may have been tampered with, or installed incorrectly, or does not meet system requirements.
SEC0005.Resolution: Check removable hardware components for correct installation. Review installation documentation.

UEFI0020.Description: The Lifecycle Controller feature is enabled.
UEFI0020.Message: The Lifecycle Controller feature is enabled.

BIOS024.Description: The operation cannot run as the attribute value cannot be modified.
BIOS024.Resolution: For more information on the attribute, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
BIOS024.Message: The set operation did not complete successfully as the attribute is read-only.

BAR090.Description: A request to create a System Profile Backup file has been made by the user of the Unified Server Configurator interface.

UEFI0048.Description: The Collect System Inventory on Restart (CSIOR) operation is not performed during this restart because Lifecycle Controller firmware could not be accessed or run properly.
UEFI0048.Resolution: Repair Lifecycle Controller using the Update Package. For more information, see the Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.
UEFI0048.Message: The Collect System Inventory on Restart (CSIOR) operation is not performed during this restart because Lifecycle Controller is not functioning.

LC010.Description: The communications encryption certificate was imported successfully.

RAC1025.Description: Some objects have dependencies on other objects that are required to perform a task. However, some of the objects are read-only because of the current system configuration and the values of the dependent objects.
RAC1025.Resolution: Verify the object dependency using "racadm help <device class>.<group name>.<object name>", and retry the operation.
RAC1025.Message: The specified object is read-only and cannot be modified due to an object dependency.

RAC0130.Description: A separate message will provide more detail about this error which was detected while creating the vFlash partition.
RAC0130.Message: An error has occurred while creating a partition.

PWR2207.Message: The system is in a mechanical off state.

PWR218.Description: Cannot enable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) the feature because the Fresh Air (FA) mode is enabled.
PWR218.Message: Cannot enable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature because the Fresh Air (FA) mode is enabled.

RAC0700.Description: An email page was successfully sent.

UEFI0225.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0225.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0225.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the DDR4 LR-DIMM Receive Buffer Training phase.

BAT0007.Description: The PERC RAID controller battery may have failed because of thermal exceptions.
BAT0007.Resolution: 1) Verify the PERC RAID controller battery installation. 2) Check the system logs for thermal related issues.

SEL1300.Description: System setup displays the system boot order. The local video screen may also show additional information. (IPMI sensor type code 1eh - offset 00h).
SEL1300.Resolution: Check system boot settings. Check mass storage controller configuration settings is applicable.

RAC1057.Description: Rollback operation did not complete successfully. The component identifier (FQDD) specified in the operation is not valid or does not have a Rollback firmware image available.
RAC1057.Resolution: Run the RACADM command "racadm swinventory" to see the list of Rollback firmware images available and the corresponding component identifier (FQDD).
RAC1057.Message: Rollback operation did not complete successfully. The component identifier specified is not valid or does not have a rollback firmware image available.

VF008.Description: Creating a partition with an image did not complete successfully.
VF008.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Rerun the command after about 2 minutes, 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
VF008.Message: Image partition creation did not complete successfully.

RAC0153.Description: Power redundancy is typically used to protect equipment from unexpected power disruption that could cause data loss or hardware damage.
RAC0153.Resolution: It is recommended to use power redundancy.
RAC0153.Message: Non-redundant power mode: Check the system hardware manual for implications.

RAC958.Description: The import or export operation cannot be started because a job is already running.
RAC958.Resolution: Wait for the currently running job to complete and then retry the operation. The currently running job can be an update, backup, export or other job type. To view the status of currently running job using the RACADM command line interface, run the racadm jobqueue view command.
RAC958.Message: Unable to start the import or export operation because a job is already running.

PWR2253.Description: The server did not turn on because a PCIe card or Mezzanine card is not installed.
PWR2253.Resolution: Install a PCI or Mezzanine card in the appropriate slot and retry the operation.
PWR2253.Message: Unable to turn on the server because a PCIe card or Mezzanine card is not installed.

SYS435.Description: The BIOS configuration data cannot be retrieved either because the system inventory is not collected, Lifecycle Controller Wipe operation is performed, or because of a system error.
SYS435.Resolution: Enable the Lifecycle Controller CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) feature, collect the system inventory, and then retry the operation. To enable CSIOR and Lifecycle Controller respectively perform the PATCH operation for these attributes on the Redfish OemAttributes URL.
SYS435.Message: Unable to retrieve the BIOS configuration data either because the system inventory is not collected, Lifecycle Controller Wipe operation is performed, or because of a system error.

RAC054.Description: The user account attributes cannot be reset to default values due to an internal error.
RAC054.Resolution: Make sure the configuration XML file contains valid values for user account attributes and retry the operation.
RAC054.Message: User account attributes cannot be reset to default values due to an internal error.

UEFI0058.Description: Uncorrectable Memory Error has occurred because a Dual Inline Memory Module (DIMM) is not functioning.
UEFI0058.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the non-functioning DIMM, and then replace it.
UEFI0058.Message: An uncorrectable Memory Error has occurred because a Dual Inline Memory Module (DIMM) is not functioning.

PWR8510.Message: Unable to set chassis power property %1.
PWR8510.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR8510.Description: Unable to set the chassis power identified in the message.

BAR080.Description: Importing the Lifecycle Controller configuration database from the system profile backup file.

SEC0042.Description: TXT CPU microcode boot cannot be completed because system configuration may have changed.
SEC0042.Resolution: Check system hardware inventory for TPM presence, clear and reconfigure TPM and TXT in BIOS setup menu.
SEC0042.Message: Processor detected a problem while performing an Intel Trusted Execution Technology (TXT) operation.

IOV104.Message: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to allocate %1 Watt for server-%2 PCIe adapters.
IOV104.Resolution: Using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) RACADM command line interface, run the command "racadm config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisPowerCap <Power cap>" to increase the power cap or add an additional power supply.
IOV104.Description: For each adapter assigned to a server, power is allocated when the server is turned on. If the available power is less than the required power, the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) will not power on the adapters associated with the server.

SEL0010.Description: When the event log is full, additional events are not written to the log or older events will be overwritten and lost. (IPMI sensor type code 10h - offset 05h).
SEL0010.Resolution: Backup and clear log at the next maintained time.
SEL0010.Message: System event log (SEL) is almost full.

VRM0014.Description: Racadm tool was unable to get the status of the USB interface.
VRM0014.Message: Unable to determine current state of Virtual Media USB interface.

UEFI0237.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0237.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0237.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Write DQ/DQS Training - Memory Test phase.

SWC8543.Message: Unable to perform the Boot Identity profile operation because the server in slot %1 does not have a Service Tag.
SWC8543.Resolution: Set the Service Tag value using the F2 System Setup boot utility. Follow the Server BIOS menu instructions for setting an absent Service Tag or contact your service provider.
SWC8543.Description: The Boot Identity operation cannot be performed because server in the slot identified in the message does not have a Service Tag.

VDR56.Resolution: Replace the missing or failed physical disk.
VDR56.Description: This message occurs when a physical disk in the disk group was removed or when a physical disk included in a redundant virtual disk fails. Because the virtual disk is redundant (uses mirrored or parity information) and only one physical disk has failed, the virtual disk can be rebuilt. Typically, the virtual disk (E.g. RAID 6) has multiple redundant disks and there is a problem with one of them.

MEM1214.Description: The memory may not be seated correctly, misconfigured, or has failed.
MEM1214.Resolution: Review system logs for memory exceptions. Re-install memory at location <location>.

UEFI0045.Description: Unable to enable the TXT feature because a TPM chip is not present.
UEFI0045.Resolution: Install a TPM chip module by following the installation procedure. Refer to the platform Owner's Manual for more information or contact your service provider.
UEFI0045.Message: Unable to enable the TXT feature because a TPM chip is not present.

SYS081.Description: Successfully previewed Server Configuration Profile import operation.
SYS081.Message: Successfully previewed Server Configuration Profile import operation.

PWR2005.Message: The OS run-time software initiated a hard reset.

SWC0045.Description: The Import operation did not successfully complete. For more information, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0045.Resolution: Exit the Import Server Profile wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, do the following: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait for five seconds. 3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0045.Message: Unable to complete the Import operation.

SEL0008.Description: When the event log is full, additional events are not written to the log; or older events will be overwritten and lost. This message may also appear if the user disabled event logging. (IPMI sensor type code 10h - offset 04h).

SUP0121.Message: Firmware update in progress [%1 percent complete]

JCP037.Message: The (installation or configuration) job %1 is successfully completed.
JCP037.Description: The (installation or configuration) job identified in the message is successfully completed on iDRAC.

SYS012.Description: The user credentials provided do not have appropriate privileges to perform the operation requested.
SYS012.Resolution: Retry operation using user credentials that have appropriate privileges to perform the operation.
SYS012.Message: User privileges are not sufficient to perform operation.

RAC0763.Description: Unable to configure the port number that is entered because the port number is already in use.
RAC0763.Resolution: Enter a port number that is not already in use and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC0763.Message: Unable to configure the port number that is entered because the port number is already in use.

LC071.Description: Unable to export or import server configuration XML because the Lifecycle Controller version on the target does not support this feature.
LC071.Resolution: Update the Lifecycle Controller version on the target system to a version that supports the export and import server configuration XML feature, and retry the operation.
LC071.Message: The Lifecycle Controller version does not support the export or import of the Server Configuration XML file.

NIC012.Description: No changes to BIOS attribute data are available between the previous configuration and the current configuration.

CTL59.Resolution: There may be a problem with the enclosure. Verify the health of the enclosure and its components. To verify the health of the enclosure, select the enclosure object in the tree view. The Health sub-tab displays a red X or yellow exclamation mark for enclosure components that are failed or degraded. See the enclosure documentation for more information.
CTL59.Description: There may be a problem with the enclosure. Verify the health of the enclosure and its components. To verify the health of the enclosure, select the enclosure object in the tree view. The Health sub-tab displays a red X or yellow exclamation point for enclosure components that are failed or degraded. See the enclosure documentation for more information.

RAC0608.Description: The message appears in Job Queue page when the iDRAC firmware update job status is downloading. Communication to the iDRAC will be lost when the iDRAC restarts to complete the firmware update.
RAC0608.Resolution: Reconnect iDRAC communications session after iDRAC is restarted. The iDRAC will be ready for login once the restart is complete.
RAC0608.Message: The iDRAC will restart when the iDRAC firmware update is complete. All current user sessions will be closed.

UEFI0290.Description: The Sub-NUMA Cluster (SNC) mode cannot be enabled because of mismatches in the memory configuration.
UEFI0290.Resolution: Check the Dual Inline Memory Module (DIMM) population to make sure that the Sub-NUMA Cluster (SNC) mode can be enabled. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0290.Message: Unable to configure the Sub-NUMA Cluster (SNC) mode because of mismatches in the memory configuration.

RDU8515.Message: CMC%1: failover was initiated by internal health monitoring process.
RDU8515.Description: A CMC failover was initiated by the CMC health monitoring process. There should be a reason listed in the chassis log.

LIC012.Description: This error may occur if: 1) The license was deleted by another user. 2) The license that is being imported may have been deleted from the temporary storage before the import operation completed.3) At start-up, License Manager does not find the license assigned to the device. This may occur if a power outage occurs before a license delete operation completes.
LIC012.Message: The license file does not exist.

OSD30.Description: The value specified for ExposeDuration is out of range. It must be between 60 and 65535 seconds.
OSD30.Resolution: Rerun the command with a ExposeDuration value between 60 and 65535 seconds.
OSD30.Message: Invalid value for ExposeDuration - must be 60 - 65535 seconds

LOG510.Description: The operation cannot be completed because of an unknown issue.
LOG510.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset CMC and then retry the operation.
LOG510.Message: Unable to complete the operation because of an unknown issue in the CMC.

DIS005.Message: Auto Discovery communicated successfully with Provisioning Server %1.
DIS005.Description: Message was sent successfully from Auto Discovery to Provisioning Server to request certificate.

JCP029.Message: A Job of JobType %1 already exists.
JCP029.Resolution: Wait until the existing job is complete or delete the existing job and then retry the operation.
JCP029.Description: Only one Job of the JobType requested can be created or scheduled at any time. A job of the same type already exists in the job queue.

RAC0303.Description: This error message is displayed when Virtual Console feature is unavailable.
RAC0303.Resolution: Enable Virtual Console and ask the administrator to grant Access Virtual Console privilege.
RAC0303.Message: Virtual Console is disabled or you do not have the Access Virtual Console privilege.

UEFI0001.Description: A CPU software breakpoint exception (type 0x03) occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment. The software used it for debugging purposes.
UEFI0001.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.

IOV117.Description: The PCIE Slot or PERC Virtual Adapter(VA) identified in the message has been unassigned/unmapped from the server identified in the message.

PWR8593.Description: The chassis power operation cannot be performed when a chassis infrastructure firmware update is in progress.
PWR8593.Resolution: Retry the operation after the chassis infrastructure component firmware update is complete.
PWR8593.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on or turn off the chassis because the chassis infrastructure component firmware update is in progress.

SYS242.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported proxy hostname value, %2.
SYS242.Resolution: Make sure that the correct proxy hostname value is entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS242.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an unsupported proxy hostname value.

RAC0767.Message: Unable to assign USB NIC IP address %1 to the OSBMC device because IP address setting conflicts with existing network interface IP.
RAC0767.Resolution: Enter an unique IP address for OSBMC USB NIC that is not the same as another NICs IP address, and then retry the operation. For information about supported IP addresses, refer to the iDRAC Users Guide available at the support site.
RAC0767.Description: The USB NIC IP address identified in the message cannot be assigned to the OSBMC device because IP address setting conflicts with existing network interface IP.

SWC8521.Message: Unable to modify timeout for session: %1: %2-%3
SWC8521.Resolution: Make sure: 1) The login credentials for the operation have chassis config administration privilege, 2) The session timeout given is valid. If the issue persists, restart the CMC and retry the operation.
SWC8521.Description: Unable to modify the timeout for the session.

BAR104.Description: Unable to collect system branding data to copy to backup Server Profile.
BAR104.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
BAR104.Message: Unable to collect system branding data.

VDR115.Description: Background initialization of a virtual disk resumed.

RAC1121.Description: The command could not be successfully run, because one or more values about the proxy server was not entered.
RAC1121.Resolution: Make sure that you enter the following data, and then retry the operation:- proxy server address- proxy user name- proxy password.
RAC1121.Message: Unable to run the command, because the data entered for connecting to the Proxy server is insufficient.

AMP0313.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0313.Message: System level current is less than the lower critical threshold.

SUP0107.Description: The file path provided as a parameter is too long.
SUP0107.Resolution: Shorten the length of the string given as file path by either moving the file or renaming the folders along the path.

PDR59.Message: A bad disk block was reassigned on %1.
PDR59.Resolution: Monitor the disk for other messages or indications of poor health.
PDR59.Description: The disk has a bad block. Data was remapped to another disk block. No data loss has occurred.

SWU8506.Message: Completed the Firmware update operation for CMC%1.
SWU8506.Description: Completed the Firmware update operation for the CMC identified in the message.

VLT0218.Message: The %1 voltage is less than the lower warning threshold.
VLT0218.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0218.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

VFL0710.Message: vFlash is not enabled; the SD card could not be initialized.

SUP0106.Description: There is no firmware image present at the specified path.
SUP0106.Resolution: Check if the firmware image is present at the specified path.
SUP0106.Message: Unable to locate firmware image file in specified path.
