VDR53.Message: The consistency check logging of inconsistent parity data is disabled for %1.
VDR53.Resolution: See the storage hardware documentation for more information on consistency check operation. Contact technical support.
VDR53.Description: The consistency check can no longer report errors in the parity data.

MEM9012.Description: BIOS logged the major and minor code of a Memory Reference Code (MRC) warning. This information can be reviewed by using a tool which displays raw IPMI SEL data such as IPMI tool with the -vvv option or RACADM with the -E option.
MEM9012.Message: A Memory Reference Code (MRC) warning code is logged.

RAC0103.Description: Smart Card login is only supported in newer versions of Internet Explorer.
RAC0103.Resolution: See the iDRAC help text or documentation for a list of supported browsers.
RAC0103.Message: This browser does not support Smart Card logon on iDRAC. Use Internet Explorer version 7.0 or later to use this feature.

HWC2004.Message: The system board %1 cable or interconnect is connected.

IOV113.Description: Chassis Infrastructure firmware re-installation is successful.
IOV113.Message: Chassis Infrastructure firmware re-installation is successful.

MEM9010.Description: BIOS logged the major and minor code of a QuickPath Interconnect (QPI) Reference Code warning. This information can be reviewed by using a tool which displays raw IPMI SEL log data such as IPMItool with the -vvv option or RACADM with the -E option.
MEM9010.Message: A QuickPath Interconnect (QPI) Reference Code warning message code is logged.

CTL33.Message: The %1 debug log file has been exported.
CTL33.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SYS429.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the property %1 is not in the list of valid properties for the resource.
SYS429.Resolution: Remove the unknown property from the request body and retry the operation.
SYS429.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the property is not in the list of valid properties for the resource.

SWC0133.Resolution: Specify either the connect or the disconnect option with the subcommand.

PWR8597.Message: The Power Supply Unit (PSU) %1 is turned off because it is not supported by the Chassis.
PWR8597.Resolution: Replace the PSU identified in the message with an appropriate unit, and then retry the operation. For a list of PSUs that are compatible, consult the system Owner's Manual or contact your service provider.
PWR8597.Description: The identified Power Supply Unit (PSU) is turned off because it is not supported by the Chassis.

RAC0664.Message: Exporting the RAID Controller Log will take less than %1 minutes. Job ID: #{jobID} is created for the RAID Controller Log Export operation.
RAC0664.Resolution: To check the progress of the job click the Job Queue button.
RAC0664.Description: Exporting the RAID Controller Log will take less than the number of minutes identified in the message. The job identified in the message is created for the RAID Controller Log Export operation.

LOG001.Description: One or more required parameters needed for the method invoked in the operation are missing.
LOG001.Resolution: To provide the correct value for the specified parameter, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
LOG001.Message: Missing required InstanceID or JobID parameter.

SWC8610.Message: Job ID: %1. CMC sent all settings of profile %2 to Server (Service Tag: %3) in Slot %4.
SWC8610.Description: All settings of the selected profile were sent to the server identified in the message and the operation is captured in the job identified in the message.

RAC959.Description: The content of the configuration XML file used for import is invalid because of incorrect modifications or content.
RAC959.Resolution: Correct the modifications to the configuration XML file to be imported or specify the correct file, and retry the operation. Check the Lifecycle Log for more details.
RAC959.Message: Invalid file used for configuration XML file import operation.

SWU8546.Description: The firmware update operation of the Standby CMC was not successful.
SWU8546.Message: Unable to update the Standby CMC firmware.

SWC0272.Description: The syntax for the config command is invalid.
SWC0272.Resolution: Refer to the help text for the 'config' subcommand.
SWC0272.Message: Invalid syntax. The -g option is only valid with -o, -i, and -c.

OSD38.Description: There was an error while copying the ISO from the network share.
OSD38.Resolution: 1) Make sure the network connection is functional. 2) Make sure the Dell vFlash does not have hardware issues by accessing it through the iDRAC GUI.
OSD38.Message: Copying the ISO image from the network failed.

USR0023.Description: The user privilege is invalid. This may be due to invalid combinations of privileges given to the user.
USR0023.Resolution: Request the administrator to assign appropriate user privileges to the specific user.
USR0023.Message: The current user privilege is not valid.

UEFI0011.Description: A CPU general protection (type 0x0D) exception occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0011.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.

RAC028.Description: The attributes "DNS Domain Name From DHCP" and "DNS From DHCP" are dependent on the attribute DHCP being Enabled. Currently DHCP is configured as Disabled.
RAC028.Resolution: Set DHCP attribute to Enable to be able to Enable DNS Domain Name From DHCP or DNS From DHCP.
RAC028.Message: Unable to Enable "DNS Domain Name From DHCP" or "DNS From DHCP" because DHCP is Disabled.

RAC1113.Description: The configuration XML preview operation cannot be executed because the -b, -s, and -w options must not be used with the --preview option.
RAC1113.Resolution: Remove the -b, -w, and -s options when using the --preview option and retry the operation.
RAC1113.Message: Unable to perform the preview operation because the options -b, -c, -w, and -s must not be used with the --preview option.

UEFI0062.Description: One or more attributes were successfully changed.
UEFI0062.Message: One or more attributes are successfully changed.

SEC0004.Description: The LAN is disconnected. Network performance may be degraded.

SEL1211.Description: The time stamp on system event log events may not correlate to the system time. (IPMI sensor type code 12h - offset 05h).
SEL1211.Resolution: Cycle system input power, if problem persists call support.
SEL1211.Message: The time-stamp clock could not be synchronized.

SWU8517.Message: Unable to update the iDRAC firmware on the server in slot %1. The Image file is not accessible. ErrorCode=0x%2.
SWU8517.Resolution: Make sure the iDRAC firmware Image file is available in the given path and retry the operation.
SWU8517.Description: Unable to update the iDRAC firmware. The firmware Image file is not accessible.

RAC062.Description: The attribute can not be set if the IPMI Watchdog state is disabled.
RAC062.Resolution: Enable the IPMI Watchdog state and retry the operation.
RAC062.Message: Unable to set the attribute because the IPMI Watchdog state is disabled.

UEFI0271.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the network connection to DHCPv6 server is not established.
UEFI0271.Resolution: Check the network cable connection of the initiator or the DHCPv6 server and retry the operation.
UEFI0271.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the network connection to DHCPv6 server is not established.

SEC0613.Description: The default username and password is changed.
SEC0613.Message: The default username and password is changed.

UEFI0096.Description: The Advanced ECC memory operating mode cannot be enabled because the current DIMM population or system configuration does not support Advanced ECC mode.
UEFI0096.Resolution: Check DIMM population and system configuration to make sure Advanced ECC memory operating mode can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0096.Message: Unable to enable the Advanced ECC memory operating mode because the current DIMM population or system configuration does not support Advanced ECC mode.

BAR023.Description: The process is entering the component update phase of the restore operation.

OSD51.Description: There are pending System Services tasks on the host system that are preventing the execution of this method.
OSD51.Resolution: Reboot the host system. The system will automatically enter System Services and complete the pending tasks.
OSD51.Message: Reboot the system to run pending System Services Tasks.

RAC1030.Description: The custom signing certificate present on iDRAC was deleted.
RAC1030.Message: The custom signing certificate was deleted.

RAC0685.Message: A pending operation has been created for this %1 operation.
RAC0685.Resolution: To view the pending operations click the Pending Operations button.
RAC0685.Description: A pending operation has been created for this operation identified in the message.

RED039.Message: Settings for a recurring operation of type %1 were cleared.
RED039.Description: Settings for an Automatic Server Profile Backup, Automatic Update, or other recurring operations identified in the message were cleared. The recurring operation identified in the message is deleted.

STOR034.Description: The requested operation cannot be completed because an invalid value is specified for RebootJobType.
STOR034.Resolution: Enter a valid RebootJobType value and retry the operation. For more information about the RebootJobType parameter, see the RAID Profile specification.

AMP0301.Message: The system board %1 current is less than the lower critical threshold.
AMP0301.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.

SWC0236.Description: The specified public key was deleted from iDRAC.

RAC0709.Resolution: Acquire the latest Chassis Management Controller (CMC) firmware that supports the server indicated and update the CMC to at least that version.

UEFI0097.Description: The Advanced ECC memory operating mode cannot be enabled because of mismatches in the DIMM channel configurations.
UEFI0097.Resolution: Make sure identical memory modules in corresponding slots of channel pairs are populated. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0097.Message: Unable to enable the Advanced ECC memory operating mode because of mismatches in the DIMM channel configurations.

BAT1032.Message: The battery temperature on %1 is normal.
BAT1032.Description: The battery temperature is within the normal operating range.

RAC1055.Description: The Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings must already exist in order to be cleared.
RAC1055.Message: Unable to clear the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings because there is currently no configuration.

IOV009.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) runs this function only when the chassis is turned off.
IOV009.Resolution: Turn off the chassis and retry the operation.
IOV009.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to reset to factory default or pre-factory default settings.

UEFI0202.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.
UEFI0202.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0202.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Health Check phase.

CMC8531.Message: Unable to perform the requested action on the Sleeve or Sled %1 because of insufficient user privileges.
CMC8531.Resolution: Use a different user account that has server administration privileges, and retry the operation. For more information, contact your system administrator about necessary privileges.
CMC8531.Description: The user account does not have sufficient privileges to perform the virtual reseat operation on the Sleeve or Sled specified in the message. The server administration privilege is required to perform a virtual reseat operation. This applies to Sleeve or Sled components.

RAC945.Description: The dedicated NIC or shared NIC scan time value is not between 5 and 255 seconds.
RAC945.Resolution: Make sure to set the scan time value between 5 and 255 seconds, and retry the operation. For more information, see RACADM help.

CTL22.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

VDR6.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC929.Description: The category or subcategory specified is incorrect. The recurrence interval is applicable only to the TMPS subcategory and system category.
RAC929.Resolution: See the command help text, for a list of valid categories.

STOR004.Description: Provided parameter value is not valid.
STOR004.Resolution: Refer to the RAID profile to determine the valid parameters values.

PDR1024.Message: Drive mismatch detected for drive %1 in disk drive bay %2.
PDR1024.Resolution: Verify the disk meets the array requirements.
PDR1024.Description: The installed disk does not meet the array requirements, for example a SATA disk may not operate in an array containing SAS drives.

SYS195.Description: The OEM ID Module installation process completed with no errors.
SYS195.Message: The OEM ID module is successfully installed.

SWC0228.Description: Invalid values passed to the function.
SWC0228.Message: Partition label must be an alphanumeric character string.

SWU8542.Description: The firmware update operation for the CMC was not successful. The Image file could not be transferred.
SWU8542.Resolution: Make sure that the CMC firmware Image file is available at the location specified in the operation, and then retry the operation.
SWU8542.Message: Unable to update the Active CMC firmware. The Image file transfer process was not successful.

RAC1006.Message: Unable to process the %1, and the update was not applied.
RAC1006.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Download the correct Update Package from your service provider. 2) Use the Lifecycle Controller repair package to repair Lifecycle Controller. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller User's Guide. 3) Wait until the current update operation is complete.
RAC1006.Description: The update was not applied because of one of the following reasons: 1) The Update Package is invalid. 2) Lifecycle Controller is corrupted. 3) Another update is in progress.

SWC0213.Message: Disable the Virtual Console from a local Console

PWR8656.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to turn on the component %1-%2 because of insufficient power.
PWR8656.Resolution: Make sure there is sufficient power available, and then retry the operation. To increase available power, add more PSUs, use PSUs with higher voltage inputs or a higher power rating, remove unused components from the Chassis, or change the redundancy policy to Redundancy Alerting Only or Non-redundant.
PWR8656.Description: CMC could not successfully turn on the component identified in the message, because of insufficient power available.

ISM0012.Description: The iDRAC Service Module is successfully ended on the server OS.
ISM0012.Message: The iDRAC Service Module is successfully ended on the server operating system (OS).

SWU8536.Message: Unable to update the LKVM firmware, because the Image file could not be accessed. ErrorCode=0x%1.
SWU8536.Resolution: Make sure that the iKVM firmware image file is available at the specified location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8536.Description: The LKVM firmware update operation was not successful, because the firmware Image file could not be transferred.

BAR027.Description: The component restoration on the host system is complete. The Host System will shutdown.
BAR027.Message: Host System Component Restore complete, shutting down Host System.

BAR015.Description: The Backup file information was not properly processed and the operation cannot continue. This can be due to resource constraints within the processing environment. If the network share is read only, this error will be thrown also.
BAR015.Resolution: If this is backup to network share, check to make sure network share is read/write accessible. Restart the Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC) and retry the operation.

SYS085.Message: Successfully exported the ePSA Diagnostics results.

PDR94.Message: Microcode update on %1 has timed out.
PDR94.Resolution: Retry the update. The update utility may have already performed the retry operation.
PDR94.Description: The attempt to update the physical disk has timed out. This may be due to too much activity on the bus, a bad update package, or a bad disk.

STOR020.Description: The controller key cannot be set because a key is already present.
STOR020.Resolution: Delete the current key and retry the operation.
STOR020.Message: A controller key is already present.

PSU0033.Message: The temperature for power supply %1 is outside of range.
PSU0033.Resolution: Check the system operating environment, including airflow and inlet temperature. Check system logs for temperature and thermal component failures.

CTL34.Message: A foreign configuration was cleared on %1.
CTL34.Description: This is the result of a user operation.

CMC8516.Message: The I/O Module %1 did not boot within the expected time.
CMC8516.Resolution: Verify the I/O Module is turned on using CMC Web Interface or RACADM CLI and retry the operation. Otherwise, reinsert the I/O Module and retry the operation. If the problem persists, contact technical support.
CMC8516.Description: The I/O module may have taken more time to boot than was expected or the I/O module did not boot.

SUP013.Description: The update process is underway and cannot be deleted.
SUP013.Resolution: Do not try to delete the job when the update process is underway. To revert to the previous version of the update, download and update the firmware to the version desired or run the rollback command to go back to the previous version.

RAC0715.Description: Image file does not exist in the given remote share path.
RAC0715.Resolution: Ensure that the image file is available on the share path provided. Retry the operation.
RAC0715.Message: Image file does not exist in the given remote share path.

SUP0531.Description: The repository location is invalid or the repository does not contain the Update Packages.
SUP0531.Resolution: Enter another repository location that contains the desired Update Packages and retry the operation.
SUP0531.Message: Unable to install the Update Packages.

CPU0806.Message: CPU %1 voltage regulator module is incorrectly configure.
CPU0806.Resolution: Review product documentation for proper configuration and installation procedures.
CPU0806.Description: System performance may be degraded or the system may fail to operate.

SWC8624.Message: The network communication session between CMC and I/O Aggregator cannot be started on %1.
SWC8624.Resolution: Power-cycle the IOA and retry the operation.
SWC8624.Description: The network communication session between CMC and I/O Aggregator (IOA) cannot be started because the IOA did not respond.

SWC0156.Message: CSR file downloaded from RAC successfully

PDR39.Message: A blink operation has initiated on %1.
PDR39.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PR35.Message: Power Supply slot %1 firmware update will be performed during next system reboot.
PR35.Description: The Part Replacement feature has detected a firmware difference for the power supply and will start the firmware update process upon system reboot.

RED088.Description: The Chassis firmware cannot be updated because an update operation is already in progress.
RED088.Resolution: Wait until the current update operation is completed, and then retry the operation.
RED088.Message: Unable to update the Chassis firmware because an update operation is already in progress.

VDR28.Description: A user has caused a mirrored virtual disk to be split. When a virtual disk is mirrored, its data is copied to another virtual disk to maintain redundancy. After being split, both virtual disks retain a copy of the data. Because the mirror is no longer intact, updates to the data are no longer copied to the mirror.
VDR28.Resolution: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
VDR28.Message: A virtual disk and its mirror have been split.

PWR8508.Message: New power budget (%1W AC) may permit future degradation of redundancy.
PWR8508.Resolution: No response action is required. Make sure there are enough PSUs to support redundancy at the specified power budget.
PWR8508.Description: If the power budget exceeds the effective capacity for the current redundancy policy, it is possible for power allocations to grow beyond the effective capacity, which would reduce redundancy capabilities.

MEM1206.Message: Memory mirror redundancy is degraded. Check memory device at location %1.
MEM1206.Resolution: Review system logs for memory exceptions. Re-install memory at location <location>.
MEM1206.Description: The memory may not be seated correctly, misconfigured, or has failed.

UEFI0174.Message: A Quad Rank DIMM module is installed on memory slot %1 after an Octal Rank DIMM module.
UEFI0174.Resolution: Quad Rank and Octal Rank DIMM modules cannot be mixed on a channel. Populate memory modules in a supported configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0174.Description: A memory population violation has been detected on the identified DIMM slot.

TMP6.Message: The temperature probe minimum warning value was changed on %1.
TMP6.Description: You have changed the value for the minimum temperature probe warning threshold. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PR21.Description: The specified job did not complete successfully.
PR21.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle Log for more details associated with this failure then retry the operation.

SWC8524.Message: Unable to add %1 to Chassis Group because a member already exists with the same addressing information.
SWC8524.Description: A Chassis Group member already exists with the same hostname or IP address information as the target identified in the message.

PCI3001.Message: Device option ROM on embedded NIC was successfully updated.

SEL0002.Description: This message appears when event logging of a specific type is disabled by the user. (IPMI sensor type code 10h - offset 01h).

LOG203.Message: Lifecycle Log archived up to Log Sequence number %1.
LOG203.Description: This message is generated while archiving Lifecycle Log. All the older messages are archived and can be retrieved using the export Lifecycle Log feature.

SEL1507.Message: Communications restored with Chassis Group Member %1.

VF005.Description: A partition with no image was created.

UEFI0200.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.
UEFI0200.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0200.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Write Level Coarse Training phase.

UEFI0250.Description: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization encountered a programmatic error. The Legacy VGA range processor target is not populated. Decode was forced to the Legacy CPU socket.
UEFI0250.Resolution: Reseat all processors in the system and ensure all processors are matching. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0250.Message: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization error detected.

UEFI0078.Description: One or more Machine Check errors occurred in the previous boot.
UEFI0078.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the source of the Machine Check error and resolve the issues.
UEFI0078.Message: One or more Machine Check errors occurred in the previous boot.

CTL47.Resolution: Replace the DIMM immediately. The DIMM is a part of the controller battery pack. Refer to your hardware documentation for information on replacing the DIMM.
CTL47.Description: The Dual In-line Memory Module (DIMM) is malfunctioning. Data loss or data corruption may occur. The DIMM must be replaced immediately.

UEFI0217.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0217.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0217.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Basic Write DQ/DQS Training phase.

SYS004.Resolution: Refer to the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services documentation and retry the operation with a valid value for the identified parameter.
SYS004.Description: The value provided for the specified parameter is invalid.

UEFI0016.Description: Unable to find a Lifecycle Controller partition. No Lifecycle Controller functionality is available while in Recovery Mode.
UEFI0016.Resolution: Perform the following actions: 1)Reboot the system. 2) Press F2 during boot to enter System Setup. 3) Select iDRAC Settings then Lifecycle Controller. 4) Change Lifecycle Controller back to Enabled. If subsequent failures occur, press and hold the system ID button down for 15 seconds to reset the iDRAC. For more information on how to reset iDRAC, see iDRAC User's Guide.
UEFI0016.Message: Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible and is therefore in Recovery mode.

OSE1001.Resolution: Review system boot configuration and boot media. Verify the media in a: is bootable. See system video for additional information.

LC0101.Description: A user cancelled Lifecycle Controller actions. Any remote jobs pending execution were cancelled.
LC0101.Message: Lifecycle Controller action was cancelled by a user.

UEFI0289.Description: DDR memory initialization cannot be completed because no Dual Inline Memory Module's (DIMM's) are installed. Only processor embedded memory is available.
UEFI0289.Resolution: Populate Dual Inline Memory Module's (DIMM's) in a supported memory configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual available on the support site.
UEFI0289.Message: Unable to initialize DDR memory because no Dual Inline Memory Module's (DIMM's) are installed.

RAC1041.Description: Successfully configured the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings.
RAC1041.Message: Successfully configured the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings.

HWC5010.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.

AMP0302.Message: The system board %1 current is greater than the upper warning threshold.
AMP0302.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0302.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.

CTL51.Resolution: Make sure the SAS cables attached to the enclosure/backplane are attached securely. Refer to the storage hardware documentation for more information on checking the cables. Contact technical support if the issue persists.
CTL51.Description: The text for this message is generated by the controller during runtime and can vary depending on the situation.

RED050.Description: The download of the update package was not successful because the user name or password provided to access the network share or the proxy server settings were not correct.
RED050.Resolution: Check the network connection and access to the update package from the iDRAC. Verify that the user access credentials and proxy server settings are correct.
RED050.Message: The specified user credentials necessary for downloading an update package were not correct.

CMC8529.Message: Unable to perform the requested action on the server-%1, because of insufficient privileges.
CMC8529.Resolution: Use a different user account that has Server Administrator privilege, and retry the operation. For more information, contact your system administrator or service provider.
CMC8529.Description: The user account does not have sufficient privileges to perform the requested operation. Server Administrator privilege is required to perform the requested action.

RAC0719.Description: Not able to connect to remote file share. Virtual media devices are already in use.
RAC0719.Resolution: Stop existing Virtual Media sessions and retry the operation.
RAC0719.Message: Not able to connect to remote file share. Virtual media devices are already in use.

ENC27.Message: SAS or SATA mixing of physical disks is not supported within the %1.
ENC27.Description: The enclosure cannot support both SAS and SATA physical disks. Physical disks may be disabled. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PDR67.Description: The physical disk does not comply with the standards set by service provider and is not supported.
PDR67.Resolution: Replace the physical disk with a supported physical disk.
PDR67.Message: An unsupported physical disk drive has been detected.

SUP0539.Description: Update Packages are missing from the specified repository.
SUP0539.Resolution: Enter another repository location that contains the desired Update Packages and retry the operation.
SUP0539.Message: Update Packages missing in the repository.

TMP0133.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.
TMP0133.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0133.Message: The control panel temperature is greater than the upper critical threshold.

SWC8513.Description: The user name identified in the message was successfully deleted.

HWC4003.Message: A hardware incompatibility was corrected between BMC/iDRAC firmware and other hardware.

PDR29.Resolution: See A Rebuild Completes with Errors for more information.
PDR29.Description: See A Rebuild Completes with Errors for more information.

FC017.Description: An internal error occurred in iDRAC and the operation cannot continue. An iDRAC reset is required to recover from the error.
FC017.Resolution: Disconnect the AC power source from the system, reconnect the power source, and retry the operation.
FC017.Message: Unable to perform the operation due to an internal error in iDRAC.

BAR049.Description: The automatic Host System power up request has erred and the system will not power up after the Integrated Remote Access Controller has restarted.
BAR049.Resolution: As indicated by the job status, wait for restore to complete. After the status displays Complete or Failed, wait for a few minutes for the Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC) to restart. After restart, power on the Host System using iDRAC.
BAR049.Message: Automatic Host System power up setup failed.

PSU0046.Message: Communication has been restored to power supply %1.

VFL0007.Description: The operations could not be completed because a vFlash SD Card is not detected.
VFL0007.Resolution: Confirm an SD Card is present in the vFlash SD Card reader slot. Otherwise, insert an SD Card and retry the operation.
VFL0007.Message: No vFlash SD card is present.

SUP023.Description: Duplicate/Invalid JobID was provided as input for scheduling.
SUP023.Resolution: Verify the job ID and retry the action. Retrieve all open jobs by issuing the GetAllJobs command.
SUP023.Message: Duplicate JobID provided as inputs for scheduling.

RED064.Description: A scheduled Update from Repository completed and no applicable updates were found.
RED064.Message: The scheduled Update from Repository job completed successfully. Applicable updates were not found.

RAC984.Description: iDRAC is unable to extract the custom signing certificate and the private key from the Public Key Cryptography Standards version 12 (PKCS12) file.
RAC984.Resolution: Check if the specified file and passphrase are valid, and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC984.Message: Unable to upload the Public Key Cryptography Standards version 12 (PKCS12) file.

TMP0110.Message: The memory module %1 temperature is outside of range.
TMP0110.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0110.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or cool.

CPU0816.Message: CPU %1 voltage regulator module is absent.
CPU0816.Resolution: If removal was unintended, check presence and re-install .
CPU0816.Description: System performance may be degraded or the system may fail to operate.

VFL0703.Message: The SD card initialization was successful.

TMP0129.Message: Disk drive bay temperature is within range.

RED041.Message: A recurring operation of type %1 was not created because the required license is not available.
RED041.Resolution: Install an iDRAC license that supports the following features: Automatic Update or Server Profile Export and Import. After the appropriate license has been installed, retry the operation.
RED041.Description: The license required to perform the operation identified in the message is expired or is not available.

UEFI0141.Description: The System Service Mode (SSM) cannot be entered because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible. This situation is caused by missing LC files.
UEFI0141.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0141.Message: Unable to enter System Service Mode (SSM) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible.

ENC26.Resolution: Verify the health of the enclosure and its components. See the hardware documentation to for more information. Contact technical support.
ENC26.Description: The enclosure or an enclosure component is in a Failed or Degraded state. It is not responding to storage management commands or there is a connectivity problem between the controller and enclosure.

SYS268.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because the proxy operation is taking longer time than the set time limit.
SYS268.Resolution: Check the file transfer parameters, health of the remote host, the proxy time limit configuration and then retry the operation.
SYS268.Description: The file cannot be transferred because the proxy operation is taking longer time than the set time limit of the proxy configuration. The other possible reasons are: 1) issue in the network 2) remote host server may not be turned on 1) remote host server is turned on but not functioning 4) an issue in protocol negotiation.

UEFI0073.Message: Unable to boot %1 because of the Secure Boot policy.
UEFI0073.Resolution: If the Secure Boot feature is not desired, disable it in System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings page. Otherwise, do the following: 1) review the Secure Boot Policy Summary in F2 System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings page. The boot option must be authorized by a public key or hash value in the Authorized Signature Database. 2) If the boot option is not authorized but it can be trusted, enter System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings page, set Secure Boot Policy to Custom, and add a entry for the boot option in the Authorized Signature Database (System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings > Custom Policy Settings > Authorized Signature Database > Import Database Entry).
UEFI0073.Description: When the Secure Boot feature is enabled, the system BIOS authenticates each boot option against the Secure Boot policy. If a boot option does not meet the policy criteria, the system BIOS does not boot to the boot option and displays this message. The Secure Boot policy consists of authorized and unauthorized X.509 certificates; signed boot images must chain to an authorized certificate. The policy may also authorize hash values of individual boot images. Users can configure the Secure Boot feature and the Secure Boot policy in System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings page.

IOV111.Description: Unable to successfully update Chassis Infrastructure firmware.
IOV111.Resolution: Refer to the release notes of the Mainboard update package for recommended action. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
IOV111.Message: Unable to update Chassis Infrastructure firmware.

OSD53.Resolution: Remove the write protect from the SD card and then proceed.

RAC1155.Description: The operation was not completed because Lifecycle Controller is disabled.
RAC1155.Resolution: Enable the Lifecycle Controller and retry the operation. To enable Lifecycle Controller, run the command 'racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState 1'.
RAC1155.Message: Unable to complete the operation because Lifecycle Controller is disabled.

SWC0103.Description: The specified log does not take in the -e option.
SWC0103.Message: The -E option is not valid for the specified log.

SWC0310.Description: The syntax of the getconfig command is invalid.
SWC0310.Resolution: Refer the help text for getconfig subcommand.
SWC0310.Message: Invalid syntax. The -f is not valid with the option specified.

ENC2.Resolution: Reinsert the Enclosure Management Module (EMM). See the storage hardware documentation for information on replacing the EMM.
ENC2.Description: An Enclosure Management Module (EMM) was removed.

IOID001.Description: After the I/O Identity optimization feature is enabled, the time during boot to configure I/O Identity attributes using the Server Configuration Profile (Configuration XML) import feature will be significantly reduced.
IOID001.Message: The Input/Output Identity (I/O Identity) optimization feature is enabled.

UEFI0027.Description: A license change for the system or a component in the system requires a system reset in order for the new license to take effect.
UEFI0027.Resolution: Wait for the BIOS to reset the system.
UEFI0027.Message: The system must be restarted for the new license to become effective.

IOID111.Message: Unable to configure the virtual address of %1 Port %2.
IOID111.Resolution: Verify that the network port is enabled and that the port has Virtual Addressing capability and then retry the operation.
IOID111.Description: The virtual address of the NIC port identified in the message could not be successfully configured because either the network port connection is not enabled or the NIC is not capable of Virtual Addressing.

CTL68.Message: Attempted to import Virtual Disk with missing Physical Disk on %1.
CTL68.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

LIC007.Description: Each License Manager object has a unique identifier by which it may be accessed. If the user supplied identifier is outside the acceptable range or the object no longer exists in the system, then this error is returned. Most common identifiers are the license entitlement identifier, the device Fully Qualified Device Descriptor, or the import transaction identifier assigned to a license when imported.
LIC007.Resolution: Re-issue this command with correct License Manager object identifier.
LIC007.Message: Invalid entry: Object does not exist or cannot be found.

SWC0216.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0216.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0216.Message: The -c option requires -l to also be specified.

SUP0104.Description: The source path needs to be lesser than 64 characters.

RAC0633.Description: The requested network file share cannot be accessed, because an invalid password is entered.
RAC0633.Resolution: Enter a valid network file share password, and then retry the operation.
RAC0633.Message: Unable to access the network file share, because an invalid network share password is entered.

PCI5002.Message: A PCIe card carrier that does not contain a PCIe card is inserted in the PCIe slot%1 .
PCI5002.Description: A PCIe card carrier that does not contain a PCIe card is inserted in the PCIe slot identified in the message.

STOR10.Description: The RAID controller was detected, however it is unable to turn on. Access to shared storage will not be available.
STOR10.Message: Access to shared storage will not be available, because the RAID controller is unable to turn on.

AMP0315.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0315.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0315.Message: System level current is greater than the upper critical threshold.

VFL0721.Description: The SD card Initialization did not complete within the maximum process allotted time.
VFL0721.Message: Error occurred while initializing the SD Card due to a timeout.

LC069.Description: The certificate does not exist for export or delete operation.

CTL97.Description: The controller identified in the message has been changed to a new personality mode (HBA or RAID).

PST0143.Description: TXT boot failed. This could be related to memory errors or an error with the system TXT configuration. A socketed TPM module may have been removed. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video.
PST0143.Resolution: Check TPM presence. Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PST0143.Message: Intel Trusted Execution Technology (TXT) fatal error.

RDU8524.Description: CMC failover action is not allowed in the current configuration.

PDR96.Description: Security on a secure encrypted disk was disabled.

SYS025.Description: There are no pending configurations to be deleted.

SWC0142.Message: Certificate successfully uploaded to the RAC.

RAC0288.Description: All characters entered must be alphanumeric or valid symbols.
RAC0288.Resolution: Enter all alphanumeric characters and valid symbols.
RAC0288.Message: Invalid entry: Entry must be exclusively alphanumeric characters and valid symbols.

PWR8663.Message: Unable to turn on the server %1 because of an inconsistency between the I/O module and mezzanine card.
PWR8663.Resolution: Make sure that the I/O module and mezzanine card are compatible. For information about compatibility of hardware components, see the Modular System Chassis Hardware Manual.
PWR8663.Description: The server identified in the message could not be successfully turned on because of incompatibility between the I/O module and mezzanine card.

ISM0010.Message: The iDRAC Service Module received a request from the %1 to stop the services of Service Module.
ISM0010.Resolution: If the requesting source is iDRAC, enable the iDRAC Service Module on the iDRAC before starting this service on the server OS. To enable the Service Module by using iDRAC GUI: Click Network, click OS to iDRAC Pass-through, and then click the USB NIC option. In the OS IP Address box , type an IP address, and then click Apply. To enable the module by using RACADM command, run the following command at the command line interface: racadm set idrac.servicemodule.ServiceModuleEnable enabled.
ISM0010.Description: The iDRAC Service Module received a request from a source identified in the message to stop the Service Module services. For example, a requesting source can be an OS or iDRAC.

SWC0276.Description: The syntax for the config command is invalid.
SWC0276.Resolution: Refer to the help text for the 'config' subcommand.
SWC0276.Message: Invalid syntax. The -p option is only valid with -f.

IOV2008.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) could not successfully connect to the PCIe subsystem.
IOV2008.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Perform an AC Power Cycle operation on the Chassis by disconnecting the chassis from AC power, wait for 30 seconds, and then reconnect AC power. 2) Turn on at least one server. Using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) web interface, select Server Overview->Power->Control and select the Power On Server option. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
IOV2008.Message: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to communicate with the PCIe subsystem.

SWC1930.Description: The iDRAC Quick Sync feature is set to automatically disable after a specified inactivity time.
SWC1930.Message: The iDRAC Quick Sync inactivity timeout feature is enabled.

CTL20.Message: Copyback and Load Balance has changed for %1.
CTL20.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RDU0012.Description: The current power operational mode is non-redundant because of a power supply exception, a power supply inventory change, or a system power inventory change. The system was previously operating in a power redundant mode.
RDU0012.Resolution: Check the event log for power supply failures. Review system configuration and power consumption.

ENC5.Resolution: Identify and replace the failed component. To identify the failed component, select the enclosure in the tree view and click the Health subtab. Any failed component will be identified with a red X on the enclosure's Health subtab. Alternatively, you can select the Storage object and click the Health subtab. The controller status displayed on the Health subtab indicates whether a controller has a failed or degraded component. See the enclosure documentation for information on replacing enclosure components and for other diagnostic information.
ENC5.Description: One or more of the enclosure components has failed. For example, a fan or power supply may have failed. Although the enclosure is currently operational, the failure of additional components could cause the enclosure to fail.

UEFI0317.Description: Secure Boot keys were configured successfully according to the iDRAC request.
UEFI0317.Message: The iDRAC request to configure Secure Boot keys completed successfully. The system is being restarted.

CMC8603.Message: Unable to read the FRU information from the server %1, status %2.
CMC8603.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the server. The Chassis Management Controller will retry the read operation of the FRU information. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8603.Description: CMC cannot read the information about the FRU, because of an internal issue with the CMC and the server. Some information such as model number may not be reported. The server may not power up if the server planar FRU cannot be read.

PWR8570.Message: Unable to communicate to the iDRAC, when trying to power cycle the server %1.
PWR8570.Resolution: Wait for few minutes, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, do one of the following: 1) Reset the iDRAC, 2) Perform a Virtual Reseat of the server, 3) Remove and re-insert the server.
PWR8570.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is not able to communicate with the iDRAC on the server identified in the message. Therefore, the server could not be power cycled. This situation may occur when iDRAC is rebooting.

FAN8503.Description: The Chassis was turned off because more than two Chassis internal fans stopped functioning. The fans with issues are identified in the CMC Hardware (System Event Log) and Chassis Logs.
FAN8503.Resolution: Make sure that the Chassis internal fans are functioning. At the command line interface (CLI), enter the following command to identify fans that are not functioning: "racadm getsel". Using the CMC Web GUI, select the chassis, click the Logs tab, and then select Hardware Log. Reinsert or replace fans that are not functioning correctly.
FAN8503.Message: The Chassis was turned off because more than two internal fans stopped functioning.

VF003.Resolution: Refer the iDRAC and Lifecycle Controller User Guides for the required input parameters for this method.
VF003.Description: The required input parameter identified in the message is missing.

UEFI0195.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.
UEFI0195.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0195.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Read Training phase.

CMC8702.Message: The Member Chassis exited from the chassis group %1 because of manual changes made on the member chassis.
CMC8702.Description: The Member Chassis exited from the Chassis group <GroupName> because of manual changes made on the member chassis.

SWC0161.Message: PK SSH Authentication operation completed successfully.

SWC0259.Description: The value of specified parameter is invalid.
SWC0259.Resolution: Refer the list of groups and enter a valid option.

STOR305.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the preserved cache is present on the controller.
STOR305.Resolution: To recover the data preserved in pinned cache do one of the following 1) Try importing foreign drives, if any. 2) Make sure that the enclosure containing the virtual drive is connected to the controller. 3) Install any drives that are reported as missed or failed. Pinned cache can be discarded if data saved in controller pinned cache is not required. For more information about managing preserve cache, refer to the PERC User's Guide available on the support site.
STOR305.Message: Unable to complete the operation because preserved cache is present on the controller.

RAC1051.Message: Unable to configure the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings. The option %1 is either invalid or not provided.
RAC1051.Resolution: Retry with a correct value for the option identified in the message. For more information, view the help details by running the RACADM command "racadm help systemconfig backup".
RAC1051.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an invalid value for the option identified in the message.

BAR082.Description: Remote access controller firmware and configuration import in progress.

RAC0764.Description: Selecting a higher SSL encryption enhances the security. However, the cryptography settings for your virtual machine environment (JVM, IcedTea) may require installing the Unlimited Strength Java Cryptography Extension Policy Files to permit usage of iDRAC plugins such as vConsole with this higher level of encryption.NOTE: Using this level of encryption may have import or export implications. For more guidance, contact your legal department.
RAC0764.Message: Selecting a higher SSL encryption enhances the security. However, the cryptography settings for your virtual machine environment (JVM, IcedTea) may require installing the Unlimited Strength Java Cryptography Extension Policy Files to permit usage of iDRAC plugins such as vConsole with this higher level of encryption. NOTE: Using this level of encryption may have import or export implications. For more guidance, contact your legal department.

UEFI0041.Description: Unable to turn on the TXT feature because the Virtualization Technology (VT) feature is not enabled on the processor.
UEFI0041.Resolution: From System Setup, enable VT, and then enable TXT. If the issue persists, update the system BIOS firmware.
UEFI0041.Message: Unable to enable the TXT feature because the Virtualization Technology (VT) feature is not enabled on the processor.

RAC1134.Description: Unable to export the Lifecycle log data, because the export file size larger than 25MB and cannot be processed locally.
RAC1134.Resolution: Export the Lifecycle Log to a network file share. Using the RACADM command line utility, run the lclog export command with --complete option and related network file share parameters, and then retry the operation. For more information about the --complete option, run the "racadm help lclog export" command at the command line interface.
RAC1134.Message: Unable to export the Lifecycle log data, because the export file size larger than 25MB and cannot be processed locally.

RAC0275.Description: If the Enable NIC checkbox is cleared, remote access to iDRAC is disabled.
RAC0275.Resolution: Disable NIC only if remote access is undesired.
RAC0275.Message: Click OK to disable the NIC. Click Cancel to keep the setting unchanged.

RAC0629.Description: The job cannot be scheduled, because the requested job type is not supported.
RAC0629.Resolution: Enter a correct job type, and then retry the operation.
RAC0629.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid job type is entered.

NIC502.Description: The value of the specified parameter cannot be changed.
NIC502.Resolution: Enable DHCP on the NIC before enabling it for DNS.
NIC502.Message: DHCP is required to be enabled on the NIC before DHCP can be enabled for DNS server or domain name objects.

BAR057.Message: Some of the configuration values not applied to Device: %1
BAR057.Resolution: The system event log captures the values that were not set, and they must be reset manually.
BAR057.Description: The configuration import was completed, but some of the imported values were not set correctly.

BIOS007.Description: A configuration job is already created on the specified target. No further command is allowed until the existing job succeeds or the job is cancelled.
BIOS007.Resolution: Wait for the job to complete. To continue with more set operations on the specified target, cancel the job and proceed.
BIOS007.Message: Configuration job already created, cannot create another configuration job on specified target until existing job is completed or is cancelled.

UEFI0244.Description: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) links failed to come up to full operating frequency.
UEFI0244.Resolution: Reseat all processors in the system and ensure all processors are matching. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0244.Message: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) links are operating in slow speed mode.

PWR8505.Description: The Dynamic Power Supply Engagement feature was not successfully enabled.
PWR8505.Resolution: Restart the Chassis Management Controller and retry the operation. To restart the Chassis Management Controller, using the WEB UI, go to Chassis Overview > Power > Control, select the Reset CMC option, and then click Apply.
PWR8505.Message: The Dynamic Power Supply Engagement feature was not successfully enabled.

UEFI0179.Message: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.
UEFI0179.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the correctable error persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0179.Description: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on the memory slot identified in the message. A corrected Read Receive Enable error was detected.

TMP0128.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or cool.
TMP0128.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0128.Message: Disk drive bay temperature is outside of range.

UEFI0292.Message: Unable to initialize the Dual Inline Memory Module (DIMM) in memory slot %1 because of a mismatch in the size of the DIMM installed in the server.
UEFI0292.Resolution: Remove the mismatched Dual Inline Memory Module (DIMM) module and replace it with a DIMM of the same size as other DIMMs installed on the Integrated Memory Controller (iMC). For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual available on the support site.
UEFI0292.Description: DDR memory initialization of the Dual Inline Memory Module (DIMM) in the specified memory slot cannot be completed because of a mismatch in the size of the DIMM installed in the server.

CMC8520.Message: The FRU on server %1 is not functioning.
CMC8520.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC of the specified server or virtual reseat the server. 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8520.Description: FRU on the server specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.

RAC1133.Description: The BIOSRTDRequested attribute was modified successfully. The BIOS reset to default values operation is pending a server restart.
RAC1133.Resolution: To apply the BIOS default values, restart the server. After the server has restarted, the default BIOS values will be accessible from the iDRAC.
RAC1133.Message: BIOSRTDRequested value is modified successfully. The BIOS reset to default values operation is pending a server restart.

SWC8559.Message: A new Virtual MAC Address Pool is created with %1 addresses from %2 for Boot Identity profile operations.
SWC8559.Description: A new Virtual MAC Address Pool is created with the number of addresses identified in the message starting from the MAC address identified in the message.

SWC0134.Message: The RAC log was cleared successfully

BAT1011.Message: Battery on %1 is in warn only mode and requires reconditioning.
BAT1011.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SWC0160.Message: PK SSH Authentication Key file successfully uploaded to the RAC.

SWC8515.Description: Successfully modified privileges of User identified in the message.

STOR13.Message: Unable to set the operation mode of the newly inserted storage sled in slot %1 to Split Single or Split Dual Host, because the storage sled has only one PERC controller.
STOR13.Resolution: Make sure that the newly inserted storage sled has the same number of PERC controllers as the previous storage sled so that the new sled will have the same operation mode after part replacement.
STOR13.Description: The operation mode of the newly inserted storage sled in the slot identified in the message cannot be set because the storage sled has only one PERC controller. The operation mode will only be Join after part replacement.

UEFI0182.Message: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.
UEFI0182.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the correctable error persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0182.Description: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on the memory slot identified in the message. A corrected Early Vref Centering error was detected.

VFL0014.Description: The vFlash SD card is not initialized. Either the card is not properly formatted or it may not be supported.
VFL0014.Resolution: Format the vFlash SD card by running the command "racadm vflashsd initialize". Make sure that the card is supported by contacting your service provider for a list of supported SD card types.
VFL0014.Message: The vFlash SD card is not initialized.

TST104.Description: The SNMP trap being tested is not properly configured.
TST104.Resolution: Configure the SNMP trap and retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset iDRAC.

RED049.Message: The job %1 is deleted because the recurring operation %2 is currently not enabled.
RED049.Description: When an Automatic Backup or Automatic Update recurring operation is disabled or the license for this feature is expired, the next job in the sequence had not started yet and was deleted.

RAC1013.Description: For any iDRAC user, SNMPv3 authentication protocol can be changed to "None" only if the SNMPv3 privacy protocol state is set to "None".
RAC1013.Resolution: Change the SNMPv3 privacy protocol state to 'None' using "racadm set iDRAC.Users.<index>.SNMPv3PrivacyType none", and retry the operation.
RAC1013.Message: The SNMPv3 authentication protocol state cannot be set to None if the SNMPv3 privacy protocol state is set to None.

PWR204.Description: Object value is successfully modified. Max Power Conservation Mode will deactivate the Extended Power Performance feature.
PWR204.Message: Object value is successfully modified. Max Power Conservation Mode will deactivate the Extended Power Performance feature.

RED007.Description: The Update Package security signature cannot be verified.
RED007.Resolution: Re-acquire the Update Package from the service provider.
RED007.Message: Unable to verify Update Package signature.

STOR013.Description: One or more storage device(s) are in a state that prevents the operation from completing.
STOR013.Resolution: Make sure the specified storage devices are in a state appropriate for the requested operation and retry the operation.
STOR013.Message: One or more storage device(s) are not in a state where the operation can be completed.

AMP0305.Message: The system board %1 current is within range.

TMP0105.Message: The system board %1 temperature is within range.

VDR99.Message: %1 is unavailable because of an ID conflict in the fault-tolerant pair.
VDR99.Resolution: Power cycle the system chassis to restore the virtual disk. If this does not correct the problem then contact your service provider.
VDR99.Description: The virtual disk identified in the message cannot be used because of an ID conflict with another virtual disk.

TMP0138.Description: Disabling the C1E state in servers with processors that have their Thermal Design Power (TDP) value set to equal to or greater than 155 Watt results in increased fan speed during high CPU workloads.
TMP0138.Message: The C1 Enhance (C1E) state is disabled in the server. Increased fan speeds can be expected during high CPU workload.

CMC8565.Message: KVM mapping is enabled for the server slot %1.
CMC8565.Description: The KVM mapping is enabled for the server slot specified in the message. The KVM cannot be mapped to this server slot.

ISM0007.Description: The iDRAC Service Module ended communication with iDRAC over the OS to iDRAC Pass-through channel. This is because either iDRAC is being restarted or the OS to iDRAC Pass-through configuration is being changed. The iDRAC Service Module will continue to try connecting to iDRAC.
ISM0007.Message: The iDRAC Service Module communication with iDRAC has ended.

PWR8565.Message: Unable to turn off the Server %1 due to iDRAC communication issue.
PWR8565.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Wait for a few minutes for the iDRAC service processor to complete startup. 2) Retry the operation. 3) If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC and wait a few minutes for the iDRAC startup to complete before retrying the operation.
PWR8565.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to communicate with the iDRAC service processor for the Server identified in the message and the Server could not be turned off. This situation may occur when iDRAC is rebooting.

RAC070.Description: The SSL Web-Server certificate was successfully restored to factory defaults.
RAC070.Message: The SSL Web-Server certificate was successfully restored to factory defaults.

NIC507.Description: For the requested operation, enable the NIC to get the NIC details.
NIC507.Resolution: Check if the NIC is disabled. If disabled, enable the NIC.
NIC507.Message: Unable to determine current NIC state.

SYS121.Description: The operation to collect OS and Application Data was cancelled using iDRAC Web UI.
SYS121.Message: The operation to collect OS and Application Data was cancelled using iDRAC Web UI.

RAC950.Description: The work note cannot be added to the Lifecycle Log if iDRAC is archiving the older records in the Lifecycle Log.
RAC950.Resolution: Wait for several minutes while iDRAC archives the older records, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC950.Message: Unable to add the work note to the Lifecycle Log.

BAT0010.Message: The storage battery for disk drive bay %1 is low.
BAT0010.Resolution: Allow the PERC RAID controller battery for the associated bay to charge. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
BAT0010.Description: To charge the battery, the system has to remain powered on.

STOR0508.Description: Unable to configure RAID as the supported RAID controller is not present.
STOR0508.Resolution: Install a supported RAID controller and the required number of physical disks for the RAID configuration, and retry the operation.
STOR0508.Message: No supported controllers present for RAID configuration.

PWR8534.Description: Unable to set Server Based Power Management Mode to enable.
PWR8534.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR8534.Message: Unable to set Server Based Power Management Mode to enable.

SWC0243.Description: SSL Certificate is regenerated successfully and the Web server is restarted.
SWC0243.Message: Certificate regenerated successfully and webserver restarted

RAC0251.Description: The vFlash partitions are attached. Therefore, the current operation cannot proceed.
RAC0251.Resolution: Detach the partitions and try again.
RAC0251.Message: One or more partitions are currently attached.

SYS436.Description: The job cannot be created because the Start Time entered is invalid.
SYS436.Resolution: Enter the Start Time in the String format, and then retry the operation For example, YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SS. For more information about recommened Start Time format, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
SYS436.Message: Unable to create the job because the Start Time entered is invalid.

CTL54.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes. The text for this alert is generated by the controller and can vary depending on the situation.

SYS225.Message: Unable to complete the job %1 successfully because of the issues listed in the Lifecycle Controller log files.
SYS225.Resolution: Verify the reason for the unsuccessful completion of the job by inspecting the Lifecycle Log entries related to the job. Correct the underlying cause of the unsuccessful completion and retry the operation.
SYS225.Description: The job identified in the message cannot be successfully completed because of the issues listed in the Lifecycle Controller log files.

SWU8561.Description: The firmware version selected for rollback does not support the current chassis hardware configuration.
SWU8561.Resolution: Make sure that firmware version selected for rollback is supported for the current hardware configuration, such as I/O modules, PSU modules, and servers. For example, a newer generation PSU may not work with an earlier iDRAC or CMC firmware. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual or CMC or iDRAC Release Notes for details.
SWU8561.Message: Unable to downgrade the firmware version because the current hardware configuration does not support rollback to the earlier firmware version.

RAC060.Message: Unable to set the attribute because OpenManage Server Administrator (OMSA) is installed on the server %1
RAC060.Resolution: Uninstall OMSA, and then retry the operation.
RAC060.Description: The attribute identified in the message could not be set, because certain features cannot be enabled when OMSA is installed on the server.

RAC0754.Description: Reset iDRAC to complete custom SSL certificate deletion action. A manual reset of iDRAC is needed for the action to take effect.
RAC0754.Resolution: Click the Reset iDRAC link to reset iDRAC.
RAC0754.Message: Reset iDRAC to complete the deletion action of the certificate.

STOR083.Description: The Physical Disk(s) specified are too small to create a Virtual Disk of the requested size.
STOR083.Resolution: Specify Physical Disk FQDD IDs of physical disk drive(s) that have a larger disk space, and retry the operation.
STOR083.Message: The Physical Disk(s) specified are too small to create a Virtual Disk of the requested size.

SYS007.Resolution: Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation for the specific attribute and retry the operation with valid value within the range of the attribute.
SYS007.Description: The input value for the attribute being set is not within the acceptable range for the attribute.

MEM1000.Message: Memory device at location %1 transition to a running state.

UEFI0111.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.
UEFI0111.Resolution: Remove input power to the system, reseat the DIMM module and restart the system. If the issues persist, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0111.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot identified in the message. The error occurred during memory test.

RDU8502.Message: CMC%1 cannot go standby since the other CMC is not present or healthy.
RDU8502.Resolution: Check the status of the standby CMC and make sure the firmware version matches the primary CMC. Then reseat the CMC and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RDU8502.Description: For failover to occur, the standby CMC needs to be present, at the same version as the primary and healthy. During failover, the active CMC resets and the standby CMC becomes active. This message is logged when the standby CMC is absent, unhealthy or at a different firmware version.

SWC0324.Description: There are no records to display. This might be a result of the log being cleared.
SWC0324.Message: There are no records available to display.

SWC0149.Description: The requested SNMP test trap alert was successfully sent.

HWC7006.Message: Server %1 health changed to a non-recoverable state from a less severe state.
HWC7006.Resolution: Review System Log or front panel for additional information.
HWC7006.Description: Server <number> health changed to a non-recoverable state from a less severe state.

LC104.Description: The new job cannot be created because a backup and restore job is already running. Any pending value will be deleted.
LC104.Resolution: Wait for the current backup and restore job to complete, and then retry the operation.
LC104.Message: Unable to create the new job because a backup and restore job is already running.Any pending value will be deleted.

RAC0236.Description: vFlash image upload failed because the image is not valid.
RAC0236.Resolution: Image may be corrupt. Try uploading a valid vFlash image.

FAN8502.Message: Unable to detect the blower %1 because the blower may not be optimally operating.
FAN8502.Resolution: Make sure that CMC is using the latest firmware, and then retry the operation.
FAN8502.Description: The current CMC firmware did not detect the blower identified in the message.

CMC8554.Description: An internal network error occurred. If none of the external sources have an issue, the CMC may have a hardware issue. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8554.Resolution: Reseat the network cable and check the connectivity to the outbound switch.

VDR92.Message: Consistency check for %1 has completed with uncorrectable errors.
VDR92.Description: This message occurs if there are medium errors in the physical drives.

PDR114.Description: The PCIe solid state device identified in the message is between 90% and 100% of reaching read-only mode.

RAC0687.Description: Some of the applied pending operations were not created.
RAC0687.Resolution: Choose to create a job for the successful operations. View successful pending operations using the Pending Operations button or click Cancel to quit job creation.
RAC0687.Message: Some of the applied pending operations were not created.

MEM9008.Message: Intel DDR Memory interconnect %1 has a non-recoverable issue.
MEM9008.Resolution: Reseat all DIMMs on the memory riser, reseat the memory riser, and restart the server. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
MEM9008.Description: A non-recoverable issue was detected in the propagation of signals on the Intel DDR memory interconnect identified in the message.

PR3.Message: Newer version of firmware found on device: %1
PR3.Description: The current component firmware version is higher than the replaced component firmware version.

LC007.Description: One of the parameters specified in the method is invalid.
LC007.Resolution: Verify that the parameters specified are correct. For a list of parameters for this method refer to the Lifecycle Controller User Guide.

RAC0765.Description: The OS IP address cannot be accessed by using the Ping process because an incorrect IP address is entered.
RAC0765.Resolution: Enter a correct IP address, and then retry the operation.
RAC0765.Message: Unable to access the operating system (OS) IP address by using the Ping process because an incorrect IP address is entered.

STOR309.Description: The command cannot be run because multiple targets must not be entered as input in the Blink/Unblink Target method.
STOR309.Resolution: Enter only one target FQDD (Fully Qualified Device Descriptor), and then retry the operation.
STOR309.Message: Unable to run the command because multiple targets must not be entered as input in the Blink/Unblink Target method.

CMC8535.Message: Unable to turn on High Power Management for the server %1
CMC8535.Resolution: Reboot CMC and retry the operation. If the issue persists, reseat the server and retry the operation.
CMC8535.Description: Unable to turn on the server specified in the message because of an internal CMC error.

LC024.Description: Unable to retrieve Lifecycle Controller Log records because of an issue internal to the firmware.
LC024.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Try the operation again 2) AC power cycle the system 3) apply the latest firmware update packages for Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC.
LC024.Message: Unable to retrieve Lifecycle Controller Log records.

RAC802.Description: iDRAC time has been set through Network Time Protocol (NTP).
RAC802.Message: iDRAC time is set using Network Time Protocol.

PR36.Message: Version change detected for %1 firmware. Previous version:%2, Current version:%3
PR36.Description: The system has detected a different firmware version than previously recorded for the indicated device. This may be due to a firmware update, rollback, or part replacement.

PCI3020.Message: A low-severity issue is detected in a component of the bus %1, device 0, function %2.
PCI3020.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the component identified in the message, and then monitor the log for a re-occurrence of the issue. If the issue persists, and occurs during server startup, update the component firmware. If the issue persists and occurs during OS runtime, restart the server and update the OS drivers for the component identified in the message.
PCI3020.Description: A low-severity issue is detected in the component identified in the message.

JCP030.Description: Unable to schedule jobs for execution while an iDRAC firmware update job is running.
JCP030.Resolution: Wait for the running job to complete, and then retry the operation.
JCP030.Message: Unable to schedule jobs while an iDRAC firmware update or configuration job is running.

RED052.Description: Processing of update packages is starting. Attempting a manual update will not be possible until current update package processing is completed.
RED052.Message: Processing of update packages is starting.

OSD11.Description: Lifecycle Controller does not have any drivers for the selected operating system. The operating system installation uses the native drivers present on the operating system media.
OSD11.Message: Driver Pack does not have drivers for the selected operating system.

RAC1059.Description: The requested firmware rollback operation could not be performed because another firmware update job is running or being scheduled.
RAC1059.Resolution: Wait until the existing firmware update jobs are completed or scheduled before retrying the operation. To monitor the status of the existing jobs, run the RACADM command "racadm jobqueue view". If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and then retry the operation after the iDRAC has finished restarting.
RAC1059.Message: Rollback operation could not be performed because another firmware update job is running.

CMC8510.Message: Unable to activate the extended storage feature on the secondary CMC: %1. The feature will return to single CMC mode.
CMC8510.Resolution: Do one of the following, and retry the operation: 1) In the CMC Web interface, go to Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration and verify if the card on the secondary CMC displays some errors. 2) Do a failover and then reprovision the card from the same GUI page. Reprovisioning is only allowed on the card of primary CMC. However, if both the options 1 and 2 fail, the card may be no longer functional.
CMC8510.Description: This happens during promotion of extended storage feature from single CMC to dual CMC. If the media on Standby CMC is not healthy, this message is displayed and the feature returns to single CMC state.

VDR43.Message: Dedicated hot spare unassigned physical disk %1.
VDR43.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PSU1007.Description: A device has been failed and the system is no longer functioning in optimal condition.

MEM1001.Message: Memory device at location %1 failed to transition to a running state.
MEM1001.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem continues, contact support.

RAC0180.Description: Certificate upload failed. Unable to get local issuer certificate. The local issuer certificate is the certificate for the Certificate Authority (CA) that has signed the certificate for the Active Directory (AD) server, unless it is self signed. The iDRAC needs to verify that the CA is legitimate.
RAC0180.Resolution: Certificate has expired. Try creating a new CSR and then upload the certificate.
RAC0180.Message: Certificate upload failed: Unable to get local issuer certificate from the Certification Authority (CA) for confirming the CA is legitimate.

TMP0203.Message: CPU %1 temperature is greater than the upper critical threshold.
TMP0203.Resolution: Check system operating environment, fans, and heatsinks.

RAC0689.Description: Unable to create a virtual disk on the selected disk drives, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
RAC0689.Resolution: To enable Lifecycle Controller, reboot the server. During server startup, press F2 to enter System Setup. Go to iDRAC Settings -> Lifecycle Controller, select Enable, and save the changes. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
RAC0689.Message: Unable to create a virtual disk on the selected disk drives, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

SYS119.Description: The OS collector cannot be exposed to the host server because of communication issues between the iDRAC and server OS.
SYS119.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and server OS.
SYS119.Message: Unable to expose the OS Collector to the server OS.

SWC0113.Description: The syntax of the setniccfg command is invalid.
SWC0113.Resolution: Refer the help text for setniccfg subcommand.
SWC0113.Message: The -6 option can only be used in combination with the -d or -s option.

PST0195.Description: The current processor configuration is unsupported or encountered a fatal exception during POST. Check the processor configuration. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST exception code C3).
