PST0195.Resolution: Review system processor configuration and reduce the system to the minimum configuration.

BAT0012.Message: The storage battery for disk drive bay %1 has failed.
BAT0012.Resolution: 1) Verify the PERC RAID controller battery installation for the associated bay.2) Check the system logs for thermal related issues.
BAT0012.Description: The PERC RAID controller battery may have failed because of thermal exceptions.

SWC0700.Description: iDRAC7 is not ready or is busy and is not responding to iDRAC7 Settings IPMI requests.
SWC0700.Resolution: Turn off the system, Remove AC. Wait for 5 seconds. Connect AC. Turn it on.
SWC0700.Message: iDRAC is not ready. The configuration values cannot be accessed. Please retry after a few minutes.

SEL9902.Description: Software on the system has logged an event that cannot be determined. You may need to review this event using a tool which displays raw data such as Ipmitool with the -vvv option or Racadm with the -E option.

RAC987.Message: Firmware update job for %1 is initiated.
RAC987.Resolution: This firmware update job may take several minutes to complete depending on the component or firmware being updated. To view the progress of the job, use the "racadm jobqueue view" command.
RAC987.Description: After initiating the firmware update job, the time taken to complete it depends on size of the update file.

BAR106.Description: Unable to import system branding data from the backup Server Profile.
BAR106.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
BAR106.Message: Unable to restore system branding data.

RAC1014.Description: The SNMPv3 privacy protocol cannot be configured to AES or DES mode if SNMPv3 authentication protocol state is set to "None".
RAC1014.Resolution: To configure the SNMPv3 Privacy Protocol for a specified iDRAC user, change the SNMPv3 Authentication Protocol to either MD5 or SHA state using "racadm set idrac.users.<index>.SNMPv3AuthenticationType <value>".
RAC1014.Message: The SNMPv3 privacy protocol cannot be configured to AES or DES mode if SNMPv3 authentication protocol state is set to "None".

UEFI0106.Message: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.
UEFI0106.Resolution: Remove input power to the system, reseat the DIMM module and restart the system. If the correctable error persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0106.Description: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on the memory slot identified in the message.

TMP0132.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.
TMP0132.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0132.Message: The control panel temperature is greater than the upper warning threshold.

RAC983.Description: The Public Key Cryptography Standards version 12 (PKCS12) file is passphrase protected, and the passphrase provided is invalid.
RAC983.Resolution: Specify the correct passphrase for the file using -p option.
RAC983.Message: Invalid passphrase provided for the Public Key Cryptography Standards version 12 (PKCS12) file.

VFL0013.Description: The request could not be successfully completed, because the vFlash SD Card is in read-only mode. Write operations cannot be performed on the card.
VFL0013.Resolution: Change the access mode on the vFlash SD Card to read-write.
VFL0013.Message: The vFlash SD Card is in read-only mode.

SWC0321.Description: Could not open the log file for reading.
SWC0321.Message: Unable to open the log for reading.

RSI0004.Description: The Remote Service database is unavailable.

STOR015.Description: A new virtual disk cannot be created because the maximum number of virtual disks are already created.
STOR015.Resolution: A new virtual disk cannot be created until one is deleted.
STOR015.Message: Maximum virtual disks allowed for this controller has been reached.

DH004.Resolution: Boot the OS. If the error persists, contact technical support.
DH004.Message: iDRAC does not have sufficient free resources to generate keys.

PDR1016.Message: Drive %1 is removed from disk drive bay %2.
PDR1016.Resolution: Verify drive installation. Remove and reseat the failed drive. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PDR1016.Description: The controller detected that the drive was removed.

PSU502.Description: The server was already down, when the user gave a power off request.

SWC8528.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to update the IDRAC "root" user password. This can happen if the communication to the iDRAC from CMC is non-functional or if the password entered is not valid.
SWC8528.Resolution: Make sure the password is valid. If communications with the iDRAC is not functioning, reset the iDRAC and retry the operation after a few minutes. Run the RACADM command "racadm ping server-<slot number> " to check the communications. If the communications are not functional, restart the iDRAC by performing a Virtual Reseat of the server using the RACADM command "racadm racreset -m server-<slot id>".
SWC8528.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to update the iDRAC root password.

SWC8512.Resolution: Correct the error described in the message and retry the operation after a few minutes.
SWC8512.Description: Unable to add user name identified in the message. The reason for this issue is described with the error code in the message.

PWR209.Description: The redundancy policy cannot be changed to either Power Supply Redundancy or No Redundancy because the Extended Power Performance is enabled.
PWR209.Resolution: Disable Extended Power Performance and retry the operation.
PWR209.Message: Unable to change the redundancy policy to either Power Supply Redundancy or No Redundancy because the Extended Power Performance is enabled.

ISM0016.Message: The BMC watchdog reset time is changed to %1 seconds.
ISM0016.Description: The BMC watchdog reset time is changed to a value identified in the message.

OSD43.Description: vFlash is not present on the server.
OSD43.Resolution: Insert a Dell-licensed vFlash and then retry this command.

LOG504.Description: The Chassis Log was successfully exported to the destination specified.

BAT0004.Description: System settings may be preserved if input power is not removed from the power supplies.
BAT0004.Resolution: Check the system board battery to confirm presence.
BAT0004.Message: The system board battery is absent.

BIOS022.Description: The BIOS password is disabled in the hardware using a jumper and can not be set. See the system owners manual for jumper location.
BIOS022.Resolution: Change the jumper setting on the system board to enable changing the BIOS password.
BIOS022.Message: Cannot set the BIOS password. Password is disabled due to a jumper setting on the motherboard.

OSD24.Description: Unable to continue with DetachDrivers - UnPackAndAttach is in progress.
OSD24.Resolution: Wait until UnpackAndAttach finishes and then run DetachDrivers. This can take more than 5 minutes.
OSD24.Message: Unable to continue with DetachDrivers - UnPackAndAttach is in progress.

SWC0311.Description: The syntax of the getconfig command is invalid.
SWC0311.Resolution: Refer the help text for getconfig subcommand.
SWC0311.Message: Invalid syntax. The -g option is only valid with -i and -o options.

RAC0218.Description: A maximum of 4 iDRAC Web GUI sessions can be open at any time.
RAC0218.Resolution: Close one or more sessions before opening another session.
RAC0218.Message: The maximum number of user sessions is reached.

NIC500.Description: The values of IP Address is not allowed to change if DHCP is enabled.
NIC500.Resolution: Disable DHCP and then modify the value.
NIC500.Message: The requested object is not allowed to be configured if DHCP is enabled.

RAC0127.Description: Size must be a whole number.
RAC0127.Resolution: Enter a whole number for the size field.
RAC0127.Message: The specified size must be a non-fractional numeric value.

PDR1000.Message: Drive %1 is installed in disk drive bay %2.

RAC0910.Description: The specified command is missing group and object name syntax.
RAC0910.Resolution: Specify the correct subcommand group and object name syntax. See the help text or documentation for the valid syntax.
RAC0910.Message: Invalid subcommand syntax: Specify group and object name.

RAC0560.Description: RAC Software Initialization error. Monitoring data will not be available for PERC and Network Cards.

USR103.Resolution: Refer to the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services documentation and provide the required parameters.
USR103.Description: One or more required parameters needed for the operation are missing.

PDR13.Resolution: Replace the failed or corrupt disk, and then start the rebuild operation.
PDR13.Description: A physical disk included in the virtual disk has failed or is corrupted. In addition, you may have cancelled the rebuild.

RAC1131.Description: The iDRAC was reset and is successfully restarted.

SWC0317.Description: The value for -c must be greater than zero.
SWC0317.Resolution: Enter a value greater than zero, for the option -c.
SWC0317.Message: The number of records to display must be greater than zero.

SEL0006.Description: This message appears when all event logging has been disabled by the user. (IPMI sensor type code 10h - offset 03h).

RAC0615.Description: The contents of the PKCS12 file was not valid because one of the following: 1) Not a valid PKCS#12 file, 2) Not a valid pfx file or 3) Did not contain a valid key.
RAC0615.Resolution: Make sure to upload the file in PKCS#12 format. OpenSSL can be used to validate a PKCS#12 file.

PSU1005.Description: The enclosure detected that a power supply unit was switched on.

SWC0701.Description: Power capping is enabled and sets user-defined power capping limits for the system.

BAT0002.Description: System settings may be preserved if input power is not removed from the power supplies.
BAT0002.Message: The system board battery has failed.

UEFI0032.Description: The TPM chip cannot be initialized because the TPM chip is not functioning.
UEFI0032.Resolution: Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system.
UEFI0032.Message: Unable to initialize the TPM chip because the TPM chip is not functioning.

RAC0686.Description: Some of the applied pending operations were not created.
RAC0686.Resolution: View successful pending operations by clicking the Pending Operations button.
RAC0686.Message: Some of the applied pending operations were not created.

POW005.Description: Host failed to power up because CMC MPCM mode is enabled. This messages has been replaced by Message ID PWR2255.
POW005.Resolution: Disable MPCM mode to power up.
POW005.Message: Power on permission error, CMC is in MPCM mode.

CPU0002.Message: CPU %1 has failed the built-in self-test (BIST).
CPU0002.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is inserted correctly, if the processor is removable. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

RAC0282.Description: This is the number of login failures attempted from an IP address before further login attempts are rejected from that address. The default value is 10.
RAC0282.Resolution: Enter a valid IP Blocking Fail Count. Expected range: 2-16.
RAC0282.Message: IP Blocking Fail Count is invalid. Expected range: 2-16.

BAR089.Description: A problem has been detected with the installation of the Unified Server Configurator (USC). This needs to be corrected before a valid Backup file can be created.
BAR089.Resolution: Obtain the Dell update package for the Unified Server Configurator and apply it. Then perform a Backup operation to save this data, for later restore.
BAR089.Message: Lifecycle Controller needs to be updated.

PST0001.Description: System BIOS detected the system is turned on.

RAC0749.Description: SNMPv3 User cannot be set to None.
RAC0749.Resolution: Set the SNMPv3 User to a value other than None and retry the operation.
RAC0749.Message: SNMPv3 User cannot be set to None.

CTL116.Description: The secure foreign locked drives cannot be unlocked because already unlocked drives are detected which have secure locked configuration that are neither imported nor erased.
CTL116.Resolution: The unlock command should be followed by an import config command to import a secure foreign locked configuration or by a cryptographic erase command. If the unlocked drives are not imported or erased, then further unlock operations on locked drives will be blocked. To import already unlocked drives on a controller, run the RACADM command at the command line interface (CLI): "racadm raid importconfig:<Controller FQDD>" where <Controller FQDD> is the FQDD identifier of the target controller. In order to erase the data on the unlocked drive, run the command: "racadm raid cryptographicerase:<Drive FQDD>" where <Drive FQDD> is the FQDD identifier of the target drive.
CTL116.Message: Unable to unlock secure foreign locked drives because already unlocked drives are detected that are neither imported nor deleted.

HWC5031.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
HWC5031.Description: The CMC has powered off the IOM.

RED096.Description: The maximum iDRAC storage space allocated for storing firmware image files is reached. The firmware image of the earlier version that was stored for a rollback operation is now deleted.
RED096.Message: The maximum iDRAC storage space allocated for storing firmware image files is reached. The firmware image of the earlier version that was stored for a rollback operation is now deleted.

CMC8540.Description: The CMC specified in the message is turned on because of a CMC insertion or due to chassis AC power on.

SYS148.Description: The BIOS is configured to reset to defaults on the next system restart because of a System Erase operation.
SYS148.Message: BIOS is configured to reset to defaults on next system restart.

PDR112.Message: The %1 has reached %2 of warranted device wear-out limit.
PDR112.Description: The PCIe solid state device identified in the message is approaching the warranted wear-out limit.

SEC0602.Description: This may apply to a physical or remote access attempt.
SEC0602.Resolution: Check system logs for intrusion attempts, and ensure strong password policies.

PWR8558.Description: A configuration change has occurred such that the current power cap is now supported.
PWR8558.Message: The System Input Power Cap is being enforced with the current Power Supply configuration.

BAR075.Description: The collection and export of system information failed.
BAR075.Resolution: Restart the remote access controller, and retry the operation. If the error continues, use the remote access controller firmware to try the operation again.

BAR114.Message: An Automatic Backup job %1 is created.
BAR114.Description: The Automatic Backup job identified in the message is created per the Server Profile automatic export schedule previously configured.

NIC021.Description: The old BIOS password used to change the password is incorrect.
NIC021.Resolution: Enter the correct old password for the BIOS and retry the operation.

VDR55.Resolution: Verify the health of attached devices. Review the Alert Log for significant events. Make sure the cables are attached securely. See the Cables Attached Correctly section for more information on checking the cables.
VDR55.Description: The controller cannot communicate with attached devices. A disk may be removed or contain errors. Cables may also be loose or defective.

PR17.Message: Some of the configuration values stored for the previous device could not be applied to device: %1
PR17.Resolution: Check the device's configuration and ensure that the new configuration is correct for the system.
PR17.Description: Some of the configuration values stored for the previous device could not be applied to the current device. This may be due to firmware version or other differences in the part.

DIS102.Description: The AutoConfig configuration import operation could not be started, because the AutoConfig .xml file is not available in the sharename or location specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.
DIS102.Resolution: Update the sharename or location in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC, make sure the AutoConfig import file is available, and then retry the operation.
DIS102.Message: Unable to start the AutoConfig import operation, because the AutoConfig import file is not available.

AMP0306.Message: Disk drive bay %1 current is less than the lower warning threshold.
AMP0306.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.

SWC8554.Message: The Virtual MAC Address Pool %1 is invalid for Boot Identity profile operations.
SWC8554.Resolution: Edit the Virtual MAC Address Pool and correct any XML schema or configuration errors present, and then retry the operation.
SWC8554.Description: The Virtual MAC Address Pool identified in the message is not valid. This can occur because the XML syntax is not correct or because of invalid configuration values.

PDR68.Message: Dedicated spare %1 imported as global due to missing disk groups.
PDR68.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

VF013.Description: The SD card is locked by another operation.
VF013.Resolution: Rerun the command after about 2 minutes.

RAC0562.Description: iDRAC automatically restored connection with CMC proxy component. Agent free Monitoring will now be supported for Chassis PCIe slots.
RAC0562.Message: iDRAC-CMC communication restored for agent free monitoring of chassis PCIe slots.

RAC0265.Description: If VLAN is enabled, specify the VLAN ID and VLAN Priority.
RAC0265.Resolution: Enter a VLAN ID and VLAN Priority.
RAC0265.Message: Specify the VLAN ID and VLAN Priority.

RAC968.Description: The configuration XML file cannot be imported from a client location when using Firmware RACADM.
RAC968.Resolution: When using Firmware RACADM, make sure to import the configuration XML file from a remote share only.
RAC968.Message: Importing the configuration XML file from a local share is not supported when using Firmware RACADM.

SEC0040.Description: Operating system generated critical stop IPMI event. (Sensor type code = 20H).
SEC0040.Resolution: Check video and operating system logs for additional information.
SEC0040.Message: A critical stop occurred during OS load.

RED043.Message: A recurring operation of type %1 was not created because the operation type is disabled.
RED043.Resolution: Enable the operation identified in the message and retry the operation. To enable the Automatic Server Profile Backup operation, run the following racadm command: "racadm set lifecycleController.lcattributes.AutoBackup 1". To enable the Automatic Update operation, run the following racadm command: "racadm set lifecycleController.lcattributes.AutoUpdate 1".
RED043.Description: The operation identified in the message is currently disabled.

SYS096.Description: The required Dell Diagnostics firmware package is not installed or cannot be found in the iDRAC internal storage.
SYS096.Resolution: Install the Dell 64bit uEFI Diagnostics firmware package, and then retry the operation. The Dell Diagnostics can be installed using the Dell 64bit uEFI Diagnostics Dell Update Package (DUP).
SYS096.Message: Unable to complete the diagnostics operation because the required Dell Diagnostics firmware package is not installed.

RAC952.Description: The allocated size for the Lifecycle Log entries has reached its maximum limit, and no further work notes can be added to the Lifecycle Log.
RAC952.Message: There is no free space to add new work notes to the Lifecycle Log.

RAC0753.Description: Reset iDRAC to apply the pending new certificate. Until iDRAC is reset old certificate will be active. A manual reset of iDRAC is needed for the new certificate to take into effect.
RAC0753.Resolution: Click the Reset iDRAC link to reset iDRAC.
RAC0753.Message: Reset iDRAC to apply the pending new certificate. Until iDRAC is reset the old certificate will be active.

VDR59.Description: This alert message occurs if virtual disk security has failed.

RAC0750.Description: The USB NIC IP address cannot be accessed by using the PING process.
RAC0750.Resolution: Enter another appropriate IP address, and then retry the operation.
RAC0750.Message: Unable to access the USB NIC IP address by using PING process.

RAC1045.Description: Individual component firmware updates may occur frequently and cause changes to the catalog on ftp.dell.com. Specifying ftp.dell.com as the catalog source for the Automatic Update feature may result in frequent system firmware updates.
RAC1045.Resolution: Creating a custom repository using the Repository Manager tool allows control of the frequency of component firmware updates.
RAC1045.Message: Specifying ftp.dell.comas the catalog source for the Automatic Update feature may result in frequent system firmware updates because the catalog on ftp.dell.comchanges often.

RED090.Description: A Chassis firmware update operation is no longer in progress. This is not an indication of success or failure.
RED090.Message: A Chassis firmware update operation is no longer in progress.

PWR1007.Description: To avoid shutdown, system performance has been degraded.
PWR1007.Resolution: Review system configuration, upgrade power supplies or reduce system power consumption.
PWR1007.Message: The system performance degraded because power exceeds capacity.

BAR100.Description: An error occurred accessing license data. Cannot collect license data to copy to Server Profile backup file.
BAR100.Resolution: Refer to License Management documentation for re-installation of license(s) instructions and retry the operation.

RAC0646.Description: The job could not be successfully scheduled, because an invalid value is entered for 'day of the week' while scheduling a job.
RAC0646.Resolution: Enter a correct value, and then retry the operation.
RAC0646.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid value is entered for the day of the week.

LC052.Description: There can only be one Server Profile Import job at a time.
LC052.Resolution: Wait for the existing Server Profile Import job to run and complete or cancel it, before retrying the operation.
LC052.Message: Cannot create multiple Server Profile Import jobs.

RAC004.Resolution: Provide a valid parameter value for specified parameter.
RAC004.Description: The parameter value for the given parameter is invalid.

RED097.Description: Unable to complete the firmware update operation because the specified firmware image is for a component that is not in the target system inventory.
RED097.Resolution: Identify and download the firmware version that corresponds to the component being updated in the target system inventory, and retry the operation. For a list of supported firmware versions, refer to the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
RED097.Message: Unable to complete the firmware update operation because the specified firmware image is for a component that is not in the target system inventory.

CTL6.Resolution: See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.
CTL6.Description: A portion of a physical disk is damaged. See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.

UEFI0044.Description: Unable to enable the TXT feature because the processor does not support TXT.
UEFI0044.Message: Unable to enable the TXT feature because the motherboard chipset does not support TXT.

STOR094.Description: The storage configuration operation is successfully completed and the change is in pending state.
STOR094.Resolution: To apply the configuration operation immediately, create a configuration job using the --realTime option. To apply the configuration after restarting the server, create a configuration job using the -r option. To create the necessary real-time and restart jobs, run the jobqueue command. For more information about jobqueue command, run the racadm help jobqueue command.
STOR094.Message: The storage configuration operation is successfully completed and the change is in pending state.

OSD14.Description: iDRAC was unable to expose the drivers as a USB device for the OS installation to proceed.
OSD14.Resolution: 1) Rerun the command. 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD14.Message: Unable to expose the USB device that contains the operating system drivers to host system.

NIC006.Description: A configuration job already exists for the specified target. No further configuration operation is allowed until the existing job completes or the job is cancelled.
NIC006.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Wait for the existing configuration job to complete and retry the operation, 2) To continue with a configuration change, cancel the existing job and retry the operation.
NIC006.Message: A configuration job already exists, Cannot set attribute on specified target until existing job is completed or is cancelled

CMC004.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the parameter %1 is invalid.
CMC004.Resolution: Enter a valid parameter and retry the operation. For information about valid parameters, see the CMC Profile document available on the support site.
CMC004.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the parameter identified in the message is invalid.

SYS084.Description: Export of ePSA Diagnostics results did not complete successfully because the iDRAC internal storage containing the results could not be accessed.
SYS084.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Delete all jobs, 2) Reset iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for at least 15 seconds, and 3) Retry the operation.
SYS084.Message: Export of ePSA Diagnostics results did not complete successfully because the iDRAC internal storage containing the results could not be accessed.

LC027.Description: The Hardware Inventory XML file export operation was successful.
LC027.Message: The Hardware Inventory file export was successful.

RAC0295.Description: This is the number of characters per Serial Over LAN (SOL) data packet. When the number of characters accepted by iDRAC is equal to or greater than the Character Send Threshold value, iDRAC starts transmitting SOL data packets that contain the numbers of characters equal to or less than the Character Send Threshold value. If a packet contains fewer characters than this value, it is defined to be a partial SOL data packet. It is recommended to use 255 characters for optimal performance.
RAC0295.Resolution: Enter a valid Character Send Threshold value. Expected range: 1-255.
RAC0295.Message: The Character Send Threshold value is invalid. Expected range: 1-255.

BAT1004.Message: The battery on %1 learn cycle has timed out.
BAT1004.Resolution: Replace the battery pack. The battery is unable to maintain a full charge.
BAT1004.Description: The controller battery must be fully charged before the learn cycle can begin. The battery may be unable to maintain a full charge causing the learn cycle to timeout. In addition, the battery must be able to maintain cached data for a specified period of time in the event of a power loss. For example, some batteries maintain cached data for 24 hours. If the battery is unable to maintain cached data for the required period of time, then the Learn cycle will timeout.

SYS417.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the value %1 entered for the query parameter %2 is out of range %3.
SYS417.Resolution: Enter a query parameter value within range and retry the operation.
SYS417.Description: The operation cannot be successfully completed because the value entered for the query parameter is out of range as identified in the message.

CBL0006.Message: Unsupported backplane %1 configuration: Multiple RAID controllers cannot be connected to the same backplane.
CBL0006.Resolution: Make sure that only one RAID controller is connected to the backplane. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CBL0006.Description: Each server model only supports a certain set of backplane configurations. For unified backplanes or split mode capable backplanes that are in unified mode, multiple controllers cannot be connected to the same backplane. In unified backplane situations any controller besides the first will not be operational.

CTL40.Resolution: Replace the Dual In-line Memory Module (DIMM). The DIMM is a part of the controller battery pack. Refer to the storage hardware documentation for information on replacing the DIMM. You may need to restore data from backup.
CTL40.Description: An error involving multiple bits has been encountered during a read or write operation. The error correction algorithm recalculates parity data during read and write operations. If an error involves only a single bit, it may be possible for the error correction algorithm to correct the error and maintain parity data. An error involving multiple bits, however, generally indicates data loss. In some cases, if the multi-bit error occurs during a read operation, then the data on the disk may be ok. If the multi-bit error occurs during a write operation, then data loss has occurred.

LOG202.Description: Unable to access part of Lifecycle Controller Log comments file during iDRAC boot. The file was truncated at the point of corruption.
LOG202.Message: Recovered from Lifecycle Controller Log comments file corruption.

SYS138.Description: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the server OS is turned off.
SYS138.Resolution: Turn on the server and wait until the OS finishes booting, and then retry the operation.
SYS138.Message: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the server is turned off.

PDR20.Resolution: Replace the disk that has received the SMART alert. If the physical disk is a member of a non-redundant virtual disk, then back up the data before replacing the disk. Removing a physical disk that is included in a non-redundant virtual disk will cause the virtual disk to fail and may cause data loss.
PDR20.Description: A disk has received a SMART alert (predictive failure) after a configuration change. The disk is likely to fail in the near future.

PST0254.Description: System BIOS detected a functional or configuration issue during system POST. Check the system video screen for more information. The system event log may contain additional details. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception code FE).
PST0254.Resolution: Check system video and review event log for additional information.

BOOT015.Description: The boot partition configuration request was successful. An unattached vFlash partition was configured for one-time boot using the ChangeBootOrderByInstanceID method. The method creates a job (to attach the vFlash partition and set the partition for one-time boot.
BOOT015.Message: Set operation successful for the boot partition.

RAC1116.Description: The command could not be successfully run, because an incorrect "restart flag" value was entered in the command.
RAC1116.Resolution: Enter a correct flag value. The recommended values are "true" and "false". Make sure that you have entered the correct value, and then retry the operation.
RAC1116.Message: Unable to run the command, because the restart flag entered is incorrect.

PWR210.Description: The redundancy policy cannot be changed to either Power Supply Redundancy or No Redundancy because the Extended Power Performance is enabled.
PWR210.Message: The redundancy policy cannot be changed to either Power Supply Redundancy or No Redundancy because the Extended Power Performance is enabled.

RAC0256.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the Preferred DNS IPv4 address does not conform to the required format.
RAC0256.Resolution: Enter a valid Preferred DNS Server Address. Expected range: [0.0.0.0 or 1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].
RAC0256.Message: The Preferred DNS Server Address is invalid. Expected range: [0.0.0.0 or 1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].

PDR117.Message: The %1 has turned off because the critical temperature threshold is exceeded.
PDR117.Resolution: Contact your service provider for further instructions.
PDR117.Description: The PCIe solid state device identified in the message has turned off because the critical temperature threshold of the device was exceeded.

PCI5004.Message: A power fault issue is detected in the PCIe adapter that was turned on in PCIe slot%1.
PCI5004.Resolution: Make sure that: 1) The PCIe adapter used is supported by the Chassis Management Controller (CMC). For a list of supported adapters, contact your service provider. 2) The adapter is not damaged. 3) The power requirement of adapter is not more than the power allocated to the slot. 4) The adapter is properly inserted in the slot.
PCI5004.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected an issue in the PCIe adapter that was turned on in the slot identified in the message.

HWC2014.Resolution: Make sure the hardware is installed correctly. Refer to the product documentation for correct configuration and installation procedures.

SYS413.Description: The operation successfully completed as all conditions have been met.

VDR91.Message: Consistency check for %1 has detected multiple uncorrectable medium errors.
VDR91.Description: This message occurs if there are medium errors in the physical drives.

RAC0697.Description: Choose to create a job from the existing successful pending operations.
RAC0697.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Click Pending Operations button to view pending operations. 2) Click Create Job button to create a configuration job. 3) Click Cancel button to quit job creation.
RAC0697.Message: Choose to create a job from the existing successful pending operations.

PWR2260.Description: The iDRAC experienced an IPMB communication issue with the Intel Management Engine and was not able to recover IPMB communications. The server thermal failsafe state is activated.
PWR2260.Resolution: Disconnect power from the server and reconnect power. Turn on the server. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR2260.Message: The Intel Management Engine is unresponsive and the server thermal failsafe state is activated.

PSU8506.Description: When the Server Power Management mode is enabled the Power cap cannot be set.
PSU8506.Resolution: To enable the ability to set the power cap, switch to external Power Management and disable the Server Based Management Mode in the CMC Web interface.
PSU8506.Message: Unable to change power cap because Server Based Power Management Mode is enabled.

SUP025.Description: Generic message to show that last command was successful.

SEL0013.Message: The system event log was created or initialized successfully.

HWC5035.Message: An over-temperature event detected on I/O module %1.
HWC5035.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Make sure fans are installed and working correctly. 2) Check the temperature sensor status for the chassis and make sure it is within the chassis operating temperature range. 3) Reseat the I/O module to clear the over-temperature condition. If the problem persists, contact the service provider.

SYS134.Description: The report size is more than the 30MB allowed size which will cause a truncated, partial report to be generated.
SYS134.Resolution: Remove older log entries so that the final zip archive size can be reduced.
SYS134.Message: OS Collector: Zip archive size exceeded the limit.

STOR100.Description: The operation cannot be completed because no drives were found that were locked by using a matching foreign key identifier.
STOR100.Resolution: Check the security status of drives in the Physical Disks Properties section and retry the operation. To check by using graphical user interface (GUI), click Controller > Properties > Security Status and Encryption Key Identifier. To check by using RACADM, run "racadm raid get pdisks -o -p securityStatus,ForeignKeyIdentifier" at the command line interface (CLI).
STOR100.Message: Unable to complete the operation because no drives were found that were locked by using a matching foreign key identifier.

SYS269.Description: The Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) attribute cannot be changed because the feature is not supported by using Server Configuration Profile (SCP), and the attribute setting is not applied.
SYS269.Resolution: To set Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) attribute to enabled using the RACADM command line utility, type "racadm set idrac.security.fipsmode enabled".
SYS269.Message: Unable to change the Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) attribute because the feature is not supported by using Server Configuration Profile (SCP), and the attribute setting is not applied.

UEFI0142.Description: The System Service Mode (SSM) cannot be entered because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was unable to complete a requested task or function.
UEFI0142.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0142.Message: Unable to enter System Service Mode (SSM) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was unable to complete a requested task or function.

STOR0511.Description: Unable to change the encryption key due to an internal error.
STOR0511.Resolution: Exit Lifecycle Controller, press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation. If the problem persists, update the RAID controller firmware to the latest version and retry the operation.
STOR0511.Message: Unable to change the encryption key.

AMP0322.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0322.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0322.Message: Chassis power level current is outside of range.

RAC925.Description: An alert recurrence cannot be set for the specified subcategory. The alert recurrence is applicable only to the TMPS subcategory.
RAC925.Resolution: 1. Check if the alert recurrence is applicable to this subcategory. To check this run racadm eventfilters get.2. To set the notifications for the specified subcategory, run the command without the -r option.
RAC925.Message: Recurrence interval is not applicable for this subcategory.

LC048.Description: The value provided to set the attribute identified in the message is invalid.
LC048.Resolution: For more information on the valid values, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation. Retry the operation with a valid value for the IPChangeNotifyPS attribute.

SWU8530.Description: The process for iKVM firmware update was not successful.
SWU8530.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8530.Message: Unable to update the iKVM firmware.

RED093.Description: Lifecycle Controller is not enabled and must be enabled in order for scheduled jobs to be created.
RED093.Resolution: Enable Lifecycle Controller and retry the operation. Lifecycle Controller can be enabled by using the F2 System Setup by pressing F2 during server startup, then select iDRAC Settings > Lifecycle Controller and enable the Lifecycle Controller feature. Retry the operation after the server restarts.
RED093.Message: The requested job cannot be scheduled because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

USR0172.Message: The Front Panel USB Management Port Mode setting is changed from %1 to %2.
USR0172.Description: The Front Panel USB Management Port Mode setting is changed as identified in the message.

SWC4004.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility detected between iDRAC in slot %1 and CMC.
SWC4004.Resolution: Check firmware versions of iDRAC and CMC. Update to latest version.
SWC4004.Description: FlexAddress is not implemented in one of the versions of firmware. Please update the firmware.

UEFI0241.Message: An error occurred during Voltage Regulator (VR) initialization on memory riser %1.
UEFI0241.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0241.Description: An error occurred during Memory Voltage Regulator initialization during the VR1 SVID Ramp phase.

CTL73.Message: Foreign configuration is imported only partially. Some configurations failed to import on %1.
CTL73.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SWC0273.Description: The syntax for the config command is invalid.
SWC0273.Resolution: Refer to the help text for the 'config' subcommand.
SWC0273.Message: Invalid syntax. The -g option requires -o to also be specified.

LNK0001.Description: The entered network share name is not valid.
LNK0001.Resolution: Enter a valid network share name and retry the operation. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.

RAC0699.Description: The value for Minimum Fan Speed must be within the range identified in the Recommended Response Action.
RAC0699.Message: Invalid value for Minimum Fan Speed.

LC042.Description: Configure Console name while Virtual Address Management is in FlexAddress mode.
LC042.Resolution: Configure the Virtual Address Management to Console mode, and then configure the name of a console.
LC042.Message: Configure Console name in FlexAddress mode

SWC0274.Description: The value of specified parameter is invalid.
SWC0274.Resolution: Enter the same command with a legal value to the object.
SWC0274.Message: Invalid syntax. An object value must be specified.

ISM0011.Description: The server OS could not start the iDRAC Service Module, because the iDRAC Service Module disabled on iDRAC.
ISM0011.Resolution: Enable the iDRAC Service Module on the iDRAC before starting this service on the server OS, and then retry the operation. To enable the module by using iDRAC GUI: Click Network, click OS to iDRAC Pass-through, and then click the USB NIC option. In the OS IP Address box , type an IP address, and then click Apply. To enable the module by using RACADM command, run the following command at the command line interface: racadm set idrac.servicemodule. ServiceModuleEnable enabled.
ISM0011.Message: The server operating system (OS) is unable to start the iDRAC Service Module, because it is set to "disabled" in iDRAC.

SWU8524.Message: Unable to update the iDRAC on the server in slot %1 firmware: ErrorCode=0x%2.
SWU8524.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source folder, and then retry the operation.
SWU8524.Description: The firmware update operation is not successful. This may be due to a problem encountered by the firmware, or because a server was removed during the firmware update operation.

SYS017.Description: The job did not complete successfully.
SYS017.Resolution: Verify the reason for the unsuccessful completion of the job by inspecting the Lifecycle Log entries related to the job. Correct the underlying cause of the unsuccessful completion and retry the operation.

SWC0249.Message: Invalid syntax. The requested subcommand requires -i %1 to be specified.
SWC0249.Resolution: Enter the proper index preceded by -i.
SWC0249.Description: The specified parameter needs to be given with its legal value.

SWC0060.Description: One or more vFlash partitions are attached.
SWC0060.Resolution: Use iDRAC Web interface to detach the vFlash partitions and retry the operation.

SWC0235.Description: All public keys stored on the iDRAC have been deleted.

SUP002.Description: Could not create a new job because of a network error or an unresponsive iDRAC.
SUP002.Resolution: Retry the action. If this fails, reboot the iDRAC.

SWC0151.Message: RAC configuration saved to file successfully

SWC8558.Description: No specified MAC addresses were deleted because they were not present in MAC Address Pool.
SWC8558.Message: No specified MAC addresses were deleted because they were not present in MAC Address Pool of Boot Identity profile operations.

BAT0011.Message: The storage battery for disk drive bay %1 is operating normally.
BAT0011.Resolution: Verify the battery installation, check the system logs for thermal related issues.

SYS174.Description: The Tech Support Report (TSR) cannot be exported because of an issue while connecting to the network share using the provided credentials or other network share parameters.
SYS174.Resolution: Make sure the entered sharetype, sharename, IP address, username and password are valid and retry the operation. The network share connectivity can be tested by using the Test Network Connection feature of the iDRAC.
SYS174.Message: Unable to access network share for exporting Tech Support Report (TSR).

RAC0260.Description: The specified IPv6 address prefix length is invalid.
RAC0260.Resolution: Enter a valid IPv6 prefix length. Expected range: 0-128.
RAC0260.Message: Invalid IPv6 prefix length. Expected range: 0-128.

PDR1107.Message: Rebuild is in progress for drive %1.

PDR1005.Message: Drive %1 in disk drive bay %2 is in the critical array.

RAC0297.Description: The Domain Controller Address be specified for Active Directory configuration.
RAC0297.Resolution: Enter a valid Domain Controller Address.
RAC0297.Message: Specify a Domain Controller Address must be configured.

SYS425.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the value %1 entered for the property %2 is invalid.
SYS425.Resolution: Enter a valid value for the property in the request body and retry the operation.For information about valid values, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
SYS425.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the value entered for the property identified in the message is not supported.

SWU8662.Message: Unable to update the I/O Aggregator (IOA) firmware because of an issue in the network communication session between CMC and IOA in slot %1.
SWU8662.Resolution: Power-cycle the IOA and if the firmware version is unchanged, retry the firmware update operation.
SWU8662.Description: The IOA firmware cannot be updated because of an issue in the network communication session between CMC and IOA.

ENC29.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PWR219.Message: The Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature cannot be enabled because the PSU in slot %1 is not a 3000 W PSU.
PWR219.Resolution: In order to use the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature, replace the PSU identified in the message with a 3000 W PSU.
PWR219.Description: The Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature cannot be enabled because PSU in the slot identified in the message is not a 3000 W PSU.

RAC0905.Description: Unable to obtain the USC version details.
RAC0905.Message: Failed to get the USC version details.

BAR060.Description: Collecting firmware inventory and copying it into the system profile backup file.

MEM0005.Message: Persistent correctable memory error limit reached for a memory device at location(s) %1.
MEM0005.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
MEM0005.Description: The memory is operational. This is an early indicator of a possible future uncorrectable error.

ASR0102.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate within the timeout period. The system was shutdown. (IPMI sensor type code 23h offset - 02h event 3:0 - 4h).
ASR0102.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0102.Message: The OS watchdog timer shutdown the system.

BIOS006.Description: A configuration job is already created on the specified target. No further command is allowed until the existing job succeeds or the job is cancelled.
BIOS006.Resolution: Wait for the job to complete. To continue with more set operations on the specified target, cancel the job and proceed.
BIOS006.Message: Configuration job already created, cannot set attribute on specified target until existing job is completed or is cancelled.

FC006.Description: A configuration job already exists for the specified target. No further configuration operations are allowed until the existing job is competed or the job is cancelled.
FC006.Resolution: Wait until the existing configuration job for the targeted component is complete or cancel the existing job before retrying the operation.
FC006.Message: Configuration job already created, cannot set attribute on specified target until existing job is completed or is cancelled.

RAC0502.Description: Virtual disks cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the host system is powered off or there are no virtual disks created.
RAC0502.Resolution: 1. Check if the host system is powered off or shutdown. 2. Check if virtual disks are created.
RAC0502.Message: There are no virtual disks to be displayed.

SEL1509.Message: Member %1 has joined the Chassis Group.

OSD19.Description: Failed to execute fork() system call to perform the task in a child process. iDRAC may be unresponsive.
OSD19.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD19.Message: The fork() command for a child process to perform the task failed.

RED035.Message: %1 Rollback successful. Earlier version:%2, Current version:%2.
RED035.Description: The firmware for the component identified in the message was updated successfully by the firmware rollback operation. The component firmware was updated from the earlier version to the current version identified in the message.

VDR52.Message: The consistency check found inconsistent parity data on %1.
VDR52.Resolution: Rerun the consistency check task. If you receive this message again, verify the health of the physical disks included in the virtual disk. See the storage hardware documentation for more information. Review messages for significant messages related to the physical disks. If a physical disk has a problem, replace it and restore from a backup copy. Contact technical support if the issue persists.
VDR52.Description: The data on physical disk members of the virtual disk does not match. Redundancy may be lost.

SYS014.Resolution: For more information, refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation and provide a valid value for the identified attribute.
SYS014.Description: The value provided for the identified attribute is invalid.

VFL0704.Resolution: Insert the SD card and try again.
VFL0704.Message: SD card is not present and could not be initialized.

FCD8531.Message: Unable to activate the %1. The chassis service tag is unavailable.
FCD8531.Description: The CMC is not responding. The chassis has the factory-programmed service tag.

SWC8535.Message: Unable to add key for slot %1 of service account, due to problem saving key file.
SWC8535.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8535.Description: Public Key (PK) SSH Authentication key file upload did not complete successfully because Chassis Management Controller is unable to access the configuration database.

VFL0002.Description: The status of vFlash SD Card or the vFlash media partition cannot be obtained, because some of the iDRAC services are busy.
VFL0002.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and retry the operation. If the issue continues to persist, contact your service provider.
VFL0002.Message: Unable to query the vFlash media status.

BAR091.Description: A System Profile Backup request made by the user of the Unified Server Configurator interface has completed.

CTL85.Message: %1 is operating at less than optimal bandwidth.
CTL85.Resolution: Perform a Powercycle operation on the Chassis. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CTL85.Description: The controller identified in the message experienced a PCIe training error and is operating at less than full bandwidth. Until this issue is resolved, a reduction in the storage performance is expected.

LOG305.Description: The Chassis Log file was cleared as a result of clear log operation.
LOG305.Message: The Chassis Log file was cleared.

SEC0002.Description: The I/O card area is open. I/O cards may be added or removed. System performance may be degraded.
SEC0002.Resolution: Close the I/O card area. Check system logs.
SEC0002.Message: The I/O card area is open.

USR0013.Description: The user does not have sufficient privileges to execute the command.
USR0013.Message: Insufficient user privileges to perform operation.

UEFI0042.Description: Unable to enable the TXT feature because Trusted Platform Module (TPM) configuration is invalid.
UEFI0042.Resolution: Go to System Setup > System Security page, select the "On with pre-boot measurement" option for TPM Security, and click the "Activate" option under TPM command. Restart the system, go to System Setup > System Security page, and then enable TXT.
UEFI0042.Message: Unable to enable the TXT feature because Trusted Platform Module (TPM) configuration is invalid.

PST0133.Description: System BIOS detected a failure with the DMA controller during system POST. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception code 85).

LC026.Description: This method is not supported in this version of the iDRAC firmware.
LC026.Resolution: Update the iDRAC firmware to a version that supports the log export.
LC026.Message: Lifecycle Controller Log Export method is not supported.

LIC902.Description: Unable to allocate the resource because of lack of memory or file space in the iDRAC.
LIC902.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation.

SYS047.Description: The input file is not compliant with the system configuration schema.
SYS047.Resolution: Make sure that the input file is compliant with the system configuration schema published on delltechcenter.com/lc in the LC profile Schema Guide.
SYS047.Message: Input file for import configuration is not compliant with the configuration schema.

JCP019.Description: A new job cannot be created until the existing Import Server Profile job is complete or deleted. Only one Import Server Profile job can be running at any given time.
JCP019.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Retry the operation after the Import Server Profile job is complete. 2) Delete the scheduled Import Server Profile job and retry the operation.
JCP019.Message: Cannot create new jobs until the existing Import System Profile job is completed or cancelled.

BAR110.Description: All the existing jobs are canceled during the Import Server Profile operation or if the Import operation fails.
BAR110.Resolution: Resubmit any jobs that were cancelled by the Import operation after the Import Server Profile operation completes.
BAR110.Message: All existing jobs cancelled because of Import Server Profile request processing.

RAC1027.Description: A test event was generated and the alert was successfully sent to the destination.
RAC1027.Resolution: Verify if the alerts were received by the configured destination. Otherwise, reconfigure the destination and retry the operation.
RAC1027.Message: Successfully sent the alert for the specified event to the configured destination.

DH010.Description: The iDRAC must be reset to apply a new certificate. Until the iDRAC has reset, the old certificate will be active.
DH010.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC. The iDRAC can be reset by pressing the Identify button for 15 seconds. Using the RACADM command line utility, run "racadm racreset".
DH010.Message: Reset iDRAC to apply new certificate. Until iDRAC is reset, the old certificate will be active.

LC017.Resolution: Verify that parameter values provided to the method are typed as they appear in the enumeration and that the parameter data type matches the Lifecycle Controller Profile documentation.
LC017.Description: A parameter value provided when the method was invoked is not valid.

SYS229.Message: Unable to transfer file, %1, because of some unknown reasons.
SYS229.Resolution: Make sure that correct file transfer parameters are set, and then retry the operation.
SYS229.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of some unknown reasons.

SWC0083.Description: The iDRAC has been successfully removed from Integrated Data Center network per user action. The iDRAC will now be set to Factory defaults. The iDRAC will be able to show up in an Integrated Data Center only when it is rediscovered.
SWC0083.Message: The iDRAC is successfully removed from the Integrated Data Center network.

MEM0007.Message: Unsupported memory configuration; check memory device at location %1.
MEM0007.Resolution: Review product documentation for supported memory configurations.
MEM0007.Description: The memory may not be seated correctly, misconfigured, or has failed. Memory size is reduced.

RAC1136.Description: The remote unattended diagnostic execution operation is initiated.
RAC1136.Resolution: Using the RACADM command line interface, run the "racadm jobqueue view -i <job id>" command to view the status of the operation.
RAC1136.Message: Remote unattended diagnostic execution operation initiated.

RAC1020.Description: Some objects have dependencies on other objects that are required to perform a task. The specified group does not contain any objects, because the dependent objects are not part of the current system configuration.
RAC1020.Resolution: Verify the dependencies of the objects under the specified group using "racadm help <device class>.<group name>", and retry the operation. For example, "racadm help NIC.IscsiSecondTgtParams".
RAC1020.Message: No objects are available under the specified group for the current system configuration.

LIC204.Description: This error occurs when the Lifecycle Controller restore operation is interrupted before it completes. This can occur due to a power outage or when the iDRAC is reset while the restore operation is in progress.
LIC204.Resolution: Repeat the Lifecycle Controller restore operation. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
LIC204.Message: The License Manager database restore operation failed.

BAR111.Description: The Import or Export job did not complete successfully. The Import or Export operation timed-out while validating or transferring Server Profile data. Possible causes are loss of network connectivity, vFlash SD card access issues, or problems encountered with system power off and on.
BAR111.Resolution: If the managed system does not turn off during Import, turn off the system and retry the operation. If the managed system turned off, restart the Remote Access Controller and retry the operation. If the export was to a network share verify the connection and try the operation again. If the export destination was the vFlash media, insert a new SD card and try the operation again.

LC047.Description: The DownloadClientCerts operation is in progress. The operation may take a few minutes to compete before the operation can be attempted again.
LC047.Resolution: Wait a few minutes before retrying retry the operation.
LC047.Message: An instance of DownloadClientCerts is already running.

VF007.Description: A partition with an image was created.

RAC0242.Description: The vFlash partition does not exist. This may be due to another user deleting that partition.
RAC0242.Resolution: Refresh the Web GUI page to see the available partitions.
RAC0242.Message: The selected partition does not exist.

PWR8591.Description: Before inserting hard disk drives, always make sure the Chassis has enough available power. Otherwise operating servers may be turned off.
PWR8591.Resolution: Make sure there is enough power supply to distribute power. Go to, the Chassis Overview > Power > Power Budget Status. In the Total Input Power Available For Allocation field, view the available power. To add more power, insert more PSUs or remove unused components from the chassis.
PWR8591.Message: Servers are turned off to allocate power to the newly inserted hard disk drives.

UEFI0171.Message: A Dual Rank DIMM module is installed on memory slot %1 after a Single Rank DIMM module.
UEFI0171.Resolution: Dual Rank DIMM modules must be installed before Single Rank DIMM modules on the channel. Populate memory modules in a supported configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0171.Description: A memory population violation has been detected on the identified DIMM slot.

UEFI0120.Description: Both of the Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) SD card media are missing, or not responding.
UEFI0120.Resolution: Make sure both the SD card media are properly installed and retry the system start up. If the issue persists, replace the SD card media.
UEFI0120.Message: Both of the Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) SD card media are missing, or not responding.

RRDU0001.Message: Internal Dual SD Module is redundant.

ASR0101.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate within the timeout period. System was reset. (IPMI sensor type code 23h offset 01 - event 3:0 - 3h if booting 4h if running).
ASR0101.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0101.Message: The OS watchdog timer reset the system.

RED044.Message: A recurring operation of type %1 was unable to create a job because the required license is not available now.
RED044.Resolution: Install an iDRAC license that supports the following features: Automatic Update or Server Profile Export and Import. After the appropriate license has been installed, retry the operation.
RED044.Description: The license required to perform the operation identified in the message either has expired or was removed and the iDRAC was unable to create the next job in the sequence.

RAC0622.Description: The certificate file is invalid for one of the following reasons: 1) CA Certificate is corrupted, expired, or does not have signing privileges. 2) CA private key does not match with CA Certificate being uploaded.
RAC0622.Resolution: Make sure the CA certificate and private key are correct and retry the operation. The certificate can be validated using the OpenSSL tools.
RAC0622.Message: An invalid certificate file is uploaded.

PSU8516.Description: Unable to set redundancy policy because PSU enumeration is in progress. The policy can be set after PSU enumeration is complete.
PSU8516.Resolution: Retry the operation after the PSU enumeration is complete.
PSU8516.Message: Unable to set redundancy policy because PSU enumeration is in progress.

UEFI0213.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0213.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0213.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Basic Read DQ/DQS Training phase.

SWC0212.Message: Perform POST Virtual Console disable from local system

VFL0020.Description: The vFlash SD card is currently in use by another operation.
VFL0020.Resolution: Wait for the current vFlash SD card operation to finish, and they retry.
VFL0020.Message: vFlash SD card is not ready.

SWC0318.Description: The value for -s must be greater than zero.
SWC0318.Resolution: Enter a value greater than zero, for the option -s.
SWC0318.Message: The starting record must be greater than zero.

VDR30.Resolution: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
VDR30.Description: A user changed the write policy for a virtual disk.

SWU8533.Message: Unable to update the LKVM firmware, because the target is not ready. ErrorCode=0x%1.
SWU8533.Resolution: Wait for the target to become ready. This may take a few minutes. After the target is ready, then retry the operation.
SWU8533.Description: The LKVM firmware update operation is not successful, because the target is not ready.

TMP0131.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0131.Message: The control panel temperature is less than the lower critical threshold.

RED075.Description: The Automatic Backup schedule operation could not be successfully created because the Automatic Backup schedule configuration already exists.
RED075.Resolution: Check the Automatic Backup schedule to verify if it is accurate or delete the existing schedule and retry the operation.
RED075.Message: An Automatic Backup schedule already exists.

UEFI0168.Message: Unable to configure memory interleaving on DIMM modules on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0168.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure interleaving can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0168.Description: Memory could not be interleaved because a negative Target Address Decode (TAD) offset was calculated during memory initialization.

RAC046.Description: The event notification selected is not supported for the event filter specified.
RAC046.Resolution: Refer to the iDRAC User Guide and Lifecycle Controller documentation and retry the operation with a valid event notification selection on the specified filter.
RAC046.Message: Unsupported event notification for the event filter specified.

RAC0746.Description: Unable to perform virtual disk(VD) operations, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
RAC0746.Resolution: Enable the Lifecycle Controller and retry the operation. To enable Lifecycle Controller, restart the server. During server startup, press F2 to enter System Setup. Go to iDRAC Settings -> Lifecycle Controller, select Enable, and save the changes.
RAC0746.Message: Unable to perform virtual disk (VD) operations, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

SUP003.Description: One of the uniform resource input (URI) string, target or reboot flag parameters is missing or exceeds the prescribed length.
SUP003.Resolution: Verify that the URI, target or reboot flag parameter values are correct and retry the action.
SUP003.Message: Invalid URI, target or reboot flag.

CPU0801.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
CPU0801.Description: System performance may be degraded or the system may fail to operate.

UEFI0218.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.
UEFI0218.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0218.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Write Timing Centering 2D Training phase.

HWC5006.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.

HWC5008.Message: Console is not available for the %1.
HWC5008.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.

RAC0761.Description: The system inventory cannot be retrieved because the maximum number of inventory collections allowed is reached, or because of an internal issue where the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled.
RAC0761.Resolution: The total number of hardware inventory instances might have exceeded the maximum limit. Wait for the operation to complete and retry the operation. If no other system inventory operation is in progress, enable the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature, restart the system, and then retry the operation.
RAC0761.Message: Unable to retrieve the system inventory because the maximum number of inventory collections allowed is reached, or because of an internal issue where the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled.

PDR1017.Message: Drive %1 in disk drive bay %2 is operating normally.

RED082.Description: The Automatic Update or Automatic Backup feature is disabled.
RED082.Resolution: Enable the correct job schedule type, and then retry the operation. For example, to enable the Automatic Update feature, select the Enable Automatic Update option.
RED082.Message: The requested job cannot be scheduled, because job schedule type such as Automatic Backup or Automatic Update is not enabled.

NIC023.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an unknown error in iDRAC.
NIC023.Resolution: Retry the action. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC.
NIC023.Message: Cannot perform the operation due to an unknown error in iDRAC.

CTL115.Description: The Secure Drive related operations cannot be performed because a key mismatch was detected between peer controllers.
CTL115.Resolution: Make sure that the encryption key for the peer controllers matches by using controller security operations such as creating a security key, modifying a security key, deleting a security key, and then retry the operation.
CTL115.Message: Unable to perform Secure Drive related operations because a key mismatch was detected between peer controllers.

CPU0700.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
CPU0700.Description: System BIOS was unable to boot the processor.

MEM1010.Message: Memory device at location %1 is off-duty.

RAC0661.Description: Various storage configuration operations can be performed on different devices such as physical disks, virtual disks, controllers, or enclosures. The operations are applied to the device by creating a configuration job on the associated controller.
RAC0661.Resolution: To complete the storage configuration operation, create a storage configuration job with the necessary scheduling.
RAC0661.Message: Storage configuration operation - #(operation) is pending on the selected #{devicetype} : #{devicename}.

STOR0505.Description: Unable to delete the existing virtual disks for unknown reasons.
STOR0505.Resolution: Exit the RAID Configuration wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists do the following: 1) Reboot the system. 2) Press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller. 3) Retry the operation.

CBL0003.Resolution: Reconnect or replace the cable identified in the message. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CBL0003.Description: The backplane cable identified in the message is disconnected or no cable is detected.

RAC045.Description: The combination of input parameters provided did not match any event filters.
RAC045.Resolution: Verify the combination of input parameters and retry the operation.
RAC045.Message: Event filter does not exist for input parameter combination.

SYS076.Description: The configuration profile contains a component node that is not supported.
SYS076.Resolution: Make sure the input configuration profile only specifies supported component. Check the import operation job configuration results for the unsupported profile node.
SYS076.Message: Invalid or unsupported component specified in the input configuration profile.

AMP0321.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0321.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0321.Message: Chassis power level current is greater than the upper critical threshold.

ISM0022.Description: The OS Collector application did not start successfully on the server operating system (OS) because the application encountered an error.
ISM0022.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the OS Collector on the iDRAC to the most recent version available, and then retry the operation.
ISM0022.Message: The OS Collector application did not start successfully on the server operating system (OS) because the application encountered an error.

SYS237.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an incorrect password value.
SYS237.Resolution: Make sure that the correct password value is entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS237.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an incorrect password value.

SYS279.Description: iDRAC is not ready for processing ISM requests. Retry after 1 minute.
SYS279.Message: iDRAC is not ready for processing ISM requests. Retry after 1 minute.

CTL89.Message: %1 is no longer fault tolerant because the peer controller is not available.
CTL89.Resolution: Check the chassis log for issues with the peer controller. If the peer controller does not resume normal operations after 5 minutes contact your service provider.
CTL89.Description: The peer controller is no longer active in this fault tolerant pair. This can be a temporary situation.

PCI5005.Message: An auxiliary power fault issue is detected in the PCIe adapter that was turned on in PCIe slot%1.
PCI5005.Resolution: Make sure that: 1) The PCIe adapter used is supported by the Chassis Management Controller (CMC). For a list of supported adapters, contact your service provider. 2) The adapter is not damaged. 3) The adapter is properly inserted in the slot.
PCI5005.Description: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected an issue in the PCIe adapter that was turned on in the slot identified in the message.

USR0019.Description: The specified username exceeds the prescribed limit (255).
USR0019.Message: Specified user name is too long.

JCP024.Description: Lifecycle Controller cannot gain access to internal storage due to use by another application or operation. This job starts when Lifecycle Controller is available.
JCP024.Resolution: Wait for current Lifecycle Controller operation to complete. Verify that the system is: 1) Not currently in Lifecycle Controller Unified Server Configurator 2) Not waiting for user intervention at F1/F2 POST error 3) Not in any of the device or controller Option ROMs.
JCP024.Message: Lifecycle Controller is in use. This job starts when Lifecycle Controller is available.

UEFI0266.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the iSCSI initiator IPv4 subnet mask address is invalid.
UEFI0266.Resolution: Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings page, make sure there is no typographical error in the Initiator Subnet Mask field, and retry the operation.
UEFI0266.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the iSCSI initiator IPv4 subnet mask address is invalid.

CTL70.Message: Attempted to import an orphan drive on %1.
CTL70.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

IOV101.Message: A PCIe adapter %1 is inserted in %2 %3.
IOV101.Resolution: If the adapter in slot identified in the message is mapped to a server, the server must be turned off then back on before server can access adapter. If the adapter in slot is a shared adapter and any server is on then the entire chassis must be turned off and turned on for the server(s) to gain access to the installed shared adapter.
IOV101.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected the insertion of an adapter in the slot identified in the message.

PWR2251.Description: The server did not turn on because the chassis cover is open.
PWR2251.Resolution: Close the chassis cover and retry the operation.
PWR2251.Message: Unable to turn on the server because the chassis cover is open.

RAC1073.Message: Unable to reset the threshold value of sensor %1 because the capability to reset this sensor threshold value is not supported.
RAC1073.Resolution: No response action is required. For more information about resetting the threshold level of a sensor, run the "racadm getsensorinfo" command at the command line interface (CLI), and then retry the operation.
RAC1073.Description: The threshold value of the sensor identified in the message cannot be successfully set because the capability reset the sensor threshold value is not supported.

BAT1012.Message: The %1 battery temperature is above normal.
BAT1012.Description: Diagnostic event for service to determine if there is an ambient temperature problem.

RAC1159.Description: The data cannot be retrieved from iDRAC because Lifecycle Controller is disabled or a DUP update is in progress.
RAC1159.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Check if a DUP fw update is progress and wait until it is finished. 2) Make sure the Lifecycle Controller is Enabled. To enable Lifecycle Controller, run the command 'racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState 1'. 3) Retry the operation.
RAC1159.Message: Unable to get the requested data from iDRAC.

SWC4010.Message: %1%2 in Server-%3 requires a version of Chassis Management Controller (CMC) firmware 5.0 or later for using the NParEP (ARI mode) functions.
SWC4010.Resolution: Update the CMC firmware to the latest version and to enable access to the advanced features available in the network device.
SWC4010.Description: The current CMC firmware does not support the ARI Mode advanced features available in the network device on the server identified in the message.

RAC0712.Description: Server failed to power up due to zero power allocated.
RAC0712.Resolution: Utilize the Chassis Management Controller web interface to check available power and server power requirements. If sufficient power is available, allocate power necessary and retry the operation.
RAC0712.Message: Server failed to power up due to zero power allocated.

SUP0515.Description: Lifecycle Controller was unable to authenticate the Update Package digital signature. The Update Package will not be applied unless it has a valid digital signature.
SUP0515.Resolution: Download the latest Update Package from your service provider and retry the operation.
SUP0515.Message: Unable to authenticate the Update Package signature.

RAC1187.Description: The remote diagnostics operation could not be initiated because the Start Time entered is invalid. It is earlier than the current iDRAC time.
RAC1187.Resolution: Enter a Start Time that is later than the current iDRAC time and retry the operation. Run the "racadm getractime" command to obtain the current iDRAC time.
RAC1187.Message: Invalid Start Time Entered. Unable to start the Remote Diagnostics operation because the Start Time entered is earlier than the current iDRAC time.

SWC8556.Message: The Boot Identity profile %1 is in use by the server that has the Service Tag %2.
